<HEADLINE>
KITNA FINALLY CRACKS UNDER PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A few weeks ago, the Seahawks trekked to Green Bay and
had a pretty fun night watching a guy named Brett Farve make a mess
out of a football game.
</P>
<P>
   Wild. Under pressure. A little over-amped to prove he was still
a great quarterback even without the guidance of his old coach and
mentor, Mike Holmgren, Favre threw four interceptions and came
unraveled as the faithful Cheeseheads at Lambeau Field watched,
perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the former Super Bowl MVP suffered the indignity of
seeing a no-name, former NFL Europe kid named Jon Kitna execute a
perfectly professional effort to lead the rising Hawks to a strong,
impressive ``Monday Night Football'' victory.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Sunday, it was Jon Kitna's turn.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay was for real and the charmed life of this extremely
likeable young quarterback was more frog than prince, more pumpkin
than chariot.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a young quarterback, it was a pretty harsh lesson,''
Seahawks coach Mike Holmgren said after the 16-3 offensive
Hindenberg in which Kitna threw five interceptions and lost one
fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kitna has too much drive, too much talent, too much
eagerness to learn to be suddenly viewed as a Cinderella. His best
days are still ahead _ maybe as far ahead as next season.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it is simply a mixed blessing, getting a reputation
for being a crucial cog on an improving football team.
</P>
<P>
   With a legion of Seahawks fans stuffed into the Kingdome to
confirm for themselves that these Hawks are playoff-ready, the
Buccaneers showed what it means to be a marked man in the National
Football League.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy's a good quarterback, make no mistake about it,''
Warren Sapp, Tampa Bay's outstanding tackle, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come in here and only throw (as few picks as Kitna
had so far this season) you can play,'' he added. ``We just did
some things today to get him out of his rhythm. That's what we
wanted to do. We didn't want him to get comfortable throwing the
ball to Joey (Galloway) and (Derrick) Mayes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kept cracking the routes, trying to put pressure on
him and we got a couple of good rushes on him. Whenever you turn
the ball over six times, it's tough. We know because we've done
it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no shame in what the Bucs did to Kitna and the Hawks _
smacking them with a loss that proved for certain that the Bucs are
a super defensive team and that Kitna and the Seahawks will use a
few more tires to screech around those daunting learning curves.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that despite a series of games since Green Bay
in which Kitna has seemed to press and the Seahawks offense has
quivered, Seattle ran off a five-game win streak and still holds an
8-3 record and first place in the AFC West.
</P>
<P>
   Denver tried to do to Kitna what Tampa Bay did Sunday. The
Broncos' entire game plan was about making Kitna beat them. In
fact, Mike Shanahan dared Kitna to beat them by stacking the run
defense on Ricky Watters, holding him to 29 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But on that afternoon, Kitna found just enough out there to pick
apart the Broncos secondary, move the ball and gain 20-17 win.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs, too, ganged up on Kitna. The pressure was there and
Kitna looked as if he was pressing to get things done, but Watters
pulled out a huge game _ opening up the offense just enough for
Kitna to find a few big passing plays to Watters and Sean Dawkins
for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   But Tampa Bay, unlike Denver and Kansas City, had exactly the
right mix of talent, motivation and game plan to make sure that
Kitna did not succeed _ which explains the rash of interceptions
and the fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever accolades Holmgren deserves for pushing the Seahawks to
this new level of respectability, Tampa Bay coach Tony Dungy is a
pro, too _ not caring one bit that the Tampa offense is ugly and
that everything the Bucs do is about their defense.
</P>
<P>
   Dungy's method was just too advanced for Kitna _ not that the QB
shied away from reprimands and responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our coaches talked all week about how our backs are going to
touch a lot of balls this week. (The coaches told me the Bucs were)
going to drop coverage. They're going to play soft. You're not
going to be able to throw the ball down field,'' Kitna said. ``On
those (first two interceptions) I just tried to make a play when
maybe there wasn't a play there. (I should have) hit the back,
maybe see what he can do. I just got a little greedy maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   With confessions like this, Kitna re-invests faith in himself _
an openness and willingness to persevere that will serve him and
his team well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach is always tough on me,'' Kitna said after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be tough on the quarterback. The quarterback has
to play well for you to win. I didn't do that today. I'm sure it
will be a humbling experience when I have to watch that film, as
it's humbling now.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the great thing about this league, we ain't got much time
to think about it. We'll learn from it. I'll learn from it. I
really feel I learn well from adverse situations, when things don't
go quite how I expect them to go. I'll be humble. I'll go in there
and take my lumps and apologize to my teammates for the way I
played today and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Kitna's performance made the Seahawks' offense look uglier
than Tampa Bay's _ an oddly impressive accomplishment. But so far,
Kitna and the Hawks have supplied no reason to doubt that from this
egg, something better can arise.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
