<SLUG> BC-BKC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILISA TRYING TO WEIGH IN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mate Milisa has a problem that isn't going to earn the 49er
basketball player much sympathy from the, shall we say, generally
robust American population.
</P>
<P>
   The native of Zagreb in Croatia is struggling to keep his weight
on. In a land where cheeseburgers and fries are considered one of
the four main food groups, Mate isn't going to find many people who
can relate. Jenny Craig can't help him.
</P>
<P>
   So the 49ers' center must depend on his own diligence in the
weight room and at the dinner table. He has one ally -- his girl
friend, Ivana, who moved here from Zagreb this summer and has been
in charge of the menu. Mate calls her dishes ``crazy food.''
</P>
<P>
   Milisa certainly won't find any allies in the Big West. He won
second-team honors last season as a way-too-lean 6-11, 225-pounder.
Now he's a muscled up 245 pounder who can fill a lane by himself.
Sunday afternoon at the Pyramid, he scored 24 points to go with six
rebounds, three steals and three blocks in the 49ers' 78-77 win
over Southern Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Milisa was identified as a talent by the basketball cognoscente
long before he arrived in Long Beach. He began playing club
basketball in Croatia at the age of 15 and he's been a member of
Croatia's national team since he was 17.
</P>
<P>
   He was recruited by Georgetown, Utah and Indiana, among others,
and one can assume Rick Majerus might have had a weight-gain tip or
two. But Long Beach got him on a lucky bounce last season, after he
played a year at James Madison University and another at a Florida
junior college.
</P>
<P>
   Milisa, who turns 24 in January, improved each year, but his
body didn't keep up. He averaged 13.9 points and 5.6 rebounds for
the 49ers last season, but he lacked the physical game so crucial
to the current era of drive-by basketball. He took care of that
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to work at it,'' he said after Sunday's win. ``I had to
change my diet and add protein shakes and supplements and work in
the weight room. This really was the first summer I had off in the
last five or six years, when I could concentrate on the weights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a struggle. I must have a fast metabolism, because
food goes right through me. I really don't know whether I will be
able to keep the weight on during the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA will follow his progress as closely as Wayne Morgan.
During a forgettable 13-15 season a year ago, several scouts made
stops at the Pyramid to take a look at his development. More will
come this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what (the scouts) say.'' Milisa said. ``My missing link
is size and strength. I want to play professional basketball, so I
care what they say. But I don't want to worry about it. I want to
focus on the games and winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning is always fun. The 49ers haven't had much fun the last
three seasons, but this is easily the most physically gifted team
the 49ers have had since Morgan replaced Seth Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Milisa no longer is the only big man on campus. Junior Grant
Stone also returned with more muscle (and shaper elbows), and 6-9
newcomer James Williams, who will literally roar at his opponents
during the game, will also be a presence once he gets comfortable
in the system.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers also are deep in the backcourt. Morgan has six options
there depending on where he wants to play Antrone Lee and how
quickly he wants to work transfer Brad Smith into the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the only go-to guy was guard Rock Lloyd, who
averaged 18 points a game. When the shooting guard's stroke is on,
he can personally ruin a defense. But a pass to Lloyd is a one-way
ticket, and like any shooter, he doesn't know when to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan stopped him Sunday. After missing seven of eight shots,
Morgan put Lloyd on the bench for good with 17 minutes left in the
game. The 49ers wobbled at the end but won anyway, primarily
because Milisa, Stone and Williams, shooting 18-for-28 combined,
stepped up inside.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan plans to use this muscle. ``But other teams will see that
we're bigger, too,'' said Morgan. ``(The Salukis) knew it, and they
tried to deny them the ball and take the ball in (offensively) and
get them out of the game. That's a battle of wills.''
</P>
<P>
   And even Milisa admits this is the first time he's ever been
considered a go-to guy. He's played with all of the Croatians now
populating NBA rosters, but usually as part of the supporting cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been in this position before,'' he said. ``The last
time I played (for the national team), I was one of three guys (in
the pivot). Rock's the guy who sets us up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a work in progress,'' said Morgan. ``I want to play
uptempo. We have a good bench. When Rock has his 17-footer working,
it makes things a lot easier. And that will happen this year.''
</P>
<P>
   In between those times, it's nice to have a bigger and better
Milisa in the paint as an alternative. I'd say he's hungry for the
opportunity, but hungry probably isn't the word he would choose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
