<HEADLINE>
FRANKEL WINS TWO TURF WARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Victory in one of the million-dollar
Breeders' Cup races continued to elude Bobby Frankel earlier this
month at Gulfstream Park in Florida. A nice consolation prize
arrived Sunday at Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   The trainer won two $500,000 races as Happyanunoit and jockey
Brice Blanc surged to a narrow victory in the Matriarch about an
hour after Super Quercus and Alex Solis swept to a mild upset in
the Hollywood Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't ask for anything better,'' said Frankel, whose barn
raked in $660,000 Sunday, including Spanish Fern's small
third-place purse in the Matriarch.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he could ask for one thing, and that would be a
Breeders' Cup win. After four out-of-the-money finishes Nov. 6,
Frankel is 0 for 35 in racing's richest event, the only blemish on
a Hall of Fame career.
</P>
<P>
   But Frankel has never seemed frustrated by his Breeders' Cup
failures. And as long as he has Hollywood Park in the fall, he'll
never have to beg.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, the six-week Hollywood fall season has been anchored
by the three-day collection of grass-course stakes known as the
Turf Festival. This year it consisted of six stakes Friday,
Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel's two wins gave him six for his career in the Turf
Festival, more than any other trainer and only one less than jockey
Corey Nakatani's seven.
</P>
<P>
   They include victories in three of the past four runnings of the
Matriarch, the year's final major race for filly and mare turf
specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Four-year-old Happyanunoit, imported from New Zealand for owner
John Amerman, the former Mattel chairman, had won the Palomar
Handicap at Del Mar in August and dominated the Vinery First Lady
at Keeneland in mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   The latter race might have set her up nicely for the Breeders'
Cup Filly and Mare Turf. But Amerman would have had to pay a hefty
supplemental nominating fee, and Frankel decided ``the mathematics
didn't figure.''
</P>
<P>
   Sent off at 2-1 odds in the $500,000 Matriarch, narrowly second
in the betting to Breeders' Cup Mile runner-up Tuzla, she found
good position in fifth early in the 1[-mile race and had a clear
shot from the outside at the top of the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   But Frankel thought Tuzla had gotten a jump on his filly. ``At
the 16th pole, I didn't think we were going to get there,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuzla's roots as a miler showed, though, in the final strides.
Happyanunoit got up by a neck and paid $6.20.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it was the extra distance, I don't know,'' said David
Flores, who rode Tuzla. ``I thought I was home free.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert, who trains Tuzla, seemed to blame Flores. ``Brice
timed it perfectly,'' he said. ``He was the more patient of the
two, and he got the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanc is becoming one of the circuit's more reliable turf
riders. The list includes Solis.
</P>
<P>
   Solis won half of the Turf Festival stakes as he rode Super
Quercus ($11) to a two-length victory over Manndar in the $500,000
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alex has been very lucky for me on turf,'' Frankel said.
``He's very patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Tenth in the 14-horse field early in the 1[-mile Derby, Solis
sent the 3-year-old French-bred to the outside turning for home and
got the lead from runner-up Manndar and third-place Fighting Falcon
as 5-2 favorite Mula Gula faded to fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Super Quercus has finished worse than second only once in eight
starts. That was a slow-starting third in the Oak Tree Derby last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hadn't been out in a year, (and) he figured to be a little
sharper the second time off the layoff,'' Frankel said.
</P>
<P>
   Now Frankel plans to rest Super Quercus for a summer and fall
campaign in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alex seems to think this horse can win the Breeders' Cup Mile
next year,'' Frankel said.
</P>
<P>
   No. 8,824: Laffit Pincay, without mounts in the richer stakes at
Hollywood Park, went to Turf Paradise in Arizona on Sunday and
rallied Kits Peak to a }-length victory for trainer Walter Greenman
in the $75,000 Queen of the Green Handicap for fillies and mares on
turf.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay is nine wins from tying Bill Shoemaker's career record of
8,833 victories.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Jockey Isaias Enriquez was examined and released from
Centinela Hospital after hitting the dirt hard following the first
race. He's expected to ride Wednesday. His mount, Melancholy Baby,
fell after finishing third, pitching Enriquez over her head; the
horse got up and appeared all right. Enriquez was unconscious
briefly and was removed from the track on a stretcher.... Fans bet
more than $1.4 million on the pick-six after Hollywood Park
guaranteed a $1 million pool. Twenty perfect tickets paid $40,539
each.... Solis also won Friday's Miesque Stakes with Prairie
Princess and Saturday's Citation with Brave Act.... Frankel's
earlier Turf Festival winners were Eternity Star in the 1991
Hollywood Derby, Wandesta in the 1996 Matriarch, Ryafan in the 1997
Matriarch, and Star's Proud Penny in the 1997 Miesque.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
