<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCLA-TENNESSEE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA WOMEN FALL TO TENNESSEE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANEL LAJ  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It can happen once, but not twice _ not against a
great team.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA played tentatively and waited until the second half to
explode for the second time this season. This time, however, the
Bruins were facing six-time national champion Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (2-1) fought uphill the entire game, and the Lady
Vols' balanced attack made the fight even more difficult as No. 4
UCLA dropped its first game of the season to No. 5 Tennessee 88-77
Sunday at Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Losing Kellie Jolly and Chamique Holdsclaw didn't necessarily
mean Tennessee would be lacking depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought losing those two players might have dropped them a
bit,'' UCLA forward Maylana Martin said. ``I thought they might
struggle a bit, but they had a couple of people step up in the end.
Tamika (Catchings) played well, and so did their freshman guard
(Kara Lawson).''
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Vols' reinforcements were key down the stretch with
their solid fundamentals and consistency. That was due in part to
their talented recruiting class. Tennessee (3-1) had three freshmen
on the floor at the end, including Lawson who finished the game
with 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to think that we rebuild, but reload,'' Tennessee
coach Pat Summitt said. ``I'm looking out there at the end of the
game, and we had three freshmen making big plays for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee established its presence early and led 40-31 at
halftime. The Lady Vols were extremely aggressive offensively
behind Catchings, a junior All-American and Naismith Player of the
Year candidate. Catchings scored 15 of her 28 points in the first
half and collected 13 rebounds for her first double-double of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Tamika's) got tremendous speed up and down the floor,''
Summitt said. ``She makes everyone else better because of her
intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebounding and depth were two key factors for Tennessee. The
Lady Vols outrebounded UCLA 45-33.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was huge,'' UCLA coach Kathy Olivier said of the
rebounding statistics. ``I think Pat does a good job knowing what
works for the basketball team. She takes a lot of pride in stopping
her opponent's strengths, ... and what works for us is rebounding''
</P>
<P>
   After shooting 13 of 36 in the first half, UCLA came out more
aggressively in the second, scoring 10 points in three minutes. The
Bruins closed within one at 48-47 after a Marie Philman layup with
14:33 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA collected seven steals and forced 10 turnovers in the
second half. Unfortunately for the Bruins, Tennessee's bench upped
the intensity and increased the lead. The Bruins once again cut it
to four, 60-56, but the Lady Vols didn't allow the Bruins to come
closer. The Tennessee bench outscored UCLA's bench 27-15.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee also had help from Semeka Randall's 11 points and five
assists and Kristen Clement's 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who played 39 minutes, had 24 points and six rebounds
for UCLA. Janae Hubbard added 12 points; while guards Nicole
Kaczmarski and Michelle Greco each had 11. Greco also had six
assists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
