<HEADER>
A3583 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-SKINS-LADN     11-29 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SKINS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLES FATTENS HIS AMPLE WALLET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIO, Calif. _ The 17th annual Skins Game turned out be a
rewarding experience, figuratively and literally, for Fred Couples.
</P>
<P>
   Couples, who said he was moved when asked to take the place of
the late Payne Stewart in the popular competition, finished with a
record $635,000 in winnings, thanks to a $510,000 day Sunday at
Landmark Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   He won 11 skins overall and also set records for most money won
in Skins Game history ($1.975 million), most money won on a single
hole ($410,000), most money won on Sunday ($510,000) and most
birdies (nine) for 18 holes.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara finished second with $170,000 and Sergio Garcia was
third at $70,000. David Duval was shut out for the second time. He
also didn't win any money in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara jokingly gave Couples a new nickname after the two-day
affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's Mr. Skins, that's all you can say,'' said O'Meara, the
defending champion. ``Freddie `Skins' Couples.''
</P>
<P>
   The low-key Couples attributed his success to good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say it every time,'' he said. ``Luck is the greatest thing
that's ever happened to the Skins Game. There is a lot of luck
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of good golf also enters into the equation, and there was
a lot of it on Sunday's back nine. Couples birdied five holes,
including one on the par-5, 563-yard 18th hole that netted him
$410,000. The 18th hole, already designated a $200,000 Super Skin,
was another $210,000 richer thanks to a three-hole carryover.
</P>
<P>
   Couples started the hole poorly when he drove into a bush left
of the fairway. O'Meara's drive went far to the right, while Duval
and Garcia found the fairway off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   Couples hacked out of trouble with an 8-iron, followed by a
210-yard 4-iron to 12 feet. O'Meara left his second shot under the
lip of a bunker short of the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a real smart play for somebody who's been playing for
20 years,'' O'Meara said after taking himself out of the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Duval also surrendered after going for the green in two but
leaving his 255-yard 3-wood short and in the water.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia was over the green and in a bunker from 269 yards out and
left his third shot about eight feet short. Couples promptly
drained his putt and Garcia missed to make Couples the big winner.
</P>
<P>
   Couples said he was surprised at the hole's sudden turn of
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``After walking up to my drive, I thought somebody was going to
make birdie,'' he said. ``I also thought David's ball was going to
carry. Sergio looked to be on the back edge, and it made my shot a
lot easier because there was nothing to lose. If I hit a good shot,
I make five and go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't think I would win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Only three of the previous eight holes were won outright.
Couples' two-putt birdie from 50 feet on the par-5 10th hole was
worth $100,000, O'Meara drained a 40-footer for birdie to win
$170,000 on the 232-yard 13th hole, and Garcia won $70,000 on the
next hole, a 314-yard par-4 in which each player attempted to drive
the green but found greenside bunkers.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia made a two-footer for birdie after almost holing out from
the sand, and Duval missed from four feet.
</P>
<P>
   Duval's putter often betrayed him over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had won some skins, but that's how this game is, the
nature of this format,'' Duval said. ``I don't worry about it. I
had a couple of chances. I would have liked another chance or two,
but just didn't make them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia also wished a few more putts would have dropped, like a
six-footer for birdie on the 17th, but he still called the weekend
a pleasant experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great time,'' he said. ``I'm just a little
disappointed I couldn't make one of the last two putts. (Duval)
also missed some, and I know how he feels.''
</P>
</TEXT>
