<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-SLUM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY SEEKS A TOUGHER POLICY ON SLUMLORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN HORSLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Knight Ridder Newspapers
KANSAS CITY, Mo. - Nearly two years ago, Kansas City launched a
``slumlord of the month'' installment on its government TV channel,
in hopes of shaming problem landlords into cleaning up their rental
properties.
</P>
<P>
   It did not work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It withered on the vine. It didn't have any real teeth to it,
if you're not hitting them in their pocketbooks. Some of them even
considered it a badge of honor,'' said Nanci Regan, neighborhood
development supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   So now, prodded by exasperated homeowners, Kansas City officials
are preparing to recommend to the City Council a more comprehensive
get-tough approach.
</P>
<P>
   Strategies will include a ``landlords school'' similar to school
for drunken drivers; intensive probation and community service;
civil court action to gain more control over the properties; and
lobbying for higher fines and more jail time.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood activists applaud the effort, but some are
skeptical and think it still does not go far enough. Some residents
want landlord licensing, something that Kansas City, Kan., now
requires but which landlords in Kansas City, Mo., have lobbied
against.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Williard, tagged the first ``slumlord of the month'' in
1998, scoffs at the new approach. Williard said the city should
stop harassing property owners who provided affordable, if not
immaculate, housing for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where will you put the poor people when we gentrify all the
areas?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Neighborhood and Community Services will
describe the plan to a City Council committee next month. An
internal memo explains that _ rather than creating new regulations
for all landlords to follow _ the department wants to ``target
problem rental property owners'' who have a history of Municipal
Court violations and convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ostracizes the bad folks, rather than doing
landlord//tenant licensing that goes after everyone,'' said Bob
Mohart, the department's director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to treat these people like multiple DUIs,'' he said.
``And when you have an aggravated problem, you march them across
the street to Circuit Court.''
</P>
<P>
   The landlord school would consist of a basic eight-hour program
for first-time offenders and a more intense program for repeat
offenders. Courses could cover landlord/tenant law, tenant
screening, housing codes, permit requirements, and the effect of
nuisance violations and poor property maintenance on the entire
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the city and neighborhood representatives want to do is
provide the foundation, the educational piece, so landlords know
what the laws are. And for those who just are not complying, there
is this additional responsibility to attend this further training,
to get them to understand that what they do affects the
neighborhood,'' said Iris Archer, neighborhood preservation
division manager.
</P>
<P>
   Even if landlords do not take the courses seriously, they would
be required to attend, Mohart said. That erases the excuse of
ignorance if future violations occur. Failure to comply could
result in house arrest or jail time.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said they were still trying to estimate how many
people might be required to attend such a school.
</P>
<P>
   Other strategies include requiring out-of-town landlords to
appoint a local registered agent, empowered to improve properties
and correct problems. The landlord might also be required to file a
letter of credit or post a bond that would be accessible for
property improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Without those controls, neighborhood activists complain,
out-of-town owners too often avoid prosecution and let their
properties slide into disrepair.
</P>
<P>
   The city's neighborhood attorney, Holly Steinhauser, also is
exploring a new legal strategy in civil court action: receivership.
Courts give those cases docketing priority, and a judge hears them.
If the property is deemed unsanitary or unsafe, the judge can
appoint a receiver with power to apply rent payments and borrow
against the property to make repairs.
</P>
<P>
   If the owner does nothing for two years, the receiver can apply
to have the property put into his name or that of a non-profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a priority of our office to attempt one of those,''
Steinhauser said. ``It is one more tool in our toolbox.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinhauser has recently sent her first letter notifying an
owner and mortgage company of her intent to file a receivership
petition after 60 days, if no abatement or foreclosure has begun.
</P>
<P>
   Mohart also is asking the council to lobby the state legislature
for several changes to add more teeth to the city's enforcement
mechanism. Among those would be authority to increase the maximum
fine for property code violations from $500 to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible course of action would be to have Missouri
toughen its control over limited liability corporations, using
Kansas as an example. Kansas requires corporations to publicly
register with the state, divulging owners and ownership percentages
and where they can be served notice of violations, so they can be
located and prosecuted more easily.
</P>
<P>
   When told of the new approach, some landlords protested that
they were being unfairly singled out.
</P>
<P>
   Williard has battled the city for years over his property
maintenance approach in north Hyde Park and the East Side. City
records show he has been cited repeatedly for properties with trash
and debris, unlicensed or disabled vehicles in the yard, broken
windows, weeds, porches and gutters in disrepair, peeling paint and
other violations.
</P>
<P>
   He and his attorney, Dan Franco, dismiss those as minor
infractions and argue that the city has carried out a vendetta
against Williard, forcing him to spend thousands of dollars on
legal fees that could have gone for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Williard acknowledged in letters to the editor and in an
interview that his properties were not ``Mission Hills'' fancy, but
he said they were often in better shape than other, neighboring
properties that were not cited. He said he provides affordable
shelter for low-income residents who might otherwise have no place
to go, or who would have to rely on government subsidized housing.
</P>
<P>
   Williard said he improves the houses that he buys, and that he
has saved properties the city would have been forced to tear down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made them into livable, usable properties,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Williard says his main opponents are owners of the majestic
stone mansions just blocks from his houses, who want to drive out
all the rental units in the neighborhood to improve their property
values.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue is the gentrification of Hyde Park,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Franco said he thought most landlords were
sophisticated investors and did not need a ``landlords school.'' He
suggested mediation and fair code enforcement that did not try to
drive a landlord out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood activists, however, argue that weaknesses in the
city ordinances seriously impede the efforts of conscientious
homeowners in areas on the verge of a renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   John Gladeau, president of the Old Hyde Park Historic District,
points to decrepit rental properties next door to beautifully
restored Victorian homes. ``It makes it hard to bring back these
transitional neighborhoods,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gladeau is particularly concerned about the high percentage of
absentee landlords in his neighborhood, out of reach of process
servers and the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first formed five years ago,'' he said, ``we submitted
a list of 38 problem apartment buildings to the city....The only
ones with any progress are the ones owned by in-town owners.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Gladeau cited one property on Wyandotte Street
that has had three out-of-state owners since 1993. A mattress has
adorned the front lawn for months. It also has peeling paint,
deteriorating columns, and broken windows, and it has been vacant
for months.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Rafoth, from Iowa, owned the building until October, when
a bank foreclosed on the property. Rafoth blamed bad tenants for
the problems and said it was a nightmare trying to keep drug
dealers and vagrants out. He said management companies and the city
bureaucracy merely added to his problems. He finally shut the
building down and boarded it up.
</P>
<P>
   But Gladeau and others think out-of-town landlords need to take
more responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Some advocate landlord licensing, which would require all
landlords to fix up their buildings or lose the ability to rent the
properties.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City proposed that several years ago, and respectable
landlords lobbied hard against it as an onerous burden. Mohart so
far is not receptive to reintroducing the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``My position is we're not going to create another huge city
bureaucracy,'' he said. ``We think, and our lawyers think, we can
get this done with existing resources.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 0040EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
