r S BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI &LR;      11-29 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCS STOP SEAHAWKS, 16-3 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ So many things had gone so well for the Seahawks
during a five-game winning streak that staked them to an 8-2
record.
</P>
<P>
   For much of Sunday's game, that was again the case.
</P>
<P>
   The offense took the opening kickoff and moved smartly through
the Tampa Bay Buccaneers' vaunted defense to a field goal by mixing
the passing of Jon Kitna and running of Ricky Watters.
</P>
<P>
   The defense was dominating, limiting the Bucs to 156 total yards
by holding them to negative yardage on six series and fewer than 10
yards on 13 of their 15 possessions.
</P>
<P>
   They even knocked Trent Dilfer out of the game when defensive
end Phillip Daniels drove the Bucs quarterback to the Kingdome turf
on a third-quarter sack, breaking Dilfer's right collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing was sorely missing: turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 20 games, the Seahawks did not force one.
Kitna, meanwhile, turned the ball over six times _ five
interceptions, one fewer than he had thrown in his first nine
starts, and a fumble.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line of this glaring discrepancy was a 16-3 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said earlier in the week that turnovers would decide the
game,'' coach Mike Holmgren said. ``We had too many and we didn't
create any. That's exactly the story of this game _ it was
turnovers.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough turnovers to gag the life from any chance the Seahawks
had of winning.
</P>
<P>
   But they live to learn from their mistakes, and try to find ways
to eliminate them next week against the Raiders in Oakland _ where
the Kansas City Chiefs outlasted the Raiders Sunday. At 8-3, the
Seahawks hold a two-game lead over the Chiefs (6-5) in the AFC
West.
</P>
<P>
   A repeat of Sunday's effort would make that a one-game lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very humbling loss but we're 8-3 and there's
absolutely no reason to go in the tank,'' guard Pete Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks can't allow the self-inflicted misery against the
Bucs to become self-doubt as they continue their quest of winning
the franchise's first division title since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a five-game win streak and we were feeling real good
about ourselves. Maybe too good,'' Watters said. ``But it's
happened everywhere I've been, even with the Niners. We bounced
back every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren was upset, a little downcast and understandably
frustrated after the Seahawks produced their lowest point total
since being shut out in back-to-back games in the 2-14 season in
1992 _ a span of 115 games over almost seven seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But Holmgren admitted his team was due for a game like this,
especially against a defense as aggressive and aggravating as the
Bucs'.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later, something like this was going to happen,''
Holmgren said as he left his post-game news conference. ``We were
playing very, very well. But games like this just happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren also agreed with Watters' assessment that perhaps the
players were feeling too good about themselves after winning five
in a row and grabbing a three-game lead in the division.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were feeling really good, and I want them to feel good,''
Holmgren said. ``But this feeling is a little new for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood in the locker room was a little too familiar for the
players who have been around as the Seahawks have failed to post a
winning record since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly what we'd done leading up to this game gave us
margin for error,'' Kendall said. ``But now we can't sit back and
think we've done anything. Like I've been saying for a while, 8-2
is a nice start, but until that little letter shows up next to your
name in the standings, it ain't over. This game proved that.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense played well enough to win this game. Holmgren said
it, and so did any offensive player who was being honest with
himself.
</P>
<P>
   With the Bucs ranked among the top 10, if not top five, in
almost every defensive statistical category, the Seahawks defenders
took it as a personal challenge to play with them, if not outplay
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been challenged all week to attempt to play as well as
their defense,'' said linebacker Chad Brown, who led the effort
with 12 tackles and a sack. ``We wanted to match their defensive
intensity. We didn't want to get shoved around. We didn't want to
be embarrassed. We just wanted to handle our stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked. Despite playing without defensive tackle Sam Adams
(sprained knee) and cornerback Willie Williams (concussion), the
Seahawks yielded a season-low 156 yards. Without their 54-yard
drive to a Martin Gramatica field goal in the second quarter and a
67-yard drive to Shaun King's 2-yard touchdown pass to Patrick
Harper in the fourth quarter, the Bucs netted 25 yards on their
other 42 plays.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of dominating effort the defensive players have
been talking about turning in all season as they were allowing an
average of 341.5 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   But what's better? Allowing a lot of yards, and coming up with a
lot of turnovers? Or not allowing yards, and not getting turnovers?
</P>
<P>
   The answer was obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough situation when you don't get any turnovers,''
said Daniels, who couldn't even force one with his
collarbone-cracking sack of Dilfer. ``You can't win like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it would have helped if the Seahawks offense could
have found a way to crack the Tampa Bay defense. The Bucs pressured
Kitna into a pathetic performance (19 of 44 for 197 yards) by
blitzing up the middle and into his face. They took away his
security-blanket crossing routes by dropping a linebacker into the
middle of the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``They obviously had a really good game plan on defense,''
Watters said. ``We were kind of scratching our heads out there. It
was as if we didn't even practice, we didn't know where they were
coming from out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Seahawks are left to scratch to regain the swagger that
was slapped out of them as they head into a stretch of four games
against division opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how good a team we are next week when we play
Oakland in Oakland,'' Daniels said. ``We'll see how well we bounce
back from this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
