<HEADLINE>
BUCS' DEFENSE COMES UP `HUGE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HOLLY CAIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Trent Dilfer had to high-five his defensive teammates
with his left hand following Tampa Bay's 16-3 victory Sunday
against the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Dilfer's right arm was in a sling and he was hurting after
breaking his collarbone in the third quarter. Still he managed to
smile broadly through the pain. Dilfer's replacement, rookie Shaun
King, had been effective. His defense had been dominating.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay forced six Seahawks turnovers _ intercepting Jon Kitna
a career-high five times _ and kept Seattle out of the end zone for
the first time in Mike Holmgren's coaching tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of reeling over the loss of Dilfer, who is likely out
for the season, the Bucs were basking in victory. It is the first
win against expansion-twin Seattle and a key momentum boost
entering next Monday night's pivotal game against Minnesota. Both
teams share the NFC Central Division lead with a 7-4 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did today ... it was huge,'' said Tampa Bay safety
John Lynch, who led the Bucs with seven tackles. ``This is a team
with a lot of pride, in our defense in particular. You look for
challenges like playing this caliber of team and we stepped it up
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's win over the surging Seahawks surprised no one in
the Bucs' locker room. The way they won may have.
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs, who had beaten only two winning teams, came to the
Kingdome ranked last in the league in turnover ratio. Usually they
are the team trying to compensate for miscues. And they didn't
expect that to change so dramatically this weekend considering
Kitna had led the Seahawks on a five-game winning streak and to the
AFC West Division lead by playing smart, mostly conservative ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ranks right up there with the our best performances,''
said All-Pro defensive tackle Warren Sapp, grinning after his
three-tackle, one-sack effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much that we got him (Kitna) rattled, we just put
him in some positions that he wasn't comfortable in. We just kept
the pressure on him and forced him to make the plays. We didn't get
the number of sacks we wanted, but we got the pressure on him and
it got to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch and Sapp said their team pretty much followed its game
plan. It naturally was concerned about facing elite players such as
Joey Galloway and Ricky Watters, but the Bucs felt they also knew
Holmgren's tendencies from his days coaching their NFC Central
rival Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warren Sapp was really destructive,'' said Seahawks offensive
guard Brian Habib, whose line allowed three sacks. ``They had a lot
of guys who came on blitzes that we were not able to pick up.
Whether it was an assignment error, or just too many guys, we
couldn't pick it all up.''
</P>
<P>
   As with the Seahawks, the Bucs' offense had helped Tampa Bay to
a four-game winning streak by being adequate, not flashy. The
defense has saved the offense on several occasions but Tampa Bay's
bench still took a collective gulp when Dilfer went down.
</P>
<P>
   Backup Eric Zeier was listed as the emergency quarterback for
this game, still not 100 percent recovered from a shoulder injury.
So King, a second round draft choice out of Tulane, made his first
regular-season appearance on the Bucs' opening drive of the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay, which amassed a meager 48 yards total to that point,
went three-and-out in King's first two drives.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick Dunn's 17-yard run in the final seconds of the third
quarter finally gave the Bucs their first first down since the
opening quarter. Five plays later King connected with Patrick Hape
for a touchdown reception and a 13-3 scoring cushion. King finished
3-for-7 for 32 yards and led Tampa Bay to a field goal in addition
to his touchdown toss.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (King) seemed very confident when he first came into the
huddle, surprisingly confident,'' said veteran Bucs center Tony
Mayberry. ``I remember my first game and I was wide-eyed, but Shaun
did a great job of not getting rattled.
</P>
<P>
   ``And thanks to our defense, we won. Again.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Holly Cain can be reached at 206-448-8015
</P>
<P>
   or hollycain &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
