u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BILLS-BO     11-29 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BILLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST LOSS DEALS PATRIOTS' HOPES A BLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. _ The Patriots have become the anti-Maytag:
They always need fixing.
</P>
<P>
   By now New England's product would have been returned and
declared a lemon. Or the repairman would have had to answer for not
doing the things necessary to fix the problem. Not once (in a 24-17
loss to the Jets). Not twice (a 27-17 loss to Miami). But three
times following Sunday's 17-7 loss to the Buffalo Bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking responsibility for this,'' said coach Pete Carroll,
whose job security is at an all-time low. ``We have to make
adjustments and right now we're not making them.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe wouldn't put it on the coach. He wouldn't put it on
his teammates. He wouldn't even put it on the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the quarterback of this team,'' said Bledsoe, who was 18
of 34 for 205 yards, with one touchdown and one interception. ``I'm
responsible for scoring points and we don't score enough of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The only New England score was Bledsoe's 45-yard pass to Terry
Glenn in the fourth quarter with the game well in hand for Buffalo.
By then mistakes, turnovers, and penalties had done in New England,
which fell to 6-5, in fourth place in the AFC East and some believe
far, far away from getting back into the running for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to see about that,'' said Carroll. ``We need some
help from other teams. Right now we can't worry about what other
teams are doing. We have to correct our problems. It's happened
three weeks in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn did not start for disciplinary reasons. He had missed the
first part of Thursday's practice, and Carroll decided to bench him
for a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't hurt the Patriots too badly, though they went down,
3-0, on Steve Christie's 28-yard field goal with 1:32 remaining in
the first. A huge interference penalty on safety Chris Carter as he
and Eric Moulds jockeyed for position on Doug Flutie's floater
inside the New England 10 set the stage for the early score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I touched him,'' said Carter. ``We were both
going for the ball. That's a judgment call. There's nothing I can
do about that one.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots felt helpless on that play, they could have done
something about the Bills' second-quarter score, a 54-yard pass
from Flutie to Moulds. It was second and 6 from the Bills' 46, and
Flutie was in the shotgun, then dropped back and watched the
situation develop. Cornerback Steve Israel fell at the 40, leaving
Moulds wide open at the 25, where he caught the pass and jogged in
for the score with 1:01 remaining in the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked the wrong time to fall down,'' said Israel. ``I think
my foot got tangled up in his. You saw what happened. We had some
missed coverages and mistakes and penalties that really cost us
today.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first half the Patriots were penalized eight times for
101 yards (they had none in the second half). The Patriots actually
ran the ball better than the Bills _ 93 yards to 92 _ but once
again failed miserably in converting third-down chances (3 of 13).
</P>
<P>
   For the first time this season, the Patriots lost a game in
which they rushed 25 or more times. They even won the possession
battle, 30:46 to 29:14.
</P>
<P>
   Every time they had something working, a penalty or mistake
would end their momentum. The Patriots had an 11-play drive working
in the first quarter when Ben Coates was called for holding. They
had driven to the Bills' 24 in their next possession when Coates
was flagged for offensive interference. From there the Patriots
were forced to pass, and Bledsoe threw an interception to Ken Irvin
on a pass intended for Troy Brown down the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had another decent drive in the second quarter, but
an intentional grounding call on Bledsoe, who was being heavily
rushed and threw the ball to the ground toward a fallen Kevin
Faulk, cost the Patriots dearly.
</P>
<P>
   The one superb play they made, punter Lee Johnson running for a
first down when pressured by Bills safety Keion Carpenter, didn't
spark anything.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was sacked six times, knocked down repeatedly, and
hurried frequently. The Bills did the same things the Jets and
Dolphins did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty down right now,'' said Bledsoe. ``To lose three in
a row is very disheartening.''
</P>
<P>
   Even trailing, 10-0, at the half, the Patriots could have come
back. But there weren't enough adjustments made in the locker room.
Chad Eaton made a play early in the third quarter when he stripped
the ball loose from fullback Jonathan Linton, Israel recovering at
the Bills 43. But the offense went three and out.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum again gone, the Bills and Flutie piled on. Starting
at their 20, the Patriots' defense left backup tight end Bobby
Collins wide open in the middle of the field for a 45-yard gain.
Then Flutie dumped a pass off to Sam Gash, who danced down the
right sideline, avoiding a tackle by Andy Katzenmoyer. Gash, who
looked more like Barry Sanders than a 245-pound fullback, dashed 31
yards for the score with 10:21 left in the third to make it 17-0.
</P>
<P>
   There seemed little hope. Still, the Patriots moved the ball
from their 33 to the Buffalo 6 as Bledsoe went to an intermediate
passing game. But Faulk, carrying up the middle on first and goal,
had the ball come loose on a hit by linebacker John Holecek, giving
it back to the Bills with 4:49 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frustrating,'' said Willie McGinest. ``That's the only word I
can come up with.''
</P>
<P>
   Can it be fixed?
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it can be fixed,'' he said. ``I can fix myself. I
can make myself better. I can't fix everybody else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
