<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3590 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKW-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     11-29 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUARD SPURNS SUMMITT, AND DAD, FOR UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Forget the final score, which favored Tennessee
88-77. A better barometer that the UCLA women's basketball team is
gaining on the Lady Vols was Nicole Kaczmarski's presence in the
Bruins' backcourt Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Kaczmarski, who started and supplied the Bruins with 38 solid
minutes, grew up on Long Island and was more than a blip on
Tennessee coach Pat Summitt's radar screen. Summitt homed in on
5-foot-11 point guard, who is the reigning national high school
Player of the Year. She showed up at two of Kaczmarski's practices
at Sachem High, the women's hoops equivalent of God appearing to
Moses.
</P>
<P>
   Kaczmarski called it ``a great honor'' to be pursued by arguably
the best coach, male or female, of the top women's program in the
land. She chose to go to UCLA anyway, which, truth to tell,
couldn't have devastated Summitt as much as it did Kaczmarski's
father, Peter.
</P>
<P>
   There were other point guards for Summitt to recruit; in place
of Kaczmarski she landed a more-than-suitable alternative in Kara
Lawson, who had 19 points and zero turnovers in 28 minutes to help
hand No.4 UCLA its first loss in three games.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Kaczmarski, on the other hand, had only one baby left in
the nest. Her decision to fly so far from the coop was hard on both
of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was big-time upset at me (for choosing UCLA),''
Kaczmarski said. ``Me and my dad are inseparable. So not being able
to look in the stands after every shot and see him is the toughest
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming to UCLA was something I wanted to do, so I did it. I
guess I really didn't realize how far it was going to be. I've had
my share of homesickness. The first week I was like, `I want to go
home!' But I guess that's normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaczmarski, 18, wouldn't have set herself up for so much angst
if she didn't think the Bruins, under seventh-year coach Kathy
Olivier, weren't really, really close to the national supremacy
that Vols fans have come to view as Tennessee's birthright.
</P>
<P>
   ``My junior year I liked Tennessee a lot, because of its success
and Coach Summitt,'' Kaczmarski said. And yet she committed to UCLA
early in her senior year because ``I wanted to go to a program
where they haven't won a championship in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   That wouldn't be Tennessee, which has won six national titles _
including three in a row this decade _ since UCLA captured its lone
national championship in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Summitt's teams have been so dominant, they've lost back-to-back
games just four times in the 1990s. As soon as the Bruins stop
beating themselves up over the fact they were within one point of
Tennessee before letting the Vols wiggle out of their grasps in the
final 13 minutes, they'll see they have many reasons to be
encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   High on the list is the fact an 11-point margin is a veritable
nail-biter for Tennessee, which beat UCLA by 23 at Knoxville last
December.
</P>
<P>
   The Vols lost three games last season and only four other
opponents managed to hang within 11 points of them. In 13 of its 31
wins, Tennessee enjoyed at least a 30-point cushion.
</P>
<P>
   Too, the Bruins fell without the services of veteran point guard
Erica Gomez, who is sidelined until January after undergoing left
shoulder surgery. And they were effectively missing starting center
Janae Hubbard, who fumbled a perfect pass from Kaczmarski under the
basket on the game's opening possession and saw her confidence slip
through her fingers along with the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard, a senior whose hulking presence underneath was a
strength the Bruins had to exploit to counter Tennessee's
considerable depth and skill, didn't have a rebound in the first
half. The Vols capitalized on Hubbard's inertia by grabbing 14 of
the 23 rebounds at UCLA's end in that span.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard missed four of her first five shots, then made four of
her final five and finished with nine points and two rebounds. All
she needs is a little more time to get in sync with Kaczmarski, who
had 11 points, four steals, three assists and two turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   The whole offense will benefit from having Gomez back. She'll
lighten Kaczmarski's load and act as a sort of security blanket for
her teammates, who look a little lost on the court without her.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's backcourt may have come straight from New York's backyard
(Gomez is from New Jersey), but local talent is what has brought
the Bruins to the cusp of greatness. Olivier is a big believer in
keeping the homegrown talent from pulling up its roots. A case in
point is senior forward Maylana Martin, who had her pick of schools
and chose to play not far from her hometown of Perris.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to players such as Martin and Huntington Beach's Marie
Philman and LaCrescenta's Michelle Greco, ``People on the West
Coast know there's a sport other than volleyball now,'' Summitt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Olivier's aim is to keep hoarding the local jewels and go
outside for the one or two gems that will complete UCLA's national
crown. It's a strategy similar to the one Summitt started with at
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Success has turned the whole country into Summitt's backyard, as
evidenced by the fact 11 of the 14 Vols on this year's squad _
including all the starters _ are from out of state.
</P>
<P>
   Now that she's here, Kaczmarski wouldn't dream of being anywhere
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all about UCLA now,'' said Kaczmarski, who survived her
first Thanksgiving away from home thanks to a huge assist by Greco,
who brought the freshman home with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all part of growing up,'' Kaczmarski said with a shrug
and a smile.
</P>
<P>
   She was talking about herself but her words rang true for the
Bruins, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 0051EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
