u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     11-29 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT CAN BE HARD TO FOLLOW THIS LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. _ These are the souls that try men's minds.
</P>
<P>
   In times like these, even the souls that have become so trying
for us all can see that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to push the panic button,'' Patriots receiver Troy
Brown said Sunday, only half jokingly, as he sat in a locker room
that was as quiet as a morgue.
</P>
<P>
   It was an hour after Brown's Patriots had lost their third
straight game, a 17-7 debacle to the Buffalo Bills in which they
did not score a point until there were less than three minutes left
in the game and most probably in their season. The silence of the
lambs was appropriate for such a situation as this.
</P>
<P>
   Hope was gone from this room despite some brave words that tried
to argue to the contrary. It is over for the Patriots and probably
for coach Pete Carroll. For this season in their case and maybe for
good in his because in three years they have tracked steadily
downward from the 1996 Super Bowl season to this _ a team with a
busload of millionaires that probably killed any chance of making
the playoffs under a fittingly leaden sky.
</P>
<P>
   This was a loss that came as a shock to these Patriots despite
their recent struggles, a loss they had grown to expect would not
happen despite the mounting evidence the last two weekends of their
slow decline.
</P>
<P>
   For three years they have played this kind of football, winning
big early then fading like autumn leaves before rallying in the
cold to make the playoffs just as all seemed lost. It had become
their pattern and so they believed nothing would change this time
when they dug another hole for themselves. But they are a year
older and their rivals in the AFC East are a bit better and this
time they have not been able to do what they did in 1996, 1997, and
1998. This time they have not been able to survive their own
malaise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in fourth place now and we gotta depend on someone
else,'' Brown said, resignation in his voice. ``Right now we're
depending on people to help us and that's a bad situation to be
in.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the worst of situations, but it is one of their own
making. After opening the season 6-2 by beating up a string of
losing teams they were ill-prepared for the iron of the AFC East.
After a week's respite at midseason they have lost to the Jets, the
Dolphins, and the Bills in ever more confused fashion, reaching a
point with their offense Sunday when they seemed incapable of
making a play.
</P>
<P>
   In three games, Drew Bledsoe has been sacked 13 times (six
Sunday) and knocked flat three times as many more, yet the
offensive line has for the most part played well enough. How can
this be, you ask?
</P>
<P>
   ``He had time to hold the ball for quite a bit and we still were
covering them, so that was a big key _ our secondary playing real
well,'' Bills coach Wade Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   They did play well, but not as well as the Patriots' receivers
played poorly. There are men locked in solitary confinement seeing
more daylight than some of the Patriots' receivers have found the
past three games, and because of that Bledsoe is taking a pounding
and looking more and more confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last three weeks we haven't produced,'' Bledsoe said after
completing 18 of 34 passes for only 205 yards with one interception
and those six sacks. ``What exactly the reason for that is, I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't know, who does?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, no one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing good teams and we're making mistakes that become
magnified because you are playing a good team and we are not able
to overcome it,'' Carroll said. ``What I will tell you is that we
have to go back to work and we have to hang together to create our
offense again because right now we don't have anything that is
giving us a chance to win football games.''
</P>
<P>
   Huh?
</P>
<P>
   This does not sound like an answer to a question. This sounds
like a man lost in space. If that is the case, Carroll is not alone
in this feeling.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have become a team in doubt. Although they try to
say the right words, what they say belies how they feel _ lost.
They doubt themselves. They doubt their coaches. They doubt the
plans they are being given. They doubt the kind of discipline that
comes too late and at the wrong time, as it seemed to Sunday when
Carroll finally decided to punish a player for his actions and
chose the worst of times to suddenly try to transform his image
from Barney into The Terminator.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll's decision to bench his best receiver, Terry Glenn, for
the first quarter Sunday because he was two hours late for a
Thursday practice and had an interlude with the local constabulary
at 4 a.m. before his arrival might have made sense had Carroll not
spent the previous two years turning a blind eye to every such
transgression.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the biggest game of the year, he benches his most potent
receiver when his team has the wind? And then puts him back into
the game in the second quarter against the wind and lets him play
the rest of the day? Is this discipline or self-flagellation?
</P>
<P>
   More than a few of Carroll's players wondered why the team was
being punished for one man's wayward ways in the biggest game of
the year. It was a question worth asking but, like most Sunday, it
had no answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what that was and I don't have any other comment on
it,'' Carroll said when asked if the benching of Glenn had been a
punishment. What the question should have been was who was he
punishing, Glenn or everyone else?
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of decision that makes you scratch your head,
but there were plenty of those Sunday. Perhaps the most glaring
came with 13 minutes to play and New England trailing, 17-0. The
ball was finally inside Bills territory at the 48, fourth and 1.
The Patriots knew what they had to do. They had to go for it.
</P>
<P>
   But not GO FOR IT, for Pete's sake.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of sneaking the ball for the first down to keep the
drive alive, something they've done successfully a half-dozen times
this year, they went for it all and threw the ball. Rather, they
tried to throw the ball, but Bledsoe never had a chance, being
sacked even though he was in the shotgun when the play began.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was that all about?'' one Patriot defender rightfully
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Good question. But do we have an answer?
</P>
<P>
   I think not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a route that we wanted to throw right there,'' Carroll
explained. ``That situation is one that is really easy to critique
and be critical of and we were taking a shot to try to make a first
down. We didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   No they didn't. Not this day and not this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
