<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARROLL NO ANSWER MAN 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. _ Having answered only a few questions, but
one too many for his liking, Patriots coach-under-fire Pete Carroll
concluded his postgame press conference Sunday with, ``I'm done.
See you.''
</P>
<P>
   If only it were that simple.
</P>
<P>
   Papa Pete, the drug-free Daddy Butch Hobson of this southbound
train, is not the only problem with the 1999 New England Patriots,
but in the wake of another no-show, drum-beating _ this one a 17-7
thumping at the hands of the Buffalo Bills _ the coach admitted,
``I'm taking responsibility for these.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll is taking responsibility, but unless he is playing dumb,
he has no answers for what is happening to his team. Many of the
folks on sports talk radio seem to have a better handle on the
problem, and that's a scary situation. Patriots owner Bob Kraft,
ever the locker room gadfly, has been conspicuously absent from the
postgame scene the last two weeks and Sunday left the premises well
ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it's abundantly clear that Carroll's players don't
take him seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Where will the fellas be partying this week? Who'll be pulled
over by the cops at 4 a.m. or be late for practice? And what will
Pete do about it? Will he place individuals on double secret
probation? Hide the car keys? Send them to bed without dessert?
Lock up the pool cues? Force them to watch ``Regis and Kathie
Lee''?
</P>
<P>
   We're told he fined defensive back Lawyer Milloy and wideout
Vincent Brisby for their part in a Thanksgiving Eve altercation at
a charity event in Saugus. And he tried to get Terry Glenn's
attention by benching the receiver for the first period Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn was late for a meeting Thursday and paid the price. Sort
of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake,'' Glenn said of this latest embarrassment.
``Live it, learn from it, and move on. That's all I've got to say.
But you are either a championship team or not a championship team,
and no coming late to a meeting is going to keep you from being a
championship team. Take that the way you want.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, let's take it this way: Glenn is dumping all over his coach.
He does it when he is pulled over by the Foxborough cops in the wee
hours of the morning three days before game day. He does it when he
is late. He does it when he works out on his own offseason program.
And he does it with his latest statement.
</P>
<P>
   Not to bring up a sore subject, but can you imagine Glenn
getting away with all this with Bully Bill Parcells in charge? Is
it an accident that Parcells got the most out of Glenn _ way back
when the gifted receiver was a rookie?
</P>
<P>
   The Carroll Patriots are in the midst of their third annual Tuna
Meltdown. Every year since Parcells left, he has beaten the
Patriots in midseason and each Tuna loss triggered a major New
England swoon. In 1997 and '98, the Patriots went 1-3 after losing
to the Jets. This year they are 0-2 since the Jets beat them. This
makes them an aggregate 2-8 in midseason stretches that start
against the Tuna.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams play us with a lot of cover two (a cornerback bumps him
at the line, backed up by a safety),'' said Glenn. ``It seems like
Bill originated it.''
</P>
<P>
   Beleaguered quarterback Drew Bledsoe (sacked six times, his team
8 for 37 in third-down efficiency over the last three weeks)
admitted, ``The Dolphins and Bills took a couple of things from
what the Jets did.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, QB Drew was a ringleader in an infamous Patriot
off-field episode when he and teammates Max Lane and Scott Zolak
did a stage dive into a mosh pit at a Boston nightclub and were
sued by a young woman who suffered a spinal injury. In the ensuing
game, the Patriots were humiliated at Tampa Bay, 27-7. It was the
low point of Carroll's rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have a new low, one that leaves the Patriots with
virtually no margin for error over the next five weeks. Once
playoff bound with a 6-2 record, they are 6-5 and have four
division losses.
</P>
<P>
   And Carroll has no answers. He continues his soft parade of
cliche and inaction. He admitted benching Glenn and fining Milloy
and Brisby, but said, ``We take care of that stuff internally. We
keep it in house.''
</P>
<P>
   Week after week, ex-Patriots beat New England. It's amazing. Has
any team ever lost three straight games that ended with one of its
former quarterbacks calling the plays (Ray Lucas, Zolak, Doug
Flutie)? Patriots fans watching Sunsday were treated to the sight
of castoff Sam Gash making a 31-yard TD catch and run. Then Gash
took his own shot at the Patriot organization.
</P>
<P>
   Leaderless, clueless, simmering on the edge of mutiny, the
Patriots lurch toward December facing a series of winnable games.
But it's hard to make a case for them this morning. It feels like
the window is closing on the young, talented group that made it to
the Super Bowl just before Carroll's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   And it feels like only a matter of weeks before Coach Carroll
utters a firm, final ``I'm done. See you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
