<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-PACERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS SEND MESSAGE TO PACERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It was late in the fourth quarter Sunday night when
Sonics guard Brent Barry threw a pass off the backboard. Ruben
Patterson trailed, caught the ball and finished a stirring
alley-oop play.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Barry wondered aloud if the Indiana Pacers thought
he was gloating near the end of the Sonics' 102-91 win in KeyArena.
When asked the last time he threw such a playground-style lob,
Barry joked: ``When I was playing NBA Live on PlayStation.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry, though, was not the only one with a joystick in his
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the game wasn't nearly as close as the final score
indicated, there were plenty of times when the Sonics seemed to toy
with the Pacers. The Sonics (11-3) built a 17-point lead in the
first quarter and cruised to their sixth consecutive victory at
home.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the Barry-Patterson connection with 46 seconds left
put an exclamation point on a message the Sonics are trying to
send.
</P>
<P>
   Said point guard Gary Payton: ``We're trying to let people know
_ like the old Sonics of two or three years ago _ when you come in
here, it's not going to be that easy for you to beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics made it difficult for the Pacers to compete, let
alone win.
</P>
<P>
   Their defense suffocated Indiana's heavy hitters _ Reggie Miller
and Mark Jackson _ early. Once the Sonics took that pair out of the
game, the Pacers offense seemed paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Payton mostly checked Miller, while Barry handled Jackson.
Miller and Jackson combined for eight points.
</P>
<P>
   Payton's 31 points led four Sonics in double-figure scoring.
Horace Grant took advantage of the Pacers slow front line. He
finished with 23 points and 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics ran circles around the aging Pacers, who appeared
slow and lacked energy. The game perhaps gave Sonics coach Paul
Westphal a bit of deja vu.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics basically won because of their energy. They
constantly beat the Pacers with fast breaks, and quick scores.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Westphal had to watch quicker, more athletic teams
outplay a ripe Sonics squad. But these Sonics gave Indiana coach
Larry Bird a taste of what Westphal has already gone through.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that hurts us is our foot speed,'' Bird said.
``We've played a lot of teams with quickness that are maybe getting
better looks. We haven't been as consistent as we'd like. Teams are
just beating us.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the Sonics keep moving right along _ surprisingly to
some and impressively to most.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Pacers' record, they are still considered one of the
top teams in the Eastern Conference. The Sonics had played just
three teams with winning records. So the victory was like passing a
quiz before taking a big test.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics face perhaps their toughest test to date when the Los
Angeles Lakers come to KeyArena Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't win any games with your mouth. So I don't want to
start talking,'' Westphal said. ``Our record is 11-3. We haven't
played anybody yet according to anybody. So when we play somebody,
we'll find out what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   They still have not put together a solid game, if you wanted to
nitpick what the Sonics did against Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   After charging ahead 35-18 in the second quarter, the Sonics
lead was cut to 54-42 at halftime. They stormed ahead 81-55 in the
third, and led by 21 points with 10:03 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Sonics' bench players could not keep the cushion
warm against the Pacers' reserve unit. Westphal wound up having to
reinsert Payton, Barry, Patterson and Horace Grant with 7:25 left
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics led 88-75 at that point. But their lead never dipped
below nine points. They compensated for 43-percent shooting by
holding the Pacers to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had lapses we shouldn't have had. But I'm not too upset
about it. We did a lot of good things. ... We got stops when needed
them,'' Westphal said. ``I still think we can get more efficient
offensively. But when you shoot 43 percent and win a game going
away against a tough team like Indiana, that's something to be
happy about.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
