<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3595 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-CARTER-BOS     11-29 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-CARTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER TOOK HIS CHANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins outshot the Islanders, 44-20, Sunday &UR;  &LR; night
at the FleetCenter, but rookie New York goaltender Roberto Luongo,
a first-round pick (fourth overall) in the 1997 draft, was the
deciding factor in the Islanders' 2-1 win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shots didn't go in, and the bottom line is you've got to
score goals; you don't win games by outshooting the other team,''
said Bruins forward Anson Carter, who had his team's lone goal,
6:02 into the second period. His score tied the game at 1, Carter
taking a feed from Jason Allison behind the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to happen sometimes. We had a lot of quality shots,
so you've got to give their goalie credit,'' said Carter. ``He made
some good saves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins kept putting pressure on Luongo, who had a 6-6-3
record in 15 games for Lowell in the American Hockey League with an
impressive 2.98 goals-against average and 90.6 save percentage.
Luongo, the highest-drafted goalie ever, got the call to the NHL
Nov. 22.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of pressure on Luongo late, but he kept the
puck from getting past him. ``There was a loose puck and I fanned
on it . . . those things are going to happen,'' said Carter, who
was switched from center to wing in the second period to give the
Bruins a lift offensively while teaming with Sergei Samsonov and
Allison.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goalie was down and everyone was in front of the net and I
thought we had a chance to chip it over his shoulder, but it wasn't
meant to be,'' said Carter, who had eight shots during his 23:44.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Pat Burns ``wanted to create some offense, (the
Islanders) really didn't have a so-called No. 1 line, and he wanted
to put me with Allie and Samsonov, hoping to generate some
things,'' Carter said. ``We didn't have much going in the first
period, and to generate more offense, he wanted more speed with
Allie to try to get the loose pucks.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal the Bruins did score was an impressive one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nice play,'' said Carter, who has seven goals and 19
points. ``Jason got it deep and I went in front of the net and I
made sure to yell at him early so he could look for me when he was
coming around.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third period, the Islanders turned defensive while
sitting on their lead, getting outshot, 12-2. Even when the Bruins'
P.J. Axelsson drew a double major late in the game, New York had no
shots on net.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were trying to protect the lead, they didn't give up the
big goal at a critical time during the game, so I have to take my
hat off to them,'' Carter said. ``I thought we'd tie it up, which
is typical of this club. We get stronger as the game goes on, but
we weren't able to get the key goal at the key time to get the
crowd into it, to get our bench pumped up.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing to the Islanders, in 14th place team in the Eastern
Conference, was tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to be successful in this league, you've got to
beat the teams you're supposed to beat, and we had a chance to beat
them and we should have beaten them,'' said Carter. ``It was a must
win for us, regardless where they are in the standings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
