<HEADLINE>
LUCK RUNS OUT FOR KITNA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He had become the Seahawks poster boy, the big-game
television promo, the local car salesman.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Jon Kitna got pulled down by the tacks, pre-empted by
Warren Sapp and taken for a test drive on his most trying day as a
starting NFL quarterback _ a five-interception, three-sack,
two-fumble shortfall in a 16-3 defeat to the Tampa Bay Buccaneers
in the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday, Kitna had led a charmed life in his brief stay in
the pros. He had avoided adversity as he would one of those
300-pounders trying to take his head off. He had averaged less than
a pass theft and just 1{ sacks per game in 18 outings.
</P>
<P>
   Sapp and his overeager defensive cronies changed all that,
forcing the Central Washington University alum into a spate of
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Facing postgame inquisitors, Kitna recognized all this. He
accepted the blame. He also didn't seem too shaken by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll apologize to my teammates and move on,'' he said. ``I
just got a little greedy, maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna started out against the Bucs as if he might be headed for
a career day. He connected on his first three passes. He drove his
club to the Tampa Bay 5 on the initial series, settling for a field
goal and what would be the Seahawks' only points.
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs had all the answers after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was just a little confusion when the game
started,'' Seahawks tight end Christian Fauria said. ``We did a lot
of checking off that put us in positions we shouldn't have been in.
We usually correct those things. I was waiting for something to
happen where we got rolling, but we never got rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   Said offensive guard Brian Habib, ``Jon got some pressure on
him. He might have made some bad throws out there, but I think we
all contributed to it. I don't think we helped him too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks linebacker Chad Brown knew what happened. He has been
on the delivery end of this sort of thing with opposing
quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can definitely feel for him,'' Brown said of Kitna. ``I'm
sure eventually he started pressing. You think you feel the rush
and you throw off the back foot and you just kind of lose what
makes you good.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the interceptions piled up, Seahawks coach Mike Holmgren
said he never once considered pulling Kitna in favor of backup
quarterback Glenn Foley.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren mentioned that veteran Miami quarterback Dan Marino, a
certain Hall of Famer once he retires, suffered through a
five-interception outing on Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a young quarterback, it was a harsh lesson,'' Holmgren
said. ``But I think it will be a lesson that he looks at and is
better because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his five misguided throws, Kitna insists he made a bad choice
on just one _ the second ball, a second-quarter toss over the
middle intended for Fauria, and intercepted by Bucs linebacker
Derrick Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second interception, that was a force and a press,'' Kitna
said. ``On the other ones, when you get down everybody knows you're
throwing and you have to try to make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Brooks victimized him, Kitna had tried to find Joey
Galloway on a slant pattern and Bucs cornerback Donnie Abraham came
up with the ball early in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay linebacker Alshemond Singleton and cornerbacks Ronde
Barber and Brian Kelly also had interceptions, while Sapp and
Brooks forced Kitna fumbles. Rubbing it in, Sapp did a little dance
after he created his turnover, holding the ball aloft while the
Kingdome crowd booed him. Sapp also was seen yapping at the
Seahawks quarterback after several plays.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna said he never got frustrated by his miscues or rattled by
Sapp's monologue.
</P>
<P>
   After the final gun had sounded, Kitna would take one more
blind-side hit before reaching the safety of his locker room. Of
course, it was Sapp. The oversize player ran down Kitna near the
Kingdome's south end zone and put him in a bearhug.
</P>
<P>
   The players exchanged good-natured words before heading to their
respective stadium corners. The healing process already had begun
for the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Maybe we'll see you in January,''' Kitna said,
referring to a possible Super Bowl game. ``He said, `If you got the
(stuff).' I said, `We got the (stuff).' ''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Dan Raley can be reached at 206-448-8008
</P>
<P>
   or danraley &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
