<HEADLINE>
CELTICS HAVE 4 DAYS TO FIND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Paul Pierce left Philips Arena Saturday night, he had
nothing to say and no answers for why the Celtics suffered another
fourth-quarter collapse, against the Hawks. He walked brusquely to
the team bus, declining to comment about Boston's three-game losing
streak.
</P>
<P>
   Let the soul-searching and problem-solving begin.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics have almost a week to contemplate what went wrong.
They will find out Friday night against Miami whether it was enough
time to fix what's broken, restore team confidence, and again find
a way to finish off teams in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday between 1 and 3, Boston held an optional workout in
Waltham. Players who needed medical attention reported, as did
those who wanted to lift weights or work on specific parts of their
game. The coaching staff was available during the two-hour session.
Monday at practice, the coaches and players officially will start
addressing the team's recent difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce was not alone in his quick exit or inability to find
suitable answers over the weekend. The visitors left the floor and
the arena as soon as possible. Following their 94-84 loss to
Atlanta, some of the men in green looked shaken. The locker room
scene was somber. The players seemed more devastated by their
final-quarter failure facing the Hawks than they had been over a
similarly scripted defeat one night earlier against the Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened,'' said point guard Kenny Anderson.
``Even when we get a lead, we have to keep playing. We just didn't
do the things we needed to do to win. Everybody has the same
schedule. We can't make excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Added forward Antoine Walker: ``Without question, it's
frustrating. If you care and you're trying to win, then you're
frustrated. We've shown that we can beat them. But we haven't put
them away. And it's coming back to haunt us. We beat ourselves
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Celtics have four days of practice to beat up on each
other in hopes of getting better.
</P>
</TEXT>
