<SLUG> BC-RAGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVERS WHO KILL GET OWN TASTE OF NO MERCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By VICTORIA HARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Gregory Francis Schmidt could spend 25 years behind
bars for not controlling his anger when a truck cut him off on the
freeway last year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of handling it as a daily irritation on a Phoenix-area
freeway, Schmidt squeezed off eight shots.
</P>
<P>
   In an instant, Gillis Champagne, 21, a passenger in the truck,
was dead. A bullet passed through his neck, severing an artery.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix area is a hotbed for such hotheaded drivers, and
prosecutors and judges in Maricopa County show no mercy for such
violent reactions. Prison sentences are sought for anyone who
flashes or uses a gun on a roadway.
</P>
<P>
   When he is sentenced in January, Schmidt, 29, can expect to join
a string of Phoenix area men spending decades in prison because of
a flash of fury behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take a very hard stance with people who solve problems on
the highway by using a gun,'' said Bill FitzGerald, spokesman for
the Maricopa County Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unacceptable. You simply can't decide to solve a problem
by getting out a gun because you don't like how somebody drives or
how someone has given you a hand signal.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, road rage is unusual. Out of 177 million drivers,
about 1,000 die each year in such incidents.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, it's a different story.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the city ranked third in the nation for dangerous
driving incidents and third again on a list of metropolitan areas
with the highest aggressive-driving death rates.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed at the growing violence, Arizona lawmakers in 1998
passed the nation's first aggressive-driving law, said Alberto
Gutier, director of the Governor's Office of Highway Safety.
</P>
<P>
   Now, brazen drivers who make multiple risky maneuvers, such as
tailgating, unsafe lane changes or overtaking and passing another
vehicle on the right shoulder, can be cited.
</P>
<P>
   But passing laws is only a start, said Leon James, a University
of Hawaii professor known as Dr. Driving, whose lifework is to
educate and prevent driver warfare.
</P>
<P>
   He works with Congress and the states to develop prevention
programs. A pilot program in Miami-Dade County, Fla., which
features a video called ``Roadrageous,'' is the first to try
education in the battle against aggressive driving.
</P>
<P>
   What James really wants is to see laws passed requiring every
licensed driver to take periodic anger-management courses.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every American is an aggressive driver, he said. The
learning starts in the infant car seat, listening to Mom and Dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aggressive driving has been here since Roman times, since the
beginning of streets and horse-drawn vehicles,'' James said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is it can lead to an act of violence, which he said
is a new phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   It began in the mid 1980s, when traffic congestion became
reality for millions of Americans. It's so widespread now that some
therapists specialize in helping drivers afraid of losing control.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol and other drugs, particularly methamphetamine, commonly
play a role in road rage, James said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Phoenix area, at least six men are awaiting trial on
charges of killing people on the roadways during the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Most of their victims were innocent passersby, people such as
Schara Marshall, 14.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Schara was killed while returning from her first
homecoming dance. She was in a car the driver of which turned in
front of a truck in west Phoenix. A chase ensued. Shots were fired,
and Schara was struck in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Her family had moved from the Sunnyslope area to a far west
Phoenix subdivision to get away from the crime, said her mother,
Bonnie Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Schara's killer still has not been caught.
</P>
<P>
   Gillis Champagne's mother, Linda, said road rage is so
commonplace in the Phoenix area, victims often end up a mere
mention in news reports.
</P>
<P>
   That devastated Champagne after losing her son.
</P>
<P>
   She wants the world to know he was the light of her life. He
loved to help others. He wanted to be a physical therapist. He was
living at home to save money to marry his high school sweetheart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so into being physically fit,'' she recalled. ``He was
always telling me, `Mom, stand up straight! Watch your posture!' ''
</P>
<P>
   She still can't get used to the quiet in the house.
</P>
<P>
   His friends, family, the neighbor children, even his dog, will
never fully recover from the loss, said Champagne, an obstetrics
nurse at Good Samaritan Regional Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could this happen?'' asked the mother, who still cries at
the mention of his name. ``He was only a passenger.''
</P>
<P>
   She still struggles to get up in the morning, but she's ready to
bring something positive from the sadness.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Roger, want to get a state law passed to
make it a crime to carry loaded weapons in a vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may not follow it,'' she said. ``But it would give
police a little more control. It might save someone's life.'' &QL; 
Victoria Harker can be reached at (602) 444-8058 or at
victoria.harker(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 0102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3600 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-HISPANIC-CENSUS-AZR &LR;      11-29 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-CENSUS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANICS RESIST ARIZONA'S REDISTRICTING LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ELVIA DIAZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Seven months after Arizona Gov. Jane Hull signed a law
that governs how boundaries for Arizona voting districts are drawn,
local and national Hispanic leaders remain hopeful that it will be
struck down on the basis that it weakens the political power of
Latinos and other people of color.
</P>
<P>
   A score of national civil rights groups and Hispanic
politicians, mostly Democrats, contend that the U.S. Justice
Department should block the law, which requires the Arizona
Legislature to use exact head counts in redrawing political
boundaries after 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say an exact head count is a flawed method that was
shown to undercount Hispanics by more than 1 million people during
the 1990 census.
</P>
<P>
   The law ``will deny minorities the representation they
deserve,'' said Rep. Ramon Valadez, D-Tucson. ``This law was
clearly passed with the intent to discriminate (against
minorities).''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics make up an estimated 20 percent of Arizona's
population, yet only four of the 30 state senators and seven of the
60 state representatives are Hispanic, Valadez said.
</P>
<P>
   Using more accurate census numbers in the next round of
redistricting will offer better opportunities for Hispanic voters
to elect a candidate of their choice, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Wes Marsh, a Republican from District 28 who championed the
law, rejects the notion the head count system will hurt minorities.
He said Friday that he is confident Arizona will be able to prove
the law benefits everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no intent to discriminate against anyone,'' Marsh
said. ``We don't want to guess. We want to use exact numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is still waiting for Arizona to submit
information, including committee reports and a list of minority
groups it has consulted about the law, that shows the law doesn't
stifle ethnic minorities' political power, a spokeswoman for the
Justice Department's civil rights division said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has already failed to reply to the Justice Department's
September deadline, Christine DiBartolo said. Still, the state can
submit the information anytime, with the caveat that the law can't
go into effect until the Justice Department signs off on it, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Stein, chief counsel for the civil rights division of the
Arizona Attorney General's Office, wasn't available for comment
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990 census, an exact head count method was used to
calculate population figures and data that ranged from age and
income to ethnic origin. Afterward, the Census Bureau randomly
surveyed 150,000 households to see how close the two sets of
numbers and data matched up.
</P>
<P>
   The findings showed that the exact head count system missed
about 5 percent, or more than 1 million, of the Hispanics
nationwide, said Marisa Demeo of the Mexican American Legal Defense
and Educational Fund, a national civil rights group.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, at least 90,000 people were not counted, more than
30,000 of whom were Latinos and roughly 20,000 Native Americans,
Demeo said.
</P>
<P>
   Demeo and other minority rights advocates theorize that
Hispanics and other people of color, especially recent immigrants,
tend not to return mail surveys because of cultural and language
differences. Many newcomers, in particular undocumented immigrants
from Mexico and other Latin American or South American countries,
fear any questionnaires would be used to deport or discriminate
against them.
</P>
<P>
   Aiming to produce a more accurate count, the Clinton
administration endorsed a plan to contact 90 percent of all
residents in the country in 2000, then use statistical sampling to
estimate the makeup of the remaining 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, however, fear sampling will overestimate minorities,
who in most cases tend to join the Democratic Party or have
Democratic leanings. Thus, congressional Republicans challenged the
census plan in court.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled against using sampling
to reallocate federal congressional seats. But the court left up to
the states to decide what numbers to apply, either exact head
counts or sampling, when redoing local political districts.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the court's ruling, the Census Bureau will now try to
count everyone, instead of just 90 percent of households originally
planned.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau will then conduct a survey of 300,000 households in
the country, said Pat Cantwell of the Census Bureau in Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   After comparing the results from the head count and the survey,
the bureau will estimate those missed and adjust the numbers,
Cantwell said.
</P>
<P>
   The department will subsequently release two sets of numbers:
the head count and those drawn from the representative sample,
Cantwell said. &QL; 
Elvia Diaz can be reached at (602) 444-7937 or at
elvia.diaz(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
