<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3601 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KC-ECOM-2TAKES-KAN &LR;      11-29 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-ECOM-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIES, STATES LOBBY FOR THEIR SHARE OF INTERNET INCOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRAD COOPER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Knight Ridder Newspapers
KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Almost every day, thousands of people plop down
in front of their home computers to buy everything from groceries
to books to cars.
</P>
<P>
   They shop without the hassle of leaving home, battling traffic
or fighting crowds. Just a few keystrokes and the merchandise is
theirs. No clerks. No lines. And, often, no sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   But what is a break for consumers now may mean tax increases for
them in the future, say city and state officials across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, consumers save on sales tax when they buy
over the Internet from a company not in their state.
</P>
<P>
   In the long term, state and municipal leaders are afraid they
will lose tax revenue to Internet sales, forcing them to raise
other taxes to offset those losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody needs police protection, fire protection, streets,
roads, schools and all the things that make a community work,''
said Randy Arndt, spokesman for the National League of Cities in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are not paying sales tax as electronic commerce
grows, what you are doing is shifting a higher and higher
percentage of the cost of services to the sales taxes collected
over the counter or to property taxes, income taxes and other sorts
of things,'' Arndt said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that states are constitutionally barred from
collecting sales taxes on businesses that don't have a
``substantial physical presence'' within their boundaries. Since
many Internet and catalog sales are made across state borders, the
transactions can't be taxed.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing their potential problem, cities and states across the
country are campaigning for the ability to tax Internet sales.
</P>
<P>
   Just how Internet sales would be taxed is complicated by the
fact that sales taxes differ from city to city and state to state.
Some items, such as food, are taxed in some states but not in
others.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 7,600 taxing jurisdictions throughout the
country. States and cities are banding together to come up with a
simplified way for multistate sellers to collect sales taxes on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Among the local businesses that sell their goods on the Internet
is Wolferman's Inc. of Lenexa, Kan. Wolferman's, a 111-year-old
gift company known for its 2-inch-tall English muffins, sells about
600,000 gifts a year. About 80,000 of the gifts are sold over the
Internet, mostly to out-of-state customers, said Mike Ruchensky,
the company's vice president of operations.
</P>
<P>
   Ruchensky said it's one thing to collect sales tax for a
Missouri or Kansas customer. It's another to collect sales tax for
some city in Pennsylvania, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He estimated that it would cost his company about $25,000 to buy
the computer software needed to collect sales tax nationally. He
said that expense could be prohibitive for some smaller companies
that sell on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have to collect (sales taxes) for every township, city
and county and state across the country, that's when it gets
complex, that's when it gets difficult,'' Ruchensky said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruchensky said he didn't think his company would lose a lot of
business if Internet sales transactions were taxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't tend to look at sales tax when they're buying
gifts,'' he said. ``People are shopping online because it's easy,
it's convenient and it's always available.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is being studied by the Advisory Commission on
Electronic Commerce. The commission was created by Congress last
year to examine issues related to taxing the Internet. At that
time, Congress placed a three-year moratorium on imposing new
Internet taxes to give the commission time to develop its
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The panel had 18 months to study the issue, after which it would
submit a report to Congress. The report is expected in April.
Congress has the final decision about whether states and local
governments can tax Internet sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cities and states want their fair share,'' said Kansas City
Councilman Kelvin Simmons, who serves on a National League of
Cities steering committee that is studying the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons said he had talked with city financial analysts to try
to figure out how much money the city is missing out on, but there
are no definitive numbers yet.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Internet sales are booming nationwide, but cities
and states share in none of that revenue. In an economic downturn,
the extra revenue could be critical to cities' financial survival,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cities would like to see the feds give great deference to them
in regard to this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is opposed by some consumer groups who note that states
have been collecting large budget surpluses in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of money grab is unnecessary,'' said James Plummer,
a policy analyst at Consumer Alert, a nonprofit consumer advocacy
group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are already paying plenty of taxes. They don't need
to have state and local governments collecting taxes from
businesses in other states.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean Andal is a member of the federal panel studying Internet
taxation. He opposes any attempt by the states to tax Internet
sales unless the seller has a substantial physical presence in the
state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 0104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3602 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KC-ECOM-2NDTAKE-KAN &LR;      11-29 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-ECOM-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIES, STATES LOBBY FOR THEIR SHARE OF INTERNET INCOME 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRAD COOPER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... the seller has a substantial physical presence in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Claims that local government will shut down if it can't tax
Internet sales are ``hysterical,'' said Andal, who serves on a
California state board that controls the state revenue department.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they got their way and they were able to start this massive
new sales (tax) compliance program...they would harm the growth of
the Internet and actually harm revenues they are getting from the
growth of the Net,'' Andal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are looking strictly at just a revenue picture, the
states are winning. There is a lot more money coming in as a result
of the Internet,'' he said. ``Those companies are hiring thousands
of people and paying good salaries.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent study conducted at the Center for Research in
Electronic Commerce at the University of Texas showed that
e-commerce has created 400,000 jobs within the past year.
Researchers surveyed 3,400 Internet companies, of which about a
third hadn't existed before 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Some studies suggest that any economic growth created by the
Internet might be choked off if Internet sales were taxed.
</P>
<P>
   Austan Goolsbee, an economics professor at the University of
Chicago, conducted his own study of 25,000 online buyers. He
concluded that imposing a sales tax on remote commerce would cut
spending by 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to taxing Internet sales is building in Congress.
Bills already have been introduced in the House and the Senate to
make permanent the temporary ban on Internet taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Republican Gov. Mike Leavitt of Utah outlined a plan
for states to phase in a voluntary, simplified e-commerce tax
system in which a ``trusted third party'' would use computer
software to calculate, collect and distribute sales taxes based on
the location of the purchaser.
</P>
<P>
   Leavitt, chairman of the National Governors' Association, will
present the proposal to the e-commerce advisory commission when it
meets in San Francisco in December.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated $170 million in taxes already is going uncollected
because of Internet sales, according to a study released last
summer by the accounting firm Ernst &AMP; Young. That figure represents
just a fraction of 1 percent of total state and local government
sales-tax collections.
</P>
<P>
   Local government leaders say they aren't as worried now as they
will be in five or six years, when Internet sales are projected to
reach between $100 billion and $200 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the current level, it may not present a significant
challenge, but I don't think you can look at it today and assume
that it's going to remain that way,'' said Overland Park Mayor Ed
Eilert. ``The correct assumption is that Internet transactions will
increase.''
</P>
<P>
   By 2003, Kansas is expected to lose about $49 million in
uncollected taxes on Internet sales, according to a report by
Shirley Sicilian, director of the Office of Policy &AMP; Research at
the state's Department of Revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Missouri is looking at estimated losses ranging as
high as $100 million by 2003, said George Rafael, director of
legislation and regulations for the Missouri Department of Revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Some have predicted that the Internet would change the face of
shopping as we know it. ``Kiss Your Mall Goodbye,'' proclaimed a
headline on the cover of a 1998 issue of Time.
</P>
<P>
   The doomsday suggestion that the Internet eventually will
replace the shopping mall couldn't have been welcome news for
cities that depend heavily on sales tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Oak Park Mall generates sales taxes for Overland Park, Kan.,
totaling about $3.9 million a year, or about 9 percent of the
city's total sales-tax collections.
</P>
<P>
   The Country Club Plaza each year generates about $20 million in
sales taxes, of which Kansas City gets between $5 million and $5.6
million, city officials estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Sales taxes from the Plaza make up 4 percent to 4.5 percent of
the $120 million that Kansas City collects in sales taxes each year
for several specific purposes such as Liberty Memorial, the Kansas
City Area Transportation Authority, capital improvements and debt
repayment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people continue to use catalog sales or Internet sales on
an increased basis, then it will affect our ability to receive tax
revenues for those kinds of programs,'' said Janice Reed, Kansas
City's finance director.
</P>
<P>
   The issue takes on added significance for some suburban
governments in the Kansas City area that get more than 25 percent
of their money from sales taxes. For example, Overland Park gets
about 46 percent of its revenue from sales taxes. Shawnee gets
about 56 percent from sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, some suburban governments depend on sales taxes,
but not to such a large extent. Independence gets about 29 percent
of its money from sales taxes. Lee's Summit collects 24 percent
from sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   At the state level, the situation isn't any better.
</P>
<P>
   Both Missouri and Kansas lean on sales taxes. This year, Kansas
took in about 40 percent of its general-fund revenue, or $1.6
billion, from sales taxes. About $1.7 billion, or 25 percent, of
Missouri's general revenue fund came from sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that revenue source is no longer there or dissipates
significantly because of Internet transactions that aren't taxable,
then where does local government go?'' asked Overland Park Mayor
Eilert.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only other taxing source that local governments have is
the property tax.''
Kansas City Star reporter Lynn Horsley and The Associated Press
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
