<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3603 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     11-29 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ He tells you he knows exactly what to
expect.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, he's telling himself, trying to convince himself that
it won't really be so bad.
</P>
<P>
   But it will. Oh, yes. It will.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind those first 14 games of Steve Francis' NBA career.
This is the night when the rookie point guard gets his real baptism
as a professional by the city _ and the country _ he spurned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever started a game at Duke's Cameron Indoor
Stadium?'' Francis asks a short, middle-aged columnist in what
might be the most ridiculous question of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I want to tell him. There was the night Michael Jordan,
James Worthy and Sam Perkins couldn't hit Tobacco Road from the
sidewalk, and I had to drop in 30 to bail out North Carolina. Or
the time when I launched an airball that Lorenzo Charles caught and
dunked, resulting in Jim Valvano's giving me a hug a midcourt.
</P>
<P>
   But his eyes are a little glassy, and Francis is staring off
into space, trying to sell himself on the notion that he has seen
and heard the worst that fans can offer. Of course, he hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those Duke students are crazy,'' Francis said. ``They're loud,
and they're all pumped up, and they never shut their mouths.
Nothing can be wilder than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not wilder, just more vicious, and shouted with much more
venom. For all of their loud reputation, the Dookies are known more
for the cleverness of their opponent-baiting. But just as the game
is different at the NBA level, here you put a deep-pocketed wise
guy in a $300 courtside seat and serve him a couple of drinks, and
the things that come out of his mouth might be enough to curl
Methuselah's hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely worried about Steve,'' said Charles Barkley.
``He doesn't know what he's in for.''
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the team, it is the second stop on the ``Friends
Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   First Scottie Pippen in Portland, and now the raft of former
Rockets _ Othella Harrington, Michael Dickerson, Brent Price and
Antoine Carr _ in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   But for Francis, it is the return to the scene of the crime. The
crime: never having made the scene after the Grizzlies took him
with the No. 2 overall selection in the NBA draft last June.
</P>
<P>
   Francis and his agent had told management he did not want to
play in Vancouver. He said it was too far away from his family in
Maryland. He said he wanted to play point guard in the NBA and
noted that the Grizzlies already had a young player at that spot in
Mike Bibby. He had made his position clear, he thought. Which
explains the look Francis wore _ that of sucking on a lemon _ when
commissioner David Stern announced his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a business decision,'' Francis said. ``Nothing personal
against anybody and nothing against the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Vancouver Province ran a large, blunt,
two-word headline: ``Head Case!''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Francis was being vilified coast-to-coast in two
countries as just another example of today's spoiled young athlete.
</P>
<P>
   So does anyone remember an All-America quarterback with a
poster-boy smile who did virtually the same thing in 1983, refusing
to play for the Baltimore Colts and engineering a trade to Denver?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to talk to John Elway about that someday,''
Francis said. ``But I guess it all eventually worked out for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what the Rockets are hoping for Francis. After 14
games, there have been flashes of athletic brilliance mixed with so
many moments of rookie bewilderment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard what they said about him right after the draft,''
said coach Rudy Tomjanovich. ``But we did our homework, we talked
to so many people, and we haven't seen signs that he's some
big-headed kid. I think he just wanted to play this position and
play someplace where he felt comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis is not Pippen, who as a free agent made a choice to join
the Rockets, signed a five-year, $82 million contract, then cut and
ran after one disappointing season.
</P>
<P>
   But just because you're a rookie, should you not use the
leverage if you have it? After all, why become the next Shareef
Abdur-Rahim, the best young player nobody knows? Why tie yourself
to a hapless franchise that hasn't had a 25-win season in four
years of existence and is in danger of being relocated to who knows
where?
</P>
<P>
   Francis is a sincere, hard-working kid who wants to be in
Houston even at 3-11 and believes he's ready to handle anything,
even this. The chants, the slurs, the personal insults.
</P>
<P>
   I'd tell him what it was like when I dumped on Larry Bird at
Boston Garden, but he'll find out soon enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
