<HEADER>
A3604 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KC-WEATH-KAN &LR;      11-29 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-WEATH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY CENTER WATCHES WEATHER OVER HALF THE PLANET FOR
AIRCRART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Knight Ridder Newspapers
KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- A three-mile-high volcano in Ecuador is spewing
a plume of ash that has drifted 78 miles. A low cloud cover
blankets a swath from the Carolinas to Florida. Low-level
turbulence over California could lead to dangerous wind shears in
canyons and passes.
</P>
<P>
   All of these weather conditions are of vital interest to any
aircraft cruising through those areas _ not to mention passengers
traveling over the peak air travel period between Thanksgiving and
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Larry Jacobs is around to warn pilots about weather
hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs sits in the Aviation Weather Center, a nondescript
concrete building surrounded by Platte County fields, not far from
Kansas City International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   But the world is at his fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   A computer monitor shows the Tungurahua volcano as a bright red
spot on a satellite mosaic of South America. Another monitor shows
thunderstorm activity over Australia and Indonesia. A bank of
screens tracks atmospheric conditions across North America and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever information we can get, we are grateful,'' Jacobs
said.
</P>
<P>
   He and other meteorologists at the Aviation Weather Center take
thousands of bits of data and weave a picture that is crucial to
pilots flying over half the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City has the National Weather Service's only center for
issuing condition alerts and warnings for American and foreign
aircraft from the Pacific to the Atlantic oceans. In March, it will
assume responsibility for the Caribbean tropics.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City also has one of two World Area Forecast System
centers that, by international agreement, divide responsibility for
the big picture of global aviation weather. The other center is
near London.
</P>
<P>
   The staff of 49 government employees at the Aviation Weather
Center work round-the-clock collecting information from satellites,
radar, weather balloons, ground stations and pilot reports.
</P>
<P>
   The meteorologists study them and issue 24-hour forecasts,
continually sending out bulletins so pilots will know about
turbulence, wind direction, icing conditions, visibility and a
range of factors that can affect a smooth and safe flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our stock in trade, providing information on hazards,''
said Fred Foss, chief of domestic operations at the center. ``If we
weren't here, then there would be no assurance to the fliers,
thence to the flying public, that some human being was constantly
looking, surveying the airspace for hazards.''
</P>
<P>
   The information is not useful just to large carriers. Private
aviators outnumber commercial aircraft by more than 10 to one and
also use the information, especially to learn about conditions that
require instrument navigation instead of visual observation.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City has had a government weather station since 1888.
Aviation forecasts became routine in the 1920s. In 1982 a national
aviation weather unit was established here.
</P>
<P>
   This year the Aviation Weather Center moved from the 17th floor
of the Bolling Federal Building downtown to the $10 million
structure it shares with the National Weather Service's training
center.
</P>
<P>
   The new building has an uninterruptible power supply and backup
generators, which already have proved necessary when a backhoe
severed a power cable. The computer screens didn't go dark.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is part of the National Weather Service, the
aviation center contributes to a system that is run by the Federal
Aviation Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Advisories and warnings from the Kansas City center are
transmitted to the 21 FAA regional control centers across the
country, such as in Olathe. From there, the pertinent portions are
radioed directly to the cockpits. The information also is sent to
the airlines' dispatching centers, which strategically manage the
movement of their fleets.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the information is available at www.awc-kc.noaa.gov on
the Internet. Various commercial outlets use the government data to
tailor products for their clients.
</P>
<P>
   Many countries provide similar services within their domestic
airspace. But regional operations are gradually being phased out as
the World Area Forecast System is consolidated into just the Kansas
City and London operations, said David Rodenhuis, director of the
Kansas City center.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from its global responsibilities, the Kansas City center
is experimenting with a project aimed at reducing delays on U.S.
flights.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA says nearly three-fourths of all flight delays in 1999
have been caused by weather. The Air Transport Association, an
industry trade group, estimates delays cost $4.5 billion in the
$775 billion commercial airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two summers, forecasters have attempted to provide
as much as six hours warning of thunderstorms. Then they
collaborate online with the FAA and with as many as a dozen private
airlines to map out a national strategy for re-routing flights and
avoiding congestion at hubs.
</P>
<P>
   Delays can be exacerbated by a projected rise in passenger
travel and an additional 2,500 aircraft in American skies by 2008.
Theoretically, greater lead-time in storm warnings, and more
cooperation between industry and government, can help air traffic
move more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is still experimental but we're trying to make it
operational,'' Rodenhuis said. ``There have been some adjustments
all along, but we're getting better at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 0107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3605 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-BILLS-FLUTIE-BOS &LR;      11-29 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BILLS-FLUTIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLUTIE WEARS HIS SUCCESS WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. _ Ex-Boston College Eagle that he is, and
always will be, Doug Flutie came to his postgame news conference
Sunday fully prepared to defend the honor of The Heights. The loss
of a friendly bet with Bills teammate Bruce Smith left Flutie in
the embarrassing position of having to wear a Virginia Tech
baseball cap to the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I'd wear it,'' said a smiling Flutie, promptly turning
the maroon Tech cap backward over his locks and topping it with,
what else, a Boston College cap. ``I just didn't say how I'd wear
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ever-creative Flutie again worked the field Sunday, much
like he did in his long-ago college days, helping to orchestrate a
17-7 win over the Patriots. Flutie tossed a pair of TD passes _ one
to top receiver Eric Moulds and another to ex-Patriot Sam Gash _
and otherwise prevented a strong New England defense from taking
away too much of the Ralph Wilson turf.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be forgotten, either, was the performance of the equally
stingy Buffalo defense. The Patriots could muster only 93 yards on
the ground (vs. 92 by the Bills) and 205 yards in the air (vs. 207
by the Bills). The difference in the score came down to the two
strikes Flutie tossed to Moulds and Gash, but it was all backed by
the grinding Buffalo defense that gave up only one big play (a Drew
Bledsoe 45-yard TD pass to Terry Glenn) all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows you to play conservatively,'' said Flutie, eager to
acknowledge his supporting defense, even if he has made a career
out of running and gunning, especially in his Canadian salad days.
``You're out there, and you know the defense is shutting 'em down.
Because the defense is playing so well, there's never really a
threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense is a rock _ it's their second shutout this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe his math is lacking some, but his touch remains much the
same. Bledsoe's TD pass to Glenn came late in the fourth quarter, a
fact that Flutie, likely along with many others in the crowd,
simply didn't factor in the final score.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie began to put away the victory with a quick-strike drive
in the closing moments of the first half. The Bills, holding a 3-0
lead, began a drive on their 42 with only 1:37 to go. He first hit
Jonathan Linton out of the backfield for a 4-yard pickup, then
connected on the next play on a 54-yard TD strike to Moulds. Two
plays, 36 seconds, game effectively finished.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Israel was in man-to-man coverage against Moulds, but
slipped just as Moulds blew past him, ultimately leaving Moulds
with open acres to haul in Flutie's relay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him get some outside release,'' said Flutie. ``Then, as
I released it, (Moulds) started to stumble a little bit. But he got
in his I've-got-to-get-it speed and went and got it. At first, I
thought, `Oh, my God, I might have overthrown it.' But he got
outside very quickly, and no way once Israel stumbled was he going
to keep up with Eric.''
</P>
<P>
   Flutie was still working with the 10-0 lead when Gash, his
trusty fullback, popped out to the right side for a familiar
play-action pass. Gash ended up trotting it in for a 31-yard TD,
after keeping just inbounds by employing a slow-rotation spin
within inches of the sideline. Solid most of the day, the New
England defense was embarrassed by the poor coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to (Gash), `You don't get your hands on it very often,
and when you do you've got to make it last,' '' said Flutie.
``Sam's one of the great leaders on this team. He keeps his mouth
shut, and does some of the real dirty work, banging up in (the
line) all the time, and he just doesn't complain about anything.
And he's also got a pair of great hands for that kind of play
action.''
</P>
<P>
   The TD strike to Gash was Flutie's 16th this season. He broke
the 200-yard plateau for the seventh time this season and has 2,536
yards through the air this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means a little more today because I know people back home
are watching,'' said Flutie, who also spent three years with the
Patriots, using most of that time wondering what in the world to do
with his talents. ``Usually, when my season ended in Canada, I'd
come back and watch their games. The Pats were my home team . . . I
know their people on the field a lot more than any other NFL team,
that's for sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
