<SLUG> BC-FBN-BILLS-GASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWARD-WINNING EFFORT BY GASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. _ Every Monday, the Bills hand out a weekly
award, for which there is no silver-plated bowl, lacquered plaque,
or even so much as a US Savings Bond. The Sam Gash Award is
presented to the Bill who plays with the most grit, determination
and 60-minute selflessness, usually between the hours of 1-4 p.m.
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Gash, who regularly did all of that during his six years with
the Patriots, played with his usual thump and bump in the Bills'
impressive 17-7 win here Sunday over New England. The wide-bodied
fullback did his usual job of playing can opener for the Bills'
running backs, but he also hauled in a career-best 31-yard
touchdown pass from Doug Flutie to help send his ex-teammates
reeling out of Ralph Wilson Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game you win is a big win,'' said the ever-humble Gash,
who showed up at the postgame podium in his standard steel-toed
work boots and rugged-wear jeans, looking more longshoreman than
million-dollar battering ram. ``But (when playing New England),
yeah, I have a lot of personal feelings that I don't care much
about. I've still got a lot of good friends over there, guys I
played with and everything . . . but as far as the team and the
organization, I'm just not a big fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Beloved by his teammates during his six years in Foxborough, the
now 30-year-old Gash departed as a free agent after the '97 season.
It was Pete Carroll's first year in charge on the New England
sideline and it was also the season Gash was building himself back
from the knee injury that ended his '96 season _ relegating him to
crutches and sideline cheerleading when the Patriots went on to the
Super Bowl in January of '97.
</P>
<P>
   Here in hard-hat Western New York, the 240-pound Gash is equally
embraced by his teammates. Come this morning, coach Wade Phillips
will call his charges together and give out The Gash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like in fun,'' said Gash, sounding slightly
embarrassed by it all, undoubtedly realizing such awards typically
are handed out in the names of players past, not present. ``I guess
it's given out to guys who play hard and who are unheralded. I
don't know much about it really other than, you know, I get it
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought he might be presented his own award Monday,
Gash smiled somewhat sheepishly and said, ``I might be in the
running.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Scott Berchtold, the club's vice president of
communications, Phillips has presented the award both seasons that
Gash has been with the Bills. The award presentation is, like Gash,
made with little fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys circle around, Coach names who it is, and the guys
stand and applaud,'' said Berchtold. ``That's about it . . . and
Sam's usually the guy who wins it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gash was somewhat out of character when he hauled in his second
TD pass of the season. Rather than boring into the New England
line, creating space for running backs Antowain Smith or Jonathan
Linton, he popped out toward the right sideline on a play-action
pass with a little less than five minutes gone in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a play we've seen a lot,'' said Phillips. ``But evidently
(New England) hadn't seen it. They were defending the run and it
kind of caught everyone in there a little bit. And I know now
everyone is going to be saying, `Why don't you run Sam more?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gash as a running back was a topic of conversation during the
week. The Bills' No. 1 runner, Smith (nine carries, 21 yards
Sunday) was limping around with a turf toe suffered two weeks
earlier. But Phillips was adamant that he wanted to keep Gash at
fullback and stick with a rotation of Smith and Linton (17 carries,
67 yards).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our best blocker, but he's not our best ball-carrier,''
Phillips had said about Gash. ``We wouldn't have a lead blocker,
and that's his position. In my expert opinion, he's not a featured
ball carrier, expect maybe for high school. What he does here is
block, and slip out sometimes and catch a pass.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just what Gash did when the Bills stood, first and 10, at
the New England 31. Flutie connected with him at the 18 and Gash,
eluding the likes of Andy Katzenmoyer and Chris Carter, made a slow
spinning move at the sideline, a square dancer suddenly slipping
into ballet slippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'd call that a Barry Sanders move,'' said
Linton, amused at the comparison made by someone in the postgame
crowd. ``That was more like Barry Word, maybe. Hey, he's a great
player, it couldn't happen to a better guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gash, no surprise, wasn't the least bit boastful about the poor
man's pirouette.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I'd pull out an old spin move from high school,'' he
said, after first crediting wide receiver Andre Reed with a clean
pick to open up the passing possibility. ``So, I just spun as slow
as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in turn, screwed the Patriots a little deeper into the
turf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
