<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE NO MISTAKE, BILLS' STRATEGY WORKED
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By WILL MCDONOUGH 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. _ The Buffalo mind-set was this: If we don't
screw it up, they won't beat us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been killing ourselves with mistakes,'' said Bills
general manager John Butler outside his team's locker room an hour
before kickoff Sunday. ``We've done some foolish things, made some
stupid mistakes at the wrong time. We can't keep doing that and
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Patriots, the Bills weren't playing
giveaway Sunday. They played a solid ``team'' game, and converted
big plays at critical times, something the Patriots could not do on
either side of the ball during a 17-7 Buffalo victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought our defense would do a good job,'' said Bills
offensive coordinator Joe Pendry after the game. ``We didn't want
to turn the ball over and give them good field position. We wanted
to stay patient, we wanted to be efficient, and we did that. Both
sides did the job. We got enough on offense, and our defense played
a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' defensive game plan surprised Pendry and Doug
Flutie in the first half. ``We knew they would play some
eight-man-up stuff on defense, but not as much as they did,'' said
Pendry. ``They were determined to stop our run, and in the first
half they did.''
</P>
<P>
   It was very windy in Ralph Wilson Stadium. ``This is a day you
run the ball here,'' said Bills former All-Pro guard, Reggie
McKenzie, before the game. ``It will be tough to throw the ball
consistently with the wind like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had a similar strategy. Throw short, try to establish
the run. The irony of the first half was that Buffalo was
outrushed, 75-11, when it was supposed to be the superior running
team, and still led, 10-0, at the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference in the game,'' said Buffalo linebacker John
Holecek, ``is that we made two big plays on defense when they were
driving the ball in our territory. We got the interception, and
then stopped them inside our 10 when we (forced a) fumble. They
were driving the ball on us, and we didn't think they could do that
to us. They had us a little off-balance. In the second half, we
made some adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo went ahead, 3-0, in the first period when a very
generous pass interference call went against the Patriots' Chris
Carter at the New England 8, a penalty that cost the Patriots 42
yards and resulted in a 28-yard field goal by Steve Christie.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, the Patriots had the ball 10 of the first
13 minutes and couldn't do anything with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we hit that touchdown pass to Eric Moulds, we had only
eight offensive plays in that period,'' said Pendry. ``We (the
defense) couldn't seem to get the ball back. They were driving it
and holding it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bills, who were being outplayed, got the ball back at their
42 with 1:37 left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the wind that period and weren't doing anything with
it,'' said Pendry. ``I asked Doug before the game if the wind was
going to bother him and he said no. So we took the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   On second and 6 from his 46, with 1:09 to play, Flutie went into
a no-back backfield. He stood in the shotgun, alone, with five
receivers spread across the field. ``They blitzed us,'' said
Pendry. ``So we knew we had man coverage. Doug saw it coming and
threw it to Eric.''
</P>
<P>
   Moulds was shoulder-to-shoulder with Steve Israel racing down
the field, but Israel fell down, and Moulds was all alone to gather
in the Flutie floater and run for the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriots gave us a few plays we hadn't seen from them
before,'' said Buffalo defensive coordinator Ted Cottrell. ``So we
made some adjustments at the half.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo went ahead, 17-0, early in the third, virtually putting
the game away when Sam Gash caught a 31-yard touchdown pass from
Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they were playing so many men on the line to stop our
run,'' said Pendry, ``play-action passes became our biggest weapon.
On the one to Sam (Gash), he released out of our backfield and
their linebacker couldn't stay with him. That type of play worked
well for us. We froze the linebackers and Doug did a good job of
getting it to the right guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Flutie was an efficient 5 for 6 passing in the first half. He
was 9 for 16 in the game, averaging more than 11 yards per attempt,
which is extremely high. Most of his throws were for 10 yards or
fewer, and they dinked and dunked their way down the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our coverage was excellent,'' said Cottrell. ``We covered
their guys. We made Drew (Bledsoe) hold the ball, and this gave our
rush a chance to get to him. We didn't blitz him as much as the
Jets and Miami did, but our front four did a great job of getting
to him. But they had time because of the coverage we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was sacked six times, Flutie once. Bledsoe had one
interception, Flutie had none. Flutie had guys open. For the most
part, Bledsoe did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't upset that we didn't get the shutout,'' said
Cottrell. ``They only scored 7, and that came late in the fourth
period. They made a great play, and we didn't. I said to
(cornerback) Thomas (Smith) after their touchdown, `Which way is
the wind blowing?' He rolled his eyes up a little bit, and he said,
`Oh, I forget Coach.' It was into the wind. Before the game I
cautioned our guys about underthrown balls into the wind, and to be
careful, and that's what happened. But we didn't come for the
shutout. We came for the win, and that's all that mattered.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 0112EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
