<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UMASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINUTEMEN ENJOY CLOSE ENCOUNTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Nothing exceeds a national championship,
particularly when you win it after coming off a 2-9 campaign, your
school's worst finish this century. Following that up with a share
of your league title this season, after a 1-3 start, is impressive,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, if you want more proof of the unprecedented success the
University of Massachusetts football team has had under second-year
coach Mark Whipple, consider this: The Minutemen have played 27
games under Whipple (22 regular season, five postseason), and in
each contest, they have entered the fourth quarter with a chance to
win.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Hofstra led UMass, 27-7, entering the fourth, and
went on to win, 27-14. That has been the toughest hill the
Minutemen have had to climb since Whipple took over.
</P>
<P>
   Even Division 1 Toledo couldn't stage a rout, leading 17-3
entering the fourth before winning, 24-3. The Minutemen's other
loss this season was a 26-21 decision to Villanova, in which UMass
failed to score deep in Wildcat territory as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, they suffered a 33-30 loss at Delaware (which led,
26-23, entering the fourth), a 44-41 overtime defeat to Connecticut
(which trailed, 41-34) in Storrs, and a 28-27 setback to UConn in
Amherst (with the score tied at 21).
</P>
<P>
   So it wasn't surprising that the defending Division 1-AA
national champions would enter overtime in Saturday's first-round
playoff game against Furman more composed than their host. Entering
the fourth quarter, UMass led, 23-20.
</P>
<P>
   The 10th-seeded Minutemen went on to beat the seventh seed,
30-23, in overtime on a Marcel Shipp 1-yard run and a solid
defensive stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably the best time I've had playing football, and
I just thank God I had the opportunity to play in it,'' said UMass
quarterback Todd Bankhead. ``I'm just glad to have the opportunity
to continue playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering the game, UMass was 10-3 in contests in which it
entered the fourth quarter either tied, trailing by 7 points or
fewer, or leading by 7 or fewer during Whipple's tenure. That
included a 3-0 mark this year.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the Minutemen entered the fourth having withstood
Furman's explosive offense and hard-hitting defense.
</P>
<P>
   Furman entered the contest having outscored its opponents,
118-34, in the first quarter, and 109-35 in the fourth. Saturday,
at a venue where the hosts had lost just once all year (in their
season opener), the teams were tied, 7-7, after the first, and
Furman outscored UMass, 3-0, in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   When Furman kicker Jason Wells missed a 37-yard field goal with
12 seconds left, the Paladins blew a big opportunity to win.
</P>
<P>
   It took UMass four plays to score in overtime, the drive capped
by a 1-yard run by Shipp, who fumbled while heading into the end
zone in the third period. ``We knew what we had to do in the
overtime,'' said Shipp. ``We just stepped it up and won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Furman then started its drive at the UMass 25, and ended its
season at the 35, having lost 4 yards on a rush, 6 on a sack, and
having thrown two incompletions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our seniors just showed up,'' said UMass junior linebacker
Kole Ayi. ``First play of overtime they try to run a quick toss and
(senior linebacker) Matt Dawson makes a play. Second play, (senior
defensive tackle) Aaron Parker makes a sack. You could tell they
didn't want the game to end.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Minutemen face a Georgia Southern team that beat
Northern Arizona, 72-29, Saturday, in what will be a rematch of
last year's national title game.
</P>
<P>
   Surely Georgia Southern, which can score, knows all about
UMass's ability to put a close game away after three periods. Last
year, UMass led Georgia Southern, 38-33, entering the fourth. The
Minutemen won, 55-43.
</P>
</TEXT>
