<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOWL A BUILDING BLOCK FOR BC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Now that Boston College has completed its regular
season, the Eagles can talk about the postseason. The first salvo
will come Monday when they will hold a press conference to announce
their acceptance of a berth in the Insight.Com Bowl in Tucson Dec.
31.
</P>
<P>
   For the Eagles, it is a quantum leap from a year ago, when they
were finishing their second consecutive 4-7 season.
</P>
<P>
   The difference this season, which ended with Friday's 38-14 loss
to Virginia Tech, is that an 8-3 record can be the foundation for a
program.
</P>
<P>
   So can a bowl game. The Insight.Com Bowl is a nice first step in
the reconstruction job that Eagles coach Tom O'Brien undertook when
he arrived at The Heights three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As O'Brien said after Friday's loss, ``Three years ago, we were
in the headlines for all the wrong reasons; this week we were in
the headlines for all the right reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowl games are recruiting tools for coaches. They provide
exposure on television, extra practice time in December, not to
mention the financial advantages for the conference and school.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College's opponent has yet to be determined and probably
will not be officially named until after Saturday's Big 12
championship game between Nebraska and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Once the champion is decided, the other Big 12 bowl commitments
can be locked up.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, it is either 7-4 Oklahoma or 6-5 Colorado. Strictly
by the numbers, Oklahoma would be the choice. But bowl pairings are
not based on numbers, at least not wins and losses.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado beat Oklahoma in the regular season, which is a factor
in its favor. The other plus for Colorado is fan support.
</P>
<P>
   Word has spread to the offices of the Insight.Com Bowl and the
Independence Bowl in Shreveport, La., that Oklahoma, enjoying a
resurgence under first-year coach Bobby Stoops, will be happy to go
to any bowl and bring fans to either venue.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado fans, however, are more picky, and may pass up the
chance to celebrate the millennium in Shreveport. Tucson? That
might work, and that is very much a factor when bowls issue
invitations.
</P>
<P>
   Some sort of decision, or preference list, will be put together
by the Insight.Com Bowl committee at a meeting Monday, but right
now the tilt is toward Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   It does not matter. BC is ready for the next level, which is
contending for the Big East title. Another recruiting class like
this season's and the Eagles will be a prime-time team in a
conference that is coming to life.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is O'Brien. He has done a solid job turning the
Eagles in the right direction. In the next few weeks, he will be
rewarded for that with another contract extension. Don't be
surprised if BC officials come up with creative ways to also extend
O'Brien's financial package, such as a funded annuity, which will
guarantee O'Brien a large package if he makes a long-term
commitment to BC.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame's last-second loss to Stanford was what Irish fans
feared. It was the first time since 1960 that the Irish have seven
losses in a season. Under three years of coach Bob Davie, Notre
Dame has lost 16 games. Only Joe Kuharich, who lost 18 games in his
first three years in South Bend, had a worse start. And it marked
the first four-loss November for the Irish since the ill-fated
Gerry Faust team lost four in 1983 . . . Nebraska's 33-30 overtime
victory over Colorado Friday may have kept the Huskers technically
alive for a spot in the BCS Championship game in the Sugar Bowl in
New Orleans Jan. 4, but the Huskers have almost no chance to catch
No. 2 Virginia Tech in the rankings, and they know it. ``By now
it's probably Florida State and Virginia Tech,'' said Nebraska
linebacker Tony Ortiz. ``Our focus right now is the Big 12
championship game.'' . . . Hawaii's Cinderella season finally hit a
speed bump when the Rainbows lost to Washington State. Still, it is
going to a bowl game against Oregon State in Honolulu Christmas Day
. . . Has any team started out with such high hopes as Arizona _
which was a consensus Top 5 pick at the start of the season _ but
never recovered from an opening-game pounding by Penn State? The
Wildcats ended their dreary season with a 42-27 loss to Arizona
State, finishing 6-6.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The University of Massachusetts's 30-23 overtime win over Furman
Saturday was one of the best games played on any level of college
football this season and shows how exciting a playoff system can be
when the stakes are that high and the quality of play is that good
. . . Despite losses by Arkansas and Texas, the Cotton Bowl is
still hoping for that matchup in its Jan. 1 game . . . Joe
Hamilton's four-touchdown effort in a 50-47 win over Georgia
Saturday keeps alive his slim chances of stealing the Heisman
Trophy from Wisconsin's Ron Dayne. But the loss to Wake Forest last
week probably doomed Hamilton, since many Heisman voters already
had sent in their votes . . . In three weeks, Penn State went from
a contender for the national championship to a three-loss team that
probably will face Texas A&AMP;M in the Alamo Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
