<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Monday,
Nov. 29. If you have any questions, please call Kevin Catalano on
the Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
KC-WEATH -- A three-mile-high volcano in Ecuador is spewing a plume
of ash that has drifted 78 miles. A low cloud cover blankets a
swath from the Carolinas to Florida. Low-level turbulence over
California could lead to dangerous wind shears in canyons and
passes.
</P>
<P>
   All of these weather conditions are of vital interest to any
aircraft cruising through those areas _ not to mention passengers
traveling over the peak air travel period between Thanksgiving and
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Larry Jacobs is around to warn pilots about weather
hazards.
By MATT CAMPBELL. Moved.
</P>
<P>
   KC-ECOM -- Almost every day, thousands of people plop down in
front of their home computers to buy everything from groceries to
books to cars.
</P>
<P>
   They shop without the hassle of leaving home, battling traffic
or fighting crowds. Just a few keystrokes and the merchandise is
theirs. No clerks. No lines. And, often, no sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   But what is a break for consumers now may mean tax increases for
them in the future, say city and state officials across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, consumers save on sales tax when they buy
over the Internet from a company not in their state.
</P>
<P>
   In the long term, state and municipal leaders are afraid they
will lose tax revenue to Internet sales, forcing them to raise
other taxes to offset those losses.
By BRAD COOPER. Moved.
</P>
<P>
   KC-SLUM -- Nearly two years ago, Kansas City launched a
``slumlord of the month'' installment on its government TV channel,
in hopes of shaming problem landlords into cleaning up their rental
properties.
</P>
<P>
   It did not work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It withered on the vine. It didn't have any real teeth to it,
if you're not hitting them in their pocketbooks. Some of them even
considered it a badge of honor,'' said Nanci Regan, neighborhood
development supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   So now, prodded by exasperated homeowners, Kansas City officials
are preparing to recommend to the City Council a more comprehensive
get-tough approach.
</P>
<P>
   Strategies will include a ``landlords school'' similar to school
for drunken drivers; intensive probation and community service;
civil court action to gain more control over the properties; and
lobbying for higher fines and more jail time.
By LYNN HORSLEY. Moved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
