<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-SHARKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS AND SHARKS TIE, 3-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By KEN GURNICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Jason Arnott's breakaway goal with 4:48 left
in the third period had given the New Jersey Devils a 3-2 lead just
after they had killed a hooking penalty on Arnott. He was set up by
the rookie Scott Gomez and beat goaltender Steve Shields.
</P>
<P>
   But San Jose's Owen Nolan tied the game again when he scored a
short-handed goal with 2:05 remaining, his 15th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   So ended a trip on which Bobby Holik was suspended, defenseman
Lyle Odelein was scratched twice and talked about leaving the
Devils and Denis Pederson was sidelined indefinitely with an
injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, in the midst of 6 games in 11 days, play six of
their next seven at home, where they are 8-1-2. Holik must sit out
one more game, on Wednesday against the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Sharks, the Devils scored 3:51 into the game on a
goal that should not have been allowed. Television replays showed
that the Devils' Claude Lemieux redirected Jason Arnott's pass with
his right skate past Shields, but the officials ruled it a goal.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose countered five minutes later when Marco Sturm's shot
glanced into the net off goaltender Martin Brodeur, who was down on
the ice and trying to scramble back in front of the goal.
</P>
<P>
   The first period included a pair of fights between the Devils'
Krzysztof Oliwa and San Jose's Brantt Myhres. They were ejected
after the rematch.
</P>
<P>
   The teams traded goals in the second period, Niklas Sundstrom
scoring for San Jose at 1:27 and Vadim Sharifijanov tying the game
for the Devils at 12:12.
</P>
<P>
   Off the ice, Holik served the second game of his suspension,
while Odelein was a healthy scratch for the second time in a week
and said he would talk to General Manager Lou Lamoriello because
``maybe it's time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Odelein had not been a healthy scratch since his rookie season
with Montreal in 1990-91 until Wednesday night, when Coach Robbie
Ftorek held him out of the Devils' 2-1 victory in Anaheim. He
started Thursday night and played almost 10 minutes in a 4-2 loss
in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely hurts to get scratched for the first time, and
now the second time,'' said Odelein, who can become a free agent
after the season. ``I thought I had a good game in Phoenix. Maybe I
have some anger, but I've got a lot of pride and I'm not going to
sit back and take it. Maybe it's time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Robbie's the coach, and I'm not going to question him,''
Odelein, 31, said. ``I know I can play and be valuable to somebody
in the league, that's for sure. I'm not going to cause problems on
this team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
