<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAT, EAT, EAT AND BE MERRY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ We must look silly to most of the rest of the
world. For the next month, our biggest worry in America, judging
from reports in the media, is that we will eat too much.
<P>
   In many countries, when the typical large family gathers for the
holiday feast, in the center of the table is a roasted and stuffed
grasshopper. Dad and the kids argue over who will get the green
meat.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not condemning our holiday gluttony. Au contraire, I'm
condemning our response to that gluttony, which is to express shame
and self-loathing, emotions that can sometimes ruin your appetite.
</P>
<P>
   Shut up and go for it. If the world ends on New Year's Eve, you
will regret every slice of pie you dismissed with that smug,
self-righteous wave. It's not like you're up for the role of lead
skeleton babe in that new Hollywood sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   Gluttony is its own reward, but as frosting on the cake, I'm
sponsoring a contest to see who can gain the most weight between
Thanksgiving and New Year's Day. A few tips:
</P>
<P>
   -- Steal a concept from the diet gurus, who recommend eating
several small meals per day. Eat several large meals per day. Or
one continuous meal.
</P>
<P>
   -- Avoid ``calorie-deficient'' foods. Pick the celery bits out
of your turkey dressing and feed 'em to the dog. Instead of pouring
gravy over your mashed potatoes and turkey, eliminate the mashed
potatoes and turkey. Try my new concept, ``reverse liposuction.''
 &UR; Waiter, bring us the jumbo gravy tureen and six &LR; 
 &UR; straws, please! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -- Avoid strenuous exercise. You could pull a groin muscle and
wind up in the hospital, where the food is not conducive to
gluttony. Avoid even minimal exercise, by using your brain. To
prevent having to burn calories by rummaging around for the
misplaced TV remote, I wear mine on a gold chain around my neck.
Stylish  &UR; and  &LR; functional.
</P>
<P>
   Send your total weight gain and tales of gluttony to me. Winner
receives dinner for two at a nice San Francisco restaurant, plus a
dinner for your companion.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S TOO EARLY to panic, but Jack the veteran cabbie scoffs at
San Francisco's plan to put 250 extra cabs on the street for New
Year's Eve. He says there's not that many extra cabs available, and
many drivers are going to stay home rather than drive through the
century's biggest party.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be lucky to get half the regular fleet onto the
street,'' Jack says.
</P>
<P>
   So go ahead and party, just don't plan to go home for a couple
of days.
</P>
<P>
   SOME OF LIFE'S great questions go unanswered, so I am patenting
the Kiddie's Counter, a small handheld computer chip device for
tots.
</P>
<P>
   Mom: ``How many times have I told you to pick up your dirty
clothes?''
</P>
<P>
   Tot (after punching in relevant data): ``Seven.''
</P>
<P>
   IN LOS ANGELES over the weekend, they had another long-distance
freeway chase of a crazy guy, telecast live on several stations via
news-copter cams. The cops finally disabled the car with spike
strips, and when the guy got out of the car and brandished a gun,
the cops shot him full of holes.
</P>
<P>
   If L.A. stations keep showing these spectacles, they're going to
have to come up with a new term to replace ``live TV coverage.''
You can't have live death.
</P>
<P>
   Last time one of these chases was telecast, the public expressed
outrage that such a grisly event would take over TV programming.
Station managers vowed that next time they would at least put the
telecast on seven-second delay, in case something gory happened.
</P>
<P>
   They lied. Several L.A. stations and two San Diego stations
carried it all live, including the grand finale. The acting manager
of a San Diego station said, ``As soon as we saw he had the gun, we
widened out.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, no close-ups of bullets ripping through flesh on that TV
station.
</P>
<P>
   I worry that they're going soft down in So Cal.
</P>
<P>
   A HOMELESS MAN pushed a massively loaded shopping cart along
Linden Street in Hayes Valley. A couple of hours later, the man was
gone, his cart was tipped over and the belongings strewn all over
the street. Atop one pile of the man's stuff was a booklet,
``Homeless Solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Clint Reilly's booklet paid off for this guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``NOW HIRING,'' says the sign in the window of the FaultLine
Brewery, opening soon at Fillmore and Chestnut in the Marina. Lou
Bristol peeked in the window and saw a pair of boxing gloves on the
table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Must be a tough job interview,'' says Lou.
</P>
<P>
   THE LADY on the TV news report was 117 years old, although she
could pass for 100. I didn't get her name, but she lives in Merced.
</P>
<P>
   As on any media report of an amazingly old person, the woman was
asked the secret of her longevity. Why do we always ask that? Why
not ask, ``What were the Wright Brothers really like?'' Or, ``Do
think we've screwed up the century?'' Or, ``Before TV, what did you
sit around and stare at?'' Or, ``Want to ride a really cool roller
coaster?''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the woman said that every day when she wakes up, she has
a cup of coffee, a sip of whiskey and a Twinkie, then she goes back
to bed.
</P>
<P>
   What the hell, I'm willing to give it a try.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 0335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
