<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 03:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3658 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-WTO-SEATTLE-SFCHRON &LR;      11-29 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-SEATTLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SEATTLE FEARS EXPLOSION OF WTO PROTESTS  &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ From City Hall to the trendy stores and boutiques
downtown, this city's movers and shakers are wondering whether the
summit meeting of the World Trade Organization this week is going
to be one big, bad headache.
</P>
<P>
   With huge protests Tuesday expected to be rowdy and rumors of
violence growing louder, politicians and business leaders fear that
the city's image _ which has been burnished in recent years as a
hip, happening place for software-writing, latte-sipping young
professionals _ will become synonymous with riots and tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   Even protest organizers, who clearly are having the time of
their lives preparing for what they call ``a festival of democracy
in the streets,'' worry that things may get out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of the protesters _ ranging from union members
to environmentalists _ are expected to be peaceful. But small
radical fringe groups are planning violence, organizers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hear (the rumors), you kind of ask, `Whose bright
idea was it to have the WTO here?' '' said Chai Mann, president of
Fox's Gem Shop on Fifth Avenue in Seattle's downtown, which will be
Ground Zero in tomorrow's demonstrations. ``WTO is the antithesis
of what we want for business.''
</P>
<P>
   Many stores in the area are expected to close all day Tuesday
and board up their windows.
</P>
<P>
   A front-page headline in the Seattle Times summed up the growing
paranoia: ``WTO _ Whose Idea Was This?'' The article went on to
warn of ``terrorist attacks'' _ without explaining further.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, a trial run of the protests went off peaceably. About
1,000 people marched through downtown, pausing before chain stores
that they call symbols of WTO-style corporate power _ Gap and
Starbucks, among others. The scene was festive. Dancing
stilt-walkers wore monarch butterfly costumes (to symbolize claims
that butterflies are being killed by genetically engineered corn).
Giant puppets of corporate executives such as Gap board chairman
Donald Fisher also joined in.
</P>
<P>
   But things will get much more serious Tuesday, at least for some
people.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the AFL-CIO's nervousness about being associated
publicly with law-breaking young demonstrators, the unions are
closing their protest march _ about 30,000 union members from
across the country are expected _ to other participants.
</P>
<P>
   The others, most of whom are loosely organized as an alliance
called Direct Action Network, will be marching separately.
Organizers say that demonstrators intend to lie down in streets or
lock themselves to police barriers or one another. They have two
goals: preventing delegates from entering the downtown convention
center for the start of the WTO talks, and getting hundreds
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Direct Action Network, whose leaders are veterans of protests
against old-growth logging in California and British Columbia, has
repeatedly stressed the importance of nonviolence.
</P>
<P>
   It's a nonviolent scene but a chaotic _ and fun _ one at the
network's base camp, ``The Convergence,'' a large former nightclub
and adjacent garage a mile from downtown in the bohemian Capitol
Hill neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of dreadlocks, pierced noses and lips and
eyebrows. There's a wildly painted hippie bus that looks like it
came from the Ken Kesey collection, and a stretch limousine with a
mock Cruise missile on the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, classes are given to the hundreds of people wandering
around. There's a nonviolence class, a legal class _ that's what to
do when you're in jail _ a puppet-making class, and others.
</P>
<P>
   At the nonviolence class, about 100 young folks listen intently
as two veterans of Humboldt County timber wars give them the
rundown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defusing anger is the most important thing,'' they are told.
``You have to recognize the humanity in the cops, show that you
realize they're human. Make eye contact.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many more detailed instructions, in a remarkably
professional lesson on the science of nonviolent protest.
</P>
<P>
   There's also role-playing, with the class divided into
pepper-spraying, violent cops and peaceable protesters. Instructors
explain what a pain hold is. Why not to wear jewelry (especially
those nose and lip rings, which make a mess of you if a cop yanks
on them). How to breathe through tear gas. Why to scream loudly
whenever a cop touches you, whether or not it really hurts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have anything like this in England,'' said one
participant, a diminutive woman named Fiona, from Brighton. ``We
just do protests, but we never get taught this. It's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   But organizers say that small Seattle anarchist groups have
rebelled against the network's nonviolent philosophy and are
planning violence. What sort, they don't know yet.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the potential for things to go wrong, Seattle Mayor Paul
Schell bristles when people raise the specter of the 1968
Democratic National Convention in Chicago, where Mayor Richard
Daley ordered police to take violent action against anti-war
demonstrators. Or of the recent uproar when New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani threatened to evict the Brooklyn Museum because an art
exhibit offended his Catholic sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no Mayor Daley, and I'm no Mayor Giuliani,'' Schell said.
``I'm confident we will not overreact.'`
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
