<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 5)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This collection of paperbacks is from the columns since the 1999
Summer Reading special.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMERICAN VISIONS: The Epic History of Art in America &LR;  By Robert
Hughes. Knopf, $39.95. A witty, impassioned survey by the
Australian critic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMSTERDAM &LR;  By Ian McEwan. Anchor, $12. A nasty satire about two
self-important Londoners.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AT THE OWL WOMAN SALOON: STORIES &LR;  By Tess Gallagher. Scribner,
$12. Blue-collar fiction set in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BECH AT BAY: A Quasi-Novel &LR;  By John Updike. Fawcett/Ballantine,
$12. The continuing adventures of the Jewish anti-Updike.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIG GIRLS DON'T CRY &LR;  By Fay Weldon. Atlantic Monthly, $13. A
wry novel about a group of women in 1970s London.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIRDS OF AMERICA &LR;  By Lorrie Moore. Picador USA, $14. Fluid,
mordant tales of articulate characters in crisis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BLINDNESS &LR;  By Jose Saramago. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $14. A
rich allegorical novel about a plague of blindness.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRAIN STORM &LR;  By Richard Dooling. Picador USA, $14. A clever
thriller about a lawyer and a brain researcher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BREAKFAST ON PLUTO &LR;  By Patrick McCabe. HarperPerennial, $13.
Macabre fiction about an Irish transvestite in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CINDERELLA &AMP; COMPANY: Backstage at the Opera With Cecilia
Bartoli &LR;  By Manuela Hoelterhoff. Vintage, $14. A naughtily witty
look at the modern opera industry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITIES OF THE PLAIN: Volume 3, ``The Border Trilogy'' &LR;  By
Cormac McCarthy. Vintage International, $13. The concluding volume
of the author's cowboy saga.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLD NEW WORLD: Growing Up in a Harder Country &LR;  By William
Finnegan. Modern Library, $14.95. Four bleak portraits of young
people adrift in society.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLLECTED FICTIONS &LR;  By Jorge Luis Borges. Penguin, $16.95. A
collection of the Argentine writer's jewel-like stories.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEATH IN SUMMER &LR;  By William Trevor. Penguin, $12.95. Dark
fiction about a widowed man whose infant child is abducted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DREAMLAND: Travels Inside the Secret World of Roswell and Area
51 &LR;  By Phil Patton. Villard, $12.95. An offbeat history of the
flying-saucer subculture.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EAT THE RICH &LR;  By P.J. O'Rourke. Atlantic Monthly, $13. A
political satirist's lively tour of the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUCALYPTUS &LR;  By Murray Bail. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $13. A
magical novel about an Australian homesteader.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EVENING &LR;  By Susan Minot. Vintage Contemporaries, $12. Elegiac
fiction about a woman looking back on her life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE EVOLUTION OF JANE &LR;  By Cathleen Schine. Plume, $12.95. A
Darwinian novel whose heroine visits the Galapagos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FARMING OF BONES &LR;  By Edwidge Danticat. Penguin, $12.95.
Sobering fiction about strife on Hispaniola in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FASHIONABLE NONSENSE: Postmodern Intellectuals' Abuse of
Science &LR;  By Alan Sokal and Jean Bricmont. Picador USA, $14. Two
physicists tackle a form of intellectual quackery.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GIANT, O'BRIEN &LR;  by Hilary Mantel. Marian Wood/Owl/Holt,
$12. Historical fiction about a huge Irishman and a scientist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GIRL IN THE FLAMMABLE SKIRT: Stories &LR;  By Aimee Bender.
Anchor, $11.95. Insouciant tales featuring unhappily single
heroines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOD OF THE RODEO: The Quest for Redemption in Louisiana's
Angola Prison &LR;  By Daniel Bergner. Ballantine, $13.95. A prison
rodeo as a window into a living purgatory.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GRAND CENTRAL WINTER: Stories From the Street &LR;  By Lee Stringer.
Washington Square/Pocket Books, $12.95. A memoir of life in the
underbelly of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HEART OF THE ANTARCTIC: Being the Story of the British
Antarctic Expedition, 1907-1909 &LR;  By Ernest Shackleton. Carroll &AMP;
Graf, $16.95. A poignant chronicle of the explorer's journey in
search of the south magnetic pole.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; I MARRIED A COMMUNIST &LR;  By Philip Roth. Vintage International,
$13. Unnerving fiction about the rise and fall of an angry Jewish
radical during the McCarthy era.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; I WILL BEAR WITNESS: A Diary of the Nazi Years, 1933-1941 &LR;  By
Victor Klemperer. Modern Library, $14.95. A German professor's
insider account of the Nazi years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KAATERSKILL FALLS &LR;  By Allegra Goodman. Delta, $12.95. A
panoramic first novel about Orthodox Jewish life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KING LEOPOLD'S GHOST: A Story of Greed, Terror, and Heroism in
Colonial Africa &LR;  By Adam Hochschild. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $15.
Belgian mayhem in central Africa from 1885 to 1908.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KING OF THE WORLD: Muhammad Ali and the Rise of an American
Hero &LR;  By David Remnick. Vintage, $13. A skillful blend of athletic
and political history.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEGENDS OF THE AMERICAN DESERT: Sojourns in the Greater
Southwest &LR;  By Alex Shoumatoff. HarperPerennial, $15. Romping
through a vast region's history and cultures.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFE: A Natural History of the First Four Billion Years of Life
on Earth &LR;  By Richard Fortey. Vintage, $15. A paleontologist's
eclectic waltz among the facts of life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LINDBERGH &LR;  By A. Scott Berg. Berkley, $16. A Pulitzer
Prize-winning study of Charles Lindbergh.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LOVE OF A GOOD WOMAN: Stories &LR;  By Alice Munro. Vintage
Contemporaries, $13. Eight tales of women who come of age in the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOVE UNDETECTABLE: Notes on Friendship, Sex, and Survival &LR;  By
Andrew Sullivan. Vintage, $13. Reflections on the end of AIDS as a
death sentence.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A MAN IN FULL &LR;  By Tom Wolfe. Bantam, $8.50. A zestful,
sprawling novel about an Atlanta mogul.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MASTER GEORGIE &LR;  By Beryl Bainbridge. Carroll &AMP; Graf, $11.95.
Historical fiction about a British surgeon and his circle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MEADOWLANDS: Wilderness Adventures at the Edge of a City &LR; 
By Robert Sullivan. Anchor, $12.95. A bold look at New Jersey's
unloved swamplands.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MISTLER'S EXIT &LR;  By Louis Begley. Fawcett/Ballantine, $12. Grim
fiction about the delusions of a terminally ill man.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOMMY DRESSING: A Love Story, After a Fashion &LR;  By Lois Gould.
Anchor, $12.95. A memoir by the daughter of a famous dress
designer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MY DOG TULIP &LR;  By J.R. Ackerley. New York Review, $12.95. A
British writer reflects on life with an elegant friend.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE NEWTON LETTER &LR;  By John Banville. Godine, $10.95. A powerful
novella with lots to say about history.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NO LEASE ON LIFE &LR;  By Lynne Tillman. Harvest/Harcourt Brace,
$12. Fiction about a New York woman's violent fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE NURTURE ASSUMPTION: Why Children Turn Out the Way They Do &LR; 
By Judith Rich Harris. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $15. A
provocative theory that children are shaped more by temperament and
peers than by parents.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPENED GROUND: Selected Poems, 1966-1996 &LR;  By Seamus Heaney.
Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $15. A generous selection of verse by the
Irish poet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE OTHER SIDE OF SILENCE. MEN'S LIVES AND GAY IDENTITIES: A
Twentieth-Century History &LR;  By John Loughery. John Macrae/Owl/Holt,
$15.95. A provocative, well-researched chronicle of gay life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OYSTER &LR;  By Janette Turner Hospital. Norton, $14. Dreamlike
fiction about a cult in the Australian outback.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PARK CITY: New and Selected Stories &LR;  By Ann Beattie. Vintage
Contemporaries, $14. Small but sharp tales of quiet domestic
rupture.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE POISONWOOD BIBLE &LR;  By Barbara Kingsolver. HarperPerennial,
$14. A novel about a Baptist family that moves to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN: A Tale of Murder, Insanity, and
the Making of the Oxford English Dictionary &LR;  By Simon Winchester.
HarperPerennial, $13. A dictionary editor's strange bond with a
contributor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RESERVATION ROAD &LR;  By John Burnham Schwartz. Vintage
Contemporaries, $13. Tense fiction about a boy's hit-and-run death.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ROAD HOME &LR;  By Jim Harrison. Washington Square/Pocket Books,
$14. A novel about three generations of a part-Sioux family.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SARATOGA: Turning Point of America's Revolutionary War &LR;  By
Richard M. Ketchum. John Macrae/Owl/Holt, $15.95. Why the British
failed in their 1777 invasion of the Colonies from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCORPION TONGUES: The Irresistible History of Gossip in
American Politics &LR;  By Gail Collins. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $14.
Two centuries of political rumor-mongering.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SEEKERS: The Story of Man's Continuing Quest to Understand
His World &LR;  By Daniel J. Boorstin. Vintage, $14. A lively overview
of Western religion and philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHAKESPEARE: The Invention of the Human &LR;  By Harold Bloom.
Riverhead, $15.95. How Hamlet and his kin define the human
condition.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SMITHSONIAN INSTITUTION &LR;  By Gore Vidal. Harvest/Harcourt
Brace, $13. Fiction that explores the what-ifs of American history.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SONG FOR THE BLUE OCEAN: Encounters Along the World's Coasts
and Beneath the Seas &LR;  By Carl Safina. John Macrae/Owl/Holt, $14.95.
A bleak tour of the world's imperiled fishing grounds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STARTING OUT IN THE EVENING &LR;  By Brian Morton. Berkley, $12.95.
A sad novel about an elderly out-of-print novelist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STEPHEN SONDHEIM: A Life &LR;  By Meryle Secrest. Delta, $14.95. A
solid portrait of the brilliant but insecure composer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE STORY OF AMERICAN FREEDOM &LR;  By Eric Foner. Norton, $15.95. A
historian argues for an evolutionary view of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUMMER OF DELIVERANCE: A Memoir of Father and Son &LR;  By
Christopher Dickey. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $14. Bittersweet
memories of life as James Dickey's son.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TECUMSEH: A Life &LR;  By John Sugden. John Macrae/Owl/Holt, $15.95.
A rich portrait of the proud, doomed Indian leader.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TENNIS PARTNER &LR;  By Abraham Verghese. HarperPerennial, $14.
A physician's lyrical account of his friendship with a troubled
young intern in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THIRST &LR;  By Ken Kalfus. Washington Square/Pocket Books, $12.95.
Brief, jarring fantasies with displaced protagonists.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THIS SIDE OF BRIGHTNESS &LR;  By Colum McCann. Owl/Holt, $13. Gritty
fiction about three generations of New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TIME OF OUR TIME &LR;  By Norman Mailer. Modern Library, $24.95.
A giant anthology of 50 years of fiction and nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TITAN: The Life of John D. Rockefeller, Sr. &LR;  By Ron Chernow.
Vintage, $16. A large-scale biography of the archcapitalist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOMCAT IN LOVE &LR;  By Tim O'Brien. Broadway, $13. Comic fiction
about an unlovable linguistics professor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TROUBLE IN MIND: Black Southerners in the Age of Jim Crow &LR;  By
Leon F. Litwack. Vintage, $17. A heartbreaking book about a
heartbreaking time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TURBULENT SOULS: A Catholic Son's Return to His Jewish Family &LR; 
By Stephen J. Dubner. Bard/Avon, $12.50. A memoir about two
generations' spiritual journeys.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TWO CITIES &LR;  By John Edgar Wideman. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin,
$13. A novel about two wounded souls who fall in love.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VIRGINIA WOOLF &LR;  By Hermione Lee. Vintage, $18. A graceful,
intelligent biography.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE VOYAGE OF THE NARWHAL &LR;  By Andrea Barrett. Norton, $14.
Gripping fiction about an 1855 Arctic expedition.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WALKING WITH THE WIND: A Memoir of the Movement &LR;  By John Lewis
with Michael D'Orso. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $15. How the civil
rights movement shook the nation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WE DIE ALONE &LR;  By David Howarth. Lyons, $14.95. A harrowing
account of a Norwegian's Nazi-era escape.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WE WISH TO INFORM YOU THAT TOMORROW WE WILL BE KILLED WITH OUR
FAMILIES: Stories From Rwanda &LR;  By Philip Gourevitch. Picador USA,
$15. An unflinching look at the 1994 Hutu massacre of Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WILD PARTY: The Lost Classic &LR;  By Joseph Moncure March.
Illustrated by Art Spiegelman. Pantheon, $12. A 1928 ribald
ballad-novel with demonic illustrations.
</P>
