<HEADLINE>
HAVING A FIT OVER CARRY-ONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(jt) 
 By JOE SHARKEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are some of the things that airline flight attendants have
watched passengers lug on board: Mariachi hats, potted palms,
boogie boards, shopping bags brimming with canned hams, a live duck
in a cage, cases of wine, covered-dish casseroles, multi-tiered
wedding cakes, a three-foot-tall religious statue for lawn display,
an automobile transmission and a freshly severed buck's head with
its antlers poking out of a trash bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen an animal head myself, but it wouldn't surprise
me one bit,'' said Tim Carey, a flight attendant who, like many of
his colleagues, dreads the long Thanksgiving holiday travel season,
which peaks today, the year's busiest single day for air travel. By
Tuesday, nearly 20 million passengers, a record, will have flown
domestic airlines during the 12-day Thanksgiving holiday travel
period, according to the Air Transport Association.
</P>
<P>
   And they're carting a lot more stuff aboard than ever before.
Today, 6 out of 10 passengers haul a suitcase with them onto
flights. In 1992, only 2 out of 10 did, according a survey cited by
the Association of Flight Attendants, a union that represents about
46,000 of the more than 100,000 domestic flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants have always traded war stories about the
things passengers bring on board. But in the past few years, as
fully booked flights have become the norm and a proliferation of
carry-on bags have overwhelmed already tight storage space, the
situation has deteriorated from an annoyance into what flight
attendants say is a serious safety problem. In fact, it's their No.
1 workplace complaint _ and a significant cause of flight delays.
</P>
<P>
   Airline employees sometimes suffer back and other injuries from
hoisting carry-on bags into storage compartments. Other injuries to
flight attendants and passengers are caused when bags fall from
overfilled storage bins. Furthermore, loose-cannon carry-on baggage
can block aisles and exits during emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   While lawn statues and animal-head trophies make for colorful
anecdotes back at the hotel, the real problem comes from everyday
bags and laptops. The flight attendants union is lobbying the
federal government to adopt an industrywide law that would limit
carry-on luggage to a single bag, weighing 13 pounds or less, whose
combined length, width and height must not exceed 45 inches.
Laptops, briefcases, purses and even diaper bags would count under
that rule, which would replace the current hodgepodge of unevenly
enforced policies at individual airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers _ especially frequent fliers _ generally dislike the
idea of restrictions. Consumer advocates say the airlines created
the problem by reducing storage space, cramming customers into
planes, reducing connection times between flights and allowing
checked-baggage service to deteriorate to the point where 1 out of
every 200 passengers reports lost or delayed baggage.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is a touchy one in the fiercely competitive airline
industry. In the last year or two, most major carriers have imposed
stricter limits on both the number and size of carry-on baggage.
But airlines are loathe to alienate their frequent flyers _
especially business travelers, who are their most profitable
market. To the dismay of the flight attendants union, for example,
Continental Airlines refit 150 of its aircraft last year with
bigger overhead storage bins to accommodate more carry-ons.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants say it's actually a small percentage of
passengers who cause the biggest problems. Among them are
infrequent flyers, especially those bound for foreign countries to
visit relatives, who trudge on board with live chickens, baskets of
food and overflowing shopping bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``People bring on jugs of gasoline because it's cheaper to buy
it here,'' said Henri Simonetti, a longtime flight attendant who,
like Carey, did not want to identify the airline he works for.
``Not that they intend to pose a safety threat, but please _ you
can't imagine a worse safety threat that a volatile fuel seeping
from the overhead bin.''
</P>
<P>
   Such passengers tend to be reasonable when the rules are
explained, flight crew members say. More difficult to handle are
hardened business passengers unable to find space for their
carry-ons. These customers are often paying full fare, and
traveling on a tight schedule that is vulnerable to the slightest
delay and conducive to frayed tempers.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-core business-trip routes are considered to be the worst.
``Los Angeles to New York can be a  &UR; very &LR;  difficult trip,''
Simonetti said. ``You'll hear: `I'm a member of your frequent flier
club. I'm on your airline five times a week. Therefore, I should be
able to bring my five pieces of carry-on luggage on board,''' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher J. Witkowski, the director of air safety and health
at the attendants union, said the only solution is a federal law to
reduce carry-on luggage by 50 percent and leave no wiggle room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got assaults that occur because passengers take out
their frustrations on the flight attendants,'' he said. ``People
are being injured and it's got to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
