<SLUG> BC-R-LAWYERS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME LAWYERS TRY TO MAKE NICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(jt) 
 By DAVID WALLIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soon after EgyptAir Flight 990 plunged into the Atlantic Ocean,
the personal-injury lawyers at R. Jack Clapp and Associates
marshaled their resources and mobilized their forces.
</P>
<P>
   Faster than you can say class-action lawsuit, the Washington,
D.C., firm, which specializes in aviation disasters, launched
EgyptAir990.com _ a Web site that at first blush appears primarily
concerned with helping the bereaved deal with loss, but on closer
examination is all about financial gain.
</P>
<P>
   Such online opportunism hardly burnishes the flagging reputation
of lawyers, a profession so unpopular that even the reviled HMO
industry now feels at liberty to smack them around.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to head off legislation that would strip health
maintenance organizations of their immunity from patients'
lawsuits, an HMO advocacy group last month broadcast a TV
commercial that explicitly portrayed lawyers as sharks: ``America's
richest trial lawyers are circling _ and your health plan is the
bait: Call Congress today.''
</P>
<P>
   But now some lawyers and bar associations are biting back _
adopting a range of strategies to reverse the profession's slide in
stature.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina's bar association, for instance, convened a
series of town meetings this year so people could air gripes about
lawyers and the legal system. The upshot: legal triage clinics
where lawyers advise walk-in clients pro bono, and sensitivity
training for cranky court personnel. In Louisiana, the bar
association has produced ``Louisiana Lawyers: Enriching Louisiana
Life(C),'' a six-minute video starring earnest lawyers feeding the
homeless at a soup kitchen; empathetic lawyers strolling with AIDS
patients; and wise lawyers teaching kids about the legal
consequences of illicit drug use.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think all we do is sit at our desks and bill
time,'' noted Michael Ferachi, a civil litigator shown painting an
elderly neighbor's house. ``But this gives us a chance to show
people that were interested in caring for others that can't care
for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   To recast lawyers as protectors rather than predators, other bar
associations have also gone the feel-good route. Cut to a classroom
brought to you in a TV spot sponsored by the Ohio bar:
</P>
<P>
   ``Class, what do your parents do for a living?'' inquires a
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad protects people,'' volunteers one boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, so he's a police officer?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah, his dad is like my mom,'' chimes in a little girl. ``She
helps sick and hurt people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, so they're doctors?'' wonders the teacher. No, say the
kids.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the exasperated teacher asks, ``So what do your parents
do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're lawyers!'' cry the tykes in unison.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Mills, a cultural critic and author of ``The Triumph of
Meanness: America's War Against Its Better Self,'' says the public
relations blitz may be too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't change the shark image when the lawyers who make the
headlines have gotten huge divorce settlements, thwarted the
Justice Department or outfoxed a district attorney on a criminal
case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sorry image of lawyers has been rounded out lately by tacky
late-night commercials for ambulance chasers; the legal lobby's
opposition to tort reform; and the one-two punch of the O.J.
Simpson trial and the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   And many lawyers cringe at the proliferation of obnoxious TV
judges past their prime (time), presiding over video kangaroo
courts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hollywood's portrayal of the profession isn't all bad. Paul
Levinson, a professor of communications at Fordham University,
believes that the popularity of TV dramas like ``Law and Order''
and ``The Practice'' has had the curious effect of both idealizing
the profession and pointing up its real-life deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   The committed, diligent TV lawyers on both shows deserve
admiration, he explains, but their decency may signal
disillusionment with actual lawyers. ``When doctors stopped making
house calls in the Sixties, `Marcus Welby' became a hit,'' Levinson
said. ``It fulfilled our wishes for an old-fashioned doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same holds true for the lawyers on `The Practice,' who are
utterly devoted to clients. We fervently wish we could fulfill
fantasies of such lawyers as knights in shining armor.''
</P>
<P>
   And now such yearnings have some lawyers looking to heal
themselves. Carl Bogus, a professor at Roger Williams University
Law School, who this year organized a soul-searching conference,
Lawyer Collaboration With Systems of Evil, argues that lawyers
needn't indulge litigious clients who file questionable suits.
Notable cases arguably include the coffee drinker who sued
McDonald's after scalding herself or, more recently, the parents of
the Columbine High School gunman who intend to target his school
district for not doing more to prevent his carnage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawyers used to say no to clients more often,'' Bogus
complained. ``Lawyers used to say, you may have a right to make
this argument but there's something offensive to making this
argument. Go get yourself another lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   But as for clients, they're pretty happy with the lawyers they
have _ suggesting the limits of a legal charm offensive in a system
that is by its nature adversarial and often cutthroat. A recent
survey by the American Bar Association, for example, found that 75
percent of people expressed satisfaction with their own lawyer's
performance, regardless of what they thought about the profession
in general. ``People think about lawyers like they think about
congressmen,'' said Stephen Gillers, Vice Dean of New York
University Law School. ``Lawyers are a bad group, but my lawyer is
real good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 0832EST &QL; 
