<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN VICTORY'S WAKE, A BATTLE OF BUREAUCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing,.) (The Week in Review) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STIMLJE, Kosovo _ Valerie Petignat Wright, a 33-year-old Swiss
official, is a symbol of all that is wrong and right with the
United Nations effort to run Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   She is one of 29 prefects appointed by the United Nations to run
Kosovo's municipalities and is in charge of the lives of more than
30,000 people around this battered town. She has intelligence,
verve and all the will in the world, but after more than two months
here, she has little money or staff to back up her titular
authority.
</P>
<P>
   In front of her office, the road that runs through town looks
like the surface of the moon _ cratered, pitted and
bone-shattering. It is constantly clogged with traffic, and Ms.
Wright would like to fix it. ``But there's no money,'' she said
darkly, hugging herself in the cold because the electricity is off
again. ``There's no money for anything.'' She sighed, then smiled.
``It's a bit of a strange status. Nothing is quite clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a few yards away is the larger, warmer office of Ruzhdi
Jashari, 44, who was appointed mayor by the Kosovo Liberation Army
and its provisional government a day before NATO forces entered
Kosovo in June.
</P>
<P>
   Jashari, a kind of village ideologue, worked in education and
joined the guerrillas relatively early, and by October 1998 he was
in charge of public relations for civil order in areas that they
controlled. He spent the war in the mountains within a few miles of
here.
</P>
<P>
   He says he respects the United Nations and is happy to work with
Ms. Wright, but he makes it clear that he believes he exercises
what passes for official control here. He sits at the head of a
long conference table. He runs education and has people's respect
as a fighter, but he has no money to fix the road, either.
</P>
<P>
   The former Kosovo Liberation Army, which has supposedly
transformed itself into a civilian force with no military or police
responsibilities, is not the only challenge to the authority of the
U.N. Mission in Kosovo, known as Unmik; the mission is also
undermined by the international civilian agencies that are supposed
to serve it, and by the sheer size and resources of the NATO-led
force here _ 42,000 troops _ whose role tends to be defined only as
peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   The civilian agencies have large organizations and budgets. They
rely on many of the same donor countries for their own financing as
the U.N. Mission here. And in many cases, they are struggling with
the mission and its director, Bernard Kouchner of France, over
responsibilities and even glory. Each of those other agencies has
its own massive office building in Pristina, its own vehicles, even
its own identity cards.
</P>
<P>
   The office of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees is in
charge of the return of the 850,000 refugees, their temporary
housing and their food. It coordinates the many aid agencies that
bustle (in so far as anyone bustles) around Stimlje. The European
Union is responsible for more permanent reconstruction, but all of
that, European bureaucrats have decided, will have to wait until
next year. And the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe is supposed to help build Kosovo's future society along
democratic lines. Effectively, that means training police and
judges, preparing elections, developing education, media and
human-rights programs.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations and Kouchner have two tasks that are hard to
reconcile: while running Kosovo's civil administration until
self-governing institutions can be put in place, they are also
supposed to be in overall charge of everyone, including the
better-financed agencies that are planning those new institutions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This adds up to a lot of agencies competing with each other at
the expense of accomplishing tasks they might be dividing up more
efficiently. For example, the Europeans are emphasizing planning
for the future rather than fulfiling commitments to help address
housing needs, even as a hard winter sets in. And while the OSCE is
planning how to democratize a multi-thnic Kosovo, a more urgent
requirement might be to work harder now with the peacekeepers to
stem the wave of hatred, killings and arson designed to drive out
Kosovo's remaining Serbs and Gypsies, further poisoning chances for
real democracy.
</P>
<P>
   There is significant overlap and conflict. In particular,
officials of both organizations say, the head of the OSCE in
Kosovo, Daan Everts, has been working successfully to take control
from the United Nations over the key human-rights portfolio, the
job of media oversight and development, including the licensing and
running of new media outlets, and the election schedule.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, Everts' success _ like the bureaucratic
infighting _ is not surprising. The United States and Britain
wanted the OSCE, an organization of more than 50 nations, to run
Kosovo, rather than the United Nations. The OSCE's members
represent the richest members of the United Nations, and the
organization easily has twice as many foreign officials here as
does Kouchner's office.
</P>
<P>
   But as usual, as the United Nations begins to be blamed for
foreseeable problems of organization and inefficiency, its main
member governments, which have been slow to provide funds and
manpower, prefer to evade responsibility. And senior OSCE officials
are relieved to be responsible ``for the future'' rather than the
present morass.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wright is one of Kouchner's volunteers. Trained in
psychology and women's studies, she had run an aid agency in
Guatemala giving vocational training to street children. She was
working on vocational training for the Swiss government when she
heard that ``people were wanted for Kosovo.'' She volunteered
without a job description.
</P>
<P>
   Now she finds herself the mayor and more for thousands of people
whose language she doesn't speak and whose history she is only
beginning to understand.
</P>
<P>
   While the NATO-led force known as KFOR patrols the center of
Stimlje, there are as yet no United Nations police because
governments have not yet met their manpower pledges. Nor is there
any fire brigade. Of the 2,000 Serbs in Stimlje last year, she
says, ``there are now 24 Serbs, and I know them all.'' They are
elderly and come from a few families, and KFOR is here to protect
them. A lot of her job is to mediate quarrels over vacant
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   She and an assistant from Cameroon, Gilbert Nantsa, are
preparing a local newsletter, to be published in English, Albanian
and Serbian. ``Well, there will be 24 copies in Serbian,'' Ms.
Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Multi-ethnicity isn't going to happen,'' she said bluntly.
``At best people will live side-by-side without killing each other.
They never really lived together before. Why should they start
now?'' The largest number of Serbs in her area, 180 of them, along
with some Gypsies, are actually in the mental hospital nearby,
which is run by the Norwegian Red Cross. She laughed ironically.
``It's the only multi-ethnic institution in the area,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her biggest problem? ``Money. It's supposed to be coming, but
with no funds it's hard to make a budget or have an impact. I can't
pay city workers, teachers or health-care workers.''
</P>
<P>
   She and Jashari meet every week, she said. Ms. Wright, a
problem-solver, will work with anyone who can help. She has noticed
that initial KLA hostility to the United Nations has ebbed lately,
in part because the former guerrillas understand that people's
frustration at the mess and inactivity hurts them too.
</P>
<P>
   Jashari pulls on a cigarette and says: ``We are facing a lot of
problems here.'' Some 15 percent of the Albanian population have
not yet returned from abroad, and some are bound to be dead, he
said. ``And the people who are back lack housing,'' he said. He
says there is a desperate need for personal documentation, identity
cards and passports. ``While we were ready to do a lot of things,
because of our respect for Unmik, we handicapped ourselves and
didn't do anything,'' he said with a straight face. So even the
KLA, which resisted U.N. authority, is blaming the United Nations
now.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wright is amused, but in a somber way. ``Everyone is more or
less panicky, because nothing much has been done before the
winter,'' she said. ``The ex-fighters promised a lot but didn't
deliver. Of course, neither has Unmik.''
</P>
</TEXT>
