<SLUG> BC-R-FIRST-FAMILIES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE'S NOT THE FIRST LADY TO LEAVE THE WHITE HOUSE BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(jt) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House, with 132 rooms of grandeur and its
aura of power, has often seemed confining to the wives of the men
who lived there. Hillary Rodham Clinton, seeking power that she did
not have to exercise through her husband, announced last week that
she was moving to an 11-room house in Chappaqua, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is not the first president's wife to find the White
House stifling and to leave a husband rattling around in the
whitewashed old pile on Pennsylvania Avenue. Louisa Adams, wife of
John Quincy Adams, appears to have been the first, but not the
last, to refer to the White House as a gilded prison.
</P>
<P>
   Several presidential wives sought refuge from the burdens of
first ladyship, from the wretched heat of Washington summers, from
painful marriages. They fled to the seaside oasis of Oyster Bay,
N.Y., to family homes in Independence, Mo., and Hyde Park, N.Y., to
an artists' colony at Cornish, N.H., and a peanut farm in Plains,
Ga. They left the White House seeking solace, solitude or personal
fulfillment. Ellen Axson Wilson, Woodrow Wilson's first wife, went
away for months at a time to practice art in New Hampshire. Louisa
Adams spent summers apart from her husband because their
relationship had soured and she despised the political atmosphere
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But none of these first ladies called a news conference to
announce a move out of the White House to live in another city.
Mrs. Clinton said Chappaqua, a suburb of New York, would be her
permanent residence as she campaigns for the Senate. She plans to
return to Washington ``from time to time,'' to attend to social
affairs such as state dinners and the New Year's Eve millennial
celebration. ``It does sound weird,'' said Carl Sferrazza Anthony,
an authority on first ladies, ``because it's unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is, at least in this sense: While all the others may have
felt personally hemmed in, even frustrated, by White House life,
Mrs. Clinton is the first to declare that she has a political life
distinct from her husband's, one that requires her to leave his
house.
</P>
<P>
   The job of first lady is nowhere defined in law or Constitution;
it has evolved over the years into a combination of national social
secretary and sometime presidential adviser. While some first
ladies, like Nancy Reagan, gloried in their hostess roles, others
discharged their duties sporadically, said Anthony, author of the
two-volume ``First Ladies'' (William Morrow and Company, 1990).
Jacqueline Kennedy spent dozens of weekends with her children at
country homes near Middleburg, Va., and commuted to Washington for
state functions; Bess Truman, who hated the White House and
decamped for her family home in Missouri every chance she got,
would often miss them altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Roosevelt used her fieldstone cottage, Val-Kill, on the
Roosevelt family estate in Hyde Park, and an apartment on
Washington Square in Manhattan as places to write her newspaper
columns and to socialize with her tight circle of friends.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Truman, who referred to the White House as the ``Great
White Jail,'' left Washington as often as she could, according to a
biography written by her daughter, Margaret. She claimed she had to
return to Independence to care for her aging mother or look after
the family house, but ``these reasons were essentially
rationalizations for Bess' retreat from the White House, the
presidency, the whole rigamarole of playing first lady,'' Margaret
Truman wrote.
</P>
<P>
   What will become of this long-distance relationship between the
Clintons, two congenital pols, one at the dawn of an electoral
career, the other in its twilight?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people want answers right away,'' said Anthony. ``But
we don't have any idea how it's going to work, we don't know how
it's going to play out. It is just a unique circumstance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 0835EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
