<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 08:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6863 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-CHINA-COMRADE-REVIE     11-29 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CHINA-COMRADE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, MISTER! YOU'RE NO COMRADE! 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(jt) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ As a greeting, it seems peculiarly unsuited to the
themes of life in modern urban China. Imagine this: ``Comrade, do
you like Starbucks' caffe latte?'' Or this: ``Comrade, how did you
do on the GRE's?'' Or even this: ``Comrade, did your stocks go up
today?''
</P>
<P>
   And so it was perhaps no surprise that the latest edition of
China's dictionary of record, Cihai (The Sea of Words), narrowed
the definition of the word tongzhi _ or comrade _ out of everyday
life, concluding that it could no longer be regarded as  &UR; the
 &LR; greeting among China's citizens.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1979 ``Sea of Words,'' ``comrade'' was ``a general form
of address among the citizens of our country.'' At the time,
comrade was China's universal salutation. In the 1989 revision of
the dictionary, ``comrade'' was ``a general form of address among
the citizens of socialist countries.''
</P>
<P>
   But the newest edition, published last month, drops all such
descriptions, noting: ``In the era of reform and opening up,
`comrade' is no longer the only form of address among ordinary
people. The Chinese words for Mister, Ma'am, Master and Miss have
returned as terms of respect and cordiality.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is very rare to hear the word ``comrade'' today in
ordinary conversations; when it appears, it sounds like a blast
from the past, like those Little Red Books of Mao's sayings that
are sold as curiosities in street markets. Even among the Communist
elite, the term appears to be waning.
</P>
<P>
   ``For everyday use, I've basically stopped using the term,''
said Dong Yuyu, a editor at the Communist Party-run newspaper,
Guangming Daily. ``But, of course, on official documents and
official meetings it's still employed.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked when they were last referred to as ``comrade,'' many
people can only think of only one recent example: when they saw
President Jiang Zemin on TV last month, wearing a Mao suit and
addressing his countrymen to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the
People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
   The shrinking sphere of the word has, of course, directly
paralleled the shrinking relevance of ideology to everyday life in
this still nominally Communist state.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, it was hard to find any ``tongzhi's'' around. Bring
up the word `comrade'' with young people and you are likely to get
a bemused smile, as if you were suggesting the use of an ancient
greeting like ``squire'' or ``goody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Comrade?'' said a 17-year-old with the surname Nie. ``No I've
never thought of calling anyone that.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 10 years, the Communist Party has intermittently
struggled against the waning use of ``comrade,'' endeavoring to
insure at least its partial preservation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, in the wake of the crackdown on student pro-democracy
protests in Tiananmen Square, the Standing Committee of the
Politburo decried the emergence of terms like Mister and Miss,
saying that ``comrade'' was the best salutation for use among
ordinary people, according to one scholar. ``Miss'' was too
reminiscent of prostitutes in pre-revolutionary China, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Just last year, an essay in the People's Daily, the Communist
Party newspaper, said that ``comrade'' should be preserved as the
greeting at least among party members. And it bemoaned the fact the
some party members were addressing others with decidedly
un-socialist greetings, for example referring to their immediate
supervisors at work as the ``lao ban,'' or boss.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, usage has declined steadily, although there remains
a bit of a generational divide regarding the term. Older Chinese
still sometimes fall back on ``comrade'' to greet peers with good
Communist histories, and in formal situations at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``In social situations I just use and Mrs., but at the
university we still use `comrade' for official documents or
meetings,'' said a senior philosophy professor and Communist Party
member.
</P>
<P>
   The word now translated as comrade originated some 2,200 years
ago in the early Qin Dynasty, when it was defined as pertaining to
people who have the same ethics and ideals. In the years before the
Communists took power in 1949, it took on a more modern cast: The
version of ``Sea of Words'' published in 1936, when ``tovarich''
was well established in Moscow, defined ``comrade'' as ``a mutual
form of address among people with the same ideological
convictions.''
</P>
<P>
   It soon became the principal salutation of the rigidly
egalitarian Communist state, where even soldiers were forbidden
from acknowledging their rank, calling each other ``comrade.''
</P>
<P>
   How to address a friend or stranger is an issue that looms large
in China, where first names are rarely used and polite sentences
often start with a surname and an identifying salutation.
</P>
<P>
   And the gradual loss of the all-purpose ``comrade'' has created
something of a void, now filled by a large variety of options that
emphasize the stratification and many social distinctions of
today's China. Comrade Zhang of 1976 has become General Manager
Zhang, or teacher Zhang, or Miss Zhang or Classmate Zhang.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't call people comrade,'' said Wang Bing, a salesman, who
was strolling on Beijing's Jian Guo Men Wai Street, under a large
array of billboards advertising Internet sites and computers. ``I
call young girls Miss. And men I call Mister. Or other times I use
their titles, like Director or Manager. Why? Because everybody
does.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 0836EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 08:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3727 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-MIDEAST-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      11-29 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MIDEAST-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MIDDLE EAST CHOICE: PEACE OR DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(jt) 
 By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the last several months, even as a final peace
between Israel and the Palestinians has come to seem more
plausible, a new element of uncertainty has been creeping into the
Middle East. The static pantheon of Arab leaders is beginning to
crumble, and generational change has started to sweep through the
region as aging and entrenched leaders give way to sons or
designate heirs. So these are anxious times, as iron men begin to
fade and courtiers plot their futures. Within five years, say
experts on the region, the current lineup of Arab leaders is likely
to be totally transformed.
</P>
<P>
   And so a new question has entered the calculations of those who
plan for peace or war in the region: Would democracies or
dictatorships make the best neighbors and partners in the emerging
peace with Israel?
</P>
<P>
   In the West, it is common to assume that the answer is simple:
democracies. But the Arab Middle East is a vast area where
Western-style democracy exists only in its infancy, if at all. Its
countries are riven with tribal, religious and ethnic fault lines,
and in many places extremes of wealth and poverty have left the
mass of people young, ill-educated and disaffected.
</P>
<P>
   So it is not a simple question whether opening the floodgates to
free expression of the tensions in these societies would provide
the quickest way to regional peace. These are places where
anti-Israeli sentiment is sometimes a passionate rallying cry for
all kinds of opposition groups, and where a monarch or dictator can
take a lead that a president who depends on consensus might not. On
the other hand, any regime maintained through repression risks,
over the years, lapsing into tyranny and instability, which are
among the worst of long-run risks to peace.
</P>
<P>
   So the question of how to think about balancing the goals of
democracy and peace is increasingly being wrestled with in
Washington as well as in Israel _ a democracy itself, but one that
has long made deals with whatever regimes would accept it, even as
it pointed out the absence of democracy in its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The region is coming to the end of the postwar era, where
countries were ruled by a king or a military personality,'' said
Stephen P. Cohen, vice president of the center for Middle East
Studies in New York. But as the era ends, the style of rule is
unlikely to evolve much, he said. ``We're in a very sensitive time
concerning the self image of the Arab world. The idea that the
fundamentalist threat can only be controlled by hard military
rulers prevails.''
</P>
<P>
   One common thread runs through the process: the new leaders are
likely to emerge for reasons of bloodline rather than merit, and it
gives some analysts pause, no matter how pro-Western or pro-peace
these leaders are.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are not being chosen for competence in modern
society but for loyalty and kinship,'' said Lisa Anderson, the dean
of the School of International and Public Affairs at Columbia
University. ``There is not a layer of technocrats who appear to be
poised to take the reins of power.''
</P>
<P>
   The two countries where change has occurred this year _ Jordan
and Morocco _ are monarchies that managed smooth transitions: King
Abdullah succeeded his father, King Hussein of Jordan, and Mohammed
VI succeeded his father, King Hassan of Morocco. Both sons are in
their 30s and have experienced life in Western democracies: King
Abdullah in Britain and America, King Mohammed in France.
</P>
<P>
   Both of their fathers were partners of Israel in making peace,
and the sons both see the need for economic reform to alleviate
poverty. So they may turn out to be the most open and forward
leaning of the new rulers in the region. Jordan, notably, has an
active Parliament and its new king sees the peace with Israel as a
lynchpin for his country's future.
</P>
<P>
   In Syria, by contrast, the dynastic impulse in a tightly run
dictatorship is literally impeding peace. President Hafez Assad is
so busy organizing the succession of his son Bashar, who faces
challenges from other pretenders, that he has put any negotiations
for peace with Israel on hold. And a driving motivation for the
Israeli prime minister, Ehud Barak, as he negotiates on final
status issues with Yasser Arafat is the belief that the ailing
Palestinian leader may well be a more reliable partner than anyone
who might succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   For Israel, the most immediate question is what will happen in
Syria, where Assad, who is from the minority Alawite tribe, has
fashioned the army, the Ba'ath party and other institutions around
fealty to him. Now 69, Assad is reported to be suffering from
memory loss. He looks haggard and is no longer able to sustain the
marathon negotiating sessions of the past, a recent American
visitor said.
</P>
<P>
   Assad has also resisted reform, and this will not help his
successor establish a peaceful transition. ``Assad knows if he
opens the door, the wind will carry him off,'' said Fouad Ajami, a
scholar of the region. ``He doesn't want to be the Gorbachev of
Syria. I don't know if he can hold it together.''
</P>
<P>
   For two decades now, Egypt has played a pivotal position in the
Middle East's peacemaking, and Americans often identify with it as
if it were a like-minded democracy. In reality, despite the
trappings of elections and a parliament, the system is tightly
controlled by one party and the military; corruption is endemic, as
is tension over Islamic activism and the repression of it. A new
class of businessmen has emerged in recent years, providing an
elite interested in keeping the peace with Israel. But it is not
much interested in basic reforms, preferring to use state and crony
contacts to maintain its income, experts here say.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, President Hosni Mubarak, who is 71, declared that his
son Gamal, a banker, would not succeed him, drawing a distinction
between Egypt and its neighbors. But that doesn't mean a democratic
succession. Ajami thinks the army will designate a successor if
Mubarak dies in office, which has become the standard way of giving
up power in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Anderson gives credit to Israeli leaders for placing value
on democracy as they think about their neighbors' futures, even as
they recognize that Israel is probably the last country that could
promote democracy in them. ``The Israelis are quite aware of the
dilemma they are in,'' she said. ``They think democracy is a good
thing but if they make it known, they run the risk of being a
political football in the domestic politics of these countries. So
there is a temptation to say: `Let's sign on with this person, even
if he's unpopular at home.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 0837EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 08:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
