<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How schools can get straight with gay students
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Family-values and religious right groups are up in alarms over a
pamphlet about gay and lesbian youths recently sent to school
administrators around the country. Their distress is
understandable. The booklet's appeal to reason has little place in
the narrow cosmography of the sexually repressive.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry for the tedious list, but it really is necessary to string
out the sponsors here of ``Sexual Orientation and Youth,'' which
deals with developmental, psychological and legal questions:
</P>
<P>
   The American Academy of Pediatrics, American Counseling
Association, American Association of School Administrators,
American Federation of Teachers, American Psychological
Association, American School Health Association, The Interfaith
Alliance Foundation, National Association of School Psychologists,
National Association of Social Workers and the National Education
Association.
</P>
<P>
   A more sober bunch would be hard to find. Their message is the
simple one that some young men and women are gay, lesbian or
bisexual, that that's all there is to it and efforts to force them
to change do far more harm than good.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the various agitated societies for the suppression
of homosexuality are promoting ``reparative'' or ``conversion''
therapies, which claim, depending upon the bent of the promoter,
that heavy counseling, intense peer pressure or prayer can make
heterosexuals out of homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual converts are mustered to witness for the therapies, but
while there is no reason to contest their individual testimony,
such claimed successes are rare, usually fragile and often are
bought at the cost of emotional damage to patients led or coerced
to perform sexually in a manner supposedly normal but in fact still
unnatural to them. Most folks, of any orientation, including the
stoutest heterosexuals, can be yelled into contrary sexual
behavior, but what has really changed? A change in mechanics is not
a change in nature.
</P>
<P>
   Homosexual youths suffer more emotional distress, try suicide
more often and engage in riskier sexual and drug behaviors than
heterosexual kids, not, as the pamphlet points out, because of
their homosexuality but because of the isolation they live in as a
result of bigotry and misunderstanding. And they shun counseling
out of fear they will be harassed and ridiculed.
</P>
<P>
   It is hardly an irrational fear, nor is the isolation imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Just days before the booklet was published, the Southern Baptist
Convention took the unprecedented step of, in effect,
excommunicating two Atlanta churches for accepting gays and
lesbians as full congregants. And GOP presidential forgone
conclusion George W. Bush made a show of refusing to meet with gay
Republicans, theatrically modeling prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   Moves like those are meant to keep gays and lesbians
anathematized and marginalized, their humanity denied and dignity
forbidden. That's a lot for 12-page pamphlet to go up against.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
