<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: More Middle East cacophony
 &HT;    For release Dec. 1, 1999.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the feverish religious fervor that has set people against
each other, the present one between Israelis, Muslims and Catholics
is among the most aberrant.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a scorecard, you can't tell the lineups.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Israelis gave permission for Muslims to erect a
mosque in Nazareth, immediately alongside the Basilica of the
Annunciation. Nazareth was the boyhood home of Jesus Christ.
Muslims see Nazareth as the burial site of Shihab el-Din, a fierce
anti-Crusader cleric of the 12th Century.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Vatican reacted with outrage to the concept that a
mosque would be built so close to the venerated church. The Vatican
strongly hinted that future relations with Israel would be in
question and said that by Israel allowing the unveiling of a Muslim
cornerstone on the site, it was ``creating a basis for instigating
division'' between Christians and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis responded with muffled words about anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   And so the battle is joined. But not without further muddling.
</P>
<P>
   Yasser Arafat and his Palestine Authority are supporting the
Christian side of the issue, while more dogmatic Muslims are
cheering the laying of the cornerstone; a division within a
division.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwile, Christian shopkeepers in Nazareth closed their shops
in protest, just as Muslim shopkeepers close theirs when they don't
like what's happening.
</P>
<P>
   I doubt that anyone will go to war over this, but it is just
another example of how religion often gets caught up in _ or
creates _ a vortex of animosity.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, discord broke out in Jerusalem about the opening of an
ancient tunnel by Israelis in the vicinity of prime Muslim sites,
including Al-Aksa mosque. Muslims screamed in outrage,
hypothesizing that the tunnel would undermine the mosque.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I don't know what the outcome of the debate was _ the
mosque is still standing _ and what's more, I don't care. This
manner of religious acrimony has been going on for centuries. It's
better to be a disinterested bystander than get swallowed in the
rancor.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just in the Middle East, either. Earlier this year,
under protest by Jews, Poland's Roman Catholic Church removed 300
crosses that bordered on the former Auschwitz death camp. One large
cross remains, hopefully uncontested. This is a continuation of the
long-held competition for the soul of Auschwitz, claimed by Jews as
a result of their monumental losses, but also claimed by the church
for the many non-Jews who died there.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, at that same site, there was a Jewish-Catholic verbal
brawl, along with some sit-ins, over the restoration of a convent
just outside the site. I believe the Catholics backed down.
</P>
<P>
   By its rabid religious reality, theological antagonism is an
uncurable muddle and will continue to be so as long as there still
are Christians, Jews and Muslims. The Middle East quandary is
analoguous to the malice there is between Hindus and Sikhs in
India, between Protestants and Catholics in Northern Ireland and
between Christians and Muslims in the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   For all the beauty and serenity preached in the Christian Bible,
the Jewish Holy Scriptures and the Muslim Koran _ liberally
interspersed with God-inspired mayhem _ the surviving religious
zealots do not practice it.
</P>
<P>
   With all these fires either burning brightly, or simmering _
none ever are extinguished _ the issue of Jerusalem lies just
ahead. If you think religious division was sharp in the past, wait
until this one.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, while watching young Israeli men graduate tank
school, I ran into a baker from Jerusalem whose son _ later killed
in the Yom Kippur War _ was among the graduates. He told me then
that he did not believe any solution could be found to the impasse
of the Middle East ``in this century.''
</P>
<P>
   A new century begins a month (or a year and a month) from now.
If I asked him today, the old baker probably would tell me a
solution won't be found in the next century, either.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
