<HEADER>
A3739 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-MURRAY-COLUMN30-COX     11-29 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Trains, planes and Paris porters
 &HT;    Sixth in a series
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Sitting in a railroad station, got a ticket for my
destination ... I was humming an old Simon and Garfunkel tune and
wishing I could remember the words.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Gare de Lyon, which, as best as I can figure,
roughly translates as ``Look out for Leon.''
</P>
<P>
   And who is this Leon I should guard against? I wasn't sure until
I was getting out of the taxi.
</P>
<P>
   There he was, a little guy, all smiles, with a buggy for our
luggage already in place at the trunk of the taxi.
</P>
<P>
   My wife thought it was good service. I thought it a bad omen.
</P>
<P>
   The only time I had my pocket picked was at a train station.
That was 10 years ago in Warsaw. Luckily, I was carrying only $40
in cash.
</P>
<P>
   I always wondered who the pickpocket was. I always wondered what
happened to him. Right now, I was wondering about Leon.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the name I gave him, my personal porter, as he led us
through the crowds and directly to the ticket counter.
</P>
<P>
   We were taking the TGV (Train a Grande Vitesse), which can
travel upwards of 200 mph, to Marseille and then switching over to
a local train to Aix-en-Provence for a few days stay.
</P>
<P>
   For all I knew, we were taking Leon with us. Indeed, he was
sticking with us.
</P>
<P>
   We had an hour or so before train time. Leon directed us to a
cafe, positioned our luggage so that we could watch it and then
promised to be watching out for us as well, which he illustrated by
pulling down the lower lid of one of his rheumy eyes. Somehow I was
not reassured.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to pay him, offering 50 francs, almost $10, generous to
my way of thinking. Leon, refusing the money, indicated that there
would be time enough to settle up later.
</P>
<P>
   I don't like train stations: Too much noise, too many people,
too much coming and going, and too little security.
</P>
<P>
   I like security. That's what I like about airports: Lots of
metal detectors, lots of dope-sniffing dogs, lots of armed guards
keeping an sharp eye out for suspicious characters.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the only person looking out for me was a suspicious
character.
</P>
<P>
   Then, all of a sudden, right at the appointed time, he was
there, just as he had promised, gathering up our luggage and
hurrying us along to the platform where the train for Marseille was
loading.
</P>
<P>
   Here was the car. Here were our seats. Our luggage was stowed.
We were all ready to saddle up and ride.
</P>
<P>
   And Leon was finally ready to settle up.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else I'm generous to a fault. What the heck, I
thought. I'll give him 100 francs.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no,'' Leon said, shaking his head at the single bill I had
offered. For a brief moment I misunderstood. Was Leon simply a good
Samaritan?
</P>
<P>
   No way. Leon was a good-for-nothing. He purposely had waited
until this last minute to establish price.
</P>
<P>
   ``One hundred francs for EACH!'' he insisted, pointing to me and
my wife.
</P>
<P>
   Too late to haggle, I shoved the money in his hand just as the
train was about to shove off. I'll always remember him waving me
goodbye, a little guy, all smiles, the world's most expensive
porter.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. Two hundred francs is something less than $40. It's a
better deal than I got in Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is P.O. Box
151108; email, jmurray(AT)lcc.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
