<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKETTES-XMAS-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKETTES GET A LEG UP ON CHRISTMAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN McTAVISH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The performances
</P>
<P>
   ``The Radio City Christmas Spectacular'' starring the Radio City
Rockettes continues Tuesdays through Sundays, through Dec. 12 at
the Grand Palace in Branson. Tickets cost $17 to $41 for adults and
$10 to $41 for children age 11 and younger; call (800) 572-5223.
</P>
<P>
   You can't keep a good gam down.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when it moves in high-kicking unison with the Radio
City Rockettes. The world-famous precision dance troupe is back in
``The Radio City Christmas Spectacular,'' running through Dec. 12
at the Grand Palace in Branson.
</P>
<P>
   It's the popular attraction's sixth season in the Ozarks, the
first place outside of New York's Radio City Music Hall where
audiences could behold the traditional holiday extravaganza. Since
1994 the show has expanded to include productions in Los Angeles;
Myrtle Beach, S.C.; Chicago; Detroit; and Mexico City. The total
effort requires the talents of more than 200 Rockettes.
</P>
<P>
   To get the word out about all those legs on all those stages,
Rockettes Corrinna Lindholm and Kim Fletcher recently visited The
Kansas City Star. After having their photograph snapped in
obligatory tandem _ Rockettes never do anything alone _ the two sat
down, crossed their respective famous appendages and amiably
chatted with this reporter. (A tough job, to be sure, but somebody
had to do it.)
</P>
<P>
   They smiled virtually nonstop and were decked out in full
``Christmas Spectacular'' regalia, from their mandatory red
lipstick to the fluffy white fur that trimmed their matching
Santa-style minidresses. And they were ready to reveal some truly
behind-the-seams stories.
</P>
<P>
   For instance: When the Rockettes form their signature 18-woman
kick line, ``you would think that we're holding on, tugging on each
other's costumes for our balance,'' Lindholm said. ``Actually, we
have specific areas to place our hands _ our right hand is high,
our left hand is low _ and we are not allowed to touch one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our choreographers actually walk behind us to make sure. If
you cannot do eye-high kicks standing by yourself, on your own with
your arms out, you shouldn't be doing them hooked up to girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Another illusion is that the Rockettes are the same height. In
fact, they range between 5 feet 51/2 inches and 5 feet 91/2 inches
tall. By placing the tallest Rockettes in the middle of the line
and the shortest on the ends, all appear to be of identical
stature.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're onstage kicking and dancing with everyone, it's a
unity thing,'' Fletcher said.``It's like everyone's a star, and
that's how you become a star.''
</P>
<P>
   Becoming part of the Rockettes' collective means knowing how to
do more than dance and sing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't just learn the show, and we don't just learn the
steps,'' Lindholm said. ``We learn how to be a Rockette.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have training for everything we do. Part of our audition
process is to go in and be scrutinized for every aspect of
ourselves _ what you look like, how tall you are, how big you are,
how you dance, how you can talk, how you present yourself. A Radio
City Rockette is just a little package.''
</P>
<P>
   That package was first wrapped in 1925, when St. Louisan Russell
Markert created the Missouri Rockets chorus line, made up of taller
and leggier female dancers who could do more than standard
waist-high kicks. For their New York debut, S.L. ``Roxy'' Rothafel
introduced the troupe at his Roxy Theater as the Roxyettes. After
Rothafel opened Radio City Music Hall on Dec. 27, 1932, the
Roxyettes became the Radio City Rockettes and an essential
ingredient to the historic Art Deco entertainment hall's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tradition behind it, and that's where the glamour
comes in,'' Fletcher said. ``All of a sudden you're a part of
history. And that's an incredible feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockettes' annual ``Christmas Spectacular'' is the
highest-profile reminder of that storied tradition. It includes
such familiar Rockettes production numbers as the ``Parade of
Wooden Soldiers'' and the ``Living Nativity,'' both dating back to
1933. But the show doesn't stay pat, either. A new scene this year
is ``Santa's Candy Castle,'' featuring the Rockettes in peppermint
twist outfits, entertaining Old Saint Nick as they dance with
5-foot candy canes.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all the Rockettes must remain on friendly terms. Not
that it's a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' Lindholm said. ``During rehearsals we have so
little time to even get to know each other, we wouldn't have time
to fight even if we wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You get closer with some girls than others,'' Fletcher said.
``But some friends, I feel like I'll probably have them for the
rest of my life. Like me and Corrinna. We didn't even know each
other, and within the first half-hour we were like soul mates.''
</P>
<P>
   Who better than a soul mate to catch you when you fall?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to rely on all of the people around us,'' Lindholm
said. ``Like in `Parade of the Wooden Soldiers,' when we all rock
back and fall like dominoes. If one person doesn't do their job,
the whole thing is going to come crashing down. So the more we
trust one another and the closer we are to each other, the more we
can feel comfortable about our job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
