<HEADER>
A3759 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-BULLY-BOX30-COX     11-29 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLY-BOX30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bully box teaches kindness, respect in schools
 &HT;    By Mara Lee
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KETTERING, Ohio _ In middle school, it's all about fitting in.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing the right clothes, using the right slang. Not being too
smart or too slow. Not being too large or too small.
</P>
<P>
   For those who refuse to toe the line or who can't camouflage
their differences, there are penalties.
</P>
<P>
   When you're 12 years old, on trial in the court of your peers,
there is no mercy.
</P>
<P>
   Hannah knows. Her best friend doesn't wear the preppy uniform
common in the south suburbs. She dresses with humor and irony, a
T-shirt with a toy from 10 years ago, baggy pants, lots of
necklaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's sort of like a freak'' in the popular boys' eyes, Hannah
said. Those boys started messing with her. ``Calling her a lesbian
and everything, during classes and after school, at football games.
She was so stressed out. She didn't know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hannah (not her real name) is an eighth-grader at Van Buren
Middle School, and this year, Assistant Principal Matt Rugh decided
to try to teach preteens about kindness and respect in a new way.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, the school has been trying to convince
students not to put each other down. They talk about empathy and
about how being different is OK.
</P>
<P>
   But at the beginning of puberty, when physical and social
differences are at their most awkward and most pronounced, that
message is a hard sell.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers who have studied bullying, including psychologist
Paula Fried, who co-authored ``Bullies and Victims: Helping Your
Child Through the Schoolyard Battlefield'' (M. Evans and Co. Inc;
$19.95), say it's natural for preteens to try to influence their
peers and to want more personal power. It's getting that sense of
power through hurting others that worries adults who work with this
age group.
</P>
<P>
   Rugh decided to go beyond lectures and bulletin boards with the
Bully Box.
</P>
<P>
   That box, which is in the guidance counselor's office, is a way
for students to let adults know what's going on outside their
earshot. Most of it is taunting, though there are a few reports of
shoving in the halls.
</P>
<P>
   At Van Buren, more than 75 percent of bullies whose names end up
in the box are boys, and most of their victims are boys who are the
same age or younger, and always smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Rugh thinks the box has helped sixth-graders come forward about
abuse they've seen or experienced. Seventh- and eighth-graders seem
to be more comfortable about directly approaching guidance
counselors or other adults.
</P>
<P>
   Half the complaints in the box come from witnesses, not victims.
Getting witnesses involved is crucial, researchers say. ``Bullies
are skilled at finding those situations where adults aren't
around,'' Rugh said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses have told him several times about special-education
students who become scapegoats.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of thing just sickens me. I think it sickens most
kids,'' Rugh said. ``Most kids are not about making other kids feel
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Hannah said her friend was afraid to put a note in the box
because she was afraid they'd find out she was the one who told.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said I have to do it because I don't want my friends to
be hurt,'' Hannah said. ``People call each other names every single
day. They just take it as normal. Sometimes it just gets out of
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Rugh said he's gotten more information about taunting since he
started this box. Once alerted, he talks to other witnesses, the
victim, the accused bully's friends, and finally the accused bully.
With that kind of evidence, he almost always gets a confession.
</P>
<P>
   He avoids casting it as, ``Johnny says you're picking on him all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Paybacks are a possibility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hannah and her friend are pleased with how those boys behave
now. Rugh said he's talked to about 40 kids (30 were warned) and he
hasn't had the same kids in twice once he's talked to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not dying to give suspensions. I'm not dying to give
detentions. I'm interested in getting a change in behavior,'' Rugh
said.
</P>
<P>
   All the middle school disciplinarians in this region face these
issues, but a sample of 11 schools found only three use written
notes, like Van Buren.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Eyler, eighth-grade principal at Northmont Middle School,
said two years ago that school began a two-week curriculum on
bullying. In those talks, teachers encourage students to tell
adults about incidents, or to leave a note in the mailbox if that's
easier.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, complaints have more than doubled. Eyler said he
gets at least one every day. The school has 1,050 seventh- and
eighth-graders. ``It's time to say no,'' he said. ``No more `boys
will be boys.'''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Mescher, assistant principal at West Carrollton Middle
School, said a peer mediation form helped convince students this
was important enough to tell administrators, not just their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were reluctant to (tell) in the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most assistant principals had not heard of this idea, even at
Kettering Middle School in the same district as Van Buren. But many
said it sounded like a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Fried said the option of writing a note helps kids get over
their fears about retaliation, and also is a good outlet for
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is to have schools acknowledge this
is really important,'' she said. ``These words and feelings don't
evaporate.''
</P>
<P>
   She said teens who are constantly victimized can become
depressed, even to the point of suicide, or can become filled with
rage. Students often skip school because they fear other students,
researchers have found.
</P>
<P>
   Rugh also works with the bullies' targets. Some have irritating
habits and seem to bring it on themselves, and he tells them that
although they didn't deserve it, they can prevent taunting by being
more mature.
</P>
<P>
   Others, he tries to pump up, saying, ``Do you really care what
that kid thinks? Your parents love you, teachers love you, you have
lots of friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Rugh doesn't know if it's reduced teasing, and said it would be
arrogant to claim that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely can't hurt,'' he said. But he has heard boys in
the hall say to each other: ``You better watch it, you're going to
end up in the Bully Box!''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
