<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLY-TIPS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keeping bullies at bay
 &HT;    By Mara Lee
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Parents can help their children deal with
bullying, whether they're witnesses, like the majority, bullies
(about 7 percent) or victims.
</P>
<P>
   Van Buren Middle School Assistant Principal Matt Rugh says:
``Listen, listen, listen. (Don't say) 'What's wrong with you?!'
It's got to be more than, `What'd you do in school today?'''
</P>
<P>
   Paula Fried, co-author of ``Bullies and Victims: Helping Your
Child Through the Schoolyard Battlefield'' (M. Evans and Co. Inc;
$19.95), says: ``Oftentimes parents don't know their kids are
bullies. Talk to them without shaming them. Help them to develop
empathy. Help (victimized kids) not to take the bullying
personally. This says more about the bully than the victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Victims can develop strategies, using a sense of humor to
deflate the bully with a one-liner, or just showing it's not
bothering them.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Mullin-Rindler, associate director of a bullying project
at the Wellesley College Center for Research on Women, says: Even
if your child is only a witness, remember they are touched by
bullying incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes them feel scared and anxious as well,'' she said.
``When bullying is unchecked, bystanders tend to lose a sense of
empathy for the victim and are more likely to join in the next
time.''
</P>
<P>
   She suggests the school's parent-teacher organization send
volunteers to watch at lunchtime and on the playground.
</P>
<P>
   WEB RESOURCES FOR PARENTS
</P>
<P>
   _ Safe Child program Web page:
http://www.safechild.org/bullies.htm
</P>
<P>
   WEB RESOURCE FOR CHILDREN
</P>
<P>
   http://www.childline.org.uk/bullying.html
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
