A3763 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LANE-COLUMN30-COX     11-29 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Payoff time for backyard citrus growers
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The orange crop is coming in early. The
fruit that survived summer's scorching heat, the winds of two
hurricanes, marauding middle-schoolers and a back yard rife with
destructive mutant insect life are glowing, yellow and bulging with
juice. It looks like a good crop this year.
</P>
<P>
   I am not a gardener by inclination. I am proud of the azaleas
because they take care of themselves, bloom madly in spring, and
don't bother anybody with a lot of demands the way roses and other
picky plants do. I extend this low-maintenance, laissez-faire
philosophy to my work as a gentleman citrus farmer.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, I forgot to do anything to the tree so I touted that
year's crop
</P>
<P>
   as organically grown. This year, however, I threw some
fertilizer on the ground during the summer, so I can make no such
claims. I will ertify that the tree is insecticide-free. I was too
cheap and pressed for time to extend insect-poisoning to the back
yard. Some call it laziness. I call it living in harmony with
nature.
</P>
<P>
   The bounty of this year's harvest runs contrary to the trend in
backyard citrus here. A series of freezes has killed back trees far
older and better tended than mine. Trees that once gave
juice-worthy fruit have been killed back to their sour and thorny
root-stock. They produce pretty oranges fit only for marmalade,
which involves arcane canning processes I do not understand.
</P>
<P>
   My backyard tree, although cut back substantially, was spared
such a fate by mere inches. Even if it hadn't, though,
fruit-quality has little to do with the backyard citrus ethos. It
has to do with living The Great Florida Myth and a little bit with
real-estate value.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us tend these trees because our friends, family and
acquaintances Up North consider orange trees outside the window to
be unspeakably exotic. They ooh and ahh and act surprised if you
allude to the matter. This may be
</P>
<P>
   helped along if you introduce the subject casually, as though
the
</P>
<P>
   things fall from the tree all year around and it's getting to be
real a
</P>
<P>
   hassle gathering them up all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Real-estate pros sometimes advise homesellers to plant banana
trees, orange trees and palms that don't naturally occur this far
north. That way, frost-belt homebuyers feel they are buying a piece
of a lush Caribbean land of fable and television travelogue. Their
very own bit of the Great Florida Myth, just like in the postcards.
Proof they are relocating to an exotic place.
</P>
<P>
   For the effort involved, it's far, far better than putting new
wallpaper on the bathroom walls.
</P>
<P>
   As easy as it is to impress out-of-town relatives with the tree,
there does come a time when you must face the practicalities of its
yield.
</P>
<P>
   More conscientious backyard citrus growers than myself take
every lost
</P>
<P>
   orange personally. Every one lying split on the ground in late
summer and early fall is a personal failing, a bad omen. They worry
for months over the vulnerable little green oranges as they ripen.
Then the first cool nights come and there's more fruit than you can
deal with.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious solution is to spread the bounty and give them to
friends. But you are not alone. Up and down the street, all through
the office, proud growers are pushing their citrus off on their
acquaintances and recipients dare not refuse. To turn down oranges
because you already have too many is like insulting somebody's dog.
Deep-seated feelings are exposed in these
</P>
<P>
   transactions.
</P>
<P>
   On receiving a home-grown orange, you must always act amazed and
grateful, as though the supermarket variety does not exist or is
too inferior to acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   And never, never, never compare them to your own. Comparing
oranges to oranges is acceptable only in elementary-school math
class.
</P>
<P>
   I'm going to admire mine for another week before picking them
and attempting to pass them off on my kids as a major treat.
</P>
<P>
   And if they don't play along, I've been saving the stickers from
the
</P>
<P>
   store-bought kind. If I stick the ``product of California''
labels on the
</P>
<P>
   backyard oranges, they may just eat them.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for the Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. E-mail:
</P>
<P>
   marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
