r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN30-COX     11-29 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Companionship has its rewards
 &HT;    (EDS: Note italics in second graf.)
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Although I've been traveling alone most of my
life, nothing leaves me with a more solitary feeling than the drive
from airport to empty house. Once I'm past the hassle of claiming
luggage and remembering where I parked the car, it's the same old
lonesome, long ride home.
</P>
<P>
   This trip it's late afternoon when I slide through the turnpike
toll booth, snatch a ticket from the maw of a machine that neither
welcomes me back nor wishes me safe journey, and meld into the flow
of traffic. I set the cruise control for three miles above the
speed limit, punch in the tape I'd been listening to on the way to
the airport, and think about why Jimmy Buffett's, ``Wish I Had a
Pencil-Thin Moustache'' always sounds so much better on my way
</P>
<P>
   (SET ITAL) out (END ITAL) of town.
</P>
<P>
   Along the south side of the highway is a string of pricey,
cookie-cutter condos. It's cocktail hour and I imagine couples
sitting down together, comfortable in their late afternoon ritual.
As I glance from one cubicle to the next, I can't help wondering if
all of the folks who live there are the same too. Do they buy the
same booze? Wear clothes with identical labels? Belong to the same
clubs, and maybe even go on the same cruises?
</P>
<P>
   Probably.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the kind of life I would choose, but that doesn't stop
me from envying the participants their twosomeness. Rather like the
couple sitting across from me earlier this afternoon in the Boston
airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Want a tangerine, Patrick?'' the lady asks the white-haired
gent slumped in the seat next to her. She gives him a minute but
when he just keeps fiddling with his bow tie instead of answering,
she repeats the question closer to his ear. ``Want a tangerine?''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick stirs and appears to be thinking up a response. Finally
he asks, ``Do I want a what?''
</P>
<P>
   His wife hollers back, ``A TANGERINE!'' Then she adds in a
normal voice, ``You couldn't hear if your pants were on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick takes a minute before he asks, ``What kind of a
tangerine you got?''
</P>
<P>
   His wife stares blankly out the window at a tiny commuter plane
pulling into the gate and then yells, ``SO HOW MANY KINDS OF
TANGERINES ARE THERE? YOU WANT ONE OR NOT?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Okay, okay,'' Patrick says, ``I'll eat a tangerine. You got a
paper towel?'' The couple settles down to what I suspect is
business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Patrick peels and sections the fruit, handing her husband
one
</P>
<P>
   segment at a time and watching carefully as he chews. ``SPIT THE
SEEDS,'' she reminds him. Patrick nods and zings one off his shoe.
She smiles and pats his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick and his wife aren't paying any attention to me but I'm
smiling too. Somewhere, way down inside, there's a part of me that
envies Mrs. Patrick. Hers is a life I understand.
</P>
<P>
   Smile sweetly, I was taught. Learn to cook if you can, and never
put starch in your husband's shorts. If you play nice, you'll live
happily ever after with a man who will smooth life's rough edges
for you.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the rules for millions of women my age now
functioning in a limbo land of semi-liberated females who, though
quite capable of fixing toilets and paying taxes, still miss
marriage. We feel sad driving expressways alone and knowing that if
we make a wrong turn, no one will notice when we're late for
supper. Or if we never show up at all.
</P>
<P>
   But we get over it and get on with it _ kind of like the
grey-haired lady on the shuttle bus this afternoon. Her ankles were
swollen over the tops of her shoes and she moved slowly, carefully
planting her cane to ensure each step. When a gentleman offered to
help with her suitcase she flashed him a broad smile and declined.
``I'm doing just fine,'' she said. ``I'm a little slow but I'm
</P>
<P>
   making it.'' On the last step she turned and added, ``But thanks
for asking.''
</P>
<P>
   I can identify with that and so can the millions of others like
me. Whether we need the help or not, it's still nice to be asked.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, Ohio 43431 or email: eschuett (AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
