<SLUG> BC-TECH-GADGETS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD kit removes scratches
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``We get calls from people all the time who are
surprised that Wipe Out actually works,'' said Marc Guest, CEO of
the company that manufactures the Wipe Out! CD Repair Kit. ``It's
pretty sad, but people aren't used to products that do exactly what
they claim to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Wipe Out, a product of the Esprit Development Corp. in
Flemington, N.J., promises to remove scratches from compact discs
and CD-ROMs. The company offers a money-back guarantee if Wipe Out
fails to permanently repair discs as advertised.
</P>
<P>
   Guest supplied Cox Newspapers with a Wipe Out sample, and it
worked quite well. It corrected the performance of one consistently
balky CD-ROM and removed a scratch from an intentionally damaged
music CD.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Wipe Out a kit is a bit of a stretch. What actually
comes in the box are instructions, a soft cloth and a bottle of
polishing liquid.
</P>
<P>
   To repair a CD, the user shakes up the polishing liquid and
applies a drop or two to the damaged CD. The user then places the
CD on a hard, flat surface and rubs the liquid into the surface for
a few seconds until the scratch disappears.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Wipe Out Web site, the damage CDs suffer is
usually in the plastic surface of the disc. The data is stored on a
metallic wafer under the plastic where it is protected.
</P>
<P>
   CDs fail when the laser in the CD player or CD-ROM drive
encounters a scratch in the plastic that makes it lose its place in
tracking the data on the metallic wafer underneath.
</P>
<P>
   Wipe Out is like a liquid sandpaper that removes the scratch and
returns the plastic to its original smooth condition.
</P>
<P>
   Wipe Out! CD Repair Kit won an Innovation Award at the 1999
Consumer Electronics Show. Guest said nearly 40,000 kits have been
sold so far with only 19 customers asking for refunds.
</P>
<P>
   Wipe Out sells for about $15, and Guest said it can be found at
Sam Goody and Tower Record stores. It also can be ordered online
from the Web site at www.cdrepair.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
