<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-WEBED30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Educational Web sites worth bookmarking
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   www.learn2.com _ The current Encyclopedia Brown of the Web,
learn2.com can help you with just about anything you'd want to
learn about, from roasting a turkey to serving as someone's best
man at a wedding. The guides on the site are clear, informative and
fun to read. Check it out and learn something new.
</P>
<P>
   www.dummies.com _ The folks behind the popular ``Dummies'' books
have cobbled together a site that takes the mystery out of not only
the high-tech world but also cooking, gardening, exercise and a
host of other subjects. Adding a daily comic strip to the mix,
dummies.com is for smarties like you.
</P>
<P>
   www.howto.yahoo.com _ If anybody knows how to find stuff on the
Internet, it's Yahoo, the most-used directory of sites on the
Internet. Yahoo's how-to guide covers the basics of Web surfing. It
starts with the reassuring message: ``Welcome to the Web. We're
glad you're here.'' A good place to start if you're new to the Net.
</P>
<P>
   www.ask.com _ Ask Jeeves is supposed to be a kind of Internet
butler _ you ask a question and without hesitation Jeeves brings
you the answer. While the site doesn't always bring back exactly
what you're looking for, Ask Jeeves is the place to go when you
want to learn something basic, such as ``Where can I find a map of
Antarctica?'' A slightly different approach to the search engine,
you might get lucky and learn a thing or two from old Jeeves.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
