<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    E-cards perfect for the forgetful
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It never fails on a holiday. There were people _
people you care about _ whom you forgot.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the turkey reduced to sandwiches, it's time to make
amends.
</P>
<P>
   That's where electronic greeting cards come in.
</P>
<P>
   They are out of the ordinary and clever, but _ better yet _ they
arrive instantly. After all, you don't have any time to waste.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with a site called Blue Mountain at www
</P>
<P>
   .bluemountain.com/. It's probably the largest electronic
greeting card site on the Web and has plenty of cards to choose
from.
</P>
<P>
   You'll be able to add music (there's a good selection) and pick
from sentiments that range from sticky sweet to downright
businesslike. Of course, as with most of these sites, you can also
customize your message.
</P>
<P>
   One of the neat features of this site is the ability to send
cards in severallanguages, including Japanese. Now that the world _
largely thanks to the Internet _ is a smaller family, the ability
to send messages tailored to other cultures is a real plus.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you're really international, you should check out
the Digital Postcard at www.all-yours.net/program
</P>
<P>
   /start20?write. If you thought it was neat to be able to send a
card in Japanese, just wait until you see the language selection
there. Maybe if you send your card saying in Arabic or Turkish,
they'll be so distracted that they will forget all about your
social lapse.
</P>
<P>
   The cards at this site can really be customized, and there's
also a database of more than 1,000 photos if you want to get fancy.
You can also include a link to a Web page with your card. If you
have your own Web site, you'll be able to add personal photos. You
can also upload a music or voice file.
</P>
<P>
   One site that is gaining in popularity is called Regard.Com at
www.regards.com/. Like some of the other sites, you can use your
own photos and images here. But one of the real pluses is the
unique animated cards that are available on this site.
</P>
<P>
   Some are so elaborate that they're very much like sending a tiny
cartoon to your friends.
</P>
<P>
   Since one of the card categories here is based on the seasons of
the year, perhaps you can send your friends a card celebrating fall
and forget about Thanksgiving altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Those who follow trends on the Internet and the Web know that
Amazon.com wants to become the one stop for almost everything on
the Web _ with its new hardware section, literally including the
kitchen sink.
</P>
<P>
   So you won't be surprised to learn that you can also find
electronic greeting cards there.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will you be surprised to learn that these are some of the
best cards on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   We talked about animation earlier, but some of these cards have
animated photos, not cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   It's well worth a visit over to cards.amazon.com to see what is
available.
</P>
<P>
   A site called Digital Greetings hangs its hat on the ability to
make a custom card. This Web page is located at www
</P>
<P>
   .digitalgreetings.com/create
</P>
<P>
   .html. Creating a card is a step-by-step process, and even for
slow learners, it's pretty simple. You pick out illustrations,
headlines and colors, and finally you end up with a card that you
created yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
