A3780 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECHNOBUDDY30-COX     11-29 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Failures are possible Jan. 1 _ just like on any other day
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I have a basement, but it is not filled with bottled
water (one gallon per person per day); nor is there any
freeze-dried food (I favor the beef stroganoff); and the only thing
down there that resembles a firearm is an old soldering gun.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I should feel guilty. Or at least get with the program.
Lately I've watched serious-sounding people on TV advise me on what
I should store to be safe when the world ends because of the Y2K
computer problems.
</P>
<P>
   All these shows seem to operate with the same script. First, I
am assured that it is foolish to worry. The public relations folks
_ all with nice hair _ from the electric, phone and water companies
tell me that all will be fine. Then these same people start talking
about pouring water into old plastic Coke bottles. It brings back
memories of fallout shelters and the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think there will be a disaster in the United States from
Y2K. But like the experts I see on television, I can't write out an
ironclad guarantee that I'm correct. Some smart people agree with
me; some smart people disagree. So you'll have to decide for
yourself how much to worry.
</P>
<P>
   Today I think I can serve you best by telling you what does
worry me about the Y2K hysteria. Unlike my opinion on how serious
the problem is, I can look you in the eye and tell you that what
you're about to hear is both important and true.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start with the fact that almost everyone has heard of Y2K.
And there are movies and books that paint apocalyptic pictures of
what it will bring.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the serious attempts on television and in print
to explain Y2K in a fair and honorable way. That means that _ even
in these fair reports _ all the possibilities, including worst-case
scenarios, are explained.
</P>
<P>
   So you have a population that has at least heard about some of
the things that can go wrong. Some of them are like you _ smart,
informed and calm. And there are some idiots, too, the folks who
have been storing guns in the basement along with the basmati rice
and Coke bottles full of water.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if you will the panic that will result if the power goes
out on New Year's Eve, or the day before. Or if one of these people
picks up the telephone to order a pizza and is met by silence. My
gosh a'mercy, it's the end of the world. Grab the Colt and feed in
a clip, lock the doors, and watch the neighbor a few houses down
closely ... he's always seemed odd.
</P>
<P>
   Now here's what scares me.
</P>
<P>
   You can be sure that somewhere in Atlanta, somewhere in most
major cities, there will be lights that are out on New Year's Eve;
there will be phones that don't work, gas service that is
interrupted and water that doesn't flow.
</P>
<P>
   Any time you try to provide these essential services to a few
million people every hour of every day, there will be outages.
Stuff breaks. Cars hit utility poles. Switches fail. Humans make
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   When that happens on a typical day, people get annoyed. But when
it happens on New Year's Eve or the next day _ and, like I said, it
will happen somewhere, maybe to you _ I worry that the result could
make the hysteria from the ``War of the Worlds'' radio broadcast
seem mild.
</P>
<P>
   So _ and I'm kidding, but just a little _ maybe you should spend
New Year's Eve in your basement with the doors locked. I think
you'll be completely safe from glitches caused by the utilities
(besides, even if I'm wrong, it's a fact that humans can live for
hours on end without running water, electricity or telephones). But
I do think that _ given the hysteria _ the basement would be a
terrific place to see in the New Year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 1050EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
