<SLUG> BC-TECH-KIDGIFTS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Great game gifts
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Deck the halls, light the menorah, jingle the
bells and have a happy Kwanzaa. It's holiday time, and that means
two things: 1) a temporal joy and peace in the world and 2) rampant
consumerism. While we can't help on the first item, we're all about
the second one. And here is the ultimate wish list for your tiny
anklebyter.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the ultimate object of his or her desire _ anything
Pokemon. The cards and stuffed animals are sure to be popular, but
think of the look on that little tyke's face when you bust out
Hasbro's interactive Pokemon Pikachu Plush ($10, www. pokemon.com).
The Pikachu is interactive in that you squeeze its hands and it
says the word that drives the kids wild, Pikachu! Also, its cheeks
glow red.
</P>
<P>
   Next on the list is Barbie. We know. Barbie used to be a WASPY,
disproportionate sex symbol who made little girls feel inadequate
if they didn't have a tiny waist and huge breasts and date a guy
named Ken. But Barbie has changed. Granted, she's still most of
those things. The difference can be found in Mattel's Working Woman
Barbie ($30, www. mattel.com). That's right, Barbie has gone to
work and she wants to talk all about it. With a touch of a button,
the day-job Barbie says lots of cool things like: ``I have
e-mail!'' ``I love going to work!'' and ``I can't wait to go
dancing with Ken tonight!'' Working Woman Barbie comes equipped
with a laptop, cell phone and a CD-ROM that enables you to design
your own stationery and do lots of other cool stuff.
</P>
<P>
   When you're done playing your own holiday games and checking
your e-mail for electronic greetings, install Michelle Kwan Figure
Skating ($30, www.ea.com, for PC) for her. In this game, would-be
figure skaters can create their own skaters (they can even use
their own photo and paste it on the character), design a routine,
land triple lutzes and take snapshots of the results. It scores
about a 5.7.
</P>
<P>
   While she's playing with Barbie and spinning Michelle Kwan, he
should be playing with his pal, 2000. Toy Biz's My Pal 2000 ($40,
1-800-634-7539) will surely be a hit this holiday season. This
14-inch handy robot and trusting pal pitches tiny foam balls for a
mini baseball game, plays interactive games with its owner and acts
as a sentry ``guarding'' a child's room from nosey siblings. Along
those lines is Tiger Electronics' new Furby Baby ($25, www.tiger
toys.com). You've met the parents, now meet a chattering younger
generation of Furbies. The Furby babies have 25 percent more
vocabulary and the programmers have added more games and the
ability to insert a pacifier when the Furby gets fussy (and it will
get fussy).
</P>
<P>
   Back on the PC, it's time for Disney's Villains' Revenge _ an
inspired set of games that works on both PCs and Macs. Run the
two-disc CD-ROM and let the kids go to town. The game, in which
Jiminy Cricket guides you through fixing seven classic Disney
stories including Dumbo and Peter Pan, is an animated treat that's
fun, gorgeously animated and easy to play.($30, www.
disneyinteractive.com)
</P>
<P>
   If your little one is more into the console side of things, you
shouldn't miss getting him or her either Universal's Spyro the
Dragon: Ripto's Rage ($50, www.universal.com, for the Playstation)
or Sony's Umjammer Lammy ($50, www.playstation. com, for the
Playstation). This is the second Spyro and he is better than ever.
This game looks better, plays faster and will keep your child more
mesmerized than the last one. And then there's Umjammer Lammy. What
can you say about Umjammer? This game is from the same bent minds
that brought you Parappa the Rapper. Only this time you're trying
to get Umjammer and her band MilkCan to the gig on time. Trust us.
It's great.
</P>
<P>
   Though we can't guarantee your children will have a merry
whatever, we can assure you that, with all these gifts in front of
them, they'll be so busy playing that they won't have time to
complain until the next holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
