<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ergonomic keyboard odd, may be useful
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An outfit called Goldtouch has sent me its new
``advanced ergonomic system,'' which includes a keyboard, a mouse,
a mousepad, two wrist rests and a separate numeric keypad.
</P>
<P>
   It's making me seasick.
</P>
<P>
   The keyboard is hinged in the middle. You can splay the two
sides out. You can also raise the middle of it. Once you have it
just the way you want it, you can lock the whole thing down
securely.
</P>
<P>
   My problem is that I never learned to type properly. I taught
myself, and my technique often involves a little cross-handed work.
Try that on a split keyboard and see what it gets you. I commonly
go for the B key with my right forefinger, and with this keyboard I
keep sticking it into the ditch.
</P>
<P>
   To make the keyboard smaller, Goldtouch dispensed with the
right-side keypad and uses a function key to turn the letter keys
on the right half into numeric ones. If that bothers you, you can
get the keypad.
</P>
<P>
   They've also moved the delete key clear to the left corner of
the keyboard, which really flummoxes me.
</P>
<P>
   The mouse is a two-button affair shaped like a buffalo with a
bad list to starboard. It is rather light, but works fine, although
I was never able to properly install its software.
</P>
<P>
   The keyboard is quite heavy and has a good touch. The mousepad
sticks to the desktop, has a slight slope to the right and has the
distinction of being the only mousepad I've seen that comes with a
user's manual.
</P>
<P>
   The manual goes on about things like splay, ulnar deviation,
lateral inclination and pronation. It also warns that the keyboard
is not intended for purposes such as controlling nuclear facilities
or weapons systems.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't do things like that, and you have problems with
your ergs, take a look at it. It seems reasonably priced at $219.
More info:www.goldtouch.com.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYFUL MOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Logitech's new Wingman Gaming Mouse, so far as I know, is the
first mouse oriented toward game-playing. Just what makes it a
gaming mouse, other than advertising and the inclusion of a
Japanese game of no particular distinction, is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   It is a sturdy, handsome mouse, gray in color, and of course,
being from Logitech, it has three buttons. It has a shape
distinctly different from two-button Microsoft mice.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the functions of the device are adjustable through
software. One, however, is not, and that is the sensitivity of the
buttons. Perhaps they are so hair-trigger because this is a Gaming
Mouse, or perhaps I'm just heavy-handed. When I sweep the cursor
across the screen, I leave a trail of menus and dialog boxes
flashing along behind.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the buttons are too easily depressed, both in and out of
games. Otherwise, it's dandy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
