<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pondering panda facts
 &HT;    By Theresa Walsh Giarrusso
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The giant pandas are finally on exhibit at Zoo
Atlanta. More than 10,000 visitors flocked to see them during their
opening weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Because the lines are long, we didn't want you to have to wait
to meet them. In honor of our panda friends, NFK presents this very
special super creature feature!
</P>
<P>
   YANG YANG (pronounced yahng yahng)
</P>
<P>
   _ I'm the boy: I was born Sept. 9, 1997, at the Chengdu Research
Base in China.
</P>
<P>
   _ Parents: My mother is Ya Ya, a panda at the Chengdu base. My
father is unknown. I remained with my mom for 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the scales: I weigh 180 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   _ I'm a daredevil: As a young cub, I spent several days trying
to learn to climb a tree. When I finally conquered the canopy, I
didn't know how to get down, and I ended up falling on my head. I
wasn't really hurt. I just kept playing!
</P>
<P>
   LUN LUN (pronounced loon-loon)
</P>
<P>
   _ I'm the girl: I was born Aug. 25, 1997, at the Chengdu
Research Base in China.
</P>
<P>
   _ Parents: My mother is Bing Bing. My father is Lin Lan. I was
separated from my mom when I was 4 months old.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rock 'n' roll girl: I was named by a Taiwanese rock star, Su
Huilun, who ``adopted'' me in China.
</P>
<P>
   _ Proud of her size: I weigh 160 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   _ I feel pretty: I'm considered very beautiful, because my
cheeks are round and fluffy. The Chinese people see round faces as
beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   PANDA FACTS
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Ailaropada melanoleuca.
</P>
<P>
   We've been around for years: Our species has existed since the
Pleistocene Era, about 600,000 years ago. But now we're dying out:
We don't breed well in captivity. There are about 110 to 120 of us
in captivity, mostly in China. Only three zoos in the United States
exhibit giant pandas: the San Diego Zoo; the National Zoo in
Washington, D.C.; and, of course, Zoo Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   We'll get bigger: As adults, our species grows to be 4 to 6 feet
long and may weigh up to 350 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Growing old together: In the wild, pandas usually live 16 to 18
years. In captivity, the average life expectancy is about 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Where you'll find our friends: In the wild, we are found only in
the mountains of central China. We live in dense bamboo and
coniferous forests at altitudes of 5,000 to 10,000 feet. The
mountains are shrouded in thick clouds, with rain throughout the
year.
</P>
<P>
   We like fiber in our diets: We live almost completely on bamboo,
and eat up to 40 pounds of it a day. We also eat irises, crocuses,
fish and occasionally small rodents. We can eat for as much as 16
hours of our day.
</P>
<P>
   Hometown bamboo: We didn't like the bamboo grown in Savannah,
Ga., so now we're munching on bamboo grown in the Atlanta area.
</P>
<P>
   Very hard to have babies: We reach sexual maturity between 4 and
6 years of age. Female pandas are in heat for only one to three
weeks of the year, usually between March and May.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky to survive: Our litters range from one to three cubs, but
usually only one survives.
</P>
<P>
   We're not like Yogi Bear: Unlike other bears, we do not
hibernate and cannot walk on our hind legs.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Zoo Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, we asked you to call us with questions you
wanted answered about the pandas. Here are some of those questions
and the answers we learned from the zoo experts:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why are giant pandas black and white?
</P>
<P>
   A: No one knows. Perhaps their coloration provides camouflage in
their forest habitats. There is a Chinese fable about a young girl
who loved pandas. When hunters came to shoot the pandas, she jumped
in front of them and was killed. The pandas expressed their grief
by rubbing their arms and legs with ashes. Their eyes became black
when they wiped away their tears, and their shoulders became black
as they hugged to console each other.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could scientists clone them?
</P>
<P>
   A: It might be possible to clone pandas, but because essential
social skills are acquired during the time infants spend with their
mothers, it would not be a very successful way of saving the
species.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do they mate for life?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, bears do not mate for life. Both females and males may
have several mates during their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will people speak to them in Chinese even though they're in
Atlanta?
</P>
<P>
   A: Like other animals, they learn certain words and gestures
from their human keepers. Lun Lun and Yang Yang will have to get
used to hearing American voices speaking English. Fortunately, they
are very young and they seem to be very smart. They also have two
of their familiar human friends from China who will stay with them
for six months to help them make the transition.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do they have the same organs as humans?
</P>
<P>
   A: All mammals, including humans and bears, have the same basic
organs, such as hearts, lungs, stomachs, livers and kidneys.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are pandas gentle or would they maul a person if they could?
</P>
<P>
   A: Pandas have big sharp teeth and claws. They could hurt a
person if they felt threatened, but they are very gentle most of
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are they bears or raccoons?
</P>
<P>
   A: For many years, scientists have debated whether pandas should
be classified as bears, raccoons, or a separate family all their
own. This debate is because the giant panda and its cousin, the
lesser or red panda, share many characteristics with both bears and
raccoons. Recent DNA analysis indicates that giant pandas are more
closely related to bears, and red pandas are more closely related
to raccoons. Accordingly, giant pandas are now categorized in the
bear family while red pandas are categorized in the raccoon family.
You can visit both giant pandas and red pandas at Zoo Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
