<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Retired UGA mascot dies
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Uga V, retired bulldog mascot of the University of
Georgia football team, died last week. He was buried with his
ancestors at the university's football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Uga V was the UGA mascot from 1990 until this fall, when he was
succeeded by his son, Uga VI. High points in his career came in
1996, when he went after an Auburn football player who came too
close, and in 1997, when Sports Illustrated named him the best
college football mascot.
</P>
<P>
   The Uga bulldogs are owned by the family of Frank ``Sonny''
Seiler of Savannah, Ga. ``It's a very significant loss,'' Seiler
said of Uga V's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was probably the most active of all the dogs and was a
great mascot for the university and its athletic teams. But he was
also a family pet, and it's always very traumatic to lose one.''
</P>
<P>
   BIBLE COURSES IN PUBLIC SCHOOLS?
</P>
<P>
   Some Georgia public schools have discussed adding courses on
Bible history, and the state school superintendent supports the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   But Georgia Attorney General Thurbert Baker, the chief lawyer
for the state government, warned last week that such courses might
not be legal.
</P>
<P>
   The problem: The Constitution says government, which includes
public schools, can't establish a religion. Baker said any Bible
courses would have to serve a nonreligious purpose, and they
couldn't be used to promote any religion.
</P>
<P>
   The state School Board will discuss Bible courses more when it
meets on Dec. 9.
</P>
<P>
   CLASS GETS 29,000 MESSAGES
</P>
<P>
   The results are in for the fifth-graders at Douglasville's Bill
Arp Elementary School who began a global e-mail campaign as a
geography project in September.
</P>
<P>
   In just two weeks, the kids received nearly 27,500 e-mails. Then
Yahoo closed their e-mail account.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 1,589 letters and postcards had come by snail mail
when the project ended Nov. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the coolest things to come from this project is the pen
pals we have gotten,'' said teacher Robert Blevins. ``Many of the
kids now have individual e-mail pen pals, but the class as a whole
is also writing to a class at the International School in
Austria.'' The students' next project is to find out what those
kids think about the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
