<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News ServiceQ: I'm in charge of putting together a
<TEXT>
special ceremony honoring three Eagle Scouts, one of whom is my
son. I've heard that you can hire someone to bring in a live eagle
and then talk about why the eagle is used as the symbol of Boy
Scouting's highest award. Any ideas on how to find such a person? _
Sue Leininger
<P>
   A: Contact Last Chance Forever, a nonprofit organization
dedicated to the rehabilitation and release of injured birds of
prey in San Antonio, Texas. A Golden Eagle and his handler will
make an appearance in exchange for a donation, says executive
director John Karger. Sounds like a good deal all around. Call
(210) 499-4080. For details click onwww.lastchanceforever.org
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a leather jacket, fairly new, that's just dusty from
hanging in the closet. No stains, no cracks or anything like that.
Checked with the cleaners on the charge and YIKES!, didn't realize
it was that high. Is there anything I can do at home to spruce it
up without taking it to the cleaners? As I said, it's not really
dirty, just dusty. But because of what the jacket cost, I don't
want to take a chance and mess it up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Linda Schoener
</P>
<P>
   A: Pick up some Aristocrat All Purpose Leather Cleaner and
Conditioner. Use a sponge with a little warm water to clean the
jacket and then wipe with a damp rag, advises Tenderfoot's Sharon
Howell. Then condition the jacket with Kiwi Mink Oil. Q: I wonder
why some waiters and waitresses at some restaurants are able to
work with their order book stuck down the back of their pants. It
seems that it should be violating some sort of health law. It
grosses me out. Am I the only person who thinks there is something
wrong with this? _ Pat S.
</P>
<P>
   A: No. It is ``an unhygienic practice,'' says retail foods
sanitarian Mike Rouff of the Texas Department of Health. Reporting
such behavior to the local health authority may not prove
productive, as the inspector would have to witness such behavior in
order to do something about it. Tell the manager what you have seen
the server do. If management does not respond, take your business
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Please ask your readers for help to get the Kombucha mushroom
for an old lady who needs it desperately as a medicinal aid. I have
taken it for years and cannot find it.
</P>
<P>
   _ E. Guzzardo
</P>
<P>
   A: Will you settle for the extract, tea or capsules? All are in
stock at Whole Foods Market. According to the Food and Drug
Administration, this tea contains acids commonly found in foods
such as vinegar. The tea should be stored only in glass or metal
containers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to go see manta rays. They are huge, beautiful sea
creatures. I am wondering if there is a fairly reliable place to go
see them. _ Jane L.
</P>
<P>
   A: Stake out their food. The largest member of the ray family
(Stevie, Sugar and Manta), manta rays can reach 19 feet long and
weigh 2,300 pounds on a diet of plankton. Manta rays gather around
reliable feeding and cleaning areas in tropical waters like Kona,
Hawaii and the Cayman Islands. Download manta ray images from
www.mantaray.com, where you also will find information on the Manta
Ray Bay Hotel in Micronesia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a moon plant and have no instructions on what to do
with it.
</P>
<P>
   _ L.K.
</P>
<P>
   A: If the moon plant, a vine with white blooms similar to the
morning glory, is potted, place it in a sunny window until spring,
advises James Owens of Sledd's Nursery. Then plant the perennial in
your garden in full sun where it will receive adequate water. If
the moon plant is already in the ground, cut it back, mulch the
area to protect it from winter cold, and hope the plant returns in
the spring. Q: Here's an interesting millennial question: At what
place on our planet does each new day officially start? In other
words, where on Earth will the year 2000 begin?
</P>
<P>
   _ Chris R. Glenn
</P>
<P>
   A: The first spot you can find west of the international date
line is where the new year starts (near the 180th meridian). The
line is rather jagged, an attempt to keep countries on the same
day. Until recently Kiribati, for example, was a country split by
the date line. The line now jogs east to include Caroline Island.
It claims to be a great place to welcome 2000. Other sites include
Fiji, where the line passes through places such as Udu Point, Rabi
Island and Taveuni, and Gisborne, New Zealand, which bills itself
as the first city in the world to see the dawn of the new year.
Feel like going all out? Put your name on the waiting list for the
``Around the World Millennium Expedition by Private Jet'' offered
by Seattle's TCS Expeditions. Having paid about $45,000 each,
passengers are whisked to the Polynesian island of Tonga to be one
of the first to see the dawn of the new year and then fly on to
Western Samoa, one of the last places to welcome 2000. Whew!
</P>
<P>
   Purists argue the only place to start a day, New Year's or
otherwise, is in Greenwich, England, home of the prime meridian,
the degree line from which longitude east and west is measured.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You gave us advice on how to preserve a Lance Armstrong
Wheaties cereal box. What about a collectible model or toy with a
battery inside of it? Keep it or not? Will it affect its
collectibility?
</P>
<P>
   _ Wayne Z.
</P>
<P>
   A: Remove the battery before acid leaks out and ruins the toy,
says Chris Noah of Hog Wild Toys. Store collectible toys in a cool,
dry place. Q: Please tell me and others how to prune rosebushes and
when to fertilize them. _ Charles Kaase
</P>
<P>
   A: Minor pruning is done every time you cut a rose from the
bush, notes rose show judge and member of the American Rose Society
Don Freeman. Cuts should be made just above a set of leaves or you
risk causing disease in the plant. Major pruning (2/3 reduction in
the size of the bush) is done annually in February. However, if the
bush seems too tall to weather winter winds, Freemen advises taking
about 1/3 off the height of the bush now.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar:
</P>
<P>
   _ Getting ready to carol in the Lone Star State, newcomers?
Don't leave home without the words to the ``Twelve Days of
Christmas, Texas Style'': ``On the 12th day of Christmas, my true
love gave to me ... 12 bulls-a-snorting, 11 tumbleweeds
(weeds-a-tumblin'?), 10 politicians, 9 horned toads, 8 Dallas
Cowboys, 7 buckin' broncos, 6 bluebonnets, 5 mockingbirds, 4
prickly pears, 3 oil wells, 2 pairs of spurs and an armadillo in an
oak tree.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Time for gift-giving games, readers. For a copy of the Night
before Christmas game, send me a stamped, self-addressed envelope.
Each participant brings an inexpensive gift. Players stand in a
circle while a moderator reads a text in which ``right'' and
``left'' often appear. Gifts are passed accordingly until the story
ends. Here is a snippet (Clement Moore, forgive us): ``He spoke not
a word but went RIGHT to his work, and filled all the stockings;
then turned with a jerk; and laying his finger to the LEFT of his
nose, and giving a nod....'' No one, of course, leaves with the
gift he brought.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
