 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Tuesday, November 30, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY30-COLUMN _ PARIS _ Sitting in a railroad station, got a
ticket for my destination ... I was humming an old Simon and
Garfunkel tune and wishing I could remember the words. This is the
Gare de Lyon, which, as best as I can figure, roughly translates as
``Look out for Leon.'' And who is this Leon I should guard against?
I wasn't sure until I was getting out of the taxi. There he was, a
little guy, all smiles, with a buggy for our luggage already in
place at the trunk of the taxi. (Murray, Cox Newspapers). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN _ Marilyn Geewax's weekly column looking at
issues raised by the coming of 2000. (Geewax, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Smile sweetly, I was taught.
Learn to cook if you can, and never put starch in your husband's
shorts. If you play nice, you'll live happily ever after with a man
who will smooth life's rough edges for you. Those were the rules
for millions of women my age now functioning in a limbo land of
semi-liberated females who, though quite capable of fixing toilets
and paying taxes, still miss marriage. We feel sad driving
expressways alone and knowing that if we make a wrong turn, no one
will notice when we're late for supper. Or if we never show up at
all. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The orange crop is coming in
early. The fruit that survived summer's scorching heat, the winds
of two hurricanes, marauding middle-schoolers and a back yard rife
with destructive mutant insect life are glowing, yellow and bulging
with juice. It looks like a good crop this year. (Lane, Daytona
Beach News-Journal) MOVED
</P>
