   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the current week. This
layout is available Tuesday after 2 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH 1130 _ Mars is just a bright dot in the sky on a
starry night, but personal computers and the Internet have brought
the Red Planet as close as your keyboard. (Gaffney, Dayton Daily
News ) Art includes one 4-column color photo illustration of mars.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MARS SITES LIST _ A list of Web sites to learn more about Mars.
(Gaffney, Dayton Daily News ) Art includes one 1-column color
illustration of a computer.
</P>
<P>
   GADGETS _ Now you can send your e-mail without using a personal
computer. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News) Art includes 1-column color
photo of VTech e-Mail PostBox.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ In diagnosing computer woes, start with the last
change made. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art includes 1
column color sig of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   TECH BRIEFS _ Online help is now available for holiday
overeaters. (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art includes
1-column color illustration of a Pokemon.
</P>
<P>
   GAME CORNER _ A new controller now offers a better grasp on the
PlayStation system (Staff, Austin American-Statesman) Art includes
1 1-column color photo of the Scorpion controller.
</P>
<P>
   PIRATE-MUSIC _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Record stores haven't gotten much
business from one 23-year-old University of Dayton senior lately _
and he may never give them a penny more. He gets his music free
from the Internet. Using the university's high-speed computer
lines, he and his friends download songs known as MP3 files from
web sites that post them illegally. He says his roommate has built
a trove of 2,000 songs, and that he has created his own compact
discs from Internet music. (Keilman, Dayton Daily News). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-WEBED _ A look at educational Web sites. (Gallaga, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-KIDGIFTS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Deck the halls, light the
menorah, jingle the bells and have a happy Kwanzaa. It's holiday
time, and that means two things: 1) a temporal joy and peace in the
world and 2) rampant consumerism. While we can't help on the first
item, we're all about the second one. And here is the ultimate wish
list for your tiny anklebyter. (Kallenberg, Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-GADGETS _ Wipe Out, a product of the Esprit Development
Corp. in Flemington, N.J., promises to remove scratches from
compact discs and CD-ROMs. The company offers a money-back
guarantee if Wipe Out fails to permanently repair discs as
advertised. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Popular column about personal computing written for
the average user. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ Software reviews. This week: Goldtouch's ergonomic
keyboard. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ What's new on the Web. This week: ``Overseas''
shopping on the Web. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ What's new on the Web. This week: Electronic cards.
(Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
