<P>
   CONSUMER-HEALTH _ Consumer column: How risky is an endoscopic
procedure? You'd probably rather have one poked down your throat or
in your ear, because ear-nose-throat doctors put protective sleeves
on theirs to prevent transmitting bacterial infections from one
patient to another. Colon-rectal docs don't do this, and say it's
not necessary. The incidence of infection is low _ only about 2
percent _ but real. What you should know if you're planning one of
these procedures. (Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-HEALTH Diabetic and heart-healthy cookbooks, internet
site, awareness days. (Guthrie/McKenna/Kim, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
