<HEADER>
A3802 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN30-C     11-29 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Broadcasters can rerun, but they can't hide
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As the Peacock crows, if you haven't seen it,
it's new to you. Conversely, if you have seen it, it's a rerun.
</P>
<P>
   But the broadcast networks want to keep you guessing.
</P>
<P>
   In January they say they'll drop the (R) designation they now
supply to TV listing services and publications like TV Guide.
Network executives argue that cable channels don't flag reruns, so
why should they? With viewers abandoning the networks in
ever-increasing numbers, executives don't want to put an exit sign
over their own doors.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Swanson, president of the watchdog group Viewers for
Quality Television, calls this ``a disservice to the viewer.'' In
an age of ever-expanding information, less information does seem
ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   The networks have been talking about axing the (R) for years,
but they reached the breaking point this fall when USA Network
began airing repeats of NBC's ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit''
less than two weeks after the original airdate without an (R).
Ditto Lifetime's same-week repeats of ABC's ``Once and Again.'' The
networks, which cut deals with the cable networks for the reruns to
offset production costs, felt the cable channels should have
designated the episodes as repeats. But the cable networks said the
programs were new to their channels and therefore new to their
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do cable channels, which came to life on the strength of
network reruns, alert viewers to multiple repeats of original
series such as ``The Sopranos'' and ``South Park.'' Syndicated
series such as ``Baywatch Hawaii'' keep their reruns secret, too.
</P>
<P>
   So the networks feel disadvantaged and plan to change. They
haven't agreed on a uniform plan, but one network executive favors
an (O) instead of an (R).
</P>
<P>
   ``My solution is to designate originals. Everything else would
not have a designation,'' says David Poltrack, senior vice
president of research and marketing at CBS. ``That way cable people
wouldn't have to label everything R. They'd just need to apply it
(an (O)) to their first-run originals.''
</P>
<P>
   If the other networks decide to drop all designations, the
viewers most affected will be ``appointment viewers,'' people who
rush home to catch an episode of ``Law &AMP; Order'' or religiously set
their VCRs for certain programs. They don't want to rush home for a
rerun. But most people aren't appointment viewers. They just plop
down and start flipping. They watch something new and sometimes
something old.
</P>
<P>
   Sitcoms do well in reruns, retaining 70 percent to 80 percent of
their original audience. Last summer, ``Friends'' finished at the
top of the Nielsens, just as it has this fall. Dramas don't do as
well, sometimes retaining little more than half their audience.
Repeats of TV movies and miniseries fare even worse.
</P>
<P>
   Reruns, of course, are a fact of life and an economic necessity.
Even in the earliest days of TV, series never aired year-round.
Some shows, like ``Playhouse 90,'' had 30 episodes a year and then
were replaced by another show. ``Gunsmoke'' had 39 originals and 13
repeats, always designated as reruns.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-'70s, when production costs began to rise and the
all-important ``sweeps'' months were instituted, it became
necessary to insert reruns during the regular season to have enough
originals for the May sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   Skyrocketing costs in the early '80s whittled the number of
originals from 28 or 30 down to the current 22. That means lots of
reruns long before summer.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the networks decide to drop all designations or use an
(O), viewers may still get the (R) from listings services and TV
Guide. That's because these services have their own databases and
can tell from episode titles and descriptions if a program is a
rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they would serve the viewers better by going with the
`Original,''' Poltrack says. ``That would allow the viewer to know
if the shows are ones they've seen or ones they just might have
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing research indicating viewers don't see as many first-run
episodes a year as they think they do _ probably less than half the
typical 22-episode run each season _ Poltrack figures ``the
probability is equal that the repeat is one they haven't seen.''
</P>
<P>
   If the networks adopt CBS's plan and switch from (R) to (O),
this whole flap will have been much ado about absolutely nothing.
Only the truly dull will not realize that a title without the (O)
is a rerun.
</P>
<P>
   But if the (R) is dropped and the (O) isn't added, listings
publications will add the (R) anyway _ thus leaving the networks
with a big (F) for fool on their faces.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
