 &HT;    With RIVERS.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A HEALTH REPORT ON MAJOR WORLD RIVER SYSTEMS
</P>
<P>
   Name; length; volume of water; condition.
</P>
<P>
   1. Amazon; 4,000 miles; 6,350,000 cubic feet per second;
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   2. Congo; 2,914 miles; 1,458,000 cubic feet per second; healthy.
</P>
<P>
   3. Ganges-Brahmaputra; 1,800 miles; 1,360,000 cubic feet per
second; very unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   4. Yangtze; 3,434 miles; 1,200,000 cubic feet per second;
unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   5. Mississippi-Missouri; 3,741 miles; 650,000 cubic feet per
second; unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   6. Nile; 6,650 miles; 110,000 cubic feet per second; unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   7. Volga; 2,293 miles; 282,000 cubic feet per second; unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   8. Mekong; 2,500 miles; 500,000 cubic feet per second; healthy.
</P>
<P>
   9. Rhine; 820 miles; 78,000 cubic feet per second; unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   10. Rio Grande; 1,885 miles; 3,000 cubic feet per second;
unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   11. Jordan; 223 miles; 615 cubic feet per second; unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   12. Murray-Darling; 2,350 miles; 400 cubic feet per second;
unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   13. St. Lawrence; 2,500 miles; 565,000 square miles; 360,000
cubic feet per second; healthy.
</P>
<P>
   14. Parana-Rio de la Plata; 2,485 miles; 777,000 cubic feet per
second; unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Encyclopedia Britannica, World Commission on Water For
the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
