A3876 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-VETERAN-TAXINGTALE-TE     11-29 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETERAN-TAXINGTALE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TAXING TALE OF A DISABLED VETERAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS VAUGHN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Susan Fitzpatrick thought her tax problem
was settled.
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service told Fitzpatrick, a former Marine,
that she shouldn't be paying taxes on her disability income from
the Department of Defense. The IRS then said it was going to cut
her a check for $11,000 for taxes she paid the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Case closed, right? Not in the least.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Finance and Accounting Service, which issues
retirement checks for military retirees, didn't fall in line with
the IRS. Instead, the defense agency maintains that, as far as it's
concerned, Fitzpatrick's income is taxable.
</P>
<P>
   Her nearly yearlong odyssey through the cubicles of the Defense
Finance and Accounting Service, the Pentagon and the IRS is replete
with contradictions, confusions and obscure subsections of federal
statutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have never dreamed it would have been this tough,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   By most everyone's account, if Fitzpatrick has been paying taxes
when the IRS says she shouldn't, there are doubtless other veterans
in the same boat who may not know it. No one knows how many that
could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the possibility this could affect others,'' said
Zanell Osowski, a spokeswoman for the defense finance agency in
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The story starts early this year when Fitzpatrick, a Marine of
14 years who retired on disability, read the fine print on her
10-99R tax form.
</P>
<P>
   The words ``disability retirement'' as nontaxable leaped out at
Fitzpatrick, a former Marine liaison at Bell Helicopter and now a
stay-at-home mom in far north Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick was retired in 1995 by a team of doctors who
believed that her migraines and her myasthenia gravis, which causes
progressive muscular weakness, made her unfit for duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called DFAS immediately,'' she said, hoping the matter would
be cleared up quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick said she was given a variety of explanations by the
defense finance agency as to why her disability pay was taxable.
Regardless of the reason, she was told, she did not fit the
criteria for nontaxable status.
</P>
<P>
   The defense finance agency wasn't swayed when she received a
letter from the IRS telling her that she was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``This letter reflects an IRS determination concerning Ms.
Fitzpatrick's personal tax liability,'' Osowski said. ``The letter
does not indicate any change in DFAS' responsibility to report the
disability retired pay as income.''
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement is caused by the agencies' use of different
regulations to determine taxability. The defense finance agency
cites the Defense Department Financial Management Regulation; the
Pentagon cites the U.S. Federal Code; and the IRS uses the Internal
Revenue Code. The wording, while similar, differs in each.
</P>
<P>
   Until Fitzpatrick receives a rating from the Department of
Veterans Affairs designating how disabled she is, the Pentagon says
her income is taxable. She has applied for VA benefits this year in
order to get that rating.
</P>
<P>
   But Richie Heidenreich, a spokesman for the IRS in Dallas,
seemed troubled that his agency's determination could not help
Fitzpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that bothers me is that she has a letter that says
it is not taxable, so I don't understand the reason for the
argument,'' Heidenreich said. ``But I know of no way we can force
the Department of Defense or Department of Energy or any other
government agency to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Van Riper, the Tarrant County Veterans Service Officer,
also seemed incredulous that Fitzpatrick, and probably others, are
paying taxes needlessly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I've ever run across a situation like
this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm has stepped in on behalf of Fitzpatrick and two
other Texans who have similar questions, asking the IRS and defense
finance lawyers to provide him an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   And the defense finance agency, Osowski said, is ``now looking
at the big picture'' and has referred the issue to the Armed Forces
Tax Council for a review of current procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS asked Fitzpatrick to submit amended tax returns for
1995, 1996 and 1997 and 1998, and refunded her taxes. And until the
situation is resolved, the IRS says she needs to send a copy of the
IRS letter with any future tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick is in perhaps the rare position of praising the IRS,
which she said was ``wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could say the same for DFAS,'' she said. ``My
frustration with DFAS is that all I need really to make the system
work is a corrected 10-99. But they report to the IRS that every
penny I receive is taxable income.''
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who wants an IRS opinion on whether his military
disability income is nontaxable, write to the Internal Revenue
Service Taxpayer Advocate's Office, 1100 Commerce St., Mail Code
1005, Dallas, TX 75242.
</P>
<P>
   (Chris Vaughn is a reporter for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7547, or e-mail:
cvaughn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
