<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-UNIONISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY PROTESTANTS IN ULSTER ACCEPT A SHARING OF POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ While the party that represents most
Protestants in Northern Ireland was approving a deal to share power
with people who once used bombs and bullets to make the place
ungovernable, its hard-line rivals were gathering on the outskirts
of this old Victorian city to denounce what they call treachery.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of venues Saturday was telling.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionists gathered at the Waterfront Hall, a
glistening, modern concert hall on the River Lagan that has so much
glass it would have been considered folly to construct it before
the peace process blossomed with the paramilitary cease-fires of
1994.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Rev. Ian Paisley's smaller, more hard-line
Democratic Unionists gathered at La Mon House Hotel, where 12
Protestants were killed by an IRA bomb in 1978. Paisley, a
fundamentalist preacher, invoked God's wrath on David Trimble, the
Ulster Unionist leader, describing him as a liar and a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   Protestants who want to retain Northern Ireland's union with
Britain are at a crossroads. But as the choice of venues on
Saturday showed, while some want to focus on the promise of the
future, others find it impossible to let go of the past.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on Saturday by the Ulster Unionists to drop their
insistence that the Irish Republican Army begin disarming before
they share power with Irish Catholic nationalists, including
members of Sinn Fein, the IRA's political wing, marked a sea change
in unionist thinking. It was a political manifestation of a growing
confidence among Protestants here.
</P>
<P>
   When it was created by fiat in 1920 by a British government that
drew a border to ensure a population of 1.5 million that was loyal
to the British crown, Northern Ireland was what one of its leaders
once proclaimed ``a Protestant state for a Protestant people.''
</P>
<P>
   But demographic changes, a growing Catholic middle class, a
British government that acknowledges there was institutional
discrimination against Catholics, and an increasingly secular
society make that an empty claim today. Catholic nationalists, even
republicans who supported violence to overthrow British rule,
realized that some years ago, and adopted a more moderate,
conciliatory stance.
</P>
<P>
   Now a growing number of Protestant unionists are doing the same,
accepting that the old days are lost and gone forever, that their
future is best served by creating a Northern Ireland that
accommodates Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 80 years, accommodating Catholic nationalists and
maintaining the union with Britain were considered mutually
exclusive goals by the vast majority of Protestants. But a growing
number of unionists are becoming, like Trimble's political tactics,
increasingly pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of marginalizing nationalists who aspire to unity with
the Irish Republic, many unionists now seek to convince them that
their rights and aspirations will be respected, and their living
standard higher, if Northern Ireland remains part of the United
Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Power-sharing, long considered the most effective way to address
the grievances of Catholics, is to begin in earnest this week as 10
people are nominated for seats in the Cabinet that will administer
local government for the first time since 1972. Among them will be
two members of Sinn Fein, including Martin McGuinness, once the
IRA's chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   It galls most Protestants that the man who once directed what
they saw as a terrorist campaign aimed at driving them from the
island will now help run a democratically elected government. The
IRA had a different view of what it considered a war of
self-determination against British rule.
</P>
<P>
   But a growing number of Protestants, such as Michael and Heather
Bambrick, accept power-sharing as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bambrick, an accountant, and his wife are about to
launch a new business together. They have four children between the
ages of 4 and 11 and live in Holywood, a comfortable Belfast
suburb. They heartily supported the decision to let Sinn Fein into
government, and believe that political stability will change
everything in Northern Ireland for the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the changes in attitude you see among the Protestant
and unionist people are about confidence,'' said Bambrick. ``It
takes bravery and confidence to put on a different set of
spectacles and try to understand what different people aspire to.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Lee, 37, who drives a breakdown assistance car for the
Royal Automobile Club, spent his life in a middle-class section of
East Belfast, which is staunchly unionist and entirely Protestant.
He said the Troubles never really touched him, although it was only
because he got delayed that he was not at the nearby La Mon House
Hotel attending the function that was bombed 21 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lee voted for the Good Friday Agreement that calls for power
sharing and for cross-border authorities that will oversee areas of
mutual interest on the island. He is not threatened by closer links
to the Irish Republic, and believes enough Catholics can be
reassured to retain the link with Britain indefinitely. He also
supports the compromise that lets Sinn Fein into government on the
promise that the IRA will turn in weapons later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it,'' he said, ``but we've got to move forward.
We can't go back to the old days.''
</P>
<P>
   By sheer demographics, there is no going back to the old days,
said Tim Pat Coogan, who came to Belfast this month to write a new
epilogue to his book ``The IRA.'' Coogan argued that Catholics, who
now make up about 43 percent of the population, will overtake
Protestants as a majority in Northern Ireland within 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Many unionists dispute the demographic changes Coogan and others
claim will change the balance of power here over the next
generation. But even they acknowledge that as the percentage of the
Catholic population rises, their task is to convince enough
nationalists that, like the 6 million Irish people living in
England, they can be Irish and live happily in the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble said his party ``recognizes and accepts that it is
legitimate for nationalists to pursue their political objective of
a united Ireland by consent through exclusively peaceful and
democratic methods.''
</P>
<P>
   Consent is the critical word. For most of this century, Irish
republicans refused to accept that they needed to seek that
consent, and unionists considered it treasonous to give such a
prospect legitimacy. But that has all changed.
</P>
<P>
   For all the doomsaying by the likes of Paisley, who says
Northern Ireland is being destroyed by concessions to the IRA, the
place has never looked better. New hotels, pubs, and restaurants
have sprung up in Belfast and beyond. At 7 percent, unemployment
has been almost halved in the past 15 years and is at its lowest
levels ever.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of traditional industries like textiles and
shipbuilding have been more than made up for by the emergence of
software, pharmaceuticals, and telephone-based service industries,
according to Jill Heron of the Department for Economic Development.
Heron said some investors have hung back, waiting to see where the
peace process was going. If the political stability promised last
week is realized, new investment, especially in tourism, will
follow, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many problems remain. The segregation of Catholics and
Protestants in housing and education remains almost total. But
there is a growing sense that they are all in it together, Trimble
said.
</P>
<P>
   Owen Lamont, head of the Northern Ireland Chamber of Commerce,
agreed, and is backing Trimble's attempt to make official the
pledge ``to promote mutual respect and tolerance rather than
division and alienation.''
</P>
<P>
   If unionists once derided the Republic of Ireland as a
priest-ridden economic basket case, they now want to emulate its
``Celtic Tiger'' economy, the most vibrant in Europe in the 1990s.
Like other business leaders here, Lamont believes political
stability will bring enormous investment.
</P>
<P>
   Given the chance, he said, expressing the newfound confidence,
``Northern Ireland can make the Celtic Tiger look like a kitten.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
