<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3901 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HOLISTIC-LAWYERS-ART-     11-29 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLISTIC-LAWYERS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERING WITH A HEART' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Six of them, all attorneys, gathered around a
conference table strewn with brownbag lunches and store-bought
salads. They spanned a wide spiritual divide _ a Methodist
minister, a traditional Buddhist, a Zen practitioner, a mystical
Jew.
</P>
<P>
   Their monthly luncheon followed a familiar pattern: warm
greetings and casual chat flowed into a free-ranging discussion on
a chosen topic. One fall Friday afternoon, the issue was
forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Facial expressions grew thoughtful as Douglas Reynolds, a senior
partner at a leading Boston law firm, offered a quote he heard not
long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Forgiveness, he said to the five attorneys seated with him in a
meeting room at Suffolk Law School, is ``giving up all hope of a
better past.''
</P>
<P>
   From this, a question arose. How can lawyers teach their clients
forgiveness in a legal system that encourages aggrieved parties to
settle their differences in court?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trained in law school to disregard any human problem
that can't be litigated,'' said Edmund Robinson, a lawyer and
ordained Methodist minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to look at clients in the context of their whole lives
and mindsets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They call themselves holistic lawyers, a description that would
strike the more cynical as the ultimate oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to bring deeper meaning to a profession widely
derided as morally bankrupt, they meet once a month over
plastic-wrapped sandwiches and take-out meals, discussing ways to
bring healing and humanism to the legal world.
</P>
<P>
   They range from academics to solo practitioners to attorneys at
big corporate firms, but they share common traits: a spirituality
they long to bring to their professional lives, and both a passion
for and quiet disillusionment with the practice of law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some within our group would probably call us preventative
lawyers,'' said group cofounder Cheryl Conner, a former federal
prosecutor who now teaches law at Suffolk. ``Lawyers who want to
understand the root causes of conflict and legal
misunderstandings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a mentality out there that lawyers are sharks out to
hurt people and get their money,'' said attorney Rita Pollak, a
family law practitioner and the group's other cofounder. ``This
group is a counterbalance to that view.''
</P>
<P>
   That there is a crisis of the heart within the legal profession
is well documented. Study upon study and poll after poll have found
that growing numbers of lawyers are profoundly troubled by the
changing practice of law.
</P>
<P>
   Their discontent has many sources: the competitive ruthlessness
that has accompanied the bar's growing ranks; the toll lawyering
can take on the personal lives of attorneys; and the industry's
``billable hour mania,'' as Reynolds puts it.
</P>
<P>
   But among the members of this group, concern runs deeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a crisis of the soul'' in the legal profession, said
Marisa Pizzuto, an Andover family law practitioner. ``People
practicing for years and years are getting trapped by golden
handcuffs . . . finding themselves very empty inside.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, ``a lot of lawyers have come to the conclusion that
it's painful to practice if you're a spiritual person,'' Pizzuto
said. ``And there's a presumption that if you're a lawyer you don't
have any spirituality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawyers are suffering,'' said Conner. ``They're suffering, and
we should ask if how we're practicing law is part of the reason for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The group grew out of a conference last year on whether lawyers
could be guided by spiritual values. The outpouring of interest was
so strong, Conner said, that a ``holistic lawyers'' group was born.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which has met monthly for more than a year, has
become a seedbed for other reform-minded programs, including a
seminar on the role of judges in encouraging civility, and a
conference on restorative justice.
</P>
<P>
   At their gatherings, where attendance can range from a handful
to more than a dozen, group members explore ways to avoid needless
confrontation: mediating rather than litigating or, in the case of
warring spouses, encouraging clients to listen without becoming
defensive.
</P>
<P>
   They also urge one another to try to understand the emotions
motivating their clients' actions and reactions. Could, for
example, a divorcing client's desire to lash out at her husband
stem from her fear that divorce will leave her destitute?
</P>
<P>
   Membership is informal, although some participants worry that
the word ``holistic'' may make potential recruits wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply for public relations purposes, I have reservations
about the name,'' said Robinson. ``The word holistic has a new-agey
connotation that makes people skeptical, and lawyers are some of
the most skeptical people in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   A better description of the group, he suggested, is ``lawyering
with a heart.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of the state's 42,000 lawyers take a more hard-headed
approach. After all, only six of them showed up for this month's
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure we're going to change the structure of the legal
profession overnight,'' said Robinson. Still, for Reynolds, 52, who
left Peabody &AMP; Arnold last week without a new job to go to, the
group has offered reassurance that his decision to step away from
lawyering is the right one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten validation that what I think is missing, there are
others who also think it's missing,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
