<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3909 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-TEEN'S-IDEAL-BODY-LIF     11-29 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN'S-IDEAL-BODY-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEENS AND PURSUIT OF THE IDEAL BODY
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes color graphic and a photo of some teenagers) 
 By MARILYN McMAHON 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The swimsuit portion of the Miss America pageant may have become
a ''fitness'' contest, and Barbie dolls may be getting new, more
realistic proportions, but the body image that teens idealize
hasn't changed a whit.
</P>
<P>
   Most girls still want to be ''pretty and skinny,'' while most
boys want to be ''tall and strong,'' says Pamela Shires Sneddon,
author of ''Body Image: A Reality Check'' (Enslow Publishers, Inc.)
</P>
<P>
   With nine children of her own, Sneddon can claim a certain
amount of savvy about the younger generation. She and her husband,
Tom Sneddon, a district attorney in Santa Barbara, Calif., are the
parents of six boys and three girls, ranging in age from 11 to 30.
They have three grandchildren, with two more expected this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But even she was surprised by the intensity of pressure on
today's teens to look good at all costs.
</P>
<P>
   Sneddon attributes this to a continuing emphasis on body image
in movies, television and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not surprising that eating disorders are the major
problem for teen-age girls,'' Sneddon said. ''Generally, the
articles that appear in magazines for girls project the same
message: Thin is beautiful, sexy is beautiful and appearance must
be beautiful. Still, it's genetically impossible for 90 percent of
American women to have the same bodies, no matter how much they
diet or exercise or how much plastic surgery they have.''
</P>
<P>
   With the pervasive media images of sleek, sexy women and strong,
powerful men, both boys and girls have a hard time with body image,
says Sneddon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I learned to appreciate what they have to deal with. In my
generation, we admired Audrey Hepburn, but we never tried to look
like her,'' she said. ''Today, the girls want to look like Cindy
Crawford, and the boys want to look like Arnold Schwarzenegger.''
</P>
<P>
   In researching the book, she had 100 students in family health
classes at Santa Barbara Junior High School fill out questionnaires
about physical appearance _ theirs and others. Students were asked
to list external and internal traits of an attractive boy and an
attractive girl.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to find out what the kids thought,'' Sneddon said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to rate what was most important in personal appearance,
''pretty'' received the most votes among girls, followed closely by
''skinny or thin'' and ''somewhat thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Boys admire ''tall'' males, who are ''muscular,'' ''strong'' and
''somewhat thin.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked to describe what an attractive person looks like,
comments included:
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) ''A tall female with blond hair and blue or green
eyes,'' said Adam, 13.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) ''Christy Turlington _ not too fat, but not too skinny.
Full figured,'' said Ophelia, 13.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) ''A strong, athletic person who likes to do things, not
sit around,'' said Grant, 12.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) ''Tall, skinny, cute,'' said Anna, 12.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) ''Strong, tall, athletic,'' said James, 12.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) ''Has curves (not skinny and flat like girls in
magazines), somewhat thin, how their eyes, lips, etc. flow with
their body and face,'' said Alyssa, 12.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) ''Boy teen-ager with good abs and muscles; girl, thin
teen-ager,'' said Manual, 12.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) ''Female, nice, funny, voluptuous, not very short hair,
not that thin, not that big, not too tall, not too short. FINE!''
said Josh, 13.
</P>
<P>
   Sneddon, who also wrote ''Brothers and Sisters: Born to
Bicker?'', researched her latest book by surfing the Internet,
interviewing experts around the country via telephone, watching
videos and scouring books, magazines and scholarly publications.
</P>
<P>
   She paid particular attention to magazines that appealed to
teens _ Glamour, Seventeen, Elle, Surfing, Sports Illustrated _ and
found that those for females focused on appearance while magazines
for males were action-oriented, focusing on sports and other
activities and hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   In her book, Sneddon quotes syndicated columnist Ellen Goodman:
''A generation ago, the average model weighed 8 percent less than
the average woman. Now, she weighs 23 percent less.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially pervasive are television messages.
</P>
<P>
   ''You see all these people on TV, and they look so happy and
thin, and they make you feel like you should be that way _ not just
to feel good, but to get men or women,'' said a 17-year-old
Wisconsin high school student Sneddon quotes in her book.
</P>
<P>
   With the popularity of celebrities like talk show host Rosie
O'Donnell and actress Camryn Manheim, Sneddon does detect some
hopeful signs for the future. Large-size models are in demand for
clothing catalogs, too.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope attitudes are changing, but I know my 11-year-old
daughter and her friends are concerned about their weight,''
Sneddon said. ''Some girls think of anorexia and bulimia as
positive behavior. One of my daughters told me she would have tried
them, but she didn't have the willpower.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Sneddon found that the pressure to be thin is
something girls place upon themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ''They think boys want them to be thin, but this isn't so,'' she
said. ''African-American women don't have the same issue about
weight, and African-American men appreciate larger women.''
</P>
<P>
   If teen-age girls have hang-ups about weight, the boys have
their own problem _ a desire to look like Arnold Schwarzenegger or
Sylvester Stallone.
</P>
<P>
   ''The modern cultural emphasis on bodybuilding has produced more
men and boys with a negative body image,'' writes Sneddon in her
book.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to girls, however, boys want to put on more weight
rather than take it off. This can lead to steroid abuse.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dr. Gary Wadler, one of the experts Sneddon
interviewed, steroid users are similar to victims of eating
disorders.
</P>
<P>
   ''One is the relentless pursuit of bigness, the other is the
relentless pursuit of thinness,'' he said. ''They're polar aspects
of the same problem. One result of this male pursuit of bigness may
be reverse anorexia, as men become compulsive exercisers or abusers
of steroids in trying to attain an otherwise unattainable ideal
body type.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this has Sneddon wondering ''if our culture is going to
be as hard on boys as it has been on girls.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Marilyn McMahon writes for the Santa Barbara (Calif.)
News-Press.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
