<HEADER>
A3910 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-TUTORS-HELP-KIDS-LIFE     11-29 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUTORS-HELP-KIDS-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS TURN TO TUTORS TO HELP KIDS WITH SCHOOL
</HEADLINE>
  By LIZ RUSCH 
 c.1999 Child magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Guerin Harris was a star pupil in kindergarten. But in first
grade his grades were all Bs and the teacher told his mother,
Rebecca, that Guerin wasn't reading well.
</P>
<P>
   After trying out extra sessions with a teacher and an
after-school study program, Harris, who lives in Evansville, Ind.,
found a solution that works: a tutor who helps Guerin with reading
at home once a week. The $100 a month is worth it Harris says.
''Diane is really attuned to my child and teaches in ways that
allow him to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Guerin brought home his first A+ on a reading test
''He was so proud of it,'' says his mother. ''Reading is still not
easy for him, but it's easier than it was before. He's even
starting to read things on his own now.''
</P>
<P>
   An increasing number of parents around the country are turning
to tutors to guide children over bumps they may encounter in their
journey through school. Some students, like Guerin, meet with a
tutor at home, at the local library, or at school, while others
flock to commercial tutoring programs so they can get up to speed _
or get ahead _ academically.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody is hiring a tutor,'' says Toks Fashola, Ph.D., an
associate research scientist at Johns Hopkins University in
Baltimore who studies after-school programs. ''A few years ago, the
families sending kids to tutors were those that had extra income.
Now families of all income levels and children of all skill levels
_ ahead, behind, and average _ see tutors.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of the number of kids tutored run in the low millions.
Sylvan Learning Systems, with 700 ''learning centers'' in all
states but Vermont serves more than 125,000 students each year.
Kumon Math &AMP; Reading Centers has 1,300 locations in 46 states and
tutors about 74,000 annually. Huntington Learning Center, with 195
branches in 33 states, reaches 45,000 children.
</P>
<P>
   Countless other kids meet with peer, volunteer, or private
tutors who charge up to $100 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Why the trend? There is a sense among parents that American
education is in crisis because of budget cuts and crowded
classrooms, Dr. Fashola says. ''Parents believe their children
aren't getting enough individual attention in school.''
</P>
<P>
   When sixth-grader Max Kramer sat down with tutor Anita Sande at
a Portland, Ore., library one Thursday afternoon, they worked on
long division. ''Anita works just with me, and that's what really
helps,'' says Max. ''In class the teacher can't spend an hour with
you when you don't get something.''
 &UR; More Practice Leads to More Learning &LR;  &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is after-school tutoring worth the millions of dollars and
hundreds of thousands of hours that families invest in it? In a
word, probably.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tutoring works largely because of the intense focus that
one-on-one attention brings,'' says Timothy Shanahan, Ph.D.,
professor of education at the University of Illinois at Chicago,
who has reviewed more than 100 studies on tutoring.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Glass, Ph.D., associate dean of the college of education at
Arizona State University in Tempe, didn't think tutoring would make
such a difference when he set out with an economist at Stanford
University to find the most cost-effective way to boost learning.
''But tutoring rose to the top, above reducing class size and
lengthening the school year,'' says Dr. Glass. ''After a month of
daily 20-minute sessions, the average student gained two-and-a-half
months in reading grade levels and four-and-a-half months in math
levels.''
</P>
<P>
   A learning disability, dropping grades, or expressions of
concern from your child's teacher that he is falling behind in
specific skills might indicate the need for a tutor. If so, don't
delay.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone has this idea that kids will outgrow problems,'' Dr.
Shanahan says. ''That's not true for 70 percent of children. The
earlier you can catch an academic problem, the greater the chance
that you can do something about it.''
 &UR; Before Your Child Gets Help &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arrange a meeting with your child and her teacher to define
concrete goals, suggests Nathan Naparstek, Ph.D., a psychologist
for the public schools in Schenectady, New York, and author of
''The Learning Solution: What to Do if Your Child Has Trouble With
Schoolwork.'' Involving your child can help her feel more in
control and engaged in the solution.
</P>
<P>
   Find out what your school has to offer. In a 1997 Public Agenda
poll, 87 percent of teachers said their schools can provide extra
help or tutoring. Some schools match children with peer tutors, a
practice that can be remarkably effective if the tutors are trained
and supervised. Or your school's principal may assign your child a
volunteer adult tutor, who also should be trained.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule a break between school and tutoring because kids need a
chance to relax and unwind after a day of classwork. Or try
scheduling early morning or weekend sessions.
</P>
<P>
   More parents than ever are turning to tutoring businesses to do
the job. They usually charge up to $45 an hour and claim rapid
learning results and high parental satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to tell if they deliver because no independent
research has been conducted on commercial programs. Before you
decide to sign on with a for-profit operation, ask to observe its
tutors at work. ''Some places just give kids worksheets that they
correct,'' says Dr. Naparstek. ''That is not tutoring.''
</P>
<P>
   A tutoring session in reading may include reading aloud,
discussion of what was read, and writing. Math tutoring may include
computation, discussion of methods, and hands-on activities that
help a child understand the underlying concepts
</P>
<P>
   ''For an hour-long session, you should see activities change
three to five times,'' says Dr. Shanahan. In several tutoring
businesses, like Sylvan and Huntington, one tutor generally works
with two or three students at once. 'Three-to-one is not as good as
one-on-one,'' says Dr. Naparstek. 'With three children in a
45-minute tutoring session, each child may get only 10 minutes of
real assistance.''
 &UR; What Makes a Tutor Top-Notch? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A good tutor does not tell students directly how to improve.
Mark Lepper, Ph.D., a professor of psychology at Stanford
University in California, discovered this after observing dozens of
experienced tutors of elementary school students. Rather, when a
child gets stuck, the tutor poses questions. For example, when one
child added 36 and 36 and got 126, the tutor asked, ''Now, how did
you get that 6?''
</P>
<P>
   ''Good tutors draw information and learning out of students,''
explains Dr. Lepper. ''Students who are more actively involved in
figuring things out are more likely to remember what they learn.''
Even when it takes six or seven questions before a child grasps a
point, an effective tutor keeps posing more specific, leading
questions rather than telling the student the answer. Look for a
tutor who encourages your child to think.
</P>
<P>
   Skilled tutors spend more time building rapport with students,
Dr. Lepper observes. They use this information to design activities
a child will enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Tutoring is about much more than boosting grades. The best
tutors inspire a love of learning and build kids' self-confidence,
parents say.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, developing a child's sense of play and
excitement about doing academic work may yield the best
improvements in a child's skills and confidence. ''School has been
more fun now that I know I can do anything'' says Max Kramer. 'When
the teacher comes up with something I've never done before, I know
I can figure it out by using things I learned from Anita.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ( Liz Rusch, a contributing editor to Child, lives in Oregon.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
