<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3911 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-SIAM-BOS &LR;      11-29 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SIAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INNOCENCE ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
SIAM 
Or the Woman Who Shot  a Man 
By Lily Tuck. The Overlook Press. 192 pp. $23.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The image of the displaced Westerner, suffering or bumbling
through foreign lands, is one of the great quick-trick themes of
modern English literature. Adrift in an exotic culture, the Lone
Ranger protagonist _ think of Conrad, Graham Greene, John le Carre
_ must rely on the familiar mercies and tyrannies of the West to
see him through. Our recognition of imperialism's failings has
taken this school to a new level of irony, where the trappings of
wealth or religion can be as cheap and lethal as bad food from a
street vendor. For narrative purposes, the alien backdrop ensures
the immediate interplay of certain elements crucial to a dynamic
plot, from dramatic tension to the enhanced character traits of an
emigre abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Lily Tuck's spare, frightening little novel takes advantage of
these traditions, hovering around the compromised borders of
Thailand during the acceleration of the Vietnam War in 1967. The
author of two previous novels, including ``Interviewing Matisse, or
The Woman Who Died Standing Up,'' Tuck has a penchant for the
understated and the strange, both of which apply to ``Siam.'' Her
American at sea is a 25-year-old New Englander named Claire whose
new husband, James, is a US military adviser rebuilding Thailand's
infrastructure in preparation for the bombing of Vietnam. The
innocent daughter of a Harvard classics professor, Claire lands in
Bangkok in the first days of her marriage _ finding a shockingly
new world where the language of military secrets is no more
comprehensible than Thai intonations and verb forms. ``Falang
falang!'' cry the women on the taxi boats in Bangkok's canals as
Claire tries to join them; they are identifying her as a foreigner,
but the phrase carries with it a barbed-wire remove that Claire
won't dare to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   The exception to this cold milieu is Jim Thompson, an
entrepreneur in the silk industry whose disappearance early in
``Siam'' becomes the spectral presence around which Claire's
transformation takes place. Thompson's character is drawn from real
life, and this insinuation of history into fiction suggests the
creepy crossover reality of the novel _ where truth is no more
reliable than the imagination, where failures of communication have
as much to do with the heart as the tongue. Thompson is a
charismatic man who is kind to Claire when she and James attend a
dinner party at his home; he vanishes in Malaysia a few weeks
later, and his fate becomes Claire's obsession, as though his
absence itself is the black hole into which all losses and gains
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Learning her tenses and sing-song rhythms from her Thai language
instructor, Claire also holes up at the library, reading the
newspaper accounts of the search for Thompson along with
revisionist Thai history and US press reports of military bombings.
As Claire's fixation with Thompson grows, so does the spooky
ambience of ``Siam'' _ a Thai soldier fires a gun into a luncheon
crowd; a woman who was supposed to be Thompson's friend seems
complicit in his disappearance. The Bay of Siam, where Claire and
James go to swim, turns out to be a breeding ground for sharks;
when they see a native woman being raped on the beach, James drags
Claire away.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the stark, white-walled environs of ``Siam,'' such
symbols begin to seem heavy-handed; searching for its identity, the
novel too often feels like bad Joan Didion trying to be Graham
Greene. It is most successful, of course, when it stays away from
both antecedents. What Tuck does with chilling finesse is create an
ominous world of disintegration, where Claire's
outsider-observations of an alien culture are eclipsed by what may
be her own personal fragmentation. In a Thailand overrun by
military advisers playing Truth or Dare, reality itself is up for
grabs; in Claire's increasingly solitary, alienated frame of
reference, time and space are malleable constructs. The achievement
of ``Siam'' is to mirror this dissolution in narrative form, so
that what contaminates Claire's fallen innocence finds its way into
the reader's world as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Siam'' is an ominous, unsettling novel that is more
intellectually enticing than emotionally resonant; like Jim
Thompson's disappearance, it makes a great deal out of what isn't
there. This is often frustrating: In such a sparsely crafted
narrative world, Tuck must rely on external devices such as
newspaper accounts to further her plot, and such ploys often bear
the creak of off-stage contrivance. Her continual use of Claire's
efforts to master a foreign language, too, quickly reach their
finite potential as a metaphor of estrangement. As for why she
decided to take the denouement of her story and sling it into the
novel's subtitle, I am clueless; perhaps she wanted to underscore
what was always sure to be a less-than-happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   The American involvement in Southeast Asia was full of wounds
and crimes and mysterious legends, and ``Siam'' draws its shadow
territory from that treacherous past _ including a horrid incident
involving a monkey that I'd heard before, but could have done
without. That's the nature of this novel: Tuck's narrative gifts
are sort of creepily admirable. Containing all the consequences of
a cowboy war, her subtitle finale even has an anti-Gatsby twist to
it _ suggesting that innocence itself was a dangerous illusion of
the American myth. But maybe even that myth is too many thousands
of miles away to be of use in ``Siam'' country, where old points of
reference are merely antiquated tools. When Claire begins learning
a board game, her teacher, Priya, announces that she, Priya, will
be called East.
</P>
<P>
   ``East?'' Claire asks her. ``Does that mean I'm West?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Priya answers, shaking her head. ``In mah-jongg there is
only East.''
</P>
</TEXT>
