<HEADER>
A3914 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-29 1506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE GNMAS A CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 67 and retired. I receive a total of $2,300 a month from
Social Security, a pension, and a deferred compensation plan. I
have two IRA accounts worth a total of $100,000. The more
diversified of these is a $50,000 account at Fidelity with 50
percent invested in Dividend Growth fund, 15 percent in High Income
fund, 10 percent in Capital Income fund, and 25 percent in Growth
Company fund. With Vanguard, the other $50,000 is 50 percent
invested in Index 500, 30 percent in Index Growth, and 20 percent
in Health Care. You recommend the Vanguard GNMA fund to many of
your readers as a fixed-income source. My year-to-date and one-year
returns on all of my accounts are 12 percent and 15 percent
respectively. My question: If the GNMA fund yields 6.5 percent,
then why is the year-to-date and one-year total return about 1.4
percent? Since I will start taking a distribution from my IRAs in
three years, I am trying to build up the total value before I reach
70. The deferred compensation income will dry up in five years, and
I will then need income from my IRAs to live on. Should I transfer
some of my Vanguard money now, or wait until I am 70? Why should I
move money into the GNMA account or bonds?
</P>
<P>
   C.D., San Diego &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, there's certainly no debate that this has been a pretty
rotten year for GNMAs and other bond funds. Higher interest rates
and fears of still more rate hikes to come have driven down their
prices to the point that many are in the red, and the best, such as
Vanguard GNMA, have had only token total returns.
</P>
<P>
   But the point of bond funds is to deliver an income stream, and
the reason most people buy a fund such as Vanguard GNMA is its 6.66
percent yield. They reason, and with good cause, that the share
price will fluctuate fairly dramatically from time to time, but
that over the long haul, it will go nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   That can be illustrated fairly dramatically by the net asset
value as this is written _ a flat $10 per share, which was
precisely the fund's net asset value when it was launched in
mid-1980.
</P>
<P>
   The reason people invest in bond funds despite their predictably
lower long-term total returns is their lower risk level _ only the
most affluent people who count on their investments as a source of
income can afford to invest their all in the stock market,
calculating that their fortune is large enough to ride through the
bumps.
</P>
<P>
   For most people, the potential shock that a series of bad stock
market years could cause to an equity portfolio is too great to
face comfortably. So they look for a bond fund that will deliver
their income checks through good markets and bad, and presume that
eventually all of those fluctuations in the net asset value will
balance out.
</P>
<P>
   As a general rule, you can expect funds such as the Vanguard
GNMA to suffer about two bad years in every decade _ a statistic
that has been born out during the 90s, with 1994 and 1999 being the
offenders.
</P>
<P>
   This long-term viewpoint is, of course, easier to accept with
equanimity when things are going well than when you're in the
middle of one of those years that turn out to be stinkers, but
that's the nature of the beast.
</P>
<P>
   Console yourself by looking at the longer-term returns, such as
the average 8.06 percent total return for the fund over five years,
and 7.93 percent over 10.
</P>
<P>
   In your situation, you're at about the perfect point to begin
making changes, which is five years before you will need to begin
relying on the savings to produce an income stream.
</P>
<P>
   You don't mention how much income you will need to replace at
age 72, and the answer to that question would dictate how
aggressively you might move toward building the fixed-income side
of the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you would need $5,000 a year in five years to augment
your pension and Social Security. You might calculate that you
would need a $77,000 fixed-income portfolio to provide that income
stream.
</P>
<P>
   If your IRAs achieved total returns of 8 percent during the next
five years _ a figure I chose both in the presumption that you will
be gradually moving to fixed-income investments, and because I
think the years of double-digit stock market gains are numbered _
your IRAs would be worth a total of $146,935 in five years.
</P>
<P>
   If you wanted to build that $77,000 fixed-income account over
the course of those 60 months, moving $1,094 a month from the stock
funds to fixed-income holdings would do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I are retired and in our mid-70s and are
withdrawing from our IRA accounts, which are all in mutual funds,
with the breakdown being approximately 60 percent in stock funds,
30 percent GNMA, and 10 percent in US Treasury funds. I would like
a better diversification for our ages. Do you recommend moving some
of our stock funds into convertible bonds or bond funds?
</P>
<P>
   L.C., Malden, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, you certainly have a greater percentage of your money
in stocks than do most people of your age.
</P>
<P>
   But the question of whether to spread more of the money into
bonds involves your overall financial situation. If you rely on the
IRAs to produce some of your income stream, and if you would be
uncomfortable if the turns of the market were to reduce your
principal, then, yes, I would suggest moving more of the money into
bond funds. Since convertibles tend to follow the swings of the
stock market as much as those of the bond market, Id suggest you
focus on straight bond funds, such as the GNMA you already have _
and take a look at the letter above and dont worry about the
horrible year GNMAs are currently having.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if your IRAs simply represent extra money
which is likely to eventually end up in your estate, and if the
withdrawals you are taking are made only because the tax rules
require them, I see no need to make a change.
</P>
<P>
   If you simply feel nervous about the stock markets _ and to my
way of thinking, thats a sign you are thinking rationally _ you
might decide to hedge your bets by moving about half of the money
in the stock funds into balanced funds. If the balanced funds you
chose divided their portfolios evenly between stocks and bonds,
this would give you 45 percent stocks and 55 percent fixed-income
holdings. If the mix was a more typical 60/40 division, with stocks
on the heavy end, it would give you 48 percent stocks and 52
percent bonds. Both positions are a little more aggressive than
most people your age prefer, but are not wildly out of line unless
you will need to rely on this portfolio for income.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are 65 and 68 years old respectively and both
retired.
</P>
<P>
   I consider myself a cautious investor with a little risk taking.
I would rather preserve my principal than take a big chance. Our
present income totals from pensions and Social Security totals
$47,000, and we have $130,000 in IRAs spread among 13 funds with
Invesco, Fidelity and Vanguard. I am concerned about the number of
funds and about the time when I must start taking my required
minimum descriptions. I want to consolidate my holdings into one or
maybe two mutual funds to make it easy when I start taking
withdrawals. When I do take the withdrawals, where is the best
place to invest the money? I do not feel I will be needing a lot of
it to live on, so I want to safely put it away for my surviving
children.
</P>
<P>
   R.R., Quakertown, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   A. Heck _ it may be a lot of funds, but thats a carefully built
portfolio, and I hate to see it broken up. I hope you realize that
when it comes to the time of mandatory distributions, you simply
total all of your IRA holdings, calculate the required distribution
based on the ages of yourself and your beneficiary, and then you
can take the withdrawals from wherever you like. You could take it
from any one of the 13 accounts, or any combination you like.
</P>
<P>
   But if you simply dont want to keep track of all these funds,
you can view the portfolio as having three major segments: A total
of 44 percent is in money market funds; there is 22.9 percent in
fixed-income holdings (a category in which I included your
utilities fund position, since its mostly geared to income, and
half of your balanced fund balances) and 33.1 percent in stock
funds, generally weighted toward value holdings.
</P>
<P>
   So will you let me advise three funds to replace the thirteen?
If you would, and if you go with Vanguard, you might put 44 percent
in its Prime Money Market fund, 22.9 percent in its GNMA fund, and
the final 33.1 percent in its Index Value fund. If you went with
Fidelity, you could use the same percentages with its Cash
Reserves, GNMA, and Value funds.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you re happy with such a portfolio, you could
reinvest the distributions in taxable accounts in the same funds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
