<HEADER>
A3921 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MURDER-PLAN-BOS &LR;      11-29 1575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDER-PLAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLER TOLD ALL ON THE WEB, AND NO ONE LISTENED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ In the days before he emptied a semiautomatic
handgun into 20-year-old Amy Boyer, whom he had developed a crush
on when they were both in junior high, Liam Youens ran his options
by an Internet audience.
</P>
<P>
   Should he go forward with ``Plan Amy,'' the slaying of Boyer,
then working as a dental assistant, or opt for ``Plan Owen,'' the
assassination of another former classmate who, like Boyer, could
barely have picked him out of a police lineup?
</P>
<P>
   Or would it make a bigger splash to storm into Nashua High
School at lunchtime, Columbine-style, and kill as many students as
he could?
</P>
<P>
   During the weeks that led up to Boyer's slaying on Oct. 15 and
Youens' suicide that day, the 21-year-old loosed all his thoughts
on his Internet site. A recently released 489-page police report,
drawing on that site, supplies a finely drawn portrait of a young
man preparing to kill.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that preparation, Youens told an imagined audience,
consisted of developing the ``courage'' to open fire on an unarmed
former classmate. And part of it consisted of on-line investigation
services that charged him hundreds of dollars to find Boyer's birth
date, Social Security number, address, and finally, the location of
the Main Street dentist's office where she worked.
</P>
<P>
   It was there, weeks later, that he pulled up alongside her car
and let loose a barrage of bullets that exploded into the side of
her face and broke both of her arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually obsene (sic) what you can find out about people
on the Internet,'' he wrote on his Web page, beside the subject
headings ``Youth group people,'' and ``Mass murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the day Boyer died, when he learned of two Web sites
devoted to stalking her, her stepfather, Tim Remsburg, has focused
publicly on the role the Internet played in her death. Remsburg saw
the police report _ a haunting unfolding of Liam Youens' on-line
life _ for the first time on Nov. 19, and read through the thick
stack of papers until early the next morning, weeping. Remsburg,
42, had pressed hard for police to release the material, which he
said could be useful in a civil suit he is considering against
Geocities and Tripod, the two on-line communities where Youens
maintained Web sites announcing his intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Although a Tripod official said almost no one visited Youens'
site, Remsburg said the threats were made publicly and should have
been reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be one thing if this kid had written this in a
diary,'' Remsburg said. ``But he wrote this on the Internet. Now
don't you think he expected someone to read this?''
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Strawbridge, director of membership services at Tripod,
destroyed the site in the early morning hours on the night Boyer
died, minutes after a police detective called him. He said Tripod
would certainly have notified authorities if anyone had seen the
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a site like that before, and I've seen
millions of sites,'' Strawbridge said.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether threats on Web pages should be monitored
emerged this spring after the shootings at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., where Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold had stated
their intentions on a Web page. Strawbridge said his company does
its best to monitor both pornography and on-line threats, but that
the technology to weed out threatening pages does not exist yet.
Ordinary searches for words like ``hate'' and ``kill'' would turn
up an unfathomable volume of material, he said.
</P>
<P>
   During the three months when Youens maintained the Tripod site,
the number of visitors to the site was in the ``single digits,''
said Strawbridge. He added that many of those hits may have been
Youens himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that he was the only visitor to his own site,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A Geocities spokesman refused to comment on Youens' second site.
</P>
<P>
   According to Remsburg, an unrelated grievance concerns the ease
with which Youens tracked down Boyer using the Internet. Reading
through the paper trail of Youens' month-and-a-half-long search for
Boyer's workplace address, Remsburg said, he was enraged that
on-line investigation agencies such as Docusearch and Infoseekers
had made money revealing his daughter's whereabouts to her killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was back at square one,'' Remsburg said. ``I felt almost as
violated as I did when I found out that Web site had been up for
two years.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for one on-line agency says it uses public sources
such as court or motor vehicle records for its research.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information that we're providing is public information,
and it's accessible through other means,'' the spokeswoman said.
``The only thing we're doing is saving people time.''
</P>
<P>
   She asked that her firm not be identified because no officer was
available to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Youens' journal, which was posted on the Tripod site, recounts
the history of a one-way relationship: the humiliating day she
brushed past him in the lunchroom, the painful Valentine's Day when
he realized she had received a rose from a new boyfriend. He pasted
several purloined pictures of Boyer to his page, airbrushing one
which he felt was not flattering. He also recalled a day in 10th
grade when Boyer turned around on the school bus to yell back at a
friend and Youens realized he was in love with her. Shortly after
that he decided to kill her and himself. ``That was the basic plan
for the next half decade,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives and acquaintances of Liam Youens who were interviewed
after the killing described him as withdrawn and occasionally
violent. His mother, Clarissa London, recalled a 1996 incident in
which Youens had thrown her china cabinet down the staircase when
she dismissed as ``silly'' his desire to get plastic surgery for a
``sunken chest.'' London called the police, who arrested Youens. He
was convicted on domestic violence charges and later attended anger
management classes at Nashua District Court, she told police.
</P>
<P>
   After high school, Youens left Nashua for a miserable year at
the Rochester Institute of Technology, after which he returned home
and began taking steps to track Boyer down. But he found himself
stymied, in part because she was constantly surrounded by family.
The challenge was to find her workplace and her license plate
number without arousing suspicion. On the Web site, he railed
against New Hampshire Governor Jeanne Shaheen for legislation that
made it impossible to obtain license plate numbers from a Social
Security number.
</P>
<P>
   But starting in mid-September, he had more luck with Internet
services like Docusearch, whose sitepromises to help ``track down
debtors and deadbeats.'' One investigator from Infoseekers
apologetically e-mailed back, ``I couldn't find much on Amy, I
guess she's relatively young, she may not have a very long paper
trail yet. . . . Good luck!!!'' Finally, late in September,
Docusearch provided him with the address of the Main Street
dentist's office.
</P>
<P>
   He found her there, and by Oct. 7, he was chastising himself for
``making excuses.'' On Oct. 12, he had no spot to shoot from. On
Oct. 15, he found his spot. The killing took place at 4:30 in the
afternoon. Youens had last updated the ``Amy Boyer'' Web site at
3:49.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most disturbing passages in Youens' journal
described the things he did not do. Youens wrote admiringly of the
shootings at Columbine High School, and wrote of plans to carry out
his own ``rampage'' at Nashua High School. (Original spelling
preserved):
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan to start shooting in the courtyard as fast as I can.
reload, I am told that two Nashua Police officers will be in the
school (this is why I need a vest). If those cops don't blow my
brains out, I figure I'll have one minute before the cavalry comes
. . . ill go for head shots head shots head shots! they are a
MUST.''
</P>
<P>
   He also apparently considered another random killing of an
acquaintance: Owen Banks, a 20-year-old college student who had
attended Nashua High School with Youens. On his Web page, Youens
relates several attempts to ``snipe him from his backyard'' and one
occasion when he ``drove to (Banks's) house and coincidentally saw
him taking out the trash. As I drove by we looked at each other
square in the eye. I was stuned.''
</P>
<P>
   But when police visited Banks four days after Boyer's death,
Banks drew a blank when asked about Youens.
</P>
<P>
   Banks ``states that he . . . does not know who Liam Youens is,''
reported a Nashua detective that day. ``He states that he cannot
recall any in-depth conversation that he has ever had with Liam. .
. . He cannot find a single, solitary reason why Liam would want to
harm him, and is very puzzled by Liam's desire to kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks, reached at his parents' home in Nashua last week, said he
did not want to talk about the killing. Remsburg said he believed
Youens had focused on Banks because Banks once told him that Boyer
had a boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Remsburg said it would be hard to guard against such a bizarre
crime. Still, he wishes that somehow, three days before her death _
on an evening when she spent three hours surfing the Internet _ Amy
Boyer had run a search for her own name.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Donations to the Amy Lynn Boyer Memorial Fund Against Criminal
Violence may be sent c/o BankBoston, 157 Main St., Nashua, NH
03062.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 1354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
