u a BC-PUERTORICO-DIVORCE-BO     11-29 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-DIVORCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUERTO RICAN SPLIT: MUSIC STOPS AS BASEBALL STAR FOULS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN _ It was a Hollywood relationship from the start,
complete with lies, infidelity, and even DNA testing. Now it's over
_ and it's on the mind of everyone in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The island's most celebrated couple _ merengue queen Olga Tanon
and Detroit Tigers baseball player Juan ``Igor'' Gonzalez _
announced last week they are splitting.
</P>
<P>
   Their divorce will dissolve a union that entwined two of Puerto
Rico's most prized treasures: music and baseball. Separately, Tanon
and Gonzalez are international icons, the premier ambassadors of
Puerto Rican culture. Together, they embodied a passion taken
straight from a Univision soap opera, a romance of two superstar
millionaires that was not meant to be.
</P>
<P>
   Though the news didn't shock many people _ most Puerto Ricans
say they saw it coming _ it is the talk of the island. For four
days, it was on the front page of every major Puerto Rican
newspaper, with tabloid-style headlines such as ``Olga puncho a
Igor,'' or ``Olga struck out Igor.''
</P>
<P>
   Radio DJs are playing Tanon's music with even greater frequency,
making innunendoes with the titles of such songs as ``Muchacho
Malo'' (``Bad Boy''). And all over, from nightclubs in Old San Juan
to health clubs in Ponce, people talk about the couple as if they
are intimate friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell from the beginning it wasn't going to work,''
said Nitza Gonzalez, a 32-year-old accountant from Humacao. ``He's
always had problems with women.''
</P>
<P>
   The public's appetite for each twist and turn of the
relationship has everything to do with the couple's star status.
</P>
<P>
   Tanon is easily the most popular female merengue singer in all
of Latin America, a woman who pushed open the door to others in the
male-dominated genre. Her face is splashed on billboards and
magazine covers across Latin America. She's known as ``mujer de
fuego,'' or ``woman of fire,'' because of her energy.
</P>
<P>
   Her music employs the catchy, hip-twitching rhythm that is the
trademark of merengue, though her lyrics don't fall into the
typical why-did-he-leave-me mode. Her modern-day woman lyrics speak
of taking charge. ``If he tells you, `I love you.' If he says
`Without you I die.' . . . He's a liar. He's a liar, that man,''
she sings on ``Es Mentiroso,'' or ``He's a Liar.'' Yet, she sings
as if she's having the time of her life.
</P>
<P>
   People know her songs by heart. That's because many lives
revolve around music. Mothers sway to it while they cook dinner. It
blares from jukeboxes in restaurants. And on plazas on weekends,
bands draw crowds that are always ready to groove.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that comes close to many Puerto Ricans' love of
music is their love of baseball. And their number one man is
Gonzalez, the island's greatest gift to the Major Leagues since
Roberto Clemente. Gonzalez has twice won the American League's Most
Valuable Player award, in 1996 and 1998, when he was with the Texas
Rangers. Among sports lovers here, he's known as ``el bateador de
bateadores.'' (The batter of batters.)
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, he's tall and handsome. Women swoon for him. Men
and little boys alike wish they could trade places with him, even
for just a day.
</P>
<P>
   In Puerto Rico, when the two wed last December, it was as if
Madonna had married Babe Ruth. It captured the attention of Puerto
Ricans here and on the mainland. News photographers acted like
snipers, hiding to get revealing, intimate shots. Many had hoped
that if anyone could, Tanon would straighten out Gonzalez, who had
a revolving door of women in his life. But that proved to be a vain
hope.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez secretly began dating Tanon five years ago while he was
married to Elaine Lopez, a Puerto Rican volleyball champ and sister
of Atlanta Braves catcher Javier Lopez. Gonzalez left Lopez, his
second wife, for Tanon. Two years later, Tanon was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, a woman named Liza Ferrer Garcia said
she also was pregnant with Gonzalez's child. Gonzalez rebuffed
Ferrer publicly, saying, ``The only baby I'm expecting is from
Olga.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanon gave birth to a girl, Gabriela. And Ferrer had a boy, whom
she named Igorcito, or ``little Igor.'' When his mother dressed him
in Texas Rangers jerseys for the TV cameras he looked like a
mini-Igor.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, after a court-mandated DNA test proved the the
child is his, Gonzalez said he would make child-support payments,
but would not recognize him as his son. Last month, however,
Gonzalez conceded and said he would accept Igorcito.
</P>
<P>
   Most Puerto Ricans think that was the last straw for Tanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was with so many women and now he has no one,'' said Hanzel
Arroyo, 72, a Korean War veteran. ``As we say in Puerto Rico,
`Perdio la soga y la cabra' _ He lost the rope and the goat.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone seems to side with Tanon. People see her as a
good woman who was wronged by a womanizer.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got tired of his scandals,'' said Alfonso Cordero, owner
of Islander Feeling Crafts in Old San Juan. Cordero said though he
condemns Gonzalez's actions, he's not surprised that men admire
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of men think he's got it all. He's like James Bond. He's
got a ton of women and all this money,'' Cordero said. ``Nothing
happens to him. He comes out unscratched.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
