<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INEVITABLE GLOBALIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now that another national shouting match is looming
over trade, smack in the middle of a presidential campaign season
no less, the combatants should pause long enough to think about two
of the most important, bridging figures of the post-World War II
era _ John Kennedy and Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to helping the country and world grow, and shrinking
the obstacles to international commerce, Kennedy and Reagan shared
a devout refusal to play either/or games with a subject so
obviously central to America's economic health.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's at this week's pivotal discussions of the
still-fledgling World Trade Organization, or the effort to
implement the Clinton administration's agreement with China over
the terms of its watershed entry into the WTO, the either/or,
yes/no shouting match misses many important points that address the
key element of most Americans' attitude toward what is now called
globalization _ ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, without losing his credentials with a labor movement
that in the early 1960s was far more powerful and
manufacturing-based than it is today, led his party into
responsible internationalism. The negotiating round that he won
authority to conduct after a tough struggle was the first major
effort to begin dismantling then-huge barriers to the flow of goods
and services around the world and was the ice-breaker after more
than a decade of inaction. But it was also Kennedy who first
advanced the concept, and then an actual program, of what became
called ``adjustment assistance'' to help workers and communities
severely impacted by outside forces cope and adapt.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan, whom no one could ever accuse of being a
protectionist, was equally at home on the tightrope. Like Kennedy,
however, Reagan was not content to simply conserve his base, among
free-traders in the conservative movement and the business
comnmunity. Not only did he get the most recent rounds of
trade-expansion going _ this was the round that ended up producing
the WTO under Bill Clinton _ Reagan was no slouch when it came to
granting relief to US industries hit by suddent surges of imports.
</P>
<P>
   In cars, in steel, and other important sectors, Reagan took heat
from his free-trade purists in negotiating _ under threat of more
formal actions _ agreements with major trading partners that
limited their exports here while domestic businesses used the grace
periods to become more fit for genuine competition.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s and the 1980s, there was no question of the basic
direction toward more of a global economy, but there was also no
question that the government was widely (if far from universally)
perceived as prepared to step in and smooth out the bumps along the
way, particularly those that stemmed from sharp surges in imports.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the political atmosphere is much different. President
Clinton has earned broad support for his economic policies, and the
conventional wisdom around here is that he starts out in a strong
position in the wake of the successful conclusion of the WTO
negotiations with China. At a minimum, to implement the deal,
Congress will have to pass a basically clean bill granting
permanent, normal trade relations status for China, ending the
ridiculous process of recent years that require annual votes _ and
therefore annual shouting matches.
</P>
<P>
   There is also broad support _ again, stemming from the
unprecedented, broad-based prosperity _ for a new round of trade
talks under WTO auspices that will get underway this week in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   But there continue to be loud cries of dissent from those who
believe that globalization is a benefit for corporations more than
people, that it promotes the export of US manfacturing jobs more
than goods and services, that it winks at harmful environmental
practices, and that it compromises basic human rights values.
</P>
<P>
   I don't share the dissent, but the basis for much of it is
legitimate and the Clinton administration should pay it more than
lip service in the interests of broadening the support for trade
liberalization.
</P>
<P>
   An excellent example has just emerged from the Center for
National Policy here _ a study by trade expert Greg Mastel urging
much more vigorous use of a basic provision in US law designed to
guard against unexpected surges in imports as well as dumping.
</P>
<P>
   The legal provision _ Section 201 of the law _ has a poor
history, Mastel argues, under presidents easily dissuaded by
foreign policy as well as domestic political considerations. But by
loosening the standards for action, requiring quicker responses to
reported import surges, and limiting presidential discretion,
Section 201 could become a much more useful tool. It would also
more credibly buttress strong safeguards against surges in specific
imports from China that were negotiated as part of the WTO deal.
</P>
<P>
   Open markets and open trading systems are clearly in the
ascendancy politically in ways they have not been in the past. But
the future will be a lot more politically secure if safeguards are
made even stronger. This isn't protectionist, as Kennedy and Reagan
found out, it's the glue that keeps the nation more united as
inevitable globalization proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
