<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3933 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-WHALE-STORY-BOS &LR;      11-29 1830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHALE-STORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHALE BOATS CHURN SOUTH AFRICA DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTUCKET, Mass. _ For years on this tiny island where names and
loyalties go back centuries, it was called ``the secret'': the
harrowing but true story of how members of a local whaling crew
survived for 90 days adrift on the open sea after losing their ship
in the Pacific and running out of food.
</P>
<P>
   The disastrous voyage of the Essex, which was rammed and
eventually sent to the ocean's bottom by a great bull whale,
inspired Herman Melville to write ``Moby-Dick.'' But the real story
of the Essex, and its grim coda, never truly reached the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, with lurid stories of ocean tragedies like ``The
Perfect Storm'' begetting a lucrative publishing phenomenon, the
dark past of this island better known for its wealthy tourists is
being packaged as a literary smash.
</P>
<P>
   Viking books paid Nantucket author Nat Philbrick a reported $1.2
million advance to write an account of the tragedy, which is
expected to be released in six months. For the past year Philbrick
has written from the dim basement of his quaint Nantucket home.
Filed in his makeshift office are neatly labeled folders: Whaling,
Starvation and Dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   And one more: Cannibalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has always been a reticent, always been a closed
community,'' explained David Wood, a Nantucket native and retired
schoolteacher. ``The secret is out of the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   The secret dates back to the island's heyday, the early 1800s,
when Nantucket was the world's greatest whaling port. The roofs at
the top of shingled houses were used as lookouts for incoming
ships. For a Nantucketer, the whale's oil, so precious that it was
used to anoint the pope, provided unimagined riches.
</P>
<P>
   But like so many sources of wealth, it came with a heavy cost.
</P>
<P>
   The bloody whale trade claimed many casualties _ the lookouts
atop the whalers' homes became known as ``widows' walks'' _ but the
Essex tragedy was the one that would rock the Quaker town through
the ages.
</P>
<P>
   The account of the tragedy unravels from Philbrick's research
and the memoirs of the ship's first mate.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 12, 1819, Captain George Pollard and his crew of 20
boarded the Essex and began their voyage to the rich whaling
grounds of the Pacific. The officers on the ship were all
Nantucketers. Many crew members were from Cape Cod. One came from
England, and five whalers _ all African-Americans _ arrived from
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The tour went well for more than a year. By October 1820, the
crew had gathered 900 barrels of sperm oil before reaching the
Galapagos Islands. But a month later, on Nov. 20, the voyage took a
deadly turn.
</P>
<P>
   Owen Chase, the first mate, was repairing his smaller whaleboat
on deck when he turned and saw a giant sperm whale lying quietly on
the sea surface. As he gazed at the huge mammal, it suddenly rushed
the boat, thrusting and parting the waters like a locomotive.
</P>
<P>
   Chase was stunned. Whales usually were either docile or playful.
With a shudder, Chase realized that the pursuers of whales were
about to become the pursued.
</P>
<P>
   The giant animal struck the boat with a terrifying heave,
sending crew members sprawling across the deck. Then it turned and
attacked again. Within minutes, the Essex was taking on water. Soon
it was a crumpled, listing wreck.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a supposedly dumb beast to deliberately sink a ship _ that
is horrifying,'' said Renny Stackpole, a Nantucket native and
maritime scholar. ``Melville locked on to this modus for the
conclusion of ``Moby-Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Captain Ahab, Melville's doomed protagonist, the crew of
the Essex seemed to be led by supernatural forces of bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   Their ship beyond repair, the men retreated to three smaller
whaleboats, with some provisions, and headed south. For one month,
they floated at sea on the 28-foot skiffs before landing on a
barren island. The portents were bad: They found little food, very
little water, and, ominously, the skeletal remains of six men who
apparently had been shipwrecked there decades in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the crew members elected to remain on the island while
Pollard and the other 17 crew members returned to the sea. The
three boats, leaking and ragged, took to the sea with one commanded
by the captain; another headed by First Mate Chase, and a third
under the command of another officer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their efforts to stay together, a severe storm soon
separated the boats. With provisions running out, three crew
members starved to death.
</P>
<P>
   It was after one sailor became delirious and died on Chase's
boat that the first mate suggested using the body for food. His
crew of three men agreed _ grimly separating the limbs and
``devouring'' the heart, according to his later account.
</P>
<P>
   The three men removed the flesh from the body, roasted it, and
ate for nine days before being rescued off the coast of South
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew not whose lot it would fall next, either die or be
shot,'' wrote Chase, explaining that the starving men were prepared
to resort to murder to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an even grimmer story was unfolding on the boat
commanded by Pollard. The captain's boat had briefly reunited with
the third boat, only to be swept apart again by another violent
storm. The third boat was never seen again.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Pollard's crew members began starving. On Feb. 1, 1821,
the last four survivors, all Nantucketers, picked straws. They
apparently agreed that the loser of the lottery would be killed and
then consumed by the remaining crew. The shortest lot went to the
captain's teenage cousin, who agreed to be shot and then eaten.
</P>
<P>
   ``My lad, my lad,'' exclaimed the captain. ``If you don't like
your lot I will shoot the first man who touches you.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy, uncertain whether to choose death or continued
suffering, said he would accept his fate like a man.
</P>
<P>
   He was shot and eaten.
</P>
<P>
   Another man died naturally and was used for food before the
captain and another teenage crew member were rescued off the
Chilean coast.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, all three men who chose to stay on the barren island
were rescued months later by a vessel sent from Nantucket to search
for the crew of the Essex. But only five men _ all Nantucketers _
made it off the whaleboats alive.
</P>
<P>
   News of the shipwreck had already reached the island newspapers
by the time of the rescues. Rumors of cannibalism, the worst
abomination in the eyes of Quakers, blew through the town like a
tempest.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the survivors' return to Nantucket, dozens of
islanders stood by the bay not uttering a word as the weary men
walked to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mother of the youngster that pulled the unlucky lot
couldn't stand the sight of the captain after he told her of her
son's fate,'' said Philbrick.
</P>
<P>
   But, Philbrick said, many Nantucketers felt sorry for the
captain and supported him by giving him another job as commander of
a ship. But when that was shipwrecked, too, near the Hawaiian
Islands, the 34-year-old captain was deemed unlucky, and never went
to sea again. He spent the rest of his years walking the
cobblestone streets as the town's night watchman.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, there are aspects of the Essex disaster that puzzle
Nantucket scholars.
</P>
<P>
   One mystery, say Stackpole and Philbrick, is why the four black
men on the captain's boat were the first to die. It may have been
mere coincidence, since there is no evidence to show that the men
were killed. But their unexplained deaths have always haunted the
abolitionist community that knew too well of the sometimes brutal
treatment of black whalers.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, the story of the Essex became an international
scandal, with reporters from as far away as Australia covering it.
Melville and Ralph Waldo Emerson would visit the captain, said
Philbrick, and pepper him with questions.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the Essex shipwreck, Melville was known mainly as
the author of pulp adventure novels, drawing on his youthful
experience as a whaler. ``Moby-Dick,'' punctuated by the dramatic
whale attack drawn from the Essex tragedy, became the greatest
American novel in the eyes of many scholars.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after its publication, as the fame of ``Moby-Dick'' grew,
memories of the Essex disaster waned: It was no longer a legendary
story of survival but the backdrop for a great novel. Soon the
stories that once scandalized the island quieted into a delicate
silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nantucketers wouldn't talk about it for the better part of the
century,'' said Stackpole.
</P>
<P>
   But when the whaling industry was replaced by tourism and all
the blood relatives of the victims had died, locals began to accept
the tragedy as part of their history, said Jim Patrick, a local
writer and house painter.
</P>
<P>
   Philbrick, 43, moved to Nantucket to become an author 14 years
ago, carrying memories of childhood tales of the Essex disaster. As
a little boy in Pittsburgh, Philbrick's uncle and father, both
maritime scholars, would tell him stories of the whale that
destroyed the Nantucket vessel.
</P>
<P>
   So two years ago, when Philbrick, who heads an institute on
maritime tradition in Nantucket, was trying to get Sebastian
Junger, author of ``The Perfect Storm,'' to speak on the island, he
mentioned the idea of writing a book about the Essex to the
author's agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a boy it was a story about a whale, but as an adult who
moved to Nantucket, I began to relate to these men,'' Philbrick
said. ``I began to see what living this tragedy must have been
like.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, in Nantucket, discussions of the Essex and the impending
book can be heard in local coffee houses, and even in a senior
community center.
</P>
<P>
   Sarcasm about cannibalism is common on the island: ``You mean
the story about our ancestors eating our other ancestors,'' quipped
a local waitress as she served lunch to her customers.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Atlantic Cafe, a popular tavern, Peter Eldridge, a
burly carpenter, sipped a beer and defended the actions of the
Essex survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long time ago,'' he said. ``If you strip off our
clothes and put us out there _ we are all animals. It would be no
different if the people had been from anywhere else in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of Eldridge, the survivors, especially the doomed
captain, are heroes.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no evidence that the survivors saw it that way.
</P>
<P>
   The first mate, Chase, went on to become a successful seaman,
one of the wealthier captains on Nantucket. But in his twilight
years, memories of cannibalism began to haunt him.
</P>
<P>
   The feeble old man, still living on the island, would order
twice the amount of groceries needed for his prosperous household _
enough food for an entire ship's crew _ and hoard it in the attic,
so he would never grow hungry.
</P>
<P>
   He died insane.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from ``The Loss of the Essex: Sunk by a Whale'' by
Edouard A. Stackpole was used in this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 1402EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
