<SLUG> BC-TV-WEBRIOT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MTV'S ATTEMPT AT HARMONIC CONVERGENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four contestants are suspended on spherical chairs that hang
like miniature meteors on a futuristic set. Their eyes are glued on
host Ahmet Zappa, who is projected on a gigantic screen.
Fashionably bald with a polished pate and aerodynamic glasses, the
animated Zappa pushes his face right up to the camera and does a
shout-out for the folks at home. ``Log on. Do it now,'' he says,
with a kind of ironic urgency. This is, he announces, ``the only
game show where you get to play naked.''
</P>
<P>
   The on-air contenders, who go by such cyber nicknames as
VidKitten, D'Lite, and Flirtz a Lot, are suitably clothed for the
MTV universe, but the folks playing along at home could, in fact,
be competing in the buff. That's part of the zany appeal of
``webRIOT,'' the first interactive game show that allows viewers to
play along on the Internet at MTV.com. The weekday music trivia
show, which debuts on MTV  &UR; today &LR;  at 5 p.m., allows some 50,000
at-home viewers to compete for prizes as they answer the same
questions as the on-air contestants.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, game-show enthusiasts have been playing along at home
for years, screaming answers like ``Who is John Galt?'' and advice
like ``Buy a vowel!'' at their television sets. But with
``webRIOT,'' the answers at home actually count.
</P>
<P>
   The program is an experiment in convergence, the term for the
merging of television and Web programming. As more and more
television viewers go on line, entertainment executives are racing
to find ways to bring the two mediums together. An estimated 23
percent of American households have a computer and television in
the same room, according to a recent study by Paul Kagan Associates
and Showtime Networks, and that number is sure to grow. But past
attempts at convergence have delivered lots of hype and little
substance, doing nothing more than combining taped sitcoms with
live, on-line chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The MTV effort pushes the interactivity a bit further while also
attempting to bring together the enthusiasm for such on-line games
as ``You Don't Know Jack'' with the attitude and swagger of hip-hop
and rap. Zappa, a live wire who admits a fondness for caffeine,
courts the viewers at home with his irreverent patter. Yet he knows
there is something contrived about conducting a conversation with
the cyber audience; the show is taped, so the at-home contestants
are playing ``live'' against a taped broadcast. ``When I do a
shoutout like, `Hey, all you gamers in Cincinnati!' I know it's not
the lamest thing, but it's pretty close,'' Zappa says during a
telephone interview from the ``webRIOT'' studio in Los Angeles. ``I
try to make it entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, which will air Monday through Friday, is produced and
taped like most other game shows, although MTV is showing two
different versions on the East and West coasts, which will go on at
different times. ``That's to minimize cheating,'' says Rick
Holzman, vice president of MTV Online. ``We don't want you to be
able to call your friend in Sheboygan for the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   The system is set up to accommodate 25,000 on-line competitors
each for both the East and West coast segments; it also
accommodates players at any connection speed. The top 10 players at
home are announced in a graphic at the end of the show, which
includes other ``live'' graphics recognizing what's happening in
the on-line game. Bright-colored windows pop up on the television
screen to report the on-line activity: In the pilot, these
informational boxes included tidbits like ``USC Grl had two perfect
games in a row. Higher education pays off.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is designed to look like a computer screen with
multiple windows. On the television screen, music videos by such
artists as TLC and the Red Hot Chili Peppers play in one window
while the contestants answer trivia questions about the featured
artists. Factoids pop up in separate windows at appropriate times;
during a Beastie Boys video, the screen flashed this gem: ``The
Supreme Court has never officially recognized the right to party.''
</P>
<P>
   The show tries to blend geek humor and youth culture. The grand
prize for the on-line players is a 2000 Volkswagen Beetle _ or as
Zappa says, a Y2K Bug. On ``webRIOT,'' it's cool to be a nerd.
``I'm a total loser,'' says Zappa, 25. ``I love e-mail, and I love
the Internet.'' He also loves playing the role of cyberhost, both
on and off camera. ``I'm a robot from the future programmed to make
`webRIOT' the most infectious show on the planet,'' he says.
``People are going to catch it like a cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's a pitch. The host goes on to say that his father,
the late rocker Frank Zappa, landed on another planet and beamed
him back to Earth. The young Zappa will tell you a lot of things,
but he'll also tell you he is ``totally making all this stuff up.''
</P>
<P>
   He is claiming to be an android because the show is aiming for a
futuristic feel. At the same time, it is exploiting the
old-fashioned game-show genre that is so popular this season with
the success of ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody would mistake Zappa for ``Millionaire'' host Regis
Philbin, but he does admit an affection for old quiz shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a child I watched them all the time, and I'm peachy pleased
with the whole scenario,'' he says. ``I'm a huge fan of `Press Your
Luck,' `The Price Is Right,' `Let's Make a Deal.' `Tic Tac Dough'
was the best _ and `The Joker's Wild.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``WebRIOT'' is a kind of retro-futuristic-musical hybrid _ ``The
Jetsons'' meet ``Jeopardy.'' But it's still unclear if the on-line
part will work. In January, when ABC tried to synchronize a
televised college bowl game with a Web program, the experiment was
an exercise in frustration because most viewers couldn't access the
Web site. That's why MTV capped the number of contestants _ to
avoid logjams, says Holzman.
</P>
<P>
   MTV has been working up to ``webRIOT'' with experiments in
convergent programming, such as an on-line auction of items from
the ``Real World'' set and a discontinued show called ``Yak Live,''
which let viewers chat on line as they watched music videos on
television. The network faces increasing competition for young
viewers, as on-line entertainment companies like Den.net and
Pseudo.com offer Web programming. Everybody in Hollywood, in fact,
is trying to figure out how to bring their existing products into
the virtual world. But Den, in particular, is aggressively trying
to become ``the MTV of the Y Generation.'' So far, most attempts at
on-line entertainment have simply mimicked television, and it's not
clear yet if ``webRIOT'' is any different. Naturally, Holzman
thinks it is. ``Everyone else wants to be the MTV of the Internet,
but MTV is the MTV of the Internet,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
