<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BEAUTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UGLY `AMERICAN BEAUTY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reviewers have lavished some of their highest praise this year
on ``American Beauty,'' the Sam Mendes film anchored by two of the
screen's most intelligent actors, Kevin Spacey and Annette Bening.
Its subject _ the profound dysfunction of the American family _ is
always timely, if not particularly original. So the package will no
doubt be a contender for statues on Oscar night.
</P>
<P>
   Yet something went very wrong here. The performances of Spacey
and Bening, which unfold with perfect pitch, mutate into the
grotesque. The film implodes into a parody of itself and collapses
under the weight of overwriting and overacting. It tries to be both
a comedy and a profound look at suburbia. Because it reached for
both, it failed at each.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Spacey's brains are plastered al dente on his
kitchen wall _ an unneccessary display of organ tissue _ every
character in the movie has lost his or her shape. They end up
resembling distorted faces in a fun house mirror, initially amusing
but ultimately revolting. If this was Mendes's intention, he could
have achieved it with a discipline and a spareness utterly lacking
in this film. What we are left with is an intriguing,
self-indulgent mess.
</P>
<P>
   Why the raves from serious critics? Perhaps because of the
paucity of quality films this year. Quick, what are the class acts
of 1999? Where is the ``Saving Private Ryan'' or ``Shakespeare In
Love''? ``American Beauty'' was a brave project that descended into
bathos as it progressed. Still, how many efforts have there been
recently that even attempted to scale such heights? Critics are
suckers for such stabs, and this film is a case in point.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is referred to as a comedy, but it ceases to be funny
long before it ends. Its emotional and physical violence is coarse,
and there is too much of it: marital disintegration, homophobia,
homosexuality, teenage and adult drug use, adultery, promiscuity,
all-purpose anomie. Is there anything I missed here?
</P>
<P>
   Some womhave seen the film complain that it is
misogynist, that all of the women in it are portrayed in an
unflattering way. Yet most of the men fare no better. The only
happy people appear to be the two gay neighbors who bring a welcome
basket to the door of the twisted Marine colonel, overplayed by the
fine actor Chris Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   Truly harrowing screen relationships are powerful. Witness the
torque of Edward Albee's ``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'' The
entire cast, Richard Burton in particular, reduces us to aspic.
Really good movies like that don't need to spell out every shard of
dysfunction presented in ``American Beauty'' to make their point.
</P>
<P>
   The film does have its moments. The home movie footage taken by
the colonel's son, played by Wes Bentley, of an empty pastic bag
blowing in a vacant wind is mesmerizing. Bening's contributions to
the motel sex she has with Peter Gallagher, a fellow realtor in the
film whose license plate reads ``R.E. KING,'' are heroic. Spacey,
as always, is droll and distant. We accept that he is in on a
cosmic joke he will never share with us. He has earned that
latitude. And Thora Birch, who plays his daughter, Jane, is often
excellent as a tortured, untethered teen.
</P>
<P>
   But we don't need Spacey to give up his career for a fast-food
job, trade his Camry for a vintage red Firebird, start pumping iron
and smoking dope to grasp that he craves to rekindle his lost
youth. Any two of those would have done fine. Bening need not
clutch a pistol while listening to a motivational tape about power
and control in her Mercedes SUV to convince us that she is
contemplating something extreme.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Cooper truly did not need to blow Spacey's head off at
point-blank range, and his kid could have toned down his addictive
filming of Spacey's daughter, Jane, with his hand-held camera. The
unmasking of Jane's friend, Angela, from man-eating vixen to
insecure virgin had nothing much to do with anything. All in all,
this is a stew that gives heartburn.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps superior actors like Spacey and Bening will continue to
seduce us against our better instincts when they work in such
flawed productions. They are, after all, such joys to watch. But we
should resist such laxity. We can adore them without losing our
bead on the movies they make. ``American Beauty'' is no American
beauty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 1411EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3946 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-NIXON-BOS &LR;      11-29 1707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-NIXON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN ADAMS LISTENS TO HIS OWN PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard M. Nixon made headlines when he went to China in 1972,
and John Adams and Alice Goodman made headlines 15 years later when
they made an opera about that historic journey. The production of
``Nixon in China'' Peter Sellars created for the Houston Grand
Opera went round the world, and it made its composer famous in some
quarters, notorious in others.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically there has not been a complete performance of
``Nixon in China'' in New York since its debut season. This week
Robert Spano leads concert performances of the opera with the
Brooklyn Philharmonic and two members of the original cast, James
Maddalena (Nixon) and Thomas Hammons (Henry Kissinger).
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn performances coincide with Nonesuch's release of
``The John Adams Earbox,'' a 10-CD celebration of the composer's
unparalleled 14-year association with the label. The box collects
most of Nonesuch's Adams recordings, along with a new recording of
``Harmonium,'' and two previously unrecorded works, ``Slonimsky's
Earbox'' and ``Lollapalooza.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently Adams came onto the phone from the Nonesuch offices to
talk about his career as a ``California composer'' who was born in
Worcester (Feb. 15, 1947) and whose education included six years at
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at Harvard from 1965 to 1971, the turbulent years, in
the thick of it all,'' Adams says. ``The month before I graduated
as an undergraduate was when Harvard Yard was invaded by the Boston
Police. I didn't occupy University Hall, but I did march, and I was
once chased down Mass Ave. by a cop from Brockton. It was like a
duck shoot for the police. I was bonked on the backside and I lost
my glasses, but I have no real stripes to show for the
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams describes his academic experiences with some care. ``There
were key people who were very meaningful to me, above and beyond
all, Luise Vosgerchian. I met her before I went to Harvard, when I
was still a high school kid, at a summer course up at Darmouth. She
discovered me. I had a lot of weaknesses. I was not really a
pianist, not really a clarinetist, but she was able to see whatever
was there in its embryonic form, and she encouraged me. That's why
I still feel an enormous affection and gratitude towards her.
Later, during my time at Harvard, I came into contact with Leon
Kirchner, and he is so strong a figure that it was impossible not
to be influenced by him in one way or another. We still stay in
touch today.''
</P>
<P>
   During his Harvard period, Adams says he was more active as a
conductor than as a composer. ``One of my events there was a
production of `The Marriage of Figaro' in Leverett House that I
conducted. It was directed by John Lithgow, and one of the sopranos
was Lucy Shelton. I also conducted the Bach Society Orchestra,
which provided an opportunity which no other university or
conservatory in the country offers; I could do everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams says he began composing ``in earnest'' during his senior
year. ``This was the period of high modernism. The faculty was torn
between Schoenberg and Stravinsky; that was the big issue. Webern,
if not consciously, at least obliquely, was held up to us as a
model of what a composer should be. I was experiencing severe
cognitive dissonance between Paine Hall and Harvard Square. This
was a time, between 1968 and '71, when I could encounter some of
the greatest pop music ever produced. I even wrote rock criticism
for The Crimson, and I realized, `Now wait a moment, there's a
major split going on here.' On the one hand, I was being a good boy
and writing what was expected of me; on the other hand, what I
really loved was far looser, more in touch with American culture,
and more expressive of what it means to be an American living at
this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was inevitable. ``I fled in my Volkswagen bug. I went
to San Francisco, where the only person I knew was the late
composer Ivan Tcherepnin, who was teaching at the San Francisco
Conservatory. Ivan was one of the dearest people I have ever known.
I found a job on the waterfront, working in a warehouse in Oakland.
I had a year of being a blue-collar worker and then I realized I
was not going to be able to make an Ivesian career out of composing
on the weekends.''
</P>
<P>
   Gradually Adams began to discover his voice. He taught and
conducted new-music concerts at the San Francisco Conservatory; he
composed his first ``minimalist'' works, ``Phrygian Gates'' for
piano and ``Shaker Loops'' for string septet. He made a connection
with Edo de Waart, who appointed him new-music adviser for the San
Francisco Symphony, and in 1981 he composed ``Harmonium.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Recording relationship &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The connection with Nonesuch came in 1984, thanks to
``Harmonium.'' ``That's when I met Bob Hurwitz, who runs the
company. Back then he was working for ECM, which is mostly a jazz
label, the label of Keith Jarrett. But the company wanted to branch
out and do some new orchestral music. They sent Bob out to San
Francisco when the first performance of `Harmonium' was going on,
and we made the first recording. Within a year, Bob had moved over
to Nonesuch, and I was one of the first people he called. He
proposed a long-term relationship, on the model of what Stravinsky
had had at Columbia Records, but I think my relationship with
Nonesuch has been far better than either Stravinsky or Aaron
Copland enjoyed with Columbia. Nonesuch has been absolutely
faithful and devoted, and they have recorded the good, the bad, and
the ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   The recording of ``Harmonium'' with de Waart and the San
Francisco Symphony was on ECM, never on Nonesuch, so there is a new
recording, with Adams himself conducting the San Francisco Symphony
and Chorus, in the ``Earbox.'' The set includes highlights from the
complete recordings of ``Nixon in China'' and ``The Death of
Klinghoffer,'' as well as the single disc of ``I Was Looking At The
Ceiling and Then I Saw The Sky,'' which was never recorded
complete.
</P>
<P>
   One controversial scene from ``The Death of Klinghoffer,'' the
Klinghoffer family gathered around the television console, was
never recorded, and Adams has dropped it from the score. ``I lopped
it off, not only because it was unnecessarily controversial and
misleading, but it also made the first act ridiculously long. And
it didn't add to the gravity of the work. My only fear is that one
day somebody like Roger Norrington will unearth it and peform it!
Pierre Boulez once said that the worst thing he could imagine would
be to recreate the premiere of his `Le Marteau sans Maitre.' ''
</P>
<P>
   All three Adams operas were first staged by Peter Sellars, and
Sellars has been involved in one of Adams's big, new upcoming
projects, an oratorio about the life of Christ that will be
premiered next December in Paris. ``It can be done as a fully
staged work or as an oratorio. With Peter there is some deep
chemistry that seems to work despite the fact we fight tooth and
nail every inch of the way, particularly once we get up on stage.
My past is as a lapsed Episcopalian, but one of the few rituals I
love is the Christmas season. I think this story is something I
have always wanted to do, and something he might like to stage, the
way he staged Stravinsky's `Oedipus Rex.' The texts are all by
Hispanic women _ Mexican, Nicaraguan, Chilean _ along with the King
James Version of the Bible. Alice Goodman was originaly involved
with this project too, but had to withdraw, but I want to say how
fervently I hope to work with her again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nixon'' is due for a new staging in London and later in San
Francisco. ``There will also be a new production of `Klinghoffer'
in Finland, so despite what you may read in The New York Times, the
opera is alive and healthy. My feeling about opera is that writing
one is a little like buying a long-term bond. There is so little
room in the repertory, that it takes time, often several
generations, for a new work to break in. Look at Leonard
Bernstein's `Candide' and how much ridicule that took before it
started being done. It was completely dormant at the time I was
growing up, but now of course it is recognized as an important part
of the American repertory.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Major minimalist &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adams was a key figure in the so-called ``minimalist school,''
although he wrote comparatively little purely minimalist music.
``We use handles to describe things, and they are very useful. If I
say `Victorian novel,' you know I am not talking about Joyce.
Minimalism has been a major force in my musical language, and I
don't have a problem with the term; people know what we're talking
about when you use the word, and it is threaded through my music.
Some pieces show more minimalist principles than others. `The Death
of Klinghoffer' was a kind of watershed for me, a very serious
story engaging very heavy issues. Much as I love the minimalist
classics, they operate on a certain level, not superficial _ but on
a narrow emotional band width. I felt absolutely prodded by the
story and by Alice Goodman's text to find a language that was
deeper and more complex, and I took a lot of criticism for that. My
language became less rigorous, more diffuse, more synthetic. I came
out of the opera with a larger, more volatile, compositional
palette, including dissonance, and a more mercurial formal
language. I have followed it with some kind of wacky results.''
</P>
<P>
   By ``wacky'' Adams probably means ``unpredictable.'' The Chamber
Symphony, for example, he describes as ``very good-natured.'' The
Violin Concerto, on the other hand, ``starts off in `Klinghoffer'
mode and then lights off into new territory. My most recent pieces
are `Century Rolls,'' for piano and orchestra, and a big orchestral
piece, `Naive and Sentimental Music.' I'm still so close to these
pieces that I can't tell you where the language has gone or is
going, except that it may be more emphatically tonal than ever.
I've been heartened to see composers of younger generations taking
what I did as a cue for a more embracing synthesis of languages
rather than pursuing any kind of purist or modernist path.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
