<HEADLINE>
A CRISP VIEW OF THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Quentin Crisp, Writer and Actor on Gay Themes, Dies at 90,''
read the headline on The New York Times obituary. He would have
enjoyed his obit's prominent placement _ at the top of the page _
although he might not have appreciated the characterization. True,
he was a writer and an actor, and he was openly and flamboyantly
gay long before it was acceptable, the self-described ``stately
homo of England.''
</P>
<P>
   More than any of these things, he was famous for being himself.
``I am what I am and that's that,'' he said in an interview with
Gyles Brandreth of the Sunday Telegraph a few days before he died.
</P>
<P>
   If style is wit, as he observed, Crisp was one of the most
stylish individuals of his era, the author of countless pointed
epigrams. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   --``To know all is not to forgive all. It is to despise
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   --``Live alone. The continued propinquity of another human being
cramps the style after a time, unless that person is someone you
think you love. Then the burden becomes intolerable.''
</P>
<P>
   --``Never try to keep up with the Joneses. Drag them down to
your level. It's cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   He was often compared to Oscar Wilde, a comparison he did not
relish because he believed that Wilde was ashamed of his own
homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Crisp came to Boston in 1981 to promote one of his books, ``How
to Have a Lifestyle.'' In the muted light of the Ritz Bar, he
looked from a distance like a Boston dowager, wrapped in scarves
and flowing garments. His white hair was swept up under a soft
black hat. He wore eye shadow, lipstick, and too much foundation _
a mistake for a man, or a woman, of a certain age, but it was part
of the Crisp style to trowel on makeup. He acquired the habit when
he was young, in London before World War II, when he was developing
an effeminate look and manner that regularly got him beaten up by
strangers, fired from jobs, and thrown out of restaurants and bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wore very little (makeup) at first,'' he told one
interviewer, ``but exhibitionism becomes like a drug. Eventually
you can take a dose that would kill anyone just starting out.''
</P>
<P>
   Crisp was born Denis Pratt, the third son of a middle-class
English family. His father was a London solicitor and his mother a
former governess who, he once wrote, ``rightly regarded the
suburbia in which we were compelled to live as a sort of purgatory
of style.''
</P>
<P>
   He was effeminate as a child, ``an object of mild ridicule from
birth,'' a misfit at school. As a young man, he changed his name
and tried several artistic lines of work. For a few months he was a
prostitute. In 1942, he became an art school model, and for the
next 30 years he earned a living posing nude. During these years,
he became a familiar figure in London's bohemian circles. He lived
in a single room, which he never cleaned. ``The dust doesn't get
any worse after three years,'' he observed.
</P>
<P>
   His autobiography, ``The Naked Civil Servant,'' was made into a
television film starring John Hurt in 1975. At 66, Crisp became a
celebrity. He launched a career as an actor, in a one-man show
about his life. In 1977, he moved to New York, where he resided
until his death. In England, he said, ``the system is benign and
the people are hostile. In America, the people are friendly and the
system is brutal.''
</P>
<P>
   Crisp's life was a study in gay pride, although he insisted that
the term was an oxymoron. He resisted the idea that homosexuality
is ``normal.'' This did nothing to endear Crisp to many in the gay
community, but it was his style never to try to endear himself to
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe Columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
