<HEADLINE>
HOW DO YOU MEASURE A BLACK HOLE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Can any object become a black hole? Is there a formula for
determining the dimensions of, say, the earth, if it became dense
enough to become a black hole?
</P>
<P>
   R.G., San Antonio &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. As black holes continue to absorb matter, wouldn't they grow
in physical size?
</P>
<P>
   A.A. Medford, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. First, a simple definition of a black hole, thanks to Roger
Brissenden of the Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory. He helps
run the orbiting Chandra X-Ray Space Telescope, which tries to find
things like black holes.
</P>
<P>
   He says a black hole is an object in space so massive and dense
that the gravitational force is too powerful for anything, even
light, to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists think they form in a couple of ways. One is stellar
death. A star burns by fusing the nuclei of its hydrogen and helium
atoms together. Ultimately, toward the end of the star's fuel
supply, these reactions can lead to a fantastic explosion called a
supernova. Brissenden says the explosion sends some of the star's
material outward, and some inward. If enough material is sent
inward, it can collapse into a black hole.
</P>
<P>
   Some stars don't become supernovas when they die, they just
collapse, and they can produce black holes too.
</P>
<P>
   A non-stellar theory is that gravity starts to draw clouds of
interstellar gas together, ultimately drawing in enough matter so
the mass condenses into a black hole. Astrophysicists think there's
a black hole like this at the center of our Milky Way galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   Though we can't see them, we can tell black holes are there
because we can see what their gravitational pull is doing to
objects nearby. For example, a black hole in what astronomers call
a binary system, a kind of celestial pas de deux with a normal
star, is pulling material away from the edge of that star and
toward the black hole. That material forms an accretion ring, kind
of like Saturn's rings, around the black hole, since there's too
much matter to be pulled into the black hole all at once.
</P>
<P>
   The material in the accretion ring is hot and gives off light
and X-rays that devices like the Chandra and Hubble telescopes can
detect. Brissenden says ``We can see it right at what we call the
event horizon of the black hole. That's the very edge of the black
hole itself. We can see X-rays from accretion ring material less
than one second before it disappears into the black hole.''
</P>
<P>
   To become a black hole, an object has to be really big. ``It has
to have enough material to be three times heavier than the sun in
order to condense that much,'' Brissenden explains.
</P>
<P>
   Brissenden says the formula for figuring out the size of black
holes is: 2 times G (the gravitational constant) times M (the mass
of the object) divided by C-squared (the speed of light, also a
constant). Applying the formula to determine the size of black
holes to the sun, you get an idea of how incredibly dense a black
hole really is. The entire mass of the sun, which is approximately
870,000 miles wide, would shrink down to 7.45 miles across.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
