Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-CHILD (Miami) _ A 5-year-old Cuban boy who survived a
Thanksgiving Day rafting tragedy by clinging to an inner tube for
two days has become the focus of an international tug-of-war. Cuba
blames the United States for the tragedy and says the child had
been kidnapped by his mother, who died during the voyage. The boy's
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, and Cuba's Foreign Ministry have
demanded his return. Gonzalez has filed a complaint with the United
Nations to draw international attention to the issue. By David
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNS-UNION (Undated) _ The National Labor Relations Board,
reversing itself, says that medical interns and residents at
private hospitals can form unions. Public hospital interns already
have unions but those at private hospitals have been banned because
of an earlier NLRB ruling that said interns are students not
employees. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BOOK (New York) _ A small Manhattan publishing house has
agreed to publish 25,000 copies of James Hatfield's controversial
book on George W. Bush, ``Making of an American President.'' The
author stands by the drug charges in the book but admits to his own
prison past. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-CALLS (Undated) _ For Ruth Smith, the telephone call from
prison was a way for her cousin to speak with his dying mother. For
Tulen Rivera, the calls from prison are an opportunity for her
three boys to speak with their father. For Ruby Jackson, speaking
by phone with her imprisoned husband was a chance to talk without
having to spend eight hours on an overnight bus. But for New York
state, like most other states, telephone calls from prison are
something else. They are a way to make money. Under current state
policy, the families of inmates are charged the highest possible
rates for calls from prisons, and most of the money is kept by the
state. By John Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
