   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   For other Science Times stories, see the separate science
budget.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CAROLINA-FLOODS (Undated) _ Scientists fear that the
post-hurricane flood of eastern North Carolina has created an
ecological time bomb, and they fear for the biologically rich
waters that separate the famous Outer Banks from the Carolina
mainland. This complex of sounds, bays and inlets comprises the
second largest estuary in the country, after Chesapeake Bay, and is
one of the nation's most important incubators of marine life.
Rarely have ecologists confronted such a striking example of what
can happen when a first-order natural disturbance is combined with
a first-order disturbance of the natural world by humans. By
William K. Stevens. (1700 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COSMOLOGY-PHYSICS (Undated) _ Continued evidence over the
last year that the expansion of the universe is accelerating has
provided fresh new evidence of the distressing finding that
something in the wastelands of space could be pushing against
gravity. So scientists are reluctantly accepting the notion that
something in the most fundamental theories of physics is terribly
wrong. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-POLIO (Undated) _ The Doctor's World: The provocative
theory that AIDS is a manufactured disaster arising from early
testing of the polio vaccine in Africa seemed farfetched when it
first came to public attention, in an article in Rolling Stone in
1992. Most scientists dismissed it after a scientific committee
reviewed the theory and deemed the probability very low. But that
panel based its conclusion in part on a published finding that was
later shown to be in error. And now a remarkable new book, ``The
River'' by Edward Hooper, offers tantalizing clues to revive and
expand the polio vaccine theory. By Lawrence K. Altman. (1900
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Beijing) _ The recent trade agreement between the
United States and China has prompted a flurry of activity among
small Chinese investors and would-be investors, who have flocked to
one of the country's many new brokerage firms for the masses. A
slice of urban China, they came filled with hopes and worries,
theories and predictions about the economic impact of the deal. By
Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR-YEN (Undated) _ The Bank of Japan sells yen, its 10th
currency intervention in the last five months, but the currency is
little changed against the dollar and the euro in early trading.
Traders say they expect the yen to continue to strengthen in the
absence of any indication that either the United States or the
European Central Bank will join the Bank of Japan. By Jonathan
Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-BANKS (London) _ Royal Bank of Scotland announces its
$42.4 billion hostile bid for National Westminster Bank, in an
attempt to trump the Bank of Scotland. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
