<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTENSIFIED ATTACKS ON FREE PRESS DISTURBING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Tough hides are essential survival gear for
politicians and members of the news media who write about them, but
we all have chinks in our armor.
</P>
<P>
   People who criticize my work _ and there are folks out there who
think my thinking is muddled and my talents mostly invisible _ are
doing what I am doing, which is practicing the First Amendment. And
as biting as some of their letters and e-mail might be, I respect
their right to speak their minds.
</P>
<P>
   But every time I see another public opinion survey doubting the
wisdom of allowing free expression by the media, my skin thins a
bit.
</P>
<P>
   The latest came across my desk just the other day, and it
included two media-related questions.
</P>
<P>
   According to this survey by the Scripps Howard Texas Poll, half
of Texans don't like the way the media have been covering the 2000
presidential campaign so far, while only 38 percent of Texans
approve. The rest either didn't know what they thought or refused
to answer the question.
</P>
<P>
   Those answers don't particularly bother me because some of our
coverage has been good and some hasn't. And even reporters involved
in the coverage may not necessarily agree with each other on which
has been which.
</P>
<P>
   But it may be helpful for pollsters to try to distinguish
between the public's opinions of the print and the electronic
media. There may not be a wide difference in public perception
between the two, but there often are significant differences
between how newspapers and most television or radio stations and
networks report and present stories.
</P>
<P>
   There also are major differences between commercial and
noncommercial radio and TV. The breathless, pseudo ``news'' shows
that compete with ``Bonanza'' reruns and ``Oprah'' on afternoon
television, for example, are an entirely different animal from what
one reads in most newspapers or hears on National Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   The more disturbing part of the Texas Poll, though, were the
answers to the second question, which asked which of the following
statements best reflected the respondents' thinking:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``There are times when the press should not be allowed to
publish or broadcast certain things.'' Or ... .
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Freedom of the press should be protected under all
circumstances.``
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-eight percent said that freedom of the press should be
protected, and 54 percent said the press should be restricted.
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown almost makes me wonder if we would have even had a
First Amendment if this group of Texans had been among our nation's
founding parents.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone who answered in favor of press restrictions would
probably insist that they are strong supporters of free speech,
free press and other First Amendment guarantees. They just think
that there should be certain restrictions on, say, reporting
violence, the private lives of public officials or any other type
of coverage that periodically angers readers and viewers. I sense
that many Texans are still worn out from the media's zealous
coverage of the Bill Clinton and Monica Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But, except for imposing recourse for libel, government can't
restrict press freedom without, in essence, destroying it. Freedom
of speech, freedom of the press, freedom of religion, all under the
First Amendment, mean just that _ freedom, not freedom with an
attached list of the latest politically correct exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Many people still want to shoot the messenger, blaming the
media's reporting for numerous social ills that government,
churches, the business community and everyone else have been unable
to solve.
</P>
<P>
   But we in the news business _ often in our competitive haste to
be the first with the latest development in a major story _ also
are guilty of mistakes, misjudgments and excesses that damage our
own credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Those mistakes occur in both print and electronic media. But
such problems are magnified by 24-hour, televised news coverage,
which encourages correspondents involved in live coverage of a
disaster or political controversy to hurriedly broadcast the latest
rumor around the country, often without a shred of substantiation.
</P>
<P>
   And the problems of shoot-from-the-lip reporting will only
worsen with the arrival of the Internet, where thousands of
information disseminators with computer access can report just
about anything with absolutely no regard for veracity.
</P>
<P>
   So, it is not difficult to conclude that the First Amendment's
guarantees of press freedom will come under even more attacks in
the foreseeable future _ from people exercising their First
Amendment guarantees of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 1424EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
