<SLUG> BC-MALL-BANS-WWW.STORES-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JITTERY MALL OWNERS BAN CYBER-SAVVY TENANTS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: St. Louis, MO)   (This 450-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``f'' financial news files.)  
  
 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The owners of the Saint Louis Gallery, a gleaming
shopping mall near the banks of the Mississippi River, have had a
vision. And it frightens them to death.
</P>
<P>
   In it, they see their beloved Galleria stripped of people.
Escalators that were once clogged with customers are empty and
switched off. Parking lots are deserted.
</P>
<P>
   Has the next recession hit? No. What they are fretting about in
St. Louis is the Internet and the notion _ exaggerated or otherwise
_ that the time will come soon when e-commerce will rule. When
nobody will bother to tramp around shops any more and will instead
buy almost everything online.
</P>
<P>
   Such is their anxiety that the Galleria owners have taken an
unprecedented step: they have barred all their tenants from
promoting their Web sites or anything to do with the Internet on
the premises.
</P>
<P>
   Anything that might direct customers to the World Wide Web is to
go. No www. addresses on shopping bags, no stickers on windows, no
posters or signs guiding shoppers to cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts are now watching to see whether other malls in
the United States will follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear, however, whether the Galleria can make the ban
stick. At least one of the shops, The Right Start, which
specializes in educational toys, has said it will sue to overturn
it. The Gap, which has no fewer than five shops in the Galleria,
said it might also take legal action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the Internet is a positive advertising tool that
actually drives traffic to the stores,'' a Gap spokeswoman
commented. ``We think it's an additional convenience for the
customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailers can assume they will get the income either way,
whether it comes via the Internet or over the traditional counter.
For the mall businesses, however, the issue is understandably more
urgent. ``It is important we protect our interest while initiating
important dialogue,'' a spokesman for the Galleria said.
</P>
<P>
   While Internet shopping in the U.S. still represents only a
fraction of overall retail sales, it is growing rapidly. Jupiter
Communications, an Internet consultant, predicted this week that
Americans this November and December will spend $6 billion online,
compared with $3.1 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it is often the wealthiest shoppers that turn to
online shopping, leaving the less prosperous in the malls.
</P>
<P>
   Another study, by the NPD group, offers mall owners some
consoling news, however. Americans are still loathe to buy clothes
via their computers. They want to try them on and touch them. In a
poll taken by NPD, nearly half of all Internet users in the U.S.
said they would never buy clothing online. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 450-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
