<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3986 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-THEATER-PARTY-SIMON-I     11-29 1547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-PARTY-SIMON-INTERVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEIL SIMON HAS NO RESERVATIONS ABOUT `THE DINNER PARTY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: Fact box at bottom) 
By REED JOHNSON 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; Take six characters in search of some painful personal truths.
Season generously with comic banter. Add a dash of topical
references to e-mail, the Internet and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, stir in the reputation of Neil Simon, America's most
commercially successful playwright of the past four decades, and
bake 90 minutes. Serves approximately 700.
</P>
<P>
   That, in simple form, is the recipe for ``The Dinner Party,''
the Neil Simon comedy-drama that will have its world premiere
Wednesday night at the Mark Taper Forum in downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Connoisseurs of the Simon canon are sure to recognize familiar
elements in ``The Dinner Party,'' which its producers hope to
transfer to Broadway sometime next year. But there's at least one
significant new ingredient in the author's 31st stage concoction.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than the playwright's usual Upper Manhattan milieu, ``The
Dinner Party'' is set in the private dining room of an exclusive
Paris restaurant. All six characters are French, as it happens, and
each is unaware of why he or she has been invited to this strange
repast or who the host is.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that's only the start of the surprises in store.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone connected with ``The Dinner Party'' is being mum about
the exact nature of those surprises and about the sharp turn the
play takes from farcical comedy to something much darker about
two-thirds of the way through. Still, from the details provided by
Simon and the cast, you might guess the play's continental
flavoring had some crucial bearing on its thematic substance.
</P>
<P>
   Au contraire, says the author.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't have to be French, they could've been anything, but
I wanted to make it a universal play,'' says Simon. ``If I made it
a New York play, I would've had to have written it differently. It
would have to be set there, the locale would be there, the speech
would be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I have the feeling that this is something that happens
with all married people _ the sense of it, anyway. The play is
slightly abstract, I think, because it's part farce, and then it
gets into this very interesting action of the play. I've never
written anything quite like this before.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon says parts of the new play are ``surreal,'' a description
that also fits the slightly incongruous makeup of the ensemble. It
includes three actors best-known (though by no means exclusively)
for their New York stage work _ Frances Conroy, Veanne Cox and
Edward Herrmann _ and two others, John Ritter and Henry Winkler,
more famous from TV and film roles.
</P>
<P>
   The cast's sixth member, Anette Michelle Sanders (``Diagnosis
Murder''), was named last Wednesday to replace Rita Wilson, who
left the show as a result of what Taper producing artistic director
Gordon Davidson described as ``mutual agreement based on creative
differences.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope and expect to work with Rita again on a future
project,'' Davidson said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The production is being directed by John Rando, whose work in
Southern California includes the recent Geffen Playhouse
productions of ``All in the Timing'' and ``Merton of the Movies,''
and ``The Comedy of Errors'' and ``Sylvia'' at the Old Globe in San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lid that's being kept on the show, a few salient
facts have emerged. Sex and haute cuisine are both involved (this
is France, after all). So are marriage and divorce, as you'd
probably expect from a playwright known as a kind of gourmet of
domestic discord.
</P>
<P>
   Cast members describe the dialogue as being like English
translated into French and then back into English, with Simon
employing longer, more complicated syntax than if the play were set
in, say, Yonkers or the author's native Brighton Beach in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler says the play's structure is ``like an onion'' with ``a
really delightful skin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts very much in a Neil Simon style, which is very
smart, very funny, very quick, and takes a left,'' he says. ``I've
watched it when I'm not in a scene, (and) you hear something new
all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the 72-year-old playwright has gone through at least
seven rewrites _ about normal for him. Gradually, the rewrite
process convinced him that the intermissionless work had to be
divided into two distinct moods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried in different drafts of this thing ... to get into
the real characters of the people and see what they're really like
in a dramatic way. And it didn't work. Once you start the comedy,
you've got to go with it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so the comedy moves on and on in the piece, and then
slides into this other place, where then they really reveal
themselves. And that's why I try to present them in sort of comic
situations so that you don't see them coming. Because that's what I
think life is like. We're not necessarily in comic situations, but
we're not in a major dramatic situation all the time. And then at
some point in our life they do come up.''
</P>
<P>
   Audiences who lost track of Simon's career sometime around the
Nixon administration may be surprised at what a serious playwright
he has become. Having learned his craft as a gag writer for TV
comic Sid Caesar, Simon has always been able to spin out one-liners
by the yard. But beginning in the late 1960s and early '70s, he has
increasingly bitten off tougher and more painful subject matter,
such as alcoholism and infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the first step I took in that direction was in `The
Gingerbread Lady,' and even in `Plaza Suite,''' says Simon. ``It
was around that time I said, you know, `It's got to be about
something, not just comedy for comedy's sake.'''
</P>
<P>
   That trajectory accelerated following the death of his first
wife, Joan Baim, in 1973 and on through his four subsequent
marriages, to actress Marsha Mason and, twice, Diane Lander. Simon
recently married actress Elaine Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   Digging increasingly into his own youth and early manhood, Simon
has produced the most critically acclaimed work of his career,
including the Brighton Beach trilogy (``Brighton Beach Memoirs,''
``Biloxi Blues'' and ``Broadway Bound''), the Pulitzer
Prize-winning ``Lost in Yonkers'' and his 1993 autobiographical
memory play about working with Sid Caesar, ``Laughter on the 23rd
Floor'' (which Showtime is adapting into a movie starring Nathan
Lane).
</P>
<P>
   Simon insists, however, that there are no autobiographical
elements in ``The Dinner Party.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not a thought,'' he says quickly. ``I mean, you never know
that, because your own personality comes through in the plays. But
I can tell you if I'm any of those people, or any of the people I
was married to are those people: They aren't. I think also by
putting it in France, it excluded that from happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet by all accounts, ``The Dinner Party'' demonstrates Simon's
later-life willingness to grapple with painful emotions and awkward
experiences. Simon titled his first volume of memoirs ``Rewrites,''
and in a way he seems to be continually rewriting certain aspects
of his plays in search of broader truths.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's reaching out from the center of his creative life, which
is basically the Catskills and Sid Caesar, you know, and the
vaudeville tradition, to a wider sense of what human beings are all
about,'' Herrmann observes.
</P>
<P>
   ``And like any good writer, he writes out of what he knows, like
`Brighton Beach Memoirs.' But in (``The Dinner Party''), it's like
a late Shakespeare play _ not to be too grandiose _ but he's
speculating on something the subject of which he knows a great deal
about: marriage and divorce and pain and the relationship between
men and women. I think he chose France because love is so
desperately important there. They define themselves largely by
their relationship to the opposite sex, where in the United States
we're fatuous enough to think that we define ourselves by other
things, not realizing of course that we're exactly the same. But we
define ourselves by our work, mainly.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves one mystery in this big `what if' of a play: What
will the actors actually eat during performances? No one seems to
know yet for sure.
</P>
<P>
   But as befits a story of food and relationships (however
flawed), cast and crew members regularly have been bringing in
goodies to pass around at rehearsal. Simon has treated the actors
to dinner, Winkler brings in suckers to share, and one night the
hairdresser stole the show with three boxes of Krispy Kreme
doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   And ``John Ritter gave me a birthday gift, which was a gigantic
basket of fruit, which was then donated to the room,'' Winkler
says. ``So then we all fed on that.''
</P>
<P>
   As they say in Paris, bon appetit. &QL; 
____ &UR;  &QL; 
What: &LR;  ``The Dinner Party.'' &UR;  &QL; 
Where: &LR;  Mark Taper Forum, Music Center of Los Angeles County, 135
N. Grand Ave., downtown. &UR;  &QL; 
When: &LR;  Wednesday through Jan. 16. Performances 8 p.m. Tuesdays
through Fridays, 2:30 and 8 p.m. Saturdays, 2:30 and 7:30 p.m.
Sundays. Matinees at 2:30 p.m. Dec. 23 and 30. Additional
performances at 8 p.m. Dec. 20 and 27. No performances Dec. 24, 25,
31 or Jan. 1. &UR;  &QL; 
Tickets: &LR;  $33 to $42. Call (213) 628-2772. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
