<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4050 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-ALMODOVAR-FEATUR     11-29 1592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ALMODOVAR-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALMODOVAR INDULGES FASCINATION WITH THE FEMININE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Pedro Almodovar, the movie maestro of Spanish
excess, has always loved women. He has often been characterized as
a filmmaker with an acute sensitivity to feminine feelings of the
most intimate, extreme and wacky sort.
</P>
<P>
   With his latest widely acclaimed feature, ``All About My
Mother,'' that unmistakably emerges as Almodovar's dominant
concern. More than ``What Have I Done to Deserve This?'' more than
``The Flower of My Secret,'' more than even his biggest
international hit, ``Women on the Verge of a Nervous Breakdown,''
``Mother'' dissects, tests and celebrates female sensibility in
strange and wonderful ways.
</P>
<P>
   It all began with a certain fascination that the 48-year-old
writer-director had as a child growing up in a small town in
Spain's central La Mancha region.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women who surrounded me in this village were very
interesting,'' Almodovar, wearing an olive guayabera shirt and his
trademark mop of unruly black hair, says in a mixture of English
and translated Spanish. ``It seemed to me that they possessed the
secret of life, that they seemed to live it better than the men
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only referring to my family, but men to me represented
power, and a power without explanation. I don't think that anymore,
but in the '50s, La Mancha was a very conservative, reactionary and
machista area. To get what they needed to get done, the women
learned how to act very well in real life. They were like
natural-born actresses who never went on stage but were always
acting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All About My Mother'' is all about acting one's way through
life's travails, among many other things. The central figure is
Manuela, played by Argentine actress Cecilia Roth. Her life as a
Madrid nurse who convinces grieving survivors to donate their
deceased's organs for transplant is upended when her own teen-age
son, Esteban, is killed. She sublimates her grief by returning to
her hometown of Barcelona in hopes of finding the father Esteban
never knew but longed to meet.
</P>
<P>
   In the coastal city, Manuela becomes friends with an odd
assortment: La Agrado (Antonia San Juan), a transsexual hooker and
full-time self-dramatist; Huma Rojo (Marisa Paredes), an actual
actress, in town playing Blanche DuBois in ``A Streetcar Named
Desire,'' whose on-stage majesty both belies and reflects her
hopeless infatuation with a much younger, drug-addicted actress;
and Sister Rosa (Penelope Cruz), a young nun whose kindness to
Manuela's wayward ex has left her pregnant and HIV positive.
</P>
<P>
   These women form a kind of pickup family, supporting one another
through tribulations both devastating and absurd. In the process,
they display incredible emotional resilience, although it often
takes a little subterfuge to achieve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what he says about women as actresses in life,'' says
Cruz, the stunning young actress who is rapidly becoming Spain's
hottest cinematic export since that other Almodovar discovery,
Antonio Banderas. ``Pedro is a big observer, and he figured out as
a child that his mother and the aunts in his family were ... not
liars, but they would tell little lies to avoid trouble in such a
professional way that everything would turn out OK. I think that's
very funny, because we all do it, especially women. And I think
that's when he started to love actresses.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth first worked with Almodovar in the early '80s, after her
family had fled to Spain from the military junta that had taken
over Argentina. In those days, Almodovar films such as ``Dark
Habits'' expressed the wild gusts of freedom that were blowing
through the post-Franco nation following decades of its own fascist
repression.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after working back in Argentina for many years, Roth sees a
new depth and maturity to her old friend's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I read the script, I understood Manuela deep
inside _ I smelled her,'' the petite blonde explains. ``After the
death of her son, she became a zombie, an empty vessel. But slowly,
her decision to go back through her life leads to filling herself
up again through these encounters and relationships with these
other characters. She becomes, again, a mother in different senses
with different people. At the end of this odyssey, it's all very
hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran Paredes has worked with Almodovar off and on from
the '84 ``Dark Habits'' through the more recent features ``High
Heels'' and ``Flower of My Secret.'' She's probably best-known
outside Spain these days for her role as the grandmother in Roberto
Benigni's ``Life Is Beautiful,'' but there's something about Pedro
that always draws her back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro knows well the types of relationships that form among
women, their character and complicity,'' Paredes says. ``He knows
that the feminine condition unites women. He has always observed
that women have the capacity to invent or transform reality to make
it more livable, more pleasant. This is what gives women this
innate capacity to act and perhaps comes from the fact that they've
been socially conditioned or repressed until very recently (and)
denied their physical, psychological and emotional needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of transforming ... San Juan, the popular Madrid
cabaret performer Almodovar picked to play the film's most
outrageous character, likes to keep the real nature of her own
sexual makeup enigmatic. Whatever her original gender may have
been, though, she thoroughly understands the imaginative female
survivalists Almodovar so adores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, women have spent a great deal of time alone,
talking to themselves,'' a chuckling San Juan says through a
translator, ``looking at themselves in the mirror, changing dresses
20 times, thinking alone; so they have developed this incredible
imagination. Also traditionally, men have been out on the street,
interacting and doing things, and because of that have not had a
chance to develop this kind of imagination. Women invent
constantly. They are creators, and it comes out of their solitude,
their loneliness.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the film's bent toward melodrama and artifice, Almodovar
encouraged his actresses to play even the most outlandish,
emotionally extreme incidents in a down-to-earth manner quite
different from those of the filmmaker's earlier volatile heroines.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, I was conscious that I wanted to make a
much more sober film,'' Almodovar says. ``I call this a screwball
drama, rather than a comedy; I was much more interested in keeping
things completely transparent, even if some thought that that might
appear too simple. It talks about real and basic emotions, but not
in a loud way. In fact, the actresses were sometimes worried that
they weren't doing anything, but they were much more expressive
when they were like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The actresses concur _ and admit that tamping down their
emotions wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest challenge was to be austere and modest in my
performance,'' Roth admits, ``make it so subtle yet still express
all the pain that was happening inside her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a very expressive person _ I have to get it out of
myself,'' adds Cruz, who'll next be seen opposite Matt Damon in
Billy Bob Thornton's production of ``All the Pretty Horses.'' ``But
this approach makes this movie much stronger. All of the characters
are in very extreme situations, and all of them are together, so if
it had been done in a different, less-measured way, it could've
been crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's still fairly weird. Almodovar gets a bit defensive when
asked about the trademark gender-bending and sexual provocations
that link ``Mother'' to his other films, but he admits that taking
such risks was thematically vital to the piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film is not only about the maternal instinct, it's about
the need to procreate,'' he explains. ``And that is a need that
even a transsexual can still have. I know such material is
delicate, but I think my talent is to mix it up and make it appear
natural. These characters do make up a family _ a peculiar family _
in the end, and it was very important to portray that as being as
natural as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   All of Almodovar's artistic and thematic strategies seem to have
paid off. ``Mother'' is a huge hit in Europe, a top contender for
the European Union's film awards, Spain's official Oscar entry, and
it won its maker the directing prize at last spring's Cannes Film
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, it seems to have elevated the onetime enfant
terrible of Spanish cinema to a new plateau of respect among
critics _ both the aesthetic and cultural kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm, again, hot,'' he says with a chuckle,
acknowledging that ``Women on the Verge,'' is more than a decade
old. ``But what is really good for me _ and I'm very surprised by
it _ is that everybody likes the movie. Always, in my career, there
have been people that really like my work but, also, people that
really dislike or hate it. There was always something
controversial, or a contentious situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now, I guess because people are more familiar with what I
do, people have all been surprisingly accepting. That's put me in a
situation to do whatever I want. I did that in the past, but now I
don't feel that burden when I do a new movie. I feel free, like
people are going to watch what I do without prejudice or
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 13 movies, it seems, everyone now respects my
independence.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 1503EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
