<HEADER>
A4062 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap5     11-29 1601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap5-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: DANCING IN THE DARK  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter five is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Director Bob
Farnell by phone, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Max and his friend Ralph Rizzo, a Catholic
priest, enjoy an evening in one of the wilder parts of town,
ill-prepared for an encounter with a young group of Watchers.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   In a funk, Max would yell that he ``hated nature,'' but, truth
be told, he hated technology more. Not all technology, of course.
He loved his car, a 1965 Mustang convertible. And he loved his VCR
although he never could figure out how to program it. And he loved
his little CD player, although he once told a friend that CDs made
music sound ``colder and more brittle'' than old vinyl records.
</P>
<P>
   On most days, he loved his computer and the ease of revision it
offered the writer, instead of the endless retyping he could still
feel in his fingers from the 1970s. But tonight he could not get
his printer to work.
</P>
<P>
   He retried and retried and finally hollered ``I hate
technology'' and pounded his fist on the desktop. The printer
suddenly bleeped to life _ flashing green and yellow lights and a
burble of R2D2 noises _ and printed out the day's work.
</P>
<P>
   That morning he had read yet another news article about the
millennium's most frustrating technological glitch, known to
insiders as the Y2K problem. Y2K stood for the Year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a computer,'' the story read, ``1998 is merely 98, 1999 is
just 99, and so on. The trouble will arrive when 1999 rolls over to
2000 and computers get confused about how to interpret the double
zeros. The computers may think we've flashed back to 1900.''
</P>
<P>
   Max couldn't figure out why this problem would take more than 10
minutes and 10 dollars to fix, but experts insisted it would take
billions to kill the bug.
</P>
<P>
   Without a fix, great computer networks would crash, plunging
air-traffic control, nuclear power plants, military installations,
international banking systems into chaos. Max could almost hear
computer after computer failing, clicking down, click, click,
click, like an equator of dominoes around the globe, click, click,
click, click ... click ... and then silence.
</P>
<P>
   The idea reminded Max of one of his favorite old books, ``Cat's
Cradle,'' by Kurt Vonnegut. Max remembered two details from the
story, that in a future world men and women made love through the
soles of their feet, and that the world ended when a renegade
element is loosed into the environment, turning all the world's
water to ice, slamming the future shut like a great iron door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, Max, glad I found you decent.'' It was Kate Banks, and
even her soft voice made Max jump. ``Sorry I startled you. I buzzed
in at the front. When you didn't answer, I let myself in with my
key.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been fighting with my damn printer _ I mean your damn
printer.'' He handed her a file with about 30 pages of text. Not a
bad day's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go over it on our way to dinner,'' she said. ``Let me
treat you. Do you like Italian?''
</P>
<P>
   Kate drove an old, gold Volvo sedan, vintage 1978 _ a quarter of
a million miles on her, said Kate proudly _ and Max enjoyed
watching her at the wheel. The car was in great shape, and Kate
looked wonderful driving it, wearing a pair of comfortable jeans, a
Florida State University T-shirt, white socks, and the only
extravagance, what looked like a $200 pair of running shoes.
</P>
<P>
   She snapped off the radio, which was playing classical. ``Tell
me what you've found out, Max.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well you were right about The Watchers, Kate.'' It was the
first time he had used her name in conversation and wondered
whether it marked some kind of turning point. ``They are a classic
doomsday cult. Better yet, let's use your word: They are
millenarians. They don't seem to be Christians, in the conventional
sense, but they tend to quote the Bible _ especially the
apocalyptic stuff. They are very specific about the date Jan. 1,
2000. They associate it with something big, but it's not clear
what. The end of the world? A new world order? The Buccaneers win a
Super Bowl? Lions lying down with lambs? Lambs eating the lions?
What I can't tell you yet is how dark this thing is, or whether
they pose a risk to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What about members?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of their pamphlets make one of those unprovable claims _
more than a million members worldwide. We'll know a little more in
the fall. They're planning a huge convention _ at the Star Dome if
you can believe that. But I don't think there are more than a
thousand in the area, and most of them live in Gulfport. They
actually own the Conquistador Hotel on Cosmos Key.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A group of corporations is listed as the owner, but they all
trace back to Raoul Glaber, their leader. He's the one who scares
me. By all accounts he has this mesmerizing effect on people _
especially the young. The Watchers come in all ages, color and
sizes, but his recruiting efforts seem targeted toward the
alienated young, the kids we ran into _ or who ran into us _ in
Ybor City last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Kate nodded as they pulled into the parking lot of a restaurant
called Meat Balls. The place was owned by three Italian brothers
from the Bronx. In one room, which had about 12 tables, they served
the best Italian food Max had ever eaten _ a veal cacciatore,
tender beyond imagination, like butter. Max closed his eyes with
pleasure. Kate devoured the linguine with red clam sauce, and they
split a bottle of cheap Chianti.
</P>
<P>
   There were three large rooms in the back. One had a bowling
alley with only two lanes. You could use it at no charge, but you
had to replace the fallen pins by hand, like the old days. An
adjacent room had four pool tables, and Max and Kate shot two games
of eight ball.
</P>
<P>
   Max was winning the first, but scratched on the eight ball. Kate
won the next game in a rout. She was full of surprises, Max
thought, as he watched her lean over the table to kiss the winning
ball in the side pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you think they call me Kate Banks?'' she said, laughing
at her own pun.
</P>
<P>
   The final room was a lounge with an old juke box and a tiny
dance floor. If you wanted to dance, you had to take off your shoes
to protect the shiny old wooden floor. Max couldn't believe how
relaxed he was feeling, or the renewal of his good spirits at a
time he assumed his life and work would be in continuous decline.
</P>
<P>
   They shared more wine and conversation, until Kate reached under
the table, undid the laces of her shoes and kicked his shin with a
stockinged foot. ``You up to a dance, Max?''
</P>
<P>
   He loved music, but not what was playing, some corny old disco
number by the Bee Gees. He had told himself, over the years, that
more than nature and technology, he hated disco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not much of a dancer,'' he said, ``especially after a long
day of writing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Suit yourself,'' she said with a smile, and scooted off to the
lady's room. Max suddenly felt oafish and over-the-hill, and walked
dejectedly over to the juke box, staring into its yellow light,
glancing for several minutes at the selections. One caught his eye,
an old favorite. The Stones had done the most famous version, but
the original was recorded by the great Stax-Volt artist, Irma
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   He felt a hand on his shoulder. ``See one you like?'' It was
Kate, and her touch was like a jolt. He popped the number K-24.
``Ti-i-ime is on my side, yes it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Irma sounded like she was singing with a thousand-voice choir,
and Max felt like a parishioner in the Church of Soul. ``You'll
come runnin' back ... you'll come runnin' back, to me-e-e.''
</P>
<P>
   Max turned and Kate's hand slid across his shoulders. He glided
one arm around her waist, and the other down her arm to her hand.
They locked fingers. Her cheek touched his, and he inhaled some
delicate flowery fragrance behind her ear. Max slipped off his
loafers and kicked them free. She put her feet softly on his. They
rocked gently back and forth in the light of the juke box like two
teen-agers transported back to the past, with a thousand years of
time ahead of them.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: LIGHTNING STRIKES AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
