<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap6-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: LIGHTNING STRIKES AGAIN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter six is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Director Bob
Farnell by phone, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Max ponders the Y2K computer bug before a
rendezvous with his editor Kate, an evening that turns to romance.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Max Timlin was known as a fearless journalist, but, truth be
told, he was afraid of two things: lightning and high places. He
traced these phobias to a single event in his childhood, when a
baby sitter dragged him onto a roller coaster at the Georgia State
Fair. He could not have been more than 5 years old. He was so
terrified he could neither close his eyes nor scream. A bolt of
lightning crashed out of a dark blue sky. He wet his pants. And
that was that.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, he lived in the lightning capital of the world.
Three golfers were already dead this summer, the result of ignoring
the warning signs or trying to seek shelter under a tree.
</P>
<P>
   What a way to go, he thought, imagining some poor duffer raising
his sand wedge above his head, only to be zapped in midswing.
</P>
<P>
   He had read that a lightning strike could heat the surrounding
air to a temperature hotter than the sun. And this, it seems, had
been a record year for strikes, many of which had ignited forest
fires around the state.
</P>
<P>
   For two years, the El Nino water currents in the Pacific were
being blamed for disaster after disaster. Tornadoes. Floods.
Droughts. Fires. Hurricanes. If one were looking to the skies for
signs of the last days, you didn't have to look too long or too
hard.
</P>
<P>
   But Max had more immediate concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you think we should go in, Kate?'' He turned a weather
ear to some distant rumblings over the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a while longer, Max. This breeze is so beautiful. And
look, there's a rainbow.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, to the southwest, a glorious rainbow arced from
Tampa Bay into the Gulf of Mexico, right over the Skyway Bridge. A
bridge over the bridge. But across the sky, blue-black clouds
gathered and billowed cinematically, illuminated from the inside by
lightning.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Mississippi ... two Mississippi.'' He counted to six. A
faint rumble. They were still safe, he thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max, will you answer me please?'' She reached up and punched
him on the arm.
</P>
<P>
   He now had proof that Kate was one hell of a journalist. Either
that, or she really was interested in him personally, and, in spite
of last night's slow dance, he found that hard to believe.
</P>
<P>
   They had been walking along the beach for more than an hour now,
and she had asked him only a dozen questions. In return, he had
revealed to her all his secrets, including that he was petrified by
lightning.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he had been born in Atlanta, to a Catholic mother and a
Jewish father. That made him something of an outsider in a land
full of Protestants. He attended a small parochial school, St.
John's Elementary; a public high school in Buckhead; and got into
Emory on an academic scholarship, but left after a year.
</P>
<P>
   He hustled a job at a community weekly paper, the Auburn Caller,
covering high school sports. The decision broke his mother's heart
_ she thought of her only son as a doctor, or lawyer, or maybe even
a priest. His father, a criminal defense attorney, thought writing
would suit Max just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Max himself considered becoming a lawyer, mostly because his
favorite television show was ``Perry Mason.'' He imagined himself
the center of some dramatic courtroom scene, getting an arrogant
witness to admit that, yes, yes, he was the one who had committed
the murder, and that the beautiful, shapely blonde was _ in a
manner of speaking _ innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I visited my Dad's courtroom. I was about 12, and
realized that all that Raymond Burr stuff was just a crock. That
most trials were really boring. Then it occurred to me that what
had fascinated me was not the law, but the stories, the
characters.''
</P>
<P>
   The breeze picked up and the sky lit up. ``One Mississippi, two
...'' This time the thunder rolled in at four. ``Let's go in,
Kate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not until you tell me about your marriages.'' Not a topic he
usually talked about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The short version is that I married and divorced twice. And
you'll find this interesting. Both times my wife ran off with the
same guy.'' More thunder. Kate looked at him in disbelief, and
tried to suppress a little laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's true. His name is Lionel Cropper, but, of course, I
call him Crapper. He was my best friend _ once _ an editor who gave
me great assignments, but while I was all over the country, he was
all over my first wife, Helen. She died in a car crash. He was
driving.''
</P>
<P>
   Kate reached over and squeezed his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the rebound, I fell in love with a young reporter, Jamie
Nelson, a beautiful, talented kid who I think was infatuated with
what she perceived to be a big-time reporter. We were married less
than a year, before Crapper managed to get her assigned to his
desk. As far as I know, they're still together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you thought of putting a hit out on this guy?'' A flash
of lightning. Louder thunder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come to think that maybe it's all been for the best, that
I'm not cut out to be with somebody _ not in marriage anyway. At
least we were smart enough not to have any kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you regret that, Max? About the children, I mean.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to being alone, finally. My mom's still alive and
well _ I've got few friends _ but good ones. I love dogs. Wish I
had one. But sometimes I wonder about being the end of the line,
the last of the Mohicans.'' He looked at the sky. ``What about you,
Kate?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good marriage. Jonathan died 10 years ago. Lung
cancer. He was a terrible smoker. But those fierce blue eyes made
up for it. We made a baby, little Cassandra Banks. A wild child. A
great athlete, soccer and volleyball. She's off on her own. I don't
see her very often. I miss her.''
</P>
<P>
   Kate began to cry. It took Max by surprise, until he realized
that his eyes were burning with tears too, not from crying, but
from the salty wind off the Gulf that was now whipping into a
mini-gale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you ever think about dying, Max?''
</P>
<P>
   He had to speak louder now over the sound of the wind. ``Not
every day, if I can help it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean do you think that when you die, it's, it's _ all over _
like the way it was before you were born _ or is there something
waiting for us?'' Flash. One Mississippi. Crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is crazy, Kate. I'm shaking. Please let's go in. At least
to the car.'' She threw herself on him and kissed him hard. He
caught her. And held her perfectly still, and sustained her weight,
and let her kiss him until she was through. One Mississippi ...
two... he counted to 10.
</P>
<P>
   Zzzzznnappp! A lightning bolt snapped so close, there was no
time to count. So loud it knocked them both to the sand. He could
smell it.
</P>
<P>
   He gathered her to her feet and raced toward the top of the
beach, it was raining hard suddenly, huge drops driven by the wind
into full sheets of water. He opened the door of the Mustang and
hustled her into the back seat and climbed in after her. The rain
drove down even harder, what he once called ``tarantula rains,''
his childhood mistake for ``torrential.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No more existential questions, Kate.'' Max tried to catch his
breath. ``You've brought down the wrath of the gods on us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry, Max, but I miss Cassandra.'' She buried her head in
her hands as Max put his arm around her shoulder. ``I miss my
daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: BAD MOON RISING
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
