<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4064 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap7     11-29 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap7-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: BAD MOON RISING  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter seven is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Director Bob
Farnell by phone, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Max reveals his fear of lightning, which does
not deter Kate from leading him on a walk through a storm. She
reveals to him her concerns about her daughter. Max ponders the Y2K
computer bug before a rendezvous.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Kate had assigned Max two helpers from the newspaper, the only
other people who knew he was on the trail of The Watchers.
</P>
<P>
   Violet Rose was a crack researcher with an uncanny technical
instinct. She was in her mid-30s, tall, elegant and slightly
exotic, looking a little like NBC anchor Ann Curry. Violet was born
in Singapore, her father a British journalist, her mother a Chinese
translator.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Darling _ she received a lot of kidding after Bruce
Springsteen wrote a song with that title _ had been snapping photos
since she was a little girl in Cuba. She had a reputation as
inventive, independent, relentless and courageous, all the traits
Max appreciated in a photojournalist. Sherry was a short woman with
a delicate face and a surprisingly muscular body.
</P>
<P>
   Max knew her work and admired it. Sherry was a Pulitzer finalist
for her photographs of the 1980 Skyway Bridge disaster. A huge
tanker had hit the bridge in a fierce storm. At the exact moment
the storm cleared, Sherry was leaning out of a helicopter,
capturing startling images of the destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Folks in town still talk about her picture of the yellow Buick
Skylark, stopped dead on a span of ragged metal, dangling 175 feet
above Tampa Bay. The driver escaped, but had to be restrained from
returning to the car to rescue his golf clubs from the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tee time is in three hours!'' he exclaimed, turning him into a
folk hero for a battalion of men wearing shiny white shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Max knew the Skyway disaster story well. He had written a
profile of the only man to fall from the bridge and survive. He was
Elmo Polonski, a man in his 50s, who had been driving south in a
pickup truck, on his way to work, when the oil tanker crashed into
the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Driver and truck soared through the air, heading down, down, the
ship getting closer and closer. His instinct was to hit the brakes.
The wheels of the truck hit the bow of the tanker and bounced off
into a choppy Gulf of Mexico. The truck submerged and the driver
escaped the cab, dazed and battered, but with just enough energy to
reach up and hook his arm over a rung of a rope ladder that had
been lowered to him. He blacked out and came to on the deck of the
ship, surrounded by strangers speaking Korean.
</P>
<P>
   Max remembered his lead for the story: ``Something interesting
happened to Elmo Polonski Friday on his way to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Given their shared history as chroniclers of the Skyway
disaster, Max was delighted to hook up with Sherry and her
colleague Violet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been all over the Internet,'' said Violet, ``and the
feeling I get is an increase in activities about The Watchers. More
Web sites, more conversation in New Age chat rooms, and Kate is
right _ much of the buzz centers on West Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Violet tapped out a few commands on her laptop.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're planning a big convention _ you know about that, Max _
but they're talking like it's a Stones concert or something _ 30
maybe 40 thousand. They've booked the Star Dome. And they're making
a big deal that this is for `initiates' only.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Initiates? I haven't come across that word with them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like it sounds. Someone who has passed through an
initiation _ or joined the club _ or learned the secret handshake
or something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've checked all the photo files,'' said Sherry. ``Not much on
The Watchers _ a few photos of the leader _ but I went out and shot
some scenes around their headquarters at the Conquistador Hotel.
Take a look at these. The hotel is pink, but I might as well have
shot them in black and white.''
</P>
<P>
   The images were of young people, from late teens into their
early 30s. They were entering the hotel or standing in small groups
in courtyards, or walking along the beach. What was remarkable was
that most were dressed in black, but some in white. The contrast
was startling in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   The black tribe tended to be younger, like the kids he had seen
in Ybor City. The picture showed bald heads or spiky hair in weird
colors, tattoos, body piercing, lots of leather, even in the
Florida sun. If they were from the dungeons of Uranus, their
counterparts came from a yacht club on Neptune, neat white sports
clothes and shiny white running shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The women wore white barrettes, or scarves, or headbands, the
men white sports caps with familiar logos. Their hair was short and
neatly groomed, their postures like models in a Spiegel catalogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``My theory,'' said Sherry, ``is that we're seeing the before
and after effects of initiation.'' She explained that she dressed
like a tourist, took shots from a safe distance with a big lens,
pointing mostly at the water and sailboats.
</P>
<P>
   It was Violet's turn again. ``The Watchers draw from an odd mix
of mythologies and liturgies, on a spectrum from medieval
Catholicism to New Age Druids. I found out that initiation rites
are conducted _ all over the world _ on the eve of a full moon, and
always near the confluence of two bodies of water.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When is the next full moon?'' asked Max.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three nights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So Thursday is the eve?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The odd thing is that these are public events. They are not
clandestine. They're even advertised in the alternative weekly.
Check this out.''
</P>
<P>
   Violet had clipped a small ad from the back page of Fishwrap, a
free and funky paper popular, because of the music news, with young
people.
</P>
<P>
   Are you watching?
</P>
<P>
   Tired of watching alone?
</P>
<P>
   Then come watch with us.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   South end of Cosmos Key.
</P>
<P>
   Dress in black.
</P>
<P>
   Max knew that location well. The south end of Cosmos Key is the
closest point of land to the center of the Skyway Bridge, the exact
point where the Gulf of Mexico flows into Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that you'd look mighty fine in black, Sherry,
darlin'.'' She played along. ``Only way for you to find out, Boss,
is to rent a tux and take me to the dance.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: THE POWER OF ANGELS
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
