<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4065 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap8     11-29 1754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap8-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: THE POWER OF ANGELS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter eight is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Director Bob
Farnell by phone, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   THE STORY SO FAR: Reporter Max Timlin, out of a job and down on
his luck, is hired by editor Kate Banks to conduct a secret
investigation of a doomsday cult called The Watchers. Max begins
his research, focusing on the cult leader Raoul Glaber, a
charismatic man with a troubling message, who seems to be targeting
the young for recruitment. Max and a Catholic priest, Ralph Rizzo,
encounter a group of young Watchers in one of the wilder parts of
town. Kate begins to take a romantic interest in Max, much to his
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Max and Sherry arrived for The Watcher initiation ceremony
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll pretend to be this biker couple hangin' with the punky
kids.'' It was Sherry's idea. She owned a Harley, and brought over
some biker gear for Max to wear: black jeans, a black and gold
Harley T-shirt, and a black helmet with a swirling snake design on
the sides. Sherry wore tight black shorts over a black bathing suit
and looked ``damn good,'' Max told her.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Max had never been on a motorcycle before, so he
was stuck riding behind Sherry, and though he enjoyed holding on to
her, he was glad they were riding at night so no one could get a
good look at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like Pee-wee Herman,'' he conceded.
</P>
<P>
   As they approached the south end of Cosmos Key, Sherry slowed
down so the roar of the bike would not attract too much attention,
and then parked it near a palm tree at the north edge of the park.
</P>
<P>
   From a distance, they could see that a crowd, maybe 200 to 300
people, had gathered. Most looked young and were dressed in black,
although they were mixed with a few onlookers dressed like tourists
attending a bonfire on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Someone had lit a fire, which was illegal, although there was no
sign of the police. In general, Max hated beach cops. He'd received
too many petty parking tickets over the years, but, as Max and
Sherry walked hand in hand toward the site, not knowing what would
happen, he wished for some token of security.
</P>
<P>
   It was about an hour before midnight, a calm and cloudless
night. An almost round moon _ it would be full tomorrow _ had made
</P>
<P>
   its climb into the sky, turning colors from orange, to yellow,
to ivory. It was now positioned just to the southeast of the Skyway
Bridge. It made a nice photograph.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry had rigged a small backpack with a hidden camera. She had
used the device before, usually chasing down corrupt politicians or
scam artists or gangsters. Her most famous ``gotcha'' photo was of
a well-known televangelist soliciting a teen-age prostitute. Sherry
and a policewoman, dressed like hookers, stood on a corner across
the street and caught the rat in the trap.
</P>
<P>
   So as Max and Sherry walked through the crowd, which continued
to grow, Sherry silently snapped dozens of images.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, old biker man, can I score a smoke?''
</P>
<P>
   Max was startled by the approach of a tall, thin kid dressed
only in a pair of black Speedos and black flip-flops. His head was
shaved, but, more startling, he was completely hairless, even on
his arms and legs, and didn't appear to have any eyebrows or
eyelashes.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry pulled a pack of Camels from the front of her backpack
and handed him a cigarette and a light.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to your hair, man?'' she asked. ``You look like
an Olympic swimmer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaved it all off, biker lady. Getting ready for my
initiation.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, he ran back toward a circle of friends and sat on the
edge of the beach looking out at the moon and the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   It was now about 10 minutes before midnight and the crowd had
grown to about 500 and pressed toward the water. A few boom boxes
had been playing the same strange metallic vibrations Max had heard
in Ybor City, but they were silent now, and the crowd calmed down,
and there was almost no noise, except for the sound of surf and the
croaking of sea birds, until the young man with no hair yelled,
``Watch! Over there!'' and pointed a long arm and skinny finger
toward the middle of the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   A sleek, white vessel sliced through the sea, the boat and its
wake brilliant in the moonlight. As it came closer, its huge
engines roaring, Max recognized it as something called a
``cigarette'' boat. Fast and powerful, it was favored by drug
runners in the tropics. This one was big, a 40- or 50-footer.
</P>
<P>
   The boat ate up the distance between the bridge and shore, its
engines now in a deafening roar, and Max could make out its full
size and elegance. He counted 12 figures on deck. Eleven men,
dressed in white, and what looked like a woman in a black, hooded
robe. Sherry had moved away from Max to a location where she could
snap away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome you all to the initiation rite of The Watchers,
here on the eve of the full moon, at the confluence of two great
bodies of water.''
</P>
<P>
   The boat was wired for sound, although no speakers or
microphones were visible. The young man who issued the greeting
must have been wearing a wireless mike. He was not Raoul Glaber,
but a much younger man with hair so blond it looked almost white.
</P>
<P>
   The other men on deck looked equally young, blond and very
athletic, like TV infomercial models for exercise machines. ``Will
the candidates for initiation please come forward.''
</P>
<P>
   At various points, the crowd parted to let through several
aspiring Watchers. Max counted 24 in all, 12 men and 12 women. He
estimated that they were in their late teens to early 30s. They
formed an awkward line at the shore where sea foam washed against
their feet.
</P>
<P>
   The men on board, except the speaker, climbed down from the
anchored boat into the water, which was up to their chests, and
walked forward to meet them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stand before this bridge, an image of the world's
transformation. We watch for signs of the last days, and for that
day to come _ it is just before us _ when all that once was will
disappear, and time, newly born, will begin again.''
</P>
<P>
   He gestured toward the initiates. ``But first you must strip
yourself of the vestiges of the old, dark times.'' As if on cue,
the initiates began to remove their jewelry, most of it silver. One
man unpeeled several chains from around his neck. A girl took off
rings from each finger.
</P>
<P>
   The tall hairless kid removed earrings. One young woman, with
barbed wire tattoos on both arms, removed clips from her nose, ears
and an eyebrow. They dumped the jewelry into bags carried by the
men in white.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next startled Max, and by the buzz in the crowd,
several other onlookers. The initiates began to remove their
clothing. Off came bathing suits, and T-shirts, and caps, and black
jackets, and flip-flops, and even a pair of Doc Martens, until two
dozen figures stood in the moonlight, tall and short, doughy and
angular _ and completely naked. Sherry noticed that three of them
had the letter W tattooed on their snowy butts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a glorious new beginning, for once you wore black,
when your hearts and minds were dark, but now, washed in this
water, you will wear white.''
</P>
<P>
   What followed was a roll call: ``James Weeks, Sasha Britton,
Bethany Davis ...''
</P>
<P>
   Each initiate was escorted by a Watcher out toward the boat,
leaned backwards like a dancer being dipped, and submerged in the
waters of the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martha Kronauer, Russell Major, David Poynter ...''
</P>
<P>
   It reminded Max of the old-timey baptisms he remembered from the
evangelical South _ except for the nudity, which made this ceremony
look like a scene in a Salvador Dali painting.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the initiates were ushered back to the shoreline,
where they donned gleaming white robes.
</P>
<P>
   ``From this day forward, you will wear white,'' declared the
young man, ``until the day comes, and it will come soon _ watch for
it _ when we all will be clad in red _ the color of fire, the color
of Raoul.''
</P>
<P>
   A cheer went up from the crowd, which evolved into a chant,
something you might hear at a political rally or a soccer game.
``Ra-oul ... Ra-oul ... Ra-oul.''
</P>
<P>
   It lasted for more than a minute, followed by another cheer, as
emerging from a cabin in the center of the boat, dressed in a dark
red running suit, emerged a man with dark hair and skin so pale it
looked ghostly in the moonlight. He stood behind the woman on the
deck, reached around her shoulders, and removed her hooded robe.
</P>
<P>
   Max was startled by the action and the cheer that went up from
the crowd, for there before him stood the most beautiful woman he
had ever seen, wearing nothing but long chestnut hair that cascaded
across her shoulders. He found himself embarrassed by this intimate
vision of her and lowered his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That girl's name is Angela Powers.'' Sherry was back now,
whispering in his ear.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd began chanting her name: ``An-gel-a. ... An-gel-a
...'' until the man beside her raised his hands, silenced the
crowd, and began to speak.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: WASHED IN BLOOD, HEALED BY FIRE
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
