<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGER-SHANIA-TWAIN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHANIA TWAIN, GETTING COMFORTABLE AT THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of singer Shania Twain.) 
 By MARGY HOLLAND  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    There's hot, there's really hot and then there's Shania Twain.
 &HT;    The Canadian-born singer is closing out the millennium as one of
the most successful singers in the world. Her record-setting sales
and numerous accolades and industry awards have put her in a league
of her own: Sales of her most recent album, ``Come On Over''
(Universal-Polygram, 1997) have reached a staggering 13 million,
leaving her second only to pop/rock singer Alanis Morissette in
album sales by a female.
 &HT;    More recently, Twain received the prestigious Entertainer of the
Year award from the Country Music Association, the first time she's
received that honor.
 &HT;    So what does a 34-year-old who's risen from grinding poverty to
the pinnacle of success do when she's named Entertainer of the
Year?
 &HT;    Twain celebrated after the show by routing her limousine driver
through the Krispy Kreme drive-through window for ``one of those
great donuts they brought to us every day when we were recording
`Come On Over.'''
 &HT;    If that sounds like someone not exactly caught up in the awards
game, it should. Twain's CMA award now sits in her stable,
alongside her Grammies, gold and platinum records and untold
numbers of other honors.
 &HT;    ``I'm as excited as anyone when I get up there and win,'' she
says, ``but, to be honest with you, I don't sit there waiting. I
learned a long time ago that you just end up being very
disappointed. I think it can make you very bitter if you put too
much weight on that.
 &HT;    ``I don't want to be bitter,'' the singer says. ``I don't even
want to compete on that level, so I take it very lightly,
actually.''
 &HT;    Twain wrapped up her first world tour this past summer,
performing before sold-out crowds of as many as 30,000 _ which, she
says, means a lot more than any award.
 &HT;    ``When I went out there, I didn't feel like I needed to prove
anything to anyone,'' Twain says. ``I understood that most people
didn't know my background. They had never really seen much of me
live.
 &HT;    ``Before I got my record deal, my livelihood was singing live,''
she adds. ``That's what I did. I am no different on my stage than I
was in any club. Throughout my childhood and all of my teens, it
was just me and a bar.
 &HT;    ``It was mostly rock music,'' Twain recalls, ``which requires a
lot of energy. Rock is the hardest thing to sing night after night,
six nights a week, with a matinee, and you're traveling in a very
dumpy truck and terrible hotels and it's awful.''
 &HT;    She shrugs, then smiles.
 &HT;    ``I've done all that,'' she says, ``so going into this situation
on the road was like a luxury, it was like floating on a cloud.
I've got this amazing bus, I've got my dog with me, I've got my
horse, I've got all sorts of wonderful people around me that I've
hand-chosen, so I know I like them. I'm making a great living, and
I don't even sing every night of the week _ I'm singing sometimes
two or three shows in a row at the most.
 &HT;    ``What an easy gig!
 &HT;    ``It was like nothing compared to what I was used to,'' she says
cheerfully, ``so if you come from that background and it was your
living, this kind of touring is pretty darn easy and fun.''
 &HT;    While Twain's life has certainly changed since her childhood in
Timmins, Ont., she says that she resists the star treatment and
does her best to live a normal life.
 &HT;    ``Everyone loves attention,'' she says. ``We love the attention
when it's complimentary and we hate the attention when it sucks, so
we're all the same. I'm no different than anyone else _ but, as far
as the actual fame goes, I really don't like being treated like a
star.
 &HT;    ``I like to be just a normal, everyday person,'' Twain adds. ``I
get away with a lot. I decided in the last year, especially on the
tour, because I really felt like I was living even more in a bubble
than I had ever before, I decided to start going for walks by
myself and not taking security, and I decided to start doing things
like other people do and like I used to do.
 &HT;    ``If you dress down and you just act like a normal person and
you don't act like a star,'' she says, ``then people don't notice
you as much, and I enjoy that the most.''
 &HT;    Twain admits that there are some benefits to star power _
especially when, as with all celebrities, she gets those special
requests to meet with terminally ill people, especially children.
 &HT;    ``The beauty about being able to reach people or to help people
when they're sick and dying is that you can almost only do that as
a celebrity,'' Twain says. ``It means so much to them. It's almost
like if you can use your celebrity in those ways and no other way,
than you've got a good balance.''
 &HT;    Helping that balance, she adds, is the support of her family,
even though her two brothers and two sisters remain in Canada,
thousands of miles away from her new home in Switzerland.
 &HT;    ``I depend on my family a lot,'' Twain says. ``I need to stay
grounded, in the sense that I like to remember where I'm from. I
get lonely like everybody gets lonely. I get lonely for smelling
firewood in the air, the sound of a loon and snowmobiling with my
nephews. I get lonely for those sorts of things, and I don't get
home often enough, so I bring my family to me.
 &HT;    ``They're experimenting with new things because of it,'' she
says, ``so it's kind of neat what's happening to us as a family. We
depend a lot on each other, more and more all the time.''
 &HT;    Twain plans to fly her family to Switzerland for the Christmas
holidays. In the meantime, having completed her CBS Thanksgiving
Night special, she is working on a Christmas album for 2000, as
well as a new country album which may be released as early as next
year.
 &HT;    Her schedule seems as demanding as ever, but the singer insists
that things are different now.
 &HT;    ``I started enjoying the ride, at least in the last year,'' she
says. ``The tour has been a great release for me, because I've been
able to get out on the stage and sweat it out, be with the fans,
feel that encouragement and get a lot of my confidence back. I
think I lost that for a while _ feeling the pressure of being a
celebrity, feeling like I had to live up to certain things.
 &HT;    ``It's all a part of it,'' she says. ``Realizing that you're
really not that great _ I mean, there's always someone who's better
than you in every way, and sometimes that's a hard pill to swallow
when you're a perfectionist and you're really trying to be great.
You're trying to be the best, and you have to accept that you're
just not always the best.
 &HT;    ``You have to come to terms with that and get comfortable with
yourself,'' the singer says. ``I'm finally getting there.''
 c.1999 Margy Holland  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Margy Holland is a Nashville-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Come On Over,'' consult the
Universal Music Website at www.umusic.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
