<HEADER>
A4080 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-TOM-HANKS-IN-THE-GREE     11-29 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOM-HANKS-IN-THE-GREEN-MILE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOM HANKS WALKS `THE GREEN MILE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Tom Hanks in a scene from ``The Green
Mile.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It was late in another long, grueling day on the gloomy,
depressing set of ``The Green Mile,'' but Tom Hanks was finished
for the day, free to go.
 &HT;    So co-star Michael Clarke Duncan was all the more surprised to
find Hanks, two hours later, still on the set in full prison-guard
costume, watching actor Jeffrey DeMunn filming a scene.
 &HT;    ``I went to him and said, `Man, why are you here? If I'd wrapped
two hours ago, I'd be in my truck and gone,''' Duncan recalls. ``He
said, `Jeffrey DeMunn has to give me a look over here.'''
 &HT;    Duncan shakes his head in wonderment.
 &HT;    ``They could've gotten a production assistant to sit there,'' he
says. ``Tom said, `If Jeffrey looks and sees my face, his reaction
may be that much different or better than if he looked at a
stranger. That's why I'm here _ I want this movie to be good, so I
have to make a sacrifice.'
 &HT;    ``After that I had a new outlook,'' Duncan says. ``It's not just
about your scenes, your closeups _ it's about the whole team
effort. When I saw Tom do that, I knew this guy was one of the
greatest actors I've ever worked with.''
 &HT;    When Duncan's story comes up later during an interview at the
Park Hyatt in Century City, Calif., Hanks reacts with a faint air
of embarrassment. If he taught Duncan anything from the experience,
he says, he is glad to have been able to pass along a lesson taught
him by Oscar-winner Sally Field, his co-star in ``Punchline''
(1988).
 &HT;    ``I was shooting a scene where I was on the phone and I was
supposed to be speaking to Sally, who wasn't even working that
day,'' he recalls. ``I picked up, and she was on the other end.
 &HT;    ``I said, `Sally, where are you?''' Hanks says. ``She was in a
little room on the other side of the sound stage. I said, `What are
you doing here?' She said, `We have a scene together.' I said, `But
you're on the phone!'''
 &HT;    Hanks smiles softly at the memory.
 &HT;    ``You learn that kind of thing,'' he says. ``At a time when
you're allowed to be as cranky and lazy (as you want), when the
structure is in place to let you be the biggest a--hole you
possibly want to be, it's important that you still live up to your
responsibilities as a professional.
 &HT;    ``I don't know how to explain it,'' he says, scratching at the
beard he's grown for an upcoming role. ``This is what I do, and I
take great pride in what I do. By and large, I try to live up to
the faith everybody puts in me when they pay me the money.''
 &HT;    Given that Hanks banks $20 million a movie, there's a lot more
than faith at stake. Fortunately for all concerned, however, the
actor continues to churn out hits, from ``Sleepless in Seattle''
(1993), ``Philadelphia'' (1993) and ``Forrest Gump'' (1994) through
``Saving Private Ryan'' (1998) and ``You've Got Mail'' (1998).
 &HT;    ``The Green Mile,'' based on Stephen King's novel and set to
open nationwide on Dec. 10, casts him as the head guard on death
row at Cold Mountain Penitentiary in 1935. The film pivots on his
relationship with a hulking black prisoner (Duncan) who seems to
possess a miraculous supernatural power.
 &HT;    It's a strange story, by turns uplifting and heart-rending,
which Hanks says is exactly what he likes about it.
 &HT;    ``All true myths or folk tales, in their original form,
illuminate the paradox of what it is to be alive,'' Hanks says.
``Instead of there being a happy ending where everybody who's
innocent is rewarded and everybody who's bad is punished, for every
blessing there is a curse and for every triumph there is a tragedy.
 &HT;    ``That, to me, is the great road human beings walk every day,''
the actor says. ``We're trying to solve the mysteries of why that's
the case, and there is no solution.
 &HT;    ``That's why the movie is more oddly attractive to a big
audience than you'd think,'' he adds. ``You'd never think you'd
come out feeling somehow good or cathartic or, `Oh my God, I sure
am glad I spent those three hours on death row with those guys.'
 &HT;    ``But I think you do after this movie.''
 &HT;    Several scenes were filmed at the shuttered Tennessee State
Penitentiary, and Hanks took the opportunity to tour the prison's
old death-row building. The facility's electric chair had long
since been removed, but Hanks found the death chamber evocative
nonetheless.
 &HT;    ``The real prison was empty, but there were vibes,'' he recalls.
``It's not hard to go in and think, `Oh my God, could you imagine
coming here day in and day out?'
 &HT;    ``And the real death row was a creepy, creepy place.''
 &HT;    Creepy as it was, visiting death row _ and, for that matter, the
entire experience of making ``Green Mile'' _ didn't alter Hanks'
support of capital punishment.
 &HT;    ``It didn't change it at all,'' he says. ``I don't think the
film could possibly change anybody's idea of what they think _
you're either in favor of it or you're not. You either think it's
something important or you don't. You either think it's an
abomination or it's justice.
 &HT;    ``I'll tell you what I think,'' he says thoughtfully. ``There
are plenty of people who should be put to death for their crimes,
and there are probably people who shouldn't be put to death for
their crimes. On a case-by-case basis, I think there's a lot of
room for gray area.
 &HT;    ``I think some people are born bad and some are made bad,'' he
concludes. ``I don't believe in absolutes. I don't necessarily
believe people are born good or that they can be made good.
 &HT;    ``There are 4 billion people in the world, and 4 billion
variations on the theme.''
 &HT;    Death row is a long way from Hanks' days on the television
sitcom ``Bosom Buddies'' and his earliest big-screen success in
such goofy-guy epics as ``Splash'' (1984) and ``Bachelor Party''
(1984). He's a major star now, with formidable clout in Hollywood
and a worldwide fan base.
 &HT;    Every once in a while, however, Hanks is sitting in the living
room of the house he shares with his wife, actress Rita Wilson, and
their children. And onto the television screen flickers, say, an
old episode of ``Bosom Buddies'' or a scene from ``Bachelor
Party.''
 &HT;    ``I think, `Where did that enthusiastic young man go?''' the
43-year-old Hanks says, laughing. ``I change the channel.''
 &HT;    Well, maybe not every time, he admits.
 &HT;    ``The types of films I made early, I was thrilled to have
done,'' he says. ``I have a tendency to denigrate all the movies
I've made. That's a bad thing _ `Oh, it's some sad little movie
about a house.'
 &HT;    ``But, in fact, what I was learning at the time was really
important,'' Hanks says. ``Part of it was that those were the
opportunities I had then. The only thing I was somewhat cognizant
of was that I was trying to expand my horizons as an artist within
the confines of the options afforded me.
 &HT;    ``I think I was able to do that,'' he concludes, ``but the
nature of what fascinated me, the themes I thought I could bring
something to when I was 27 or 32, were very different from what
they are now.
 &HT;    ``But I look at the older movies and think, `Hmm, not a bad
job.'''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Green Mile,'' consult the
official Website at www.thegreenmile.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
