<HEADER>
A4082 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-MICHAEL-CAINE-IN-THE-     11-29 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHAEL-CAINE-IN-THE-CIDER-HOUSE-RULES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL CAINE, AMERICAN-STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Michael Caine with Tobey Maguire in a
scene from ``The Cider House Rules.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``I was never sexually abused,'' Michael Caine says, ``but I
look at adults in a different way than most people do.''
 &HT;    The 66-year-old actor is finally able to talk about his own
difficult childhood during World War II, thanks to his latest film,
``The Cider House Rules.''
 &HT;    Opening on Dec. 17, the film casts him as a saintly doctor
running an orphanage _ which sparked memories of his own childhood.
 &HT;    ``I was 6 years old when England was being bombed,'' Caine
recalls. ``The government evacuated the children and paid complete
monsters to take little ones in.
 &HT;    ``This woman took in me and a 4-year-old named Clarence. She
would go away and lock us in a cupboard under the stairs for three
or four days at a time. We never came out _ we just sat there in
the dark, which is where I picked up a lifelong battle with
claustrophobia.
 &HT;    ``I had it easier,'' he adds. ``She didn't break any of my
bones. She broke Clarence's foot with a tennis racket. She was a
real bastard _ she hit him because he went to the bathroom under
the stairs.
 &HT;    ``But we had been there for four days.''
 &HT;    These painful memories informed his role in ``The Cider House
Rules,'' as a doctor who ministers to orphans while also performing
abortions on the side, to keep unwanted kids from being brought
into the world.
 &HT;    ``I know it's just a role,'' Caine says over breakfast at New
York's Essex House hotel, ``but I wanted each child in this fantasy
orphanage to see me as someone who would love and protect them.''
 &HT;    Advance word has sparked talk of a second Best Supporting Actor
Oscar, but Caine doesn't want to hear about it.
 &HT;    ``Oh, please, don't mention it,'' he says hastily. ``Actors are
very superstitious people. We don't like to talk about things like
awards _ it's like what my mother used to call, `Put some mockers
on it.'''
 &HT;    At first, he recalls, Caine had his doubts about a movie version
of John Irving's best-selling novel.
 &HT;    ``I knew right away when I read it that I wanted to do it,'' he
says. ``But I had to question if anyone would want to see this
movie about an abortion doctor.
 &HT;    ``I also had to get over the title,'' he adds. ``When I first
read it, I thought, `What the hell does this mean? Maybe it's a
cheerleading movie _ the Cider House rules!'''
 &HT;    More serious was the challenge of an American accent _ a first
for the British actor, who spent weeks practicing with a speech
coach.
 &HT;    ``I've always wanted to play an American, but frankly I've
always been scared to try it,'' Caine says. ``If you screw up an
Irish or Scottish accent, there are probably 7 million people who
will know it. If I screw up an American accent, some 300 million
people will know.
 &HT;    ``Some 300 million people criticizing me at my age is too much
to take!''
 &HT;    ``Cider House'' is the latest step in a career comeback for
Caine, who by the 1980s had proven himself a world-class actor _
with Oscar nominations for ``Alfie'' (1966), ``Sleuth'' (1972) and
``Educating Rita'' (1983), plus a win as Best Supporting Actor for
Woody Allen's ``Hannah and Her Sisters'' (1986) _ who nonetheless
had a talent for bad movies.
 &HT;    He starred in Steven Seagal's directorial debut, ``On Deadly
Ground'' (1994), after all, and was unable to accept his Oscar in
person because he was on location filming ``Jaws: The Revenge''
(1987).
 &HT;    ``I didn't go in search of some of my more questionable films _
I was always on the lookout for the great roles,'' Caine says.
``When they weren't offered to me, I'd take the ones that would pay
the rent.''
 &HT;    In the early 1990s, with more than 100 films under his belt, he
seriously considered retiring.
 &HT;    ``I couldn't get a decent job,'' he says. ``Yes, I could have
gotten a job and made a lot more money doing crap scripts. The rule
is, if you get a crap script you get a lot more money, because they
can't find anybody else to do it.
 &HT;    ``But I got to the point where I just couldn't do those movies
anymore,'' Caine says. ``You know, sometimes I would even write a
letter that said, `Not only will I not do this movie, but if you
don't mind me saying _ and I don't want to be unkind _ but I don't
think you should do it, either.'''
 &HT;    The turning point was ``Blood and Wine'' (1997), which starred
Jack Nicholson.
 &HT;    ```Finally this was a picture I wasn't ashamed of,'' Caine says.
 &HT;    He nailed the part, which in turn led to a role as a second-rate
nightclub impresario in ``Little Voice'' (1998).
 &HT;    Accepting a Golden Globe award for that role, Caine got one of
the evening's biggest rounds of applause when he said, ``My career
must be slipping _ I was actually able to be here to accept this
award.''
 &HT;    Once one of the world's handsomest leading men _ his signature
role was as a self-centered womanizer in ``Alfie'' _ Caine is now
firmly out of the leading-man bracket, which he says is just as
well.
 &HT;    ``It's tough for young actors to take risks,'' he explains. ``I
look at Brad Pitt in `The Fight Club.' I don't know if I would have
had the guts to do that role when I was younger. I see very little
risk being taken among that age group.
 &HT;    ``Of course, there are a few exceptions,'' he says, including
his ``Little Voice'' co-star. ``Ewan McGregor goes out on a limb
every single time. But he's got to stop taking his trousers off _
`OK, we've seen it, Ewan.'''
 &HT;    Acting is actually more rewarding for an older man, Caine
insists.
 &HT;    ``Acting is more fun at my age because I don't get the girl
anymore,'' he says. ``I get the part.
 &HT;    ``When you get the girl,'' he adds, ``you know what you're going
to do: You're going to make love to her, you're going to lose her
and then you're going to get her back and marry her _ that's what
you do when you're a male movie star.
 &HT;    ``But when you get to my age,'' Caine says with a smile, ``you
don't get the girl anymore _ I don't have to go to bed with anyone.
So it's great in a way, because I can get involved in other types
of dramas.''
 &HT;    Once upon a time Caine was as freewheeling a ladies' man off the
screen as on, but he's now been happily married for 26 years to
Shakira Baksa, a former Miss Guyana who appeared with him in ``The
Man Who Would Be King'' (1975).
 &HT;    ``So many people ask why the marriage has lasted,'' he says,
``and it's so simple: Many men marry without finding out what's out
there. I found out what's out there, and then I got married to the
woman I love.''
 &HT;    The actor recently had a chance to revisit his past, filming the
upcoming remake of ``Get Carter,'' his 1971 gangster hit. This time
the title role is being played by Sylvester Stallone, with Caine
playing Bromby, a sleazy nightclub owner.
 &HT;    ``Sly is playing a kinder, gentler Carter,'' Caine says, ``which
is fortunate. When I did the original movie, my Carter was vicious
_ he tries to kill Bromby by throwing him off a roof.
 &HT;    ``But, thank God, Sly forgives me _ I'm too old to do big
stunts!''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
