<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4084 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-RALPH-FIENNES-IN-THE-     11-29 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RALPH-FIENNES-IN-THE-END-OF-THE-AFFAIR-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREENE SIDE OF RALPH FIENNES 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Ralph Fiennes with Julianne Moore in a
scene from ``The End of the Affair.'') 
 By JEANNE WOLF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    How do you think you'd react to spending a few days making love
with actress Julianne Moore?
 &HT;    ``I got giggly,'' Ralph Fiennes confesses sheepishly. ``I got
like a silly schoolboy every time the director said, `Cut.'''
 &HT;    The two-time Academy Award-nominated actor co-stars with Moore
in ``The End of the Affair,'' a film which features some of the
most explicit love scenes of his career.
 &HT;    ``You try to click into the intensity of the moment while the
camera is rolling,'' he says, ``and then you need an outlet. For me
it was humor, and I think it was for Julianne, too. In fact, if
you'd seen us between takes, you'd have seen a lot of laughing.''
 &HT;    Based on Graham Greene's novel and adapted by writer/director
Neil Jordan, ``The End of The Affair'' is the story of an
extramarital love affair. Jordan was adamant in not shying away
from the story's sexual content.
 &HT;    Nonetheless, Fiennes says, he didn't find it especially
arousing.
 &HT;    ``The actual process of putting it all on film is quite
mechanical,'' he says. ``You're saying to each other, `Well, should
we move this way, or what if I touch you there?' It's all mapped
out in a very technical way. When I look at it, I just see the
shot.
 &HT;    ``It wasn't erotic to film it,'' he adds, ``but I hope the
audience will find it erotic.''
 &HT;    Fiennes says that he wasn't initially sure he and Moore would
click, based on their first meeting.
 &HT;    ``We had a closing-night party for `Hamlet' when I did it on
Broadway,'' he recalls. ``It was on a boat that cruised around
Manhattan. I had always been very much an admirer of Julianne _ she
seemed so strong to me. So when I met her on the boat that night, I
think I held back a bit. I admit I was intimidated.
 &HT;    ``But when we started rehearsals for this film, we got along
famously.''
 &HT;    ``The End of the Affair'' is a semiautobiographical
fictionalization of a painful period in Greene's own life, based on
his own wartime affair with a married American woman, Catherine
Walston, to whom he dedicated the book.
 &HT;    ``Neil and I both agreed that my character is Graham Greene,''
Fiennes says. ``But I had to put that out of my head after I
understood that the story was rooted in his life. I realized that
what he put on paper, the characters he created, were changed.
That's what writers do _ they take a slice of life and add new
dimensions to it.''
 &HT;    Fiennes did, however, spend time trying to understand how a
writer captures the world around him.
 &HT;    ``I found myself taking a lot of notes,'' he says. ``I kept
writing my impressions of things in notebooks. I began to get a
sense of what it is to see the world around you and then mutate it.
 &HT;    ``A writer's view of the world is not like an actor's,'' he
continues. ``When you're an actor, you're showing yourself
physically. Writers are sort of physically anonymous _ the emotions
they give us are through words. Acting is instinctive, and you wear
your emotions on your sleeve.''
 &HT;    Fiennes was particularly fascinated by Greene's powerful assault
on religion. His character, Bendrix, is a virtual atheist, while
Moore's character is a committed Catholic, which ultimately drives
them apart.
 &HT;    ``I grew up a Catholic,'' the actor says, ``but I just hated
going to Mass. By the time I was 13, I just didn't believe in it
anymore. I pretty much rejected the church.
 &HT;    ``I think it distressed my mother,'' he adds, ``even though she
never really said much. Ironically, she ended up rejecting
Catholicism, too _ she stopped going to Mass and became much more
interested in a Buddhist approach to faith and belief.
 &HT;    ``But what I found fascinating about Bendrix was that his own
hatred of God became a sort of recognition of God's existence,''
Fiennes says. ``That was Greene's brilliant conceit. By hating God,
you have to acknowledge him.''
 &HT;    Fiennes doesn't mind discussing religion, but is less
comfortable discussing the approach to acting which has earned him
Oscar nominations for ``Schindler's List'' (1993) and ``The English
Patient'' (1996).
 &HT;    ``I'm just not good at going on with the current jargon about
emotional memory and stuff,'' he says. ``I never think through how
I'm going to act a part.
 &HT;    ``In a sense, every new role gives you a new process,'' Fiennes
adds. ``I suppose that, automatically, you must draw on your own
life _ but I never think about which of my own emotions are up
there on the screen.''
 &HT;    The actor is equally reluctant to discuss the details of his
life offscreen.
 &HT;    ``It's a funny thing,'' he says. ``As an actor, you want people
to see your work and you want them to like it, you want them to be
affected by it _ but you don't want your private life to affect
anyone but yourself. You don't want that to be a part of the
equation.
 &HT;    ``I understand the hunger that people have to know their
stars,'' he continues. ``If I'm in the audience and I see someone
on the stage or screen, I find myself wondering, `What's he really
like? Was that him, or was he just pretending?' I have that
curiosity in me, so I understand it.
 &HT;    ``But that doesn't make it any easier for me to give up my own
privacy.''
 &HT;    Fiennes has been remarkably successful in keeping his personal
life private, given the tabloid potential of his 1997 divorce from
actress Alex Kingston after the revelation of his ongoing
relationship with Francesca Annis, 20 years his senior, who played
his mother in his triumphant Broadway ``Hamlet'' in 1995.
 &HT;    ``There are parts of me that I want to keep to myself _ my
relationships with my friends and family, for instance,'' the actor
says. ``The cult of celebrity creates images that aren't real.
People don't see you, they see an image of what is created. The
danger in being a celebrity is trying to become that image.
 &HT;    ``I'm not complaining about becoming famous,'' he adds after a
moment. ``It gives me the luxury of choosing. But there's a trap in
that, too: You have to remember to keep choosing what you want to
do and not what somebody else wants you to do.''
 &HT;    That philosophy guided Fiennes' choice of his next film,
``Eugene Onegin.'' An adaptation of Pushkin's classic poem about a
jaded Russian aristocrat who kills his best friend, it is directed
by his sister, Martha, a successful director of television
commercials.
 &HT;    ``I have a friend who's a film critic and, before we started, I
asked him what he thought,'' Fiennes recalls. ``He said, `I don't
think you can possibly do it. It just wouldn't work.' So we went
ahead and did it anyway.''
 &HT;    Gambling on a long shot comes naturally to him, he adds.
 &HT;    ``Every time I step on a set or a stage for the first time,''
Fiennes says, ``and I'm surrounded by great actors, I think, `I'm
starting all over again from zero. I can't say these lines. I don't
understand this character.'
 &HT;    ``But you just have to go with it,'' he concludes. ``Like an
athlete _ you train and train, the day of the competition comes and
you've just got to go for it.
 &HT;    ``They say `action' or `curtain,' and you just have to commit.''
 c.1999 Pentacom Productions  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jeanne Wolf is a Hollywood-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The End of the Affair,''
