<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER STEP IN THE MODERATE/CONSERVATIVE TUG-OF-WAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Jerry Falwell is getting even closer to the national
Southern Baptist Convention. Recently, Liberty University, a
9,400-student liberal arts school in Lynchburg, Va., that Falwell
founded, became officially affiliated with the Southern Baptist
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   As the Southern Baptist Convention has grown more conservative,
Falwell, an independent Baptist who likes to be called a
``fundamentalist,'' has grown ever closer to the denomination.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell and other members of his Thomas Road Baptist Church in
Lynchburg have been voting delegates at the last two national
Southern Baptist Conventions. Some have even talked of Falwell
ending up as president of the 15.7-million member denomination, the
nation's second-largest after Roman Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   That would not be too surprising either. But Falwell, who
founded the now-defunct Moral Majority and who still is a
sought-after national spokesman for religious conservatives, says
he has enough to do right now.
</P>
<P>
   Linking of Falwell's university to Southern Baptists came last
week when the executive board of the Southern Baptist Conservatives
of Virginia voted to designate Liberty as a Southern Baptist
school. The Southern Baptist Conservatives of Virginia is an
alternative state organization that was created because the main
state Baptist group is controlled by moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Even though many moderate Southern Baptists won't be overjoyed
that Falwell's university now is tied to the Southern Baptist
Convention, the denomination's president, the Rev. Paige Patterson,
lauded the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the great Liberty University to be part of our Southern
Baptist Zion ... is an answer to prayer for us all,'' said
Patterson, a longtime friend of Falwell and president of
Southeastern Baptist Theological Seminary in Wake Forest, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Freddie Gage, an evangelist based in the Fort Worth
suburb of Euless, Texas, who is on the board of Liberty University,
said many of his moderate Baptist friends might like Falwell if
they knew him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Falwell is the most misunderstood man in America,'' Gage
said. ``If you ever sat down and talked with him, you couldn't help
but like the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Falwell's embrace of the Southern Baptist Convention is the
latest episode in a 20-year power battle between conservative and
moderate Baptists. The outcome isn't settled. Conservatives clearly
dominate the national organization. But now the battle has switched
to the states.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, particularly, moderates are fighting back.
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist General Convention of Texas, which has 2.7 million
members _ more than some national denominations _ has practically
declared its independence from the conservative national
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The moderates' domination of the Texas convention became even
clearer earlier this month when Texas Baptists meeting in El Paso
rejected the controversial statement championed by conservatives
declaring that wives should graciously submit to the leadership of
their husbands.
</P>
<P>
   However, Baptist conservatives in Texas are doing some rebelling
of their own. They've formed an alternative state convention called
Southern Baptists of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   That organization scored a coup recently when the 12,000-member
First Baptist Church of Dallas, known as a flagship church of
Baptist conservatives, officially aligned itself with the
conservative state convention. The pastor emeritus of First
Baptist, the Rev. W.A. Criswell, is considered the spiritual leader
of the Baptist conservative revolution of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas conservative group is still small _ about 260 churches
are aligned with it out of some 6,000 Baptist congregations in the
state. But many predict other congregations will follow the lead of
First Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   The same sort of moderate-conservative struggle is occurring in
Virginia. Moderates are in control in Virginia, too. But the
aforementioned alternative conservative state convention is
offering opposition. And Falwell is a powerful ally.
</P>
<P>
   Where all this will end is anybody's guess. Most Baptists don't
like these political struggles. But they are sure to continue into
the next millennium. So we will keep watching.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
