<SLUG> BC-TV-LITTLEBILL-TEX </SLUG>
 
COSBY'S NEW ANIMATED SERIES ON NiCKELODEON GROWS ON YOU 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the debut episode of ``Little Bill,'' Nickelodeon's fresh new
animated series _ inspired by a popular line of children's books
created by that sly preschool czar Bill Cosby _ viewers meet a
5-year-old charmer with an insatiable curiosity and the cutest
little peanut-shaped, bald head.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted upfront that nothing particularly riveting,
as least by today's TV standards for crime and punishment, actually
happens to Little Bill outside the normal tussles of
pre-adolescence. Little Bill, whose large ``B'' on his shirts makes
him look like a miniature superhero, can be rambunctious and
hardheaded, sweet and tender, talkative and alarmingly meek _ like,
um, most of us, adult and otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   On a conventional network, however, it's a certainty that Little
Bill would BE conventional, the youngest sibling of a suburban
family popping in and out of twin SUVs. And everyone would be
white, except for one kid of color written in to make its defensive
case for racial diversity. Not here, though.
</P>
<P>
   Not on Nickelodeon, which has already amassed a nice little
track record for going against the grain in children's programming
_ how else could you explain ``Gullah Gullah Island,'' the
channel's live-action show inspired by the culture of a
250-year-old slave dialect?
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, there IS a token character on ``Little
Bill.'' He's an Anglo kid with what looks like orange hair.
Practically everyone else in ``Little Bill'' is African-American,
and there are a number of Latino and Asian characters moving rather
seamlessly in and out of Bill's middle-class, multigenerational,
citified life.
</P>
<P>
   Those of you who might find the cultural shift somewhat
off-putting _ hey, we all have our issues _ remember this is The
Cos.
</P>
<P>
   Any follower of Cosby's work, particularly his breakthrough
animated series ``Fat Albert and the Cosby Kids,'' the NBC sitcom
``The Cosby Show,'' and even his current ``Cosby'' on CBS,
understand and accept how race in Cosbyworld can be brought up and
disposed of without ever mentioning it.
</P>
<P>
   This is a factual observation, not a criticism. Watching
``Little Bill,'' which premiered Sunday night, you recognize that
the basic ingredients of Cosby's universal dilemmas remain the
same. That while Cosby's modus operandi is how normality comes with
a black face, the aim here is making children feel reassured, which
any child psychologist will tell you is a recognized concept of
early childhood learning.
</P>
<P>
   What I like most about Cosby's book series and the slightly
altered TV program (Little Bill is actually younger in the TV
version) is that adults won't find it so boring they'd fall asleep,
leaving a child unchecked with the power of a remote control.
</P>
<P>
   That's because ``Little Bill'' may follow the adventures of its
young protagonist, but it's by and large a show about family that
tightly reflects Cosby's wisdom and humor, a mild-mannered comedy
that never actually cracks you up but is a litany of amusing,
gentle anecdotes making you feel warm inside.
</P>
<P>
   Voiced by Xavier Pritchett, Little Bill lives in a small
residential neighborhood in a big city with his father, Big Bill
(Gregory Hines), a natural with children who can often be found
spending quality time with his jazz collection, and his mother,
Brenda (Phylicia Rashad), who, like Rashad's characters in
Cosbyworld, is warm and sensible but firm. An 8-year-old brother
and 10-year-old sister round out the immediate clan.
</P>
<P>
   Ruby Dee voices Little Bill's spirited great-grandmother, whom
they affectionately refer to as Alice the Great. Cosby also called
on his ``Cosby'' co-star Madeline Kahn to voice a quirky neighbor,
Mrs. Shapiro. Little Bill's running buddies include Dorado, Andrew
and Kiku, an Asian girl who likes to tussle with the guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Bill'' is unique in a couple ways. Two stand-alone
stories make up each half-hour episode, and the series is digital
desktop animation. You know what I mean if you've seen
Nickelodeon's ``Blue's Clues,'' which features quirky cutout
characters also animated by computers to play with a live-action
person. On ``Little Bill,'' everything is computer-generated,
making simple shapes and primary colors come alive.
</P>
<P>
   Opening each half-hour episode with the signature greeting
``Hello, friend,'' (This was a saying of Cosby's son, Ennis, who
was killed while changing a tire on a deserted Los Angeles-area
road) ``Little Bill'' proceeds to tell simple tales teaching the
importance of friendship and family while showing children how to
solve problems creatively and fairly.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``The Cosby Show,'' the show's power lies within its subtle
language and situations. In one episode, titled ``Treasure Hunt,''
Little Bill wanders around the house on a rainy day, trying to find
his ``thing,'' (for Dad it's jazz; for Mom, it's photography; for
his big brother, it's chess. Find your passion, is what it
preaches).
</P>
<P>
   Another episode, about Little Bill and his buddies' infatuation
with a popular TV show, is quite the sly proponent of imagination
over media technology. And just in time, too, considering the
recent press reports that watching too much TV and being zoned out
on Playstation make kids fat and unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every network turned away from ``Little Bill,'' failing
to see its commercial value. Nickelodeon appears to be a better
fit. Where else could this program get a prime-time spot, and for
26 episodes?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Nickelodeon understands the world of those under the
age of 5, people who find repetition comforting.
</P>
<P>
   With its assortment of Web sites, merchandising and book series
based on its TV shows, Nickelodeon shows that it has an uncanny way
of seeing commercial treasure where others might see uncommercial
trash. Hey, more power to you, Nick.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
