<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4168 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-PAPERLESS-OFFICE-MYTH     11-29 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAPERLESS-OFFICE-MYTH-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHATEVER HAPPENED TO THE PAPERLESS OFFICE?  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 600-word ``separate-buy'' article is from the International
Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``f'' financial news files.)  
  
 By MITCHELL MARTIN  
 c.1999 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   People like paper. Despite advances in digital technologies that
were expected to lead to paperless offices, one of the biggest
growth markets in the technology world right now is for printers,
largely the ink-jet variety.
</P>
<P>
   ``The paperless home or the paperless office is a myth,'' said
Paula Burskey, who covers the sector for Dataquest Inc., a
technology-research organization in San Jose, Calif. ``People like
something to put in their hand that is hard copy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mainly, they are printing out information from the Internet, she
said. ``The on-line availability of information has driven printer
volumes.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, printer manufacturers, who tend to make most of their
money selling ink cartridges, are thinking up ways to encourage
people to print more documents.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibitors at Comdex, the computer trade show recently held in
Las Vegas, visibly brightened when asked how the printer business
was doing. ``People still need that printout,'' said Chris
Strammiello, a Xerox Corp. marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox, whose background is in photocopiers, was until recently a
proponent of the paperless-office concept. Now, however, it uses
the phrase ``digital office,'' one in which documents of all sorts
exist in computer memories but where printing is rampant.
</P>
<P>
   Across the way from Xerox, Ricoh Co. was showing off a new
product called the eCabinet, targeted at small business and
individual departments of larger companies.
</P>
<P>
   Priced at about $14,000, the eCabinet stores documents, faxes,
electronic mail and the like on a hard drive and on removable DVD
disks. The idea is keep all of a company's current documents
on-line and a digital archive of older data in easily accessible
storage.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Japanese company's American subsidiary has just returned
to the printer industry because customers demanded more than just
the storage, an exhibitor said. Unlike most of the printer
companies, Ricoh is offering only laser models.
</P>
<P>
   Ink-jet devices, however, are where the action is, accounting
for about 70 percent of the market, according to Pradeep Jotwani,
vice president of consumer sales and marketing at Hewlett-Packard
Co.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard is the dominant maker of printers, accounting
for more than 40 percent of worldwide annual shipments.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons why ink-jet printers are more popular
than lasers. One is a price as low as $49.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are so inexpensive, ink-jet units are often bundled
with computers in the consumer market, which is growing rapidly,
especially in Europe, as people link up with the Internet, Jotwani
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ink-jet technology is finding its way into multiple-purpose
machines that combine printers, scanners, faxes and copiers in one
unit. Canon Inc., among other manufacturers, had several such
products on display at Comdex, drawing a lot of interest with units
priced between $300 and $400, what a scanner alone would have cost
just a few years ago or what a basic laser printer costs now.
</P>
<P>
   Profit margins on manufacturing ink-jet printers are not high,
especially at the low end, where, Burskey of Dataquest noted, a
printer costs just $10 or so more than an ink cartridge.
</P>
<P>
   So printer makers look to profit from what Strammiello of Xerox
termed an ``annuity stream'' that comes by selling supplies,
largely ink cartridges.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox this month offered consumers free Internet and electronic
mail access with any printer purchase for the rest of the year, and
it has a Web site that offers templates to help businesses create
brochures and that offers such printing-intensive children's
projects as constructing paper cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find it in our interest to maximize consumer value of the
products that they purchase,'' Jotwani said. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
