<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4172 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-PET-ROBOTS-IHT-750&AMP;ad     11-29 1478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PET-ROBOTS-IHT-750&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBOTICS: FROM PETS FOR THE LONELY TO SURGEONS' AIDS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDITORS: Note story can stand in 750 words)   (This ``separate-buy'' article is from the International Herald
Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
CAN STAND IN 750 WORDS. TOTAL UNCUT VERSION IS 1,150.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
  
 By JUDITH REHAK  
 c.1999 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a robot that looks and swims like an ancient fish,
scales and all. Or a minuscule video camera that is positioned
during heart surgery by voice commands from the surgeon to a
robotic arm. Or a robot that selects a component from a bin on an
assembly line, then installs it with just the right amount of
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Robots were once sort of one-trick ponies that were programmed
to do a simple task, and many still are.
</P>
<P>
   But today's robots, and future generations still in research
laboratories, are increasingly complex, combining artificial
intelligence, sensors, speech recognition and other leading-edge
technologies which make them seem almost human. Indeed, they can
perform certain tasks better than a human.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide sales of industrial robots to the auto industry, by
far the biggest user, soared 101 percent in the first half of this
year from a year earlier, boosted by economic growth in the United
States and Europe, according to an annual survey by the United
Nations Economic Commission for Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The European market for industrial robots has already posted a
32 percent increase in orders this year, and is forecast to grow at
about 10 percent annually to 32,000 robots in 2002, while the
United States should see a 9 percent annual increase, the U.N.
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Fanuc Ltd. of Japan is a leading supplier of robots to the
global auto industry, where they weld, cut, paint and load and
unload machine tools.
</P>
<P>
   But robots are becoming involved in an increasing array of
industries, performing functions from painting refrigerators to
molding plastic to packaging nail polish.
</P>
<P>
   A major customer of Fanuc Robotics, the American subsidiary of
Fanuc, is the U.S. Postal Service, which uses robots to read bar
codes on mail and sort it.
</P>
<P>
   To get an idea of how robotics is evolving, consider one of
Fanuc's newest developments, a commercial, intelligent robot that
can do skilled mechanical assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Equipped with sensors and 3-D vision, it knows just how much
pressure to apply to fit one part into another, in a vertical,
horizontal or diagonal position, a major improvement over its
predecessor which could handle only vertical positions.
</P>
<P>
   Another significant difference between it and older versions,
said Sunil Gupta, the product manager for the robot, is its 3-D
vision, which gives it depth perception. ``It's not exactly human
vision, but it's getting there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So accomplished is the robot that it is being used to make other
robots at Fanuc in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But far from the assembly lines of Detroit is another robotic
field that is just beginning to tap its enormous potential _ robots
that entertain and even act as companions.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Sony Corp. came out with a metallic robot dog named
Aibo, the Japanese word for partner.
</P>
<P>
   With a camera for eyes, microphones in its ears, and artificial
intelligence software, Aibo barks, ``sings'' robotic songs and wags
its tail when it is patted on the head. It can even play ball.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for the dog in Japan, where robots are wildly popular
with individuals, especially teenagers, outstripped Sony's
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The next generation of Aibos is now under development at Sony's
Digital Creatures Laboratory, but the entertainment giant is by no
means the only player.
</P>
<P>
   Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. has produced a prototype of a
talking robotic cat, designed as a companion for Japan's elderly.
And Mitsubishi Heavy Industries Ltd. produced a robotic fish that
is already swimming in the aquarium at an amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   Robotics is also playing a role in the rapidly growing field of
less invasive surgical procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Computer Motion Inc., a California company, has developed a
robotic platform procedure for heart bypass surgery, where the
surgeon is seated at a computer console about 3 meters (10 feet)
from the operating table and operates by manipulating with voice
commands three robotic arms holding instruments and a tiny video
camera, which is positioned in the patient's body.
</P>
<P>
   Because the robotic system smooths out even the tiniest tremors
in a surgeon's hands, it allows for precise surgical procedures
that would otherwise be impossible or extremely difficult.
</P>
<P>
   It also allows heart surgery with incisions no larger than the
width of a pencil, compared with the current practice of opening
the rib cage. The result is a less painful and much faster
recuperation for the patient.  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 750. OPTIONAL COPY FOLLOWS TO 1,150) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Unfortunately for investors who find the idea of robotics
appealing, there are few opportunities unless you aspire to being a
venture capitalist.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the complex, and lengthy development of robots, some of
it extremely arcane, takes place at universities like the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, and Carnegie Mellon's
Robotics Institute, often in cooperation with small, private
companies or subsidiaries of big corporations, as in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Robotics projects that relate to space and defense are often
funded by the U.S. government and the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Both Fanuc and Computer Motion are among the few companies that
are publicly listed, and worth investigating.
</P>
<P>
   Fanuc, which is listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange, obtains
roughly 30 percent of its gross revenue from robots, most of which
are bought by the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
   Hideyuki Mizuno, who follows the company for ING Barings in
Tokyo, said that Fanuc's robot business is being driven by demand
from Europe and the United States, where cost-cutting and
improvements in productivity are crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asian companies have not used robots as extensively because of
cheap labor costs,'' he said, ``and the Asian auto industry is
still quite small,'' referring to the industry outside Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But with Japan's economy in a recovery mode, Fanuc shares have
been on a tear this year, soaring some 126 percent, and Mizuno, and
several other analysts are maintaining their buy ratings on the
stock _ not so much because of improving robot sales, he said, but
because he expects that increased capital spending in Japan will
boost Fanuc's other business _ making computerized controls for
machine tools.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Computer Motion, one of the few publicly listed stocks
in its field, jumped to almost $14 in mid-October from $9.50 a week
earlier, on the announcement that a successful heart bypass
operation had been performed using its robotic platform.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Wald, who follows the company for George K. Baum, a
specialist boutique, has a ``speculative buy'' rating on the stock.
Like most such companies, Computer Motion is losing money now, but
Wald expects it to become profitable at the end of next year _
provided it has passed its clinical trials and obtained approval of
the U.S. Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are also looking for there is a recurring revenue
stream that comes from the disposable kits that go with the
product,'' he said. He has a $20 a share target price over the next
18 months if all goes well. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this article from the International Herald Tribune, it
must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
