MARS-LANDER; MARS-EQUIPMENT; CYBER-SANTAS; HOLIDAY-CLUTTER;
TV-EXCELLENCE; FBN-RAIDERS; SALTER-COLUMN; HOLIDAYS-SINGLES and
ROBISON-COLUMN)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (The ''HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (''w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BUDGET (Washington) _ President Clinton signs the final
spending bill for 2000, a $390 billion budget package providing
money for more teachers and police officers. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VIEQUES (Washington) _ President Clinton and Puerto Rico
Gov. Pedro Rossello are continuing their telephone summitry in
search of a compromise permitting resumption of limited Navy target
practice on the Puerto Rican island of Vieques. A White House
announcement could come at any time. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-TV (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rejects an appeal by
a convicted Texas sex offender who argued that allowing
closed-circuit television testimony by a young witness denied his
right to confront witnesses against him. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-BIAS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court kills part of a
racial-bias lawsuit by a white man denied admission to a University
of Texas doctoral program in counseling psychology. The court said
a federal appeals court had wrongly ordered the case to trial
despite evidence that race played no role in Francois Lesage's
failure to gain admittance. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYORAL (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown
went on the attack against challenger Tom Ammiano in a debate that
left little doubt: The race for mayor of San Francisco is between a
consummate machine politician and an outsider eager to shake up the
status quo. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   MARS-LANDER (Houston) _ The national curiosity over the Red
Planet promises to erupt once again this week when the Mars Lander
probe, NASA's boldest Mars mission to date, attempts a landing by
parachute and thruster control. It won't be easy. A sister probe
veered off into the void a month ago because of a navigation goof.
If this probe lands, it will dig a trench in the Martian dirt at
the south pole and cook soil samples in a search for water. By MARK
CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   MARS-EQUIPMENT (Houston) _ A look at the equipment on board the
Mars Lander that will send back to Earth the sounds of Mars. It is
one of the few times an exploration mission has included listening
devices. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATUERS (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAYS-SINGLES (Albany, N.Y.) _ This is a plea to Mom, Dad,
Grandma, Titi, Nana, Auntie and all the uncles from Andre to Jarrel
to Zach this holiday season. When in the presence of single people,
think twice before starting any question that begins with the word,
``Soooooooooooo?'' The word can make even the calmest single jump.
As in, ``Soooooooooo, is there someone special?'' By CELINA
OTTAWAY.
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-SANTAS (San Antonio) _ For the cyber-savvy, there will be
no last-minute crisis over holiday gift-giving. For them, there
will be no frenzied trips to the malls, no fighting traffic, no
midnight gift-wrapping. By DON SHERON.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-CLUTTER (Albany, N.Y.) _ If your daily bread is hard to
spot beneath the piles of clutter in your house, how will you ever
find your Christmas pudding? The holidays are a microcosm of your
whole life, experts say. If it's a muddle, odds are the holidays
will be, too. But there's good news. Now is the best time to
simplify. By KATE GURNETT.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-EXCELLENCE (Undated) _ With all the thanks being given these
days, spare a little for the state of television, will ya?
Everywhere you turn, there's something of interest. Every night.
Often in the same time slot. An embarrassment of riches. Boy, life
is good. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS NEWS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RAIDERS (Oakland, Calif.) _ Wait. Weren't we just here six
days ago? You know, at that point where the Raiders' season
couldn't sink any lower, at that point where an excruciating,
description-defying loss to a hated AFC West rival took a crowbar
to the kneecaps of their season? By BRIAN MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Now that Hillary Clinton has
answered the will-she-won't-she riddle, the next questions are: How
can she balance her duties as first lady with the demands of a New
York Senate campaign and why is she doing this anyway? By this time
next year, she will be the most psychoanalyzed sitting first lady
in history. Several new books claiming to understand her inner
thoughts are in the works. By MARIANNE MEANS
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Subtitled ``Living with
conviction in a cynical time,'' Paul Loeb's latest book, ``Soul of
a Citizen'' is like a 362-page pep rally for the soul. It should be
mandatory reading for anyone over the age of 12 - especially every
woman or man who has traded ``I give a damn'' for ``I give up.'' By
STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Every time I see another public
opinion survey doubting the wisdom of allowing free expression by
the media, my skin thins a bit. The latest came across my desk just
the other day. According to this survey by the Scripps Howard Texas
Poll, half of Texans don't like the way the media have been
covering the 2000 presidential campaign so far, while only 38
percent of Texans approve.
</P>
<P>
   By CLAY ROBISON. (Already filed)
</P>
