<HEADER>
A4180 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     11-29 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, Nov. 30. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Henry Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Developments on the Chechyn front. By
Michael Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN (Moscow) _ President Boris Yeltsin is
hospitalized with what doctors say could be pneumonia. By Michael
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSIDENT (Beijing) _ A Chinese political dissident has
been held in a psychiatric hospital for more than seven years,
since he unfurled a protest banner in Tiananmen Square in 1992, his
wife and a human rights group say. The case is an unusual but
alarming example of the misuse of psychiatric facilities by Chinese
authorities to silence a political opponent, human rights advocates
say. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-POVERTY (Stutterheim, South Africa) _ This small town's
struggle to improve the lives of its residents demonstrates the
enormous challenge confronting South Africa's new president, Thabo
Mbeki, as he strives to undo the legacy of apartheid, which
banished millions of blacks to desolate towns lacking
infrastructure and industry. By Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-BOYCOTTS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agreed Monday
to decide whether Massachusetts intruded too far into the realm of
foreign policy when it adopted a law requiring state agencies to
boycott companies that do business with the military regime in
Myanmar, formerly Burma. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-STUMP (Keene, N.H.) _ In place of the stump speech, Al Gore
has discovered the stump meeting. Offering up just himself, Gore
wanders into living rooms with 30 people or into school gymnasiums
with 300. He makes a short introduction and opens up the floor to
all comers. He answers questions for an hour or so, then stays
until the last person drifts away. And after two months of
practice, Gore has these seemingly spontaneous sessions down pat.
But spontaneity has its limits. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-CALLS (Undated) _ For Ruth Smith, the telephone call from
prison was a way for her cousin to speak with his dying mother. For
Tulen Rivera, the calls from prison are an opportunity for her
three boys to speak with their father. For Ruby Jackson, speaking
by phone with her imprisoned husband was a chance to talk without
having to spend eight hours on an overnight bus. But for New York
state, like most other states, telephone calls from prison are
something else. They are a way to make money. Under current state
policy, the families of inmates are charged the highest possible
rates for calls from prisons, and most of the money is kept by the
state. By John Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-CLUB-DISCRIM (Undated) _ Just weeks after a jury in Boston
found that a suburban country club had systematically discriminated
against a group of women golfers and awarded the women $1.9 million
in damages, the Massachusetts attorney general has asked a judge to
appoint a monitor to take over the country club. The takeover, if
approved, would mark the first time that a court took such direct
control of a private country club. By Marcia Chambers.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-DEVICES (Undated) _ Thousands of heart specialists
watched on closed-circuit television monitors as a tiny
experimental device was implanted in a patient's coronary artery.
The doctors heard the voice of Dr. Martin Leon, who was describing
the operation taking place in a hospital many miles away. But Leon
was anything but a disinterested observer. What he did not tell the
assembled doctors was that he was an investor in the company that
manufactured the device. He is not the only one to wear many hats
in the world of medical devices. Inventors are researchers.
Researchers are promoters. Promoters are investors. And, finishing
the circle, investors are inventors. It is a phenomenon found in
every medical treatment using devices, from laser surgery to gene
therapy. A special report. By Kurt Eichenwald and Gina Kolata.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
