<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4185 &Cx1f; tth-z
r p BC-BOOKS-POLITICS-SPI &LR;      11-29 1711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-POLITICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN PRODUCES PASSEL OF BIOS AND AUTOBIOGRAPHIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Story moving in ``p'' and ``e'' categories)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The politicians are in overdrive. The pundits are yelling at
each other on all-news channels, and showing no sign of listening
to any ordinary citizen. The public may be driven to distraction by
the time it has to choose next November.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Campaign 2000 is upon us, the earliest and most
front-loaded race for the White House in American history.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign season already has produced a bevy of political
books. Platitudes fill ``A Charge to Keep,'' the ghost-written tome
of Texas Gov. George W. Bush. The polls may show W as the
Republican frontrunner, but he loses the autobiography battle to
Sen. John McCain's ``Faith of My Fathers'' by a landslide. A far
more insightful Bush book, ``First Son,'' by Bill Minutaglio of the
Dallas Morning News, was written without W's cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   A White House contender who dropped out, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
finally gets the biography he deserves from Adam Clymer of the New
York Times. No person in public life has endured so many awful
books.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it's entertaining to see a team of veteran political
writers, Jules Witcover and Jack W. Germond, revitalize themselves.
They've traded in shopworn, post-election insider accounts for
thoughtful, early-season reflections.
</P>
<P>
   In ``No Way to Pick a President'' (Farrar, Straus and Giroux,
303 pages, $26), Witcover coolly dissects the sometimes-dangerous
flaws in how America chooses a president.
</P>
<P>
   Under the electoral college system, for instance, three
19th-century presidents lost the popular vote but won the White
House. In the 20th century, haphazard picking of vice-presidential
nominees put the bribe-taking Spiro Agnew and an overmatched Dan
Quayle within a heartbeat of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The fall campaigns have become an image-is-everything exercise.
Sound bites and even physical positioning at debates are rehearsed.
Candor becomes controversial and a gaffe can be fatal. The
percentage of eligible voters taking part has steadily declined.
</P>
<P>
   Witcover spends more time finding faults than in spinning
solutions. Still, his is an important book: An election campaign
should fire the imagination and pump new blood through the veins of
democracy. America is falling short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fat Man in a Middle Seat'' (Random House, 262 pages, $25) is
Germond's often-funny, sometimes poignant recollection of 30 years
spent covering presidential campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many Washington, D.C., talking heads, Germond can poke
merciless fun at himself. For instance, he was convinced by 1974
that a Democratic governor would win the White House in 1976 _ not
Jimmy Carter, but John Gilligan of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gilligan, however, who toured a state fair with reporters
and was asked if he planned to attend the sheep-shearing contest.
``I don't shear sheep,'' he replied. ``I sheer taxpayers.''
Gilligan became one of the few Democrats to lose in '74.
</P>
<P>
   The best chapter, however, is on how Germond's head was turned
and his wallet filled by participation in ``The McLaughlin Group,''
the weekly panel of capital pundits. Eventually, he become angry at
himself for being part of a verbal food fight. He vividly describes
McLaughlin's egocentric and autocratic behavior, his verbal
abusiveness, and the shameless ``buckraking'' that made Washington,
D.C., journalists take it. Germond didn't. He quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fat Man'' has a central flaw common to political reporters.
Germond is transfixed and enraptured with a campaign of long ago.
</P>
<P>
   The soft spot for a hardboiled Germond is Robert F. Kennedy's
tumultuous, tragic bid for the White House in 1968. Germond is
still full of excuses as to why RFK for months refused to challenge
Lyndon Johnson. He loses no opportunity to denigrate the one
politician who did, Minnesota's quiet, witty Sen. Eugene McCarthy.
He seems to use RFK as a measure of all presidents to follow, and
mischaracterizes the strengths of George Bush (Sr.) and Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Charge to Keep'' (William Morrow &AMP; Co., 288 pages, $23)
bears the junior Bush's byline. In reality, this autobiography was
largely put together by his communications director, Karen Hughes.
The original ghostwriter, a Houston Chronicle scribe, bailed out
complaining that Bush aides had not furnished sufficient material.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint is easy to understand. Seeking to bury memories of
a feckless youth _ and heavy drinking that lasted until the age of
40 _ Bush speaks to his love of family and his dog. Spot, too, has
White House lineage as offspring of Barbara Bush's celebrated
spaniel Millie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spot and I spend a lot of quality time together. She loves to
play ball and she has trained me well. Almost every day, we play
fetch,'' Bush informs readers.
</P>
<P>
   The dog aside, this is a bow-wow of a book. Take, for instance,
Bush's account of allegedly running the Texas Rangers as
``managing'' general partner. The book claims he pursued the team
``like a pit bull on the pant leg of opportunity,'' in one of the
book's many awkward cliches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line in baseball is results: wins and losses,'' it
adds. ``It's a people business. ... We succeeded in baseball
because we had a vision and a message.''
</P>
<P>
   The real bottom line is a bit different. The Rangers were
purchased soon after George Bush Sr. was elected president. The
money to buy the team was put up by friends of the Bush family, and
those wanting association with the first family. W invested exactly
$606,000 for 1.8 percent of the team.
</P>
<P>
   As governor, Bush would sell his share for $14.9 million. Not
since Hillary Clinton's $100,000 profit on the commodities market
has a politician done so well with a little help from friends.
</P>
<P>
   W served as a kind of ``roving good will ambassador ... the out
front guy'' while a highly capable general manager actually ran the
Rangers, Minutaglio writes in his detailed, fair but unsparing
biography.
</P>
<P>
   ``First Son'' (Times Books, 371 pages, $25) covers a lot of
ground. It discusses a clan of vast connections that has supplanted
the Kennedys as the first family of American politics. Bush is the
son of one American president, and the descendant of another on his
mother's side. His paternal great-grandfather was co-founder of
Brown Brothers Harriman.
</P>
<P>
   W was the oldest, most combustible of five children, a man who
would become known by friends as the Bombastic Bushkin, a play on
the Johnny Carson character. He skated through Yale without getting
a single ``A,'' having a fine time and oblivious to the civil
rights movement and antiwar tumult of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, W has gone through life as a front man,
using family connections to raise money for business ventures.
Connections are always available, whatever the challenge. W credits
his religious reawakening to a conversation with evangelist Billy
Graham one night at the family estate in Kennebunkport, Maine. In
one sense, Bush backers will find ``First Son'' devastating. In
another, however, they stand to be reassured.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor comes across as a man lacking in depth or
attention to detail. He seems somehow far less mature than McCain,
another self-confessed C student and hell-raiser who was forced to
grow up in the hell of the Hanoi Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, George W. Bush exhibits a steel fist within
the velvet glove. W is tough as nails. It was he, not Bush Sr., who
ordered imperious White House chief of staff John Sununu to resign.
He is self-confident and appears to have licked the drinking habit
that once made him challenge George Sr. to a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Minutaglio is a lucid, witty writer. ``First Son'' is also a
primer on Lone Star culture. The author is particularly skilled in
describing the Texas rich, from their deep carpets and fawning
servants to their ruthlessness in preserving privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edward M. Kennedy'' (Morrow, 448 pages, 27.50) has a few juicy
personal revelations. Along with brother Jack, the future senator
wears a microphone as he stands before the church altar awaiting
bride Joan Bennett at the couple's 1958 marriage. Watching the film
of her wedding, Joan Kennedy hears JFK tell Ted that being married
doesn't really mean having to be faithful to your wife.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't. But Clymer's book is mainly about the public man.
Whatever his private flaws, Kennedy has emerged as a giant of the
Senate. His causes have ranged from airline deregulation to civil
rights, from community health clinics to AIDS research. He is
treated as a devil figure by Republican fund-raisers, but has found
a succession of conservative Republican collaborators (notably
Orrin Hatch) on legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The book revolves around three transformations. A succession of
family tragedies would force a pampered youngest son, while still
in his 30s, into the role of family patriarch. Although heir
apparent to the presidency, he would renounce that role and settle
into the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   A heavy drinker and womanizer for a quarter-century, Kennedy
would clean up his life in the early 1990s and settle into a happy
second marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Eyelids will drop at Clymer's penchant for legislative detail.
But some nuggets are fascinating, such as an angry Hatch putting
down an effort by fellow conservative Jesse Helms to block AIDS
education.
</P>
<P>
   The book comes alive when Kennedy takes to the road, defying
government thugs on a trip to military-ruled Chile, or debunking
the Reagan administration's ``constructive engagement'' in
white-ruled South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy has persevered, and managed to preserve what limited
help the federal government offers to mothers and kids, the
disabled and the working poor. The book's message is perhaps summed
up in a quote from the late columnist Murray Kempton as
Massachusetts' senior senator learns about rural poverty on a visit
to Appalachia:
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the first Kennedy to be a loser in politics, and he
gives every sign of not anticipating a second chance. He makes his
witness now, not as a candidate, but as a kind of steward; he
travels to call attention not to himself but to the needs of
others.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
