<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIDE EFFECTS: Hold the Phone, Save the Brain
</P>
<P>
   Cradling the phone between the neck and shoulder is certainly
not good for the neck. But for one French psychiatrist it was bad
for his brain, too.
</P>
<P>
   After the psychiatrist, 43, talked that way for an hour, he lost
the vision in his left eye and had difficulty speaking, according
to a case report in the journal Neurology. A brain scan showed that
pressure from a bone called the styloid process, which runs behind
the jaw, had caused a tear in the artery that supplies blood to the
brain, disrupting the flow.
</P>
<P>
   The psychiatrist, whose styloid processes were unusually long,
recovered the next day. He now holds the phone in his hand, his
doctor reported.
</P>
<P>
   THERAPIES: Sweating Away Pain of Juvenile Arthritis
</P>
<P>
   Juvenile arthritis often relegates its sufferers to the
sidelines. But a University of Buffalo study of weight training has
found that a carefully designed exercise program significantly
reduces pain and increases ability to function.
</P>
<P>
   The study, presented this month at a meeting in Boston of the
American College of Rheumatology and the Association of
Rheumatology Health Professionals, compared six patients with
juvenile arthritis who received eight weeks of resistance training
with five who did not.
</P>
<P>
   The children who exercised used 25 percent less pain medication
and increased their overall physical capacity by 32 percent, while
the sedentary sufferers increased their use of painkillers. Blood
tests also found an improvement in the chemicals that regulate
inflammation.
</P>
<P>
   ``While adults with arthritis are often told that careful
exercise can improve their condition, children are often told to
skip phys ed or cut back,'' said the author of the study, Dr.
Nadine Fisher, an assistant professor of occupational therapy and
rehabilitation medicine at the University of Buffalo. ``Showing
that exercise actually helps with juvenile arthritis gives parents
and children ways to manage the symptoms.''
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS: On the Trail of a Gene for Stuttering
</P>
<P>
   A study comparing identical and fraternal twins in Australia
found evidence that stuttering and its severity may have a genetic
basis.
</P>
<P>
   The study, presented last week at a convention of the American
Speech-Language-Hearing Association in San Francisco, found that
inherited traits seemed to play a much stronger role in stuttering
than environmental factors.
</P>
<P>
   Working from a database of 6,717 subjects compiled by the
Australian Twin Project, a team led by Dr. Susan Felsenfeld, a
professor of speech pathology at Duquense University in Pittsburgh,
found 407 who reported stuttering.
</P>
<P>
   After interviewing the stutterers and their twins, the
researchers found that both identical twins were more than three
times as likely as fraternal twins to be stutterers.
</P>
<P>
   While this finding was similar to an earlier survey, data from
the interviews were used to rank stutterers in terms of severity
and emotional distress related to the condition. Again, researchers
found a greater concordance on these measures among identical than
fraternal twins.
</P>
<P>
   At the same conference, researchers presented the results of a
series of brain scans given to stutterers before and after
intensive retraining in speech fluency.
</P>
<P>
   Before treatment, the scans showed higher than normal activity
in areas of the brain's right hemisphere, which organizes the
muscles used in conscious movements, said Dr. Luc F. De Nil of the
University of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   In most people, speech is automatic, he said, ``but it appears
that stutterers lack that automaticity.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, De Nil said, the ``overall levels of activation
were more like that of normal speakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rx MONEY A Lower Risk and a Much Higher Cost
</P>
<P>
   Celebrex and Vioxx are two of the hottest drugs on the market,
in large part because of their potential for reducing pain and
inflammation without the risk of gastric harm associated with
medicines like ibuprofen, naproxen or aspirin. But a pair of new
studies has led The Journal of the American Medical Association to
conclude that while those risks are indeed lowered, they are not
lowered enough to justify the extra cost of prescribing them for
most people.
</P>
<P>
   Painkillers like ibuprofen, known as nonsteroidal
anti-inflammatory drugs, work by suppressing a chemical called the
COX enzyme.
</P>
<P>
   But the two new drugs work more precisely, blocking only the
form of the enzyme known as COX-2, associated with inflammation,
while bypassing COX-1, which plays a role in the normal functioning
of the digestive tract and kidneys. Its developers hoped that as a
result the so-called COX-2 inhibitors would not promote the gastric
discomfort and ulcers that are the most serious side effects of the
older drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In one of two articles in last week's issue of the journal,
Harvard Medical School researchers gave 1,149 arthritis patients
Celebrex, naproxen or a placebo. The drugs were equally effective
in reducing symptoms, and 5 percent fewer patients receiving
Celebrex reported gastric discomfort. Only one patient, who was
receiving naproxen, developed an ulcer during the 10-week trial.
</P>
<P>
   In the other article, researchers from the University of
Birmingham in England analyzed studies involving 5,435 patients and
found that Celebrex reduced the risk of ulcer by up to 80 percent
and Vioxx by 49 percent. But the older drugs were not producing all
that many ulcers among patients at low risk for gastric bleeding,
the researchers found.
</P>
<P>
   In an accompanying editorial, Dr. Walter L. Peterson of the
University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center at Dallas, wrote
that the studies indicated that more than 500 low-risk patients
would have to be treated with a COX-2 inhibitor to prevent one
ulcer caused by taking a traditional painkiller.
</P>
<P>
   Since the new drugs, still under patent protection, cost more,
Peterson calculated the yearly cost of preventing one ulcer at
almost $400,000, a figure he said indicated that low-risk patients
should stick to the older drugs.
</P>
<P>
   BEHAVIOR: When Guns Spell Danger for the Owner
</P>
<P>
   People who buy handguns are more likely to kill themselves than
people who do not, even up to six years after the purchase, and
women who buy guns are doubling their risk of becoming murder
victims, concluded a study published Nov. 18 in The New England
Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The author of the study, Dr. Garen Wintemute, an epidemiologist
at the Violence Prevention Research Program at the University of
California at Davis, said the suicide statistics merely reflected,
to an extent, the fact that some people who intended to kill
themselves bought handguns to do so.
</P>
<P>
   And in fact, the risk of suicide peaked in the first week of gun
ownership, when the rate was more than 50 times higher than
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``But only a relatively small number fit that pattern,''
Wintemute said. Suicides during the first month after purchase
accounted for only 14 percent of gun suicides by men and 25 percent
of gun suicides by women. Most of the time, he said, a gun
``becomes a danger down the road'' when depression or other
stresses arise.
</P>
<P>
   The study compared mortality rates for the 238,292 people who
legally bought handguns in California in 1991 with the rates for
the state's population at large.
</P>
<P>
   Over six years, the likelihood of suicide was 15 times as high
for women who bought pistols as for women who did not and 3 times
as high for men who bought guns as for men who did not.
</P>
<P>
   While the main focus of the study was suicide, homicide was also
examined. Wintemute said the murder rate was slightly lower than
average for men who bought handguns, but twice as high for women.
``It may be that women purchase handguns for protection against
violence from an intimate partner and that these handguns are used
by the partners against them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
