<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Danger: Road Dust
</P>
<P>
   When the subject is the impact that automobiles have on air
quality, the focus is usually on what's coming out of the tailpipe.
But researchers from the California Institute of Technology have
looked at another effect that cars have on the air: the dust they
kick up.
</P>
<P>
   Their analysis is bad news for those who suffer from allergies.
The dust raised by passing traffic on paved roads contains up to 20
known allergens, including molds, pollen and animal dander.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, reporting in the journal Environmental Science
and Technology, noted that the problem is worse in places with
roadside vegetation, like residential and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   In two residential parts of Los Angeles, they said, road dust
contributed 5 percent to 12 percent of the allergens in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the concrete of downtown Los Angeles, however, road
dust was responsible for less than 1 percent of the airborne
allergens.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-Food Snakes
</P>
<P>
   Snakes are not dainty eaters. Most open their jaws wide and use
their upper teeth to ratchet themselves over and around their prey,
gobbling it whole.
</P>
<P>
   It may not seem possible, but two University of Massachusetts
researchers have discovered a snake with even worse table manners.
Like a teenager in a hurry to finish dinner, it shovels food into
its mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Called the threadsnake, it is a burrowing creature, often less
than five inches long and an inch in diameter, and found in the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Its lower jaw has a unique structure, with three joints on each
side. When the threadsnake eats (its usual food is the larvae and
pupae of ants and other social insects), the front, teeth-bearing
parts of the jaw move inward and outward, like a pair of swinging
doors. The food is quickly raked into the esophagus.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who wrote about their discovery in the journal
Nature, noted that this feeding technique may be related to the
snake's hazardous foraging strategy.
</P>
<P>
   To feed on ant larvae, for example, the threadsnake must invade
the nest, which is aggressively defended by worker ants that can
injure or even kill the snake.
</P>
<P>
   So threadsnakes may have evolved their fast-feeding ability in
order to be able to eat and run _ for their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Telescope Back at Work
</P>
<P>
   The Hobby-Eberly Telescope at McDonald Observatory in West
Texas, which has the largest mirror in the world, has begun regular
operations after a two-year shakedown.
</P>
<P>
   The telescope, which is being operated by a consortium of three
American and two German universities, will be used for
spectroscopy, or analyzing the spectrum of light emitted by
objects, and is particularly suited to large-scale surveys and to
the study of phenomena that vary over time, like supernovas.
</P>
<P>
   The design of the telescope has more in common with the radio
telescope at Arecibo in Puerto Rico than with most light
telescopes.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Arecibo instrument, which is a fixed bowl in the earth,
the Texas mirror is fixed in elevation, the angle at which it faces
the sky. (Unlike the Arecibo bowl, however, the mirror can be
rotated: it is on the equivalent of a lazy susan.)
</P>
<P>
   A typical telescope tracks an object by moving its mirror as the
Earth rotates.
</P>
<P>
   With the Texas telescope, an object is tracked not by moving the
mirror but by moving a platform that is suspended over it,
constantly keeping the light from the object in focus.
</P>
<P>
   This reduces the size of the mirror that can be accessible at
any one time to 362 inches from its as-built 433 inches, making it
effectively the third-largest mirror in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But having a fixed mirror also made the instrument far less
expensive than other large telescopes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
