<SLUG> BC-SCI-OLDER-ATHLETES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE VIE FOR SLOTS ON THE SENIOR VARSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By LINDA VILLAROSA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After not having touched a basketball for nearly half a century,
63-year-old Aldona Siuta of Avon, Conn., decided last year that it
was time to fulfill her hoop dreams: she laced up a pair of high
tops and threw herself into a twice-weekly women's over-50 pick-up
game she had read about in her local paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't played basketball since high school, but as soon as I
heard the ball bouncing, those 40-some years went out the window,''
said Ms. Siuta, who works part time as an actuarial analyst and has
seven grandchildren. She also plays soccer against women her age on
a team called _ what else? _ Still Kicking.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I tell people that I play soccer and basketball, they
look at me with complete disbelief,'' she said. ``But at this age,
getting out there and doing something is better than sitting
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Ms. Siuta, more and more people over 50 are realizing that
the benefits of team sports competition do not have to end with the
arrival of gray hair and stiff knees. Today's aging athletes are
healthier than their predecessors, living longer and pointedly
aware of the importance of getting and staying in shape. They are
forming pickup teams, creating senior divisions in sports leagues
and competing in large-scale events in gyms and on playing fields
across the country, a kind of senior varsity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senior team sports is an established trend and here to stay,''
said Mike May, director of communications for the Sporting Goods
Manufacturers Association, based in North Palm Beach, Fla. This
trade group, which keeps track of Americans' participation in
sports, estimated that more than twice as many people 55 and older
frequently took part in basketball and slow-pitch softball in 1998
as in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Stewart, executive director of the Fifty-Plus Fitness
Association, a nonprofit organization in Stanford, Calif., says the
increase in team sports participation is part of an overall surge
in fitness activities among people over 50. This trend, he said, is
fueled by the millions of baby boomers turning 50 every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby boomers have always been active and they want to continue
to stay in shape as they get older,'' he said. ``They know that
exercise contributes to healthy aging, and team sports allow them
to stay motivated to exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Sally Butterfield, a 53-year-old database manager born at the
front end of the baby boom, started playing soccer after cheering
for her children from the sidelines. She now competes indoors and
outdoors several times a week with other women close to her age,
near her home in Dartmouth, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got tired of watching the kids and decided I wanted to do
something for myself,'' she said. ``Soccer is important to me
because I have a sit-down job, and it's the only exercise I get.
But the camaraderie of the group, the friends I've made from
soccer, is really the best benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Those in search of higher-level competition have flooded the
National Senior Games-Senior Olympics, an annual multisport event
for athletes 50 and older. The games began 14 years ago with 2,500
participants; last month's event in Orlando drew 12,000. Similarly,
the Senior Softball World Series, for players over 50, has
ballooned to 122 teams from 68 in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Don Berg, the 78-year-old pitcher for the San Diego Silver
Hawks, has competed in 11 Senior World Series tournaments and has
eight championship rings. ``When I play in the big games, I get my
adrenaline up,'' said Berg, a retired physical education teacher
who plays softball three or four times a week. ``Out on the field I
feel like I'm in high school again.''
</P>
<P>
   Some older athletes play almost as well as they did in their
glory days. Earl Hitt, 72, plays on several volleyball teams in the
St. Louis area, including one that competes against 20- and
30-year-olds in an open league. His team has four members in their
70s and several others in their 60s. ``You can see the look on the
other team's faces when us old guys walk out onto the court,'' he
said. ``Those are the guys that are the most fun to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are in it strictly for a good time. Bobbie Emery, the
Still Kicking coach, loves to see the joy on the faces of her team,
including her mother, who just turned 75.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd expect women their age to be dignified,'' Ms. Emery
said. ``But all of them are beginners and some never even had a gym
class. It's great to see them get out there, running and falling
and making fools of themselves just for the fun of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
