<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4217 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-FEVERS-2TAKES-NYT     11-29 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FEVERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS' UNSOLVED MYSTERIES: WHEN FEVERS HAVE NO KNOWN CAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By SANDEEP JAUHAR, M.D.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fever took up residence in the young man like a squatter who
had started to break things. In the beginning it seemed benign
enough. It started one morning as a temperature of 101. That was
all: no cough, no diarrhea, no skin rash, nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors thought it was probably a run-of-the-mill viral
infection that would go away on its own. But it didn't. Soon, the
nosebleeds and abdominal pain started.
</P>
<P>
   He went to New York Presbyterian Hospital, the large academic
medical center where I work, for answers, but his medical history
provided no clues. He had been healthy his whole life. A year
earlier, he had moved from South America to live with relatives in
Brooklyn. He was faithful to his girlfriend and had never used
drugs. He had always tested negative for tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   But now, his skin was pale and his body thin. His deep-set eyes
were insecure, like those of a scared, sick child. Otherwise his
exam was normal: no mouth sores or enlarged lymph nodes or skin
rash or heart murmur. His lungs sounded clear.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors suspected he had an infection, because infections are
the most common cause of short-term fevers. But his urine had no
bacteria or white blood cells. His chest X-ray was normal. Blood
cultures did not grow any organisms.
</P>
<P>
   After a few days of negative tests, his doctors decided to send
him home. Though the fever persisted, he did not have an obvious
infection. Though he was still fatigued, the nosebleeds had stopped
and he did not seem sick enough to warrant continued
hospitalization. So he went home, with an assurance that whatever
it was that ailed him would soon go away.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't. He soon found himself back in the hospital. Infection
was still the prime suspect, so cultures were repeated, but this
time a wider net was cast. He was tested for a long list of
ailments, common and not so common: babesiosis, ehrlichiosis,
brucellosis, toxoplasmosis, Q fever, malaria, cytomegalovirus,
human T-cell lymphoma virus, histoplasmosis, herpes, bartonellosis,
HIV, tuberculosis and syphilis. All were ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer also needed to be ruled out, so doctors did blood cell
counts, a CAT scan and bone marrow biopsies, obtained through a
large needle drilled through his hip. All normal. Tests for
rheumatic diseases and various others were also normal.
</P>
<P>
   So after another month the doctors again threw up their hands
and sent the young man home. His discharge diagnosis: fever of
unknown origin.
</P>
<P>
   Fevers cause trouble, for doctors and patients. Because almost
any disease can cause a fever, the list of possibilities is long
and daunting. It is shortened only with the most meticulous of
interviewing and physical exams. Questions about travel, medicines
and symptoms become paramount.
</P>
<P>
   Patients with fever want answers. Nothing else is so firmly
linked in their minds to disease. The fever punishes them. It revs
up their metabolism, causing them to feel fatigued and lose weight.
If it lasts long enough, their muscles start to break down as the
fever literally consumes them. (Tuberculosis, a common cause of
prolonged fever, used to be called consumption.)
</P>
<P>
   Fevers can be mysterious; then, the challenges multiply. The
hospital is always filled with patients with fevers no one
understands. In some, like the young man, it is a sign of an
underlying disease that is not yet known.
</P>
<P>
   In others, like AIDS or cancer patients with suppressed immune
systems, the fever may have any number of causes, including their
underlying disease or a dangerous infection that could rapidly kill
if left untreated. Whatever the case, mysterious fevers are common,
and among the most vexing of medical problems.
</P>
<P>
   The modern definition for such fevers was proposed in 1961 by
Dr. Paul Beeson and Dr. Robert Petersdorf, infectious-disease
specialists at Yale. Their definition _ a fever of at least 101
degrees lasting for three or more weeks and defying explanation,
despite at least one week of intensive investigation inside a
hospital _ was intended to exclude all but the most perplexing
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The temperature cutoff excludes many ``low-grade fevers'' that
are not true fevers at all. (The normal average human temperature
may vary between 98 in the early morning and 100 in the early
evening.) The duration requirement excludes most viral and many
bacterial illnesses, which are either self-limited or obvious.
</P>
<P>
   In their first systematic studies, Beeson and Petersdorf found
that about 35 percent of their adult patients with mysterious
fevers had infections, 20 percent cancer and 15 percent rheumatic
diseases. The rest were in a miscellaneous category or were never
diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, relatively small changes have occurred in the
distribution. Cancer is now as common as infections, especially in
very protracted fevers. Rheumatic diseases, like lupus and
rheumatoid arthritis, are less common, probably because they can
now be caught and treated early.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Of the infectious diseases, syphilis, common in the 1950s, is a
rare cause of fever of unknown origin today. Tuberculosis, a
leading infectious killer, remains a major player.
</P>
<P>
   The fever of unknown origin has become an even bigger problem as
immune-deficiency conditions have proliferated. Doctors invariably
hospitalize people with AIDS and bone marrow transplants when they
get these fevers so they can receive intravenous antibiotics to
fight off life-threatening infections. In the hospital they are
often kept in isolation, as far as possible from people who can
infect them.
</P>
<P>
   Their diets are severely restricted: no fresh fruit or raw
vegetables that harbor fungus, no undercooked meat, no yogurt. Many
doctors even discourage patients from getting fresh flowers.
</P>
<P>
   (A nurse once removed flowers from the room of a cancer patient
of mine and afterward stopped me in the hall to tell me she felt
evil. The patient, young and newly married, called me into his room
later. With tears in his eyes he asked me if it was OK for him to
hug his wife.)
</P>
<P>
   But these measures, draconian as they may seem, save lives.
Studies in the 1970s showed that immunosuppressed patients with
mysterious fevers lived longer if they were hospitalized and
treated with broad-spectrum antibiotics. The approach is beginning
to change: a recent study suggested that outpatient treatment may
suffice for some patients whose immune systems are recovering. But
most doctors still prefer to err toward caution.
</P>
<P>
   Still, patients suffer, both from the fever and from what is
done to manage it. Consider a large group of those with compromised
immune systems: newborns. When a newborn has a fever, blood is
drawn for cultures, a bladder catheter is placed to get urine for
culture and examination, and a needle is inserted into the spine to
get fluid to check for meningitis. Though these procedures are
painful and have obvious risks, most doctors think they are
justified if an occasional baby is saved from brain damage or
worse.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is with terminally ill patients. They live longer when
their fevers are treated aggressively, but not always better.
</P>
<P>
   I will never forget a middle-aged man I treated last year, as an
intern. His doctor told him he had leukemia in the spring of 1997.
At first his disease responded to chemotherapy, and he went into
remission. But it returned and eventually proved resistant to all
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   He knew he was going to die. But first, he wanted to spend a
little more time with his two young sons to impart a few lessons
they could carry with them when he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   But he could not escape the hospital. The leukemia had ravaged
his immune system, so every time he got a new fever, every few
weeks, he would be hospitalized and placed in virtual isolation.
His sons were discouraged from visiting him because they were young
and posed an infectious risk.
</P>
<P>
   He was given antibiotics _ antibacterials, antivirals,
antifungals _ for weeks at a time, often becoming violently
nauseated and short of breath during his daily infusions. With each
passing day his frustration and sadness grew as he realized the
fever was gobbling up the precious little time he had left.
</P>
<P>
   One day, he decided he had had enough. The months of
hospitalizations and the endless, mysterious fever had taken a toll
on his mind as much as his body. He told his doctors he was going
home. They discouraged him, telling him he could rapidly succumb to
an infection, but he would not be dissuaded.
</P>
<P>
   A few days before he finally left, he called me into the small
room that had become his home. ``They say I will die if I leave the
hospital,'' he said. ``I will take that chance because here I am
already dead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
