<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4223 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CONSUMER-HEALTH30-COX     11-29 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-HEALTH30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At odds over cleanliness of endoscopes
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   How clean is clean enough?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question University of Georgia microbiologist David
Lewis is posing to the medical community about endoscopes, which
are used mostly to check out colons and lungs in about 15 million
surgical procedures a year in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Government regulators and medical associations maintain that
disinfecting the flexible tubing is sufficient. But Lewis and a
growing number of health professionals think the equipment needs to
be sterilized or sheathed to reduce the risk of disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nationwide, this is really rather a sloppy situation,'' Lewis
said. ``There is no way, with all the joints and valves and
crevices, to really get these things clean. And if you don't
believe me, look at the tubing when the repairman opens it up.
You'll find gunk all through it.''
</P>
<P>
   But does all that gunk _ tiny chunks of tissue, feces, mucus and
blood _ actually pose a risk to patients? Scientifically speaking,
the risk is very low. Between 1988 and 1992, there were 28
published cases of infection _ or about 1 infection per 1.8 million
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   And when you consider the other option _ exploratory surgery _
the gamble looks even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is relative,'' said Lynne Sehulster, a
microbiologist at the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta and
Prevention's hospital infection program. ``Nothing is risk-free.
And it's very easy to say all scopes should be sterilized. ... But
really, if they're properly cleaned, there's nothing to be gained
by making such a demand.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that it's difficult for patients to know whether
the equipment has been properly cleaned, Lewis says.
</P>
<P>
   Most flexible scopes are cleaned with glutaraldehyde, a
disinfectant. But the length of time the scopes are soaked varies
widely. The CDC does not specify times or temperatures. But Johnson
&AMP; Johnson, the manufacturer of glutaraldehyde, and the U.S. Food
and Drug Administration recommend that they be soaked for at least
45 minutes, while the industry standard hovers closer to 20
minutes, according to a study published this year in the journal
Gastrointestinal Endoscopy.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a 1997 survey in the Archives of Family Medicine showed
that a majority of primary care physicians failed to follow more
than one-third of the federal guidelines for the proper cleaning of
sigmoidoscopes, used for the detection of colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   And Lewis, along with others, questions the accuracy of the low
infection figure. They believe the scopes are cross-contaminating
patients at a higher rate, but that the majority of infections
result in mild illnesses that are not easily connected to the
endoscopic procedures. They also think doctors aren't reporting
cases because they're afraid of being sued.
</P>
<P>
   Sehulster disagrees. ``If a problem were occurring with
post-procedural infections or adverse outcomes to the extent that
is implied by the critics in the field, I'm confident that medical
professionals would have jumped right in to seek out a solution,''
she said. But Sehulster added that infection surveillance may not
be complete, because so many of the procedures are done in an
outpatient setting.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons health practitioners are hesitant to change
cleaning methods is cost. While disinfection is a relatively cheap
process, sterilization of endoscopes is a complicated endeavor. The
tubing can't be heated like most medical devices, because the
process damages the equipment. So special chemicals and equipment,
such as peracetic acid processors, have to be used, at
significantly higher cost.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some doctors and hospitals are revising their
procedures for cleaning endoscopes.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Gastroenterology Associates uses sheaths that slip over
the instruments and are discarded after a procedure. But Dr.
Russell Kramer said the practice started using the sheaths about
three years ago not because the doctors were worried about
infection rates, but because it was faster than waiting for the
scopes to soak the recommended times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, perception-wise, patients think this is much better.
But in reality, that's sort of a heart decision, not an
intellectual decision,'' he said. ``Either way is equally safe in
my opinion. When we cleaned them (and did periodic cultures on the
endoscopes), we never came up with any bacteria that was
transmissible.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some recommendations from all sides of the debate on
how to get a clean scope:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Go to hospitals, hospital-based clinics or private practices
that are large enough to have dedicated staff to clean the
endoscopes. Those facilities have more money to spend on the
cleaning process and they probably aren't under as much pressure to
reuse the equipment quickly, which could result in shorter
disinfectant soaking periods. However, even that doesn't always
guarantee a safe scope: In 1997, tuberculosis cases in Maryland and
South Carolina were linked to dirty bronchoscopes used in two
hospitals, according to a Journal of the American Medical
Association study.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shop around for a physician or hospital who cleans the
endoscope in a manner that makes you feel comfortable. Ask for a
sheath, if it's available. Be prepared to pay a couple of hundred
bucks for it though; insurance typically doesn't cover the cost.
Ask about the cleaning procedure, and specifically whether the
scopes are disinfected or sterilized. Find out whether the people
who clean the equipment are trained for the job or are doing it as
a side responsibility. Ask them if the endoscopes are checked with
periodic bacterial cultures.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ask for the newest scope the practice or hospital offers. In
recent years, manufacturers are getting smarter about making
endoscopes that are easier to clean and thus safer to use.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, none of this will guarantee that you will get the
cleanest of the clean scopes, but it does give your doctor a
heads-up that you're familiar with the issue and it's important to
you. And if there's any indication a clinic is evading your
questions, move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients have a right to get a clean scope,'' Lewis said.
``But they have to know what to ask to make sure they get one.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
