<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reynolds Price's take on Jesus' preaching
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week The New Yorker ran an essay by John Updike about his
religious faith. This week Time ($3.50) features a unique
interpretation of the Gospels according to novelist Reynolds Price.
The North Carolina author of ``Three Gospels'' was asked to take
another look at episodes in Jesus' life and to create an updated
version. Price explains that one teaching he does not agree with is
Jesus' instruction to ``Go then and make disciples of all
nations.'' That command, Price writes, ``goes on contributing
heavily to the evils of national and religious warfare,
institutional and individual hatred, imperialism and enslavement.''
</P>
<P>
   Also of interest are Jack White's essay on the ``feud'' between
Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell and Atlanta Constitution editorial page
editor Cynthia Tucker over the city's affirmative action program,
and Richard Lacayo's assessment of the Norman Rockwell exhibit on
display at Atlanta's High Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   White calls for a more ``dignified debate,'' not ``a wallow in
the mud.'' Reviewing Rockwell, Lacayo generally praises the
artist's work while bemoaning the sentimentality. ``There are parts
of this show that could make you hate Santa Claus,'' he declares.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  We've got mail: The New Yorker ($3) goes digital this week
with several fascinating articles about e-commerce, e-mail and the
Internet. Seymour Hersh explains why high-tech changes are breaking
the code breakers at the National Security Agency. Even Third World
countries have begun exchanging national security messages
encrypted in unbreakable digital code, Hersh writes. In ``Your Mail
Has Vanished,'' writer Michael Specter goes in search of lost
e-mail in Schaumburg, Ill., where AT&AMP;T Global Network Services has
its huge e-mail delivery infrastructure. And, in a clever short
essay, Adam Gopnik praises the Internet for returning us to an
18th-century love of words. Jonathan Swift and Alexander Pope would
have their own Web pages, he writes, and ``would have been merrily
scribbling short essays, anonymous accusations, flames and
billets-doux.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Millionaire fever: The show makes Mensa members laugh, but as
U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($3.50) notes, ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' appeals to ordinary Americans who can remember the
names of state capitals or sitcom chronology. The magazine explores
the TV show's impact on future programming and looks back at the
golden age of quiz shows, before the scandal. Not all the answers
on the 1950s shows were rigged. Dr. Joyce Brothers won ``The
$64,000 Question'' by answering a series of tough questions about
boxing. The sponsor, Revlon, apparently wasn't happy with her
success, writes correspondent Lewis Lord, because Brothers didn't
wear makeup.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mission to Mars: No one expects to find little green men on
Mars, but Newsweek ($3.50) looks at what the polar lander may
discover when it probes the red planet this week. Meanwhile,
Hollywood has caught a case of Mars fever. Brian De Palma's
``Mission to Mars'' will touch down in theaters in March; ``Red
Planet,'' starring Val Kilmer, should land next summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Seasonal stress: Not surprisingly, a poll by Family Life
($3.50) found that 70 percent of those surveyed said the holidays
are more stressful since they became parents. The magazine's tips
for reducing the stress level include cutting the gift list, buying
gifts online, including the children in Christmas rituals such as
singing carols at bedtime or reading stories to one another and
opting for a potluck holiday dinner.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: Sports Illustrated Women ($3.50) names the
sportswomen of the year (the U.S. women's soccer team), the athlete
of the century (Jackie Joyner-Kersee) and the 100 greatest female
athletes of the century. Joining Joyner-Kersee in the Top 5 are
Babe Didrikson Zaharias, Billie Jean King, Sonja Henie and Martina
Navratilova. ... The U.S. women's soccer team also makes Glamour's
($2.99) Top 10 list, along with singer Jewel, ``Harry Potter''
author J.K. Rowling and TV actress Camryn Manheim.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
