<HEADER>
A4235 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      11-29 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule book reviews:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``DESERT'' &QL; 
Photos by Jack Dykinga, text by Janice Emily Bowers (Abrams,
$49.50) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This book offers lots of pretty photographs of the Mojave Desert
in which Dykinga seems to concede (appearances on the cover
notwithstanding) that not everything in the rural Southwest is
fluorescent orange. The big draw for us, however, is Janice Emily
Bowers, who lives near Tucson and who has written lovely essays
(``A Full Life in a Small Place'') about the natural wonders there.
Both writer and photographer were assisted by the rains &QL; 
of El Nino during the winter of 1997-1998, which brought the desert
into abundant bloom and made their jobs even more pleasurable than
they'd expected them to be. Tourists came from far away to see the
flowers that spring, many for the first time. Bowers envied them.
``The first time of seeing the desert in bloom is almost painful in
its intensity,'' she writes, ``as if every flower were a needle
piercing your skin or a chunk of ice pressed onto your flesh. I
wanted to join that spring, as if it were a circus, and travel with
it forever.'' She acknowledges that this book might attract more
tourists, which increases her concern over the beautiful,
vulnerable desert. Are the crowds good or bad? ``Sometimes,'' she
writes, ``I don't know which group worries me most: the millions
who visit or the millions who stay away.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
``ATLANTIS FOUND'' &QL; 
By Clive Cussler (Putnam, $26.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is what Clive Cussler says about his appeal as a writer:
``I give people what they want. My books are like an old Saturday
afternoon matinee with easily identifiable characters: the big
rugged hero; the shrewd heroine (who is never a bimbo); the nasty
villain who gets it in the end . . . I never mean for it to be
anything more than entertainment.'' His sprawling novel features
his recurring big rugged hero, Dirk Pitt, who is supremely capable
and ever manly but a bit on the stiff side (he's like James Bond
without the panache). His shrewd heroine who isn't a bimbo is Pat
O'Connell, an expert in ancient languages. And the villains? There
are so many, and they fall all over themselves trying to kill
O'Connell and her colleagues and then Pitt, who makes a Bond-like
entrance and rescues them from drowning in flooded tunnels under a
mountain in Colorado. One of the assassins shows up in a ninja suit
and a ski mask, and even though he has a chest wound and is
bleeding from the mouth, he calmly discusses his motives with Pitt
before swallowing a cyanide capsule _ a Saturday matinee touch if
we've ever seen one. The plot here is impossible to describe
because it's more a collection of parts than a cohesive whole.
Among the elements: a comet that crashed into the Earth 9,000 years
ago; a frozen ghost ship discovered near the South Pole in 1858; an
underground chamber with inscriptions on its walls and a black
skull on a pedestal; a Nazi U-boat that attacks Pitt's research
vessel; and a cameo appearance by Cussler himself (a Hitchcockian
tradition that he has added to his novels). We'll let you guess who
triumphs before the final credits roll.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
``WITH WILDER'' &QL; 
By Cameron Crowe (Knopf, $35) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is a wonderful book, not just for film buffs but for those
of us who believe in preserving the stories of people who have had
long and eventful lives. That's an understated description of
director Billy Wilder, of course, but it's the spirit in which this
volume was written. In 1995, Crowe, who had adapted his book ``Fast
Times at Ridgemont High'' for film and had written and directed
``Say Anything,'' approached Wilder and asked the 89-year-old
director to play a bit part in his next movie, ``Jerry Maguire.''
Wilder said no, even when Crowe came back with Tom Cruise, who
turned on the high beams and begged. Crowe wrote about Wilder's
rebuff for ``Rolling Stone.'' Wilder read and liked the story, and
he agreed to an interview with Crowe, a project that expanded to
become this book. In question-and-answer format, Wilder talks about
working with actors (Jack Lemmon, Gary Cooper, Audrey Hepburn,
Marilyn Monroe, Cary Grant, Barbara Stanwyck, Greta Garbo), his
films (``Some Like It Hot,'' ``The Apartment,'' ``Ace in the
Hole,'' ``Sunset Boulevard''), other directors and his big
inspiration, Ernst Lubitsch. There are anecdotes on every page, and
no pretense in sight. The interviews, conducted by Crowe with the
persistence of a journalist and the giddy curiosity of a fan, took
place over more than a year, ending in 1998, when Wilder was 91. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``A PASSION FOR BOOKS'' &QL; 
Edited by Harold Rabinowitz and Rob Kaplan (Times, $27.50) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an essay written in 1981, Anatole Broyard laments the fact
that his friends borrow his books because he has more than most
people, never mind that ``I feel about lending a book the way most
fathers feel about their daughters living with a man out of
wedlock.'' Robertson Davies writes about the idiosyncrasies of book
collecting. Anna Quindlen offers a list of ``The Ten Books One
Would Save in a Fire, If One Could Save Only Ten.'' John Updike
bemoans the gray fluff of book envelopes. Robert Benchley wonders
why no one collects his books (this was in 1934 _ things have
changed). Norman Mailer names his favorite American novels: not one
of them was written by him. This collection is for people who know
what Peter Hamill was talking about when he said this: ``There are
10,000 books in my library, and it will keep growing until I die.
This has exasperated my daughters, amused my friends, and baffled
my accountant. If I had not picked up this habit in the library
long ago, I would have more money in the bank today. I would not be
richer.'' &QL; 
You can reach Anne Stephenson at amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 1804EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4238 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-ANGELFALLS-TEX     11-29 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGELFALLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELA'S REMOTE ANGEL FALLS IS NATURE AT ITS MOST STIRRING
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by ANGEL FALLS-HOW TO and ANGEL FALLS-VENEZUELA) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REBECA RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANAIMA, Venezuela _ The steady hum of the DC-3 twin-engine
propellers lulled me into serenity, while outside, the bright July
sun reflected off the crystalline pools of water below.
</P>
<P>
   As I gazed out of the small, boxy window of a plane that had
flown during World War II, the anticipation began to grow. Here, in
southeastern Venezuela, was something different, something eternal.
</P>
<P>
   Angel Falls _ the world's tallest waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela, located on South America's northern coast, is the
continent's sixth-largest country in area and one of its
wealthiest. The capital, Caracas, is the undisputed political,
economic and cultural center of Venezuela. But the country also
reveals a host of landscapes, from tropical beaches and savannah to
dense jungles and the flat-topped tepui (pronounced ``te-poo-ee'')
mountains for which the country is famous.
</P>
<P>
   The single greatest tourist draw, however, is Angel Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Nestled deep in the recesses of Canaima National Park in the
Venezuelan state of Bolivar, the towering waterfall drops from a
height of 3,212 feet off the top of Auyantepui. Known in Venezuela
as ``El Salto Angel,'' the waterfall is 19 times the height of
Niagara Falls. The mighty cascade is named for Jimmie Angel, an
American pilot who landed on top of Auyantepui in 1937 while
searching for gold. Angel's four-seater plane got stuck on top of
the mountain and he, his wife and two companions had to trek for 11
days before finding another human being.
</P>
<P>
   One trip, and the reason becomes clear. Formed more than 130
million years ago, the tepuis are massive and shrouded in clouds,
with sheer drops that make navigation seem impossible. And the
dense surrounding jungle makes you feel as if you've tumbled back
in time to a prehistoric age. In fact, the soaring tepuis were the
inspiration for Sir Arthur Conan Doyle's 1912 novel ``The Lost
World.'' Nearly a century later, millions of tourists visit the
area annually.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to Angel Falls usually requires an experienced guide
from one of the area's many tour companies. Short excursions offer
an aerial view of the falls, on a plane that circles two or three
times a day. But seeing the falls by boat is a more visceral, if
more expensive, experience.
</P>
<P>
   Our trip began with a flight from the international airport near
Caracas to Canaima National Park in the southeastern part of the
country. As we stepped onto the dirt tarmac, an achingly beautiful
symphony of colors met our eyes: a lush landscape ripe with the
bluest skies, the greenest verdure and soil the color of shimmering
copper.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere, the sun-kissed faces of smiling Pemon Indians
welcomed our group of about a dozen people. The Pemon have lived in
the region for centuries and continue to thrive in the nationally
protected park. Many of them work as guides for tour companies,
making a living while sharing their traditional surroundings with
visitors from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty minutes later, our group was ushered onto a large truck
outfitted with benches. We bumped along dirt roads and splashed
through puddles, while large tree limbs brushed up against the
sides of the truck. We made a quick stop at a nearby lodge and then
got on another truck to ride to a clearing by the river.
</P>
<P>
   When we arrived, several Pemon set about unloading our bags and
wrapping them in large plastic trash bags to keep them dry. We each
strapped on a well-worn, orange life jacket and gingerly boarded
the boat, painted a bright shade of lime green.
</P>
<P>
   Once propelled by human muscle, the canoes _ long, flat and
carved from laurel trees _ are now equipped with outboard motors to
speed up the trip. Young Pemon train for years as apprentices
before they learn the rivers well enough to navigate them. But in
the capable hands of a well-trained captain, the boats slice easily
through the tea-colored waters of the Carrao and Churun rivers that
wind through the park. The coloration comes from natural elements
that seep into the water from the surrounding riverbed and shores.
</P>
<P>
   With a Pemon perched at both ends of the canoe, we set off.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the afternoon, we arrived at the camp that would be home
for the next two nights. After picking out a hammock, we ate dinner
_ a casserole of beef and noodles _ amid the din of foreign
tongues. Italian blended with German, Spanish commingled with
French, and English peppered the mix. Night fell, and the camp came
alive with laughter, card games and dominoes played by the feeble,
yellow light of hanging lanterns.
</P>
<P>
   We slumbered deeply that night, cocooned in cotton hammocks that
swayed with each slight movement. During the night, the sky opened
up and rains fell loudly on the pitched, corrugated tin roof.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, a rooster crowed urgently as the sun began its
daily dance across the sky. I arose and went down to the river.
There, in the soft blue light of dawn, a shy Pemon named Barsiano
was fishing from a boat, his line dropping directly from his hand
into the water, as generations of his ancestors had done. The
tea-colored waters, new and exotic for us, recall an ancient way of
life for the Pemon.
</P>
<P>
   Up at camp, the delicate clink of plates and the shuffling of
bare feet on the sodden floor signaled the beginning of a long day.
After breakfast, we were back on the boat for the two-hour ride to
the falls. We sped along, dodging rock outcroppings and swift
rapids, until we finally reached a clearing. We got off the boat,
stretched our legs and prepared for the next leg of the trip _ a
one-hour jaunt through dense, wet jungle.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the jungle, with its thick canopy and outlandish
vegetation, was like slipping through a door into another world.
Spindly vines dropped from enormous trees, gnarled roots threaded
through each other like large snakes, and giant, 3-foot leaves
lined the zigzag path to the falls. As we trudged through the moist
jungle, beads of perspiration began to form on my neck, and my wet
sneakers squished] with each footfall.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly an hour later, the roar of rushing water, always
perceptible, began to get louder. ``We're almost there,'' our guide
said. One more turn, and then all of a sudden, there it was.
</P>
<P>
   The thunderous, majestic power of Angel Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, something is so beautiful and divine it takes your
breath away. For several moments, I could do nothing but raise my
eyes and stare at the tremendous cascade of water pouring from atop
Auyantepui. It hurtled nearly two-thirds of a mile toward the
earth, crashing down upon the rocks with a might that sent mammoth
clouds of spray billowing up into the air.
</P>
<P>
   Another short walk placed us at the base of a smaller cascade
where the water's force had diminished. One by one, people stripped
down to their swimsuits. Bobbing in the chilly water, against a
backdrop of huge sky broken only by the tremendous tepui mountains,
I felt a part of something timeless. Water had gushed over this
plateau for eons, and in this place, with pilgrims from around the
globe, the minutiae of life quickly paled.
</P>
<P>
   Now, four months later and thousands of miles away, the memories
have begun to fade, and somehow the photos don't quite capture the
essence of the falls. But there is something comforting about
knowing it's still there, a pristine and untouchable cascade.
</P>
<P>
   Still the stuff of novels.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
