<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4243 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-ANGELFALLS-VENEZUELA-     11-29 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGELFALLS-VENEZUELA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUERTO LA CRUZ SPARKLES WITH WATER ACTIVITIES, NIGHTLIFE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies ANGEL FALLS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REBECA RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUERTO LA CRUZ, VENEZUELA _ The 2-foot lobster landed on the
deck of the boat with a resounding splat!
</P>
<P>
   Our guide and boat captain, Raul, had thrown the hard-shelled
creature over the edge of the craft and was swimming underwater
again in his shiny, black wetsuit, small harpoon in hand. I peered
over the edge of the boat and glimpsed him gliding through the
glittering water, tracking his next catch. Just then, my meager
fishing line quivered and I reeled in my own small dweller of the
deep.
</P>
<P>
   Deep-sea fishing is just one of the things awaiting the visitor
to Puerto la Cruz, on the northern coast of Venezuela. Located in
Anzoategui state, the area is a good jumping-off point for aquatic
sports and is only an hour's flight from the international airport
near Caracas.
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1930s, Puerto la Cruz wasn't much more than a sleepy
coastal village. But oil discovered to its south created a boom
that continues to feed tourism in the area. Although its population
is only 160,000, Puerto la Cruz has become the main gateway for the
hugely popular Margarita Island to the northeast. The island boasts
white-sand beaches, duty-free shopping and a vibrant nightlife. But
for those seeking more tranquillity and less tourism, Puerto la
Cruz is an attractive choice.
</P>
<P>
   The main esplanade, the Paseo Colon, stretches along the coast
for several blocks, offering restaurants, bars and a variety of
excursions.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela has more than 1,700 miles of coastline gazing onto the
Caribbean Sea, as well as more than 300 islands sprinkled off the
coast. Most of the islands surrounding Puerto La Cruz are located
within the boundaries of Mochima National Park. Some of the islands
are barren and rocky, but a large number have nice, quiet beaches
and a coral reef suitable for snorkeling.
</P>
<P>
   Island excursions are available at tourist offices along the
Paseo Colon and typically offer a daylong trip to two or more
islands, usually with lunch and drinks, for between $30 and $40.
You can also hook up directly with a water taxi. The process is
informal. You barter a price _ in our case about $15 _ and with the
right boat captain, you can usually squeeze in a few hours of
deep-sea fishing or scuba diving.
</P>
<P>
   Our trip began with a visit to El Faro, a small beach on an
island called Chimana Segunda. The waters of El Faro are clear, the
sand is white, and open-air thatched huts are available to store
belongings or to take a break from the fierce coastal sun. Large
iguanas roam the beach freely, cautiously eying tourists for a
moment, then lumbering away.
</P>
<P>
   After we had roasted on the beach for an hour, our boat captain
Raul offered to take us fishing. We hopped on board, sandy feet and
all, while he fired up the engine. We chugged off and within 10
minutes found a spot to his liking.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh squid awaited our hooks. There's nothing quite like the
tug of a fish on the end of your pole. And the scenery was
spectacular: The water's turquoise surface was broken only by sharp
rocks, with pelicans perched on their precipices.
</P>
<P>
   After a long day at sea, we returned to Puerto la Cruz, and the
place was ready for us.
</P>
<P>
   There's a cornucopia of restaurants _ offering Indian, Lebanese,
Italian, and American cuisine _ and lots of seafood. But no trip to
Venezuela would be complete without sitting down to the country's
national dish: pabellon criollo.
</P>
<P>
   The meal, found in many restaurants, consists of seasoned,
shredded beef, white rice, black beans sprinkled with cheese, and
tajada (fried plantain). If you're just looking for a snack, the
local areperas offer up a variety of arepas, small corn patties
that can be eaten plain or stuffed with anything from cheese to
octopus to avocado. After a big meal and a beer or two _ Polar and
Solera are two common domestic varieties _ the paseo beckons.
</P>
<P>
   The sinking sun shimmers across the Caribbean Sea, and lovers
stroll along the promenade; vendors lay out their glittering wares,
and the timbre of native music hangs in the air.
</P>
<P>
   You could get used to this.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
