<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4250 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      11-29 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Nov. 30, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Cold air will spill south through the Eastern states as a brisk
windflow from the north becomes established between strong high
pressure in the Middle West and a developing ocean storm off the
Atlantic seaboard. Farther west, rapid warming will develop from
the eastern Rockies to the Plains while a series of Pacific
disturbances keep the Northwest unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   Snow showers, though fewer than on Monday, will linger over the
interior Northeast, especially near the Great Lakes and northern
Appalachians. Most of the region will have a mixture of clouds and
sun with a stiff wind that will add to the chill of the day.
Farther east, the combination of a jet stream disturbance and moist
winds from the ocean will promote snow showers near the coast of
New England. Narrow bands of heavier snow squalls will brush Cape
Cod during the day. Tuesday night and Wednesday, the growing
offshore storm will cause an area of steadier, heavier snow to
expand toward the west, threatening extreme eastern New England
with several inches of accumulation.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine will be plentiful from the eastern slopes of the
Rockies through the Plains to the Southeastern states. After a
chilly morning, gusty winds from the southwest will cause readings
to surge into the 60s over most of the western Plains and eastern
Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Damp weather will linger in much of the Northwest. Showers will
be common near the coast and in many interior valleys. An area of
steadier rain will reach the northern California and Oregon coasts.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: A Season Ends
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Atlantic hurricane season that began on June 1 ends
Tuesday. Twelve tropical storms were named in the Atlantic and nine
became hurricanes. Five were classified as major hurricanes,
packing winds exceeding 110 mph. Although the official hurricane
season is over, an unusual tropical storm or hurricane churning
across the Atlantic in December will count toward the 1999 seasonal
total. Since 1871, only six storms have formed in December, the
last in 1984. The list of storm names is changed each year. The
2000 list, headed by Alberto, will be used beginning January 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
