<HEADER>
A4255 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS &LR;      11-29 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release TUESDAY AMs, November 30, 1999  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-CABINET (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Ten members of a
Protestant-Catholic Cabinet governing Northern Ireland are named,
with undercurrents of protest. By Kevin Cullen. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-FOREIGN (Malden, Mass.) _ Bill Bradley launches a
scathing attack on US policy toward Russia, charging that mistakes
made by President Clinton and Vice President Gore have alienated
the Russian people and created direct dangers to American security.
By Charles A. Radin. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRADLEY (Boston) _ Styling himself after a popular
Republican president, Bill Bradley says he is laying out his plans
in ``dangerous detail'' to win the mandate for change that Ronald
Reagan received when he took office. By Jill Zuckman. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-MARIJUANA (Undated) _ Scores of celebrities, health
officials and others join in protesting a new US policy for medical
marijuana research for lacking compassion and being ``too
cumbersome.'' By Dolores Kong. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTE-STUDY (Undated) _ Study confirms that federal
prosecutors usually seek civil fines, rather than criminal
prosecutions, in environmental pollution cases. Point was made in a
recent Globe series. By David Armstrong. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-SUMMIT (Seattle) _ The WTO's new global trade talks could
be one of the biggest protest events as well. WTO critics are
calling it the ``Battle in Seattle.'' By Lynda Gorov and Aaron
Zitner. 1200 words. (a, i and f coding)
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-MYANMAR (Boston) _ In a case that poses questions about
human rights and how much states can interefere with a nation's
foreign policy, the US Supreme Court will review a Massachusetts
law that limits government purchases from companies that do
business with Myanmar, formerly Burma. By Frank Phillips (f and i
coding)
</P>
<P>
   TV-LOCAL-DISH (Undated) _ Federal budget bill includes a
provision that could turn satellite dish TV into a fierce new
competitor for cable TV, particularly in urban areas. Move allows
dish companies to carry local channels for the first time. By Peter
Howe. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   NLRB-INTERNS (Undated) _ US interns win a major victory in a 3-2
NLRB decision requiring private teaching hospitals to recognize
labor unions. By Richard A. Knox. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   STAPLES-WEBAD (Undated) _ They don't know who did it yet, but
Staples has filed a ``John Doe'' suit against whoever hacked their
web page and replaced an ad there with one from competitor Office
Depot. By Shelley Murphy. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   ALTAVISTA-RAGINGBULL (Undated) _ Raging Bull, an online
investment community where users swap information, agrees to be
acquired by AltaVista Co. in a stock swap. By Ronald Rosenberg. 600
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOC-REVO-COACH (Foxborough, Mass.) _ Fernando Clavijo, assistant
coach of the worst team in MLS, is hired to coach the New England
Revolution. By Frank Dell'Apa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
