<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4270 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-VIEQUES-HNS &LR;      11-29 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VIEQUES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, PUERTO RICO CHIEF SAID TO BE NEAR PACT ON TARGET RANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro
Rossello are nearing an agreement that would allow the resumption
of limited Navy target practice on the Puerto Rican island of
Vieques, two senior Clinton administration officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said an
agreement between Puerto Rico and the Navy could be announced at
any time.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello, speaking in San Juan on Monday, said he expected
Clinton to announce a decision on a compromise in a matter of days.
Rossello called the discussions ``a dynamic situation, not a static
one,'' adding: ``There are different components that are constantly
moving.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House is pushing a compromise based upon a Pentagon
report calling for steep reductions in the Navy's live-fire combat
training on Vieques, the Navy's phased withdrawal over five years
and a substantial boost in economic development assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonso Aguilar, the governor's press secretary, said in a
telephone interview from San Juan that Rossello is speaking ``on a
daily basis'' with either the president or senior White House aides
in the final stages of discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't quantify how many conversations the president and the
governor have had,'' Aguilar said. The latest discussions follow
telephone conversation that Clinton and Rossello had before
Thanksgiving while the president was traveling in southern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello, a political ally of both the president and Vice
President Al Gore, told a news conference in San Juan on Monday
that he continues to oppose any resumption of bombing on the
52-square mile island located eight miles east of the main island
of Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that we want the bombing to end and the
Navy to leave Vieques,'' Rossello said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Navy and Marine Corps are pressing for an
immediate White House go-ahead to permit combat training on Vieques
by a battle group led by the aircraft carrier USS Dwight D.
Eisenhower. The force is scheduled to sail for the Persian Gulf on
Feb. 18. To meet that time schedule, the Navy wants to resume
training on Vieques by next week.
</P>
<P>
   The target range on Vieques, opened in 1941, has been closed
since April 19 when a Marine pilot mistakenly bombed a range
observation post, killing Navy contract security guard David Sanes
Rodriguez, 35, and injuring four other civilian range workers.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico's political leaders, backed by allies in Congress,
First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, Gore, former Sen. Bill Bradley
and influential Hispanic organizations, have demanded the permanent
end to live-fire training and the phased transfer of 22,000 acres
of Navy-owned land to Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy and Marine Corps contend that Vieques is the only
location where Atlantic-based forces can conduct final combat
rehearsals that combine simultaneous Marine amphibious landings
with Navy-Marine air support and gunfire from nearby warships.
</P>
<P>
   The island is home to more than 9,300 civilians, who live on a
swath land about 10 miles from the bombing range.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials have forged backup plans to complete final combat
training for carrier-based attack aircraft with live-fire bombing
on two military target ranges in Florida and non-explosive inert
naval gunfire by surface warships against the target range on
Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Marines would rehearse their amphibious mission at Camp Lejeune,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen, in an interview with the
American Forces Press Service published Monday, called the dispute
over the target range on Vieques ``a difficult political issue,''
adding that ``we've got to overcome the political opposition'' in
Puerto Rico to continued military training on Vieques. It would be
irresponsible for the Pentagon to send forces into combat with
inadequate combat training, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Any resumption of combat training on Vieques could be
complicated by several dozen protesters camped on the 899-acre
target area since last spring to block any resumption of shelling.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico police superintendent Pedro Toledo said Sunday that
Puerto Rico's law enforcement agencies will not participate in any
round-up of civilian protesters encamped on federal land. ``The
areas under federal jurisdiction are going to be the concern of the
federal authorities,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Licatovich, a spokesman of the U.S. Marshals Service, said
that agents from the Justice Department agency would be used to
process anyone arrested on the Navy-owned property. But Licatovich
declined to discuss any plans to arrest the protestors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
