<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4271 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AMERICAN-VILLAGE-COX     11-29 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-VILLAGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'American Village' an experience in history
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTEVALLO, Ala. _ A replica of George Washington's Mount Vernon
comes to life in rolling cow pastures south of Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   Part classroom, part theater, the American Village _ a $4.5
million re-creation of a colonial town _ opens today.
</P>
<P>
   Gravel walkways crunch under the footfalls of Benjamin Franklin
and Thomas Jefferson. Airy music from a fife sweetens the air.
</P>
<P>
   In an open field, white A-frame tents illustrate Washington's
gloomy encampment at Valley Forge. A post office, print shop and
trade shop sit down the lane.
</P>
<P>
   During today's grand opening, Gov. Don Siegelman will dedicate
the facility, as will a faux Washington who will enter on a
galloping white steed.
</P>
<P>
   Around those props, costumed actors will teach the foundation of
American citizenship to Alabama's 5th- through 12th-graders.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, what we have here is a stage,'' said Thomas
Walker, who thought up the idea of bringing Mount Vernon to
Alabama. ``The drama of American self-government can be played out
from Concord Bridge to the march across the Edmund Pettus Bridge in
Selma.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, a former officer for the state PTA, decided Mount Vernon
was the best model to show students how the nation's government was
born.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main mission is teaching citizenship,'' said Walker.
</P>
<P>
   The 46-year-old directs the state-chartered Citizenship Trust,
which conducts mock elections in Alabama schools. Through a $3.9
million county bond issue, a county lodging tax and donations, the
group built the colonial classroom on a 113-acre site.
</P>
<P>
   Lessons of the revolution will be woven with topics taught in
Alabama classrooms. The state Legislature approved $300,000 to
develop historical vignettes for the village.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 50,000 students are projected to visit the first year.
Marketers eventually hope to cultivate a market throughout the
Southeast. Admission is $5.
</P>
<P>
   Students will become delegates at the first Constitutional
Convention in 1787; they'll debate cases in a courtroom inspired by
1770s Williamsburg; they'll vote on issues of the day; they'll sign
legislation in a replica of the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington said the sacred flame of liberty was entrusted to
the hands of the American people,'' Walker said. ``What we're
trying to do is show we're stewards in everyday life of that sacred
flame.''
</P>
<P>
   On Alabama land where black Angus cattle once roamed,
Revolutionary War solider Joseph Plumb Martin declared battle.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin wasn't engaging British redcoats of the 1770s.
Instead, the historical figure played by Christopher Long of
Birmingham took aim at what he said was an ever-present enemy in
today's government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soldiers went into battle and the musket _ the British Brown
Bess _ was their enemy,'' said Long, costumed in three-cornered hat
and white vest. ``Today, the fight is not for freedom but against
apathy.''
</P>
<P>
   American Village
</P>
<P>
   What: Grand opening of colonial village based on George
Washington's Mount Vernon.
</P>
<P>
   When: 11 a.m. EST
</P>
<P>
   Where: Montevello, Ala., about 30 minutes south of Birmingham
off I-65.
</P>
<P>
   Purpose: To educate students on the foundation of American
government.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: Telephone _ 205-665-6006. World Wide Web:
www.americanvillage.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
