<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4272 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BLACKS-AIDS-COX     11-29 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-AIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surgeon General looks to black schools for help in AIDS
education
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the AIDS epidemic gets worse in the black
community, Surgeon General David Satcher plans to call on
predominantly black medical schools to help spread information
about the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Satcher will lead a national satellite conference today from
Atlanta to address the devastating impact of the HIV/AIDS epidemic
in the black community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to enlist the support of historically black medical
schools to helps us get the message out about the magnitude of this
epidemic,'' Satcher said. ``We must use every means available to
educate, motivate and mobilize communities to fight HIV and AIDS.
The HIV and AIDS epidemic is a national problem, but an effective
response must occur at community and individual levels.''
</P>
<P>
   The Morehouse School of Medicine will host the simulcast from
the campus of Spelman College.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Morehouse, Satcher's teleconference also will address
Meharry Medical School in Nashville and the Howard University
College of Medicine in Washington, D.C. The schools are the
country's only three historically black medical schools.
</P>
<P>
   Satcher also will address the Charles R. Drew University of
Medicine and Science in Los Angeles; and Tuskegee University in
Tuskegee, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   In each location, a community-based AIDS service organization
that provides care to African-Americans living with HIV or AIDS
will co-host the event. Outreach Inc., will serve as the local
co-host.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel it is a most important step for the Surgeon General to
conduct this teleconference to inform the nation that the rates of
infection continues to increase in the African-American
community,'' said Sandra McDonald, founder and president of
Outreach. ``To hear this message come from the highest office in
the country is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   AIDS is now the leading cause of death among black men between
the ages of 25 and 44, and the second-leading cause of death among
black women in that age group.
</P>
<P>
   Satcher said that even though the overall death rate from AIDS
is falling, the rate of infection among blacks is growing. Blacks
make up only 13 percent of the nation's population, but accounted
for 49 percent of the AIDS deaths last year and 48 percent of the
new AIDS cases reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``This started out as a predominantly white gay male disease,
but that has changed,'' said Satcher.``I hope that the black
community is beginning to get the message.''
</P>
<P>
   Satcher said he hopes that the medical schools are able help
motivate people into changing their sexual and social habits,
adding that 40 percent of the new AIDS cases developed from drug
use.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also means talking about abstinence. Relationships should
not begin with sex,'' Satcher said. ``And we are also trying to
convince people to get tested. The earlier you are diagnosed, the
better.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald said there are thousand of people in the black
community with HIV or AIDS who for some reason -- like
embarrassment, fear of doctors or the high cost of medicine -- are
not getting treatment. He estimates that another 250,000 Americans
don't even know they have the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger with that is they could be spreading it,'' Satcher
said.
</P>
<P>
   While there is still no cure for AIDS, Satcher said new drugs
are able to suppress the virus and prolong life.
</P>
<P>
   ``What used to be a death sentence, we can prolong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Satcher's teleconference will begin at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Suggs writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
