u a BC-CUBA-CHILD-NYT &LR;      11-29 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-CHILD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER OF BOY RESCUED FROM CAPSIZED BOAT WANTS HIM RETURNED TO
CUBA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The father of a 5-year-old Cuban boy who drifted in the
Atlantic Ocean for two days on an inner tube before he was rescued
on Thanksgiving Day has enlisted the aid of the Cuban government in
seeking his child's custody.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports from Havana, Elian Gonzalez's father, Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, and Cuban government officials have lodged
complaints with American diplomats in Havana accusing Elian's
mother of kidnapping the boy. The mother was among 13 people who
had packed themselves into a 17-foot aluminum boat in an attempt to
flee Cuba. She is believed to have died along with nine others when
their vessel broke apart during the 90-mile journey.
</P>
<P>
   While immigration lawyers said that surviving parents are
normally awarded custody of their children, this case has been
complicated by the tensions surrounding U.S. relations with Cuba.
For now, Elian is staying in Miami with relatives of his father
until immigration authorities hold a hearing on his case next
month.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives said that Gonzalez, who they said worked as a doorman
at a tourist hotel in the resort town of Varadero, had originally
agreed to let Elian stay in Miami. But during a Cuban news program
last night, Gonzalez was reported to have said that he did not give
permission for his child to be taken away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the United States is such a country of human rights, they
should return my child,'' he said during the broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Sunday, the Cuban Foreign Ministry said
it had begun to draft documents to obtain the child's return. The
ministry also blamed the United States for what it called stupid
immigration policies under the Cuban Adjustment Act that grant
asylum to refugees who step foot on U.S. soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is on the government of the United States that the
responsibility falls entirely for these new and painful deaths of
Cuban citizens,'' the statement said. ``Because of the unreasonable
way in which that country promotes, stimulates and rewards illegal
immigration.''
</P>
<P>
   James Rubin, a State Department spokesman, refuted the Cuban
accusations Monday, saying that the American government did not
condone illegal immigration from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is reprehensible that anyone would suggest the U.S. is
responsible in any way for these tragic deaths,'' Rubin said. ``We
stay strong in our commitment to encourage safe, legal and orderly
migration and urge individuals in Cuba to refrain from attempting
to migrate illegally.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Associated Press, Gonzalez said he
would be willing to go to the United States to claim his son.
Spencer Eig, a lawyer representing Elian, hoped he would come to
the United States, although for other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``After what Elian has been through, the last thing he needs is
more conflict,'' Eig said. ``We are hoping the United States
government takes a humanitarian approach and allows the boy to stay
as a Cuban refugee. I also think it would be helpful if they make
it possible for his father to visit him here. He would see how
wonderfully his son is adjusting to life.''
</P>
<P>
   He would also see how his son has become a symbol beyond a mere
custody fight.
</P>
<P>
   Elian has literally become a poster boy for the Cuban American
National Foundation, the influential exile lobbying group. The
foundation has printed 4,000 posters that feature a picture of
Elian under the caption: ``Another Child Victim of Fidel Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   Eig elevated Elian to the status of a millennial icon. ``He is a
heroic boy,'' he said. ``He is perhaps the last hero in the 20th
century battle against totalitarianism.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   David Abraham, a professor of immigration law at the University
of Miami, said the politically and emotionally charged themes
swirling around the custody case could obscure the basic issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is sad, because the Cuban American National Foundation is
using this boy as a poster child of immigration to demonstrate the
tyranny of the Cuban regime,'' he said. ``They're saying it's
forcing even 5- year-olds to leave the country, but he is a
personal victim of these tragedies,'' Abraham said. ``He lost a
parent and now he's in a situation because his father is still in
Cuba. These tragedies are the result of the failure of both
countries to regulate immigration normally.''
</P>
<P>
   The failure to do so, combined with Cuban unhappiness over the
island's economic and political climate, have also led to an
increase in rafters attempting to enter the United States, where
they are usually granted asylum.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   A Coast Guard spokesman said that 1,265 Cuban immigrants were
picked up this year, doubling last year's total.
</P>
<P>
   Max Castro, a senior research associate at the North-South
Center at the University of Miami, said the refugee flow was
spurred by a belief among the would-be refugees that there was
little change they could expect from the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of rebelling against the government is not something
they believe in or can see,'' he said. ``They do not see that as
something imminent. So what do they do? As perilous as it is, the
softest wall in this equation is the wall of the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that both the Cuban government and the United States
could take measures to allow for easier immigration and improved
economic chances for the Cuban people.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the players could do things to ease the situation,'' he
said. ``But it is at an impasse and the people are getting crushed.
What they look at for as a best option, at least some people, will
lead inevitably to more tragedies like this. But nobody wants to
say uncle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
