<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOMMERCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For E-tailers, shopping season already a success
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Only five days into the official holiday shopping
season and online retailers are already reporting record numbers of
shoppers and dwindling supplies of the season's hottest gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping products in stock and providing customer service to
millions of first-time Web shoppers is an uphill battle for
retailers that not every e-commerce site will be able to win in the
war for the $6 to $8 billion consumers are expected to spend online
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holiday shopping will not be problem free, but it does beat
the mall,'' says Jupiter Communications analyst David Schatsky.
``Some sites like JCrew and Toys 'R Us spent a lot of money getting
their houses in order,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Schatsky says the hordes of online shoppers means an increased
number both people accessing the sites and increased orders, which
means the potential for technology failures and shipping foul-ups
are a lot higher than they were last year. He says the biggest
problems consumers are likely to see will be in order delivery not
in accessing the the sites themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Schatsky's predictions are already evident on several
retailing sites. Several e-tailers have already run out of some of
this season's top-selling items. The Toys 'R Us Web site already
has a caveat on its homepage warning holiday shoppers that many
items advertised on the site might not be available. Many sites
have also run out of Pokemon, the hot Nintendo game and trading
card phenomena, items.
</P>
<P>
   Toy stores running out of toys isn't unusual online or offline
at Christmas, but Bluefly.com, an discount online clothing store
has already run through its stock of trendy pashmina shawls.
Pashmina is a combination of cashmere blended with silk.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bluefly founder and CEO Ken Seiff says that running out
of hot items is the nature of his business. ``We are an off-price
retailer.'' We sell last of season products from 250 designers at
up to 75 per cent off. Sometimes, you get a very limited quantity
of great products. So we sell out of products very frequently and
are continually replenishing with new items.''
</P>
<P>
   Bluefly's pashmina wraps were selling for $79, much lower than
retail prices of $200 to 400. Seiff says because of the item's
popularity Bluefly opted not to replace it and expects it to be
back in stock late next week.
</P>
<P>
   Even while struggling with sold-out pashmina, Seiff says
business is up 700 per cent over the Friday, Saturday and Sunday
following Thanksgiving Day last year. Like most of online
retailers, Seiff says everything this holiday season depends on
state-of-the-art technology and customer service. ``We upgraded our
hardware and customer service two weeks ago,'' he says. ``We
wouldn't have made it out of the weekend and held up under the
traffic without it.''
</P>
<P>
   Traffic and spending was up at almost every online retailer.
Portal site Yahoo said transaction volume in its shopping and
auction area was up more than 400 per cent Friday from the same day
last year. Yahoo also said that in the 10 days preceding the
so-called ``Black Friday'' Yahoo shopping processed more orders
than during the entire 1998 holiday season. The most requested
items were Pokemon toys, cards and games for kids.
</P>
<P>
   America Online reports that spending over the Thanksgiving
weekend nearly tripled over last year and the number of shoppers
using AOL was 2.5 times higher than last year. Spokeswoman Wendy
Goldberg says AOL shoppers are buying toys, apparel, flowers and
sporting goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``People this year are expecting more from online shopping,''
says Goldberg. ``It's out of the experimental phase. They want
great customer service, great tools like search and
personalization. They also want great graphics so they know what
they are buying.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
