A4284 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELTA-UNION-COX     11-29 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-UNION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta union members, management ratify agreement
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pilots at Delta Air Lines ratified a pay agreement
covering two new aircraft types, enabling the Atlanta-based carrier
to proceed with purchase plans.
</P>
<P>
   The accord sets pay rates for the Boeing 777 and 767-400
widebodies, both of which are key to Delta's effort to upgrade its
fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Ratification of the pact, reached by pilot union and management
negotiators in September, means Delta will resume 777 purchases
after deferring nearly a dozen orders last summer amid a stalemate
in pay talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to talk to Boeing in the next few days about
rescheduling the orders,'' spokesman John Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta got its first two 777s in March but then delayed further
purchases, citing pilot union threats to ground the planes without
a ratified pay agreement by this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The two-engine 777 is a highly-efficient international jet
already flown by several of Delta's trans-Atlantic rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The 767-400 is a new, stretched version of the existing 767 and
will be used by Delta to replace aging L-1011s on high-volume
domestic routes. The first plane is set for delivery in May 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The pay pact passed with 63.4 percent of the rank-and-file vote,
the Air Line Pilots Association said. About 96 percent of Delta's
9,200 pilots voted, the union said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an all-time record for us,'' said Charles Giambusso,
chairman of Delta's ALPA unit. ``It certainly indicates our pilots
are extremely engaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Some pilots who voted against the pact felt it would dilute the
union's leverage in new contract talks that started in September.
</P>
<P>
   Those talks are still in preliminary stages, with both sides
hoping for an agreement by May 2000, when the pilots' existing
four-year contract becomes amendable.
</P>
<P>
   Under the interim accord for the two new planes, 777 captains
will get base pay of $250 an hour, or about $225,000 a year,
retroactive to May 1. The rate will increase to $265 an hour, or
about $238,500 a year, on Jan. 1, when 6 percent profit sharing is
converted to salary for all Delta pilots. Captains of 767-400s will
get $243.80 an hour, or $219,420 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The pact also includes a 3 percent raise for pilots of most
other planes in Delta's fleet, and it eliminates the lower
``B-scale'' pay schedule for junior pilots. Those elements were
pot-sweeteners by the company to break last summer's logjam.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
