<HEADLINE>
DOWNLOAD, RIP AND PLAY WITH MP3 FILES
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   About a year ago, a friend of mine brought over a CD, put it in
the CD player, and we listened to songs. There were 16 cuts on the
disc, with music by top-name country stars, light opera and jazz,
all playing clearly and crisply.
</P>
<P>
   Where did he buy this eclectic music collection?
</P>
<P>
   There is no such CD for sale. ``The amazing part of it,'' he
added, ``is that I don't own one of those albums with those songs
on it. I downloaded them all from the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   I have a collection of old-time radio shows _ the Great
Gildersleeve, Amos 'n' Andy, the Shadow, Lum and Abner, Jack Benny
_ all downloaded from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   These little stories give recording-company executives apoplexy.
And at the same time, those executives salivate at the thought of
an easy, cheap way to market, distribute and sell music over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The format used is MP3, industry shorthand for ``Moving Picture
Experts Group audio player 3.'' It's a compression system, used to
slim down audio files so they may be transmitted quickly without
loss of quality when expanded back to their original form.
</P>
<P>
   For the listener, the format means new artists who can never
seem to get accepted by record labels but turn out to be big hits
with the public, can gain exposure for their music on their own Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   A typical 3-minute song, for instance, takes up about 30
megabytes of disk space. Compressed into MP3 format, the file is
about 3 megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   The file can be played by an MP3 player (WinAmp is a popular one
on the Internet, available from www.winamp.com) on a computer.
</P>
<P>
   It can be transferred to a CD, but CD players can't recognize
the MP3 format. (However, there are some CD players now being
produced that can decompress MP3 files on the fly and play them.
The advantage: A CD, instead of holding 60 minutes of music, can
now hold about 150 to 200 songs.) There are serious legal issues
with posting copyrighted songs on the Internet, but that hasn't
stopped every cut from recently released CDs from showing up in MP3
format soon after the CD's release in stores (and in many cases,
even before). But there are many aspects of MP3 use that are
perfectly legal.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder, then, that MP3 is the second-most frequently used
search word on most search engines. (In case you wonder, ``sex'' is
in the lead.) ``I Want My MP3!: How to Download, Rip &AMP; Play Digital
Music'' by Bill Mann (McGraw-Hill; $19.99) gives a complete
overview of MP3. The 374-page book also comes with a CD-ROM that
contains all the software covered in the book, including the
Sonique stand-alone player (one of the popular ones available) and
a collection of MP3 fills.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the press release says, I had MP3 up and running on the
computer in less than 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It provides information on installing and setting up players,
using programs that do ripping (taking tracks from CDs and
converting them to MP3), and gives types on utilities for working
with MP3 files.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites suggested in the book include: www.mp3.com;
www.musicmatch.com; www.rollingstone.tunes.com; www.listen.com.
</P>
<P>
   For information on the book: www.osborne.com/iwantmymp3
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
