<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ENGLAND-ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANCHESTER DOCKLANDS GET SPIFFYNEW LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Dec. 5) 
(mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, England _ Ask just about anyone here what he
associates most with the paintings of L.S. Lowry and he'll probably
talk _ with misty nostalgia or utter relief _ of the passing of the
industrial north of England depicted in Lowry's spare cityscapes,
where stick-figure people are dwarfed by the smokestacks and
viaducts.
</P>
<P>
   So there is quite a delicious irony in the glittery $200 million
project named for the artist that is rising on what used to be the
drear and depressing docklands of the Salford district where Lowry
lived all his life _ the very emblem of the urban regeneration that
has, in recent years, devoured the last vestiges of his Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   Called simply the Lowry, this complex of theaters, galleries and
spaces, with its attendant cinemas and shopping, is set to open
April 28 and has been earmarked by the British government _ by the
National Landmark Millennium Project for the Arts _ as a flagship
arts project of the millennium year, financed to the tune of $100
million by Britain's National Lottery. Private investors, city
authorities and the European Union are providing the rest of the
money.
</P>
<P>
   Here, on Pier 9 of what used to be Britain's third busiest
docks, the Salford authorities hope visitors will be enticed by
what is said to be the world's greatest Lowry collection _ an
assemblage of over 330 works that the city has been squirreling
away for years.
</P>
<P>
   Two theaters for dance, drama and music _ one for 1,730 people _
will flank two more galleries, and a plaza will provide space for
up to 10,000 at outdoor performances. The opening program includes
the Paris Opera Ballet performing Rudolf Nureyev's ``Bayadere''
from May 4 to 7, and a South African dance extravaganza called
``Gumboots'' from May 22 to 27. Tickets can be ordered from
(44-161) 876-2000.
</P>
<P>
   A commercial complex of shops, a hotel and movie theaters will
be similar to an American mall. A separate building is to house
what is called the Digital World Center, a showcase for
technological advance and research. Nearby a footbridge shaped like
a dinosaur's spine will lead to a projected Imperial War Museum for
the North, complementing the existing Imperial War Museum in
London, and, not so incongruously in this eclectic blend of
offerings, to the Old Trafford soccer stadium of Manchester United.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is nothing new about the conversion of old
British docklands into landmarks for the late 20th century, some
closely tied to the turn of the millennium. The phenomenon is
already familiar in east London with the high-rises of Canary Wharf
and the Millennium Dome. But for anyone who knew Salford in the
past _ as a stubborn blight of row houses akin to the toughest
areas of the old Bowery in New York _ the project is more than the
sum of its parts.
</P>
<P>
   There are still some people who consider Salford a kind of no-go
area, said Michelle Bowey, spokeswoman for the Lowry, ``but the
regeneration of Salford Quays is well advanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the modernization of Manchester's docklands says
something about the forces that have reshaped northern England
since William Blake wrote of the ``dark Satanic mills'' of
industrial Britain in the early 19th century, or even since
Britain's oldest television soap opera, ``Coronation Street,''
first turned Salford's gritty working-class life into the stuff of
drama more than 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that history has its roots in the Victorian era, when
rapid industrialization spurred expansion of the empire. The
Manchester Ship Canal, of which Salford is the inland destination,
brought cotton from the colonies for the textile mills that
provided Lawrence Stephen Lowry (1887-1976) with the inspiration to
find a cohesion and lyric beauty as well as a sense of isolation in
the early-20th-century industrial landscape. The works for which he
is best known were done between 1905 and 1925.
</P>
<P>
   Textiles enriched the barons of industry but did little for the
growing industrial proletariat. The crude capitalism of the era
threw up the boxlike workers' row houses where Lowry's stick
figures lived. Railroads rattled across viaducts, belching smoke _
another familiar image from a body of work that extends to
minimalist seascapes and bright depictions of yachting.
</P>
<P>
   In postwar Britain, though, the decline was already well
established. Areas like Salford came to represent the mean streets
of Greater Manchester from which Salford now seeks to distance
itself with the Lowry.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s Salford's docks, opened by Queen Victoria in 1894,
had become a wasteland of dereliction. In 1982 they closed forever
to shipping. And as services gradually replaced industry as the
northwest's newest source of wealth, so, too, did Salford's docks
become a target for gentrification. Restaurants, bars and lofts
replaced Lowry's industrial vistas.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not such a break with the past as it might seem.
Lowry's paintings imposed a vision on a grim and gloomy urban
sprawl. Today's urban planners are trying to do the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
