<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIME MINISTER IS RE-ELECTED IN MALAYSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ Malaysia's fledgling reform movement
made few inroads Monday in a parliamentary election that returned
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad to power after a campaign that
stressed stability and economic well-being.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the hardest-fought elections in recent years, the
governing National Front won 149 seats, well exceeding its goal of
maintaining a two-thirds majority in the 193-member Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Though a coalition of opposition parties did reduce the National
Front's seats from 162, most of the opposition seats went to a
popular Islamic party rather than to the democratic reform party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the National Front is still the party of choice of
the peoples of Malaysia,'' said Mahathir, 73, who has been given a
new five-year mandate after 18 years as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   But in a televised victory speech at 3 a.m. Tuesday, he
acknowledged a setback that dented his standing in the country's
Malay heartland and could cause him trouble within his own
Malay-based party, known as Umno. His backing among the ethnic
Chinese and Indian minorities remained strong.
</P>
<P>
   After a fierce campaign in which each side charged the other
with dirty tricks, the Islamic opposition party, Pas, expanded its
control from one to two northern state assemblies, out of 11 that
were contested nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keadilan has lost, and lost big,'' said William Case, an
expert on Malaysian politics, referring to the new reformist party
that was formed in protest against the jailing last September of
Mahathir's chief political rival, Anwar Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   The firing and trial of Anwar, who had been deputy prime
minister, touched off demonstrations and inspired a reform movement
that attempted to emulate the groundswell that toppled Indonesia's
former president, Suharto, in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that can be read into this result is that
not very much has changed after all,'' said Case, who teaches at
Griffith University in Brisbane, Australia. ``It is possible to
paint a picture of real continuity to the years prior to the whole
fallout over Anwar.''
</P>
<P>
   That continuity, he said, placed Malaysia's political cleavage
between the secular Umno and the Islamist Pas. ``And in that fault
line Keadilan _ progressive and democratic _ has slipped right
through the crack,'' Case said.
</P>
<P>
   But the strength of the Islamic party, Pas, which formed a
temporary and ill-fitting tactical alliance with supporters of
Anwar, posed a new problem for Mahathir.
</P>
<P>
   Pas' repeat victory in the state assembly of Kelantan and the
extension of its control to the state of Terengganu opened the
possibility of a backlash against Mahathir within his own party.
</P>
<P>
   The political action now moves to Umno's party congress next
year. But with Anwar, who had been Mahathir's heir apparent, now
out of politics, the party does not appear for now to have a
credible challenger to his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The current political drama began in mid-1998 when Anwar
appeared to be preparing the ground for a challenge to Mahathir. In
response, Mahathir fired him, then had him put on trial in the most
lurid political drama Malaysia has seen in years.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar has since been sentenced to a six-year prison term for
corruption and a second trial has begun on charges of sexual
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   In the opposition's biggest symbolic victory Monday, his wife,
Wan Aziza Wan Ismail, won one of the few seats to be taken by the
party she founded, Keadilan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy yet sad because I wish my husband were
around,'' she said. ``I have called the prison tonight to tell my
husband of our victory but the prison said it was already too late.
First thing tomorrow I will convey the good news to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked Tuesday morning if he found her victory significant,
Mahathir displayed some of the animosity that has emerged in his
comments about his former protege.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a lot of sympathy when you go around with
your child and cry,'' he said. ``It pulls at the heartstrings of
people. The question is whether she can contribute anything at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Other opposition heavyweights, both in Keadilan and in a vocal
ethnic Chinese opposition party, lost their parliamentary races.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Mahathir's animosity has also been directed at the
foreign press, which has at times lionized Anwar. At the victory
celebration, a member of the crowd called out to the prime
minister, ``I want you to tell the foreign press not to write
anything bad about us anymore!''
</P>
<P>
   Still smiling his victory smile, Mahathir took the bait.
``That's freedom of the press,'' he said, ``to write or not to
write or to tell lies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
