<SLUG> BC-THEATER-CALISTA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALISTA FLOCKHART AND CO. SHINE IN `BASH'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: lower case in ``bash, latter day plays'' is cq. Fact box at
bottom.) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Odd thing about tragedy: It sometimes can be appallingly funny.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, ``A Gaggle of Saints,'' the final one-act
presented in ``bash, latter day plays,'' Neil LaBute's
pre-millennial post-mortem on contemporary American morality.
</P>
<P>
   In this torturously tense, sharply written vignette, which takes
a vicious left turn about midway through, Calista Flockhart and
Paul Rudd play Boston College sweethearts who've returned for the
weekend to their New York home for a big formal party at the Plaza
Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   As the story moves forward and back through dueling monologues,
Sue (Flockhart) tells us how her boyfriend John (Rudd) accidentally
pricked himself with a needle while pinning on her corsage. The
sight of John's blood excited her, Sue confesses, as she lets out a
strange, hysterical giggle that causes some in the audience to
giggle nervously, too.
</P>
<P>
   That Sue's bizarre, vaguely comic anecdote should prefigure a
much uglier and bloodier incident, involving a pair of gay men
unlucky enough to be in Central Park at the wrong time of night, is
indicative of LaBute's chilling ability to conceal big, nasty
surprises in pretty packages. It's hardly coincidental that Sue is
being played by the actress known as America's prime-time
heartthrob, Ally McBeal, in what amounts to a brutal rebuttal of
prefabricated pop-culture expectations (although Rudd's crafty,
cockeyed performance is the one worth watching here).
</P>
<P>
   It's probably fair to say that ``bash,'' which opened a limited
run Sunday night at the Canon Theatre in Beverly Hills, won't
provoke many mixed reactions. As with LaBute's two highly praised
feature films, ``In the Company of Men'' and ``Your Friends and
Neighbors,'' this theatrical triptych is unsparing in its evocation
of the casual viciousness of modern-day life, especially as
practiced by the male half of the species.
</P>
<P>
   While some viewers have taken that viewpoint as evidence of the
author's misogyny, or worse, what finally stands out from these
cold-blooded parables is an unflinching, if savagely ironic
humanism, which is offset by the kind of cryptic fatalism you'd
expect from a Greek oracle.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly unrelated at first, the three one-acts jostle each
other in disconcerting ways. Like a Polaroid slowly materializing,
the nebulous trio of narratives gradually takes on sharper coloring
and resolution.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening monologue, ``Medea Redux,'' Flockhart (in the
stronger of her two appearances) portrays a young, blue-collar
Midwestern woman testifying about a love affair gone horribly wrong
with her former junior high school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting alone at a table with only a tape recorder and a glass
of water, harshly lit by an overhead lamp (James Vermeulen supplies
the ominous lighting design), she recounts the disturbing details
of the romance to a group of unseen interrogators whose responses
can only be inferred.
</P>
<P>
   Dragging on cigarettes and dropping her ``g's,'' Flockhart
convinces us of her character's mix of naivete and knowingness,
innocence and calculation, just as the playlet itself skillfully
situates a modern tabloid-style subject within the highbrow
literary context of Euripidean blood-lust (as its title suggests).
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, classical Greek ideas about fate, and whatever gods
still exist, surface throughout this otherwise very late-'90s
drama. In the middle vignette, ``Iphigenia in Orem,'' a blandly
likable Utah traveling salesman (played by Ron Eldard with
disarmingly creepy candor) admits to a horrifying deed while
pondering its cosmic significance in, of all places, a Las Vegas
hotel room. When he momentarily loses his story line and tells his
(again, unseen) confessor that, ``I have gotten off the path
somehow,'' he fingers the deeper sense of moral dislocation that
hovers over the play like a brooding deity.
</P>
<P>
   Like Scott Pask's starkly metaphorical set design, LaBute's
writing is straightforward but allusive, edged with references to
corporate mergers, sharks, Mormonism, childhood, Hollywood movies
and so on. If his style occasionally feels heavy-handed, Joe
Mantello's sensitive, hyperbole-free direction keeps the
production's focus on its three engaging young actors.
</P>
<P>
   Though the actions they speak of are supremely ugly, ``bash'' as
a whole exhibits a startling beauty, hard and cold to the touch,
yet packed with a warming truth. &QL; 
____ &UR;  &QL; 
What: &LR;  ``bash, latter day plays'' &UR;  &QL; 
Where: &LR;  Canon Theatre, 205 N. Canon Drive, Beverly Hills. &UR;  &QL; 
When: &LR;  Through Dec. 19. Performances at 3 and 8 p.m. Saturdays, 3
and 7 p.m. Sundays. &UR;  &QL; 
Tickets: &LR;  $60 to $75. Call (310) 859-2830. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;  3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
