<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-CABINET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER COALITION CABINET NAMED, AMID HISSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ When Martin McGuinness was nominated
Monday to be the Cabinet minister in charge of education in
Northern Ireland's new government, there was a sharp intake of
breath in the august chamber at Stormont, and Sammy Wilson looked
like he was about to keel over.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, a schoolteacher, and his Democratic Unionist colleagues
had just spent the better part of three hours inside the reconvened
Northern Ireland Assembly denouncing McGuinness and other members
of Sinn Fein as a bunch of murderers unfit for public office.
</P>
<P>
   But at 5:45 p.m., local time, Martin McGuinness, a former leader
of the Irish Republican Army, became Sammy Wilson's boss.
</P>
<P>
   The gasps from Wilson's corner were quickly followed by hisses,
and John Alderdice, the assembly's moderator, threatened to clear
the house.
</P>
<P>
   McGuinness, Sinn Fein's chief negotiator who has spent a decade
persuading the IRA to let politics take over in their campaign for
a united Ireland, ignored the hecklers, taking his pledge of office
in Irish, then English, and yet another milestone in the peace
process had been passed.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's nomination of the 10 Cabinet ministers who will
administer the first power-sharing government to include all shades
of opinion in Northern Ireland was the first step in a weeklong
process of returning political power here since 1972, at the height
of the violence that has killed some 3,500 people since 1969.
Britain has ruled directly from London since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday the British Parliament will begin the legislative
process that is expected to see power devolved to Northern Ireland
by Thursday. On that day, the IRA is expected to designate a
representative to discuss disarming with an international group
headed up by a retired Canadian army general.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's meeting of the 108-member assembly was its first since
July 15, when it was suspended amid scenes of farce. Four months
ago, McGuinness was nominated as minister for agriculture, leading
Wilson and others in the Democratic Unionist party led by the
fundamentalist preacher Rev. Ian Paisley to yell that McGuinness
knew a lot about fertilizer _ a less than subtle reference to the
IRA's practice of using fertilizer for some of its bombs.
</P>
<P>
   But those nominations were declared null and void after just 15
minutes, and the assembly suspended, when the largest party, the
Ulster Unionists, refused to take part in the process. The Ulster
Unionists, who represent most Protestants in Northern Ireland,
refused to sit in government with Sinn Fein until the IRA began
disarming.
</P>
<P>
   In desperation, the British and Irish governments asked George
Mitchell, the former US Senator from Maine, to save the Good Friday
Agreement he had brokered in April 1998, which created the assembly
and was supposed to transform the debate over Northern Ireland's
status from a violent to a strictly political one.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly three months of Mitchell's patient diplomacy,
Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble agreed to drop his party's
``no guns, no government'' policy in return for evidence that the
IRA was serious about disarming. On Saturday, Trimble, who is the
assembly's first minister, got his party to back the compromise
only after promising he would resign and collapse the assembly if
the IRA does not begin disarming by February.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension of the assembly in July came after Seamus Mallon,
deputy leader of the Social Democratic and Labor Party, which
represents most Irish Catholic nationalists, resigned as the
assembly's deputy first minister. The assembly's first order of
business Monday was to approve a motion rejecting Mallon's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The motion passed easily, 71-to-28, but not before those who
want the assembly, and the whole Good Friday Agreement, to collapse
spent three hours complaining that the rules had been bent to avoid
a new election that could have seen Trimble and Mallon replaced.
Paisley's deputy, Peter Robinson, suggested Mallon should be called
``the minister for loopholes.''
</P>
<P>
   Paisley also failed to get the 30 votes needed to debate his
motion calling for Sinn Fein to be excluded from holding office in
the assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams tried to assuage hard-line
unionists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unionists have nothing to fear from sharing power with
republicans,'' he said. ``Our future is bound up together.''
</P>
<P>
   But the hard-liners were having none of it, and they continued
to make catcalls. When some spectators coughed on cue in an attempt
to drown out Adams, he complained that there were ``latcheekoes''
in the gallery. The coughers, young men who support Paisley, looked
at each other perplexed, unaware they had been called buffoons in
Irish slang.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's session showed how much a work in progress the assembly
remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Point of order!'' Robinson yelled at one point. Robinson said
that while it was common knowledge that parliamentary privilege
allowed him to call someone a liar without fear of legal
repercussions, he wanted to know whether it extended to calling
someone a murderer. Looking as perplexed as the young toughs who
had been called latcheekoes, Alderdice said he didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   There had been fears that Paisley and his crowd would use
parliamentary procedure to throw a wrench into the strict timetable
for returning power to politicians here. But for all their
complaints, the Democratic Unionists took their two seats in the
Cabinet alongside McGuinness and Bairbre de Brun, the Sinn Fein
official who was put in charge of health.
</P>
<P>
   Paisley said the distinction was that his people would not sit
in the same room with Sinn Fein Cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of the day, as people here are fond of saying,
Paisley's people were in the same room as Sinn Fein, and Martin
McGuinness was still Sammy Wilson's boss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
