<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4301 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     11-29 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPRAH WINFREY LAWSUIT SILENCES PUBLIC DEBATE ON FOOD PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1996, Oprah Winfrey and her television guest, former rancher
Howard Lyman of the Humane Society, were sued by Texas cattle
barons for disparaging cattle. And freedom of speech was mugged.
</P>
<P>
   Winfrey and Lyman, in light of England's ``mad cow disease'' and
possible links to a fatal degenerative brain disease in humans, had
questioned the feed practices of the cattle industry in the United
States on her TV program.
</P>
<P>
   Although Winfrey won convincingly in the lower federal court in
1998, the judge did not strike down the Texas food disparagement
law as unconstitutional. The law is still on the books. And still
being used to try to silence critics.
</P>
<P>
   The cattle ranchers appealed the lower court's decision to the
U.S. Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals. The appellate court will
render its decision soon. Nevertheless, the cattlemen's $10 million
lawsuit has already cost Winfrey over a million dollars to fight
it. Most citizens and many companies could not afford the risk of
such a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The cattlemen's lawsuit has sent waves of caution across the
nation. Who can afford to fight a food industry in a court of law?
</P>
<P>
   And that is the point. Stifle all discussion about food
processing, growth hormones and other chemicals used to produce
larger crops or fatter livestock, pesticides and herbicides,
genetically engineered foods, irradiating fruits and vegetables,
questionable practices in feeding livestock, slaughterhouse
techniques, pollution from hog farms.
</P>
<P>
   The list is formidable and important to our health.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen states now have food disparagement laws. And two other
states, California and Michigan, currently have bills pending in
their legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, states want to protect their farmers and
ranchers from losing business. They need consumers to trust their
products. But these food disparagement laws violate both the spirit
and the letter of the First Amendment _ worse, they stifle debate
on public health issues.
</P>
<P>
   Agricultural groups and producers advertise the safety and
quality of their foods in local and national media. They have every
right to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Having done so, however, means those groups and producers are
now ``public figures.'' And First Amendment principles that are
applied to them change and are more strict.
</P>
<P>
   Under settled First Amendment law, to recover damages in a libel
lawsuit, a public figure must first prove that the person who is
accused of libel has made a damaging public statement that is
factually false and did so knowing the statement was false, or with
reckless disregard for its truth or falsity.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions, like ``I hate broccoli,'' are protected under normal
First Amendment jurisprudence. No so in food libel laws.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, most of these food disparagement laws will be struck
down, but not before they have endangered the health and nutrition
of the American public.
</P>
<P>
   Even though only 13 states have these laws, they have an effect
nationally. A book on food published in New York might cause a
lawsuit to be filed in Idaho, which has a food disparagement law.
Oprah Winfrey's television program originates in Chicago, but she
was sued in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The April issue of the Nation reported that actor Alec Baldwin
approached numerous television channels and networks with a
proposal for a documentary entitled ``The History of Food'' and
that he was turned down. The Nation story quotes Baldwin: ``But all
of these outlets, they're like, `Oh, God! We can't do that, because
of that Oprah Winfrey beef lawsuit.' I mean this is what I'm
getting from the History Channel. They just say, `We'll call you.'
And I never hear from them.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Robert Hatherill is a research scientist and faculty member
of the Environmental Studies Program at the University of
California at Santa Barbara. He wrote a commentary piece for the
Los Angeles Times in April in which he describes his publisher
having ``stripped lengthy passages'' from his new book, ``Eat to
Beat Cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatherill wrote: ``I was not allowed to disclose dangers
inherent in some common foods like dairy and meat products, as well
as over-the-counter medicines like calcium supplements and
nonprescription pain remedies. The problem had nothing to do with
whether there was sufficient evidence to support the claims _ there
is _ it came down to fear of litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told, `We could win the lawsuit, but it would cost us
millions, and it's just not worth it.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to try to protect the produce of your local
rancher and farmer with these food defamation laws, quite another
to end up protecting corporate giants like Monsanto Co. According
to a June 1, New York Times front-page story by Melody Petersen,
over a year ago, ``Vital Health Publishing of Bloomingdale, Ill.,
canceled a book, `Against the Grain: Biotechnology and the
Corporate Takeover of Your Food,' after the manuscript had been
sent to the printers. The publisher had received a letter from a
lawyer at Monsanto Co. who said he believed the manuscript, which
he had not seen, included false statements that would disparage a
herbicide called Roundup, made by Monsanto.''
</P>
<P>
   Toxicologist Marc Lappe, who co-authored the book, said the
manuscript had already been approved by the publisher's lawyer.
``But Monsanto's letter changed the lawyer's mind.'' Lappe and his
co-author, Britt Bailey, found another publisher, Common Courage
Press, which published the book last November. And, according to
the New York Times story, the new publisher has not heard a word
from Monsanto.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly it was a bullying tactic made by a giant corporation
that has the resources to take anyone to court and bury them, even
if those they take to court eventually win.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the United Fresh Fruit and Vegetable Association
threatened an environmental group in Vermont for distributing
reports questioning the health safety of irradiating fruits and
vegetables. In a letter from United's law firm, the group, Food and
Water, was told that nearly 30 states had passed or were
considering legislation that allowed lawsuits against anyone who
disseminated false statements against agricultural products. The
letter ended, ``We must advise you that Food and Water's actions
will be closely scrutinized.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the final verdict in the Oprah Winfrey lawsuit, the
damage has been done to public discourse about issues concerning
food, diet, health and nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   The few illustrations of how public debate on these issues was
smothered shows only the surface of the problem. It reaches
ordinary individuals who educated themselves on these issues in
order to speak out in concern for public health. Many have been
silenced.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas beef barons have crammed their bull manure into the
mouths of legitimate public debate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
