   &UR; THE THREE-NAME THING IS EXPLAINED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At an opening party for the movie ``Flawless'' at the New York
club Hush recently, actor  &UR; Philip Seymour Hoffman &LR;  told  &UR; Baird &LR; 
 &UR; Jones &LR;  why he's one of those thrice-named stars (think  &UR; Jennifer &LR; 
 &UR; Love Hewitt &LR;  et al.):
</P>
<P>
   ``People think we do it because it is elegant, like we are the
new nobility. It is the opposite. We have to. There are so many
actors now in the union that almost everyone with two names has a
duplication problem. It is either three names or a meaningless
middle initial like  &UR; Michael J. Fox &LR;  has. ... You never heard of
this problem before because studios just used to arbitrarily make
up star names. ... I had to insert the Seymour part, and I hate
it.''
</P>
