<P>
   &UR; BUDDHA'S BAD BACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Art Commission is helping the Japanese Tea
Garden's 210-year-old Buddha, suffering the burden of
enlightenment, with new innards to help bear the load. The
particular burden is the monument's satori, which rises up from
behind its shoulders and represents enlightenment; it is so heavy
it is causing the Buddha's body to cave in.
</P>
<P>
   The Buddha, which weighs 3,000 pounds, will be taken apart Dec.
2 and transported to the fabricator Rocket Science, where a new
armature will be built to support the satori. Thence, it will be
transported to the workshop of  &UR; Genevieve Baird &LR; , who will
supervise cleaning, restoring, recoloring and reinstalling it in
the tea garden next spring.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Shortly after I started collecting Beanies, my company
relocated and I lost my job. Then a few weeks later, my husband
also lost his job! That was a surprise and a real blow! Neither one
of us has found employment as of yet. ... Whenever I am feeling
down, I head out to the stores and Beanie shop. It is fun and lifts
my spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``Heartfelt Stories About Beanie Babies and Those Who
Collect Them,'' collected by Pam Knapp (Beckett; $9.95).
</P>
