<HEADLINE>
SMALL SOUTH AFRICAN TOWNS STRUGGLE TO EMERGE FROM APARTHEID'S
SHADOW
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUTTERHEIM, South Africa _ A city councilman proudly pointed
out the progress here on a recent day, stamping on a stretch of
recently tarred road. Someday, he said, the roads will all be
paved.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed at the new reservoir that supplies communal taps that
used to run dry. Some day, he said, every house will have indoor
plumbing. He pointed at the 500 new houses rising from stacks of
bricks, to be equipped with sinks and toilets. ``Soon, we will all
be flushing,'' said the councilman, Lloyd Mgwangqa.
</P>
<P>
   But a noisy constituent jeered at his words, her bare feet
slapping against the sandy lane as she trailed behind him. She
jabbed her finger toward crumbling mud houses and miles of dirt
road. ``What do you say about my house, councilor?'' she hissed.
``When will we get what you promised?''
</P>
<P>
   This small town's struggle to improve the lives of its residents
demonstrates the enormous challenge confronting South Africa's new
president, Thabo Mbeki, as he strives to undo the legacy of
apartheid, which banished millions of blacks to desolate towns
lacking infrastructure and industry.
</P>
<P>
   Staggering under the weight of their poor citizens, without an
adequate tax base and staffed by inexperienced and sometimes
corrupt officials, at least a third of this country's 843
municipalities cannot meet their basic financial obligations, much
less build houses for people who need them, government officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki has committed his government to providing basic services
to the poor, to bridge the yawning gap between well-off whites and
impoverished blacks.
</P>
<P>
   But in this town of 35,000, there is not enough money to pave
roads, to install sewer pipes or to build houses for the remaining
2,000 families who need them.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Mgwangqa and six other black activists swept
onto the City Council with the slogan ``One house, one tap.'' They
hung the photograph of Stutterheim's first black mayor, one of the
seven, in Town Hall. But they quickly learned the limits of
political power.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about 60 percent of the overwhelmingly unemployed
population does not pay taxes or service fees, leaving the town
with little cash for capital improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of good plans, and we made a lot of promises,''
admitted Mgwangqa, who still uses an outhouse and a communal water
tap at home. ``But the means are not there.''
</P>
<P>
   Burdened with cities and towns that cannot provide necessary
services, the national government plans to overhaul the entire
system of local government. Officials announced in early November
that they would merge weak towns with stronger ones to maximize
resources, reducing the number of municipalities by 60 percent _ to
about 330. The change is to be made in time for local elections
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Stutterheim, in fact, is often celebrated as a strong town,
because it has managed to make some improvements while continuing
to pay creditors and salaries. Indeed, much progress has already
been made since the end of apartheid, with 3 million people housed.
</P>
<P>
   But the need remains enormous. About 7.5 million people in this
country of 39 million still lack access to running water, officials
say. Twenty-one million go without sanitation. And 3 million more
need housing.
</P>
<P>
   The government is encouraging struggling localities to team up
with other towns, community groups and private sector partners to
provide services more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Pending legislation would require local officials to meet
performance standards and to eliminate property tax exemptions and
rebates for wealthy country clubs, rural landowners and
government-owned property.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the package of reforms, all of them complement
one another to build an effective system of local government,''
said Jackie Manche, the acting deputy director general of the
national Department of Provincial and Local government. ``It will
make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The transformation will be far from painless. Under the new
system, Stutterheim expects to inherit several rural villages with
about 20,000 more underserved people.
</P>
<P>
   It is a prospect that local officials dread.
</P>
<P>
   They say it would cost about $8.3 million over the next five
years to build houses, install sewer systems, pave roads and
provide basic services for just the town's current population. But
the current budget allows only $1.5 million in capital spending in
that time. The 500 houses under construction are being built with a
combination of grants and national and local government money.
</P>
<P>
   If they cannot serve their own people, the officials say, how
can they possibly serve 20,000 more? As it stands, the town will
have to borrow money next year to help cover operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   In Pretoria, national officials say they are searching for
financing to help such towns. In Stutterheim, local officials are
praying for some kind of miracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could find a fairy godfather somewhere, I'd show you what
this town could do,'' says Leslie DuRandt, the town manager.
``Right now, we're not doing enough. We just don't have the
money.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
