<HEADLINE>
ALL OUTS; NO INS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The always cheery Wired magazine has compiled a list of 100
things that should be put in the dump file before they ``cross the
glittering rainbow bridge to the third you-know-what.'' Some
selections:
</P>
<P>
   :-) and all its brethren emoticons, recovered memory syndrome,
 &UR; Courtney Love &LR; , white stretch limos, ``What's Sexy Now!,''
spinning (not fibers), forwarded e-mail jokes, zero tolerance,
trilogies,  &UR; David Letterman &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   P.S. The latest issue of Food &AMP; Wine praises a dozen
``creative'' San Francisco restaurants _ Boulevard, not-yet-open
Chaya, Red Herring, Shanghai 1930, Fifth Floor, Montage, XYZ,
Delfina, Foreign Cinema, Gordon's House of Fine Eats, Campton Place
and Gary Danko _ but calls Pier 39 a ``culinary abyss.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE THREE-NAME THING IS EXPLAINED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At an opening party for the movie ``Flawless'' at the New York
club Hush recently, actor  &UR; Philip Seymour Hoffman &LR;  told  &UR; Baird &LR; 
 &UR; Jones &LR;  why he's one of those thrice-named stars (think  &UR; Jennifer &LR; 
 &UR; Love Hewitt &LR;  et al.):
</P>
<P>
   ``People think we do it because it is elegant, like we are the
new nobility. It is the opposite. We have to. There are so many
actors now in the union that almost everyone with two names has a
duplication problem. It is either three names or a meaningless
middle initial like  &UR; Michael J. Fox &LR;  has. ... You never heard of
this problem before because studios just used to arbitrarily make
up star names. ... I had to insert the Seymour part, and I hate
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OLYMPICS GIFT LIST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   What do you give an official you want to buy? Atlantans who
lobbied the International Olympic Committee to have the 1996 Summer
Olympics there prepared profiles of committee members, some of
which appear in the latest issue of Harper's. A sampling:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Prince Albert de Monaco &LR; : ``Honest, open and fun. Likes the
good life: wine, women (some say men as well) and song.
Relationship is all-important here. If he likes you, you got a shot
at getting his vote. Visit to Atlanta should be low-key with press
but an all-out orgy for Al &AMP; his friend.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Raymond Gafner &LR; : ``Fan of ice hockey. Perhaps we could get a
stick signed by  &UR; Wayne Gretzky &LR; . Maybe a hockey puck that we would
say is from some famous game (whether that is true or not). Perhaps
an agreement to publish his novel in English?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Louis Guirandou-N'Diaye &LR; : ``Gifts are okay. Gift of female
okay.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Milla Jovovich &LR; , who plays Joan of Arc in ``The Messenger,''
revealed to W that she's not quite as dynamic as her role model.
``She was a real mover and shaker,'' Jovovich said. ``... I got
smoke all over me and stuff, but it was nothing compared to what
she went through.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Shmattes 'n' shoes: The  &UR; Duchess of York &LR;  employs a uniformed
$375-a-day man who comes a-calling to polish her shoes, reports the
Mirror of London. And reporting on the sale of  &UR; Yves &LR; 
 &UR; Saint Laurent &LR;  to Gucci, the New York Times noted that  &UR; Miuccia &LR; 
 &UR; Prada &LR;  used to wear Saint Laurent clothes ``while distributing
flyers for the Communist Party.'' Furthermore, to correctly credit
 &UR; Princess Diana &LR; 's blue velvet Travolta- &LR;  dress, mentioned here
before T-giving, it was designed by  &UR; Victor Edelstein &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUDDHA'S BAD BACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Art Commission is helping the Japanese Tea
Garden's 210-year-old Buddha, suffering the burden of
enlightenment, with new innards to help bear the load. The
particular burden is the monument's satori, which rises up from
behind its shoulders and represents enlightenment; it is so heavy
it is causing the Buddha's body to cave in.
</P>
<P>
   The Buddha, which weighs 3,000 pounds, will be taken apart Dec.
2 and transported to the fabricator Rocket Science, where a new
armature will be built to support the satori. Thence, it will be
transported to the workshop of  &UR; Genevieve Baird &LR; , who will
supervise cleaning, restoring, recoloring and reinstalling it in
the tea garden next spring.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Shortly after I started collecting Beanies, my company
relocated and I lost my job. Then a few weeks later, my husband
also lost his job! That was a surprise and a real blow! Neither one
of us has found employment as of yet. ... Whenever I am feeling
down, I head out to the stores and Beanie shop. It is fun and lifts
my spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``Heartfelt Stories About Beanie Babies and Those Who
Collect Them,'' collected by Pam Knapp (Beckett; $9.95).
</P>
