<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4307 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-SAFRICA-POVERTY-ART-2     11-29 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-POVERTY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
STUTTERHEIM, South Africa: the money.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the white national government's final year in power,
Stutterheim, then a white town of 5,000 people, had a municipal
budget of about $2 million, officials say. The adjacent black
township of 25,000, known as Mlungisi, had a budget of about
$600,000.
</P>
<P>
   The math tells the story: $400 spent on each white citizen, $24
on each black citizen. Even today, with both communities united in
one municipality, blacks peer down the hill at the brick houses and
paved roads of the white world below and shake their heads.
</P>
<P>
   History still speaks through the dirt roads, the crumbling
shacks and the outhouses that sag in most backyards of the hilltop
black community. The neglect is visible in black communities across
the country, which were deemed unworthy of investment under the old
government.
</P>
<P>
   Mlungisi's black politicians share their community's
frustration. Of seven black council members, three are still
unemployed even now, four years after voters swept them into power.
Sometimes they feel ill-equipped to serve on the front lines of
their nation's transformation process, stymied as they are by
limited resources and their own inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   They are teachers, a former miner and a woman who sold goods in
the local market, many of whom took office without ever having
balanced a ledger, who must now push and prod their town out of the
apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were coming in to redistribute wealth, to make things
happen,'' said Mayor Chris Magwangqana, recalling the heady days
after the municipal elections of 1995. ``We said, ``We'll take from
the haves and give to the have-nots.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Mxolisi Mbulawa, the deputy mayor: ``And get big houses
and tarred streets and all of those things. Those were dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, some found their tongues twisting over the new
vocabulary of contract bidding and budgets, heretofores and
hereafters. Many felt intimidated by the two white council members,
who represent the white wards, and by the all-white staff of civil
servants who spoke the language of ordinances and bylaws as
fluently as the black council members spoke their native tongue,
Xhosa.
</P>
<P>
   The white members were determined not to let the white section
of town deteriorate, even if that meant the former township would
be upgraded only gradually, and they easily dominated the early
meetings and the first budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``White people were jumping up and talking and we were so
reserved,'' Mbulawa remembered. ``You're thinking, `What am I going
to say? Is it the correct way of doing this?'''
</P>
<P>
   The two sides say they now share similar goals. Councilman
Daniel A. Kropf, 65, drove to Mlungisi for the first time in his
life two years ago, to see it for himself. ``It showed me what a
mess the last government had made,'' he said recently. ``Things
should have changed.''
</P>
<P>
   The black council members agree now that the town must spend
money on pruning trees, minding community gardens and repairing
roads in the white section of town if they hope to lure new
businesses and ease unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   But there is painfully little money available.
</P>
<P>
   In Mlungisi, despite the prodding and pleading of public
officials, about 73 percent of the population still is not paying
water and sanitation fees. Residents currently owe the town $1
million money that could be used for capital projects _ and that
debt is increasing by about $17,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, residents owe municipalities more than $1 billion,
despite a national campaign to encourage payment. Here, when the
town cuts service to debtors, people simply reconnect their water
illegally or go without.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty and unemployment are often the reason people do not pay.
But there is another reason. After years of using payment boycotts
as a way to protest apartheid, people still find it hard to see why
they should pay, especially when not much has changed in the way of
service.
</P>
<P>
   Yongama Gxowa, chairman of the council's finance committee, has
seen such doubt glimmering in the eyes of his constituents. He
remembers explaining at a community meeting that he led why people
must pay for services and how much they must pay.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd listened politely and then asked for clarification
from the white town treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like bursting,'' Gxowa said. ``You elect your own
people and the trust is still with the white man?''
</P>
<P>
   But for many poor people, it is simply hard to believe that the
white town's treasury is not overflowing with cash.
</P>
<P>
   When the council first presented its housing plan to the
community, for instance, some people complained that the two-room
houses looked like outhouses. Even the apartheid government would
have done better, they said.
</P>
<P>
   And when the process lagged for months as officials haggled with
contractors, some constituents accused their leaders of embezzling
the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, you don't feel happy you're a councilor,'' Mbulawa
said. ``You get into a rowdy meeting. You hear people shouting and
singing your name. You go home. You sit down with your wife. Your
wife says, `These people are singing about you. Why are you
sticking to this council? I don't want any troubles sticking to our
children.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And you ask yourself, `What shall I lose if I give up?'''
</P>
<P>
   But the council does not give up. Instead, they designated an
employee to persuade people to pay their water bills. They buy road
maintenance equipment second-hand. They left a staff engineer's
position vacant to save on the salary.
</P>
<P>
   They offered space to a local foundation, which has financing to
build a sports center. They allowed needy black villagers to graze
cattle on council land.
</P>
<P>
   And they acknowledge that their work will not get easier any
time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to see what we're achieving even now,'' Kropf
said ruefully. ``We've had no road repairs for 18 months. And
definitely, there's a deterioration as far as whites are
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the black council members are concerned, the community
will have to put the big dreams on hold. But they say they will
keep searching for grants, for investors, for ways to make small
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our progress here is not in leaps and bounds,'' Gxowa said.
``It's just one step forward, one step forward. But it's moving.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
