<HEADER>
A4309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FRANCE-DEGAULLE-ART-N     11-29 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-DEGAULLE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL HOLDING COURT, THE MYTHIC GAULLIST WHO WAS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBEY-LES-DEUX-EGLISES, France _ Coming here is a ritual of
French politics. Even some of the country's highest office holders
come to this small village, three hours from Paris by car, every
year on the anniversary of Charles de Gaulle's death.
</P>
<P>
   They go to Mass in the simple church next to the former
president's grave. They lay flowers by his modest marker in the
cemetery, which stands out mostly because of the nearly 100 other
plaques honoring him that are planted all around it.
</P>
<P>
   The general has been dead for almost 30 years. But there is
still political mileage to be gotten from being associated with his
name. In fact, a fierce battle is under way over who are the real
Gaullists.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac's party, Rally for the Republic, has
always claimed the title. But after a disastrous 1997 legislative
election and a poor showing in recent European parliamentary
elections, Chirac is now facing competition from a breakaway group
eager to claim that they are the real Gaullists.
</P>
<P>
   What is a Gaullist these days? It's hard to get an answer. Part
of the problem is that it is hard to imagine what the general might
have had to say about some of today's issues. Would he have
reproached Jose Bove, who bulldozed a McDonald's to protest U.S.
taxes on Roquefort and pate? Would he have invaded Kosovo? Bought
British beef?
</P>
<P>
   Even those who came to pay homage at his grave recently didn't
agree.
</P>
<P>
   Some said that being a Gaullist means being devoted to French
sovereignty and French values. Others said it is more of a question
of morality. Even when he was president, de Gaulle paid the tab for
his guests at Elysee Palace.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear, however, is that the general still casts a long
shadow over French politics and remains one of the country's most
beloved figures. A new play about him, ``The Man Who Said No'' (a
reference to his refusal to accept Germany's domination of France)
was sold out for months before it opened on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The play is a gaudy two-hour-and-10-minute history lesson
without an intermission and regularly punctuated with drum rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some 3,000 people _ ranging in age from those who might have
actually been in the French resistance to those who are way past
their bedtime _ attend each show. They applaud whenever the actor
playing de Gaulle rallies the French underground, tells Winston
Churchill what he will or will not tolerate or calls for unity
among the Allies.
</P>
<P>
   The critics have applauded it as a ``spectacle.'' Many have
simply written their own odes to de Gaulle, who was a virtually
unknown rebel at the start of World War II. Yet he managed, with no
power other than his lucidity and will, to claim that he was the
legitimate voice of France.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to bully his way toward his goals, restoring France's
power, integrity and status _ even at a time when he was wholly
dependent on the good will of the Allies.
</P>
<P>
   This year's anniversary pilgrimage to Colombey-les-deux-Eglises,
which is in the Champagne region, was more complicated than usual
because of the rivalry between the Rally for the Republic and the
breakaway group, the Rally for France, now under the leadership of
a former interior minister, Charles Pasqua.
</P>
<P>
   The day had to be carefully choreographed so the two groups
would never meet. Pasqua is seen as the kingmaker behind Chirac,
and his defection may be a serious blow to the president's
ambitions to be re-elected in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   But because Chirac is still president he is able to claim
certain privileges. He came first to visit de Gaulle's grave on
Nov. 9. He observed a minute of silence and bowed from the waist
before launching into a round of handshaking and autograph signing
that was carried on the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   The Rally for France supporters came next, issuing gentlemanly
jabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here to look for inspiration,'' said Phillipe Pemezec,
a legislator who joined Pasqua. Chirac's supporters, he added
``were coming to confess their errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, the two tour buses unloaded members from
Chirac's team. ``The general belongs to all French people,'' said
Patrick Devedjian, a long-time legislator, staring into the
television cameras. ``But some of us try to carry on with his
principles.''
</P>
<P>
   De Gaulle was not actually born in Colombey. He bought his house
here in 1934. After the Allies liberated Paris in 1944, he briefly
became the country's president, then returned here to live. In
1958, the French called him back to lead again, and for more than a
decade he rebuilt and dominated France.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his retirement in 1969, he returned here again and died the
following year.
</P>
<P>
   He was essentially pushed out of office after badly losing a
referendum on government structures that he had instigated. But few
French people dwell on that fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a man who even paid his own electric bill,'' said
Jacques Alexandre, 66, the manager of a fiber optics company who
traveled several hours to mark the general's death. ``He stood for
morality. Not like today when all our politicians have their hands
in the till.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
