<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4310 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-BUDGET-HNS &LR;      11-29 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SIGNS $385 BILLION BUDGET MEASURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton signed into law Monday the final
2000 budget bill, giving himself and Republicans a pat on the back
for reaching agreement on the massive $385 billion spending package
that he said would build a ``stronger, better America'' in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   Saying the bill makes ``real progress'' toward fulfilling his
goals of hiring 100,000 new teachers and 50,000 more police
officers, Clinton nonetheless acknowledged that the spending
measure does not provide the managed healthcare reforms he had
sought or relief for the elderly hard-hit by high prescription
costs. He also expressed disappointment at Congress' refusal to
increase the minimum wage or pass new gun control laws.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vowed to fight on for those issues when Congress
reconvenes in January. He used the White House signing ceremony to
challenge Republicans to put aside political differences in next
year's election to work on business ``left undone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the weeks and months ahead, we can achieve these vital
goals if we keep in mind that the disagreements we have are far
less important than our shared values and our shared
responsibilities in the future,'' the president said at the signing
event, where he shared a stage with teachers, police officers and a
bipartisan group of lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The spending bill, which rounds out the federal budget for the
2000 fiscal year that began Oct. 1, was nearly two months late
because of disputes between Clinton and Republican leaders over
funding for new teachers and police, overdue U.S. payments to the
United Nations and provisions that would have weakened
environmental regulations.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after both sides gave a little on some issues that a
deal was struck on the final bill funding the Departments of
Education, Labor, Commerce, Interior, State, Justice, and Health
and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton used the signing ceremony to tout his
accomplishments, such as a downpayment on the $1 billion owed to
the United Nations and $1.8 billion for the Middle East peace
process, Republican lawmakers who attended also did some boasting.
</P>
<P>
   They took credit for making Clinton agree to a 0.38 percent
across-the-board spending cut in all government departments and for
insisting that the 2000 budget not rely on Social Security
surpluses to pay for increased funding in some programs. They also
cited increases in spending for defense, veterans affairs, and
health research above what Clinton had originally requested in his
budget proposal back in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new dynamic in budgeting is not to spend the Social
Security trust fund money,'' said Senate Budget Committee Chairman
Pete Domenici, R-N.M.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, while the president claims ... a number of victories to
his own platform, we contend we did a number of things that we
wanted to do. And most of all, and most importantly, we did not
touch the Social Security trust fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to next year, Domenici said Republicans would try
once again to pass another ``major tax cut,'' despite the fact that
their $792 billion plan last summer failed to win public support.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was proud that the spending plan will maintain
``the fiscal discipline that has turned deficits into surpluses and
gives us what will be in February the longest economic expansion in
the history of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 1915EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
