r e BC-MUSIC-CDS-TEX     11-29 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOURTH WEEK OF HOLIDAY CD RELEASES MORE INSPIRING THAN FRUSTRATING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN, MARK LOWRY and MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And so it is over _ having continuously stayed up (and left the
office early), we critics have survived the four Super Tuesdays of
mega-releases by mega-popular artists.
</P>
<P>
   No, pre-Christmas releases by major artists are not over _ still
to come is a CD of previously unreleased material by Notorious
B.I.G., a long-overdue live set by Guns 'N Roses (Axl, Axl, where
``are'' you?) and new music from Rakim, Ghostface Killah and DMX.
</P>
<P>
   But the majority of the releases expected to make the dead
presidents fly from the wallets has come to an end. And, we're
happy to report, with more good music than last week.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Beck, ``Midnite Vultures,'' Geffen: Like a joke, you'll either
get this, or it'll go over your head. The fourth disc from sonic
junkie Beck is his foray into party music. In Beck's twisted-genius
tradition, it's done with his tongue digging so far into his cheek,
his mouth is almost bleeding. Intriguing, fun stuff, but you gotta
be a Beck fan, not a ``Loser'' fan.
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Malcolm Mayhew
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Metallica, ``S&AMP;M,'' Elektra Entertainment: This pairing of San
Francisco's metal heroes and the city's symphony orchestra (with
Michael Kamen conducting) is ... not bad. The inherent drama and
sweep of the band's music fits an orchestral setting, and the
arrangements are sometimes brilliant in the way they work with the
original material, and yet not overblown. Too many songs from
``Load'' and ``Re-Load,'' however, make this a less successful
diversion than it might have been.
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Phish, ``Hampton Comes Alive,'' Elektra Entertainment: This is
the biggie, Phishheads: Six CDs, documenting two complete shows in
Virginia last November. Based on the one-CD sampler I've heard,
though, this verges between inspired jamming and just performances;
the 14-minute ``Bathtub Gin'' is everything the band's about, but a
take on Stevie Wonder's ``Boogie On Reggae Woman'' also shows that
the quartet can be pretty slack, too.
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Dave Matthews Band, ``Listener Supported,'' RCA Records: Yep,
another DMB live record _ this time taken from a show in Jersey in
September. Sound and song selection are great, and the playing
frequently sparkles. This is really all you need to know about the
band, both as a pop group and a jam band.
</P>
<P>
   4 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Beastie Boys, ``The Beastie Boys Anthology: The Sounds of
Science,'' Grand Royal Records: Sprawling two-CD collection of
those New York wiseacres, drawn from all of their well-and
lesser-known releases, and featuring their new and very fine single
``Alive.'' So where the heck are ``She's Crafty'' and ``Paul
Revere?''
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Alanis Morissette, ``MTV Unplugged,'' Maverick: Is it
``already'' time for a live career retrospective? Really? Methinks
not. Morissette is so determined to show us (still!) how miserable
she is that she covers the Police's ``King of Pain'' _ changing the
chorus, of course. But Alanis, didn't we already know that?
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Reba McEntire, ``So Good Together,'' MCA Records: Thank the good
Lord no, it's not a duets record. What it is, is too maudlin in
spots, too rock in others, and just not in the same league as her
best work _ which is, frankly, receding into the mists of time.
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Third Eye Blind, ``Blue,'' Elektra: Because band singer Stephan
Jenkins' mouth is almost as big as his ego, this San Fran pop-rock
quartet quickly gained a bum rap, causing critics to either slam or
ignore the band's excellent 1997 self-titled debut. They should
have saved the mud-slinging for ``Blue.'' What a mess: Out of tune,
out of focus and out of ideas, 3EB stumbles through ``Blue,''
offering only one or two decent moments. Here was their chance to
prove the critics wrong; they blew it.
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Malcolm Mayhew
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   And one from last week:
</P>
<P>
   Ani DiFranco, ``To the Teeth,'' Righteous Babe Records: The good
news: Ani DiFranco has a new album. The bad news: It's her second
this year. The artist who tries too hard to defy categorization _
she has mixed her folk roots with punk, pop, funk, acid jazz and
you-name-it styles over the years _ needs to take a breather and
think before releasing another album.
</P>
<P>
   3 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Mark Lowry
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman, Mark Lowry and Malcolm Mayhew are pop culture
critics for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
