<HEADLINE>
IS RUSH TO LASER SURGERY SHOTSIGHTED?
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by EYE SURGERY-HOMEWORK) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From her first losing encounter with an eye chart as a
kindergartner, glasses were Karen McCormick's constant childhood
companion. Later came contact lenses and the almost daily
irritation caused by chronically dry eyes.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed for the Keller High School honor student one
morning this month at a posh Arlington, Texas, clinic called TLC
(The Laser Center). With the rat-tat-tat of a laser machine,
microscopic amounts of tissue were removed from the cornea of each
eye. When the $4,600 procedure called LASIK surgery was finished
after only 15 minutes, McCormick could immediately read a wall
clock without glasses or contacts, for her an almost unprecedented
feat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my gosh,'' McCormick said a few days after the surgery that
corrected her acute nearsightedness to virtually perfect vision.
``Just today I got out of the shower and went to get my glasses,
then I thought, `Wait a minute. I don't need glasses anymore.' I
tell people that it seems almost like magic. It's just incredible
in that short of time you can have that much improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Such happy incredulity is increasingly familiar in a country
where the number of LASIK patients has roughly doubled every year
for the past four. This year an estimated 1 million people will
undergo the surgery. They are people who now play tennis, jog,
water ski, see the morning alarm clock, or shave their legs in the
shower without glasses or contacts, many for the first time.
Celebrities, from Tiger Woods to Troy Aikman, have cashed in on the
LASIK craze, too.
</P>
<P>
   So why then the spate of recent articles, which, while not
exactly raining on the LASIK parade, have struck decidedly
cautionary notes? It seems that somewhere in the growing
celebration, the stories say, an important message has been lost:
With LASIK, as in any surgery, there are risks, relatively minimal
(less than a 5 percent risk of complications for experienced
surgeons using the best equipment), but risks nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   And some insist that the whole thing is moving too fast.
Inexperienced doctors eager to cash in, critics say, can be too
prone to operate on high-risk patients, who themselves are too
eager to gain the seemingly miraculous benefits. Thousands can
testify to the irksome and occasionally disabling consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Carver, an electrical engineer in Beaumont in East Texas,
said no one at a bustling Houston eye clinic warned him that his
degree of astigmatism made him a poor candidate for the procedure.
(The clinic did not return a recent telephone call inquiring about
Carver's case.) After two LASIK surgeries, in September and
December of last year, Carver's sight is much worse than it was
before. His career has been disrupted. He can no longer drive at
night. His condition, which pitched him into a severe depression
for weeks, is not correctable with available technology.
</P>
<P>
   Through an Internet site devoted to the risks of LASIK
(www.surgicaleyes.org), Carver has encountered scores of people,
many of them with LASIK outcomes even worse than his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want people to think we're down on the surgery
itself,'' Carver said. ``For the right person with the right doctor
and right equipment, it's very good surgery. But the problem is
that the industry has gotten ahead of itself, and there are
casualties being created because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   For almost a half-century, specialists around the world have
targeted the cornea, the eye's curved, transparent outer layer, in
their attempts to find surgical remedies for the most common visual
maladies. The reason is that much of the eye's refraction, or
bending of light to form an image inside the eye, takes place
through the cornea. A cornea too steeply curved commonly produces
nearsightedness, one too flat, farsightedness.
</P>
<P>
   As far back as the 1960s, specialists in Japan and the Soviet
Union reshaped corneas with a series of incisions, a procedure
known as radial keratotomy, or RK. But the surgery was painful,
generally took months to heal and was prone to complications, and
the cornea often failed to retain its new shape. Largely as a
result, RK never really took hold in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the excimer laser, which was first developed in the 1970s
as a tool to etch computer microchips. The laser's precision was
such that it could cut notches in a strand of hair without severing
it. And the excimer was a cool laser, meaning it would not burn
tissue if applied to surgical use.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen Trokel, a Columbia University ophthalmologist, was
among the first to realize that potential application. In the early
1980s, in a visit to a computer lab, Trokel experimented with the
excimer on the eye of a calf. A few years later at Louisiana State
University, the laser was tested on the eyes of humans whose
blindness was believed to be irreversible, said Irving Arons, a
Massachusetts-based consultant to the medical laser industry. One
of those patients had her vision restored, Arons said.
</P>
<P>
   The excimer emergence first spawned a procedure known as PRK
(photorefractive keratectomy) in which the cornea's outer layer was
gently scraped away with a scalpel and the laser then used to
reshape the tissue beneath. When the outer layer grew back, the
cornea retained its corrected shape.
</P>
<P>
   Although an improvement over RK, healing from PRK could still be
slow and painful. That changed with LASIK, (laser-assisted in situ
keratomileusis), in which pain generally abates in a few hours and
patients can gain visual benefits almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   The real advance of LASIK is not in the laser itself, but in the
method of exposing the inner layer of the cornea for reshaping.
Using a device called a microkeratome, surgeons delicately peel
back a layer of the cornea about the thickness of a grape skin,
leaving one end of the layer attached to create a corneal flap.
</P>
<P>
   In Karen McCormick's recent surgery at TLC, located at The
Ballpark in Arlington, the patient's nervous parents watched on a
television monitor as the microkeratome slid across her eye,
creating a flap that her eye surgeon, Dr. Robert Gillett, gently
folded out of the way. When the computer-controlled laser treatment
was finished, Gillett teased the flap back into place on the
cornea, patting it down with several strokes of a small brush. The
burning sensation in McCormick's eyes abated in a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, creating the flap is the most delicate and risky
portion of the procedure, and not until the mid-1990s, when
microkeratome technology had advanced enough to make it safe, did
LASIK begin to find an audience among eye specialists and their
patients. But once it did, because of the quick healing and almost
instantaneous results, LASIK became a snowball rolling downhill, a
phenomenon that grew, at least in the early stages, by word of
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, as LASIK advertising accelerates, the experience of
friends, relatives and co-workers often is the most powerful
endorsement. Carolyn Ender listened for months as colleagues at a
Las Colinas investment firm spoke of their LASIK miracles. At the
same time, Ender's husband, Brad, had grown weary of putting in
contact lenses for his early morning jogs, inspiring the couple to
undergo LASIK one after another, a few hours after McCormick's
surgery at TLC.
</P>
<P>
   Then they had ``miracle'' stories of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our procedure at 2, and at 8 that night my wife and I
are both sitting there watching a movie without glasses,'' Brad
Ender said. ``It's like you have a brand-new pair of contacts in,
but it's better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   But there are other LASIK stories, those of annoyance, even
heartbreak, that until recently have remained in the shadows. Just
in the last few months, those tales have begun popping up in the
American media, from The New York Times to Forbes to an Oct. 11
cover story in Time. The Time article did not ignore the successes,
quoting the typically gleeful patients after procedures that went
as planned.
</P>
<P>
   But Time also pointed out, as would good doctors, that people
requiring a high degree of correction in glasses or contact lenses,
or those with unusually large pupils, may not make good candidates
for LASIK. The story detailed the glare, starbursts and halos
around lights that sometimes afflict LASIK patients, generally at
night.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting industry studies, Time said that an estimated 10 to 15
percent of LASIK patients must undergo a second surgery to get
their correction right. Time's LASIK package also included the
personal story of a magazine staffer, who, after her own
unsuccessful surgery, wondered whether she would ever see her
children in clear focus again.
</P>
<P>
   Letters from around the country poured in.
</P>
<P>
   ``People responded to the fact that there was any downside
mentioned at all,'' said Christine Gorman, who wrote the Time
article, ``that this was elective surgery on your eyes, and not
something you should jump into. ... We got all kinds of letters
from people with problems who said things like `I thought I was the
only one.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors also responded, Gorman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a really nice array of letters, including those from
ophthalmologists who do the surgery, thanking us for piercing the
hype, so to speak,'' she said. ``Interestingly enough, some of the
more commercial doctors were not too happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The message from such articles, one that would not be disputed
by reputable physicians, is thus: Prospective patients, as eager as
they may be to discard glasses and contacts, need to take a deep
breath and do their homework. It is their only set of eyes, after
all.
</P>
<P>
   A Fort Worth woman says she was sobered by her recent LASIK
surgery in which her corneas were apparently overcorrected. It
became dangerous for her to drive at night because of the myriad
circles that surrounded each lamp and headlight. She has been
assured by her doctor that the problem can be corrected with a
second surgery. But her case illustrates the fact that problems do
occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be sure to get a lot of information about what they're doing
and what options there might be,'' the woman said of her advice to
potential LASIK patients. ``But also they should ask themselves
just how uncomfortable they are with contacts. It is a big deal. I
think they are doing so many and you see so much coverage on TV
that some people think it's like going to get a hamburger at
McDonald's. And it's a serious matter.''
</P>
<P>
   So where does the LASIK truth lie?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is surgery. It's not perfect. There will be
complications,'' said Dr. Stephen Slade, a Houston surgeon who has
pioneered LASIK surgery in the United States. ``The good news is
the complication rate is very low.''
</P>
<P>
   So low, Slade says, that eye doctors are undergoing LASIK
surgery in much larger percentages than the general public. And
risk, Slade says, can be minimized by patients who recognize the
surgery's seriousness and act accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a once-in-a-lifetime thing for a patient,'' he said.
``The patient needs to look around, talk to different doctors and
different patients, read something. The best combination is an
experienced surgeon and an experienced patient.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
