<HEADLINE>
REVAMP OF HEALTH SYSTEM NEEDED TO ROOT OUT ERRORS, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rooting out deadly medical errors will require a top-to-bottom
transformation of America's health care system, including a
controversial requirement that hospitals and other providers report
their mistakes to the government, the nation's most prestigious
medical group warns.
</P>
<P>
   Prescribing the wrong drugs, removing the wrong organs, making
the wrong diagnoses and other common mistakes kill between 44,000
and 98,000 people a year at US hospitals, and many more at
day-surgery centers, nursing homes and other settings, according to
the report from the National Academy of Science's Institute of
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Using even the most conservative estimate, the authors added
Monday, more people die from medical errors each year than from
suicides, highway accidents, breast cancer or AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the errors especially tragic is that so many could be
prevented so easily as the Boston Globe reported in a series on
medical errors earlier this year. But since medicine is making so
little progress, the institute decided to call for an ambitious
series of steps to be taken, soon, all of which it says can cut
mistakes by 50 percent over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   First, it called on Congress to create a National Center for
Patient Safety. Modeling itself after agencies that regulate
airlines and workplaces, the center would set national
error-reduction goals, track progress in meeting them, and sponsor
research on new safety strategies.
</P>
<P>
   The institute also recommended laws that require hospitals and
other health care providers to report to state governments errors
that lead to serious injuries or deaths. And it called on HMOs,
corporations and the public to push health providers to design
systems that standardize procedures, simplify equipment and
otherwise build mistake-prevention into everything they do.
</P>
<P>
   Those steps would be expensive, with the Center for Patient
Safety eventually receiving upwards of $100 million a year. But
that pales next to the $15 billion to $30 billion a year that
preventable medical errors cost each year in terms of added health
expenses and lost days of work.
</P>
<P>
   The report, the first in a series the institute is issuing to
improve the quality of health care in America, was prepared by the
nation's leading experts in patient safety, including several from
Boston. Massachusetts has been a leader in requiring hospitals to
report their serious mistakes and in encouraging them to implement
the kinds of error-reduction strategies outlined in the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely makes sense,'' Andrew Dreyfus, executive vice
president of the Massachusetts Hospital Association, said of the
new study. ``I think if national leaders want a model of how to
comprehensively approach the problem of patient safety and medical
errors, they ought to come and look at what we've begun in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to see real results in hospitals and we're
seeing a surge of energy within the larger health care community .
. . We're doing it not government versus provider, or hospital
versus physician, but we're doing it all together.''
</P>
<P>
   Janet Corrigan, who directed the institute study, said that
while its recommendations are bold, they also ``are doable. I don't
want to say it will be easy, but it can be accomplished. It's very
reasonable to expect a 50 percent reduction in medical errors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
