<SLUG> BC-ALTAVISTA-RAGINGBULL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALTA VISTA ACQUIRES RAGING BULL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CMGI Inc., looking to strengthen two of its fast-growing
Internet investments, said Monday its AltaVista Web portal will
acquire Raging Bull Inc., an online investor chat forum that CMGI
helped launch.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the stock-for-stock transaction between the two
privately-held companies weren't released. AltaVista Co. is based
in Palo Alto, Calif. and Raging Bull is headquartered in Andover,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI, the venture capital investment and holding company based
in Andover, whose stock has grown sevenfold in the past 12 months,
saw its shares surge again Monday, closing at 155 1/2, up 8 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   By merging Raging Bull into AltaVista, CMGI furthers its
longstanding goal of linking its Internet portfolio of companies
together to create a destination site designed to appeal to a wide
audience . By adding Raging Bull's Web surfers to its AltaVista
portal, CMGI expects to build traffic and attract significant
advertising revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today it's Raging Bull for investors, but we see branching out
to create other online communities, like Raging Sports, Raging
Travel, Raging Health, even Raging Recipes,'' said Stephen Killeen,
who will continue as Raging Bull president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   His firm, which raised $20 million in venture capital since it
was formed in May 1998, is 50 percent owned by CMGI. It caters to
investors looking to swap information about stocks and chat about
strategies. Free to site visitors and supported by such long-term
advertisers as Fidelity Investments, National Discount Brokers and
Morgan Standley Dean Witter, Raging Bull has attracted significant
advertiser interest because people spend more than 20 minutes per
visit.
</P>
<P>
   In creating a community for non-professional stock pickers,
Raging Bull this year has also become the second most popular
online investor forum behind Yahoo! Inc.'s stock market and finance
section. Killeen said that of the 1.76 million Raging Bull
visitors, 315,000 are registered members, enabling them to post
messages and obtain real-time quotes.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista, initially created by Digital Equipment Corp. and
subsequently acquired by Compaq Computer Corp., became part of CMGI
earlier this year, when CMGI bought 83 percent of the Web portal
for $1.9 billion. Compaq is now a minority investor.
</P>
<P>
   The Raging Bull acquistion also strengthens CMGI plans for an
expected AltaVista initial public offering next year, noted some
Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raging Bull brings world-class financial content and one of
the Web's top indivicual investor communities to AltaVista,'' said
Rod Schrock, president and chief executive of AltaVista Co.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, AltaVista was the nation's 11th most visited site,
according to MediaMetrix, Inc. a New York-based Internet research
firm. With the acquistionn of Raging Bull, CMGI claims AltaVista
will rise to become the ninth largest portal, surpassing Amazon.com
and Time-Warner Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 1922EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
