u f BC-BOEING-SAFETY-BOS &LR;      11-29 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-SAFETY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TO SCRUTINIZE BOEING PRODUCTION METHODS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Aircraft-Safety)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Concerned about quality control problems at Boeing Co.
production facilities that led to parts failing flammability tests
and rivet guns left inside fuel tanks, the Federal Aviation
Administration said Monday it will begin an in-depth review of
quality assurance at the Seattle airplane manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials said there was no immediate safety concern
involving Boeing airplanes currently in service, but said the
special audit _ which will begin Thursday and last at least three
months _ will determine if the previous quality assurance slips are
isolated or something ``more systemic in nature,'' said Beth
Erickson, director of aircraft certification for the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   The evaluation comes a month after EgyptAir Flight 990, a Boeing
767-300 aircraft, crashed off Nantucket, Mass. killing all 217
passengers and crew. The National Transportation Safety Board,
which is investigating the crash, has found no mechanical problem
that would have caused the crash. Some investigators believe a
copilot may have deliberately caused the plane to crash.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials stressed that none of the four quality assurance
``slips'' resulted in accidents, and they believe them to be
isolated incidents. Each was discovered by Boeing or one of its
customers and the manufacturer alerted the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   The review will take place across Boeing's commercial product
line. Officials could not say whether it will affect the delivery
schedule of airplanes. ``That is a secondary issue for us,'' said
Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson said special evaluations ``always result in
improvements.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing had a scheduled audit in May 1998, and its last special
audit was in January 1998 concerning fasteners in 737 tail
assemblies.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson said the current audit ``is more in-depth and focused''
than a regularly scheduled biannual audit and will look at
communication between engineering and manufacturering, and parts
receiving and manufacturing planning. ``In essence, we are checking
requirements to see that the design that is spelled out is
implemented,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, you do not like to have the kinds of issues and
visibility we have had in the past few weeks,'' said Boeing
spokeswoman Susan Bradley. ``But we welcome the opportunity to
validate a system that we think works well.''
</P>
<P>
   The four recent problems that necessitated the special review
are:
</P>
<P>
   --American Airlines, in doing a heavy maintenance check of one
of its 767 aircraft discovered improperly tightened bolts in the
vertical fin of the airplane. Boeing then discovered a similar
problem in some planes in production.
</P>
<P>
   --Ventilation ducts in 737, 757 and 767 airplanes had an
adhesive sprayed on them to keep a Fiberglas wrapping in place,
rather than having the adhesive placed in strips as designed. As a
result, the excess adhesive failed a flammability test.
</P>
<P>
   --Fuel cell doors in airplanes are cleaned with a fluid and then
coated with an anticorrosive. Boeing changed the type of cleaning
solution used because of Environmental Protection Agency
requirements, and the coating no longer adhered as well. The
Associated Press reported debris such as sealant tubes and rivet
guns were left behind in some tanks.
</P>
<P>
   --Earlier this month, Boeing and the FAA said the company was
halting delivery on 747s, 757s, 767s, and 777s because a piece of
cockpit insulation was being manufactured improperly and in a burn
test ``failed miserably,'' said a high-ranking FAA official. A
different type of adhesive was used on the insulation, known as
drip shields. New drip shields were installed in planes in
production.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson said the FAA is still studying how best to remedy the
problems in planes that are in service. Together, the four problems
could affect thousands of aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA will have eight people working full-time on the audit
and will use the four cases as guideposts to look at how Boeing
builds airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of the bolts being undertightened, we saw an
inappropriate translation from an engineering requirement to a work
instruction and that could be a similar system issue in other
areas,'' said Erickson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
