<HEADER>
A4331 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-NLRB-INTERNS-BOS &LR;      11-29 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NLRB-INTERNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNS WIN RIGHT TO UNIONIZE AT PRIVATE HOSPITALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Labor Relations Board agreed Monday with a group of
Boston Medical Center interns and residents that
physicians-in-training have the right to unionize in private
hospitals across the nation _ and strike if they choose to.
</P>
<P>
   Partisans on both sides predicted the board's 3-2 decision _
overturning a 23-year-old precedent _ will be a watershed in the
relations between US teaching hospitals and the interns and
residents who provide much of their patient care.
</P>
<P>
   Many said it is also likely to boost emerging US efforts to
unionize American physicians in general. ``This changes the
climate,'' said Ross Rubin of Physicians for Responsible
Negotiations, a doctors' union recently organized by the American
Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to imagine that this decision won't stimulate that
kind of activity,'' agreed Dr. Jordan Cohen, president of the
Association of American Medical Colleges, which strenuously opposed
the recognition of interns' and residents' unions. ``This is not a
happy day for the medical profession.''
</P>
<P>
   However, many within the profession _ from the president of the
AMA to left-wing unionists _ were buoyed by the federal board's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas Reardon, the AMA president, said in an interview that
residents and interns convinced the association that ``they were
not being heard by hospitals and deans on issues like working
hours, reimbursement, and patient care concerns.'' The AMA filed a
brief supporting the Boston doctors' case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many residents will be pleased'' by the federal board's
decision, said Dr. Andrew Yacht, chief medical resident at Boston
Medical Center. ``With hospitals merging right and left and
ancillary staff being cut, I don't think anybody's happy waiting
around to see where the ax falls next.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the National Labor Relations Board decision,
Boston Medical Center must hold an election within 30 days on
formal recognition of the House Officers Association, which was
born in 1948 at Boston City Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Although Boston Medical Center argued against compulsory union
recognition on the grounds that it would disrupt training programs,
the hospital's general counsel, Edward J. Christiansen, said in a
statement that the outcome ``will have little effect.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision resulted from a petition filed three years ago by
the House Officers Association at Boston Medical Center,
representing 430 interns and residents.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from the Boston City Council, the House Officers
Association won grudging recognition on a voluntary basis from
Boston Medical Center when the private nonprofit hospital was
created in mid-1996, through the merger of Boston City Hospital and
the private University Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors' group then petitioned the National Labor Relations
Board to overturn its 1976 decision, in a Los Angeles case, that
interns and residents were not entitled to collective bargaining
rights because they are primarily students, not employees.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the Los Angeles decision and a similar 1977 one ``flawed
in many respects,'' the majority of the the Labor Relations Board
said it was convinced by ``the overwhelming weight of judicial and
scholarly opinion that the Board reached an erroneous conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're delighted with the board's decision because it gives
collecting bargaining rights to over 90,000 hardworking interns and
residents on the front lines of health care,'' said Dr. Ladi
Haroona, president of the New York City-based Committee of Interns
and Residents, a national union of which the Boston House Officers
Association is a local arm.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the 1976 decision, only 10,000 of the nation's
103,000 interns and residents are unionized. They work primarily in
public hospitals in states that give collective bargaining rights
to public-sector employees, but not the right to strike.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Levy, executive director of the Committee of Interns and
Residents, said the group, an affiliate of the Service Employees
International Union, will step up efforts to organize doctors in
private hospitals, especially in California and the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there will be organizing in New York and the Boston
area,'' Levy said. ``We have had had phone calls and meetings with
residents. That will continue on a different level now that people
have rights.''
</P>
<P>
   There was general agreement Monday that the federal board's
decision will change the balance of power in perennial disputes
over such issues as trainees' working hours, even in hospitals that
stave off unionization.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, whose organization represents US medical schools and
teaching hospitals, said he hoped his members would step up efforts
to make interns and residents feel their complaints about hours and
working conditions are being heard so they won't ``feel the need to
align themselves with traditional labor unions.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Labor Relations Board decision gives residents,
interns, and postgraduate trainees called fellows the right to
strike, that issue is a sensitive one among physician organizers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that issue is really a smokescreen,'' Levy said.
Official recognition of collective bargaining rights, he said,
``should decrease the chances of conflict'' between physicians and
teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   In organizing interns and residents across the country, the
Committee of Interns and Residents will be competing against an AMA
spinoff, Physicians for Responsible Negotiations, which has
renounced the right to strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are physicians first and foremost,'' said Yacht when asked
about the possibility of striking. ``I would hope and pray nobody
in our position would ever jeopardize patient care. However, we may
need to take action sometimes to protect our ability to take care
of patients.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, members of the House Officers Association at Boston
City Hospital went on a six-day strike, but they maintained
staffing for emergencies during the job action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 1929EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
