<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4332 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-R-SCI-COSMOLOGY-PHYSI     11-29 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SCI-COSMOLOGY-PHYSICS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALCULATING THE WEIGHT OF NOTHINGNESS CALLED SCIENCE'S NO. 1
MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to correct slug on 2nd Take)  (nk) 
 By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the sorcerer's apprentice, who could not banish the spirits
that his spells had conjured up, astronomers around the world have
been trying _ with increasing desperation _ to disprove an
astonishing discovery announced early last year: Distant galaxies
are being swept apart, ever faster, by a tide formed of apparently
empty space.
</P>
<P>
   Although scientists have long known that the universe is
expanding, they had assumed that the expansion was gradually
slowing because of the gravitational attractions of the galaxies.
Instead, scientists announced last year, some antigravity effect
seemed to be accelerating the expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The finding was such a challenge to conventional theories that
most scientists assumed they would quickly discredit the theory.
But almost two years of effort to do so has yielded observational
data that only support the conclusion. Last month, a subtle but
initially promising objection to the measurements of the
accelerating expansion by one group of astronomers was disproved by
a new analysis of that data.
</P>
<P>
   And just last week, a different team of astronomers reported its
observations of ripples in the gases of the young universe, before
stars and galaxies had even formed. Though the observations
supported a favored theory of how the universe began, they also
provided fresh new evidence of the distressing finding that
something in the wastelands of space could be pushing against
gravity. So scientists are reluctantly accepting the notion that
something in the most fundamental theories of physics is terribly
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   To explain their observations, scientists say, they must answer
a question that sounds paradoxical: How much does emptiness weigh?
</P>
<P>
   Although the answer has eluded scientists since Einstein first
raised the question more than 70 years ago, physicists are
comfortable with the idea that a seemingly perfect vacuum could
weigh something. According to the theory of elementary particle
physics, even a vacuum is filled with fields containing energy and
evanescent particles that flit in and out of existence, adding heft
to nothingness.
</P>
<P>
   According to Einstein, this ``funny energy,'' as cosmologists
have sometimes called it, would be so different from ordinary
matter and energy that it would have the opposite gravitational
effect, producing repulsion instead of attraction.
</P>
<P>
   But when physicists try to use conventional theories to
calculate how much energy should repose in emptiness, the result is
a vacuum so monstrously heavy that it would blow the universe
apart. Galaxies, stars, planets and life could never have formed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest embarrassment in theoretical physics,''
Dr. Michael Turner, an astrophysicist and cosmologist at the
University of Chicago, said of the weight problem. ``Every attempt
to calculate it has gotten an absurd answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Frank Wilczek, a particle physicist at the Institute for
Advanced Study in Princeton, N.J., called the nothingness problem
``maybe the most fundamentally mysterious thing in basic science.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeff Harvey, a physicist at the University of Chicago, said,
``Basically, people don't have a clue as to how to solve this
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Some physicists have gone so far as to wash their hands of the
search for a solution, suggesting simply that all of the calculated
weight of a vacuum is the product of imperfect theories and that
some other strange inhabitant of empty space could be pushing the
galaxies apart. They call this shifting, flowing form of energy
quintessence.
</P>
<P>
   Though any weight of the vacuum should stay the same over cosmic
time, accelerating the expansion with a steady nudge, quintessence
could push more strongly at some times, more weakly at others.
Because the key to those changes may lie in the properties of
matter and space as they exist at energies that are unattainable on
earth, the universe would become in effect a giant physics
experiment, said Dr. Andreas J. Albrecht, a physicist at the
University of California in Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Quintessence or no quintessence, until the weight problem is
solved, physicists are forced to concede that they do not have a
fully working theory of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, not only for cosmology but for elementary particle
theory, this is the bone in our throat,'' said Dr. Steven Weinberg,
a professor of physics and astronomy at the University of Texas,
who shared a Nobel Prize in 1979 for his work in theories of
elementary particle physics.
</P>
<P>
   And for all the difficulties presented by the observations that
distant galaxies are flying apart faster and faster, those
observations have actually helped to solidify other cosmic
theories, especially one that predicts the amount of matter and
energy in the universe and explains how it formed large structures.
That makes the observations impossible to dismiss.
</P>
<P>
   The provoking measurements were first reported last year by two
teams of astronomers, one led by Dr. Saul Perlmutter of Lawrence
Berkeley National Laboratory and one by Dr. Brian Schmidt of the
Mount Stromlo and Siding Spring Observatory in Australia. The
astronomers used the unexpected dimness of exploding stars in
far-off galaxies, the dimness indicating their unexpectedly great
distance, to show that the cosmic expansion discovered decades
earlier has been speeding up over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most astronomers, it was a very uncomfortable, unsettling
thing,'' said Dr. Robert Kirshner, a member of Schmidt's group at
the Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the new observations of cosmic acceleration were so
unsettling, said Albrecht of the University of California, that ``a
reasonable position for someone to take is that the observations
are wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   So astronomers have done everything they can to find a flaw. But
since the first announcements, dozens of new observations have
offered nothing but support.
</P>
<P>
   Now Perlmutter has proposed a satellite that would observe
thousands of exploding stars a year to make even more stringent
tests of the original findings.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If there is a sorcerer in this tale of nothingness, it would be
Einstein, who formulated his theory of general relativity in 1915.
That theory successfully describes how gravity warps space and
moves galaxies, stars, planets and other matter around in the
cosmos. But when Einstein applied his theory to the entire
universe, which was thought at the time to be static and
unchanging, he realized that the mutual attraction of all its
galaxies would rapidly cause them to collapse together in a fiery
catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   So Einstein theorized in 1917 that some other force must be
holding things apart. He called this theoretical fudge factor ``the
cosmological constant'' and thought of it as a uniform energy
permeating all of space. Because of Einstein's equation describing
the equivalence of mass and energy, E(EQ)mc2, the energy of the
cosmological constant can also be regarded as mass, or weight.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years later, though, Einstein was rethinking his
fudge factor. By then, astronomers had discovered that galaxies
were not static, after all, but were flying apart as a legacy of
what they theorize was the Big Bang explosion, to which most
cosmologists attribute the origin of the universe. Gravity would at
most slow down the expansion and cause a re-collapse hundreds of
billions of years in the future, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   The fudge factor was unnecessary; in fact, Einstein renounced it
and called it his ``biggest blunder.'' Though the idea saw sporadic
revivals over the decades, it ended in obscurity. So the discovery
that Einstein might have been right in the first place has left
physicists at a loss. ``Clearly, there is something that
everybody's missing,'' said Wilczek, who happens to live in the
house Einstein once occupied in Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   The weight problem ``would be No. 1 on my list of things to
figure out,'' said Dr. Edward Witten, a physicist at the Institute
for Advanced Study, who leads the effort using an advanced theory
called string theory to unify what is known about the interactions
of all particles in the universe.
</P>
<P>
   That urgency has led Weinberg and others to a suggestion that
some physicists regard as desperate. He has raised the possibility
that there have been many Big Bang universes, most of which really
do have huge cosmological constants that are incompatible with
life. But by the luck of the draw, a very few would have lighter
vacuums like the one in this universe, and only in such universes
could life, and physicists, exist to ponder the problem.
</P>
<P>
   But not even Weinberg seems convinced that this solution is the
right one. In one of his papers on the topic, he included a poem by
Hughes Mearns that captures the endless frustration that physicists
have faced in calculating the weight of emptiness:
</P>
<P>
   As I was going up the stair
</P>
<P>
   I met a man who wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't there again today.
</P>
<P>
   I wish, I wish he'd stay away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 1930EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4336 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-STEMCELL-RESEARCH-BOS     11-29 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEMCELL-RESEARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOETHICISTS URGE PANEL TO OVERSEE STEM CELL USE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been a year since scientists reported isolating ``stem
cells'' from days-old human embryos, saying it could open a new
medical frontier in which specialized cells derived from stem cells
might be used to repair almost any body part damaged by disease or
aging.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this potential, stem cell research has lagged because of
unresolved ethical and political debates over the use of human
embryos to obtain the key cells.
</P>
<P>
   Now, three bioethicists are calling for an end to the impasse
and the establishment of a federal panel to oversee all embryo and
stem cell research, both public and private.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that research using human embryos can secure US
public support if that support is accompanied by much more explicit
and open federal regulation and oversight,'' the ethicists write in
a commentary being published Tuesday in the journal Nature
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The authors are George Annas of the Boston University School of
Public Health, Arthur Caplan of the University of Pennsylvania
Medical Center, and Dr. Sherman Elias of the University of Illinois
at Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, federal funds can't be used for any research in which
human embryos, such as those created by in vitro fertilization, are
destroyed. As a result, private funds were used in isolating the
stem cells, and private firms are carrying out most of the research
aimed at medical applications of stem cells. This is
``unsatisfactory public policy,'' the ethicists said, and called
for private and public embryo research to be overseen by the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The ethicists specifically criticized a Massachusetts biotech
company that's pursuing stem cell research, Advanced Cell
Technology Inc. of Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   ACT officials said last November that they had combined adult
human cells with cow eggs that had been stripped of their nucleus.
The result, a clone made much the way Dolly the sheep was created,
was a hybrid human-cow embryo which did not, however, develop into
a fetus. Their intent, ACT officials said, was to produce stem
cells for making repair organs and tissues, not to create an
individual.
</P>
<P>
   But ACT's announcement of the human-cow embryo research was made
to a newspaper, not a scientific journal: company officials said it
was intended to spark a national ethical debate. The bioethicists
called the episode ``disturbing'' and said ethics ``must be
discussed before proceeding, not after the research is a fait
accompli.'' They also said the potential dangers of mixing human
and cow DNA are not well understood, and added, ``there is a
powerful moral case against using this source of stem cells in
human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, ACT chief executive officer Michael West said in an
interview Monday that the bioethicists' objections are moot,
because other research suggests that the small amount of cow DNA in
the laboratory-made embryo eventually vanishes, leaving a wholly
human embryo.
</P>
<P>
   West said he knew he was risking criticism by announcing the
human-cow research to a newspaper instead of reporting it in a
scientific journal, but wanted to launch a wide debate on the
ethics before going further with the project.
</P>
<P>
   The ethical dilemmas of stem cell research have been reviewed by
the National Bioethics Advisory Commission, the National Institutes
of Health, and the American Association for the Advancement of
Science. The NBAC issued a report in September saying it was
morally appropriate to take stem cells from embryos created by in
vitro fertilization for couples who decided they no longer want
them. (Such research could not be funded by the federal government
under current law.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it does make sense to sacrifice some embryos'' to make
stem cell research possible, said Caplan, the Pennsylvania
bioethicist, in an interview Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, Caplan said, the various parties in the controversy
have avoided facing that issue head-on. What's needed, he said, is
to have a debate in Congress on whether embryos remaining after
fertility treatments can ethically be used to obtain stem cells,
and if the answer is yes (as he and the other ethicists think it
should be), the research could go forward under the oversight of
the special federal panel they recommend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
