<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-TV-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES REFUSE TO REVIEW CLOSED-CIRCUIT TV CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Over the objection of two justices, the Supreme
Court on Monday refused to consider the appeal of a convicted Texas
child molester who claimed he was denied a fair trial because of
the television testimony of a young accuser.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Steven Marx said his constitutional rights were violated
because a young witness to his sexual assault of a 13-year-old girl
was allowed to testify against him by closed-circuit television.
This televised testimony violated the Sixth Amendment requirement
that criminal defendants be permitted to confront their accusers in
open court, argued Marx's attorney, F.N. ``Trey'' Brown III of
Burnet, Texas, in the ill-fated appeal to the high court.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas disagreed with the
court's refusal to hear Marx's case, saying that ``the plain
meaning of the Bill of Rights'' demands that defendants have the
right to confront their accusers in person.
</P>
<P>
   Under Supreme Court practice, at least four of the nine justices
must vote to consider an appeal. The high court did not disclose
whether any other justice joined Scalia and Thomas in voting to
hear Marx's case.
</P>
<P>
   The court's refusal to consider the appeal sets no national
precedent. But the justices' action leaves in place Texas court
decisions that allow young child-abuse witnesses to testify by
closed-circuit television.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of televised testimony arose at Marx's April 1995
Burnet County trial on charges of aggravated sexual assault. The
judge, at prosecutors' request, permitted the alleged victim and
the young witness, identified in court papers only as J.M., to
testify via closed-circuit television.
</P>
<P>
   The judge concluded that both girls would be ``traumatized'' if
required to testify in Marx's presence.
</P>
<P>
   The jury, after hearing all the testimony, convicted Marx of
aggravated sexual assault. He was sentenced to 23 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The case went to the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals, which
affirmed the conviction, 5-4. The state justices, by the slimmest
of majorities, said having the 6-year-old witness give televised
testimony did not violate Marx's Sixth Amendment right to confront
his accusers.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the Texas court cited the U.S. Supreme Court's
1990 decision in Maryland vs. Craig that the Constitution permits
televised testimony in limited circumstances, such as when an
alleged victim of child abuse would suffer serious emotional trauma
if required to testify in front of her alleged attacker.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, Marx's attorney, appealed to the U.S. Supreme Court,
arguing that the 1990 ruling allowed young victims _ but not mere
witnesses _ to testify outside the presence of their alleged
attacker.
</P>
<P>
   The high court, without explanation, rejected the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 1941EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
