<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Dec. 5) 
(jt) 
 By JOSEPH SIANO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking for Maigret
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are there any tours that focus on the Parisian locations
mentioned by Georges Simenon in his Inspector Maigret novels? _
Sheila Lesser, The Bronx, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. You could start where the chief inspector ``lived,'' along
the Boulevard Richard Lenoir _ at 132, based on references in the
novels _ in the 11th Arrondissement. In the popular novels by the
Belgian author Georges Simenon, Chief Inspector Jules Maigret also
regularly dined at a fictional restaurant, Chez Paul, which is on
the very real Place Dauphine on the Ile de la Cite, in the First
Arrondissement. Elsewhere on the island, you'll find the
headquarters of the Police Judiciaire, at 36, Quai des Orfevres,
where Maigret (and his real-life counterparts) set to solving
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But be aware that most of Simenon's 100-plus Maigret novels and
short stories were written 30 to 60 years ago, set in a Paris of
long ago. And while Simenon was a master at capturing the feel of
the city, he did not rely on the kind of specific locations that
make it easy to assemble the kind of tour you seek.
</P>
<P>
   But there are guidebooks to provide some clues. Try ``Cafes of
Paris,'' by Christine Graf, which identifies a number of favorite
haunts. A 192-page paperback, it costs $13.95 plus $4 shipping from
The Literate Traveller, 8306 Wilshire Boulevard, No. 591, Beverly
Hills, Calif. 90211; (800) 850-2665.
</P>
<P>
   There's also an out-of-print book, ``Simenon's Paris,'' a guide
to the Paris of Maigret by the man who ought to know, Simenon
himself. This 1970 hardcover book (Dial Press, New York) is
available at www.barnesandnoble.com, at prices varying from $49 to
$63, depending on condition, or www.alibris.com, for $23. At
www.amazon.com, they'll query used-book dealers to try to find a
copy for you, too. It has maps on the endpapers and illustrations
by Frederick Franck. Just be sure (if you cannot read French) that
you buy an English-language edition.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Discovering Paris Bistros'' (Interlink Publishing Group,
Northampton, Mass.), Gaston Wijnen devotes a chapter to tiny
restaurants that the inspector would have enjoyed. This 1991 book
is out of print, but the online booksellers listed above had copies
for $10.36 to $17.
</P>
<P>
   There's an online chat room, www.trussel.com/maig/maibul.htm,
that can put you in touch with fellow Maigret fans, and you can
call up www.trussel.com/maig/marcom.htm for a discussion of Paris
addresses in Maigret novels.
</P>
<P>
   You can also contact the Paris Convention and Visitors Bureau,
127, Avenue des Champs-Elysees, (33-8) 36.68.31.12.
</P>
<P>
   Ferry to Venice
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be in Trieste, Italy, in the spring and would like to
go to Venice by boat. Is there passenger service between the two
cities? _ Camille Hardy, New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is no ferry between Trieste and Venice, but if you are
determined to make this crossing of the Gulf of Venice, a 50-minute
trip south to Portoroz in Slovenia will take you to a boat that
does so.
</P>
<P>
   The hydrofoil Prince of Venice, a 128-foot vessel with 330
seats, a bar and a gift shop, operates from April 1 to Oct. 31.
Next year's schedule has not been set; this year, there were
departures from Portoroz daily at 8 a.m., with arrival in Venice at
10:30 a.m. It returned from Venice at 5:30 p.m., arriving in
Portoroz at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The one-way adult fare was $42, and round trip was $60; for ages
4 to 14, the round-trip fare was $30. For more information, contact
the Slovenian Tourist Office at (212) 358-9686 or
www.slovenia-tourism.si.
</P>
<P>
   Estate Planning
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there public transit from Paris to Vaux-le-Vicomte? What
about from London to Chatsworth? _ Lawrence J. Wathen Jr., Houston.
</P>
<P>
   A. Both of these large estates can be reached by public transit
or, in the case of Chatsworth, a package that includes breakfast,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with that one. Midland Mainline, (44-990) 125 242,
operates at least three trips a week to Chatsworth from April
through October. It begins with a train from St. Pancras station in
London to Chesterfield, the rail station nearest Chatsworth. From
there, a bus will take you to Chatsworth, where the private art
collection of the Duke and Duchess of Devonshire includes
4,000-year-old Egyptian carvings and works by Rembrandt and
Gainsborough. The rates are $49.80 for standard class (including
admission to the house and garden), $54.78 for first class (with
admission to the house, garden and Regency Scots Room) and $66.40
for all of that plus a full cooked English breakfast (all prices at
$1.66 to a pound). The train leaves London 8:30 a.m. and reaches
Chatsworth by 11:30. The bus leaves Chatsworth at 4:30 p.m., and
you should be back in London by 7:45. Departures are Tuesday
through Thursday, more often if there is enough demand. Or you can
take the train to Chesterfield, then a public bus to Baslow, a
short walk from Chatsworth.
</P>
<P>
   To reach Vaux-le-Vicomte, the estate of Nicholas Fouquet
completed in 1661 that is considered to be the inspiration for
Versailles, you would go to the Gare de Lyon in Paris and take the
D2 line of the RER (the suburban Paris rail system) to Melun (about
a 30-minute ride). From Melun, it is about a four-mile cab ride to
the chateau.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson's Other Home
</P>
<P>
   Q. We have been to Monticello, but only recently heard of
Jefferson's second home near Forest, Va. Can you tell us what is on
display and details of visiting it? _ Richard and Nancy Russell,
Jersey Shore, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   A. The house, Poplar Forest, is off Route 661 near Lynchburg,
(804) 525-1806, near the Blue Ridge Parkway. It is about a two-hour
ride from Charlottesville (two and a half days in 1806, when
construction began), and was a hideaway for Jefferson, where he
could read, write and play with his grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   After Jefferson, the estate passed through several hands and was
extensively modified. About 20 years ago, it was close to being
demolished, but local residents bought the house. In 1986, it
opened to visitors and restoration work continues.
</P>
<P>
   The six-room octagonal house is undergoing renovation to bring
it back to its original condition, and watching this work is the
main attraction for visitors, as are a number of archaeological
digs on the 501-acre property. The house contains no furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   Poplar Forest is closed for the year. It will reopen in April.
Hours will be 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. daily through November. Admission:
$7, seniors $6, 6 to 16 $1.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
