<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4346 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-MISSING-CHILDREN-B     11-29 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-MISSING-CHILDREN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBERS SCAN BIBLE FOR CLUES TO MISSING CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investigators trying to find two children missing from an
religious sect in Attleboro, Mass. are turning to the Bible for
help as they try to decode hundreds of pages of notes laden with
religious allusions.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the Christian sect helped maintain copious
notes about the group's activities, according to Gerald Fizgerald,
a Bristol County assistant district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The notes, filling enough notebooks to pack a box of office
paper, ``are chock full'' of references to passages in the Bible,
Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're obviously very religious people,'' Fitzgerald said.
``Each reference might be relevant, so you look it up. You've got
to, to make sure you know what you're talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Police say they suspect that in September members of the
religious community buried the bodies of two children in Baxter
State Park in central Maine.
</P>
<P>
   One of the children, Samuel Robidoux, age 1 1/2, may have
starved to death because a sect member had a vision in which God
ordered that he be fed breast milk instead of solid food, according
to an entry in one of sect's journals seized by police.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel's cousin, Jeremiah Corneau, was stillborn.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators seized the notebooks from the group's Knight
Avenue home in Attleboro on Nov. 19 and ``went through them once
quickly,''looking for direct references to where the two boys might
be buried in Maine, Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a group of police officers are rereading the material ``for
all the content, an extremely laborious process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a Bible as guide, it is sometimes difficult to make
sense of the notes, because they are written only for members of
the insular community, according to Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like sitting down and reading a book,'' he said.
``You can't knock it off like a mystery novel. ``The notes assume a
certain knowledge. They're not written for a second or third
party's eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   A key piece of information in the case was provided by a
9-year-old girl who belongs to the sect and told authorities that
Samuel ``wasn't feeding'' before he died and that the infant was
born ``without a breath.'' The girl also said that the children's
bodies were taken to Maine in a truck and buried in the state park
during a camping trip two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   A four-day search of Baxter State Park with dogs trained to
sniff for corpses was suspended a week ago after police combed the
area but failed to locate any remains.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen adults and 12 children belonged to the religious
sect, which follows a version of Christianity devised by Roger
Daneau and Samuel's grandfather, Roland Robidoux, who works as a
mason and a chimney sweeper.
</P>
<P>
   They interpret the Bible themselves and reject modern medicine,
to the point that group members could not wear glasses or seek
dental care, according to people who have dealt with the sect.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the group have refused to provide any information on
the missing children.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel's father, Jaques Robidoux, is in jail on charges of
contempt of court after refusing to tell authorities the location
of his son. Karen Robidoux, the mother of the missing child, was
released from jail when she invoked her Fifth Amendments rights
against self-incrimination after investigators asked about her
son's whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   David Corneau, Jeremiah's father, told authorities his son was
stillborn in August and ``never had a breath of life.'' But Corneau
refused to say where he buried the baby.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Social Services has taken custody of the
other children belonging to the community.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
