<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4347 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LONDON-YOUNG-ARTISTS-     11-29 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-YOUNG-ARTISTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LONDON, THE LAST `SENSATION' GIVES WAY TO THE NEXT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: the Netherlands, Calif.) (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ When you ask regulars of the London art scene what they
think of the furor caused in New York City by ``Sensation,'' the
exhibition of work by young British artists (or YBA's) at the
Brooklyn Museum of Art, you get a range of reactions.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are proud that the show packs such a wallop abroad.
Others seem taken aback by the vehemence of the outcry against it,
like the London gallery owner who exclaimed: ``My God! In the land
of the free!'' Still others cynically commend Charles Saatchi, the
English advertising executive who owns all the work in
``Sensation,'' for orchestrating further publicity for his
collection and the artists.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Dinos Chapman, whose sexually mutated mannequins,
produced in collaboration with his brother, Jake, have contributed
to the Brooklyn controversy. Feigning perplexed anxiety, Chapman
asked, ``Does this mean I have to go back to being a YBA again?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sensation'' is dead. Long live ``Sensation.'' A paraphrase of
that famous royal news flash seems to sum up the lively artistic
mood in London right now. The emergence of the YBA's _ or
``Sensation artists'' or ``Saatchi artists'' _ is a historic moment
that changed the stature of contemporary English art at home and
abroad. Yet the artists and Saatchi are being absorbed into an
expanding art scene.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of this expansion are numerous. The most prominent is the
coming of the Tate Modern, the gargantuan annex of the Tate
Gallery, which will open on the south side of the Thames next
spring. One of the world's largest museums devoted exclusively to
20th-century art, it will undoubtedly change the balance of power
in the international art world, especially among museums of
contemporary and modern art. Perhaps in anticipation, the gallery
scene is in a state of flux characterized by relocations and new
arrivals and is increasingly international. A small but telling
detail: The New York art dealer Larry Gagosian will open a London
branch next spring, something an American has not done in years, if
ever.
</P>
<P>
   The pace always quickens before the announcement of the Tate's
Turner Prize for a British artist. The work of four artists on this
year's short list has been on view at the Tate since late October.
The winner, on whom English bookies take bets, will be announced in
London on Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Turner show probably shouldn't be taken as a sign
that the reign of Saatchi is ending. Nonetheless its balance is
noteworthy. It contains only one YBA, Tracy Emin, down from a high
of three out of four in 1995, when the YBA ringleader, Damien
Hirst, won the prize, which is accompanied by nearly $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Emin is almost a caricature of YBA flamboyance. She makes
sensationally autobiographical art. (Her piece in the Brooklyn show
is a tent appliqued with the names of all the people she's ever
slept with.) By now she is as well known as Hirst; her name and
picture are constantly in the British papers, and she is said to be
idolized by teenage girls. Her display in the Tate show includes a
disheveled bed surrounded by drug paraphernalia, condoms and dirty
underwear. The day after the show opened, The Times of London ran a
cartoon with the caption: ``I don't care if it is art _ make it!''
</P>
<P>
   The other three Turner show artists all make cerebral works in
videos or photography. Jane and Louise Wilson, who specialize in
four-screen video installations of ``sites of power,'' have
unveiled a piece alternating long tracking shots of an empty Las
Vegas casino and the inside of nearby Hoover Dam. (The Wilsons also
exhibited three similar but better pieces at the Serpentine Art
Gallery this fall, including one on the Houses of Parliaments.)
</P>
<P>
   The reclusive tinkerer Steven Pippin is showing several suites
of murky photographs depicting himself or a horse in Muybridge-like
sequences, all taken and developed with washing machines that he
converted into cameras and darkrooms. Steve McQueen is represented
by three toned-down videos, including a particularly modest
1970s-style one that centers on a tape recorder emitting fast
clackity-clack sounds that is suddenly pulled heavenward by a
balloon.
</P>
<P>
   If, as is often said, London is having its New York-style 1980s
in the '90s, this gathering suggests that it is on schedule to
begin its version of the relatively dour early '90s just after
2000. Either Ms. Emin or McQueen is favored to win.
</P>
<P>
   Contrasting with the dryness of this year's Turner show is the
cute and cuddly work in ``Neurotic Realism, Part II,'' the latest
offering at Saatchi's gallery on Boundary Road. Visitors there
lingered near the door to study a display of front pages from New
York newspapers featuring ``Sensation'' and related political
cartoons, all neatly framed and hanging on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Including five artists of widely dispersed sensibilities and low
quality, ``Neurotic Realism'' seems to be an attempt to collate and
name an art movement instead of just collecting new or emerging
trends. It also seems designed to showcase the work of Martin
Maloney, a painter of large, pleasantly faux-naif figurative works
who is included in ``Sensation'' and is especially close to
Saatchi.
</P>
<P>
   The best impression is made by Peter Davies' big, bright
paintings that entertainingly diagram the art world and also reveal
the obsessive inner workings of an artist's mind. ``The Hip One
Hundred'' charts the artists, both living and dead, whose work has
inspired Davies, listed in order of admiration, with notes.
</P>
<P>
   Even better is ``Fun With Animals: Joseph Beuys Text Painting,''
a large canvas featuring bright circles connected by dizzying
networks of lines that plot the artists and art movements of the
20th century in terms of influence, stylistic affinities,
personality traits (``machoness'' is a particularly busy juncture,
for example), subject matter (terrorism) and materials (food).
Davies' abstract paintings are similarly seriously entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   The unevenness of ``Neurotic Realism'' illustrates what many
people forget about Saatchi when they froth on about his power and
influence: His purchases are almost as random and indiscriminate as
fate itself. The vast majority of the artists whose work he buys
and exhibits are quickly forgotten; those who become
internationally known are validated in many other quarters by
dealers, collectors, critics and museums. This point is further
underscored by a quick browse through a thick new book about his
British art holdings that is immodestly titled ``Young British Art:
The Saatchi Decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you call the decade, it will end on May 12, when Queen
Elizabeth II opens the Tate Modern, across the Thames from and to
the east of the Tate Gallery, which will be renamed the Tate
Britain in March. To measure the new museum's probable effect on
London, think of Paris with the Eiffel Tower, Centre Beaubourg and
Musee d'Orsay rolled into one.
</P>
<P>
   The structure has been redesigned by the widely admired Swiss
architects Jacques Herzog and Pierre de Meuron, who have left it
handsomely plain. With 84 galleries featuring 150,000 square feet
of exhibition space and a high frequency of tall ceilings and
natural light, it will be one of the best showcases for
contemporary art in the world and is expected to attract collectors
with works to donate or at least place on extended loan from all
over. A remnant of its days as a power station is a flatbed car and
train tracks once used to move engines around the vast Turbine
Hall; they will be used to move large sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   The cathedral-size Turbine Hall is the museum's entry hall,
thrilling to walk into or to overlook from the four floors of
galleries. This space, along with the Tate Modern's riverside
location and views, should make it an instant landmark. The
two-story frosted-glass penthouse with which Herzog and de Meuron
have crowned their redesign handsomely complements the original
boxy brick monolith, and taxicab drivers already point it out. A
footbridge designed by the architect Norman Foster and the sculptor
Anthony Caro will stretch from the Tate Modern's esplanade across
the Thames to the steps leading up to St. Paul's. (MORE)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   London's gallery scene is giving off several forms of heat, much
of it international. More and more London galleries are being
opened by non-British dealers and more and more are showing
non-British art, a function that Saatchi's gallery largely filled
in the 1980s. This fall's offerings included the Americans Doug
Aitken at Victoria Miro, Michael Askin at Emily Tsingou Liz Craft
and Pentti Monkkonen (two Los Angeles artists who have not shown in
New York) at Sadie Coles HQ; Tim Claasen, a Dutch sculptor, at
Stephen Friedman; and two young Italian artists, Francesco Vezzoli
at Anthony D'Offay and Stefano Arienti at Greengrassi.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly galleries are opening in or relocating to London's
sprawling East End, where artists live and work in great numbers,
and loftlike light-manufacturing buildings abound. The area already
merits its own a small bright yellow map, put out by the Pale Green
Press, which lists 22.
</P>
<P>
   One point of East End concentration is the area around the
Bethnal Green subway station, where one can find Maureen Paley's
relocated and expanded Interim Art, showing the latest video _ a
Roshomon-like tale of two drunken suburban couples _ from Gillian
Wearing, the 1997 Turner Prize winner. At the Approach, a few
minutes away above a pub by the same name, one can see big
paintinglike embroideries of glamorous action heroes by Enrico
David, an Italian artist who lives in London. Around a couple of
corners is the Anthony Wilkinson Gallery with a show of new work by
the witty neo-Conceptualist who calls himself Bob and Roberta
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   New clusters in the Clerkenwell- Shoreditch area of the East End
include the Cabinet gallery near St. John Street, Laure Gennillard
and Andrew Mummery. Perhaps the most significant sign of this drift
is the news that Jay Jopling and Ms. Miro, two of the most
prominent West End dealers in contemporary art, are opening in this
area. Jopling has bought a large building on Hoxton Square and
plans to open it in April or May. Ms. Miro is buying a 19th-century
former furniture factory off City Road near the Old Street subway
stop and plans to open in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   One of the quietest signs of London's embrace of contemporary
art is ``Ecce Homo,'' a public sculpture by Mark Wallinger, whose
unremarkable paintings of thoroughbred horses, depicted at
life-size, are in the Brooklyn ``Sensation'' show. The London piece
is unremarkable, too, but strikingly so: it is a life-size statue
in cast and sculptured marbelized resin of Jesus standing with his
arms bound behind his back and his head slightly bowed, isolated
and alone, on a giant plinth in Trafalgar Square.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the commotion of traffic, architecture and monuments, which
include occupied plinths and of course Nelson's column, it is as
easy to miss as the plunging figure with the melting wings in
Bruegel's ``Icarus.'' But once you find it, its dramatic quiet and
smallness accentuate the grandiosity of everything around it.
</P>
<P>
   Wallinger's piece, which will come down in February, is part of
the city's millennial celebrations and the first of three six-month
installations commissioned for the square's ``fourth plinth,'' left
bare for more than 100 years because it could not be decided whom
it should honor. Works by Bill Woodrow and Rachel Whiteread will
follow. Ms. Whiteread will make a full-scale 70-ton resin replica
of the plinth that will double the plinth's height, but be
inverted. The piece will be created on the spot, with a single
giant pour of resin into a cast built atop the plinth. This should
be the kind of spectacle London is used to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
