<HEADER>
A4349 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-POLLUTE-STUDY-BOS &LR;      11-29 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLUTE-STUDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT CITES LAX US ENFORCEMENT IN POLLUTION CASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most US companies suspected of breaking environmental laws are
never charged with a crime, with federal prosecutors sometimes
opting to seek civil fines instead of pursuing criminal sanctions,
according to a government report released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors declined to prosecute 70 percent of the
cases referred by the Environmental Protection Agency and other
investigators against US companies for possible criminal
environmental violations, the study by the Bureau of Justice
Statistics found.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, corporations investigated for polluting were less
likely to be prosecuted than individuals accused of similar crimes,
according to the study. Fifty-five percent of the cases involving
individuals investigated for environmental crimes were declined by
federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton Administration has been criticized by some
environmental groups for being too lenient with corporate
polluters, and for overall lax enforcement of environmental laws.
The administration has denied those charges and pointed to several
high-profile cases across the country, including recent lawsuits
brought against more than two dozen Midwest utility plants.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bundy, the US attorney for Alaska and chairman of an
environmental task force for the Department of Justice, said most
environmental cases are declined because of weak evidence or
because lawyers determine the offenses are not federal violations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, US attorneys with limited resources are careful to
concentrate on offenses that result in the most severe
environmental harm. ``We want to make sure they are the right cases
and good cases to bring,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal prosecution of environmental violators is intended
to be the ultimate deterrent in the government's arsenal to enforce
pollution laws.
</P>
<P>
   The study says some US attorneys ``often decline to prosecute
organizational defendants for criminal violations in favor of civil
sanctions.'' Nationwide, one in ten criminal referrals to the
Department of Justice were declined in favor of a civil
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   For companies, a larger civil fine is often preferable to a
criminal conviction, which carries with it the stigma of being
publicly labeled an environmental felon, said John Scalia, a bureau
statistician who conducted the environmental crime study.
</P>
<P>
   ``Organizations tend to shy away, particularly large ones, from
being convicted felons if they can,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The study found the fines levied in civil cases averaged $2.5
million while the average fine in a criminal case was only
$308,000.
</P>
<P>
   There are other reasons companies strive to avoid a criminal
conviction for environmental offenses, including a potentially
costly prohibition from doing business with the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the minds of corporations and executives there is a huge
difference,'' between civil and criminal cases, said Mark Cohen, a
Vanderbilt University professor who has studied government
environmental enforcement policies. ``From the management
standpoint, you don't want to be associated with criminal charges
against the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Bundy said the study of environmental crimes also fails to
account for the complexity of cases today. He said US attorneys
avoid looking at their prosecution numbers and instead focus on the
kinds of cases they are bringing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at how can we maximize the impact on protecting
the environment instead of developing numbers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics bureau is part of the US Department of Justice
and is the primary source of criminal justice statistics in the
country. Scalia said the agency decided to examine environmental
crimes after receiving many inquiries for the statistics, primarily
from defense lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The study examined environmental prosecutions in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 1945EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4350 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-PLOTKIN-RAINFORES     11-29 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PLOTKIN-RAINFOREST-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROMANCE WITH A RAIN FOREST AND ITS ELUSIVE MIRACLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: La., Pa., Calif.)   (Science Times)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JON CHRISTENSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has the makings of a good story and Dr. Mark J. Plotkin
clearly relishes the beginning. If only it had a happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   Deep in the Amazon jungle, on a prospecting mission for Shaman
Pharmaceuticals, Plotkin was living out the romantic dream of every
scientist who studies how people use plants. The company had staked
millions of dollars on finding a breakthrough drug by sending
ethnobotanists like Plotkin to confer with shamans in the rain
forest and bring back promising plants.
</P>
<P>
   Adding poignancy to the quest, Plotkin was searching for plants
to treat diabetes, which had killed his grandmothers.
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin described the symptoms to a medicine man from the
Sikiyana-Chikena tribe: sores between the toes, incessant thirst,
fading eyesight. He then followed the shaman into the forest and
watched him pick a trailside herb, peel long strips of bark from a
towering tree and drain sap from a twisted vine.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the village, he boiled all the ingredients together in a
clay pot over a wood fire. That night, the shaman gave the thick
reddish-brown liquid to a young Indian woman with a nearly fatal
case of diabetes. The next morning her blood sugar level was almost
normal. Within a few days she was well enough to work in her garden
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was knocked over,'' Plotkin said. ``He literally raised that
woman from the dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the medicine did not pan out back in the lab at Shaman
Pharmaceuticals in South San Francisco. And when the Food and Drug
Administration sent the company's most promising new drug prospect,
a diarrhea remedy from an Amazon tree, back for more clinical
trials, Shaman Pharmaceuticals' stock slid until it was virtually
worthless.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1999, the company abandoned the quest to make drugs
from rain forest remedies and decided to sell dietary supplements
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin has since severed his ties with the company, which has
changed its name to ShamanBotanicals.com. He also had the company
remove every reference to his name from its Web site. He renounced
bioprospecting, the search for medicines and other useful products,
because it had become too controversial in South America, where
indigenous tribes had complained that bioprospectors were stealing
their secrets and getting rich from them.
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin said the idea that bioprospectors were profiting from
Indian knowledge also hindered his ability to raise money for his
own nonprofit organization, the Amazon Conservation Team, which
works with shamans in Colombia and other countries to preserve
their knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   For Plotkin, 44, this falling out represented a career crisis,
although he played down its significance. His experience is
emblematic of the changes that have occurred in a field in which
old-fashioned botanists once toiled in obscurity until saving the
rain forest became a cause celebre, and ethnobotanists like Plotkin
linked their fortunes to the pharmaceutical industry, only to
discover that medical miracles are rare, even in the rain forest.
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin had built his reputation on the claim that the rain
forest was a pharmacy filled with wonder drugs known to traditional
healers who were eager to share their knowledge. Shaman
Pharmaceuticals was one of many companies that wanted to find the
proof and help provide a financial incentive to save the rain
forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all had a mantra that we had to save the rain forest
because it was a repository of natural drugs,'' said Dr. Wade
Davis, who studied ethnobotany at Harvard and watched Plotkin's
rapid rise.
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin had followed a roundabout path to the rain forest. The
son of a Jewish shoe salesman in a poor black neighborhood in New
Orleans, he dropped out of the University of Pennsylvania's biology
department after less than a year because he was more interested in
studying whole organisms than cells and microbes.
</P>
<P>
   He went to Cambridge and got a job unpacking specimens at the
Harvard Zoological Museum, and went to night school through the
university's extension program. He went on to study at Yale and
Tufts and worked as a research associate at the Harvard Botanical
Museum under Dr. Richard Evans Schultes, who inspired Plotkin and
others with his tales of Indian ceremonies and hallucinogenic
potions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't interest people in rain forests, hallucinogenic
plants, and naked people,'' Schultes liked to say, ``then you're in
the wrong line of business.''
</P>
<P>
   For his doctoral research, Plotkin cataloged the medicinal
plants of the Tirio tribe in Suriname. At the same time, he began
carving out a career away from the academic world as an
environmental activist working for Conservation International and
the World Wildlife Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Both organizations were eager to publicize the exploits of the
dashing young ethnobotanist who was working with Indians to
discover medicines and save the rain forest. His reputation was
cemented in a 1989 Smithsonian magazine cover story that showed
Plotkin in face paint and an Indian ceremonial headdress deep in
the Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   Profile writers have compared him to Indiana Jones, and quoted
sympathetic colleagues who called Plotkin the Carl Sagan of the
rain forest. But there have also been strong undercurrents of
skepticism about his showmanship and his affection for feathers and
fame over peer reviewed science, where his record is thin.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing great stuff educating people and trying to save
indigenous knowledge,'' said a former colleague, Dr. Tom Carlson,
vice president for medical ethnobotany of the company
ShamanBotanicals.com. ``But in terms of rigorous ethnobotanical
science, very little of his work was useful. And a lot of that had
to do with sloppy research.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example Carlson cites the story of the putative diabetes
cure. Plotkin, he said, did not actually measure the patient's
blood sugar level before the shaman administered the potion in the
Amazon, and the plant specimens he sent back were poorly preserved
and incorrectly labeled.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, although Plotkin concluded that the plants he sent
back from the jungle showed no effects in laboratory tests, Carlson
said that two of the plants did lower blood sugar in tests with
mice, just not enough to justify further research.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Carlson said, is developing a line of
glucose-lowering snacks for diabetics. But not with Plotkin's
plants.
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin admits that he has been less than prolific in the
scientific realm of enthnobotany. He said he had not shared his
findings or contributed many plant collections to museums, the
hallmark of a botany career in colleagues' eyes, because he does
not want people to search his writings or botanical collections for
clues to Indian medicines.``My trust with the Indians is more
important,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the increasing distrust of scientists among the Indians,
in addition to the failure of the diabetes remedy, and the crash of
Shaman Pharmaceuticals that finally made Plotkin give up on
bioprospecting. But he is sticking with the shamans.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Plotkin brought a group of Colombian shamans to the
United States to protest scientific research on their plant
knowledge without their consent. Draped in necklaces of bright
beads, jungle seeds and jaguar claws, the shamans met with
activists and donors across the country.
</P>
<P>
   They presented a statement condemning ``anthropologists,
botanists, physicians and other scientists who are conducting
experiments with yage and other medicinal and sacred plants without
taking into account our ancestral wisdom and our collective
intellectual property rights.''
</P>
<P>
   But on this trip, unlike others, Plotkin did not take the
shamans to meet with any pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   Some colleagues say Plotkin has contributed to an atmosphere of
distrust by promoting the potential for finding profitable
medicines in the Amazon, and then by joining the debate about
property rights and royalties for products that have yet to pan
out, even in the lab.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Plotkin is not the only one responsible for the heavy
promotion of the curative potential of the rain forest. Davis said
he also played a role. ``But the rhetoric ran away from reality,''
Davis said. ``And the whole thing has backfired. We have not found
new drugs. And the fact that the idea is deeply flawed is never
questioned.''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it is pretty clear why the hypothesis was wrong,
Davis said. The field had already been closely scrutinized. The
Indians do know the forest after thousands of years of screening
plants for medicinal properties, he said. But newcomers, starting
with the Spanish conquistadors, quickly picked up the most
obviously efficacious and economically valuable medicines, like
coca, the basis for cocaine, the antimalarial medicine quinine, and
the arrow poison curare, which is the basis for a muscle relaxant
used in surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Although his own bioprospecting venture was a failure, Plotkin
still believes in the magic of shamanism and the potential for new
drugs. But if the idea ever does pay off, Plotkin will not be part
of it. He is working with South American shamans to encourage them
to preserve their sacred methods of healing.
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin now argues that his experience with the diabetes remedy
illustrates the limitations of what he calls a reductionist
approach: breaking the traditional jungle medicine into its
chemical constituents to test it in a modern laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the medicine works more like a magic shotgun blast, he
said, than a magic bullet. ``When they couldn't reproduce it in the
lab, it brought me up short,'' he said. ``But when I went back to
the jungle and saw the woman was still alive, it said to me, well,
maybe the lab can't do everything it needs to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
