<SLUG> BC-VODAFONE-MANNESMANN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANNESMANN BEGINS 5-DAY DEFENSE CAMPAIGN, CALLING VODAFONE'S BID
LOW  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Fighting the largest hostile-takeover attempt ever
made, Klaus Esser, chief executive of Mannesmann of Germany, began
a long-awaited defense Monday against the wireless giant Vodafone
PLC, arguing that the $127.7 billion bid was too low and
forecasting that his own company would enjoy booming growth for
years _ alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value of Mannesmann is significantly higher than the offer
on the table by a wide margin,'' Esser told reporters in the Savoy
Hotel ballroom here, where Vodafone began its assault on Mannesmann
almost two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the two companies are fighting to dominate the
lucrative European telecommunications market, both arguing that
their different strategies will reap the greatest reward from an
expected boom in voice and data transmission driven by new
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Esser spoke after a four-hour meeting with securities analysts,
starting five days of efforts in Britain, Germany and the United
States to swing investors against the all-share bid, which
Vodafone, the world's biggest wireless operator, plans to send them
next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mannesmann shareholders will get significantly richer by
holding onto their shares,'' Esser said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock rose nearly 2 percent Monday to 204.50
euros, or $206.44 _ still far below Vodafone's offer of 240 euros,
suggesting that investors had doubts about whether the deal would
succeed. Vodafone shares fell 1 percent, to 2.9525 pounds, or
$4.74, and its American depository receipts fell $2.5625, or more
than 5 percent, to $46.1875.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who attended the presentation gave it mixed reviews.
``It didn't come out with a blastingly aggressive defense case, so
it rather helped Vodafone,'' said an analyst from a European
investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   But Christian Kern, telecommunications analyst at Salomon Smith
Barney, called the meeting ``quite upbeat in terms of presenting
the numbers'' in key areas of Mannesmann's business.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone's attempt to acquire Mannesmann has been the most
notable move in a tortuous year of shifting telecommunications
allegiances that began with the British company's $62 billion
acquisition of Airtouch Communications of San Francisco in January.
That deal propelled Vodafone into the American wireless market,
providing access to Airtouch stakes in European mobile operators
including Mannesmann's D2 network. It reinforced a partnership then
between Vodafone and Mannesmann.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Vodafone struck a joint venture with Bell Atlantic,
in which it took a 45 percent stake, reflecting its ambition to
cement its position as the global leader in exclusively wireless
telecommunications. Then, in October, Mannesmann moved onto the
offensive, announcing it would acquire Orange PLC, Britain's No. 3
wireless operator and a Vodafone competitor, for $33 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The result was that the two partners became competitors, each
voicing a sense of betrayal by the other. ``We are different
companies with different strategies and different portfolios that
just do not fit,'' Esser said.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, he left open the door to some kind of
future relationship with Vodafone, saying he did not want existing
partnerships between the two companies to become a ``legal issue''
and would instead look for ``additional opportunities for
cooperation'' in the mobile data business.
</P>
<P>
   In making his defense now, Esser said Mannesmann's commitment to
integrated fixed-line and wireless voice and data businesses
offered far greater prospects for growth than Vodafone's exclusive
commitment to wireless technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strategic crisis for Vodafone,'' he said. ``Their
strategy doesn't work for the future.
</P>
<P>
   To make his point, he stepped down from the podium to show
reporters a new Mannesmann product called D2-Three Pack, offering
mobile, fixed-line and Internet services _ all in a single box
prepackaged for holiday sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
