<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-MARIJUANA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW US MEDICAL MARIJUANA POLICY PROTESTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an indication of growing public support for legalizing
marijuana for medical use, scores of celebrities, health officials,
Congressmen, and others Monday joined in protesting a new US
medical marijuana research policy for lacking compassion and being
``too cumbersome.''
</P>
<P>
   The policy spells out the conditions under which studies
involving marijuana can be conducted _ conditions that critics say
are so stringent as to make the research virtually impossible _ and
fails to expand legal access to medically approved patients through
``compassionate use'' programs.
</P>
<P>
   Signing on to letters of protest Monday were such nationally
known names as actors Susan Sarandon and Woody Harrelson; comedians
Richard Pryor and Bill Maher; Harvard scientist Stephen Jay Gould;
rock band Hootie &AMP; The Blowfish; former US Surgeon General Joycelyn
Elders; and former Reagan administration official Lyn Nofziger.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Democratic Congressmen Barney Frank, James
McGovern, and John Olver also joined the effort, along with US
representatives from around the country, including three
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The letters, addressed to the US Secretary of Health and Human
Services Donna Shalala, come just weeks after Maine became the
sixth state to legalize medical marijuana through a ballot
question. The other states are California, Arizona, Washington,
Oregon, and Alaska, which allow certain patients to both grow and
smoke their own, or allow them to possess it legally. Marijuana is
used medically to control nausea and other effects of cancer
treatment and ease symptoms of AIDS and other conditions.
</P>
<P>
   While an attempt in Massachusetts to bring the issue to the
voters in next year's elections fell short of getting the necessary
signatures by this month's deadline, organizers of the effort vow
to try again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the people of Massachusetts really support doctors'
ability to prescribe marijuana,'' said Bill Downing, president and
chairman of MASS CANN/NORML, the state chapter of the National
Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws that helped get more
than 20,000 signatures in support of a ballot question to legalize
medical marijuana and change other aspects of the law, but fell
short of the nearly 60,000 required.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1990s, Massachusetts has had a research program
on the books that would allow medically approved patients to get
marijuana under controlled conditions, but the state Department of
Public Health has never been able to get legal access to the drug
from the US government.
</P>
<P>
   Even the new US research guidelines that go into effect
Wednesday will not give patients access to the Massachusetts
program, said Paul Jacobsen, deputy public health commissioner.
``It basically doesn't provide us with an approvable source (for
the drug),'' said Jacobsen. ``We have our program. It's up, it can
run, but without a source, it's a moot point.''
</P>
<P>
   A US Department of Health and Human Services spokesperson could
not be reached for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, patients like Jim Harden, 49, of Virginia, are
in pain and angry at the government policy. He was one of the
patients cited in a recent federally commissioned Institute of
Medicine (IOM) report as someone who should have legal access to
medical marijuana, as only eight other patients nationwide do right
now under a US program that stopped allowing new people in years
ago. The report, released in March, also found medicinal uses for
marijuana in treating people with AIDS, cancer, and other diseases,
and urged the federal government to expand compassionate use
programs.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in front of the US Department of Health and
Human Services Monday _ coordinated by the Marijuana Policy Project
of Washington, D.C., to announce the letters of protest _ Harden
got up from his wheelchair, holding a copy of that IOM report, to
tell his story.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview later, Harden described his multiple
health problems over the last three years, from end-stage liver
disease as a result of hepatitis contracted from a blood
transfusion to chronic pain as a result of being crushed by a drill
while working as a state of Virginia geologist, from the nausea to
the vomiting from the medications he uses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to have 17-inch biceps and a 46-inch chest. Now I have
a 34-inch chest and my biceps are around 10 inches,'' he said.
``Marijuana allows me to eat,'' said Harden, who has only been able
to get the drug illegally. ``The marijuana was really instrumental
in saving my life, in allowing me to live so long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 1948EST &QL; 
