<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4358 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      11-29 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: LONG SHOTS ANONYMOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This Thursday, George W. Bush is going to emerge from his burrow
and take part in a debate with the other Republican presidential
candidates in New Hampshire. Unless, of course, he sees his shadow.
In that case we will have six more weeks of autumn, during which
the governor of Texas will have to stay home and squire his wife to
more awards ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Presuming Bush does finally make an appearance, you'll notice
that he and Sen. John McCain are sharing the stage with a number of
strange men you've never seen before. This is the Republican Field,
and it consists of:
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch. You may remember Hatch reading ``The
Exorcist'' at the Clarence Thomas hearings, and suggesting that
Anita Hill's story had been cooked up by ``slick lawyers'' from the
left.
</P>
<P>
   The characteristics that separate Hatch from the herd include a
tendency to refer to himself in the third person, and to call
campaign donations ``monies.'' As chairman of the Judiciary
Committee, he argues that he is best qualified to nominate new
federal judges. There are quite a few of those jobs to fill since,
under Hatch, the Judiciary confirmation pipeline has become more of
a clogged drain.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes, a radio talk-show host, is referred to as
``ambassador'' in reference to his work as the Reagan
administration's representative to the United Nations Economic and
Social Council, an organization he nostalgically refers to as that
``rat hole of United Nations waste.'' His only election victory has
been in the race for president of the Ronald Reagan Alumni
Association.
</P>
<P>
   In debate, Keyes provides the critical function of scaring the
audience into wakefulness. ``We proliferate laws!'' he told a woman
in Hanover who had only asked about the war on drugs. ``We even
have started to invade property rights and do other things that are
tearing down our system of liberty! Why? Because we are out of
control!''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes. Sometimes a candidate comes along who can unite
all Americans _ rich, poor, young, old, black and white _ behind a
single thought. Forbes is such a man, and his unending race for the
presidency has caused the entire nation to join together and
calculate all the better ways they could have found to spend $54
million of their own money.
</P>
<P>
   Recent history demonstrates that Americans don't like incredibly
rich candidates who want to start at the top, but Forbes just keeps
spending along. He takes pride in the way his signature issue, the
flat-tax plan, has gotten support from other Republicans. That's
because ``flat'' sounds like a synonym for ``low.'' Rename it the
``no-mortgage-deduction tax plan'' and see how far it flies.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer is yet another of the Republican candidates who have
prepared for the presidency by never being elected to anything. The
head of conservative lobbying groups, Bauer worked for the Reagan
administration as under secretary of education. In what may be an
effort to differentiate himself from Keyes, Bauer says that the
bureaucrats working for him were ``good people,'' albeit misguided.
</P>
<P>
   With a crowd this large, Bush is not going to have much trouble
with the debates. He'll get a 15-minute rest between questions, and
it will be hard for the audience to hear him anyway, with Alan
Keyes ringing in their ears.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'd like a more exclusive format _ say a debate
limited to candidates whose name you can connect to ``president''
without causing your hearers to break into laughter or faint dead
away. But nobody is leaving without a fight. Keyes and Bauer, who
travel very light, seem to regard campaigning as a career. Forbes
treats it the way his father collected Faberge eggs and yachts _ as
a hobby whose very expense makes it more desirable. Hatch, who is
running simultaneously for his Senate seat, also seems optimistic.
``In January, when voters start focusing on the race, they're going
to say: `Hey, what about Orrin Hatch?''' predicted the senator's
campaign spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it just shows you what a great country this is. Any
middle-aged man in America can decide he will grow up to be
president, despite overwhelming evidence to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
