<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4359 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-WTO-FACES-SPI &LR;      11-29 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-FACES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELEGATES, PROTESTERS, COPS AND COFFEE MIX ON STREETS OF SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHUONG LE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Some of the people on hand for the World Trade
Organization meeting in Seattle:
</P>
<P>
   Mohamed Sultan
</P>
<P>
   trade representative
</P>
<P>
   Djibouti, Djibouti
</P>
<P>
   Even though the World Trade Organization is all about meetings,
trade delegate Mohamed Sultan wouldn't mind a chance to explore
what Seattle has to offer. After all, he was prepared Monday with
an umbrella for the city's unpredictable weather.
</P>
<P>
   Sultan has never been to Seattle before. The 33-year-old heard
little of the city, except that it was home to The Boeing Co. and a
large Ethiopian community. ``We'd love to go to a nightclub or
disco,'' he said with a mischievous smile. ``Are there any around
here?''
</P>
<P>
   Sultan and his colleague, Nour Roda Daher, 30, are part of a
seven-member trade delegation from Djibouti, a developing northeast
African country that shares borders with Eritrea, Ethiopia and
Somalia, and achieved its independence from France in 1977. Because
of its strategic port location and status as a free trade zone,
Djibouti's economy is based on services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to negotiate our interest in services, such as port
and telecommunications,'' Sultan said, speaking in both French and
English outside the Sheraton Hotel where he waited to attended a
meeting of developing countries. ``We're trying to negotiate the
benefit of preferential treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Still tired from his Sunday flight from Djibouti, Sultan said he
looks forward to his last day in town when he may have enough free
time to venture to the downtown shops. And, of course, the
nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Westbrook
</P>
<P>
   Barista
</P>
<P>
   Seattle
</P>
<P>
   Tall drip coffees for the steelworkers. Lattes and cappuccinos
for protesters dressed as sea turtles. Emily Westbrook served up
cup after cup of java to regulars and visitors yesterday with the
charm of a classic Seattle barista.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great for business,'' the tongue-pierced 21-year-old
said, behind the City Grind espresso stand near the First United
Methodist Church downtown. A sidewalk sign touting the daily mocha
special also welcomed ``union and protesters.'' The stand quickly
turned into a warming station for dozens of steelworkers and
environmentalists who rallied along the block.
</P>
<P>
   Westbrook couldn't be more pleased, humming several bars from an
anti-WTO song that repeatedly blared from a parked van nearby. ``I
can sing it myself,'' she joked. A few months ago, Westerbrook had
never heard of the WTO or knew what it did. Yesterday, she proudly
wore a yellow ``woman of steel'' button on her blue fleece jacket,
a gift from another ``woman of steel,'' to show her support for the
unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I'm against the WTO,'' she said, her consciousness
raised by recent events. ``I think it does more harm than good.
It's pro-corporations. It hurts small businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   A Seattle native, Westbrook enjoyed the fact that protesters
could ``emphasize their right to free speech.'' ``I think it's
great that they're here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   George Hylkema
</P>
<P>
   Wooden boat builder
</P>
<P>
   Balboa, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   George Hylkema sees power in information so he wants people to
be informed about the World Trade Organization. Every opportunity
he gets, he passes out taped lectures and discussions on issues
relating to trade, the environment and human issues. ``We get info
and we pass it on to everyone,'' the white-bearded 63-year-old said
as he held a painted anti-WTO sign high above his head to protest
the conference. ``I carry these tapes with me and hand them out to
anyone who will listen,'' said Hylkema, a former engineer and
physicist who now builds wooden boats. The tapes are Hylkema's way
of counteracting the forces of the WTO, which he said makes
decisions in secret that affect the rest of the population. ``It's
multinationals going for the gold,'' he said. ``This is a power
grab. Who loses out? All third-world countries. And we lose out.''
Hylkema and his friend, Coeli Nenzes, the artist who painted the
protest sign, decided a month ago to fly to Seattle to take part in
the forums. They wanted to learn more about the event, and they
wanted to hobnob with other liked-minded protesters. ``This is
perhaps the event of the century,'' said Hylkema, who arrived from
Southern California on Friday. ``If it goes as the planners hope,
we'll have out major work cut out for us in restoring the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose Lu-qui
</P>
<P>
   Television reporter
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong
</P>
<P>
   Only an hour after landing in Seattle for her first-ever visit,
Hong Kong television reporter Rose Lu-qui had already staked out
her spot on the corner of Pike Street and Seventh Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   As WTO delegates, protesters and Seattle police were jostling
each other for space outside the Washington Trade and Convention
Center, Lu-qui was in the midst of the crowd. With microphone in
hand and a cameraman nearby, the cropped-haired broadcaster waited
anxiously as the action unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very sleepy,'' she said, with a weak smile, appearing
decidedly fresh and composed after a flight from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Lu-qui and her colleagues from STAR TV _ a Mandarin-language
television station based in Hong Kong but broadcast all over Asia _
watched as small pockets of protesters marched to the intersection
and chanted anti-WTO statements. Nearby a phalanx of police
officers kept the protesters at bay while neatly groomed delegates
waited to enter the convention center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what will happen,'' she said. ``We knew coming
that there were protesters but we didn't imagine that there would
be any bombings.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old reporter is one of an estimated 2,500
journalists in town to cover the WTO trade conference. A reporter
who covers trade and politics, Lu-qui plans to focus on trade
relations between the United States and mainland China. Her
broadcasts will reach more than 100 million people in China and
other parts of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Chorush
</P>
<P>
   Animal rights activist
</P>
<P>
   Seattle
</P>
<P>
   If there is a rule somewhere that says you cannot dress as a sea
turtle and simultaneouly cruise the streets of Seattle in
inline-skates, then Bob Chorush sure doesn't know it.
</P>
<P>
   After four months of planning, the 52-year-old animal rights
activists hit Fifth Avenue, wearing black inline skates and a sea
turtle outfit artistically fashioned from a refrigerator box. ``The
strangest thing I've seen?'' Chorush asked. ``It's that people
understand why we're out here as sea turtles.''
</P>
<P>
   Chorush and a brigade of protesters wearing bright sea-turtle
outfits, painted in cool shades of aqua, forest green and teal,
walked in front of the First United Methodist Church yesterday to
prove a point. ``I'm very concerned about the way the WTO responds
to animal and environmental issues ... and there's hardly any area
for human issues,'' he said. ``It feels like government without
representation.''
</P>
<P>
   In the face of that, Chorus said, ``This is it. We're taking to
the streets. That seems to be the only way.'' Chorush hopes the
city shuts down as the demonstrators hit the streets in the next
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even people who are tired of politics realize that it's
important and the impact that this has on everything,'' he said,
before skating off to see a fellow sea turtle.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Pendergrass
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Police Officer
</P>
<P>
   South Seattle
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, so good'' is what Seattle police officer Paul
Pendergrass thought yesterday morning as he directed tinted vans
and luxury sedans through a vehicle checkpoint set up at Sixth
Avenue and Pike Street. This is the role Pendergrass played as the
theatrics of the World Trade Organization unfolded in Seattle, one
block from his traffic post. Wearing fluorescent orange and yellow
vests and gloves, Pendergrass had a seemingly simple task: make
sure only vehicles with the proper credentials were allowed to pass
up along Pike Street. This is life on the WTO detail.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Pendergrass helped monitor more than 400 street
theater performers and protesters as they marched from Capitol Hill
to the downtown shopping district.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows what to expect as the demonstrators are expected to
descend on Seattle this week. ``Today is not over yet,'' cautioned
the 37-year-old, as the streets remained relatively quiet for much
of yesterday morning. ``I don't know what to expect,'' said the
15-year police veteran, who had been on duty since 6:30 a.m. ``It's
one of these wait-and-see types. Everything so far has been
orderly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
