<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commissioner Kramer coy about possible disciplinary actions
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ SEC Commissioner Roy Kramer said Monday he will not
disclose whether the officiating crew that worked Saturday's
Georgia-Georgia Tech game will be disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Gaston, the SEC supervisor of football officials, conceded
Sunday that his crew had missed the call at the end of the game.
The ruling was that Georgia's Jasper Sanks had fumbled at the
Georgia Tech two-yard line with five seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The score was tied at 48-48 when the ball was awarded to Georgia
Tech, which went on to win the game in overtime, 51-48.
</P>
<P>
   The officiating crew, rated as the SEC's best, was scheduled to
work the SEC championship game Saturday night at the Georgia Dome.
Kramer would not say if the crew would be prohibited from working
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer also said that any discipline of the officials would be
handled internally and that no public announcement would be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have policies in place where we rate officials and, if the
need arises, we discipline them,'' Kramer said. ``One of those
policies is that we do not discuss those things in public.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials who are found in error can be disciplined with
suspensions that range from one game to a permanent ban from
working for the conference.
</P>
<P>
   QB questions
</P>
<P>
   Both coaches are keeping everyone guessing about the quarterback
rotation for Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   At Florida, Steve Spurrier alternated Doug Johnson and Jesse
Palmer every play during the loss to Florida State on Nov. 20.
Spurrier said that both quarterbacks would be ready for Saturday's
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll make an announcement about Thursday so these guys don't
get bombarded with questions all week,'' said Spurrier, who has not
ruled out the possibility of rotating the quarterbacks again.
</P>
<P>
   At Alabama, coach Mike DuBose said that both Andrew Zow and
Tyler Watts will would play. Zow is still recovering from an ankle
injury, but in the 40-39 win at Florida on Oct. 2 he threw for 336
yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Still, DuBose wasn't ready to say that Zow would start. ``I
think I want to keep everybody guessing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   We meet again
</P>
<P>
   Alabama running back Shaun Alexander said that, even after the
Crimson Tide won at Florida, he expected to meet the Gators again
in Atlanta. Florida, he said, also expected a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the game they congratulated us, but they all said, `See
you in Atlanta,'' Alexander said. ``They had already beaten
Tennessee and knew that nobody else in the conference could beat
them. So they've been thinking about this game as long as we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida tailback Robert Gillespie, who has been out since
breaking his right hand in the Georgia game, will not play
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida linebacker Keith Kelsey, who sprained an ankle against
Florida State on Nov. 20, is expected to play.
</P>
<P>
   _ This game will be the fifth that Florida and Alabama have met
in the SEC Championship Game. Florida leads 3-1, winning in 1993
(28-13), 1994 (24-23) and 1996 (45-30). Alabama won the first SEC
championship game in 1992 (28-21) and went on to win the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   _ For the first time since 1994, the SEC title game will have no
bearing on who plays for the national championship. Florida played
for the national title after winning in 1995 and 1996, Tennessee
the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
