<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another game, another right knee injury for Falcons
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons learned Monday that strong safety
and leading tackler Marty Carter might miss the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who suffered a partially torn medial collateral ligament
in his right knee, is expected to miss four to six weeks; five
games remain.
</P>
<P>
   He will not need surgery, but the Falcons will miss his 109
total tackles, which lead the team by 24.
</P>
<P>
   The injury happened when the LaGrange, Ga., native took on
Panthers fullback William Floyd, who was leading a running play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like on film . . . , as I was stumbling back, I
tried to put my foot down and it buckled,'' Carter said. ``It kind
of looked funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter had signed a five-year, $15 million contract last
offseason after four years with the Bears and four with the Bucs.
Running back Gary Downs and rookie center Todd McClure were lost
for the season to right-knee injuries on the second day of training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Jamal Anderson suffered a season-ending right-knee
injury in the second game, and linebacker Keith Brooking missed
three games with a right-knee injury similar to Carter's.
</P>
<P>
   A nagging right thigh muscle of reserve cornerback Michael
Booker, who plays on nickel and dime defenses, could leave the team
short two defensive backs. The Falcons might not wait for Carter
and instead put him on injured reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Teams out of the playoffs this late in the season often activate
players from their practice squad, or from another team's,
sometimes at a different position.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have no defensive backs on the practice squad. The
practice squad also has no running backs, where their lack of depth
is most glaring, especially with the ongoing left-knee problems of
Byron Hanspard.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons could sign a free agent. One possibility is rookie
cornerback Derrick Gardner, who began the season on the Falcons'
practice squad and saw action in two games before being waived.
</P>
<P>
   Booker hobbled off Sunday night, shortly after he was beaten
down the left sideline by Panthers wide receiver Donald Hayes
Sunday night on a 37-yard pass play that set up a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   He first tore the muscle in his right thigh Aug. 7 in a
scrimmage against Jacksonville and missed the first three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is continuing to be a problem,'' coach Dan Reeves said.
``We have got to look at that very seriously, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 1957EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
