<SLUG> BC-MAG-LALLI-GEORGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY'S FORMER MANAGING EDITOR NAMED EDITOR OF GEORGE MAGAZINE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Undaunted by the prospect and challenges of stepping
into a role established by John F. Kennedy Jr., Frank Lalli, a
former managing editor of Money magazine, has agreed to take over
as editor in chief of George magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Jack W. Kliger, the chief executive of Hachette-Filipacchi
Magazines, a unit of the Lagardere Group, announced Monday that
Lalli, 57, would begin his new job immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The position of editor in chief at George has probably been the
most difficult job to fill in the magazine industry this year, if
not this decade. after all, who would want to step into a role
established by a favorite son of America? Who would want to tackle
the formidable editorial and business problems facing the magazine,
issues that may have been glossed over precisely because of its
famous editor?
</P>
<P>
   Kliger said he waited several months to hire an editor because
he wanted to do so only after Hachette had bought out the Kennedy
family's 50 percent stake in the magazine, which the company did in
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first focus was on getting George magazine into
Hachette-Filipacchi as a full and viable property,'' Kliger said.
``I was not comfortable hiring an editor until we owned the
magazine outright.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Lalli is a seasoned editor, he is relatively
inexperienced in the political arena. He was managing editor of
Money magazine, which is published by the Time Inc. unit of Time
Warner, until July 1998, when he became a senior executive editor
at Time Inc., which he left last year to start a magazine
consulting firm. He was president of the American Society of
Newspaper Editors from 1996 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money certainly wasn't a political magazine, but it certainly
dealt with public issues,'' Lalli said. ``It dealt with people who
have the power to change America. For George, that currency is
political power.''
</P>
<P>
   Kliger said that he did not consider Lalli's relative
inexperience in political reporting a liability. ``At the end of
the day, Frank's a great editor, and that's what this magazine
needs,'' Kliger said.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, however, George needs more than stellar editorial
skills. The magazine has been without a publisher since March, when
Stephen McEvoy resigned. Until his death, Kennedy had been acting
as publisher and editor. Advertising pages have dropped drastically
over the last year despite an uptick in the October issue that
served as an homage to Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Total advertising pages for the issues from January to October
this year were 377, down 28 percent from 525 in the period a year
earlier, according to the Publishers Information Bureau.
Advertising revenue fell 18 percent for the same period, to $12.8
million from $15.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   George editors attributed the decline to the departure of
several members of the sales staff, which left the department with
only three full-time sales people.
</P>
<P>
   Circulation has also fallen. Newsstand sales have fallen 11
percent for the six-month period that ended in June, and overall
circulation has dropped to 405,000 from 420,000 for the same
period, according to the Audit Bureau of Circulations.
</P>
<P>
   Since July, several members have left the small editorial staff,
including Kennedy's longtime assistant, her assistant, an associate
editor, the magazine's chief copy editor, a member of the research
staff and the photo editor.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members said that Richard Blow, the executive editor who
has been running the magazine since July, would resign before the
end of the week. Blow declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Garfinkle, the director of print media at the
advertising agency McCann-Erickson, said that the magazine needed
to clearly and quickly redefine its mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that there is potential, but it's got to go almost
more Vanity Fair, more the gossipy side of political,'' Ms.
Garfinkle said. ``If that is the direction they take it in, I think
there is the potential both reader-wise and advertiser-wise for
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Lalli, whose resume does not exactly evoke the word gossipy,
said that he had no immediate plans for the magazine and was
waiting to meet the staff, which he did Monday afternoon, and
discuss changes with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took this job because I believed in John's mission,'' Lalli
said. ``I think it is a challenge, but I would not be sitting here
today if in that sense I did not have a very direct connection with
George.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
