<HEADLINE>
SATELLITE TV FIRMS GET OK TO BROADCAST LOCAL CHANNELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Satellite television systems can begin providing subscribers
with local channels for the first time, boosting their ability to
compete with cable TV, under legislation President Clinton signed
into law Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Echostar's Dish Network service planned to begin beaming six
Boston stations to subscribers by Tuesday as part of a 13-city
nationwide rollout of local channels. Its bigger rival, DirecTV,
which has nearly two-thirds of the 11 million US digital dish
customers, planned a quick rollout to seven US cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to begin the next stage of the video
revolution,'' said US Representative Edward J. Markey of
Massachusetts, the ranking Democrat on the House telecommunications
subcommittee, a top proponent of the new law. ``Many people have
not subscribed to satellite TV because they have not been able to
get local channels. Today that choice becomes possible.''
</P>
<P>
   So far satellite dishes have proven highly popular in rural
areas without cable. But they have also begun making inroads in
areas served by cable by offering hundreds of channels and
extensive packages of football games and other sports.
</P>
<P>
   Echostar, which has just under 4 million customers nationally,
plans to charge $5 a month for local channels, on top of basic
monthly packages that start at $20.
</P>
<P>
   While cable TV has a huge lead over satellite dishes _ 66
million customers nationwide compared to 12 million for digital and
older C-band dishes _ being able to carry local channels could make
dishes a more viable alternative to cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes away a barrier, but it doesn't necessarily cause
people to flock to digital broadcast satellites,'' said Bruce
Leichtman, an analyst with the Yankee Group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In part because many communities have cable franchises that
offer dozens of channels, Massachusetts ranks last among all US
states in the rate of households signing up for TV dishes, with a
total of 108,000 compared to 1.7 million cable homes, Leichtman
said.
</P>
<P>
   But, Leichtman said, ``People that have DBS really like it, and
our surveys show 85 percent of people say they would recommend it
to a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   The new law allows prohibits satellite firms from carrying a
distant network affiliate to homes within a radius of approximately
50 to 75 miles from the site of a local affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Jenkinson, spokesman for MediaOne Group, said ``of course
we're concerned'' about the prospect of stronger competition from
dishes, but added, ``We still feel that our product provides better
value.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the typical $100 up-front cost for buying or renting a
dish and having it installed, satellite dishes generally work only
on one television set per house without expensive extra wiring,
while a cable hookup can serve multiple sets.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving out the installation fee for dish TV, cable and direct
broadcast generally charge about $30 a month for 60 channels,
although dish companies offer plans with up to 500 channels and
more pay-per-view offerings than cable.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite TV plan, which was approved by the House and
Senate separately, was included in the budget bill Clinton signed
Monday. It allows satellite TV systems to begin rebroadcasting
local channels immediately and at no expense for 6 months before
they must negotiate rebroadcast pacts with local stations.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 2002, satellite TV systems will be subjected to
the same ``must carry'' provisions that cable systems face to offer
all the channels serving a local viewer's area, Markey said.
</P>
<P>
   Leichtman cautioned that ``it's not going to be easy'' for the
dish companies to negotiate deals to carry local channels, and they
will be motivated only to pick up local stations in big markets
like Boston before the 2002 deadline takes effect.
</P>
<P>
   Under a system comparable to what governs the retransmission of
over-the-air stations on cable, stations will be able to require
dish companies to pay or barter for the right to rebroadcast their
stations.
</P>
<P>
   WCVB-TV (Channel 5) general manager Paul La Camera said station
owner Hearst Argyle Corp. will allow dish companies to carry the
station in Greater Boston markets if they also agree to carry a new
Lifetime channel Hearst partially owns. It made a similar deal with
cable companies trading rebroadcast rights for a promise to carry
the EPSN-2 channel, another Hearst investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously in our interest to get our signal up on these
things,'' La Camera said. But given that more than 80 percent of
homes in the local viewing area have access to cable, La Camera
said he thinks the chief market for dish systems to expand locally
will be among people ``who want to watch eight NFL games on a
Sunday afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Goldman, general manager of WBZ-TV (Channel 4), said the law
would spare his station an administrative headache of dealing with
``quite a few'' requests from people in remote parts of
Massachusetts who could not get Channel 4 over the air and so
wanted permission to get a CBS-affiliate station from another city
included in their satellite package.
</P>
<P>
   DirecTV president Eddy W. Hartenstein said his company plans to
make local channels available to 50 million US homes, beginning in
New York and Los Angeles, moving to Denver, Detroit, Miami, San
Francisco, and Washington, D.C., as it aims for 24 major
metropolitan markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
