<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYORAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO MAYOR GOES ON THE OFFENSIVE IN DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco Mayor
Willie Brown went on the attack against challenger Tom Ammiano in a
debate that left little doubt: The race for mayor of San Francisco
is between a consummate machine politician and an outsider eager to
shake up the status quo.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taking the tenor of mayoral debates to a new level of animosity,
Brown used Sunday's forum in Bayview-Hunters Point to paint
Ammiano, president of the Board of Supervisors, as an ineffective
legislator.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can only get one other vote on any issue at the board...
maybe two,'' Brown said. ``The other eight members of the board
will not follow his leadership, unlike when I was in the (state)
Legislature, when everyone followed my leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano, who landed in the runoff with a last-minute write-in
campaign, defended his abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many different styles of leadership, and I think
that the 120,000 votes I got for president of the board shows the
kind of leadership that I have. It's not always about numbers at
the board: I've been able to turn to the public to get many issues
passed.''
</P>
<P>
   After the debate, Brown continued to lambaste Ammiano as
``totally and completely ineffective in everything he undertakes -
and he whines about it.''
</P>
<P>
   With this tactic, Brown is taking a chance with voters. Polls
show that voters see Brown as a strong leader but are wary of what
they perceive as his arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Ammiano has criticized Brown for running
roughshod over the 11-member Board of Supervisors, six of whom were
appointed by Brown since he took over the mayor's job four years
ago. Early in his administration, Brown boasted of his ability to
secure a majority of votes on the board whenever he wants and
sparked controversy by referring to legislators as ``mistresses''
that needed to be ``serviced.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano often has found himself at odds with the board majority,
seeing many of his legislative initiatives stymied.
</P>
<P>
   For example, his proposal to enact a living wage in San
Francisco, which would boost them wage for employees who
work for city contractors or businesses that lease property from
the city to $11 an hour plus benefits, has been put on the slow
track by his opponents on the board who are closely allied with the
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation has been stalled at the board while a task force
reviews the plan. Ammiano said the legislation has been
stonewalled.
</P>
<P>
   And, with Brown's support, the board blocked Ammiano's plan to
ban banks from double-charging customers to use ATMs. However,
Ammiano took the plan to the voters earlier this month, winning
overwhelming support.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who served as the powerful speaker of the California
Assembly before running for mayor and has the endorsement of most
of San Francisco's elected officials, pointed to the living wage
issue as one of Ammiano's failings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't make speeches; I act,'' Brown said. ``I don't complain
that somebody is blocking me. If you want to be mayor of this city,
you've got to be able to produce the leadership to get things
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano, who said he represents an independent voice for San
Francisco, suggested that Brown's style of governing may not be
what's best for the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Board of Supervisors and the mayor are co-equal and they
shouldn't be beholden to each other,'' Ammiano said.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates' one-hour debate touched on several other issues,
most of which focused on Bayview-Hunters Point - an economically
depressed neighborhood with a large population of African
Americans, and one of Brown's traditional strongholds.
</P>
<P>
   The debate, sponsored by the League of Women Voters, was not
broadcast on television or radio, but was held in front of a live
audience heavily weighted toward the mayor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
