<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE AGREEMENT SPURS STOCK BUYING IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In a dark, cavernous room literally tucked under the
seats of the Beijing Workers Stadium, hundreds of Chinese spend
time sitting on coarse wooden benches squinting to see red and
green numbers march down an electronic display screen half as long
as a football field.
</P>
<P>
   In groups of two or three, the spectators, all men, chat and
joke. They smoke and drink tea. Occasionally one grabs his wallet
and rushes to the transaction terminals under the screen, anxious
to make a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   With its smoky haze and cement floor littered with butts, the
room has the look of a subterranean Off Track Betting office. In
fact, it is an office of the Beijing International Trust Investment
Co. and Security Exchange _ one of China's many new stock
brokerages for the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Small Chinese investors and would-be investors have been
converging at such places all over China, particularly in the past
couple of weeks since China and the United States signed a trade
agreement that is expected to lead to China's membership in the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   A slice of urban China, they have come filled with hopes and
worries, theories and predictions about the economic impact of the
deal, which theoretically will give foreign companies far greater
access to China's markets and give Chinese companies increased
opportunities to sell goods overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I heard the thing was signed I put all my money
in,'' said Liang Yongbin, a cheerful 31-year-old chef, who stood
before a screen of computer graphics at the brokerage one recent
day, studying the saw-tooth path of Chinese stock-price behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Since the trade pact was signed Nov. 15, the domestic stock
markets have seesawed, rising and falling on shifting opinions and
rumors about winners and losers among Chinese companies.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the 135-nation trade group's ministerial meeting
in Seattle, some of the investor euphoria surrounding the prospect
of China's membership seems to have abated. Part of the reason may
just be a broad realization that China will not officially join the
trade group until sometime next year, and that its power to
influence the meeting is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   But for long-term investors, the more important fact is that
China and the United States have a significant trade agreement that
is likely to greatly expand their commercial relationship and could
make some Chinese stocks very attractive several years from now.
And it should lead eventually to a major overhaul of China's
bloated state-owned companies, freeing up economic resources for
more efficient use.
</P>
<P>
   Liang said he started buying stocks _ textiles mostly _ when he
first heard that the long-stalled negotiations appeared to be
making progress a week or so before the pact was signed. And when
prices fell dramatically for some stocks just after the pact was
announced, he threw in his entire fortune, buying stocks he
considered undervalued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think WTO will have a big impact here, but I think many
stock buyers in China are not experienced enough to understand
it,'' he said. ``And everyone here has a different idea.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the behavior of the stock markets in China, which
are barely a decade old, is not necessarily a reliable barometer of
investor opinion or a forecaster of China's economy. Although the
trade pact has been celebrated as a triumph in the state-controlled
press, Chinese investors have little concrete information, since
only sketchy details of the agreement have been presented in
newspapers and the television news.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately following news of the trade deal, many Chinese
investors quickly dumped the stocks of car makers and
telecommunications companies, industries they believed were poorly
equipped to handle foreign competition. The two Chinese markets,
one in Shanghai and the other in the southern city of Shenzhen,
both fell about 1.5 percent that day.
</P>
<P>
   But over the next few days the same markets surged, as the press
aggressively touted the advantages of the deal. ``Investors are
becoming convinced that China will gain more than its loses from
WTO, thanks to the upbeat media coverage,'' an article in the China
Daily said.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of that week the market had fallen again, with
investors _ on further reflection _ unsure. The same pattern of up
one day, down the next prevailed last week as well. As of the end
of today both the Shanghai and Shenzhen markets had basically
returned to where they were a few weeks ago, off only about 1
percent from their closing levels the day the trade deal was
signed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the initial excitement that the trade deal caused among
the growing populace of stock-market dabblers in China provides
some insight into how far the art of investing has come in this
nation, which once regarded financial markets as contemptible tools
of greedy capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came right over when I heard prices were low and today I'm
buying medicine and information stocks,'' Yu Xiyong, a 30-year-old
in a tweed jacket who works as a clothes seller near the Beijing
Workers Stadium, said one day last week as the market was falling.
He explained that he hoped a WTO agreement might in some way help
traditional pharmaceutical firms export their products and make
more investment available to China's fledgling high technology
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ups and downs, there have been some clear winners
and losers.
</P>
<P>
   Textiles were almost universally seen as a good buy, since the
trade deal requires the United States to remove import tariffs on
Chinese garments within five years. Among the biggest gainers in
the days immediately following the trade deal were Shanghai's No. 3
Woolen Mill Co., partly owned by the state, which rose nearly 23
percent, and China Garments Co., a maker of silks fabrics and
artificial fur, which rose 8 percent. Shares of Jingwei Textile
Machinery Co. rose more than 50 percent, though they have since
relinquished much of their gain.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese automotive industry, on the other hand, suffered
dearly: many of the big losers on both exchanges were companies
which manufacture cars, busses or trucks. Nanfang Motors Co., for
example, which makes small and midsized cars, motorcycles and auto
parts, has fallen more than 10 percent and Monday reached a 52-week
low. Jinan Diesel Engine Co. has fallen 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Under the trade pact, China has promised to drastically reduce
its 80 to 100 percent import duties on foreign-made vehicles _
duties that have forced China's emerging middle class to chose from
a rather sorry range of domestic cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sold cars and bought textiles and electronic equipment the
day after the agreement,'' said Wei, a gnarled unemployed man in a
rust-colored jacket with a cigarette hanging from his mouth. He
predicted that many state enterprises could go bankrupt from the
effects of membership in the WTO.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a country where information is scarce and so much of the
economy is still ultimately under government control, playing the
stock market requires diverse skills: scavenging for financial
facts, watching corporate profits and loss and also trawling for
hints of the government's intentions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when the market jumped immediately following news
of the trade pact, many who follow the stock market suspected that
large investment companies partly owned by the state were buying
stocks at the government's behest to energize a market that had
been sagging.
</P>
<P>
   There are many imponderables in the Chinese stock market. And at
places like Workers Stadium stock exchange, many people play it
safe, wandering in to watch the big board rather than to buy. It is
at once a stock exchange, social club for middle-aged men,
gathering place for retirees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's purpose here is different,'' said Liang, the chef,
who bought Internet stocks when the market slumped a week ago.
``Some come here to make money. Some to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Liang said that in the last three years he had made enough money
with stocks to pay for his wedding and a small apartment. And he
feels that in the long term, membership in the trade organization
would be good for Chinese business and that stock prices would
rise.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he explained, ``I know the stock market here is still a
kind of gambling. But I'm young and earning money, so it's OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
