<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS-TRADE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With Thrashers slumping, GM listening for right offers
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thrashers general manager Don Waddell got calls Monday
morning from four counterparts. A newspaper story had suggested
that the struggling expansion team might be preparing to clear
roster space by cutting loose veteran players. ``I think a lot of
GMs, like me, bookmark newspaper Web sites,'' Waddell said.
</P>
<P>
   At least six teams have contacted Waddell since he said last
week that a number of rookie recalls from the minors and early
evaluation of veterans could lead him to ``move some veteran guys
out of here.'' Waddell took the response as good news. If a general
manager wants anything, it's a bidding war.
</P>
<P>
   But no deals had developed as of Monday. The Thrashers made only
one roster move, reassigning goalie Rick Tabaracci to Orlando,
ostensibly to get him into a game Wednesday at Kansas City while
the Thrashers have a four-day break. Tabaracci played strong hockey
for two periods Sunday against Dallas, then allowed three goals in
the third period of a 4-2 loss, the team's 11th in 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   Tabaracci's return before Friday's game against Florida hinges
on the health of Damian Rhodes and Norm Maracle, both
rehabilitating from ankle sprains. Maracle, who has been practicing
and appears to be ahead of Rhodes, could be activated before
Friday. If neither makes it back, Tabaracci will return. The
concussion suffered Saturday by right winger Nelson Emerson, out at
least two weeks, might have bought some time for a Thrasher. When
defenseman Petr Buzek was activated from injured reserve, Emerson
went on IR to make roster room. Otherwise, Buzek's activation would
have taken up a spot.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one move will have to be made when left winger
Jason Botterill is recalled from Orlando, possibly before the team
leaves on a West Coast trip next week.
</P>
<P>
   Botterill was recalled Oct. 30, played three games, missed three
with a back injury and was sent back down for two weeks of
conditioning. But he suffered a concussion in his first game with
the Solar Bears. He returned Friday and has a goal and two assists
in three games.
</P>
<P>
   Other potential moves in the near future include activating
defenseman Maxim Galanov from injured reserve and recalling
defenseman Brett Clark from Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell said only that he is ``on the phone every day'' and
would not speculate on roster changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we feel like we can improve the team, we'll trade for a
player or draft picks or create room on the roster for young
players to get more ice time,'' he said. ``But I'm not going to
make a deal to hurt anybody. I'm only going to make a deal if
something makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
