<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4382 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-EXXON-MOBILE-HNS &LR;      11-29 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXXON-MOBILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANNED EXXON-MOBILE MERGER TO BRING 2,000 WORKERS TO HOUSTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
and MICHAEL DAVIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON_ More than 2,000 workers are expected to relocate to
Houston in the wake of Exxon Corp.'s planned $83.5 billion purchase
of its longtime rival Mobil Corp., sources close to the merger
talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state regulators are poised to approve that merger
Tuesday, after wrenching promises from the oil giants during
pain-staking, yearlong negotiations to sell off or end contracts
with more than 2,400 service stations nationwide, including about
84 Mobil-branded stations in the Greater Houston area, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been like an elephant giving birth,'' said Fadel Gheit,
an oil analyst with Fahnestock &AMP; Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   When Exxon and Mobil first announced plans a year ago to pull
off the largest industrial merger to date, they envisioned slashing
9,000 jobs worldwide as part of the consolidation effort.
</P>
<P>
   Now industry analysts expect those job cuts to be even deeper.
But the influx of new jobs to the Houston area is expected to
offset those losses and provide a net employment gain for the local
economy.
</P>
<P>
   This combined company, to be known as Exxon Mobil Corp., plans
to consolidate its exploration and production business as well as
its chemical operations in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the more than 2,000 employees relocating to Houston will
be pulled from Mobil's offices in Dallas, as well as Mobil's
corporate offices in Fairfax, Va., and even from operations
overseas, sources close to the negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon employs about 12,800 workers in the Greater Houston,
including 4,000 at the company's refinery in nearby Baytown. Mobil
has 575 workers in the area, and another 2,300 in Beaumont.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kollaer, president of the Greater Houston Partnership, the
city's business booster, said consolidations occur in the energy
sector ``Houston seems to come out O.K.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission and attorney generals from Texas,
California and a number of other states are expected to approve the
merger Tuesday. Regulators from the European Union, Canada,
Australia and several other countries have already signed off on
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Attorney General John Cornyn ``is optimistic that the
conditions of the merger will preserve a competitive marketplace
for Texas,'' said Cornyn spokesman Ted Delisi.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal has voiced
concerns about the merger, but he does not have the power to block
a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of a consent decree to be unveiled Tuesday,
Exxon and Mobil will sell more than 2,400 service stations,
representing about 15 percent of the companies' stations
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Those locations are primarily in the Northeast and California,
sources said. In Texas, the agreement will affect more than 330
service stations, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of those locations are owned by Tetco Stores, a joint
venture between Mobil and San-Antonio-based Tetco, which operates
service stations stretching from San Antonio to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Mobil also will pull out of a joint venture with Dallas-based
Southland involving 10 stations under the 7-Eleven banner in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Gheit said he was somewhat surprised by the number of service
stations the combined company will be expected to sell. ``I thought
it would cost a pound of flesh, and it cost a pound and a half,''
Gheit said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with regulators is expected to allow the new
owners to continue selling gasoline under the Exxon and Mobil names
for the next decade. Motorists could continue to use their Exxon
and Mobil credit cards and could continue to purchase gasoline
feature Exxon and Mobil proprietary detergent packages, the
features that distinguish one brand from another.
</P>
<P>
   Service station dealers, meanwhile, are fearful regulators _ in
their zeal to find buyers large enough to represent real
competition for Exxon Mobil in the retail business _ will try to
circumvent a regulation that gives independent owner operators the
right of first refusal in the case of a sale. They have threatened
to sue if the consent decree does not give them that option.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators also insisted the combined company sell a
129,500-barrel-a-day refinery owned by Exxon in Benicia, Calif., in
the northern part of that state. Mobil owns the 130,000
barrel-a-day Torrance refinery near Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Those refineries serve different parts of the state. And Equilon
Enterprises, the Houston-based refining, marketing and
transportation joint venture between Shell Oil Co. and Texaco,
already controls a greater share of the refining market in
California than a combined Exxon and Mobil would.
</P>
<P>
   But California only has a handful of refiners supplying its
special blend of gasoline, and regulators feared any consolidation
would send already high California pump prices even higher.
</P>
<P>
   A combined Exxon Mobil also will control about 18 percent of the
refining capacity along the Gulf Coast, with Exxon's Baytown and
Baton Rouge, La., plants, and Mobil's Beaumont refinery and joint
venture with the Venezuelan state-owned oil company in Chalmette,
La.
</P>
<P>
   Many refining analysts had expected regulators to force the new
mega-giant to sell off one of these plants. Instead, government
officials were satisfied with promised changes in the lube oils
business.
</P>
<P>
   By purchasing Mobil, Exxon not only will secure its position as
the largest publicly traded oil company in the world but also _ at
least for now _ become the largest corporation in the United States
as measured by revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Many have raised concerns about regulators allowing these two
companies to stitch together two of the main pieces of the old
Standard Oil Co. broken up nearly a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teddy Roosevelt, where are you when we need you,'' Sen. Paul
Wellstone, D-Minn., lamented recently, referring to the president
who took on Standard Oil.
</P>
<P>
   Wenonah Hauter, an activist with Public Citizen, called the
merger ``terrible news for consumers, because it is likely to lead
to higher prices at the gas pumps and decreased competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new oil company is expected to have staggering annual
revenues, possibly larger than the economies of Denmark, Austria or
Greece,'' Hauter said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the concerns, combining these two oil majors will not
recreate the kind of monopoly enjoyed by Standard Oil. The two
companies' combined oil production in 1998 _ 2.5 million barrels a
day _ is only slightly more than the 2.3 million barrels a day
Mobil produced in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Merging the companies is not expected to be simple or easy. When
British Petroleum merged with Amoco, a culture clash took place and
the same is expected to occur at Exxon Mobil.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have two excellent companies with strong heritages which
makes for very strong cultures,'' said Jonathan Crystal, senior
director with the Houston office of executive search firm Spencer
Stuart. ``Anytime you try to combine such strong cultures, it will
be more difficult than less difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Crystal's office has already begun working to find new jobs for
current or former Mobil employees, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon shares rose 1 3/8 Monday to close at 79 3/8 on the New
York Stock Exchange, while Mobil's stock rose 9/16 to close at 103
1/2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 2004EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
