<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4383 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-HOLIDAYS-SINGLES-HNS &LR;      11-29 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAYS-SINGLES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAYS BRING UP A SINGLE PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CELINA OTTAWAY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ This is a plea to Mom, Dad, Grandma, Titi, Nana,
Auntie and all the uncles from Andre to Jarrel to Zach this holiday
season.
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask. Don't hint. Don't tell.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when in the presence of single people, think twice
before starting any question that begins with the word,
``Soooooooooooo?''
</P>
<P>
   The word can make even the calmest single jump.
</P>
<P>
   As in, ``Soooooooooo, is there someone special?''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``Soooooooooo, how do you like my dentist's nephew who I
invited for dessert and sat next to you even though it meant
rearranging the whole table and making your Uncle Lou sit in the
kitchen?''
</P>
<P>
   And the cut to the chase, ``Soooooooooo, grandchildren?''
</P>
<P>
   Jumpy. Very jumpy. Stomach-turning-can't-hold-the-pumpkin-pie
jumpy.
</P>
<P>
   Put yourself in their shoes for a second.
</P>
<P>
   The single person in your life comes over for dinner and is
hugging a table leg between his three married sisters and their
husbands. Or maybe your sister, who just broke up with her fiance,
flies in to spend the holiday with you and your poodle, Boom Boom.
Or your daughter takes a break from her 70-hour-a-week job to bake
with you for an afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Holidays are filled with expectations. Everyone is in love.
Families (read large groups of couples linked by blood and more
importantly MARRIAGE) are perfect. Turkeys are juicy.
</P>
<P>
   Nagging about someone's love life during the holidays is like
reminding them that life didn't turn out like all those holiday
movies. And it is their fault.
</P>
<P>
   I asked singles to write about their visits home for the
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize that they're trying to show their interest in me,
but it makes me feel like I'm not living up to what they expect of
me,'' wrote one woman from Troy, N.Y. ```So, seeing anybody
special? When's the wedding?' It's gentle pressure toward their
idea of a good life, which involves marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If instead they asked, `How are you? What's new and exciting?'
they'd show their interest in my life, being completely supportive,
without putting pressure on me about my love life.''
</P>
<P>
   If any of your single relatives actually want to talk about
their love lives, they will. As one man _ who welcomes his mother
collecting phone numbers on his behalf _ wrote, ``I can use all the
help I can get.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the rest, here's how it looks.
</P>
<P>
   If they have a ``special someone'' and are ready to talk about
it, they would have been gushing on the phone a week ago. Asking
over the mashed potatoes just makes them feel embarrassed when they
have to answer, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help if you follow this up with, ``Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   And the real topper is, ``Well, when I was your age ...''
</P>
<P>
   Mentioning your prayers, lit candles and imminent death is not
helpful either.
</P>
<P>
   As one 36-year-old University at Albany grad student said, ``If
you have to ask, do it while your child has a mouth full of sweet
potatoes and marshmallows so they can't yell immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Prodding, she said, just makes her think about the differences
between the time when her father was in his 30s and married with a
circle of married friends and her own generation in which she and
most of her friends are single.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman e-mailed me with her family's annual holiday
question:
</P>
<P>
   ``I always hear, `Do you have a boyfriend yet?''' she wrote. ``I
always answer, `No,' and I can see the fear on their faces that I
will never marry. That I will only amount to a miserable, old,
single woman for my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't the turkey _ juicy or dry _ be nicer without that?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 2006EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
