<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-BOYCOTTS-NYT &LR;      11-29 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-BOYCOTTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT TO DECIDE WHETHER BOYCOTT LAW INTERFERES WITH U.S. POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.J.)  (mk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court agreed Monday to decide whether
Massachusetts intruded too far into the realm of foreign policy
when it adopted a law requiring state agencies to boycott companies
that do business with the military regime in Myanmar, formerly
Burma.
</P>
<P>
   So-called Burma laws _ descendants of the numerous state and
local laws that barred trade with South Africa during the era of
apartheid _ have proliferated in the last few years. This case,
with its overtones of federalism and with billions of dollars in
public purchasing power at stake, is likely to be one of the most
closely watched disputes on the court's docket.
</P>
<P>
   New York City and more than two dozen localities have barred
their departments and agencies from buying goods and services from
companies that trade with Burma, Cuba or other authoritarian
regimes.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling last June, the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in
Boston, declared the Massachusetts law unconstitutional as an
``impermissible intrusion into the foreign affairs power of the
national government.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision upheld an earlier ruling by a federal district
judge in Boston, in a lawsuit challenging the 1996 law filed by the
National Foreign Trade Council, an association of companies that do
business overseas. Thirty-four of the group's member companies were
on the state's ``restricted purchase'' list. The European Union
filed a brief in the district court opposing the law, and both the
European Union and Japan brought formal complaints about the law to
the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Striking down the law in an opinion by Judge Sandra Lynch, the
appeals court said that while there was no debate over the
existence of ``deplorable'' conditions in Myanmar, a state had no
constitutional authority to regulate conduct beyond its borders.
Judge Lynch said the law was a ``direct attempt to regulate the
flow of foreign commerce,'' a sphere of activity she said was the
exclusive province of the federal government under the foreign
commerce clause of the Constitution. That clause of Article I gives
Congress the power to ``regulate commerce with foreign nations.''
</P>
<P>
   In the state's Supreme Court appeal, filed by Andrew Natsios,
the Massachusetts secretary of administration and finance, the
state makes the contrary argument that ``not one constitutional
grant, prohibition, or command requires the states to trade with
dictators.'' Noting that 23 states and 80 cities had once had
``selective purchasing'' laws aimed at South Africa, the
Massachusetts brief said that ``nothing in our federal Constitution
denies to the states the right to apply a moral standard to their
spending decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   A broad spectrum of groups filed friend-of-the-court briefs
urging the justices to hear the Massachusetts appeal, Natsios vs.
National Foreign Trade Council, No. 99-474. A group of state and
local governments as well as nonprofit and human rights
organizations told the court to overturn the appeals court's
decision, while business groups including the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce and the National Association of Manufacturers said the
justices should take the case in order to affirm the appeals court
and make its decision binding on the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   In her opinion, Judge Lynch, noting that there are 39,000
different governments in the country, said there was the potential
for cacophony if many others followed the Massachusetts model. She
observed that there were substantial differences between the
Massachusetts law and the more flexible approach the federal
government took almost simultaneously in imposing trade sanctions
on Myanmar. ``In the federal Burma law, Congress has chosen to rely
on both carrots and sticks'' while ``Massachusetts uses a cudgel,''
Judge Lynch said, adding that the state law ``interferes with the
ability of the federal government to speak with one voice.''
</P>
<P>
   In another significant development at the court Monday, the
justices agreed to hear a constitutional challenge to New Jersey's
hate crime law. That law provides enhanced sentences for crimes
that a judge finds were committed ``with a purpose to intimidate an
individual or group of individuals because of race, color, gender,
handicap, religion, sexual orientation, or ethnicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Under New Jersey's Ethnic Intimidation Act, enacted in 1990, a
jury determines whether a defendant is guilty beyond a reasonable
doubt of the underlying offense. The judge then decides, by the
lower standard of ``a preponderance of the evidence,'' whether the
defendant had a ``purpose to intimidate.'' If so, the sentence can
be doubled.
</P>
<P>
   The case, Apprendi vs. New Jersey, No. 99-478, is an appeal by a
white man who received an enhanced sentence, 12 years instead of
10, after pleading guilty to firing a rifle into a nearby house
owned by the only black family in his Vineland neighborhood. While
Charles Apprendi did not dispute that he fired the eight bullets,
he did dispute the judge's finding that he was motivated by a
desire to intimidate the residents because of their race; he
asserted that his act was provoked by an obsessive-compulsive
disorder, aggravated by medication and heavy drinking, and that the
victims' race was not a factor.
</P>
<P>
   In the New Jersey Supreme Court, he argued that in any event,
his motivation was an element of the offense that the prosecution
was constitutionally obliged to prove to a jury beyond a reasonable
doubt. The judge's determination, by a lower standard of proof as
part of the sentencing phase, deprived him of his Sixth Amendment
right to trial by jury, he argued.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Supreme Court rejected the constitutional
challenge and upheld Apprendi's sentence in a 5-2 decision last
June. For its part, the U.S. Supreme Court has indicated
considerable doubt, in other contexts, about the constitutionality
of treating questions about a defendant's state of mind as simple
sentencing factors rather than as essential elements of the offense
that need to be proved to a jury.
</P>
<P>
   In the hate crime context, the approach of providing increased
penalties for crimes motivated by prejudice has won wide acceptance
since it was proposed in the 1980s by the Anti-Defamation League of
B'nai B'rith. Michael Lieberman, a lawyer here for the
Anti-Defamation League, said in an interview Monday that 40 states
and the District of Columbia have enacted some version of the
organization's model statute. He said the majority of these laws
would not be affected by the Supreme Court's decision in the New
Jersey case because, unlike the New Jersey law, most of the laws
make the defendant's motive an element of the offense that a jury
has to find beyond a reasonable doubt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 2008EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
