r l BC-CYBER-SANTAS-HNS &LR;      11-29 1508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBER-SANTAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-SHOPPING'S GREAT FOR MANY, BUT NOT FOR ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DON SHERON  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ For the cyber-savvy, there will be no last-minute
crisis over holiday gift-giving. For them, there will be no
frenzied trips to the malls, no fighting traffic, no midnight
gift-wrapping.
</P>
<P>
   They know that dolls, baseball gloves and computer software are
just a mouse click away and very far from crowded parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Clement of San Antonio is just the kind of online shopper
that dot-com companies cherish. Clement, a parent who has
discovered the joys of shopping online, plans to do at least some
holiday shopping online.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an efficiency freak,'' said Clement, senior vice
president, corporate development for American TeleSource
International Inc., a San Antonio-based telecommunications/Internet
software company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's being the typical man. I know what I want. I get it (from
the online store) and get out,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday season isn't the only time people shop online,
however. ``I can do it late at night or whenever I want,'' said
Doug Weatherston, a restaurant owner in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   He has bought for himself a 1976 Rolls Royce from the eBay
auction site, as well as replacement china, a jacket, jewelry and a
CD player from online retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   Weatherston views online shopping much like shopping by catalog,
only easier. ``I don't have a stack of mail-order catalogs at home,
but I have the equivalent with the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done more shopping online during the past six months than
I have by catalog during the past six years.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the millions who have joined Clement and Weatherston to
shop online, Internet retailing remains an infant industry compared
to its brick-and-mortar sibling. Consumer e-commerce in the United
States now generates less than 1 percent of the nation's overall
retail sales of $2 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   But holiday sales and Internet commerce are getting greener,
much greener.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 million people plan to do at least some holiday
shopping online this year, according to some surveys. They are
forming a growing part of e-commerce that will explode from sales
of $20.5 billion this year to $147 billion by 2003, according to
Dataquest, a San Jose, Calif.-based market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   This holiday season some of the hottest retail categories, as
measured by one firm, are expected to be beauty products, toys and
video games. For these products, online buying will be twice was it
was last year, according to the international marketing information
company, NPD Group, based in Port Washington, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   NPD Group estimates that 68 percent of the Internet users it
surveyed plan to buy something from an Internet site during the
holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   But not clothing. NPD said last week that a majority of people
polled for a recent study - 85 percent of 2,399 respondents - said
they were concerned that they would not be able to try on a piece
of clothing before buying it. Half of the Internet users surveyed
said they never plan to buy clothing online.
</P>
<P>
   For other goods, though, the growth in e-commerce cash will
parallel the increase in the number of e-commerce sites. Today,
there are more than 2 million sites, four times the number last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just increasing at an amazing rate,'' thanks to
e-commerce sites becoming easier to create, said Carol Ferrara,
senior analyst in San Jose with the Stamford, Conn.-based
GartnerGroup, which owns Dataquest.
</P>
<P>
   And while Web sites may proliferate, they have to be able to
pull in online shoppers. Some e-retailers, for example, are
offering consumers the opportunity to cash in coupons or collect
``rewards'' such as gift certificates just for surfing the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, for example, has been offering its customers a $10
gift certificate for any toy or video game in its online bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   ``In e-commerce, it's a very big trend,'' said Hilary Billings,
president and chief executive of RedEnvelope Gifts Online,
originally called 911gifts.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``These incentives are important to get new buyers to come in.
Then the pressure is on you to make sure that (shopping) experience
is going to keep them coming back,'' Billings said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, San Antonio retailers are expecting a strong shopping
season this year. TeleCheck Services, a check approval company,
estimates that retail sales nationwide will jump 3 percent to 5
percent over last year's holiday season. In San Antonio, sales may
climb 4 percent to 5 percent higher than last year, said economist
Keith Phillips at the San Antonio Federal Reserve Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers know that online sites can't give consumers the direct
contact with products they get in a traditional store.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see it as a picture, but you can't test drive it,''
said Clay Killinger, a San Antonio-based partner and retail analyst
with the national accounting firm Arthur Andersen. ``You really
need to know what you're buying.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than competition, traditional retailers see the Internet
as an additional marketing tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finding that it (online selling) doesn't have a
tremendous impact on our stores,'' said Rob Wallstrom, general
manager of Saks Fifth Avenue in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   But Saks, like many well-known names in retailing, won't ignore
online selling. The New York-based retailer plans to launch its own
Internet site in the spring. ``It becomes an enhancement to
brick-and-mortar stores. It's more branding for the store,''
Wallstrom said.
</P>
<P>
   Saks will be joining high-end retailer Nordstrom, which has more
than one Web site, including the new Nordstromshoes.com, along with
such other well-known retailers as the Gap, Lands' End and outdoor
apparel and equipment seller REI.
</P>
<P>
   Brick-and-mortar stores and Internet retailers may be chasing
after the same dollars, but they aren't necessarily treading on
each others' toes. To survive, retailers will need to offer
consumers multiple shopping options, whether in traditional stores,
by catalog or over the Internet, says Dataquest's Ferrara.
</P>
<P>
   Having multiple shopping options means that savvy consumers can
compare prices and check up on the best Internet retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do a lot more effective research on the Internet,''
Killinger said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the online version of Consumer Reports began this
month evaluating Web sites just as it has for traditional stores.
Consumer Reports Online's e-Ratings is available to members at:
</P>
<P>
   www.consumerreports.org
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Forrester Research, an independent research firm
based in Cambridge, Mass., also ranks top commercial Web sites for
apparel, computing, books, toys, flowers, health and general
merchandise at:
</P>
<P>
   powerrankings.forrester.com When shopping online, however,
consumers should watch what they are doing. In other words,
practice safe shopping.
</P>
<P>
   The American Bar Association has created a new Web site with a
tip list to help consumers. It's at: www.safeshopping.org
</P>
<P>
   These tips include:
</P>
<P>
   Trust your instincts.
</P>
<P>
   Be knowledgeable about Web-based auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Double-check pricing.
</P>
<P>
   Review the return, refund, shipping and handling policies and
other legal terms.
</P>
<P>
   Check to make sure that the Web site is using security software
to protect your Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   Pay by credit card, so if there is a problem later on you can
dispute it more easily.
</P>
<P>
   Print out a copy of the terms and conditions of the
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Ensure the safe delivery of your purchased items.
</P>
<P>
   Inspect your purchase.
</P>
<P>
   If a consumer has a complaint about an online vendor or needs
free information about how to spot or avoid a fraudulent business
practice, call the Federal Trade Commission, toll-free, at (877)
FTC-HELP (382-4357), or visit the FTC Web site and click on the
link to Consumer Protection at:
</P>
<P>
   www.ftc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Safe shopping is only part of the online adventure. Consumers
want a Web site that is easy to access and download.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web right now is more of a transactional medium than a
relationship-building medium,'' said Ferrara, the GartnerGroup
analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retailers still have a ways to go to providing customer
service and establishing better relationships with customers,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Customer service issues such as on-time shipping and the
consumers' ability to return merchandise just now are becoming
integral in business-to-consumer e-commerce. Such services may be
fully in place within the next year or two.
</P>
<P>
   That's because online shoppers are expecting to have some of the
same conveniences as if they were shopping in person, she added.
``The online population is beginning to mirror the offline
population.''
</P>
<P>
   For any number of goods, customers still will walk into
brick-and-mortar stores rather than shop for these items online or
through a catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Even Clement of San Antonio admits that most of his Christmas
shopping will be done in the old-fashioned brick-and-mortar
environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
