<HEADLINE>
RESIGNATION SHAKES UNITED ASSET MANAGEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Turmoil rocked United Asset Management Corp. Monday as
the troubled investment management firm saw its number two leader
resign suddenly and its longstanding top executive and founder
announce he would retire soon.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise changes, which some industry analysts said
reflected fundamental problems with UAM's core strategy, left a
question mark over the company's immediate future and prompted talk
that UAM might undertake a dramatic restructuring or spin off some
of its languishing assets.
</P>
<P>
   Barely 18 months after joining the company, president Charles E.
Haldeman Jr. said he was leaving to head the Philadelphia-based
investment management arm of Lincoln National Corp., a leading life
insurer. Haldeman, 50, rose through the ranks of a UAM affiliate
and had been charged with turning around the parent's cash-flow
problems.
</P>
<P>
   His resignation, which he said was for personal reasons,
prompted Norton H. Reamer , UAM's 64-year-old chief executive,
board chairman, and founder to announce he would step down once a
new leader was found to assume both Reamer's and Haldeman's duties.
</P>
<P>
   The two men had functioned as co-leaders, and Reamer, who had
not publicly discussed retiring until Monday, said it would be
easier to recruit a single new top executive rather than try to
fill two slots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're losing Ed (Haldeman) and we wish we weren't, but we
still have five out of six of the main people here,'' said Reamer.
</P>
<P>
   Haldeman was born and raised in Philadelphia and spent 23 years
at Philadelphia-based Cooke &AMP; Bieler, a UAM affiliate, before
moving to the parent company last year.
</P>
<P>
   UAM stock fell 1/4 Monday to close at 19 3/4. It is down about
24 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   UAM is a publicly-traded umbrella organization for 50 investment
management, marketing and distribution companies throughout the
United States and abroad. At a time when booming stock markets have
enriched money management companies, UAM has seen large outflows of
money. UAM, which oversees $193.6 billion in assets, saw clients
pull $19.8 billion in assets last year _ about 10 percent of its
asset base _ and $16 billion in 1997. The company lost about $11.5
billion in assets so far this year, but outflows had slowed in the
past two quarters to half the rate of previous periods.
</P>
<P>
   UAM has said it is the victim of a successful stock market in
which pension fund clients, its core customers, do not have to put
fresh money into plans run by UAM affiliates. UAM argues that the
market is giving them good returns and enabling them to forgo
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts cite poor investment performance and flaws in
UAM's basic strategy. UAM owns 100 percent of its affiliates, a
structure some observers have said leaves little incentive for the
subsidiaries to boost business. ``Ed (Haldeman) was there to try to
turn things around, and there was not terrific evidence that it was
working,'' said James P. Hanbury of Schroder Securities. ``The 100
percent equity ownership has proven to be faulty.''
</P>
<P>
   Reamer said UAM would continue a revamp launched last year under
which the company will selectively finance only its top businesses,
rather than offer equal support to all affiliates, and create
incentive plans linking compensation to cash flow improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think our turnaround strategy is unfolding fairly well and
will continue with that strategy,'' Reamer said, adding that the
company was putting $25 million a year into its top 18 firms.
</P>
<P>
   UAM tried last year to sell a once-ailing affiliate, Pilgrim
Baxter &AMP; Associates, but the deal fell through when the buyer,
Nationwide Financial Services, backed out. Earlier this year, a
noted Pilgrim Baxter fund manager, James McCall, moved to Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co. UAM tried but failed through a lawsuit to force him to
stay under a non-compete clause in his employment contract. A UAM
spokesman, Tucker Hughes, declined to say whether UAM would seek a
new buyer for Pilgrim Baxter now that the unit's assets are up to
$14 billion from $10 billion at the start of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
