u f BC-AIR &LR; - &UR; FARES-NYT &LR;      11-29 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN, CONTINENTAL AND UNITED REVERSE COURSE ON FARE INCREASE _
FOR NOW  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 - FARES-NYT   By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 3 percent increase in air fares last week was quietly rolled
back when American Airlines, Continental Airlines and United
Airlines threw in the towel _ American on Sunday, Continental and
United on Monday. But analysts say that sooner or later, probably
sooner, the airlines will try to raise fares again.
</P>
<P>
   The cancellation appeared almost inevitable when Delta Air
Lines, which had followed American's lead in raising fares across
the board eight days ago, decided on Thursday to rescind its raise
``to remain competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   That was an apparent reference to the refusal by Northwest
Airlines, US Airways, Trans World Airlines and America West
Airlines to go along with the increase.
</P>
<P>
   The about-face by Delta, the third biggest airline, put pressure
on United, the unit of the UAL Corp. that is the leading carrier;
American, the AMR Corp. unit that is No. 2; and Continental, No. 5,
to reverse as well.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines attributed the proposed increases to rises in the
cost of aviation fuel, their second biggest expense after labor.
Tim Smith, a spokesman for American Airlines, said Monday that the
3 percent fare rise was intended to help offset a fuel-cost
increase of 15 percent in the third quarter over the same period in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   That increase, he said, resulted in a $456 million fuel bill for
the quarter, up from about $400 million in the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Murphy, an analyst for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co.,
said, ``With profits expected to be down 20 to 30 percent this
year, mostly because of fuel costs, you would figure it would be
easy to pass on part of the fuel increase. What the cancellation
shows is that this is an industry that still cannot cover its cost
of capital or adopt rational pricing, even in a strong economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts said, expect the carriers to return to the
issue. ``Higher fuel prices impact airlines across the board, so to
the extent that you see oil at elevated levels for an extended
period of time, we'll certainly see airlines come back with another
increase,'' Sam Buttrick, an analyst for Paine Webber, said.
</P>
<P>
   David Swierenga, the chief economist of the Air Transport
Association, the industry's trade group, said that although there
have been several substantial fare increases this year,
``Passengers are paying eight-tenths of 1 percent less this year
than a year ago, because they have shopped for better bargains.''
</P>
<P>
   Buttrick agreed, saying that while posted leisure fares are up
15 percent this year, the actual fare paid is down almost 1
percent. ``Posted fares are increasingly irrelevant,'' he added,
``as leisure and business travelers shop for and find lower fares,
aided by the Internet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 2010EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4396 &Cx1f; tad-z
