<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley outlines inclusive, general foreign policy
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDFORD, Mass. _ Democrat Bill Bradley pledged Monday to return
bipartisan consensus to American foreign policy decisions if
elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an old saying that political divisions stopped at
the water's edge,'' Bradley told students and faculty at Tufts
University. ``Sadly, that consensus has vanished. Foreign policy
has become more of a political football or is made through polling
or focus groups to score domestic political points. I deplore
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech and in response to questions afterward, Bradley
offered few specific solutions to hot spots around the world.
Instead, Bradley sought to cast himself as a principled leader who
understood the changing global economy.
</P>
<P>
   He said the three goals of foreign policy in his administration
would be to act to protect U.S. national security, maintain
America's leadership position in the world and ``talk honestly to
the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   He portrayed himself as a strong internationalist who would rely
heavily on help from organizations such as the United Nations to
quell unrest abroad before those conflicts became major threats to
world peace.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley called for a new round of nuclear arms reduction talks
between the United States and Russia. The United States should
pursue the negotiations, he said, even though Russia has not
ratified the last negotiated treaty, START II.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said the goal of the third round of START talks should
be to reduce the number of nuclear warheads on each side to between
1,000 and 2,000, down from a level of 6,000 warheads per side
established under the first START treaty.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the threat posed by Russia's aging arsenal of
nuclear warheads, Bradley also listed Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein,
instability on the Korean peninsula and international terrorists as
the major threats to U.S. security in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the multinational response to bloodshed in East Timor
and the 1991 intervention in Kuwait as examples of how nations can
work together to defend American interests. Bradley voted against
the 1991 Senate resolution authorizing President Bush to use force
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley spokesman Eric Hauser later described the vote as an
effort to give economic sanctions more time to work, and said
Bradley supported the use of U.S. troops in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Republican front-runner George W. Bush spelled out his foreign
policy vision in a speech Nov. 19 at the Ronald Reagan Presidential
Library in Simi Valley, Calif. Bush called for a foreign policy of
moderation in which the United States is not the world's cop but is
not afraid of wielding its clout, either.
</P>
<P>
   Bush keyed on Russia and China, adding a nod to India's growing
importance.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Monday, Bradley took no direct shots at the
Clinton-Gore administration. But he criticized the United States'
handling of Russia since the fall of communism, saying a succession
of American leaders had failed to leverage weapons reductions out
of Russia in exchange for economic assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also sought to draw attention to his experience in
foreign policy. In his 18 years as a senator from New Jersey,
Bradley served eight years on the Senate Intelligence Committee. He
also belonged to the congressional task force that helped launch
the round of trade negotiations that led to the creation of the
World Trade Organization in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's speech Monday came as the Clinton administration is
hosting world leaders in Seattle to launch a new round of world
trade talks.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, an ardent free trader, did not talk about the WTO
summit in his remarks. But in response to a question he said
changes should be made to the world body's controversial conflict
dispute resolution mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said the WTO, which has been criticized for ignoring the
environmental impact of rulings, should have greater input from
interest groups and open more of its proceedings open to the
public. He also called for temporary wage supplements to U.S.
workers who lose their jobs because of trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are all things we can try to do to mitigate the negative
impact aspects of international trade, while keeping in full view
the overwhelmingly greater positive aspects of international
trade,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit
the Cox News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
