<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-CLUTTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY SEASON MAY BE THE RIGHT TIME TO GET CLUTTER OUT OF YOUR
LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATE GURNETT  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ If your daily bread is hard to spot beneath the
piles of clutter in your house, how will you ever find your
Christmas pudding?
</P>
<P>
   The holidays are a microcosm of your whole life, experts say. If
it's a muddle, odds are the holidays will be, too. But there's good
news.
</P>
<P>
   Now is the best time to simplify.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, now. Especially now.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't this the worst time to plunge into a new habit? Hardly. If
you don't, remember, you'll be exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   Taking care of the things you can control helps you cope with
those you can't, like the stack of invitations in the mail or the
line of traffic snaking ever slower. Or Mother Nature dropping a
foot of snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let it snow!'' you exclaim as you go through your happy tasks.
I am organized!
</P>
<P>
   To help, local clutter-buster Helen Volk has written a 33-page
booklet that highlights the key steps a person can take to handle
the holidays. Titled ``Organize and De-Stress the Christmas
Season,'' it costs $8.50 and is available on Volk's company Web
site, http://www.beyondclutter.com.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with a step back, Volk said. An attitude check. If
you're whining, or bah-humbugging, stop.
</P>
<P>
   All those tasks you gave yourself? They're choices. View them as
such. After all, you selected them. Do them with a sense of fun and
excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop telling yourself you must get ready for the next
happening,'' said Volk. ``Deal with each event as it arrives. Don't
worry about next week's party while you're picking out a Christmas
tree -- it won't make the party any better or help you enjoy
tree-selecting now.''
</P>
<P>
   This time of year, people are too stressed out to read a
200-page book, said Volk, a former pack-rat attorney who quit her
job to de-clutter her life and create the consulting firm Beyond
Clutter.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are so busy paying bills and keeping the house clean,
they don't ever stop and ask, 'What do I want to do with my
life?''' adds Janet Luhrs, a fellow ex-lawyer and Seattle
simplicity guru. ``They're unhappy, they want meaning in their
lives, they're stressed, so they just keep going in lockstep.''
</P>
<P>
   She suggests calling a family meeting to talk about what the
holidays mean to you and how you'd like to celebrate. ``Once you've
got that umbrella of values in place, things can fan out from
there,'' she said. ``The point is to focus on people, not things.''
</P>
<P>
   Set a holiday budget. Remember, money does not equal love. ``I
don't want people to work extra hours and go into debt to get me a
gift,'' said Luhrs, author of ``The Simple Living Guide'' (Broadway
Books 1997), which has a chapter devoted to the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Luhrs' final bit of advice: Quit shopping.
</P>
<P>
   It took several years for simple-living advocate and author
Elaine St. James to bow out of the holidays, she recalls in her
book, ``Simplify Your Christmas: 100 Ways to Reduce The Stress &AMP;
Recapture the Joy of the Holidays'' (Andrews McMeel 1998).
</P>
<P>
   First, she advises, figure out what is complicating your
holidays. You don't need to change everything. It might be just
Christmas cards, or preparing family meals, or attending office
parties, or giving too many gifts.
</P>
<P>
   St. James and her husband stopped trimming a tree (whenever they
did, the cats trashed it anyway). They limited gift-giving to those
young children in their lives who still believed in Santa Claus.
</P>
<P>
   St. James offers alternatives. Focus on the solstice, for
example. Watching the sun rise and set each day with your children
will give them a sense of the seasons. Have them keep a chart of
the times as they watch the days quickly get longer. Or take walks
in the woods or mountains. ``Adopt'' an endangered species by
giving to a conservation organization.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, experts agree, is this: Simplifying is not
organizing. Organizers often shuffle the same list of things. When
you simplify, you actually eliminate things you feel you have to
do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
