<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN IS HOSPITALIZED WITH SUSPECTED PNEUMONIA  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin was hospitalized Monday for the
second time in less than two months after doctors detected possible
pneumonia during a checkup, his press secretary said.
</P>
<P>
   Dmitri Yakushkin, the press secretary, said that Yeltsin was
taken to the elite Central Clinical Hospital after doctors examined
him at his country residence. Yeltsin, 68, spent two days in the
hospital in October with the flu.
</P>
<P>
   He was reported ill with acute bronchitis last week. His ailment
led to the postponement of the signing of a treaty for union with
Belarus that is unpopular with some Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Yakushkin on Monday denied once again conjectures that the main
purpose of signing such a treaty would be to enable Yeltsin to run
for president of a new union.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Russian Constitution, he can serve only two terms, and
his second term will end next July.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's plans are ``absolutely unambiguous,'' Yakushkin said.
``He leaves office in the summer of next year and intends to serve
out his presidential term and hand over power to the next
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, Yakushkin reported that Yeltsin was still being
treated for a cold at his country residence and that his voice ``is
still hoarse.''
</P>
<P>
   Television footage was shown that was described as a meeting
Monday with Alexander Voloshin, his chief of staff, and it showed
Yeltsin looking alert and well, but later, Yakushkin reported that
Yeltsin had been hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has disappeared from public view at critical junctures a
number of times. He was reported to be having minor nose surgery in
December 1994, just as Russian troops first invaded Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1996, shortly after his re-election to a second
term, Yeltsin had quintuple bypass surgery. The Kremlin later
admitted that his disappearance just a week before the critical
vote against the Communist leader, Gennady Zyuganov, was because he
had a series of heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has been hospitalized four times this year, spending a
total of nearly six weeks in the hospital and much of the rest of
the time recuperating in his country residence or in a sanitorium
outside Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the public reaction to Yeltsin's ailments no longer
causes the panic it did even a year ago. On the one hand, he is
often ill. On the other hand, his chosen successor, Prime Minister
Vladimir Putin _ whose appointment this summer when he was the
little-known head of the Federal Security Service elicited
puzzlement _ appears to be firmly in control.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, not Yeltsin, is the one who is by all appearances in
charge of the current Chechen operation. The prime minister's
approval rating is higher than that of any other candidate to
succeed Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his popularity seems to have reduced the chances of the
man who was thought to be the strongest competitor for the job,
Mayor Yuri Luzhkov of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has been known to grow jealous of the popularity of his
own appointees, though. He has fired two prime ministers this year,
but so far, there have been no signs of Putin's imminent removal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
