<HEADER>
A4405 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-EXCELLENCE-HNS &LR;      11-29 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-EXCELLENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE TV A LITTLE CREDIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN   
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all the thanks being given these days, spare a little for
the state of television, will ya?
</P>
<P>
   We're in a kind of creative boom economy on television. There
are riches all around us. It's the kind of environment in which,
even if you decide to give up on ``Once and Again'' just for the
week, you find that time-slot mate and fevered competitor,
``Judging Amy,'' delivered a wonderful Thanksgiving episode that
was superb enough to make you think, ``Perhaps I'm watching the
wrong show.'' Or, at the very least, ``I need to figure out this
VCR.''
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make you as giddy and angelically naive as
Jennifer Love Hewitt. Everywhere you turn, there's something of
interest. Every night. Often in the same time slot. An
embarrassment of riches. Boy, life is good.
</P>
<P>
   Except that if you look a little closer, you can tell that the
TV networks are not feeling comfortable with success, that they are
tampering in the worst kind of ways and that, cynically, you could
say a major blunder across the board is taking shape.
</P>
<P>
   But let's take a look at this one moment. On Tuesday, ABC is
expected to make an announcement about the state of ``Who Wants to
Be A Millionaire.'' When the network unleashed this game show on
the country, everybody went berserk. Then, after the initial run,
the network took it off the schedule and put it on the Big Guns
shelf.
</P>
<P>
   You know, as a kind of security. Then, this sweeps month, it
brought it off the shelf and fired the dang thing at all the other
networks. Down they fell, along with their ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Did you love ``Who Wants to Be A Millionaire'' the second time
around? Most people did. But it grated on you a little, too, didn't
it?
</P>
<P>
   Just when you were losing faith, out popped the first
millionaire in the show's history. That's why this British show was
imported in the first place. Nobody in England was greedy enough to
go for the really big bucks. But in America, everybody wants to be
a millionaire, and damn if we didn't get somebody all the way to
the top.
</P>
<P>
   OK, let's regroup. ABC has to make a decision about the show.
Put it back on the Big Guns shelf or make it a staple on the
schedule - two, maybe three days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Red flags should be popping up everywhere if you really, dearly
love TV. Because ABC has no idea what to do with success. That it
couldn't manage to bring ``NYPD Blue'' back in the fall - because
``Once and Again'' was a hit - proved yet again that the
decision-makers there have spilled their little box of clues.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but ABC seems perplexed on how to turn ``Sports
Night'' into a hit. Pulling it from sweeps, as the network did, is
not the answer. And now, the befuddled folks at the Mickey Mouse
network face a decisive moment: How to handle this luxury of having
so many good shows.
</P>
<P>
   Unless it decides to dump a couple of ``20/20'' nights - don't
count on it - something will have to give. The fear here is that a
good show (or shows) will be scuttled to make room for a game show
that could prove little more than a fad. Yeah, it's hot now but the
format is so limiting and Regis Philbin is so annoying that, soon,
people will tune out. And by then, good comedies or dramas may have
been replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Put your hand on the ground and divine what lays ahead. Meditate
on where things are going. Are you nervous? You should be. What
started in September as a season that looked chock full of good
quality the likes we haven't seen in perhaps a decade is slowly
devolving into game shows, sweeps stunts and the persistent
survival of newsmagazines (and here cynics thought at least one
evil, game shows, would supplant another - but they foster each
other, like weeds).
</P>
<P>
   An argument also could be made that wrestling, which dominates
cable and has resuscitated UPN, is a blight that shows no sign of
abating. In fact, look for additional wrestling shows to pop up
soon - potentially displacing sitcoms or dramas.
</P>
<P>
   Why couldn't we have been given most of the TV season to simply
enjoy and, yes, give thanks for this bounty? Even UPN, when it's
not showing wrestling, has good shows. Most fans of TV have
complained that there's almost too much quality now, and no time to
watch all the shows. That's why we needed time to grow into the
fall schedule. Some people are only now appreciating ``That '70s
Show'' from last season, turning it into a hit. Sometimes, when the
``The X-Files' seems too scary or confusing, ``Snoops'' is a light,
weightless alternative - like a greasy burger that tastes great
even if you're watching your fat grams.
</P>
<P>
   When you're constantly forced to choose between two good shows
in the same time period, it's kind of nice to skip your usual one
night and sample something else. But all of this is in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the real killer: January.
</P>
<P>
   You know what this January thing means, right? To make room for
those new shows, the networks will have to cut loose some old ones.
Unfortunately, old never seems to mean really bad shows such as
``Jesse'' or ``Two Guys and A Girl,'' but old in the sense of ``new
fall shows that people couldn't support because there were so many
other fine offerings.''
</P>
<P>
   Yep, just around the corner could be a rush of fresh sitcoms and
dramas that may catch our imaginations, prick our intellect and
give us soaring hope in television. If you lost ``Sports Night'' or
something else, would that be a fair trade? Could you give up on
``Action'' or maybe a ``Felicity'' to take on something new? What
if that new Levinson-Fontana cop show were really great - could you
drop ``Law &AMP; Order'' or ``The Practice''?
</P>
<P>
   And we haven't even brought ``The Sopranos'' into the equation.
Lord help us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
