<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-DUI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUNKEN DRIVING ARRESTS DIP SHARPLY IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Close enforcement of tougher laws and a shift in
culture have led drunken driving arrests to drop dramatically,
falling by more than half in the past 13 years, according to
figures released by the Boston Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp decline, from 1,357 arrests in 1986 to 397 to date,
comes as Boston Police Commissioner Paul F. Evans says overall
traffic stops and citations by officers have reached an all-time
high.
</P>
<P>
   The plunge, which mirrors a national trend of fewer arrests and
drunken-driving-related deaths in the same time period, follows a
1985 law that made Massachusetts the first in the nation to ban
``happy hours'' in bars and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Evans and others also attributed the falling rates to the slow,
less perceptible work of advocates who have transformed perceptions
around drinking and driving, bringing stiffer punishments and
strong cultural shame to behavior once more widely tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, before groups like Mothers Against Drunk Driving
and others, the criminal justice system didn't really treat driving
under the influence the way it's being treated today,'' said Evans.
``Now there is a lot more public awareness, and a justice system
that does not tolerate repeat offenders.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans said the spiraling numbers were encouraging, particularly
since his patrol officers are busier than ever. They have logged
141,414 traffic stops and citations so far this year, Evans said, a
record number for the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we getting all the offenders out there? Of course not,''
Evans said. ``But the numbers being down is a positive sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet on the heels of a Mothers Against Drunk Driving ``Rating the
States'' report that gave Massachusetts a C- for its record on
combatting drunken driving, MADD officials and other advocates said
Monday the city and the state still have a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   While praising the 1985 ban on happy hours and other significant
legislation, MADD Massachusetts executive director Barbara
Harrington said the laws still are not tough enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that more people should be arrested and more people
should be effectively prosecuted, and we are trying to make changes
so that will happen,'' Harrington said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 192 people died statewide in alcohol-related
accidents, according to Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   According to FBI crime statistics, drunken driving arrests
nationwide jumped in the mid-1970s and continued to rise during the
1980s to about 1.9 million. Since then, the numbers have steadily
fallen, to about 1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   But drunken driving still leads all categories in total traffic
arrests: About 10 percent are for impaired driving, according to
Ralph Hingson, professor at Boston University School of Public
Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of me says it's good that the arrests are going down,
because it also reflects a decline in deaths,'' Hingson said. ``But
we still have a huge problem, in Boston, Massachusetts, and across
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, close to 40 percent of all traffic deaths are
alcohol-related, Hingson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
