<HEADER>
A4408 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-RAIDERS-HNS &LR;      11-29 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAIDERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIDERS FALL ON THEIR SWORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRIAN MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Wait. Weren't we just here six days ago?
</P>
<P>
   You know, at that point where the Raiders' season couldn't sink
any lower, at that point where an excruciating, description-defying
loss to a hated AFC West rival took a crowbar to the kneecaps of
their season?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we were. Except this time, the only snowball is the
Raiders' runaway season, tearing downhill, careening out of
control. And out of the playoffs, most likely.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it was ancient rival Kansas City providing the
breaking of hearts, the shredding of Raider souls. This time, on an
overcast Sunday afternoon at the Coliseum, it was the Chiefs who
somehow overcame a 14-point fourth-quarter deficit, who somehow
willed Raiders kicker Michael Husted to miss a 44-yard field goal
attempt with 2:56 left, who somehow then gained the requisite
yardage to set up their own kicker, Pete Stoyanovich, to make the
same 44-yard attempt with no time left on the clock for a 37-34 win
that has to rank among the Raiders' five most bitter losses since
their return to Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Wait. Didn't we just say that last week, in Denver, after the
now-legendary snowball overtime loss at Mile High Stadium?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we did.
</P>
<P>
   That makes for a tough six-day stretch in Raiderland, a six-day
stretch in which the Raiders transformed from a talented, hopeful,
playoff contender on the rise into a team that can't finish, can't
get lucky and can't win.
</P>
<P>
   It gets so that even brilliant young talents like Raiders
cornerback Charles Woodson are faced with the ugly mug of truth.
Asked if he thought the 5-6 Raiders - who trail Buffalo (8-4) by
21/2 games for the third and final wild-card spot in the AFC, and
who trail the AFC West-leading Seattle Seahawks by three games with
five to play - still could think about the playoffs, Woodson didn't
bother with any false hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Woodson said. ``Not losing games like we're losing.
We've been in every game and we have found a way to lose. No team
going to the playoffs can do that. Now our season is dependent on
other teams losing. We have to win out and we haven't proven we can
win two or three in a row. At this point, it doesn't look good.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did any Raiders who struggled to explain this, their
18th loss in 20 tries to Kansas City in the 1990s. If the Monday
night loss at Denver was the punch to the stomach that doubled them
over, Sunday's loss to the Chiefs was the uppercut that sent them
reeling into oblivion from that doubled-over state. All over the
locker room, Raiders grappled with what had just happened.
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Jon Ritchie tried to describe the pain, but wound up
chuckling in disbelief. It was either that or start crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. ... I don't know how to describe this. ... it's
utter disappointment, utter disbelief,'' Ritchie said. ``I'm having
a hard time swallowing what went down out there.''
</P>
<P>
   So was coach Jon Gruden, whose postgame face looked like a
combination of a man who drank a pint of castor oil through a beer
bong and a guy who had a blast of sand blown into his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am again,'' Gruden said, as if he didn't know what else
to say. ``Obviously, that's a difficult loss. ... Obviously, our
playoff aspirations aren't as bright as they would be if we had
won.''
</P>
<P>
   All over the locker room, the Raiders grappled with the fact
that quarterback Rich Gannon, the ex-Chief who burned to beat his
old team, threw two interceptions in the third quarter, one that
led to a Stoyanovich field goal and another that was returned by
Cris Dishman 47 yards for a touchdown and a 20-13 Chiefs lead. They
grappled with the fact that Gannon then led a nifty 60-yard TD
drive to tie the game, capped by his 6-yard scramble.
</P>
<P>
   They especially grappled with what happened at 20-20: how Chiefs
quarterback Elvis Grbac threw an interception to Raiders linebacker
Greg Biekert, who returned it to the Raiders 3-yard line to set up
a Gannon-to-Ricky Dudley touchdown pass and a 27-20 lead; and how,
just four minutes later, Woodson made his first interception of the
year and returned it 15 easy yards for a score and a 34-20 lead as
the third quarter ended.
</P>
<P>
   A 34-20 lead when the fourth-quarter opened! How could the
Raiders blow that one?
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs, eerily, knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is about the Raiders,'' Grbac crowed,
``but when we play them, no matter how many points we're down, we
believe we can come back to win. Fourteen points is nothing. We had
15 minutes left.''
</P>
<P>
   Unbelievable, but true: Grbac hit tight end Tony Gonzalez on a
play-action that deked everyone and went for a 73-yard score when
Gonzalez ran away from a zone defense that bit on the run fake. It
was 34-27, Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the play of the game: With six and a half minutes left, a
waggle pass from Gannon to another ex-Chief, tight end Derrick
Walker, went for what looked like a nine-yard gain and a first down
as Walker was tackled by safety Jerome Woods.
</P>
<P>
   But wait! There went Dishman, scooping up the ball and running,
untouched, into the end zone, for a Chiefs touchdown. You could
almost hear Raider Nation gasp: What? How could it have happened?
And then the instant replay forced into play by the Raiders, who
challenged the call, showed what happened: Walker fumbled the ball
just before hitting the ground and Dishman gobbled it up for the
game-tying score.
</P>
<P>
   For Gannon, who lost the game he so badly wanted against his old
teammates, there was only truth as stark as the sight of
Stoyanovich's field goal sailing through the south side goalposts:
``We've played 11 games and we've been in every one. Unfortunately
for us, we didn't get it done again. We have to live with
ourselves, we have to live with our 5-6 record, and we have to live
with the fact that we're not considered very good by league
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
