<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4409 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BLACKHEALTH30-COX     11-29 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKHEALTH30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prevention still the wisest path to good health
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As director of a leading national women's health office, Yvonne
Green encourages women to take more responsibility for their own
health by eating more fruits and veggies and fewer chips and fries,
being physically active and getting regular check-ups for heart
disease, cancer, and osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   But Green, 46, admits she was ``the average woman'' when it came
to incorporating healthy habits into her daily life as a younger
woman. ``I didn't think much about it in my 20s,'' she said. ``Then
in my 30s, I started thinking more about it. Then in my 40s, I
actually started doing more about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, she was appointed director of Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention Office of Women's Health after
working 15 years for CDC reproductive health programs. Green is a
certified nurse midwife by trade and a gardener by hobby. She spoke
recently about preparations for the Dec. 6 SciTrek invitation-only
presentation on African-American women's health issues.
</P>
<P>
   Q: African-American women hear they are more at-risk for certain
diseases, but often hear different statistics and don't know what
to believe. What diseases do they most need to worry about?
</P>
<P>
   A: The leading cause of death for black women is the same as for
white women _ heart disease _ but African-American women are more
than 50 percent more likely to die than white women of heart
disease. Also, lung cancer is the leading cancer among black women
just as it is among white women, and breast cancer is the
second-leading cause of cancer death. In 1999, over 18,000
African-American women will be diagnosed with breast cancer and
5,600 will die from it. Stroke is the third-leading cause of death
among African-American women and diabetes the fourth-leading cause.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can women do to keep themselves out of these statistics?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``There's a saying by an African-American woman, Fannie Lou
Hamer (a civil rights worker in Mississippi), now deceased, that
many know and I use when I talk to women's groups: `I'm sick and
tired of being sick and tired.' Finally, in the last year of the
1900s, women are taking more responsibility for their health ... We
could significantly reduce mortality and morbidity of major killers
with lifestyle changes to diet, exercise, nutrition, not smoking,
reducing stress as well as with early detection and screening for
diseases. Prevention is really the key. Many leading causes of
death are preventable.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've heard about the high rate of death of black women during
pregnancy and childbirth. What are the differences between black
and white women when it comes to maternal mortality?
</P>
<P>
   A: Pregnancy complications are a big deal among African-American
women. They are three to four times more likely to die in
childbirth than white women. Little or no prenatal care can explain
some of it, but it doesn't fully explain the disproportionate risk
of death.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you do to keep healthy and in shape?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm a big gardener. I garden sometimes for hours, digging
holes, moving logs, it's a workout and great for stress. And I try
to find as many walks that are raising money for health causes and
enter them, such as breast cancer walks, AIDS walks. I did one
recently for the brain injury foundation. I'm not one to walk
around a block 100 times so this a good way to inspire me. It
accomplishes three things: I get in a good walk, I'm financially
contributing to a worthy cause, and it's usually a walk in a
neighborhood where I haven't been so I see a different part of the
city.
</P>
<P>
   AT GREATER RISK
</P>
<P>
   African-American women have extra worries when it comes to heart
disease, stroke, cancer and childbirth. That's because they are
much more likely to die of these conditions than white women.
Social factors, such as lower income, less education and less
access to medical care, are some of the reasons for the disparity
but they don't explain them all. Some of the added risks of
African-American women when compared to white women:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Heart disease: 70 percent greater risk of death.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hypertension: Twice the risk.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Diabetes: Twice the rate.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pregnancy, childbirth: Fourfold risk of dying.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Breast cancer: 20 percent higher risk of death.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stroke: 70 percent higher risk of death.Sources: Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention, National Institutes of Health,
American Heart Association; research by staff reporter Patricia
Guthrie
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
