</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4410 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MEDIA-HEALTH30-COX     11-29 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-HEALTH30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Demand for alternative medicine knows no limits
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consumers' appetite for information about alternative medicine
seems to know no limits _ and publishers are eager to feed it. Some
recently published books on the subject:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dr. Duke's Essential Herbs'' by James A. Duke, Ph.D. (Rodale
Reach, Emmaus, Pa., $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   The longtime chief of medicinal plant research at the U.S.
Department of Agriculture, Duke is one of the foremost American
experts in botanical medicine. In this follow-up to his
million-seller, ``The Green Pharmacy,'' the 70-something scientist
discusses the ``13 vital herbs'' that he most often recommends.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The People's Pharmacy Guide to Home and Herbal Remedies'' by
Joe Graedon and Teresa Graedon, Ph.D. (St. Martin's Press, New
York, $27.95).
</P>
<P>
   The husband and wife pharmacologist-anthropologist team who
wrote one of the original consumer guides to prescription drugs
apply the same formula to ``grandmother medicine'': herbal formulas
and old-wives-tale remedies. It includes an alphabetical listing of
common herbs, appropriate doses and potential interactions.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The American Pharmaceutical Association Practical Guide to
Natural Medicines'' by Andrea Peirce; introduction by Andrew T.
Weil, M.D. (William Morrow, New York, $35).
</P>
<P>
   An expensive, hefty (728 pages) and thorough encyclopedia of
plant and herbal remedies. It draws on other sources, such as the
British Herbal Compendium and the books of James Duke and Varro
Tyler, but delivers their information in accessible language under
headings such as ``Will it work for you?'' and ``Will it harm
you?''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The New Encyclopedia of Vitamins, Minerals, Supplements and
Herbs by Nicola Reavley (M. Evans and Co., New York, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   A paperback behemoth at 792 pages, this thorough reference by an
Australian nutritionist goes beyond herbal remedies to explore
therapeutic uses of minerals and other supplements. It includes
careful cautions about interactions with other drugs and negative
effects on existing medical conditions.
</P>
<P>
   _M.A.J. McKenna
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Complete Guide to Herbal Medicines,'' by Charles W.
Fetrow, Pharm.D., and Juan R. Avila, Pharm.D. (Springhouse
Publishing, Springhouse, Pa. $21.95).
</P>
<P>
   A layperson's version of an earlier book by the same authors
called ``The Professional's Handbook of Complementary and
Alternative Medicines,'' this paperback has the virtue of being
written and compiled by pharmacologists. Thus close attention is
paid to the chemical constituents of herbs and their interactions
and contraindications. References after each chapter, to specific
articles in medical and pharmacological journals, suggest that the
contributors did their homework.
</P>
<P>
   WEB SITE OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   You know why your doctor gave you the drug she just prescribed
for you. You know what's on the list of warnings that the
pharmacist presented. But reactions to drugs can differ by
individual. What can you actually expect when you start taking it?
</P>
<P>
   No one can guarantee how you'll react to a drug, but the
Internet Drug Index (www.rxlist.com/) can help. Among the features
of this long-standing site is RxBoard, a set of bulletin boards
where people trade descriptions of their experiences with the 20
drugs most frequently prescribed in the United States, as well as
some alternative medications. Among the entries: arguments over
whether Prozac causes weight gain, testimonials to the new
painkiller Celebrex and a report of fever and headache after taking
ginkgo biloba.
</P>
<P>
   The site was originally created as a public service by
pharmacist Neil Sandow. Recently it began being hosted by
HealthCentral, a medical-themed Internet portal that, like many
medical gateways these days, includes a link to an online pharmacy.
As with all sites on the Net, exercise caution and judgment.
</P>
<P>
   _M.A.J. McKenna
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
