<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4419 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-29 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS NEED TO TAKE A BREAK FROM CYNICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By Stephanie Salter   
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Irony has only emergency use. Carried over time, it's the
voice of the trapped who have come to enjoy their cage.'' - poet
Lewis Hyde
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When Paul Loeb was researching his latest book,
``Soul of a Citizen,'' he came upon an ad for Microsoft's online
magazine that seemed to epitomize what people of conscience are up
against these days.
</P>
<P>
   Touting Slate as a forum for ``what everyone is talking about,''
the ad promised that the magazine would deliver information ``with
a certain insouciant smirk that thinking people find compelling.''
</P>
<P>
   What, asks Loeb, is so attractive about a smirk - insouciant,
certain or otherwise?
</P>
<P>
   ``People smirk when they're full of themselves, smiling
arrogantly...'' he writes. ``All of us, the ad suggests, should
approach life with such hip detachment... We simply need to
acknowledge that the world is inherently corrupt, bought and paid
for, and that all talk of changing is naive.''
</P>
<P>
   This ``culture of contempt,'' says Loeb, has been embraced by
much of the news, ad and entertainment media; it contributes
mightily to despair and a social paralysis that threaten our moral
core.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did so many of us become convinced that we can do nothing
to affect our common future?'' he asks. ``And how have some other
Americans managed to remove the cataracts from their vision and
work powerfully for change?''
</P>
<P>
   Subtitled ``Living with conviction in a cynical time,'' Loeb's
book is like a 362-page pep rally for the soul. It should be
mandatory reading for anyone over the age of 12 - especially every
woman or man who has traded ``I give a damn'' for ``I give up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Soul of a Citizen'' is packed with wise thoughts from an
eclectic array of philosophers and social activists - Rainer Maria
Rilke to Marian Wright Edelman. It also offers real-life examples
of ordinary people who made extraordinary things happen.
</P>
<P>
   Most are like Virginia Ramirez, a San Antonio wife and mother of
five, who went from making cookies and punch for her kids' PTA
meetings to testifying before the U.S. Senate about an innovative
job-training program she and other neighborhood activists created.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like civil rights activist Rosa Parks, are well known
now. But they weren't when they took their first step (and the
first thousandth) on the path of change.
</P>
<P>
   ``What always gets lost in the telling of the Rosa Parks story -
one day she refused to give up her seat to a white person and move
to the back of the bus - is all the commitment and hard work she
put in before that day,'' said Loeb by phone from his Seattle home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her decision didn't come out of nowhere. She'd spent 12 years
before that, helping to lead her local NAACP and learning about
labor and civil rights activism. To ignore that is to demean her
accomplishments and those of the people who came before her in the
struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   An associated scholar at Seattle's Center for Ethical
Leadership, Loeb is the author of three previous books, a
commentator for print and electronic news media and a lecturer at
more than 200 colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried not to candy-coat things in this book. Social
activism is frustrating and not always easy,'' he said. ``But I
honestly believe it's a richer way to live, even if it's hard.
People say, 'I just don't have time,' but we spend plenty of time
and work hard for lots of trivial, unsatisfying things. Isn't it
better to work for something that's worthwhile? To be glad we
aspire to make things better instead of being ashamed that we
try?''
</P>
<P>
   In some 30 years of researching citizen responsibility, Loeb
says he has observed countless people ``getting stuck'' in social
and moral circumstances they despise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stay trapped, but not because they don't care,'' he said.
``It's because they believe that nothing they do will help. The
landscape they see is pretty bleak; the voices of doubt and 'why
bother?' are powerful. So they retreat. But by retreating we don't
escape from the world's problems so much as submit to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as one activist in his book puts it: ``There's a process of
dying that happens when you shut yourself off to the inequalities
and injustices in front of you.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most effective ways to break out of the torpor is to
follow the advice of a 101-year-old activist friend of Loeb's named
Hazel Wolf: ``Get out of yourself and focus on what needs to be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   As Loeb writes in ``Soul of a Citizen'':
</P>
<P>
   ``We liberate ourselves from cynicism by replacing the
all-knowing but soul-destroying smirk with compassionate curiosity
about our fellow human beings. When we do so, we find ample reason
for hope.''
</P>
<P>
   And when we hope, we find the time and energy to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``All around us, every day, are people who do act,'' said Loeb.
``They had to overcome the doubts and recognize, 'If not me, then
who?' And, at some point they all had to give themselves permission
to not know everything. We don't have to have all the answers. We
just have to get out there and engage with our fellow human beings.
It's a great antidote to despair.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
