<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4421 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-2     11-29 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS BEGIN TO ENCOUNTER HEAVY RESISTANCE FROM CHECHENN
MILITANTS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo (NYT23) is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After two months of steady advances into Chechnya's
heartland, the Russian military said on Monday that it is beginning
to encounter serious resistance from Islamic militants, and that
the fighting is likely to intensify in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The resistance is growing day by day,'' Col. Gen. Georgy
Shpak, the commander of Russia's airborne troops, said in an
interview on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After retreating from the Russian onslaught, Russian officials
said, Islamic fighters are fortifying their positions in the
Chechen capital of Grozny and the towns of Urus-Martan, Shali and
Argun.
</P>
<P>
   And Salman Raduyev, the warlord who led a daring hostage-taking
raid into Russia during the last Chechen war, is commanding a band
of militants in Novogroznensky, a settlement in eastern Chechnya,
according to Russian military officials.
</P>
<P>
   An indication of the battles that may lie ahead came on Monday
when the Russian government belatedly acknowledged a firefight on
Nov. 17 that decimated a Russian reconnaissance patrol.
</P>
<P>
   A macabre video of the corpse-laden battlefield was supplied by
Islamic militants to Russian television networks, which broadcast
much of it during their prime-time news programs on Monday night.
And Russia's generals seemed to be trying to prepare the nation for
some tough clashes ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They realize that there will be no peace negotiations, and
that we are determined to complete this operation,'' Shpak said of
the militants. ``So they are trying to generate huge losses on our
side to get us to change our mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The first phases of the offensive have gone very well from the
Russian military's point of view. After a ferocious air
bombardment, Russian troops began by seizing the plains north of
the Terek River, good terrain for armored vehicles and a region
with a largely pro-Russia population.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the Russian forces were on the southern bank of the river
as well. Moving eastward from Ingushetia and westward from
Dagestan, Russian forces also advanced into Chechnya's lowlands,
making their way toward Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   There have been vocal protests from Western governments about
the risk to civilians. But the Russian military's casualties have
been low _ at least compared with the last war. As of Friday, 305
Russian soldiers and Interior Ministry troops were reported by the
government to have been killed since the Islamic rebels ignited the
war in August by invading neighboring Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officers say there are several reasons for their gains.
Instead of charging into Chechnya's cities and engaging in
casualty-inducing urban warfare, they have laid siege to the cities
and demanded that local elders evict the rebels and let in the
Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of being pummeled into submission by Russian bombs and
artillery, local leaders in Gudermes, Chechnya's second largest
city, and the town of Achkhoi-Marten, complied.
</P>
<P>
   To keep up morale among the troops, the Russian government has
promised to pay its soldiers in Chechnya a hefty bonus that could
bring their monthly pay to as high as $1,000. Income of that level
would amount to a substantial sum in Russia's depressed economy.
The military has also sought to use volunteers and experienced
soldiers, though with some 100,000 soldiers in the field it has
also been relying on relatively green conscripts with as little as
six months military service.
</P>
<P>
   But the militants have not given up the fight. Russian generals
estimate that the rebel force numbers some 15,000 and say there are
an equal number of Chechen sympathizers also fighting. And the
winter weather will make it harder for Russian air power to target
its enemy.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Their resistance is on the rise,'' Shpak said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, much of the fighting is concentrated around Grozny,
which Russian forces are bombarding with aircraft and artillery.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai P. Koshman, the Russian government's representative to
Chechnya, said on Monday that the militants are hoping to lure
Russian soldiers into the city so that they could turn it into a
killing field, complete with minefields and vats of burning oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to turn it into the Last Day of Pompeii for our
assault troops,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military seems determined to keep its distance for
now and rely on its long-range firepower. Some 45,000 to 50,000
civilians, however, remain in Grozny, according to Koshman and
their plight is worsening by the day.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military has sought to arrange an escape route to
the north, but many of the civilians are sick, infirm and wounded.
And Koshman charged that the rebels were preventing some civilians
from leaving so that they could use them as human shields.
</P>
<P>
   As Moscow tried to blame the rebels for the civilians'
predicament, it rebuffed an request by the chairman of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe to visit
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians promised at the summit meeting in Istanbul this
month that they would allow a visit to the region by the Norwegian
foreign minister, Kurt Vollebaek, who is chairman of the OSCE. But
after meeting with Russia's foreign minister in Moscow on Monday,
Vollebaek said no visit has been arranged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not be honest if I said I was wholly satisfied or that
I had achieved the results I came for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another battleground lies to the south and east of Grozny. And
the newly disclosed firefight in southeastern Chechnya gives a
sense of some of the resistance the Russians may face _ especially
if they fulfill their vow to chase the rebels into the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The episode occurred on Nov. 17 when a 14-man patrol left
Botlikh in Dagestan and crossed into Chechnya. After spying a
convoy of rebel trucks near the town of Kharachoi, the patrol
opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   The patrol reported the fighting, but its radio went dead after
an hour of shooting. Shpak's men dispatched reinforcements, but the
ground troops could not make it through the heavy snow and Russian
helicopters turned away after being fired at.
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic fighters were more successful. More than a 100 of
their reinforcements arrived in Kamaz trucks, according to Shpak.
</P>
<P>
   Russians officials said that 12 of the patrol were killed and
two captured.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians claim that more than 50 rebels were killed in the
Kharachoi clash, but it is difficult to confirm that since the
fighters took their dead with them. To get its dead back, the
Russian military is now negotiating to exchange bodies with the
militants, on the basis of two Chechens for one Russian.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
