<SLUG> BC-TRADE-MYANMAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT TO REVIEW MASS. LAW BANNING TRADE WITH MYANMAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a move that could have far-reaching implications for
states that seek to punish human rights abuses abroad, the U.S.
Supreme Court agreed Monday to review the Massachusetts law that
restricts state purchases from companies doing business in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision to rule on the constitutionality of the
1996 law comes a year after U.S. District Court Judge Joseph Tauro
in Boston struck down the statute on the grounds it interfered with
the federal government's sole authority over foreign policy. An
appeals court upheld Tauro's decision last June.
</P>
<P>
   At stake are the efforts by states and local governments to take
stands on controversial international human rights issues with
sanctions against companies that do business with repressive
regimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big deal,'' said state Representative Byron Rushing,
the Democrat from the South End, who guided the bill through the
Legislature. He noted the very strong odds that petitioners
normally face in asking the Supreme Court to review a case.
</P>
<P>
   The law was passed in response to widespread human rights
violations by the military regime in Myanmar -- formerly known as
Burma. In effect, it prohibited the state from buying goods and
services from companies that conduct business with Myanmar, unless
the firm submitted a bid 10 percent lower than all other bids.
</P>
<P>
   The law immediately set off a storm of protest from America's
trading partners, including Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Rushing, noting that the court review comes at a time of
mounting tensions in Myanmar, said the court is obviously intrigued
by the constitutional issues. Over 30 other jurisdictions have
adopted similar so-called restrictive purchasing laws, most of them
targeting Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Supreme Court decides will make clear whether
American citizens who are concerned with human rights violation
will have an ally with local governments,'' Rushing said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Thomas Reilly, whose office will prepare the
appeal, said he expects a decision by June and feels Massachusetts
has a strong case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legislature spoke very clearly, saying it doesn't want the
state to be doing business with his regime,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Other states have filed friend-of-the-court briefs in support of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, led by the National Foreign Trade Council, a group
that represents U.S. businesses that operate overseas, said they
welcome a Supreme Court ruling because it will clarify what has
become a confusing legal landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Kittredge, the president of the business council, said 30
of his members do some business with Myanmar and have landed on
Massachusetts' restrictive purchasing list as a result.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a longstanding issue that affects many of our
important trading relations and we believe a Supreme Court ruling
is the best way to get an authoritative national decision,''
Kittredge said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce also opposes the Massachusetts law.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the White House, under heavy pressure from
European leaders, sent its trade officials to Beacon Hill to try to
persuade Rushing and other lawmakes to repeal or amend the law.
They were rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   While the Massachusetts law is on hold in the First Circuit,
which includes New England, similar Burma sanctions still stand in
other jurisdictions, such as in New York City and Los Angeles,
which both have passed similar selective purchasing Burma laws.
Massachusetts is the only state to have passed a Burma law.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Stumberg, a professor at Georgetown University Law
Center, said he feels Massachusetts has a good chance of convincing
the high court to overturn the lower court rulings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case that can defend state powers but also promote
human rights,'' Stumberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The use of selective purchasing sanctions began in the 1980s to
force the racist apartheid South African regime to turn over the
country to pro-democracy forces. The effort was credited with
creating strong economic pressure on the government to negotiate
with the African National Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Other jurisdictions have imposed sanctions against such regimes
as in Nigeria, Indonesia, Cuba, and China. Some forbid pension
funds from investing in corporations in Northern Ireland that
discriminates on the basis of religion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 2030EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4424 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TRADE-MYANMAR-BOS &LR;      11-29 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-MYANMAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT TO REVIEW MASS. LAW BANNING TRADE WITH MYANMAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a move that could have far-reaching implications for
states that seek to punish human rights abuses abroad, the U.S.
Supreme Court agreed Monday to review the Massachusetts law that
restricts state purchases from companies doing business in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision to rule on the constitutionality of the
1996 law comes a year after U.S. District Court Judge Joseph Tauro
in Boston struck down the statute on the grounds it interfered with
the federal government's sole authority over foreign policy. An
appeals court upheld Tauro's decision last June.
</P>
