<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4429 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TRADE-SUMMIT-BOS &LR;      11-29 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS DOMINATE ON EVE OF WORLD TRADE MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a, i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE -- So far, the protesters have unfurled banners from
rooftops and taken over an abandoned building. They have marched
through the downtown area, gray-haired grandmothers alongside
college students with pierced eyebrows, scientists in suits beside
demonstrators dressed as sea turtles. Together they have built
giant puppets and packed classes in non-violent protest tactics.
They've braced themselves for arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Representing scores of countries and hundreds of organizations,
they have descended on Seattle by the thousands to oppose the World
Trade Organization, the international body that they accuse of
favoring trade expansion over all else. With its powers to decide
issues affecting the globe, the Geneva-based WTO has spurred union,
environmental and human rights activists to band together in one of
the largest protest efforts in recent history -- and the first ever
for many of the younger demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was involved in protesting the Vietnam War and this is way
bigger because it affects the entire world,'' said Dennis Jennings,
46, an Alameda, Calif., firefighter who paid his own way to Seattle
to join the protest. ``The decisions they make affect every aspect
of our lives. It's a way of controlling us, our food supply, you
name it, through transnational corporations.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the latest round of talks, which open Tuesday, are not
expected to end in anything more than an agreement for the 135
member nations to keep talking, past rulings have convinced
activists from around the world that the WTO is indifferent to
their concerns. And those rulings, they complain, are made by
unelected ministers who answer to no one but themselves. The entire
process, they say, is not only dangerous but undemocratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're basically like a New World Order, and that scares
me,'' said Michael McKinnon, 20, a first-time protester who
delivers pizza for a living in Eugene, Ore. ``It's not thinking
about human beings or the environment. It's all about how
corporations can make more money.''
</P>
<P>
   The assembled Groups range from the unknown to the securely
established _ the Raging Grannies and the Sierra Club, respectively
_ and from the radical left to conservatives like Patrick Buchanan,
who also reviles the WTO. They see the ministerial meeting as a way
to get word out about an organization that many people are unaware
of and relatively few can define. To that end, Seattle has been
turned into a massive stage for street theater intended to
counterbalance the panel discussions, and concerts also taking
place around the city.
</P>
<P>
   Monday alone, a coalition of groups that included the Humane
Society sent more than 2,000 marchers into downtown, many of them
banging drums, all of them chanting anti-WTO slogans. A block over,
a smaller group led by demonstrators from Korea held a march of its
own, this one featuring a building-sized Satan puppet to represent
the trade group. After holding a mock trial, a group calling itself
the Global People's Tribunal issued a citizens arrest warrant for
the trade ministers from the seven leading industrialized countries
and marched over to the convention center to deliver them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The broad message we're trying to send is: review and
repair,'' said Mary Botarri, an official with the non-profit
organization Public Citizen, based in Washington, D.C. ``Before we
do any launching of new talks, we need to take a hard look at the
WTO's record.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Andrea Durbin, an official with Friends of the Earth,
``We're not at all opposed to the idea of the WTO. Our concern is
that the trade rules right now are so strongly biased against the
environment. The rules themselves flatly need to be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, member nations have taken 167 trade disputes to the WTO
since it was created in 1995 as a formal judicial body, replacing
the General Agreements on Tariffs and Trade. GATT, as its
predecessor was known, had heard 300 disputes in its entire 47-year
history.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with tariffs mostly cut, the WTO has been grappling with
more complicated issues, such as whether a nation can set tough
food-safety, child-labor or environmental laws that might bar
imports from a nation with lower standards. The debate is not
abstract. The United States has already been forced to defend its
laws before the WTO, and sometimes it has lost.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the cases that galvanized environmental and animal
activists, in 1991, Mexico won a ruling from the WTO's predecessor
challenging a US ban on tuna imports from producers who killed too
many dolphins. Then three years ago, the WTO ruled against a US law
that required gasoline to meet cleanliness standards. At the same
time, US farmers complain that other nations use health concerns to
bar or limit US imports of hormone-fed beef and other foods.
</P>
<P>
   On a more local level, Robert Stumberg, a Georgetown University
law professor, said the WTO could trample empowerment zones,
``buy-American'' programs and other laws that favor the United
States over others.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``You should care because the Seattle negotiations
could change the rules of democracy, and you would see the
difference in terms of the capacity of your state or local
government to pass laws that affect how your tax dollars are spent
on purchasing, or how your state can pass laws to promote economic
development, or your state's authority to protect the environment
or manage it's own resources.''
</P>
<P>
   To show his support for the WTO, President Clinton is expected
to be in town. A rumor that may be little more than wishful
thinking has it that Fidel Castro will arrive later in the week to
voice his opposition. With the help of a Bay Area group called the
Ruckus Society, which held two camps specifically to train
protesters for the WTO meeting, the activists say they are ready
for anything, including arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Leone Reinbold, a 22-year-old spokeswoman for protest umbrella
group Direct Action Network, said police should expect low-tech
blockades (people) and lock downs (people chaining themselves to
eachother or objects). The goal, she said, is to shut down the WTO
-- and the hundreds of mostly young people sitting on the floor of
the network's headquarters, eating macrobiotic food and learning
how to resist arrest peacefully, sounded prepared to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole effort just shows that things can be run by the
community and now how they are run now; this all took place from
the bottom up,'' said Melanie Grubman, 20, who flew in from
Connecticut, where she attends Wesleyan University and is active in
grassroots organizing. ``I couldn't miss everything that's
happening. This is right on stuff and it could change our future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
