<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL NOTEBOOK: Cowher names Tomczak as QB for next game
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With five games left this season and his team fading from the
playoff race, Pittsburgh Steelers coach Bill Cowher is facing
increasing pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh (5-6) has lost six of its past seven games at home
and is three victories behind Buffalo in the AFC wild-card race.
After losing to the expansion Cleveland Browns in Three Rivers
Stadium earlier this season, the Steelers lost to the lowly Bengals
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me just say this: I think we have more talent than
Cleveland and Cincinnati,'' said Tom Donahoe, the team's director
of football operations.
</P>
<P>
   Cowher benched struggling quarterback Kordell Stewart in the
second quarter of last weekend's game, replacing him with
journeyman Mike Tomczak. Tomczak, who becomes a free agent next
year, completed 19 of 35 attempts for 264 yards, almost rallying
the Steelers from a 21-point deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Cowher said Tomczak will start Thursday's game at Jacksonville.
Stewart will return to his ``Slash'' role of wide receiver and
part-time quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Tomczak might be Pittsburgh's quarterback now, but Stewart's
days under center probably aren't over. He was given a $27 million
contract extension in the offseason, including an $8 million
signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at this from a team standpoint,'' Cowher said.
``That's the most important thing to look at. I'm not getting
involved with how much a guy makes or what a guy doesn't make. When
you start getting involved with that stuff, it's not coaching. It's
managing. I want to coach players.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowher also is denying a published report in the Pittsburgh
Post-Gazette, which detailed three media reports that had him
looking to
</P>
<P>
   leave the Steelers. The reports said Cowher was considering a
job as a television analyst with Monday Night Football, or coaching
the new Houston franchise, which will begin play in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Cowher has three years left on his contract with the Steelers at
$2 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   King's opportunity
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay quarterback Trent Dilfer will be sidelined 4-6 weeks
with a broken right collarbone. Backup Eric Zeier, the former
Georgia star, still hasn't recovered from a rib injury, so rookie
Shaun King will start against Minnesota on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Dilfer, who played well in four games after being benched a
month ago, was hurt when he was sacked by Phillip Daniels in the
third quarter of a 16-3 victory over the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   King, the team's second-round pick from Tulane, completed three
of seven passes for 32 yards, including his first touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   With only five games remaining, Dilfer could miss the rest of
this season. If King or Zeier plays well, the team might not extend
Dilfer's contract after this season. The Bucs also must decide
whether to bring Dilfer back if they're still in the playoff
race.Dishing it out
</P>
<P>
   After Raiders receiver Tim Brown beat Kansas City cornerback
Cris Dishman on a 31-yard pass Sunday, Chiefs coach Gunther
Cunningham told his assistants he was going to bench Dishman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked, `Do we go with (backup Eric) Warfield right now?'''
Cunningham said. ``I asked (secondary coach) Ron Zook, `Do you
think Dishman's going to get it done?' and he said, `Absolutely.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dishman responded with the two biggest defensive plays of the
Chiefs' 37-34 victory over the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   He intercepted Rich Gannon's pass in the third quarter and
returned it 47 yards for a touchdown, giving the Chiefs a 20-13
lead. In the fourth quarter, Dishman recovered Derrick Walker's
fumble and returned it 40 yards for a touchdown to tie the score
34-34.
</P>
<P>
   A second chance
</P>
<P>
   It was a rough weekend for Washington's Brett Conway, the former
all-state kicker from Parkview High.
</P>
<P>
   Conway missed a 28-yard field goal on the final play of
regulation, forcing the Redskins into overtime against the
Philadelphia Eagles. But Washington won the coin toss and drove to
his 27-yard field goal for a 20-17 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a kick I'm going to make 999 times out of 1,000,''
Conway said. ``I can't explain how I missed it. If I hadn't had
that week last week, we'd be laughing about that 28-yarder. Now,
I'm worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Conway, who also missed a 43-yarder against the Eagles, is 17 of
25 this season. He missed three of six attempts against the New
York Giants the previous game. Five of his eight misses have been
from 50 yards or beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Conway was booed by the home crowd when he walked out to kick
the game-winner against the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of them are drunk and don't know what they're talking
about anyway,'' he said. ```And to add to that, if I had been part
of that crowd, I would have booed, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Aiming for Bears' mark
</P>
<P>
   Surrendering 23 points for the second consecutive week hurt the
Jaguars' chances of breaking the NFL record for fewest points
allowed in a season. Having given up 125 points in 11 games, an
11.36 average, the Jaguars still are ahead of the pace of the 1985
Chicago Bears record of 187 points in a season. The Bears held
opponents to an average of 11.7 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
