<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES REJECT DOCTORAL CANDIDATE'S CLAIM OF BIAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: optional ending included) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday dealt a blow to a white
Texas doctoral candidate who claimed the University of Texas at
Austin rejected him for admission because of his race.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, in an unsigned opinion, rejected the bulk of
Francois Lesage's argument that the school violated his
constitutional and federal statutory rights by maintaining an
admissions policy that favored minority applicants.
</P>
<P>
   The high court returned to the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
only Lesage's claim that the university continues to operate a
discriminatory admissions process, an argument the state rejects on
behalf of its school.
</P>
<P>
   In their ruling, the justices overturned a 5th Circuit decision
in favor of Lesage's claim that he was a victim of illegal reverse
discrimination. A federal district court had earlier dismissed
Lesage's lawsuit, saying he was rejected because he was an inferior
candidate, not because he is white.
</P>
<P>
   Texas urged the high court to reverse the 5th Circuit, saying
the university would have rejected Lesage's application even
without a race-conscious admissions policy, which the school has
since abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, agreeing with Texas, declined to address Lesage's
claim that his rights had been violated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply put, where a plaintiff challenges a governmental
decision as being based on an impermissible criterion (such as
race) and it is undisputed that the government would have made the
same decision regardless, there is no cognizable injury warranting
relief'' under federal law, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   The high court noted that the school accepted only about 20 of
the 223 candidates who applied to its doctorate counseling
psychology program for the 1996-97 academic year. At least 80
applicants had higher undergraduate grade-point averages than
Lesage's, the justices said.
</P>
<P>
   Lesage's case is reminiscent of the lawsuit Cheryl Hopwood
brought in 1992 against the University of Texas law school,
alleging that the institution rejected her because she is white.
The 5th Circuit agreed with Hopwood, saying the university's policy
of favoring minority candidates violated the constitutional right
to equal protection.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, without comment, let that decision stand in
1996. In response to the court action, Texas universities stopped
consideration of race as a factor in admissions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In other action Monday:
</P>
<P>
   _ The justices, without comment, cleared the way for two
Victoria High School teachers to sue the Victoria Independent
School District board in Texas for allegedly violating their First
Amendment right to free speech. Teachers Dwight Harris and Gene
Martin were reprimanded and transferred to other schools after
publicly calling for the principal to be replaced and warning that
faculty members would revolt if action wasn't taken.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge dismissed the teachers' lawsuit, saying they
were employees and not entitled to criticize their boss. But the
5th Circuit reversed, saying Harris and Martin's statements were
constitutionally protected comments on a ``matter of public
concern.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Delving into the issue of hate crimes, the high court agreed
to decide whether judges, rather than juries, can decide whether an
attack was motivated by prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Apprendi Jr., who is white, pleaded guilty to a firearm
violation and bomb possession in connection with shots fired into
the home of a black family in Vineland, N.J., in 1994. The crimes
carry a maximum 10-year prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge, acting at prosecutors' request, sentenced
Apprendi to the enhanced 12-year prison sentence available under
the state's hate-crimes law.
</P>
<P>
   Apprendi, who is appealing his sentence, argues before the high
court that a jury, not a judge, must decide whether a crime was
racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
   _ The justices agreed to decide whether states and local
governments can restrict their purchases from companies that do
business in foreign countries with poor human-rights records. The
1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals struck down a Massachusetts law
that limited foreign purchases, ruling that it interfered with the
federal government's authority to conduct foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state law, Massachusetts could not buy products from
companies doing business with Myanmar _ formerly called Burma _
unless the company's bid was 10 percent lower than anyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
