<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVO-COACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION TURN TO CLAVIJO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution have yet to establish a
viable on-field identity after four Major League Soccer seasons.
But the naming of head coach Fernando Clavijo Monday gives an
indication of the team's intended direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``From Day 1 of the league, we have made a commitment to
entertaining and attacking soccer,'' said Sunil Gulati, managing
director of Kraft Soccer Properties. ``We will make every effort to
make this team successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo and Gulati will have some difficult decisions to make
before training camp begins in January. They want to build the team
through the middle _ goalkeeper, central defense, central midfield,
and striker. But they appear to be counting on only two current
Revolution players in those positions _ Leonel Alvarez and Dan
Calichman.
</P>
<P>
   So significant changes should be expected, starting with the
addition of a proven midfield choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player I always appreciated an up-front and honest
coach,'' Clavijo said. ``I don't mean someone who is always nice,
but who speaks to my face without bending the truth. Players might
not accept it right away but in the end they realize it is better
this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of work ahead of us. We have to look to the long
term and where we want to go with long-range goals. But it is
crucial we start to win right away, and this team is not too far
away from being able to do that. We need players who are committed,
who are willing to sacrifice for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Three previous Revolution head coaches have made similar
statements. But the Revolution have failed miserably on the field,
winning a total of only 12 games in regulation time with a playoff
berth at stake in the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo and Gulati shouldn't be expected to make the Revolution
title contenders immediately. This will be Clavijo's first attempt
as head coach of an outdoor team. But Clavijo has had success
coaching professional indoor teams, and he performed at a high
standard for the US national team, retiring as a player after the
1994 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo has potential advantages over previous Revolution
coaches. Clavijo, 42, is the oldest and, theoretically, most mature
coach the team has had. He is also a contemporary of many of the US
players, though his life experience is different from most.
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo retired from soccer after playing for Atenas in Uruguay
and moved with his wife, Martha, to Elizabeth, N.J., where he found
a job cleaning floors in a factory in 1979. But there was a lively
semi-professional soccer scene in the New York area, and Clavijo
was soon recruited by a wealthy restaurateur/team owner.
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo then carved out a successful career with the Golden Bay
Earthquakes of the North American Soccer League and prominent
indoor teams such as the New York Arrows and San Diego Sockers.
Clavijo earned US citizenship in 1987, and Bora Milutinovic brought
him into the national team program at age 34. Remarkably, Clavijo
then played 61 times for the US national team, retiring after a 1-0
loss to Brazil in a second-round match of the 1994 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Though Clavijo kept a relatively low profile with the national
team, he was one of its most effective players. He then began
coaching indoor teams, and last year was an assistant to
Milutinovic with the MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do whatever it takes,'' Clavijo said. ``This is my
reputation, my life, on the line. We can be a contender for the MLS
Cup. And if we get the players we want, we can be a good contender
for MLS Cup 2000. Why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make sure everyone believes in what we are working
for. Winning is a habit. We might have to change some attitudes.
You can be a winner or a loser but what we have to do is
concentrate on winning and we will be all right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
