</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CLUB-DISCRIM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLF CLUB FACES STEEP PENALTIES IN SEX BIAS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARCIA CHAMBERS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Massachusetts attorney general's office has asked a state
judge to appoint a monitor to take over a private country club,
after a jury in Boston found that the club had systematically
discriminated against a group of female golfers and awarded them
$1.9 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   The takeover, if approved, would mark the first time that a
court has taken direct control of a private country club because it
had discriminated against women. Court-appointed monitors are a
familiar remedy in many other types of legal cases, ranging from
court-ordered school desegregation to union locals accused of
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit against the Haverhill Golf and Country Club was
brought by nine women, nearly all of them spouses of members, who
accused the club of sex discrimination for denying them full
membership and equal access to the golf course. At Haverhill, which
is 30 miles north of Boston, only male club members were permitted
to tee off at prime times, like weekend mornings, a common practice
at many country clubs.
</P>
<P>
   After a monthlong trial in State Superior Court in Boston, a
jury decided unanimously late last month that the club had unfairly
manipulated waiting lists and denied the women primary memberships
with full access to the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   The jury also found that the plaintiffs were correct on a
crucial legal point _ that Haverhill, although a private club, had
conducted its membership and business practices in ways that
qualified it as a public accommodation and thus made it subject to
state antidiscrimination laws. As a result, the jury was entitled
to impose sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   In the annals of country club discrimination cases, the
$1.9million jury award for compensatory and punitive damages is a
landmark both in its size and its message. And it may get worse for
the club's members if Judge John C. Cratsley, who presided over the
trial, also accepts a pending consumer protection claim that, under
Massachusetts law, would let him triple the award.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Rodriguez, a deputy state attorney general who helped
try the Haverhill case, said the verdict had set a significant
precedent. ``Country clubs are on notice now that they will be
accountable for their policies and practices under civil rights
laws,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some golf officials agreed that the decision would affect
country clubs as they consider questions of equal access.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the impact is going to be felt not only by clubs in
this state, but also nationally,'' said Thomas E. Landry, executive
director of the Massachusetts Golf Association. ``If clubs haven't
been reviewing their bylaws and membership policies and privileges,
the size of this award will certainly put them on notice.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely, though, that the case will set precedents in
cases that involve allegations of racial discrimination in
admissions to country clubs. When a club admits a man, whatever his
race, color or national origin, he usually receives full membership
rights, including full access to the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   But clubs sometimes grant only limited memberships to women who
apply for full memberships. These women then receive limited access
to the golf course and many other club facilities. It is this
practice that the jury found illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, private clubs in the United States are being held
to be public accommodations and therefore subject to
antidiscrimination laws. Typically, a private club may be defined
as a public accommodation if it advertises its facilities for
rental by outsiders, is less rigorous than other clubs in its
selection criteria for membership or leases itself out for business
and other purposes to nonmembers.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months alone, a number of private country clubs
have found themselves before state human rights commissions accused
of sex discrimination. In New York, an administrative law judge for
the State Division of Human Rights is currently hearing a
10-year-old case that pits Nancy Saunders, a commercial real estate
agent in Greenwich, Conn., against the Westchester Country Club in
Harrison, N.Y. Saunders says she lost her own membership in the
club because she married a member.
</P>
<P>
   The Meadowlands Golf and Country Club in Blue Bell, Pa.,
recently acknowledged as part of a settlement that it was a public
accommodation. And last week in Ohio, the State Human Rights
Division held that the Tippecanoe Golf and Country Club in
Canfield, Ohio, was a public accommodation and therefore subject to
the state's antidiscrimination laws.
</P>
<P>
   In the Haverhill case, the nine women filed suit in 1995, and
the Massachusetts attorney general's office joined the lawsuit the
following year on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial Marsha Vs. Kazarosian, the plaintiffs' lawyer,
presented evidence that the country club's top officials had
manipulated waiting lists or destroyed them altogether so that only
a few women achieved full membership. One woman, Nancy Peterson, a
member who was called to testify by the club to show that it had
not discriminated, learned under cross-examination that men who had
applied after she had were admitted before she was.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, the deputy state attorney general, asked the judge 10
days ago to appoint a monitor to run the Haverhill Golf and Country
Club. He also asked the judge to permanently ban the club from
manipulating the waiting list ``to the detriment of women
applicants.'' He also asked that the club be barred from offering
junior membership to boys and not to girls.
</P>
<P>
   To make the club fully accountable, Rodriguez contended that an
independent monitor should be appointed to oversee the club's daily
operations and decision making for five years. If Cratsley agrees,
the monitor would oversee club policy, rewrite the club's bylaws
and investigate any complaints involving sex discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Under the request, the Haverhill club would be required to elect
a new board by next April. All current and former board members
would be ineligible to run for the board for six years. All board
members, heads of the major committees and club employees would
have to undergo sensitivity training for the next six years. The
training would address sex discrimination under state and federal
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the golf season winds down in the East, the country club
world is abuzz about the jury's decision. At Haverhill the club's
members, who are called bondholders, have called a series of
meetings to discuss their strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The club's lawyer, Henry Owens 3rd, said the club disagreed with
the jury's verdict and would appeal. He contended that the club's
bylaws were neutral with respect to sex and that the women who
filed suit simply did not want to pay new initiation fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt about it, the plaintiffs won the first half,'' Owens
said. ``We are confident we will prevail in the second half. This
is a very complicated case.''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the verdict, the plaintiffs have been
shunned; club members refuse to talk to them or play golf with them
or their spouses, they say.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
