<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATTERSON THRIVING AS SONICS' BOOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Ruben Patterson has burst onto the Seattle scene as a
high-flying scorer and rebounder. But as a Los Angeles Lakers
rookie last season, he left teammates with a different kind of
impression.
</P>
<P>
   Painful, lasting impressions. Bruises. Scrapes. Cuts.
</P>
<P>
   He was quickly dubbed ``Wild Thang II'' by teammates for his
reckless hustle and the bodily damage he did in training camp. No
one left unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   But in Seattle, Patterson's called ``Sky Pilot.'' In 14 games,
all as the starting small forward, he's averaged 14.6 points and
7.1 rebounds a game. All from a player considered a defensive
specialist by the Lakers, who let him leave as a free agent this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Patterson's emergence is surprising no one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when he was here I was very very impressed with him,''
said executive vice president Jerry West, who drafted Patterson in
the second round in 1998. ``I thought he had the ability to be a
player in the league, and under the right circumstances will be a
real fine player.''
</P>
<P>
   The right circumstances didn't exist in L.A. Patterson was
blocked at small forward by Glen Rice and Rick Fox. He started the
season third at shooting guard, behind Eddie Jones and Kobe Bryant,
but even after Jones was traded, Patterson rarely got off the
bench. He played in 24 of 50 games, averaging 2.7 points in 6.0
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Lakers drafted another swingman, Devean George, whom
new coach Phil Jackson viewed as a better fit in the triangle
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very tough for him to be in our kind of offense,''
Jackson said of Patterson. Because of the emphasis on passing and
moving? ``Shooting,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not surprised Patterson is thriving on a running,
gunning unit paced by Gary Payton, Brent Barry and Horace Grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He runs well, scrums the ball out, good offensive rebounder,
got a lot of hustle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He's got a lot of mouth, too. Upon signing a three-year deal
with the Sonics in August, Patterson promptly proclaimed himself
the ``Kobe Bryant stopper.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I dominated Kobe, and everybody knew it,'' Patterson said.
``They called me the Kobe stopper (in practice). He hated when I
guarded him _ all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Lakers guard Derek Fisher chuckled at those comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We read some of that stuff. I was at practice every day, and
for the most part you guys (reporters) were here from time to time,
so you don't even really have to think about what he's saying,
really,'' Fisher said. ``It's good that he has that type of
confidence, but there's no one guy in this league that can stop
Kobe.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson will have to wait to test that theory _ Bryant's out
at least another week while rehabbing a broken right hand.
</P>
<P>
   As for Patterson's sudden burst from obscurity to front-line
player, Fisher is not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing what he does best, and that's go out and play hard
and make hustle plays and things like that,'' he said. ``Seattle is
a basketball team that plays with reckless abandon, sometimes on
offense but definitely on defense, and Ruben has made the best of
that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Guard Brian Shaw (sprained ankle) returned to
practice Monday and is expected to play tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Tyronn Lue also practiced but Jackson said he's not ready
to be activated from the injured list.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is scheduled to have his hand re-examined today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 2041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-CLUB-DISCRIM-2NDT     11-29 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CLUB-DISCRIM-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: they say.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kazarosian, the plaintiffs' lawyer, said the club's actions
after the judgment could only harm it further. ``I see how the
Haverhill Country Club has reacted to this judgment,'' she said,
``where 14 jurors have pointed the finger at this club and said,
`You can't do that anymore,' and they have gone the other way and
said, `No one is going to tell us what to do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for both sides will argue the attorney general's request
for a court monitor at a hearing scheduled for Dec. 10. Owens said
last week that he would not comment on his response until he files
it with the court, but he is expected to oppose or seek to modify
the broad scope of the request.
</P>
<P>
   In court, the Haverhill women described vindictive conduct
toward them by the club's top officers. It was this conduct that
prompted the high punitive damages, which make up the bulk of the
awards.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Richardson, this year's Massachusetts Women's Open winner,
testified that in the summer of 1995 she and the Haverhill women's
association were in conflict with the men's golf committee over how
to run a weekend tournament at the club.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament had been run by the women in the past. The board
accused Richardson of insubordination and suspended her from the
club for 21 days. The suspension came just as Richardson and the
other women were filing their lawsuit and as she was preparing for
state championship tournaments. The jury awarded Richardson
$342,000, its highest single award, of which $250,000 was in
punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Brochetti has been a member of Haverhill for 20 years with
her husband, Jim. On a Sunday in 1995, Brochetti said that she, her
husband and two of their three sons were standing on the first tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to wait until 1 p.m. to tee off, even though there
weren't many people out there,'' she said. ``One of my sons was
playing as a guest and the other was a junior member. They could
have gone off, but we had to stand there because I was with them.
My oldest son said, `Mom, I can't believe you let them treat you
this way.'''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the plaintiffs' husbands said they have paid a
price for the lawsuit. Richardson's husband, Chet, said his name
was crossed out on the pairings sheet for his usual four-ball
competition just one day after the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a shame this had to happen, because it never had to get
to this point,'' Chet Richardson said. ``They could have settled
this four years ago. It would have saved them a lot of money and
everyone a lot of grief.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
