<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-LANDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA SPACECRAFT NEARS ITS LANDING ON MARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ After an 11-month journey from Earth, the squat Mars
Polar Lander, NASA's boldest attempt to find water on Mars, will
begin a searing, 4-mile-per-second plunge into the Red Planet's
atmosphere Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Even with everything working to perfection, the landing will be
risky.
</P>
<P>
   A jarring parachute descent and a final drop of nearly a mile
controlled by untried pulsing thrusters must unfold precisely to
ensure the spacecraft reaches the Martian surface intact.
</P>
<P>
   The Sept. 23 loss of NASA's Mars Climate Orbiter, a $151 million
mission that was to study the planet's weather and act as a
communications relay for the Polar Lander, is proof that less
challenging missions can go awry.
</P>
<P>
   A navigational error later attributed to an embarrassing mix-up
among ground controllers over the use of metric and English
measurements led to the Climate Orbiter's demise. Faced with less
demanding maneuvers to place it in orbit around Mars, the Climate
Orbiter instead dived too steeply into the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that landing is a more challenging job than going
into orbit,'' said Edward Stone, director of NASA's Jet Propulsion
Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif., which manages both missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have successfully landed before. We know how to do it,''
said Stone of the $221 million Polar Lander mission. In the wake of
the Climate Orbiter loss, Stone scrambled to improve communications
between overworked operations and navigation personnel, to augment
their ranks and to institute new checks and balances for the
procedures leading to the lander's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants something to go unnoticed,'' said Stone. ``My
team is very focused on landing on Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, of 29 previous missions launched to Mars over the last
four decades by the United States, the former Soviet Union, Russia
and Japan, fewer than a third can claim full success. But among the
most recent was NASA's successful Mars Pathfinder mission. After
reaching the planet July 4, 1997, the camera and rover-equipped
Pathfinder lander revealed an ancient equatorial watershed strewn
with sedimentary rocks.
</P>
<P>
   With the Polar Lander, NASA's destination is a 124-mile by
12-mile corridor of gracefully rolling terrain on the northern
fringes of the previously unexplored Martian south pole. Layered
accumulations of dust and ice in the barren, windswept north and
south polar regions of Mars began to pique the attention of
scientists more than 25 years ago when images were transmitted to
Earth by the U.S. Mariner 9 orbiter. Among Mariner 9's revelations
was a dust storm, reversing a prevailing notion that there was
little dynamic about the Martian weather.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by findings from bygone missions and those of NASA's
camera-laden Mars Global Surveyor, which began orbiting the planet
in 1997, scientists say the region may hold proof that the Martian
poles function as geologic sponges, retaining frozen reservoirs of
underground water.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say water once flowed and pooled on the now arid
surface of Mars. According to a competing theory, the water is
released periodically in response to warming events linked to Mars'
orbital track and subtle changes in the tilt of the planet's axis.
Both factors could alter the amount of sunlight and heat reaching
the polar caps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first big question is whether there is water present. The
second is can the surface and ground act as a big sponge that holds
lots of water,'' said Richard Zureck, NASA's chief scientist for
the Polar Lander mission. ``If so, that really strengthens the
arguments that the water that was present early in Mars' history on
the surface is still on the planet, it's just under the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   The finding would also bolster the 1996 claims of a small team
of NASA scientists that a meteorite of Martian origin harbors the
fossilized remnants of microbial life. A frozen reservoir would
become a target for robotic rock and soil sample return missions
that the space agency is planning soon after the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   If the Polar Lander reaches its destination safely, NASA ground
control teams will transmit commands that awaken a 6.5-foot-long
mechanized arm tipped with a clawlike scoop and other instruments.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of the Climate Orbiter's relay function will force
ground controllers to communicate directly with the Polar Lander,
slowing the exchanges of images and other data from Mars.
</P>
<P>
   During a process that could be drawn out for two to three
months, Polar Lander's arm will dig for ice. A trenching procedure
would enable the digging tool to reach depths of up to 3 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The probe is equipped with a small oven designed to receive up
to eight tiny samples of excavated material. As samples weighing no
more than a tenth of a gram are heated to temperatures of nearly
1,900 degrees, laser-driven sensors have been calibrated to detect
the presence of escaping water and carbon dioxide vapors.
</P>
<P>
   If the hunches of scientists are correct, Polar Lander will land
atop relatively young terrain, possibly only several million to a
hundred million years old and more than 1 1/2 miles thick. This
layered terrain was built as the water on Mars dried up, and winds
swept dust into the atmosphere, where it mixed with water vapor in
the planet's thin atmosphere of carbon dioxide.
</P>
<P>
   When the crystals of frozen water and dust got big enough, they
fell to the surface at the poles.
</P>
<P>
   The robot arm and the cameras of the Polar Lander will work
hand-in-glove, allowing scientists to expose and examine the
layering much as a climatologist would survey the rings of an old
tree for clues about past weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
   As the carefully screened samples are heated, the quantity of
moisture released will be closely assessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can estimate the volume of water the surface holds, the
total size of the reservoirs, by how much these mineral samples
hold,'' said Zureck.
</P>
<P>
   The Polar Lander also carries two softball-size probes, dubbed
``Deep Space 2'' by NASA. The microprobes were designed to separate
several minutes before the Polar Lander begins its plunge into the
Martian atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Without parachutes or braking rockets, the microprobes will dive
into the atmosphere, encased in protective shells about the size of
basketballs.
</P>
<P>
   Their trajectory should direct them toward the same layered
terrain as the Polar Lander. Engineers calculate they will hit
about 50 seconds to 85 seconds ahead of the Polar Lander within 60
miles of the main spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   The force of the 400-mph impact will shatter the protective
shell and separate the rugged microprobes into components.
</P>
<P>
   The impact will drive a bullet-shaped penetrator three feet into
the subsoil. The aft-body will remain on the surface linked by a
Kevlar communications tether to the penetrator.
</P>
<P>
   Within the penetrator is a tiny drill and oven. In response to
commands from Earth, the drills on the penetrators will gather a
tiny sample of the subsoil and warm it. The aft-body will radio the
vapor analysis to the orbiting Mars Global Surveyor, which will
relay the results to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency considers Deep Space 2 an experiment that could
pave the way for cheaper planetary probes and as a small insurance
policy for the Polar Lander.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 2045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
