<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4439 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCOTUS-WHISTLEBLOWERS     11-29 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-WHISTLEBLOWERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT HEARS VERMONT CASE TESTING FEDERAL WHISTLE - BLOWER
LAW  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Finding itself with a far-reaching constitutional
challenge to the federal whistle-blower law suddenly on its hands,
the Supreme Court appeared uncertain Monday about how to proceed
through a jurisdictional thicket of its own making.
</P>
<P>
   Just 10 days ago, the justices unexpectedly converted a narrower
case into a major test of a law that dates in one version or
another to the country's earliest days. Congress passed the False
Claims Act in 1863 as a tool against widespread fraud against the
government by Civil War contractors; it authorizes private
individuals to bring suits on behalf of the government and to
receive as their reward a share of any recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The case argued before the court Monday had raised only the
issue of whether states could be made defendants in False Claims
Act suits by private plaintiffs, a significant but scarcely
earth-shaking question. Then on Nov. 19, the justices, without
explanation, ordered the parties in the case to address the
question of whether private plaintiffs have standing to bring False
Claims Act suits _ against states or anyone else. That question
goes to the constitutional heart of the law, and if the answer is
no, the False Claims Act will essentially be a dead letter.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Vermont, the defendant in the case before the
court, was quick to take up the justices' invitation in the
argument Monday. An employee of the state's Agency of Natural
Resources brought a False Claims Act suit alleging mismanagement by
the agency of federal grants under the Clean Water Act and the Safe
Drinking Water Act. With triple damages under the False Claims Act,
the state's potential liability of $25 million is more than the
agency's annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``The claim is that the United States has been damaged,'' J.
Wallace Malley Jr., Vermont's deputy attorney general, told the
justices, while the plaintiff himself suffered ``no greater injury
than any other taxpayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a generalized injury, Malley continued, did not meet the
``irreducible minimum of standing,'' which the court has long
defined as ``injury in fact,'' meaning an individualized and
specific injury to be redressed by a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of receiving up to 30 percent of the government's
recovery provides private plaintiffs with a strong incentive,
Malley said, but a litigant's ``fervor'' alone is ``not enough to
grant standing.''
</P>
<P>
   In its new form, this case, Vermont Agency of Natural Resources
vs. United States, No. 98-1828, presents the justices with a
dilemma. Ordinarily, the court strives to decide cases on narrower,
statutory grounds if at all possible, avoiding unnecessary
constitutional decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the court has put the question of standing in play,
it would appear to have no alternative but to decide that most
far-reaching question of all, despite indications Monday that a
number of justices think that Vermont might well be entitled to
immunity on the narrower ground that Congress, when amending and
broadening the False Claims Act in 1986, never meant to include
states as possible defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the court's doctrine of standing serves as a
barrier to entry into federal court in the first place, a hurdle
that recent decisions have raised higher and higher. If there is no
standing, then as a constitutional matter there is no jurisdiction
at all, and the court's own precedents indicate that the justices
cannot now simply vault that hurdle to decide the easier question
first.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing the state on behalf of the federal government, Edwin S.
Kneedler, a deputy solicitor general, said that the plaintiff in
this case, Jonathan Stevens, did have standing to bring his
lawsuit. While Stevens had no prior injury, Kneedler said, ``once
he files his suit he has in effect distinguished himself from every
other taxpayer and gained the exclusive right to bring the state to
judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Kneedler added: ``Congress has created a concrete private
interest in the outcome of the suit, a prospect of recovery that is
sufficient for standing.''
</P>
<P>
   Theodore B. Olson, the lawyer for the plaintiff, used his
argument time to address what has now become the secondary question
in the case: whether states are immune from False Claims Act suits.
Vermont argued unsuccessfully, in an effort to get the lawsuit
dismissed in the lower federal courts, that private False Claims
Act suits are barred by the 11th Amendment, which provides states
with immunity from suits in federal court not brought by the
federal government or explicitly authorized by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of recent decisions, the Supreme Court has enlarged
the states' 11th Amendment shield and made it much harder for
Congress to abrogate state immunity. By agreeing last June to hear
Vermont's appeal, the justices had appeared to signal that they
were about to extend these immunity decisions to include the False
Claims Act.
</P>
<P>
   But because these suits are brought ``in the name of the United
States to redress an injury to the United States,'' the 11th
Amendment immunity should not apply, Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your position seems to require quite a few props,'' Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist said drily.
</P>
<P>
   In his few minutes of rebuttal time at the end of the hour,
Malley, the Vermont lawyer, summarized the challenge facing his
opponents, as well as the conundrum for the court. On the one hand,
he said, the government conceded that the plaintiff had no prior
injury ``and if that's the case, there is no standing.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Malley continued, the government's view was
that once the suit was filed, the private plaintiff ``captures it
and makes it his own.''
</P>
<P>
   In that case, he concluded, the barrier to proceeding was the
11th Amendment.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 2049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4440 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-MARS-EQUIPMENT-HNS &LR;      11-29 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-EQUIPMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANDER'S `BUGS' EXPECTED TO GIVE NEW INSIGHT INTO MAKEUP OF MARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Using camera-equipped space probes, scientists have
gradually pieced together a picture of Mars as a cold, arid realm
with rugged geological features that suggest the planet once had
flowing water.
</P>
<P>
   Not once in those four decades, though, have the experts
attempted to listen to the Red Planet's sounds.
</P>
<P>
   That is about to change.
</P>
<P>
   With parachutes and a braking rocket to slow its descent, NASA's
Mars Polar Lander is on course to touch down near the Martian south
pole Friday, ending an 11-month journey from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Polar Lander carries the first microphone ever dispatched to the
Red Planet, a $100,000, privately financed device, weighing less
than two ounces and fashioned from hearing aid components and
computer audio chips.
</P>
<P>
   If the Polar Lander survives a high-velocity plunge through the
Martian atmosphere, it will use a small robotic arm to dig for
evidence of frozen water in the subsoil, photograph the rolling
terrain that surrounds the landing site and collect weather
observations.
</P>
<P>
   With the ``Mars microphone,'' developed by scientists at the
University of California at Berkeley and paid for by the Planetary
Society, a nonprofit pro-space organization, the lander will
attempt to tune in its alien surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to hear Mars,'' said Janet Luhmann, a space plasma
physicist at the California school who studies planetary
atmospheres and participated in the initiation of the unusual
project several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are extending our sense of hearing for the first time to
planetary exploration,'' said Kevin Polk, the Planetary Society's
science and technical coordinator. ``This is bound to give us some
surprises and that is what exploration is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with an atmosphere so thin it would mute the tones of
normal human conversation to a soft whisper, Mars could have
something interesting for audiophiles.
</P>
<P>
   Luhmann's favorite candidates are the crackle of Martian
thunder, the roar of swirling dust devils, and wind gales that
whistle across the desertlike terrain with the velocity of a weak
hurricane. Something as exotic as a meteor streaking through the
Martian sky could announce its invasion with a sonic boom.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, however, those involved in the microphone project
hope the first sounds of Mars relayed to Earth will help bring the
alien realm to life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine putting on a pair of good ear plugs and walking around
for a day. You would experience your world differently,'' said
Luhmann as he drew a terrestrial analogy. ``So, I think by taking
the ear plugs out _ basically by having this microphone _ we will
be appreciating things in a slightly different way on Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the sounds of Mars could also have a sobering
influence on the design of human and robotic spacecraft launched to
the planet in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent features of Martian weather are raging dust
storms and feverish whirlwinds. Like the rainstorms of Earth, the
dust storm of Mars may discharge thunder.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these dust clouds charge and discharge, they probably would
not discharge in quite the same way as a rain cloud on Earth,''
Luhmann said. ``There might be more of a crackle than a boom.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, even the soft crackle of thunder on the Red Planet
could be cause for alarm to those on Earth responsible for plotting
the future exploration of Mars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you send humans, then it's one thing to have some dust blow
by you. It's another thing if it's charged and discharging to your
equipment, your space suit and yourself,'' Luhmann said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the electrical environment there in dust clouds and
outside the dust clouds is of interest to (NASA's) human
exploration experts as well as the people who are planning various
robotic activities.'' Luhmann said. ``This could impact their
operations significantly, their planning and design of their
equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ground control teams for the Polar Lander at NASA's Jet
Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif., plan to activate the
recording device soon after the spacecraft lands.
</P>
<P>
   The history of space microphones is sketchy. The late astronomer
Carl Sagan, among the founders of the Pasadena, Calif.-based
Planetary Society, proposed that NASA include them on its twin
Viking probes in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The missions, which included orbiters and landers, were a
success, but the space agency nixed the microphones.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, the Russians incorporated a microphone in a
robotic mission to Venus, detecting sounds that some interpreted as
thunder.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Luhmann and colleagues in her university's space
physics research group proposed the use of microphones on a Mars
mission to measure wind velocities.
</P>
<P>
   When the proposal was rejected on meteorological merits, it
found support as a public relations and educational tool.
</P>
<P>
   The Planetary Society will copyright the sounds it obtains with
the microphone but will make the sound bites available to the
public over the organization's Internet site:
http://www.planetary.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
