<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4454 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-COKE-WWF-COX     11-29 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-WWF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke ad cut hits home at WWF
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (a) General news (f) Financial and (l)
Lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After a body slam by Coke, the World Wrestling
Federation is cleaning up its act.
</P>
<P>
   The WWF _ whose shows have drawn fire for foul language and lewd
story lines _ promised late Monday it will tone down its
performances, starting with Thursday's ``Smackdown.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a kinder, gentler WWF follows the announcement
that Coca-Cola had severed its two-year advertising relationship
with the federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As good business people, we are willing to initiate change,''
said Jim Byrne, senior vice president of marketing for the WWF. The
shows will contain ``less use of colorful language and less
sexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Coke said earlier Monday it pulled its advertising because the
WWF ``no longer was an appropriate environment for advertising our
brands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It crossed the line in terms of content _ language and
character portrayals,'' Coke spokesman Bob Bertini said.
</P>
<P>
   Coke said it would continue to advertise with WWF's main rival,
World Championship Wrestling, a subsidiary of Time Warner's
Atlanta-based Turner Broadcasting System.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the same content issues with the WCW at this
time,'' Bertini said.
</P>
<P>
   The initial response by WWF Chairman Vince McMahon was to blast
Coke's decision as ``discriminatory, hypocritical and an affront to
free speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Coke is not the first advertiser to jump out of the WWF ring.
Earlier this year gum maker Wrigley said it would not renew its
contract with WWF because of the content of the shows.
</P>
<P>
   And the WWF has been under pressure from the Parents Television
Council to clean up its ``Smackdown'' broadcasts on the UPN
Network.
</P>
<P>
   Coke spokesman Bertini acknowledged having received complaints
from the Parents Television Council, but they were not what caused
the soft-drink company to yank its advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The WWF's sex-and-violence content has turned off more than just
Wrigley and Coke: Last month, four retailers _ Wal-Mart, Target,
Toys R Us and Kmart _ pulled a WWF action figure off their shelves
because of complaints that it was in bad taste.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the WWF is riding high. Ratings for its ``Raw'' and
``Smackdown'' shows are far ahead of WCW's ``Monday Nitro'' and
``Thunder,'' giving it an edge in the battle for $200 million in
annual TV wrestling advertising, and its toys are hot sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the WCW has begun styling its shows more like
the WWF's.
</P>
<P>
   ``WCW is changing its shows, making them more adult-oriented,''
said Bill Apter, editor-in-chief of World of Wrestling Magazine.
``The necklines on women's dresses are getting lower, and the
bikinis are getting smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffry Scott writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Henry Unger and The Associated Press contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 2106EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
