<HEADER>
A4457 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-BOOK-NYT &LR;      11-29 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCUTTLED BY WARY PUBLISHER, BUSH BIOGRAPHY FINDS NEW ONE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Soft Skull Press, an irreverent micro-publisher that
got its start in a Kinko's copy store, is reviving a disputed
biography of George W. Bush that was recalled last month amid
revelations that the author had a criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   Soft Skull's founder and senior editor, Sander Hicks, 28,
announced Monday that his company had struck a deal with J.H.
Hatfield to reissue Hatfield's book, ``Fortunate Son: George W.
Bush and the Making of an American President,'' a book that the
original publisher, St. Martin's Press in New York, had discarded
as ``furnace fodder.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, who wears his hair in a mohawk cut and describes himself
as the ``punk of publishing,'' said that in January he would
publish 25,000 copies of an updated version of the biography of
Bush, the Texas governor who is seeking the Republican presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The book will still contain its more controversial accusations,
from anonymous sources, that Bush was arrested in 1972 for cocaine
possession, a record supposedly expunged by a judge as a favor to
Bush's father, former President George Bush. They are accusations
that both Bushes have denied.
</P>
<P>
   Some bookstores, like the Borders Group chain, have quietly
continued to sell the biography despite the recall by St. Martin's
Press. St. Martin's dropped the book in October, saying Hatfield
could not be trusted after he lied to the company repeatedly about
a report in The Dallas Morning News, which revealed his conviction
11 years ago for hiring a hit man in an effort to kill his boss in
a car bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, though, said he had faith in Hatfield, who he said had
``lied about his prison record because he was under extreme
stress.''
</P>
<P>
   For Soft Skull, publishing the Bush biography is a grand gamble
because it has never printed so many copies of a title. Hicks
started the press seven years ago behind the counter of a Manhattan
Kinko's shop where he was a shift manager. Its backlist of books
ordinarily caters to more eclectic, less commercial tastes,
including ``Jesus Was Way Cool'' by John S. Hall, the leader of the
art-house rock band King Missile, and ``Ripe Tomatoes,'' billed as
a novel of love, politics and a sexy red tomato.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush biography will include a new introduction, possibly
some explanation from Hatfield about his predicament, and a new
cover, with a photograph of Bush and a red band boasting ``The Book
They Burned Is Back!''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Hatfield has refused even to admit that he is the
same Hatfield with a prison resume. Monday, the author continued to
maintain his silence, saving his version of events for a prime-time
news program, Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's told me now that he will tell everything when the time is
right,'' Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he did not know the names of Hatfield's three
anonymous sources, but he noted that he had confidence in the
information, partly because he said Hatfield had telephone records
that documented his calls to people to research the biography.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the event that we're ever taken to court,'' Hicks said,
``those sources would likely be subpoenaed. And what we're counting
on is that this is so volatile for the candidate and that it points
to the truth so that the candidate will not want to take us into
court.''
</P>
<P>
   At St. Martin's Press, where an editor in chief quit in protest
over the book's publication, there was little interest in
revisiting the subject. This despite the fact that Soft Skull
issued a packet of information that compared its new cover with the
St. Martin's version with the tart observation: ``Original cover
here from St. Martin's. Sure is ugly, eh?''
</P>
<P>
   John Murphy, a spokesman for St. Martin's, issued a one-sentence
statement: ``We really don't comment on what other publishing
houses decide to publish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 2107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
