<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING'S UNAPPROVED DESIGNS LEAD TO FEDERAL SAFETY REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Aviation Administration will conduct a
special three-month safety audit of Boeing's factories, after
learning that the company built hundreds of airplanes that did not
meet approved designs, the agency said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The errors do not pose an immediate safety threat but the agency
wants to determine if they are ``indicative of systemic issues in
the production system,'' said Beth Erickson, the agency's director
of aircraft certification.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Erickson said Boeing had reported four ``slips'' in its
quality control system recently. It delivered a 767 with a bolt
that was not tightened enough, and for years it has been building
planes with air ducts and moisture barriers that fail flammability
tests because they have too much glue, she said. In addition, at
the urging of the Environmental Protection Agency, Boeing switched
the cleaner it uses to scrub fuel tank parts before anti-corrosion
coatings are applied to them, she said, but as a result, pieces of
the coating have been peeling off into the fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Erickson said that starting early next month, about eight
inspectors would try to determine whether these were isolated
problems. They should finish by the end of February, and the agency
will make recommendations by spring, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA does not plan to fine Boeing for any of the problems
found thus far, she said, but could do so if it finds more
problems. ``We're going to take appropriate action if necessary, to
make sure the system produces airplanes that can be flown safely,''
Ms. Erickson said in a conference call with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Boeing, Yvonne Leach, said the problems were
isolated and had been corrected in the factories. ``We're producing
conforming parts,'' she said, although she noted that the company,
the FAA and the airlines were still discussing what to do about the
hundreds of planes already in service that were not built according
to specifications.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the audit comes at a time of heightened
scrutiny of one Boeing plane, the 767, after the crash on Oct. 31
of EgyptAir 990, with the deaths of all 217 people on board. But
safety investigators are leaning toward the idea that that crash
was caused by a pilot's suicide, not a mechanical problem.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The bolt problem, although it was found on only one airplane,
could represent a broader problem, Ms. Erikson said. In that case,
the engineering department specified a requirement for tightening
the bolt, but the tooling department gave ``an inappropriate
translation'' in telling workers precisely which wrench to use, and
how to use it, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The audit will examine production systems for nearly the whole
range of airliners _ 737s, 747s, 757s, 767s and 777s _ in Everett,
Renton and Auburn, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA conducted a similar special audit in January 1998, after
investigators said that a 10-month-old 737 that crashed in
Indonesia appeared to be missing bolts in its tail. But the
inspectors found that planes then under construction had all the
required fasteners, and aviation experts later said that the
missing bolts were probably a result, not a cause, of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The problem of the moisture barriers above the cockpits of 747,
757, 767 and 777 jets was detailed before.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the audits could delay delivery schedules, which have
been a problem recently for Boeing, Ms. Erickson said: ``When we do
an evaluation like this, the FAA's concern must be that we focus on
what we're doing with the evaluation. Their ability to deliver
aircraft comes as a secondary issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has insisted that no airplanes be delivered with parts
different from those specified when it approved the plane's design.
But the agency and the company are still discussing what to do
about planes that have already been delivered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
