<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4473 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     11-29 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINKEL IN SOLID POSITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By virtue of being in charge of Mike Tyson's career, Shelly
Finkel has solidified his position as one of the most powerful
figures in the turbulent world of boxing.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lofty plateau he's been hovering around since the 1984
Olympics when he and Main Events formed a partnership and began
signing up such future champions as Evander Holyfield, Pernell
Whitaker, Meldrick Taylor and Mark Breland.
</P>
<P>
   But Finkel's alliance with Tyson just might be the most unlikely
this side of Susan Faludi and Patrick Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson is a malevolent fellow with an explosive temper who
did a four year stretch for rape, a street-hardened felon with a
lengthy history of anti-social behavior, a junior high school
dropout who long has settled differences with his fists and has a
lengthy rap sheet reflecting his violence.
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Finkel is a mild-mannered, articulate graduate of New
York University, a devoted family man of 23 years who has two
daughters and a son, a professorial-looking person with a bald pate
who affects the intellectual persona of a physics teacher rather
than a fight manager and wages his battles with rhetoric rather
than fists.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is the 55-year-old Finkel is now calling the shots
for Tyson, and he will be the one who ultimately decides if Lennox
Lewis realizes his ambition of facing Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, they say opposites attract,'' laughs Finkel, who this
Saturday night will be at the Chinook Winds Casino in Lincoln City,
Ore., to watch another one of his fighters, the heralded IBF junior
middleweight champion, Fernando Vargas, defend his title against
Winky Wright in match that will be shown on HBO. ``I've known Mike
since 1982, and always got along with him. When he needed help, he
called me and I was there for him. Mike's obsessed with becoming
the heavyweight champion again.''
</P>
<P>
   And Lennox Lewis is obsessed with Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment it was announced that Lewis was a unanimous
winner over Evander Holyfield and the undisputed world heavyweight
champion, Lewis has been loudly clamoring for a showdown with
Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   No financial dummy, Lennox Lewis realizes that Tyson is the only
megabuck gate attraction in the division.
</P>
<P>
   He realizes that the public won't be storming the turnstiles to
see him defend his title against one of the alphabets' No.1
challengers the WBA's Henry Akinwande, the WBC's Johnny Ruiz and
the IBF's David Tua.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Lewis-Tyson fight is going to happen late next
year,'' says Finkel. ``Tyson called me a couple of times during the
Lewis-Holyfield fight, and kept saying, `I wanna fight Lewis. I
know I can beat him.' But Mike realizes he's going to have to have
a few warmups before he faces someone the caliber of Lewis. After
all, Mike's only fought six rounds in the past three years. He
needs some work.''
</P>
<P>
   Finkel says he has a fight lined up for Tyson on Jan.22 in
Europe, but an opponent hasn't yet been found.
</P>
<P>
   There, of course, is no finishing school that prepares you for
the wacky, unpredictable, bizarre, weird orbit of boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Don King spent his youth running numbers in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Arum was a tax attorney in the Bobby Kennedy justice
department.
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Finkel?
</P>
<P>
   He spent his younger days operating a Long Island nightclub
called the Action House, and booked into it such groups as The
Doors, Cream, the Little Rascals and Mitch Ryder and the Detroit
Wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget one time after an early performance by The
Doors, Jim Morrison came up to me and said, `Look how good I did.
Why don't you buy me a drink?''' relates Finkel. ``I told him,
`Jim, the bar's yours. Have all you want.' I soon found out what a
mistake that was and how much he liked to drink. Jim was totally
drunk for the second performance and fell off the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also was managing a band called The Pigeons. I took them
over to Columbia Records, and they told me it was the worst band
they ever heard. I then took them over to Atlantic, and they said
they'd record their song if they'd change their name. Well, they
changed it to Vanilla Fudge and their song, `You Keep Me Hanging
On' went gold in four weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Finkel soon became one of the biggest promoters in rock
music, working with Jimi Hendrix, Janice Joplin, The Who and many
others before staging the legendary Watkins Glen, N.Y., concert in
July of 1973 in which more than 600,000 fans showed up to observe
the Grateful Dead, the Allman Brothers and The Band.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was even bigger than Woodstock,'' says Finkel. ``Only four
hundred thousand attended Woodstock. Unfortunately, there is no
film footage of Watkins Glen like Woodstock because the Grateful
Dead wouldn't allow it.''
</P>
<P>
   Finkel over the years has done concerts with the Rolling Stones,
Elton John, Paul McCartney, George Harrison, Bruce Springsteen, Led
Zepplin, the Eagles, Van Halen, the Beach Boys, Crosby, Stills &AMP;
Nash, Fleetwood Mac, U2, and countless other high-profile acts.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1977 a neighborhood boy lost his father, and Finkel and
his wife began taking the youngster to the movies and to Central
Park and to amateur fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started following the career of a young amateur named Alex
Ramos,'' says Finkel. ``I started to go to more and more fights,
got to know people like Lou Duva, and before you knew it I was
involved in boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   It would become a full-time vocation after he and the Duvas'
Main Events consummated their L.A. Olympic coup that also included
the signing of Tyrell Biggs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Tyson and Vargas, Finkel is now supervising the
IBF's No. 1 ranked junior welterweight, Zab Judah, the talented
welterweight Vernon Forrest and David Tua, who scored a 20-second
knockout over Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Mike Tyson who has vaulted Shelly Finkel into the
glaring spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people don't know about Mike Tyson is that he's a true
historian of boxing and understands the sport fully,'' says Finkel.
``All he keeps telling me is, `Lennox Lewis is a good fight for
me.' And it will happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
