<SLUG> BC-HOFHEINZ-INDICTMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA GRAND JURY INDICTS FORMER HOUSTON MAYOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH TEDFORD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Houston Mayor Fred Hofheinz was indicted Monday on
federal charges that he made $2 million in payoffs to a
``high-level public official in Louisiana'' in an effort to win
public contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana rancher Cecil Brown and Texas businessman Guy Thompson
were also named in the nine-count indictment returned by a grand
jury in Baton Rouge, La. _ part of the broad-ranging probe of
alleged corruption in former Gov. Edwin Edwards' administration.
</P>
<P>
   Hofheinz would not comment Monday, but he had said Sunday he had
been informed of his indictment and that the allegations are untrue
and stem from the government's decades-long attempt to convict
Edwards of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This matter would not be happening if not for the U.S.
attorney's interest in Edwin Edwards,'' Hofheinz said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards was acquitted twice on federal racketeering charges
during the 1980s. When he retired from politics in 1996, he
estimated he had been before 22 grand juries.
</P>
<P>
   Hofheinz and Brown are each charged with conspiring to
``corruptly influence'' a public official and three counts of
interstate travel to aid an unlawful activity.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was also charged with four counts of extortion and Thomson
with being an accessory in interstate travel to aid an unlawful
activity.
</P>
<P>
   The charges stem from three business ventures in which Hofheinz
was the principal partner in companies vying for contracts in
Louisiana. Those ventures were:
</P>
<P>
   _ Viewpoint Development Corp.'s plan to develop a juvenile
detention facility in Jena, La.
</P>
<P>
   _ A plan by Top Rank Inc. to lease an arena and bring a
professional basketball team to New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   _ A plan by Bayshore Environmental Inc. to obtain municipal
waste disposal contracts for a Texas company called Evergreen
Global Resources.
</P>
<P>
   Although Edwards, already facing charges in two cases resulting
from the investigation, was not named in Monday's indictment, U.S.
Attorney Eddie Jordan of New Orleans said he believes that the
former governor was involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``He profited in the sense that he received the money, we
believe,'' Jordan told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors allege that Brown, a longtime friend of Edwards,
extorted money from Hofheinz for payment to ``a high-level public
official.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown allegedly used his company, Lousiana Consultants, to
receive bribe money meant for the official. Brown even threatened
Hofheinz, telling him the official could call members of the
Legislature to stop funding for certain projects even after leaving
office, prosecutors allege.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the activities detailed in the indictment relate to the
contract to build the juvenile detention facility.
</P>
<P>
   The conspiracy count alleges Hofheinz made payoffs to Brown from
1993 through April 1997, giving him $245,000 in cash in September
1993 from Viewpoint Development. That money was meant to pave the
way for Viewpoint's participation in developing the $35 million
detention facility, prosecutors allege.
</P>
<P>
   Although Viewpoint ultimately signed an agreement with the
Louisiana Department of Corrections to build the facility, it could
not come up with the money to finance the deal and eventually sold
its rights to the contract.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also alleges Top Rank and Viewpoint gave Brown
four checks totaling $599,000 in June 1994 _ also as part of the
conspiracy. However, prosecutors said Brown returned $400,000 by
cash and wire transfers the following month because Top Rank was
having difficulty in its bid to move the Minnesota Timberwolves NBA
basketball team to New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   In the bribery counts, Hofheinz allegedly gave $600,000 to Brown
on behalf of Top Rank in December 1994; $100,000 in checks in April
and May 1995 in behalf of Bayshore and signed a ``lobbying
contract'' with Louisiana Consultants, agreeing to pay a $1.3
million fee when funding was secured.
</P>
<P>
   Hofheinz, who served as Houston mayor from 1974-77 and still
resides here, has said that he and others became involved in
several business ventures at the behest of brothers Michael and
Patrick Graham, whom he believed to be legitimate businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   Hofheinz said he later learned the two were convicted felons who
had cheated a number of people out of money, and that he _ and the
FBI _ are victims of an elaborate con.
</P>
<P>
   The Grahams are the chief witnesses against Hofheinz, according
to court documents filed in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are wholly and totally unreliable,'' Hofheinz attorney
Michael Ramsey said Monday. ``They have been found to be forgers,
guilty of theft, tax evasion, civil fraud and falsification of
documents. I was informed today that they _ at least Patrick _ are
on the government's payroll. If I pay a witness, it's called
bribery. If the government pays a witness, it's called justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Hofheinz and Brown could get five years in prison on the
conspiracy count and on each of the three bribery counts.
</P>
<P>
   Brown could get 20 years in prison on each of his four extortion
counts, Thompson 2 1/2 years in prison on his accessory to bribery
count.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
