<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON MUST FACE INFLAMMATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles Clippers history reminds us the alphabet is
responsible for such franchise terrors as A-C-L (anterior cruciate
ligament) damage and B-S (bad shooting) sickness.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be trifled with is S-T-E-R-L-I-N-G, which spells doom.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Clip letter bomb is a new one on us ... F-M-I. It stands
for Facial Muscle Inflammation.
</P>
<P>
   The victim is shooting guard Derek Anderson, whose status for
tonight's game with the Phoenix Suns at Staples Center is listed as
an emphatic ``day to day.'' According to trainer Jasen Powell,
Anderson's response to a medication change will determine his
availability.
</P>
<P>
   What previously was believed to be a lingering sinus infection
seemingly matured into great discomfort for Anderson during
Saturday's loss to Portland. After scoring 52 points in his first
two games back from a concussion-related three-game absence,
Anderson was limited to 29 minutes and 6 points.
</P>
<P>
   He's missed the last two days of practice and regardless of how
he handles the new meds figures to be far below peak efficiency if
his condition improves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't assume anything until I get the report back from the
doctor,'' said Clippers coach Chris Ford, who has been forced to
wear out that sentiment in the last two weeks. Eric Piatkowski
figures to start at shooting guard, with Tyrone Nesby pulling on
the leash as sixth man.
</P>
<P>
   The good karma is represented by Maurice Taylor, who appears to
be playing without pain after missing two weeks with a foot sprain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's ready to play ... mentally,'' Ford said. ``We'll see how
he is after a couple of trips up and down the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor will march back into the starting lineup, with Brian
Skinner who was heroic in Taylor's absence going back to his role
of low-post sub.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get Brian back to his comfort zone,'' Ford said
of the power forward/center who had just 4 points and 7 rebounds
combined in two weekend losses after posting a string of
double-doubles on the road. ``He had been playing a lot of minutes;
I think it affected him over the last two games.''
</P>
<P>
   Good, bad numbers: The good number is 11 _ that's how many
Clippers suited up for Monday's practice at Veterans Park
SportsComplex in Carson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's two days in a row we've had enough guys to scrimmage,''
said Ford, whose team hadn't been in that predicament for two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day streak includes participation from point guard Eric
Murdock; the crafty veteran did provide a few swell moments on the
team's five-game road swing, but chronic knee pain has limited his
contributions since.
</P>
<P>
   The bad number is 32.9, the team's field-goal percentage in
Saturday's loss to Portland.
</P>
<P>
   After all the strategic dress rehearsals, medical reports and
psychological Ping-Pong is examined, Ford believes the scoreboard
dilemma can be traced to marksmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have to shoot the ball much better,'' he said. ``You
can't shoot 41 percent and win a lot of games. Our defense, at
times, hasn't been that bad, but we're not nearly good enough
defensively to get by with the way we've been shooting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 2131EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4477 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-IMMIG-DETAIN-ART-NYT &LR;      11-29 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIG-DETAIN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. FREES EGYPTIAN JAILED IN 1996 ON SECRET EVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 25 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Attorney General Janet Reno declined to block the
release Monday night of an Egyptian man who had been held for three
and a half years in a New York jail on secret evidence that the FBI
had said linked him to terrorists in the United States and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   With the attorney general not intervening in the case of Nasser
Ahmed, Ahmed was allowed to leave the Metropolitan Correctional
Center in lower Manhattan Monday night, and was met by his wife,
Salwa Elbayadi, and their three children. In a brief statement,
Ahmed thanked his lawyers for his freedom and lashed out at his
accusers in the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're liars, and they know they are liars,'' Ahmed said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's decision came 10 days after the INS commissioner, Doris
Meissner, took the unusual step of citing ``national security
implications'' as a basis for asking Reno to order that Ahmed not
be released on bond while his case was reviewed by the INS.
</P>
<P>
   The immigration service, based on classified evidence, had been
seeking to deport Ahmed, who is seeking political asylum. Ahmed,
39, had worked as a legal assistant to Sheik Omar Abdel Rahman, the
blind Egyptian cleric convicted of conspiring to blow up the World
Trade Center and other New York landmarks. Although Ahmed has
admitted to being an admirer of Abdel Rahman, he has denied any
involvement in terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   One of Ahmed's lawyers, David Cole, said Monday night that with
Reno's decision, he is now ``very optimistic'' that Ahmed will be
granted political asylum, which he has been seeking for more than
three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the attorney general rejected the immigration
service's argument that he is a threat to national security should
dispose of this case,'' Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno had said she would decide whether to intervene in the case
by 5 p.m. Monday, and with no action by her as the deadline neared,
the INS said that ``upon further review'' it was withdrawing its
request that Ahmed continue to be held.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ahmed's case is not yet over _ he remains free on bond
pending a final ruling by the Board of Immigration Appeals on
whether he should be granted asylum _ Reno's decision not to
intervene is likely to be seen as another major blow to the use of
secret evidence by the INS in deportation proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general has the authority to review and overturn
decisions of the immigration courts, which are part of the Justice
Department. Last summer, an immigration judge, after reviewing the
government's classified evidence against Ahmed, concluded that it
was weak, that he was not a threat to national security, and
ordered that he be granted asylum.
</P>
<P>
   The INS then appealed to the Board of Immigration Appeals, which
recently ordered Ahmed released on bond pending its review of his
case. It was that decision to free Ahmed that the INS then appealed
to Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, in a case involving a Palestinian immigrant, a
federal district judge in New Jersey ruled, for the first time in
the United States, that it was unconstitutional for the government
to detain an immigrant on the basis of secret evidence. Shortly
thereafter, the INS dropped its efforts to hold Hany Kiareldeen,
who had also been accused of terrorism and had been held for 19
months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Reno nor Meissner would respond to questions through
spokesmen about the case.
</P>
<P>
   But Ahmed's lawyers and others who have sharply criticized the
practice of using secret evidence as a violation of due process,
said they hoped that the decision indicated a rethinking of the
practice at the highest levels of the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased that he's released,'' said Rep. David Bonior,
D-Mich., who has introduced legislation to ban the use of
classified evidence in deportation proceedings, ``but we still have
about 20 others who are being held, and it's a travesty of justice
that this continues in our country without people having the right
to face their accusers.''
</P>
<P>
   The release of Ahmed was also hailed by Arab-American groups
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Aly Abuzaakouk, executive director of the American Muslim
Council in Washington, said: ``Three and a half years is a long
time to wait. Should we celebrate tonight, or should we decry the
fact that in America, a man was behind bars for so many years on
the basis of secret evidence?''
</P>
<P>
   Abuzaakouk charged that secret evidence was unreliable, unjust
and unconstitutional, and added: ``The only thing that keeps secret
evidence alive is the politics of fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed, who was taken into custody in April 1996, had been held
longer than any others who have been detained on classified
evidence. Some, like Ahmed, have been held for long periods in
solitary confinement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
