u w BC-BUDGET-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      11-29 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SIGNS FINAL BUDGET BILL AND TURNS TO NEXT YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly two months after the start of the
government's fiscal year, President Clinton signed the last piece
of the federal budget into law Monday, saying the agreement that he
worked out with the Republican-led Congress had been worth the
weeks of tortured negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a budget for a government that lives within its means
and lives up to the values of the American people,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But even as he was signing the bill, which covers $390 billion
of spending on education, law enforcement, foreign aid, health care
and the environment, the president was turning his attention to
next year's budget and the continued political battle over
apportioning projected surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton held his first meeting with his aides on the
administration's spending and tax proposals for next year, and he
used Monday's bill-signing ceremony in the Rose Garden to set out
an agenda for his last year in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we celebrate what we've accomplished, I ask us all to be
humble and mindful of what we still have to accomplish,'' Clinton
said as he offered a list of initiatives, including giving patients
more protection in dealing with managed care companies, putting new
restrictions on gun sales, bolstering Social Security's financial
strength and adding prescription drug coverage to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how much progress Clinton and Congress will make
on those and other issues in an election year. The budget fight in
particular seems likely to be as hard fought as it was this year,
with Republicans in Congress vowing Monday to pass another big tax
cut over Clinton's objections and Republican presidential
candidates proposing tax-cutting plans of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the front-runner in the race for
the Republican presidential nomination, is expected to lay out his
plan this week to reduce income tax rates, provide tax breaks for
the working poor and some married couples, and phase out the
inheritance tax. Clinton vetoed a $792 billion, 10-year tax cut
passed this summer by the Republicans, saying it would endanger the
nation's newfound fiscal health.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore attacked Bush's approach Monday, and also
criticized a plan by his rival for the Democratic presidential
nomination, former Sen. Bill Bradley, to devote a big chunk of the
surplus to making health care more accessible. Both plans, Gore
said, would risk plunging the government back into deficit and do
nothing to address the long-term problems facing Social Security
and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``In both cases, the economic future of the country is put at
risk because of higher interest rates and ignoring the lessons of
the last seven years,'' he said in a conference call with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   If there is hope for a compromise that gives both sides some of
what they want despite election-year politics, it stems from the
possibility that the projected budget surpluses will grow as the
economy roars along and tax revenues flow into the Treasury. ``I
expect the surplus projections to be up significantly,'' Sen. Pete
Domenici, R-N.M., who is chairman of the Senate Budget Committee,
said as he left the White House ceremony. ``We will be back next
year with another major tax cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides emerged from the standoff over this year's $1.8
trillion budget with enough of what they wanted to claim victory.
Domenici said Republicans had achieved their main goal of limiting
spending sufficiently to avoid dipping into the portion of the
surplus generated by excess Social Security payroll taxes, an
assertion that may or may not prove true depending on how fast the
surplus grows this year.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, the legislation signed Monday, which rolled
together five spending bills that had proven particularly difficult
to pass, contained money for most of the programs he had said were
his priorities. Surrounded by police officers and teachers, Clinton
said the budget would help reach his goal of hiring 100,000 new
teachers to reduce class sizes in the early grades and would help
communities hire another 50,000 police officers in neighborhoods
with high crime rates.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also requires federal agencies to trim their
spending by 0.38 percent this year, a total of $1.2 billion. And it
contains myriad provisions for special interests and narrow issues,
including one authorizing but not requiring the president to
provide food aid to rebels fighting the government in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   As they start planning for next year, Congress and the
administration are in something of a hole. To avoid spending any of
the Social Security surplus, their self-imposed standard for fiscal
discipline, the two parties agreed on a number of budget gimmicks,
including deferring more than $20 billion that would otherwise have
been spent this year onto the next fiscal year's books.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they have that much less room to propose new
spending or tax cuts for next year, having already allocated more
than half of the $38 billion non-Social Security surplus projected
for next year by the Congressional Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus projections themselves are in flux. Both the budget
office and the White House have so far based their forecasts on the
assumption that spending would remain within tight caps required by
the 1997 balanced budget agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But the two parties have shattered the caps for two years in a
row _ by about $30 billion this year _ and future surpluses could
be substantially smaller than projected if spending continues to
grow faster than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   If the economy remains strong, however, the surplus for this
year and next could be revised upward. And because government
economists are increasingly convinced that the economy's growth
potential is higher than they previously believed, they are
considering increasing their economic growth estimates for the next
decade, a step that would generate a corresponding increase in
estimated tax revenues and therefore in the size of the surplus.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 2133EST &QL; 
