<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MASSGRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
200 REPORTED BURIED IN MASS GRAVES NEAR U.S.-MEXICO BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TIM GOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mexican authorities, working with a team from the FBI, began on
Monday to excavate sites near the U.S. border that they believe may
hold the bodies of scores of Mexicans and Americans killed over the
last several years as a part of a campaign by drug traffickers
seeking to eliminate their enemies.
</P>
<P>
   The search for bodies, an American law enforcement official
said, was spurred by a tip from an informant recruited by the FBI
who acknowledged complicity in several murders and identified the
locations of at least two mass graves on the outskirts of Ciudad
Juarez, the Mexican city just over the border from El Paso, Texas.
The informant, who officials said has passed a polygraph, or lie
detector exam, said as many as 200 people may be buried in several
graves.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said the digging began Monday and that, as
yet, no complete human remains had been recovered.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, prosecutions of Mexican drug traffickers along
the Texas border have been hindered by the disappearance of
witnesses and informants, some of whom have been kidnapped from
American soil. Dozens of people have disappeared from the Juarez
area without explanation.
</P>
<P>
   According to American officials, some of these people had been
informants for the Drug Enforcement Administration and the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Others had no apparent connection to the drug trade.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican attorney general's office, the country's chief
federal law enforcement arm, issued a statement Monday confirming
the search for bodies, which was first reported Monday night by CBS
News.
</P>
<P>
   ``This investigation is focused on resolving a series of
assassinations and disappearances related to drug trafficking,
perpetrated against Mexican and United States citizens, apparently
by members of the so-called cartel,'' the statement said. ``Over
the last four years and possibly longer, in Ciudad Juarez,
Chihuahua, citizens of both nationalties have disappeared without a
trace.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican authorities said they have set up toll-free telephone
lines in both countries for relatives and others with information
on missing people.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by citizens groups in Juarez and other parts of
Chihuahua state, the Mexican authorities carried out a lengthy
inquiry into the disappearances, but had little success.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Mexican attorney general, Jorge Madrazo Cuellar,
acknowledged that drug traffickers had infiltrated a police agent
into the special unit which was investigating the disappearances.
</P>
<P>
   The informer who described the killings to the FBI said some
were carried out by Mexican federal policemen who working as hired
assassins for the drug gangs that operate from Juarez, one of the
main gateways for cocaine and other drugs being shipped north
through Mexico into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said that a team of FBI specialists is
waiting in El Paso to receive and examine any bodies recovered in
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said they have been working closely with Madrazo,
who is a former human rights lawyer. Officials said the FBI began
quietly examining the case several months ago. The Mexicans were
informed about three weeks ago, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials said they have established a joint base for
the inquiry in El Paso.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
