<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- IMMIG-DETAIN-2, 11-29 --
Nasser Ahmed kisses his five-year old daughter Nagwi as his wife
Salwa Elbayadi looks on Monday night after Ahmed was released from
the Metropolitan Correctional Center in lower Manhattan. At center,
Ahmad, 10, carries his father's belongings. Attorney General Janet
Reno declined to block Ahmed's release Monday night following three
and a half years of detention on secret evidence that the FBI had
said linked him to terrorists in the United States and Egypt.
(Frances Roberts/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- IMMIG-DETAIN, 11-29 --
Nasser Ahmed, flanked by his sons Omar Ahmed, 7, left, and Ahmad
Ahmed, 10, carries his belongings after being released from the
Metropolitan Correctional Center in lower Manhattan Monday night.
Attorney General Janet Reno declined to block Ahmed's release
Monday night following three and a half years of detention on
secret evidence that the FBI had said linked him to terrorists in
the United States and Egypt. (Frances Roberts/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- MRSCLINTON-B&AMP;W, 11-29 --
First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton speaks at an event to raise funds
for Rep. Joseph Crowley, D-N.Y., standing in the background, on
Monday. Abortion rights activists complained Monday about Mrs.
Clinton's appearance on behalf of Crowley, a Democrat who opposes
abortion rights and faces a re-election challenge from within his
own party. Mrs. Clinton, who is running for Senate from New York,
said she looked forward to serving with Crowley, but she did not go
as far as to endorse him for re-election. (Michelle V. Agins/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) MOSCOW -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA, 11-29 --
Col. Gen. Georgy Shpak, the senior commander of Russia's
paratroopers, during an interview on Monday. Shpak said Monday that
rebel resistance was growing in Chechnya and that Russian troops
had suffered a serious setback last week and expected more
casualties in the weeks ahead. (Jaqueline Mia Foster/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- OBIT-BARRETT-B&AMP;W, 11-29 --
John J. Barrett, a Manhattan lawyer and former chairman of the New
York Urban League, died Friday at Mount Sinai Hospital. He was 95
and lived on the Upper East Side of Manhattan. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- NY-FASHION-SMITH, 11-29 --
From left, Wynn Smith includes everyday streetwear in the simpler,
trendier Wink collection; a school-girlish cotton suit from the
Wink spring 2000 line; the Wynn collection shows his acclaimed
instinct for proportions. (Corina Lecca/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- MEDICAL-DEVICES-3, 11-29
-- Dr. Martin B. Leon, a prominent cardiologist, at a recent
convention of his colleagues in Washington. During his speech, Leon
promoted an item called a Paragon stent - a tiny wire cage that can
hold blocked arteries open - without telling the assembled doctors
that he was an investor in the company that manufactured it. (Carol
T. Powers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) CAMDEN, N.J. -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- MEDICAL-DEVICES-2,
11-29 -- Surgeons hold stents, tiny wire cages that can hold
blocked arteries open, during an operation last month at Cooper
Hospital. A doctor promoting the device before an audience of
colleages recently is also a top investor in the company making it.
Scientists on the front line of such medical research, whose work
can help determine treatment options for countless of Americans,
often can earn vast
wealth so long as their results are positive. It is an immense
financial pressure that would be unacceptable in any other field of
medical research. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SEATTLE -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- WTO-PROTESTS-3-SPI, 11-29 --
Protestor Douglas Mackar, right, holding a copy of the U.S.
Constitution, yells through a bullhorn opposite Seattle Police Lt.
Daniel Whelan during a demonstration against the World Trade
Organization on Monday. Activists turned up the heat on the WTO,
taking their message to the streets and announcing plans for mass
acts of civil disobedience when the ministerial conference begins
Tuesday. (Dan DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) SEATTLE -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- WTO-PROTESTS-2-SPI, 11-29 --
Cheri Honkala is arrested by Seattle police after she tried to
break through police lines outside the Washington State Trade and
Convention Center, site of the World Trade Organization meeting, on
Monday. Honkala and several other protesters said they were trying
to serve ``arrest warrants'' on officials representing the nations
comprising the G-7. Critics of the WTO contend the Geneva-based
organization puts trade promotion goals above other interests such
as human and worker rights and environmental protection. (Rick
Giase/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) MEDFORD, Mass. -- Nov. 29, 1999 --
BRADLEY-FOREIGN-POLICY-2, 11-29 -- Bill Bradley, the former U.S.
Senator from New Jersey, delivers an address on foreign affairs
issues to an audience at Tufts University on Monday. Laying out his
philosophy on American policy overseas, Bradley, running for the
Democratic nominatin for president, called Monday for immediate
talks with Russia to cut nuclear warheads to even lower numbers
than the Clinton-Gore administration wants. (Stephen Crowley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MEDFORD, Mass. -- Nov. 29, 1999 --
BRADLEY-FOREIGN-POLICY-1, 11-29 -- Bill Bradley, the former U.S.
Senator from New Jersey, fields questions on foreign affairs from
students at Tufts University on Monday. Laying out his philosophy
on American policy overseas, Bradley, running for the Democratic
nominatin for president, called Monday for immediate talks with
Russia to cut nuclear warheads to even lower numbers than the
Clinton-Gore administration wants. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- PRISON-CALLS, 11-29 -- Ruth
Smith, whose cousin is serving a 25-year sentence on a drug
conviction, outside a substance abuse center on Monday where she is
a director. Ms. Smith, estimated she spent $100 a month to speak
with her cousin. Under current state policy, the families of
inmates are charged the highest possible rates for calls from
prisons; at least a third more than rates available to the general
public. Most of the money is kept by the state. (Librado Romero/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- SWISS-HOLOCAUST, 11-29 --
Bella Youngwirth, 80, a holocaust survivor, outside the federal
courthouse in the Brooklyn on Monday during a news conference. A
loophole in a proposed $1.25 billion settlement between Holocaust
survivors and Swiss Banks accused of profiting from looted Jewish
assets could allow Swiss companies and museums to keep artwork
stolen by the Nazis, holocaust survivors warned at a hearing held
in the Brooklyn courthouse. (Richard Perry/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON, -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- MEDICAL-DEVICES, 11-29
-- Heart specialists watch on closed-circuit television monitors as
a tiny experimental device is implanted in a patient's coronary
artery last month. The operation was being narrated by Dr. Martin
Leon, in monitor at right, who was describing the operation taking
place in a hospital many miles away. What Leon did not tell the
assembled doctors was that he was an investor in the company that
manufactured the device being implanted. (Carol T. Powers/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) HANOVER, N.H. -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- GORE-STUMP-SPEECH,
11-29 -- Vice President Al Gore speaks to members of the audience
after a debate with former Sen. Bill Bradley in October. When he
announced two months ago that he was overhauling his foundering
presidential campaign, Gore was fond of saying that he was
``throwing away the script.'' But sponteniety has its limits. And
while Gore uses questions as a springboard to say exactly what he
wants, it usually is exactly what he said at the previous open
meeting. (David L. Ryan/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- BALLET-STRIKE, 11-29 --
Striking musician Ethan Silverman handing out flyers in front of
Lincoln Center before Saturday night's performance of ``The
Nutcracker'' by the New York City Ballet. Orchestra members went on
strike a week ago in a labor dispute; during negotiations taped
music has accompanied performances of ``The Nutcracker.'' (Nancy
Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SEATTLE -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- SCI-CHILDREN-SPEECH-2, 11-29
-- Dr. Patricia Kuhl analyzing a conversation between mother and
baby using a spectrographic display showing vocal amplitude and
frequency. Neuroscientists are using advanced new tools to look
into the inner workings of the brains of infants and toddlers,
hoping to gain insight into the biological basis of language. (Greg
Owen/University of Washington Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SEATTLE -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- SCI-CHILDREN-SPEECH-1, 11-29
-- An 11-month-old is wired for brain-wave recordings in Dr.
Patricia Kuhl's laboratory. ``In this past decade, we have learned
a tremendous amount about how much learning goes on in this early
period, and language is a great example,'' says Dr. Kuhl. ``Now we
know that while babies are quiet, there is a tremendous amount
going on in the brain.'' (Gavin Sisk/University of Washington
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LONDON -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- LONDON-YOUNG-ARTISTS, 11-29 --
The Tate Modern is to open in London in the spring, reflecting the
ferment in the British art world. One of the world's largest
museums devoted exclusively to 20th-century art, it will
undoubtedly change the balance of power in the international art
world, especially among museums of contemporary and modern art.
(Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PAMLICO SOUND, N.C. -- Nov. 29, 1999 --
SCI-CAROLINA-FLOODS, 11-29 -- Sabrina Varnam, left, and Megan Black
of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration using
instruments to measure water composition and health in areas of the
Pamlico Sound estuary. Scientists fear the recent flood here has
created an ecological time bomb that could bring disaster to the
biologically rich waters that separate the famous Outer Banks from
the Carolina mainland. (Kevin Hovel/NOAA Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SEATTLE -- Nov. 29, 199 -- WTO-PROTESTS-SPI, 11-29 -- In
the shadow of Seattle's most famous landmark, the Space Needle, a
demonstrator with the Rainforest Action Network hangs from a
construction crane near Interstate 5 Monday morning to protest what
the organization calls the World Trade Organization's
anti-democratic policies. Several activists have already been
arrested for unfurling anti-WTO banners across local landmarks.
Organizations and protesters vow to disrupt the four-day 135-nation
summit through acts of civil disobedience. (Jeff Larsen/Seattle
Post-Intelligencer Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- SCI-AIDS-POLIO, 11-29 -- In
``The River,'' Edward Hooper finds disturbing links between an
experimental oral polio vaccine given in Leopoldville (now
Kinshasa, Congo) in 1959 and the beginnings of the AIDS virus. The
virus, he says, could have originated in chimpanzee tissues used to
make the vaccine. (Tony Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SAN FRANCISCO -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- SCI-PLOTKIN-RAINFOREST,
11-29 -- Dr. Mark Plotkin, second from right, with a group of
Colombian shamans who visited the United States in October. Plotkin
staked his reputation on finding new medicines in the rain forest,
but his earliest efforts at finding great medicines failed, forcing
the recognition that even in the rain forests medical miracles are
rare. (Jon Christensen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOSTON -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- HOLISTIC-LAWYERS-BOS, 11-29 --
Attorneys Cheryl Conner, right, and Rita Pollak at the Suffolk Law
School. The two are the co-organizers of a group of holistic
lawyers; lawyers who determined to bring deeper meaning to a
profession widely derided as morally bankrupt. ``Some within our
group would probably call us preventative lawyers,'' said Ms.
Conner, a former federal prosecutor who now teaches law at Suffolk.
``Lawyers who want to understand the root causes of conflict and
legal misunderstandings.'' (Janet Knott/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) AVON, Conn. -- Nov. 29, 1999 -- SCI-OLDER-ATHLETES, 11-29
-- Aldona Siuta, 63, has used sports like basketball to help her
stay active. A new generation of older athletes are healthier than
their predecessors, living longer and pointedly aware of the
importance of getting and staying in shape. They are forming pickup
teams, creating senior divisions in sports leagues and competing in
large-scale events in gyms and playing fields across the country.
(George Ruhe/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
