A4495 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NIRELAND-CABINET-NYT &LR;      11-29 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-CABINET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABINET MEMBERS NAMED FOR NEW NORTHERN IRELAND ASSEMBLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Leaders from pro-British Protestant and pro-Irish
Catholic parties took a major step Monday night in moving their
age-old conflict into the political arena, naming the members of
the cabinet that will run the new power-sharing Northern Ireland
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The action in the Stormont parliament chamber in Belfast, held
off for many months while negotiators labored to break a deadlock
over guerrilla disarmament, puts Sinn Fein into the government of
the British province, which Sinn Fein's paramilitary wing, the
Irish Republican Army, fought a decades-long war to abolish.
   ``Whatever you think about their past, they are people now
committed to politics, not to violence,'' Peter Mandelson,
Britain's Secretary for Northern Ireland, said of the Sinn Fein
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The new ministers, chosen in keeping with the strength shown by
their parties in the June 1998 election of the assembly's 108
members, reflected the Protestant-Catholic division of authority
that is the hallmark of the new government. The voting rules for
the assembly require the support of both Protestant and Catholic
communities for decisions to be approved.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrating the enormity of the challenge facing the North's
politicians in converting their angry disputes into civil ones and
cohabiting the same political institutions was the naming of Martin
McGuinness, Sinn Fein's chief negotiator and a past IRA commander,
to the same cabinet that includes Nigel Dodds, a member of the
hardline Democratic Unionist Party who was the target of an IRA
assassination attack three years ago in the corridors of a Belfast
hospital where he had gone to visit his sick son.
</P>
<P>
   Dodds and the deputy leader of his party, Peter Robinson, who
also gained a cabinet seat, are opponents of the April 1998 peace
agreement that created the legislature. In accepting their posts
Monday night, they vowed ``every ounce of our power and influence
to frustrate and thwart Northern Ireland being pulled into a united
Ireland.'' Unionists favor keeping Ulster British while republicans
and nationalists want to see it eventually incorporated into the
Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Paisley Jr., the son of the leader of the Democratic
Unionist party and a member of the assembly, said, ``We will not be
sharing power and making collective decisions or indeed, coming to
a collective policy with gunmen or their representatives who will
be in this government.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, the preacher-politician who is a lifelong foe of
sharing power with Catholics, delayed proceedings for nearly three
hours with a series of motions, objections and adjournment
recommendations aimed at excluding Sinn Fein from the body and at
denying Seamus Mallon of the moderate Catholic Social Democratic
and Labor Party the right to take up his position as deputy to the
legislature's first minister, David Trimble of the Protestant
Ulster Unionists.
</P>
<P>
   Mallon had resigned that position in anger last July when the
Ulster Unionists torpedoed an earlier attempt at naming the
ministers to the assembly. An 11-week rescue mission by former U.S.
Sen. George Mitchell succeeded in ending the stalemate standing in
the way of Monday's action and persuading Mallon to rescind his
resignation. The assembly Monday night turned aside Paisley's
blocking motion by a 71-28 vote.
</P>
<P>
   The mood was understated for such an important event in the
troubled history of Northern Ireland. Most of the exchanges were
about procedural matters, phrased in the formal language of
legislative rules. The members of Paisley's party threw out
combative asides, and there was hissing from the public balcony at
the mention of the Sinn Fein nominations, prompting Lord Alderdice,
the presiding officer, to threaten to clear the gallery. The Sinn
Fein speakers all introduced their comments with words of greeting
in Gaelic.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's development followed a vote by the Ulster Unionist
party on Saturday to abandon its insistence on IRA disarmament
before entering government with Sinn Fein. Trimble secured the
support of 58 percent of the party's ruling council by promising to
reconvene in February to test the Sinn Fein commitment to
nonviolence by seeing if there had been adequate turnover of IRA
weapons by then. If not, he said, he and his colleagues in the
assembly leadership would resign their positions, thereby bringing
the legislature to an end.
</P>
<P>
   McGuinness complained that the added condition departed from the
Mitchell review's conclusion that disarmament must be voluntary. He
argued that the new pressure tactic and the implied deadline would
make the job of getting the IRA to abandon its arms more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The new cabinet draws its occupants from four parties.
</P>
<P>
   In two days the British parliament is to pass legislation
transferring home rule authority from London to Belfast. Thursday
sees the first meeting of the fully empowered Northern Ireland
Assembly. On that same day, an IRA official will be appointed as a
representative to the commission charged with disarming Northern
Ireland's paramilitary forces by next May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
