<SLUG> BC-FREE-PC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MORE GIVEAWAY COMPUTERS AS FREE-PC'STO BE BOUGHT BY E-MACHINES 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As it turns out, there is no such thing as a free PC.
</P>
<P>
   Free-PC.Com, one of the most audacious experiments in
advertising, said Monday it would no longer give away free
computers and Internet access. Rather it has agreed to be acquired
by eMachines, a maker of low-cost personal computers that intends
to use Free-PC's software to put advertising on the screens of its
computers and to collect data about what users do.
</P>
<P>
   Free-PC's original business plan was to give away computers in
exchange for being allowed to target on-screen ads to its users and
to gather data about users' Internet surfing and PC usage habits.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed. Both Free-PC and eMachines
are private, although eMachines has filed for a public offering
that it hopes to complete early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The sale reflects a sharp turn around for Bill Gross, the
chairman of IdeaLab, a Pasadena, Calif., company that has launched
dozens of Internet start-ups, including eToys, Goto.Com and
Ticketmaster-Citysearch, as well as Free-PC.
</P>
<P>
   Gross, a peripatetic entrepreneur, once boasted that Free-PC
would someday be bigger than Microsoft, according to people he had
tried to recruit as investors. His idea was to turn the computer
from an appliance into an advertising-sponsored medium, much like
network television.
</P>
<P>
   To get a computer from Free-PC, users were to fill out a
detailed financial and demographic survey. Then strips on two sides
of the screen were always filled with advertising. And everything
they did with the computer, including which Internet sites they
used, would be monitored so that advertisers could target ads.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Free-PC needed to take in $30 a month per
user in advertising to cover the cost of providing the computer and
Internet access. That is a high hurdle, particularly with such a
small base of users. More than a million people applied to get the
free PCs, but as of Monday the company had delivered only 30,000
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Gross said that he had not been looking to sell the company, but
that when eMachines approached him he decided that selling would be
more lucrative than a business model that was developing slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believed that to get the business model to work we needed
at least one million users,'' he said. ``We were scaling as fast as
we could, but at 10,000 a quarter, we couldn't get to one million
fast enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In the year since it sold its first computer, eMachines has
become one of the largest PC makers in the country by focusing on
machines in the $400 to $800 price range. Since several Internet
service providers are now offering $400 rebates for people who
commit to three-year contracts, its lowest-cost models appear to be
free. Of course, the user then must typically pay $22 a month for
Internet service. Free PC's Internet service was also free.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen A. Dukker, the founder and chief executive of eMachines,
said the company had no interest in giving away computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business model has caused people like Packard Bell and IBM
to throw in the towel,'' he said, alluding to recent decisions by
those companies to pull out of the low-end PC market.
</P>
<P>
   In October, eMachines was the No. 3 computer maker, after Compaq
Computer and Hewlett-Packard, with 12.4 percent of the market,
according to PC Data.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, eMachines figured that the market for computers
would come to resemble wireless telephones, where the phone is
typically given away and subsidized by the monthly fees. But in
recent months, it shifted its strategy to focus more on
opportunities to use computers as an advertising medium. Already,
it charges advertisers to put icons on the computer desktop or even
buttons on the keyboard that link to a certain Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Now, eMachines will use the Free-PC software to place
advertising on users' screens as well.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising will take up less screen space than it does the
Free-PC computers, and unlike with Free-PC, users will have the
option to not see the advertising. However, eMachines hopes that
they will keep the ads in place, however, by linking them to a
``tool bar'' with buttons that will make it easy for new users to
navigate the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   This software, moreover, will send data about the computer users
back to eMachines to use for advertising selection. The company
declined to say what data would be collected but said that at first
it would be less than Free-PC had gathered. Ultimately, however,
the company says it hopes to persuade at least some of its users to
allow their activities to be monitored.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even if the user does not agree to have any data
collected or any advertising on the screen, eMachines will still be
able to profit. Whenever the user connects to the Internet, its
software will still be able to place new advertising icons on the
desktop or to change the advertiser linked to each keyboard button.
</P>
<P>
   The company is largely controlled by two Korean electronics
makers, the TriGem Corp. and Korea Data Systems. In the first half
of the year, it lost $3.9 million on sales of $351 million. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
