<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOOR-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGNS ARE TAKING TO THE STREETS TO RAISE AWARENESS OF
PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The battle among advertisers for eyeballs is not
limited to the Internet. There is still warfare being waged street
by street as more marketers _ including dozens of dot-coms _ turn
to outdoor advertising to increase awareness of their products and
services.
</P>
<P>
   The growing popularity of the outdoor medium, particularly in
urban centers where consumers are concentrated, is underscored by
two ad blitzes scheduled to begin Wednesday. One is for
Powerstreet, the new brand for the online brokerage services of
Fidelity Investments, and the other is for Moe Ginsburg, the
venerable apparel retailer. Both are spending extensively in the
next four to eight weeks to blanket cityscapes from subway
platforms to telephone kiosks to bus shelters with pitches meant
for mass consumption.
</P>
<P>
   In both instances, the goal is to cut through the clamorous
clutter that bewitches, bothers and bewilders passers-by on crowded
streets. But those who recall the Yogi Berra-ism about nobody going
to a popular restaurant anymore because it's too crowded may wonder
whether nobody will see the signs because there are so many of
them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I would agree that it's getting a little cluttered,'' said
Steve Cone, president for corporate and retail marketing at
Fidelity in Boston. ``On the other hand, I've never seen Times
Square busier, and Broadway is rocking and rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We created Powerstreet to remind people that we are a major
player in the online brokerage business,'' he added, and the
``broad reach'' that outdoor ads provide ``is a critical part of an
integrated media plan.'' His reference was to the television, radio
and print campaign for Powerstreet _ formally known as Powerstreet
Online Trading at Fidelity.com _ that continues as the outdoor
advertising arrives in Boston, New York and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want the wallpaper effect,'' said Rob Hofferman,
vice president and account director at Korey Kay &AMP; Partners in New
York, the Ginsburg agency. ``You want something that could generate
not only visibility but also impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Korey Kay has arranged with Outdoor Systems, which sells ad
space for the Metropolitan Transportation Authority, to replace all
the signs on the uptown and downtown sides of the N and R subway
station at 23rd Street and Broadway in Manhattan with Ginsburg
displays.
</P>
<P>
   The ``brand station,'' as it is called, is intended to
complement the ``brand trains'' sold by Outdoor Systems, limiting
ads in subway cars to one or two advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clutter is an issue,'' said Sheri Baron, president of Gotham
Inc. in New York, the Powerstreet agency, ``but what this is about
is presence and dominance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In locations where people are out and about,'' she added,
``there's no better way to own `share of mind' than this use of
outdoor.''
</P>
<P>
   Gotham, part of the Interpublic Group of Cos., plans to
virtually cover the five boroughs of New York by peddling
Powerstreet with pithy posters on 6,000 displays owned by TDI
Worldwide. The signs are to be posted on buses, phone kiosks,
commuter rail stations and walls. They will carry headlines like
``Ask New Yorkers for personal info, and they'll tell you where to
go'' and ``New Yorkers take everything personally. Why not online
trading?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's New York bravado,'' Don Allman, president at TDI, said,
laughing, ``New York as the center of the universe.'' There will be
similar displays, though not Big Apple-centric, on TDI ad space in
Boston and at the Embarcadero station of Bay Area Rapid Transit in
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The New York portion of the campaign is ``the largest
concentration in one market we've ever done,'' said Allman, whose
company is the outdoor advertising unit of Infinity Broadcasting,
majority owned by the CBS Corp. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some degree it's akin to a television roadblock,'' he
added, using the term for a commercial that runs at the same time
on numerous networks or stations so viewers perceive it to be
inescapable. ``In a word, it's going to be awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's also going to be, in three words, ``the most
expensive'' campaign TDI has ever sold to a single advertiser in a
single market, Allman said.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity is estimated to be paying $2.5 million for ad space
valued at about $5.5 million. The discount is part of a deal
Fidelity signed under a program named CBS Plus that packages
sponsorships among CBS media outlets. The total budget for the
Powerstreet introduction is estimated at $50 million to $60
million.
</P>
<P>
   The budget for the brand station was estimated at $20,000 by
Harve Ganz, manager for New York transit at Outdoor Systems, which
is coincidentally being acquired by Infinity.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, people have asked about buying a whole
station, so this is an experiment,'' Ganz said. ``The brand train
was slow to take off, but once people started seeing it, it caught
fire.'' Brand train advertisers include the Bronx Zoo, Kenneth
Cole, New York University, Procter &AMP; Gamble and Seagram. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the Ginsburg station, which a half million people are
estimated to use each month, ``it would be a lot cheaper and easier
to run the same ad or two over and over,'' Hofferman said. ``But to
keep people involved and engaged, we're going to run every ad we've
done'' since landing the account in September.
</P>
<P>
   That amounts to 12 to 14 ads, which carry cheeky headlines like
``You didn't spend two years at Wharton to get noticed for the
latest trend in pleats'' (for the retailer's traditionally styled
suits) and ``You're too sexy for glen plaid, too sexy for two
buttons, too sexy to blend in'' (for designer suits).
</P>
<P>
   Consumers concerned about ad clutter outdoors may want to hide
indoors for the next month, especially if they traverse Times
Square. To capitalize on the throngs expected to celebrate the
arrival of 2000, gathering in front of sites including 1 Times
Square and 2 Times Square _ where ad space is sold by Sherwood
Outdoor _ marketers are rushing to affix additional signs to
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Among the newcomers to Times Square are De Beers, JVC and the
World Wrestling Federation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
