<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW OFF 40.99 ON WORRIES ABOUT FAST PACE OF ECONOMY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Worries that the economy is showing few signs of
slowing despite the efforts of the Federal Reserve swept through
the bond market Monday, pushing interest rates sharply higher.
Stock prices, which have been on a torrid run, fell in sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Important reports on the economy are expected later this week,
including November employment data on Friday. But as bond traders
returned to work after the Thanksgiving weekend Monday, anecdotal
evidence of a strong start to the Christmas shopping season was a
fresh source of concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the early reports on Christmas have been gangbusters,''
said Donald J. Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset
Management. ``There is scant information the economy is slowing
down, and the bond market is getting really nervous about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Selling began in the morning and continued throughout the
session. By late in the day, the price of the benchmark 30-year
Treasury bond had fallen 31/32, to 97 19/32. The bond's yield,
which moves in the opposite direction from the price, rose to 6.30
percent, from 6.23 percent on Friday. It was the worst one-day
performance for the bond market in seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Led by interest-rate sensitive financial service issues, stock
prices moved lower. Technology shares, which have jumped sharply
this month, moved higher early in the session, but faltered later.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year the market has been dominated by technology, and
people are willing now to lock in some gains and get defensive
going in to Y2K,'' said Thomas M. Galvin, chief investment
strategist at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. ``The unfriendly bond
market gave an excuse for investors to take profits.''
</P>
<P>
   At the close, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 40.99
points, or 0.37 percent, to 10,947.92. American Express, General
Electric and J.P. Morgan were big contributors to the decline.
</P>
<P>
   Among broader averages, the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500
stocks fell 8.79 points, or 0.62 percent, to 1,407.83. The Nasdaq
composite index dropped 26.44 points, or 0.77 percent, to 3,421.37.
Nextel, Qualcomm and Intuit were among the biggest losers.
</P>
<P>
   Small company stocks also fared poorly. The Russell 2000 index
slipped 1.99 points, or 0.43 percent, to 456.95.
</P>
<P>
   Robert E. Turner, chairman and chief investment officer at
Turner Investment Partners Inc. with $4 billion under management,
said the slight decline in technology shares could prove
transitory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credit Suisse First Boston is sponsoring a technology
conference this week, and I have to believe that many of these
stocks will benefit from that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pretty optimistic about tech stocks from here on out. For
the most part, fourth quarter earnings, which we won't see for
another 45 days or so, are going to be pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Among financial stocks, General Electric, whose GE Capital
subsidiary is the largest nonbank finance company, fell 2{, to
133[. American Express fell 4 13/16 to 147 13/16. J.P. Morgan
dropped 2 1/16 to 131{. Bank of America, a component of the S&AMP;P
500, fell 3 9/16, to 56 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Among technology stocks, Intel fell 2 13/16, to 78 11/16 after
Advanced Micro Devices, its biggest rival in the microprocessor
market, announced a new chip that it contends is faster than
Intel's most advanced design. Shares of Advanced Micro gained 1
9/16, to 29\.
</P>
<P>
   Investors took profits in Qualcomm. The stock fell 13 13/16, to
371 3/16. Since Nov. 17, Qualcomm stock had risen 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, another good performer recently, fell 2~, to 80
1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Nextel dropped 3, to 90. Intuit shed 7 3/16, to 52 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks were among the day's winners.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson &AMP; Johnson, a Dow component, gained 1~, to 105 5/16.
Pfizer was up 1 7/16, to 37 7/16. Eli Lilly gained 3 1/16, to 75].
Warner-Lambert rose 2], to 91].
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T gained 2 7/16 to 59~, after a Salomon Smith Barney analyst
raised his rating on the telephone company to ``buy'' from
``neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   Early reports about strong holiday sales helped retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Gap gained 2 7/16, to 41]. Best Buy jumped 8} to 66|. Circuit
City rose ], to 50|.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
