<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HOME FOR SCIENCE IN DOWNTOWN COLUMBUS  
 PAN AM STRATEGY: ALTERNATIVE AIRPORTS  
 COVENT GARDEN REOPENS WITH A FLOURISH  
 THE GEORGE V REOPENS, AS A FOUR SEASONS HOTEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Center of Science and Industry in Columbus, Ohio, has moved
to a new home on the banks of the Scioto River after 35 years on
the other side of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The center, which opened Nov. 6 in a fancy new building designed
by Arata Isozaki and incorporating part of a former high school,
has two theaters, two large spaces for temporary exhibitions, a
restaurant and seven permanent exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   One of these seven is the Ocean Learning World, entered through
a simulated shipwreck. Visitors then pass a dive tank 30 feet wide
and 14 feet deep, where a dive show is held, with a discussion of
such things as the effects of pressure and why people go under
water; a diver in scuba gear performs various tasks, including
working with a mechanical arm. Submersible vehicles and other tools
of sea exploration can be operated. Other interactive stations
include fountains and laserlike squirt guns that explore the
physical properties of water.
</P>
<P>
   Progress, another exhibit, allows visitors to walk down the same
street at two different periods in American history. The worlds of
1898 and 1962 come head to head and show technological advances and
how people have responded to innovation.
</P>
<P>
   The other Learning Worlds include I/O, an extensive arcade that
explores the way electronic games have evolved in the last few
decades, and Life, a look at health, medicine and living things on
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The center, at 333 West Broad St., is open daily. The entrance
fee is $12, $16 with admission to one theater, $19 with admission
to both. Children 2 to 12 pay $7, $11 and $14. Information: (877)
257-2674.
</P>
<P>
   PAN AM STRATEGY: ALTERNATIVE AIRPORTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to capture a share of some big markets by flying out of
smaller airports nearby, the newly revamped Pam Am Airlines has
begun flying 727s _ carrying between 25 and 50 passengers daily
except Tuesday _ between Portsmouth, N.H., 66 miles from Boston,
and a little airport north of Orlando, Fla., in Sanford. The fare
advantage is that a traveler can buy a ticket and fly the same day
with no penalty. The typical walk-on round-trip fare is $216, as
opposed to about $975 between Boston and Orlando without the 14
days' notice.
</P>
<P>
   The airline started its second route _ between Sanford and Gary,
Ind., right outside Chicago _ in October. The comparable walk-on
fares are $168 and $1,295. Sanford will be a mini-hub for the
airline, which is looking at starting other flights into St. Louis,
San Juan and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The old Pan Am went into bankruptcy in 1991, and the name was
revived by Guilford Transportation Industries, which dominates the
freight railroad system in New England. To lure Pan Am, the small
Sanford-Orlando International Airport waived landing fees for six
months and persuaded it to move its 15-member maintenance staff
from Fort Lauderdale. The airport is building a new terminal that
is expected to open in June.
</P>
<P>
   Although only 1,000 passengers rode the Boeing 727 on the
Sanford-Portsmouth route in October, the startup month, the airline
was able to boost its income by shipping 16,000 pounds of fresh
Maine lobsters for Florida restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   COVENT GARDEN REOPENS WITH A FLOURISH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Backstage tours, exhibitions and free concerts will be offered
by the Royal Opera House at Covent Garden when it reopens Dec. 6
after a two-and-a-half-year, $360 million renovation, which
included a new 420-seat studio theater, a rooftop terrace and
reconstruction of the cast-iron floral hall.
</P>
<P>
   The new Amphitheater Bar and Restaurant will be open daily from
10 a.m. to 3 p.m., and a coffee shop and Royal Opera House Shop,
both new, will be open from 10 a.m. to 8 p.m. There will be free
lunchtime concerts and other events starting in January.
</P>
<P>
   The 75-minute backstage tours begin Dec. 6, and will be
conducted three times a day from Monday to Saturday. Visitors will
see the costume department, the props and scenery-making area, and
the new wagon system that shifts scenery from storage onto the
stage. There will also be a chance to visit a ballet studio. The
refurbished main auditorium and the new Linbury Studio Theater will
be included on the tour if they are not in use for rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   Tours (limited to 25 people) will take place at 10:30 a.m.,
12:30 p.m. and 3 p.m. and will cost $9.95 ($8.25 under 18 and
seniors). Reservations: (44-171) 212-9389.
</P>
<P>
   THE GEORGE V REOPENS, AS A FOUR SEASONS HOTEL
</P>
<P>
   Upon its opening, in 1928, the George V was hailed as the last
word in opulence. World affairs were conducted at the grand hotel
on the Avenue George V in Paris' 8th Arrondissement (it became an
official branch office of the League of Nations), and during the
liberation of Paris, Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower made it his
headquarters. Yves Saint Laurent, among others, presented his
collections in its grand ballroom. The dining was, even in Paris,
renowned; the vast wine cellar is a former quarry.
</P>
<P>
   Now owned by Prince Al Waleed, a member of the Saudi Arabian
royal family, and officially named Four Seasons Hotel George V,
Paris, it is the first property in France to be managed by the Four
Seasons. The hotel was named for King George V of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Closed for two years for renovation and modernization, the hotel
is scheduled to reopen Dec. 18. Two-line speakerphones come with
every room, as do high-speed Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   For less businesslike pursuits, there are two restaurants and a
bar serving lunch and snacks; the wine cellar can be reserved as
its own dining space. The cuisine is overseen by Philippe Legendre,
the former chef at Taillevent.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation has reduced the number of rooms and suites from
300 to 245, 30 of which come with terraces or balconies with a view
of the Eiffel Tower, the Pantheon and Notre Dame. Original wood
paneling and fireplaces have been kept. Rooms range in size from
420 to 4,000 square feet. The largest is one of two Presidential
Suites, which comes with its own workout room and sauna. The
hotel's health club includes an indoor pool, exercise equipment,
whirlpools and a staff of pamperers.
</P>
<P>
   The George V is an easy walk from the Louvre, the Jardin des
Tuileries and the ``Golden Triangle'' of haute couture shops around
the corner on the Avenue Montaigne.
</P>
<P>
   Double-occupancy rooms start at $535 a night, and one-bedroom
suites at $1,310. The most expensive suites are $7,200 a night.
Hotel George V, 31 ave. George V, 75008 Paris; reservations: (800)
332-3442 in the United States, (33-1) 53.53.28.00 direct to the
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   A CORRECTION
</P>
<P>
   The Practical Traveler column on Nov. 28, about the cost of
travel-package components, misstated the level of lodging used by
Petrabax Vacations in Spain. By the Spanish government rating
system, they are mostly four-star hotels, not two-star.
</P>
</TEXT>
