<HEADLINE>
HOLOCAUST SURVIVORS URGE SPEED IN RESTITUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT13 _ is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Holocaust survivors from around the world implored a
federal judge in Brooklyn on Monday to quickly distribute the
proceeds of a $1.25 billion ettlement between Swiss banks and
Holocaust survivors, and to block lawyers from collecting what the
survivors called exorbitant fees.
</P>
<P>
   Yakov Goodman, president of a group representing Jews from
Belarus, delivered some of the most pointed remarks of a day filled
with the grim memories and anxious pleas of aging Holocaust
survivors who said they had waited a half-century for justice.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman urged Judge Edward R. Korman of Federal District Court
to quickly distribute the settlement money before more Holocaust
survivors died, and criticized the half-dozen lawyers in the case
who are requesting $12.5 million in fees for their work. Two dozen
other lawyers representing Holocaust survivors, their relatives and
Jewish groups are working on the case at no charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those gold rings and gold teeth which were taken from the
Jews were placed here on the table, I don't think any of the
attorneys would reach for them,'' Goodman said. ``Maybe I'm naive,
but that's what these attorneys are reaching for now.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Swift, one of the lawyers requesting payment in the case,
said the criticism was unfair. He said the lawsuit was a tremendous
success and warned that qualified lawyers would not take on similar
cases if they went unpaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the comments I heard about fees were repugnant,''
Swift said. ``We worked extremely hard at great risk to accomplish
a world-class result.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's daylong session was the first of several hearings that
allow public comment on the precedent-setting 1998 settlement, the
first to involve a major European industry paying damages for the
seizure or looting of Holocaust victims' property during World War
II. The settlement has helped spawn a series of similar lawsuits
against European banks, insurance companies and manufacturing
companies accused of profiting from Holocaust victims' looted
assets or from using slave labor.
</P>
<P>
   More than 440,000 people from around the world have applied to
be included in the settlement, which is intended to resolve
thousands of claims that Swiss banks kept the money of Jews and
others killed in the Holocaust. How the money will be divided is
still being disputed. Some survivors contended on Monday that the
money should be paid directly to them and their relatives. But
Jewish groups have called for some of the money to be used to
establish Holocaust studies or religious education programs.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 28, a special master appointed by Korman will release an
initial plan on how to distribute the money, said Burt Neuborne,
the lead lawyer for Holocaust survivors and a professor at New York
University Law School who is working on the case at no charge.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing allowing public comment on that proposal will be held
in May. A final ruling by Korman is scheduled for June. If no
appeals are filed, the distribution of the money will begin next
summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
