<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A $42.5 BILLION ROYAL BANK COUNTEROFFER FOR NATWEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Royal Bank of Scotland announced a $42.5 billion
hostile bid Monday for National Westminster Bank, Britain's third
largest, touching off a potentially bruising bidding war.
</P>
<P>
   The move, which had been expected, pitted the Royal Bank against
its crosstown rival in Edinburgh, the Bank of Scotland, which has
made two of its own bids for Natwest, both of them rebuffed. The
Royal Bank's bid underlines the pressure on European financial
institutions to bulk up or risk being left on the sideline as
marginal competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The hostile bid Monday sets the stage for a brawl that is likely
to further shake the staid culture of the City of London, Britain's
financial center.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Royal Bank's bid is so close to that of the Bank of
Scotland _ it had offered $41.3 billion _ that analysts said the
battle to persuade shareholders would be less about arithmetic and
more about the management teams that run the two Scottish
institutions. They suggested that the battle could easily turn
nasty as both banks consider personal attacks on each other and
plead with shareholders to avoid being left out of the takeover
attempt, the largest in British banking.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Bank's bid values Natwest at 15.90 pounds a share _ in
all 26.5 billion pounds, or $42.54 billion, $1.24 billion more than
Bank of Scotland's offer.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Bank is offering 0.968 share and a 3.05 pound note for
each share of Natwest stock. The Bank of Scotland's recently
increased bid is for 14.57 pounds a share and a special dividend
that could be worth 1.20 pounds a share.
</P>
<P>
   The unsolicited offer by the Royal Bank came 24 hours after a
long negotiating session with Natwest, aimed at brokering a
friendly merger, had broken down.
</P>
<P>
   After dismissing the Royal Bank's informal offer over the
weekend, Natwest withheld judgment on the new bid until late Monday
afternoon, when its board rejected the offer as ``inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Scotland also started its assault on the Royal
Bank's bid, calling it ``inferior,'' and taunted its rival by
saying that its counteroffer came after ``months of
procrastination.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and stock traders, who had higher expectations for the
offer, sent shares of Royal Bank down 87 pence, to 12.41 pounds.
That cut the value of the offer by 4.9 percent, to 25.1 billion
pounds, or $40.3 billion. But the Bank of Scotland got a lift from
investors, who sent its shares up 4.5 pence, to 7.285 pounds, on
expectations that it might prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is saying that Royal Bank is paying too much,''
said John Tyce, an analyst at SG Securities here. ``I certainly
thought Royal Bank would win, but now I'm not so sure.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was shared by institutional investors, which were
also surprised by the Royal Bank's offer. The Royal Bank's bid
``doesn't give it much room to fiddle about,'' Tyce said, echoing
the thoughts of several institutional investors. ``For Royal Bank
to make this happen, it has to go like clockwork. It has to be
perfect; otherwise it'll be a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Bank said it could squeeze 1.18 billion pounds in
annual savings from a combined company, more than the Bank of
Scotland's pledge to cut costs by 1.02 billion pounds. Royal Bank
said it would not close any branches but would eliminate 18,000
jobs. Natwest has said it will cut 15,000 jobs by 2002 as part of
its defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Bank also said it would sell Natwest's fund management
unit, Gartmore Investment Management, and its investment banking
unit, Greenwich Natwest. The Bank of Scotland said it would also
sell Natwest's venture capital unit, Natwest Equity Partners, and
Ulster Bank in Ireland. Natwest has said it would dispose of all
those assets as part of its defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Bank would still need regulatory approval to move
forward with a bid. Britain's panel on takeovers has until Dec. 6
to decide whether Royal Bank's offer should be referred to the
Competition Commission. Last Thursday, the panel ruled that the
Bank of Scotland's bid would not be referred to the commission.
</P>
<P>
   To finance its bid, the Royal Bank has enlisted the support of
Banco Santander Central Hispano and the Royal Bank's largest
investor. The Spanish bank said Monday that it would buy 1.2
billion pounds of Royal Bank shares. The agreement would give
Santander a 6.5 percent stake in a combined company. A British
insurer, CGU PLC, said it would buy 300 million pounds of Royal
Bank shares and acquire a 50 percent stake in the Royal Bank's life
insurance unit, Royal Scottish Assurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
