<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-NGO-SPI </SLUG>
  
 AFTER SECURITY SCARE, WTO GETS AN EARFUL FROM NGO'S
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE   
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ While anti-WTO activists took to Seattle's streets
Monday, members of the trade orgainzation held a unique complaint
session inside the besieged convention center.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some quarters, the WTO has become the institution that
people love to hate,'' British Development Minister Clare Short
told a symposium at which environmental, labor and other
organizations were allowed to voice concerns about world trade
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this criticism is misplaced,'' she said in her
keynote speech to representatives of so-called non-governmental
oganizations, or NGOs.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the symposium was to encourage an informal
dialogue between members of the five-year-old World Trade
organization, which sets the rules for world trade, and the more
than 700 non-governmental organizations that have been accredited
to the WTO ministerial conference in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend the Geneva-based WTO places global trade
liberalization above other legitimate interests such as human and
worker rights and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Short, those who spoke included Mike Moore, the
WTO's new director general, Pascal Lamy, the European Commission's
commissioner for trade, and U.S. Trade Representative Charlene
Barshefsky.
</P>
<P>
   They got an earful of criticism once the session was opened to
three-minute comments from representatives of the many
non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Khor of the Third World Network, based in Penang,
Malaysia, called the program ``less of a dialog and more of a
lecture.''
</P>
<P>
   He said numerous groups have decided they want no new round of
issues _ not investor rights, procurement, competition, biotech,
environment or labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``These would put the developing countries to further
disadvantage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The rich countries have broken their promises to gradually open
their market to textiles and to reform their anti-dumping laws,
Khor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one is not willing to do these things, one does not have
the right to portray one's proposals as a `development round.'''
Khor said. ``It is a fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Maude Barlow of the Council of Canadians, a nationalist group,
also said the NGO Day had been ``you speaking and us listening.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the Canadian government had given out a list of private
sector news sources on WTO issues, and that they were all employer
confederations or wealthy men. ``They didn't give any of our
names,'' she said. ``We were not welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she would express her opinions Tuesday, in the street.
</P>
<P>
   There was no clear theme to the voice of protest inside the
convention center.
</P>
<P>
   Some called for sweeping changes of the WTO and its trade
policies; others were more measured in their criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The symposium got off to a slow start when Seattle police shut
down the convention center because of security concerns. It was not
opened until about 10:30 a.m., which delayed by a couple hours the
start of the symposium.
</P>
<P>
   Those attending had to pass through metal detectors and at one
point a parade of protestors that included the Sierra Club, members
of labor unions and animal rights activists.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, the WTO director general, said he hoped the protests
would not overshadow the WTO's good work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am told there could be up to 50,000 demonstrators against
us,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But remember: In over 30 countries, 1.5 billion want to join
the WTO,'' he said, referring to the 30 nations including China
that have WTO membership applications pending.
</P>
<P>
   He said the WTO will listen to its critics. Economic growth that
has resulted from free trade policies, he acknowledged, has caused
``pain and problems'' for many people around the world.
</P>
<P>
   He said ``freedom fighters'' of the past of now protersting the
WTO in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we goign to tell hem the old ways are best?''
</P>
<P>
   He said the WTO was in Seattle to ``open the door to working
families everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   In her keynote speech, Short said liberalized trade will benefit
developing countrues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the WTO and its rules, the rich and powerful could
bully the rest as they used to,'' she said. ``Let's face it, no
rules is when the rich and powerful do bully the poor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 2225EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
