<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4555 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     11-29 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV19-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., DEC. 19, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I find it difficult to sand ornamental or carved moldings
because there are often grooves and narrow spaces that sandpaper
won't reach into or around, even when the paper is folded into
narrow strips.
</P>
<P>
   I have tried using steel wool, but this still doesn't always
conform to the shape and can often leave a residue of fine metal
shavings that is almost impossible to clean off _ which is
important if I am preparing it for a clear varnish or lacquer
finish.
</P>
<P>
   Is there an easier way to sand and smooth such curved or carved
surfaces?
</P>
<P>
   A: The most common method for sanding and smoothing such
surfaces is to use a sanding sponge. This is a small sponge covered
with fabric-backed sandpaper on all sides. The sponge can be
squeezed into various shapes and thus permits sanding inside curves
and grooves or rounded edges.
</P>
<P>
   If you do not have a sanding sponge, or you find that even this
won't reach into some places, then an alternate method is to use a
deck of cards with a sheet of sandpaper folded around the edge as
shown here. The edges of the cards can be forced into almost any
curve or shape to reach into grooves and nooks.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We recently bought a house that has moss growing on one side
of the roof. Should we remove this moss and, if so, how do we do
this?
</P>
<P>
   A: You should remove the moss as it can eventually damage the
shingles.
</P>
<P>
   There are chemical products sold in some home centers and garden
supply stores for getting rid of moss (one widely sold brand is
De-Moss), or you can use a copper sulfate solution (one-half ounce
to 10 gallons of water).
</P>
<P>
   Scrub on, then wash off the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Bear in mind that these chemicals can damage metal and some
shrubbery, so be careful about the runoff and flush away all
drippings with plenty of water.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We want to remove some very old linoleum that was put down
over a solid hardwood floor years ago. Can you tell us how to do
this without damaging the wood flooring?
</P>
<P>
   A: Linoleum has not been made or used in this country for many
years, but if the material is real linoleum (not some type of
vinyl, which seems more likely) then a linoleum paste was probably
used to put it down.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of paste can be softened with hot water. However, if
this doesn't work, then scraping will be your only solution.
</P>
<P>
   A heat gun will usually help soften the flooring material and
thus will make it easier to pull up, but be careful to avoid
scorching the wood or starting a fire, and keep an extinguisher
handy _ just in case.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our bathtub has a lever on the overflow plate near the top of
the tub to open and close the drain.
</P>
<P>
   We flip it up to close the drain and push down to open it. There
is no stopper or drain cover visible.
</P>
<P>
   The drain leaks and allows water to drain out even when the
lever is pulled all the way up.
</P>
<P>
   How can I fix this without calling in a plumber?
</P>
<P>
   A: This type of drain stopper usually has a brass plug on the
inside which drops down onto an internal seat to seal off the drain
when it is lowered.
</P>
<P>
   However, when this drain plug accumulates a build-up of
oxidation, or an accumulation of soap and hair or lint, then the
stopper will not seat properly. You have to clean the linkage and
the brass stopper at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Start by removing the screws that hold the overflow plate and
its lever in place, then carefully pull out the linkage which has
the brass stopper attached at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these may have lock nuts for adjusting the length, so
first see if these have loosened or need realigning.
</P>
<P>
   Then clean all parts with fine steel wool and wipe on a light
coat of waterproof grease before reassembling the linkage.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``USING DECK OF CARDS TO SAND MOLDING''
goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Sandpaper wrapped around edge of a deck of cards can be
molded or shaped to conform to the shape of the molding.
</P>
