<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-POWERFUL-CROWS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Something to crow about: A big flock flies and power dies
 &HT;    By Thomas R. Collins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKEECHOBEE, Fla. _ A flock of startled crows caused a freak
mishap that left nearly 2,000 central Florida homes without power
for much of the day Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,961 homes lost power when a flock of crows in western
Okeechobee County flew away en masse, causing the 1,500-foot-long
ground wire they were sitting on _ and bending _ to snap upward
like a giant bow string, strike a live wire, and short out.
</P>
<P>
   When workers arrived, wires were wrapped around each other.
About 700 of the homes in the area got power back shortly after the
8 a.m. incident, but the rest didn't until 6 p.m., said Ed Henne,
Florida Power &AMP; Light's Treasure Coast area operations manager.
</P>
<P>
   His company is used to problems caused by all kinds of wildlife,
but the crow problem is a new one, said Henne, a 36-year veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say it's unique,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The birds couldn't have found a more delicate spot to land,
Henne said. The long wires extend over the Kissimmee River and,
under an environmental permit, the poles they connect to have to be
110-feet tall, he said. So fixing the problem was serious business,
complete with a 142-foot crane, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've assembled a 10-man crew. There's a lot of rigging to fix
that wire.''
</P>
<P>
   Utility officials never would have known how the outage happened
if it weren't for a fisherman casting a line off the State Road 70
Kissimmee River bridge, who told workers about the crows, Henne
said.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, animals cause problems only by actually touching the
electric generators, not indirectly as in the crow incident, Henne
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish they'd quit but I guess we should thank our lucky stars
that we don't have those pterodactyls that they had flying around a
million years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Collins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: thomascollins(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
