<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4594 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     11-29 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE ONLY PLAYOFF TEAM ON HOFSTRA'S CAMPUS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The only playoff coach at Hofstra University
on Monday couldn't say enough about his football team. How it had
not given up when it was 10 points behind last weekend, how it
refused to surrender to tragedy a month ago or earlier this season
when its star running back went down for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' Joe Gardi said with all due sympathy for the
other coach on campus, ``we didn't lose our starting quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinny Testaverde didn't survive one game this season, but
Hofstra's Giovanni Carmazzi threw for 258 yards against Lehigh last
Saturday in the Division I-AA playoffs. That is why Gardi was
formulating his game plan Monday for his next round, while Bill
Parcells was nearby, making his Jets' postseason concession speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``By and large, they've hung in there,'' Parcells said on the
morning people awoke from a fantasy that starred Ray Lucas as
Dorothy and Parcells as the Wizard. ``But now we're in a little
different situation. I'll try my best to keep 'em going.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant along the road to nowhere, which the Jets and Giants
will start walking together Sunday at Giants Stadium. You want
football playoffs? Hofstra plays host to Illinois State in the I-AA
quarterfinals on Saturday, while over in New Jersey, Montclair
State faces Rowan in the quarters of Division III.
</P>
<P>
   The serious portion of our local pro football season is over,
miracles and mathematics be damned. After the Jets' run last year,
after the Knicks, after the Yankees and the Mets, I think we may
all ultimately benefit from one sports season devoid of provincial
hype.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells knew the score on his offense weeks ago, but played
along with the pipe dream to keep his players frothing through
their face guards. The Jets played competitively, commendably,
Sunday in Indianapolis, but reality was a fourth-and-19 Lucas
aerial to Oz, through the hands of Wayne Chrebet, sure-handed 1995
graduate of Gardi's program.
</P>
<P>
   Delving deeper inside this little family circle, Gardi is also a
Jets alumnus. From 1976 through 1984, the Harrison, N.J., native
served three Jets coaches in various assistant's roles. Next came
five years in the National Football League office as an assistant
supervisor of officials, and then he just tired of being an
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   As the head man at Hofstra, he has won 81, lost 28, tied 2, but
has not ridden down Hempstead Turnpike in a championship parade.
His first year at Hofstra, then a Division III program, Gardi
reached the third round of the playoffs. His quarterback got hurt.
He hasn't been that close again, which carries us back across
campus to Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   The general excellence of the Jets' defense suddenly makes it
easier to wonder where they would now stand if not for Parcells'
blunder of starting the season without a capable backup
quarterback. Could they have reversed two of those early defeats?
Three? In a league of shifting power, of no sure things, who can
say they could not have won a Super Bowl without Testaverde?
Another Parcells team did exactly that, winning with a backup
quarterback, at the start of this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, things change so much in the off-season, the makeup
of your team,'' Parcells said, when asked if he was now hoping to
establish momentum for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, he was saying that the increasingly transient pro
game is not all that different from the college game. Which is why
Gardi said he would take the opportunity to hang in the locker room
the colorful poster he pulled from a pile in his office. It
featured a championship trophy with this inscription: The Flying
Dutchmen: We Want the Ring.
</P>
<P>
   Making the playoffs seemed questionable when Vaughn Sanders went
down early last fall, 7 yards shy of the school rushing record.
Another backfield starter was lost. A senior offensive lineman. A
month ago, the starting offensive tackle John Ciampi died suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been difficult, but we've held together,'' Gardi said.
``It helps to have these playoff games. Everywhere on campus,
people are excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost everywhere. To drop in on the Jets, Gardi must cross
Hemsptead Turnpike, after leaving Margiotta Hall, next door to the
15,000-seat football stadium. In the pre-Parcells days, he visited
often, but hasn't bothered since last season, when a security guard
treated him like a spy from New England or Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway,'' he said, ``I don't want to go over there and have
people say, `He still thinks he's coaching the Jets.'''
</P>
<P>
   He'll stay on his side of the road, where the only playoffs are.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
