<SLUG> BC-WTO-BOVE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOSE BOVA GETS THE STAR TREATMENT IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT L. JAMIESON JR.  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Walking through the streets of downtown Seattle
Monday, Jose Bove got the type of treatment usually reserved for
rock stars on tour: cameras flashed, hands jockeyed to tug his
leather jacket and young women shrieked ``Jose! Jose! Jose!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a farmer,'' Bove whispered softly, shrugging as he
cut through a throng of supporters that included people wearing
black hoods, businessmen in elegant suits and folks costumed like
sea turtles.
</P>
<P>
   But the 46-year-old sheep farmer from the south of France, who
sports a handlebar mustache and carries a tobacco pipe, is a
national hero in his homeland for having taken a big stand against
a food Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   And judging by Monday's public reaction, Bove's potential for
folk hero-dom on this side of the Atlantic _ at least during this
week's World Trade Organization gathering _ is red hot.
</P>
<P>
   Bove was arrested this summer for vandalizing a McDonald's
restaurant under construction in Millau to protest U.S.-imposed
tariffs on Roquefort cheese and other products. The WTO had
authorized the tariffs in retaliation for the European Union's
refusal to import hormone-treated beef.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rocquefort was taken hostage by hormone-treated beef,'' Bove
explained Monday as he made his way to a downtown McDonald's for a
rally to criticize the chain he says symbolizes the reach of
multi-national, industrial food concerns.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's hurts small farmers worldwide, he believes, and
spreads ``mal bouffe'' _ French for ``bad eats.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bove also sounded off against Monsanto and large companies
that create genetically modified foods _ known as GM foods or
``Frankenfoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Bove hoped the 2 p.m. rally would unfold without a violent
hitch, as press from all corners of the world cataloged his every
breath.
</P>
<P>
   He had to work hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Push back, push back,'' he told the crowd of more than 500,
urging the masses to step a few feet away from the fastfood
restaurant where a large, homemade sign urged people to ``Resist
McDonaldization.''
</P>
<P>
   The rally had one lone flashpoint: a few anxious seconds in
which a window was shattered and someone tagged the building with
obscenity-laced graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   Managers temporarily closed the eatery, locking uniformed
restaurant workers inside as people outside banged drums, cheered
and _ in one case _ deposited an uneaten hamburger at the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   A restaurant manager said no customers or workers were injured.
No one was sure exactly how the glass was shattered, a McDonald's
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   During his brief speech, Bove stood before a blue picnic
blanket, spread in front of the McDonald's, adorned with three lit
candles, French bread, American cheddar cheese, Gabriel Court
Roquefort, grapes and bottles of French wine _ Cabernet Sauvignon,
vintage 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Lambasting fast food, Bove said: ``People don't want this kind
of food ... the food of WTO. They want safe food.''
</P>
<P>
   Several minutes later Bove, trailed by dozens of pushing,
shoving, anxious newspeople with cameras _ clambered to the roof of
a white van parked in the middle of an intersection.
</P>
<P>
   He was joined by farm representives from the United States and
India who voiced support of Bove's criticisms of the globalization
of agriculture, which they said WTO policies encourage.
</P>
<P>
   One of the van-top speakers, Prof. Nanjunda Swamy of India, drew
thunderous applause when he mentioned India's successful efforts to
keep fast food chains out of his country.
</P>
<P>
   Another speaker, Bill Christison, president of the National
Family Farm Coalition, said global agriculture was ``killing'' the
small farmer worldwide. ``Corporate food is bad food,'' he said
later in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to early media characterizations, Bove said he is not
anti-American. He said French farmers and American farmers share
similar concerns. ``We are in this together,'' he said, noting that
global trade waters down cultural diversity and lowers quality.
</P>
<P>
   For Bove, who looks like a college chemistry professor, Monday
was deja vu. In August, he organized the vandalization of the
McDonald's in France because the tariffs were hurting farmers like
himself who sell sheep's milk to make Roquefort cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Bove faces state criminal charges next year in a French court;
McDonald's decided against filing for civil action in part because
they did not want to make him a martyr.
</P>
<P>
   Before drifting off to an interview with a stand-up comedian and
satirist for British television yesterday, Bove laughed at a
suggestion he would have a Big Mac for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way!'' he said emphatically.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's, however, did prove handy. Protestors asked for
plastic knives to cut the French bread and spread the cheese.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
