<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IRAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: IRAN JAILS A CRITIC  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, Nov. 30:
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah Nouri, one of Iran's most popular and courageous
political reformers, has been unjustly sentenced to five years in
prison and banned from running for office until 2004. His alleged
crime consisted of publishing newspaper articles critical of
official Iranian policies. That such a harsh sentence could be
imposed for exercising basic journalistic freedoms is a measure of
how fearful and out of touch Iran's ruling conservative clerics
have become in the face of popular demands for greater democracy
and individual liberty.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure for change is likely to be the main theme of
crucial parliamentary elections to be held in February. Until his
sentencing last Saturday, Nouri was to lead the ticket of
candidates pledged to support the reformist policies of President
Mohammad Khatami. Iran's Islamic Constitution gives clerical
conservatives ultimate control over policy and the courts. But
Khatami, who won election two and a half years ago with an
overwhelming 70 percent of the votes, has challenged their power. A
reform victory in February could let him go further. Khatami's
support is particularly strong among young people, who make up a
large and growing share of the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Nouri is an Islamic cleric once known for his support of
revolutionary fundamentalism. But in recent years he has come to
understand that Iran's revolution will only survive if it adapts
itself to popular yearnings. First as the most liberal member of
Khatami's cabinet, and later through the pages of his newspaper,
Khordad, Nouri became a fearless champion of open political debate,
improved relations with America and acceptance of Palestinian peace
talks with Israel. He also denounced as illegitimate the immense
power wielded by unelected clerics.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred by the prospect of severe punishment, Nouri
skillfully used his trial to broadcast these views to the larger
Iranian public. His words proved so eloquent that prosecutors
abruptly cut short the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Now reformers must continue their parliamentary election
campaign without Nouri, who was a top vote-getter in municipal
elections earlier this year. His forced exclusion from politics
follows last year's imprisonment of another leading reformer,
Gholamhossein Karbaschi, the mayor of Tehran. If Khatami and his
reform allies can overcome the handicap of these exclusions and win
a parliamentary majority, they may be able to diminish some
clerical powers.
</P>
<P>
   With control of military and internal security forces,
conservative clerics can for now stifle the aspirations of
Iranians. But with nearly two-thirds of the population of 70
million under the age of 25, the clerics will face mounting
opposition if they fail to understand the demand for
liberalization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 2249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0473 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-RADIO-CITY-NYT &LR;      11-29 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-RADIO-CITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKETTES MOVING OVER FOR JONES TO TAKE THE STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The chocolate-dipped strawberries were large and
luscious. The champagne was perfectly chilled. The string quartet
was melodiously soothing. Boxing was the only thing that seemed out
of place at Radio City Music Hall Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Jones Jr., the undisputed light-heavyweight champion, and
David Telesco descended the spiraling staircase into the Art Deco
lobby, both with a Rockette on each arm, to announce that they will
meet at Radio City Music Hall in a 12-round title bout on Jan. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The match, which will be telecast on HBO, will be the first
sporting event to take place at the theater, which recently
underwent a $70 million face lift.
</P>
<P>
   The ring for the fight will be set up on the stage, which will
be lowered by about two feet. Tickets will be sold for 5,500 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he relished the opportunity to be the first boxing
champion to fight at Radio City Music Hall, because he is always
looking for challenges. In 1996, Jones, arguably the best boxer in
the sport, played in a basketball game in the afternoon and scored
a 12th-round technical knockout against Eric Lucas that night.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first major boxing match in New York City since
the controversial Lennox Lewis-Evander Holyfield heavyweight
unification bout at Madison Square Garden on March 13. That fight,
which arrived with a huge buildup, disappointed almost everyone
involved, ending in a controversial draw that spawned an
investigation by the Manhattan district attorney's office that is
continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at HBO and Madison Square Garden are hoping that a
good showing by Jones and Telesco in a fabulous showplace like
Radio City will go a long way toward erasing some of the bad
feelings left by the Lewis-Holyfield match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't change the perception of boxing itself,'' Jones said.
``But it will allow people to see that there are some boxers who
can go to another level. It will show that not all boxers have a
poor background. People will get a chance to see that I'm a great
athlete, who happens to be a boxer.''
</P>
<P>
   This bout represents both a change of site and a change of
opponent for Jones (40-1), who will turn 31 the day after the bout.
Jones was originally supposed to fight Graciano Rocchigiani of
Germany at the Garden. But the Knicks were playing at the Garden on
Jan. 15, and Rocchigiani could not commit to the schedule of the
news conference in New York and to the date of the fight. So, the
fight was shifted to Radio City, which is owned by Cablevision, the
parent company of Madison Square Garden, and Rocchigiani was
replaced by Telesco (23-2).
</P>
<P>
   Jones last fought in New York City when he appeared at the
Garden on July 18, 1998, beating Lou Del Valle of the Bronx in a
12-round decision to add Del Valle's World Boxing Association title
to his World Boxing Council title.
</P>
<P>
   In Telesco, of Port Chester, N.Y., Jones will face another New
York-bred fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Telesco, 31, has pestered Jones for a fight for the last year
and a half. He has had people carry signs at Jones' bouts, trying
to bait Jones into a match, and he has shown up at Jones'
post-fight news conferences shouting at Jones to make the fight.
But Jones said it will not raise the level of animosity for the
fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to respect a guy like that,'' Jones said. ``For him
to know he's going to get beat as bad as he's going to get beat and
still go around begging for that beating, you have to respect
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Telesco, who has never been to Radio City _ not even for the
Christmas show _ does not feel overmatched against Jones. He said
that he promised his mother, Mary Teresa Telesco, who died while he
was serving a jail sentence for drug possession from 1993 to 1996,
that he would someday win the world light-heavyweight championship.
That drove him to challenge Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to stay on top of him so I would be forgotten,''
Telesco said. ``I wanted Jones to remember me. I wanted him to look
in the mirror and say, `I'm ashamed of myself for ducking this
guy.'''
</P>
<P>
   The two of them will have a chance to work out their differences
on one of the most famous stages in New York City. HBO plans to use
eight cameras to televise the fight, and two big screens will be
set up on the side of the stage. The cable network is accustomed to
broadcasting boxing in nontraditional sites. Two years ago it
broadcast a ``Boxing After Dark'' show at the Apollo Theater in
Harlem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 2250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
