<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0480 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4712 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-DOT-COM--ADVERTISING-     11-29 3078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOT-COM--ADVERTISING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Dot-Com Madness Heats Up Ad World  &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Dot-com madness has brought a blizzard of new revenue _ and a
multitude of new challenges _ to Bay Area advertising.
<P>
   Here in the technology epicenter, e-tailers accounted for 17
percent of spending on radio ads in the first half of the year and
11 percent of outdoor ads, according to Competitive Media
Reporting, a New York research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, advertising by dot-coms in conventional media nearly
tripled in the first half of the year compared to the comparable
1998 period, reaching $755 million, CMR reported.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the make-or-break fourth quarter, ``My guess is those
numbers will be off the charts _ four, five or 10 times bigger''
than in the first half, predicted Tom Bedecarre, chairman of Citron
Haligman Bedecarre Euro RSCG, a San Francisco ad shop whose
billings have doubled in the past two years to $200million.
</P>
<P>
   This quarter is crucial because venture capital for e-tailers
that fail to make a name for themselves this holiday is expected to
dry up by early next year. That will cause painful fall-out among
dot-coms and also hurt their business partners.
</P>
<P>
   A dramatic jump in agency revenues is the most obvious outgrowth
of the dot-com advertising orgy. But the hot new sector has also
caused fundamental changes in the way agencies do business.
</P>
<P>
   Among other changes, it has put ad agencies in the driver's seat
on choosing clients, altered billing practices and caused a new
aggressiveness in the way ad space is bought and sold.
</P>
<P>
   Dot-com mania has even changed the nature of ads themselves as
agencies attempt to cut through the clutter at any cost, sometimes
sacrificing good taste _ or any taste at all.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of e-commerce ``has completely transformed our
agency,'' said Tom Bedecarre, chairman of Citron Haligman Bedecarre
Euro RSCG, a San Francisco ad shop whose billings have doubled in
the past two years to $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our constraint to taking on new business is not winning it,
but being able to find enough people to handle the accounts,''
Bedecarre said.
</P>
<P>
   Agencies have suddenly found themselves in the unheard-of
position of being able to select from an array of potential
clients, rather than vying with rival ad shops for every scrap of
available business.
</P>
<P>
   In introductory meetings, e-tailers now do as much pitching as
the agencies do, said Courtney Buechert, managing director of
Leagas Delaney in San Francisco. To figure out which dot-coms have
good long-term prospects, agency executives sign nondisclosure
agreements and study the e-tailers' business plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're meeting with Clorox, you pretty much know what they
do,'' said Buechert. ``Beltbuckle.com has to explain itself.'
</P>
<P>
   Dot-com income has changed business for publishers and ad
brokers as well. But even as they get fat from the ad glut, they
face challenges they never would have dreamed of two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Industry Standard, a San Francisco-based technology
magazine, is hard pressed to produce enough articles to keep its
ad-to-content ratio at a reasonable level, said publisher Steve
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole brand is about countering the noise,'' said
Thompson, whose weekly recently ballooned to more than 300 pages
and 70 percent ads. ``We're trying to offer a distinctive voice. .
. . The last thing we want to do is contribute to the clutter.''
</P>
<P>
   For other ad sellers, the dot-com madness is like a gift from
the blue.
</P>
<P>
   At Alice 97.3, a popular rock radio station, several 60-second
spots sold recently for the astronomical sum of $6,000, said Steve
DiNardo, general manager. In last year's fourth quarter, top spots
might have gone for $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is funny money _ it's the difference between (startups
backed by) venture capital and the people who are really running a
business and have to turn a profit,'' DiNardo said.
</P>
<P>
   In October, dot-coms accounted for about 30 percent of Alice's
ad revenues, compared to less than 10 percent last year, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, dot-com mania is taking its toll on old-line
advertisers, ``effectively pricing them out of the marketplace,''
said Roger Becker, president of Becker Media of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Radio stations routinely bump traditional advertisers, such as
auto dealers and malls, from scheduled spots when a higher offer
from a dot-com comes in, Becker said. ``It's always been a dirty
business, but we've gotten into the arena of the surreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ad rates aren't the only surreal aspect of dot-com advertising;
content has also become questionable.
</P>
<P>
   A magazine ad for Luckysurf.com shows a pizza delivery boy being
greeted at the door by a nude, curvaceous blonde with a shocking
amount of exposed breast. ``Feeling lucky?'' the ad says.
</P>
<P>
   Cybergold ads on bus sides feature a reclining young woman and
the tagline, ``I Get Paid for Doing It.''
</P>
<P>
   In a television commercial for Cnet that ran earlier this year,
a proctologist snaps on a rubber glove and prepares to conduct an
anal exam on a young man looking for information about technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there is no point of differentiation (among e-commerce
companies), advertising has gone down the tubes,'' said Denis
Scheyer, president of Scheyer/SF. ``People are resorting to potty
humor. They're resorting to bad jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   Even ad executives don't always understand the spots. ``I see
these ads and I don't know what they're talking about half the
time,'' said Bob Coen, director of forecasting for McCann-Erickson,
a large New York agency.
</P>
<P>
   But there is some evidence that over-the-top advertising is
losing favor. Cnet moved its TV account from Citron Haligman
Bedecarre to Leagas Delaney this fall after research showed that
viewers didn't understand the point of the ads _ that Cnet is the
best source for technology information.
</P>
<P>
   The new Cnet commercials are almost a parody of clarity. In a
typical spot, a man wearing a Cnet T-shirt directs a man wearing a
shirt that says ``You'' away from a fellow whose shirt reads ``The
Wrong Digital Camera'' and toward one whose shirt says ``The Right
Digital Camera.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that simplicity in the midst of the madness would be a
very provocative message,'' Buechert said.
</P>
<P>
   Memorable advertising is particularly tough to create for
dot-coms because ``every ad ends in www.fillintheblank.com, so that
part of the ad gets lost'' said Scheyer. ``It's as if every
supermarket commercial ended with the phrase `can of peas.'''
</P>
<P>
   The glut of ads in conventional media has inspired advertisers
to look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Monster.com has been flying a bright orange blimp over the Bay
Area. Floating billboards for AdAuction.com have appeared on boats
in San Francisco Bay. Citron Haligman Bedecarre received an award
from a trade association for plastering Cnet ads on the passenger
ramps that connect airplanes to airport terminals.
</P>
<P>
   While agencies enjoy the current spate of dot-com wealth, some
are also girding against a widely-expected consolidation among
e-tailers in highly duplicative categories such as pet supplies,
personal care products and fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Scheyer, for example, still has just five people on the payroll,
despite a four-fold increase in revenues since 1997. The agency's
work for eMusic, eTranslate and other dot-coms, which will generate
$3million to $4million in revenues this year, is handled largely by
a pool of 50 free-lancers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose one of our dot-coms, it doesn't bother us,''
Scheyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Billing practices have also changed to reflect the risk of doing
business with dot-coms. Media brokers demand payment for ad space
up front, and some agencies have followed suit for their own fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not set pen to paper before we have 50 percent,'' said
Scheyer. ``We get the other 50 percent before it goes into
production.''
</P>
<P>
   Many agencies have begun accepting stock options as part of
their compensation _ but the smart ones insist that expenses be
covered with cash, said Buechert.
</P>
<P>
   Stock options have proven to be a mixed bag for local agencies,
he said. ``Some have tried it and gotten burned; some have tried it
and it has turned out OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Leagas Delaney, whose clients include Beyond.com and Red
Envelope.com, has accepted stock options as partial payment from
about one-third of its clients, said Buechert. But none of them has
gone public yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them are trying to get through the fourth quarter, and
if they survive, they'll IPO by summer,'' Buechert said. ``So the
big return remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   In the highly-wired Bay Area, ad space in what media in the
fourth quarter sold out in record time _ and for record prices,
according to local media brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, e-tailers spent $755 million in the first half of
1999, nearly triple the total in the comparable 1998 period,
according to Competitive Media Reporting, a New York research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Spending locally, at the tech epicenter, has become
</P>
<P>
   The multiples are expected to be many times that amount in the
most-wired markets, particularly the Bay Area, during the fourth
quarter, a make-or-break period for many dot-com startups.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of 1999, tech companies, mostly dot-coms,
accounted for 17 percent of spending on Bay Area radio stations and
11 percent of outdoor advertising, although just 4 percent of total
ad spending, according to Competitive Media Reporting, a New York
research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, e-commerce companies spent $755 million in the first
half, nearly triple the total in the comparable 1998 period, CMR
found. Only about 1 percent of spending goes to ads that actually
appear on the Web; most run in conventional media: radio,
television, newspapers, billboards and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   In the highly-wired Bay Area, ad space in what media in the
fourth quarter sold out in record time _ and for record prices,
according to local media brokers.
</P>
<P>
   While it is too early to measure fourth-quarter dot-com
spending, ``My guess is that number will be off the charts _ four,
five or 10 times bigger'' than in the first half, predicted
Bedecarre.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Ehringer, a top creative director at San Francisco ad shop
Leagas Delaney, used to spend his workdays brainstorming about
billboards, dreaming up taglines and directing television
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   But these days Ehringer has an additional duty: Evaluating the
business plans of hordes of Internet companies that come knocking
on his agency's door.
</P>
<P>
   Many startups, desperate for an advertising agency that can
catapult their brands into mass awareness, have millions of dollars
in venture capital at the ready, but little or no track record. Ad
agencies face the challenge of choosing clients with good long-term
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're meeting with Clorox, you pretty much know what they
do,'' said Courtney Buechert, Leagas Delaney's managing director.
``Beltbuckle.com has to explain itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehringer's new role as business analyst _ which requires him to
sign nondisclosure agreements and examine potential clients'
resumes and revenue projections, among other things _ is just one
example of how dot-com mania has radically altered the Bay Area
advertising sector.
</P>
<P>
   Among other changes, it has put agencies in the driver's seat on
choosing clients (historically, the client has chosen the agency),
altered billing practices and caused a new aggressiveness in the
way ad space is bought and sold.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Web ad glut is an economic boon to sellers of ad
space, it also poses new challenges. The Industry Standard, a San
Francisco-based technology magazine, is hard pressed to produce
enough articles to keep its ad-to-content ratio at a reasonable
level, said publisher Steve Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole brand is about countering the noise,'' said
Thompson, whose weekly magazine sometimes balloons to more than 300
pages. ``We're trying to offer a distinctive voice. . . . The last
thing we want to do is contribute to the clutter.''
</P>
<P>
   No one expects the Internet windfall to last forever. In fact,
many executives are forecasting a fallout among e-tailers after
this holiday season. But agencies and ad brokers in the Bay Area _
and to a lesser extent the rest of the country _ are enjoying the
ride.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of 1999, tech companies, mostly dot-coms,
accounted for 17 percent of spending on Bay Area radio stations and
11 percent of outdoor advertising, although just 4 percent of total
ad spending, according to Competitive Media Reporting, a New York
research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, e-commerce companies spent $755 million in the first
half, nearly triple the total in the comparable 1998 period, CMR
found. Only about 1 percent of spending goes to ads that actually
appear on the Web; most run in conventional media: radio,
television, newspapers, billboards and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   In the highly-wired Bay Area, ad space in the fourth quarter
sold out in record time _ and for record prices, according to local
media brokers.
</P>
<P>
   While it is too early to measure fourth-quarter dot-com
spending, ``My guess is that number will be off the charts _ four,
five or 10 times bigger'' than in the first half, predicted
Bedecarre.
</P>
<P>
   Radio and outdoor ads are favored since they are cheaper than
television and enjoy broad reach among professionals who commute to
work.
</P>
<P>
   At Alice 97.3, a popular rock radio station, several 60-second
spots sold recently for the astronomical sum of $6,000, said Steve
DiNardo, general manager. In last year's fourth quarter, top spots
might have gone for $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is funny money _ it's the difference between (startups
backed by) venture capital and the people who are really running a
business and have to turn a profit,'' DiNardo said. In October,
dot-coms accounted for about 30 percent of Alice's ad revenues, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, dot-com mania is taking its toll on old-line
advertisers, ``effectively pricing them out of the marketplace,''
said Roger Becker, president of Becker Media of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Radio stations routinely bump traditional advertisers, such as
auto dealers and malls, from scheduled spots when a higher offer
from a dot-com comes in, Becker said. ``It's always been a dirty
business, but we've gotten into the arena of the surreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ad rates aren't the only surreal aspect of dot-com advertising;
the content has also become questionable.
</P>
<P>
   A magazine ad for Luckysurf.com shows a pizza delivery boy being
greeted at the door by a nude, curvaceous blonde with a shocking
amount of exposed breast. ``Feeling lucky?'' the ad says.
</P>
<P>
   Cybergold ads on bus sides feature a reclining young woman and
the tagline, ``I Get Paid for Doing It.''
</P>
<P>
   In a television commercial for Cnet that ran earlier this year,
a proctologist snaps on a rubber glove and prepares to conduct an
anal exam on a young man looking for information about technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there is no point of differentiation (among e-commerce
companies), advertising has gone down the tubes,'' said Denis
Scheyer, president of Scheyer/SF. ``People are resorting to potty
humor. They're resorting to bad jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   Even ad executives don't always understand today's dot-com
spots. ``I see these ads and I don't know what they're talking
about half the time,'' said Bob Coen, director of forecasting for
McCann-Erickson, a large New York agency.
</P>
<P>
   But there is some evidence that over-the-top advertising is
losing favor. Cnet moved its TV account from Citron Haligman
Bedecarre to Leagas Delaney this fall after research showed that
viewers didn't understand the point of the ads _ that Cnet is the
best source for technology information.
</P>
<P>
   The new Cnet commercials are almost a parody of clarity. In a
typical spot, a man wearing a Cnet T-shirt directs a man wearing a
shirt that says ``You'' away from a fellow whose shirt reads ``The
Wrong Digital Camera'' and toward one whose shirt says ``The Right
Digital Camera.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that simplicity in the midst of the madness would be a
very provocative message,'' Buechert said.
</P>
<P>
   Memorable advertising is particularly tough to create for
dot-coms because ``every ad ends in www.fillintheblank.com, so that
part of the ad gets lost'' said Scheyer. ``It's as if every
supermarket commercial ended with the phrase `can of peas.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The glut of ads in conventional media has inspired advertisers
to look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Monster.com has been flying a bright orange blimp over the Bay
Area. Floating billboards for AdAuction.com have appeared on boats
in San Francisco Bay. Citron Haligman Bedecarre received an award
from a trade association for plastering Cnet ads on the passenger
ramps that connect airplanes to airport terminals.
</P>
<P>
   While agencies enjoy the current spate of dot-com income, some
are also girding against a widely-expected consolidation among
e-tailers in highly duplicative categories such as pet supplies,
personal care products and fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Scheyer, for example, still has just five people on the payroll,
despite a four-fold increase in revenues since 1997. The agency's
work for eMusic, eTranslate and other dot-coms, which will generate
$3 million to $4 million in revenues this year, is handled largely
by a pool of 50 free-lancers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose one of our dot-coms, it doesn't bother us,''
Scheyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Billing practices have also changed to reflect the risk of doing
business with dot-coms. Media brokers demand payment for ad space
up front, and some agencies have followed suit for their own fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not set pen to paper before we have 50 percent,'' said
Scheyer. ``We get the other 50 percent before it goes into
production.''
</P>
<P>
   Many agencies have begun accepting stock options as part of
their compensation _ but the smart ones insist that expenses be
covered with cash, said Buechert.
</P>
<P>
   Stock options have proven to be a mixed bag for local agencies,
he said. ``Some have tried it and gotten burned; some have tried it
and it has turned out OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Leagas Delaney, whose clients include Beyond.com and Red
Envelope.com, has accepted stock options as partial payment from
about one-third of its clients, said Buechert. But none of them has
gone public yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them are trying to get through the fourth quarter, and
if they survive, they'll IPO by summer,'' Buechert said. ``So the
big return remains to be seen.''
</P>
