<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 &HT;    Converting an IRA to a Roth &HT;    By Arthur Louis
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; Q: &LR;  I would like to take some money out of one of my &LR; 
 &LR; individual retirement accounts and convert it to a Roth &LR;   &LR; IRA (I
don't have one yet). However, I don't know whether I am &LR;   &LR; permitted
to do this, because I don't have any wage income. All &LR;   &LR; I have is
nontaxable disability income, dividends and interest. &LR;
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &LR;  A: Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller says
that even though you don't have taxable wages or professional
income, you may be entitled to convert a traditional IRA to a Roth.
But you can do so only if you and your spouse (if you have one)
don't have total adjusted gross income greater than $100,000 in the
year you make the conversion.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to convert, remember that you must pay taxes on the
earnings from the old IRA, as well as on any deductible
contributions you may have made.
</P>
<P>
   Starting a new Roth from scratch, rather than rolling funds
over, is a different story. To create a new Roth, you or your
spouse must &UR;  &LR; have some taxable wages, salary or professional
income.
</P>
<P>
   You can piggyback on your spouse's income if you don't have any
yourself. If your spouse has at least $4,000 in wages, each of you
can contribute the maximum of $2,000 to your new Roth. If your
spouse earns less than that, your total IRA contributions are
limited to that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Here, too, there are income limits at the upper end. A single
person whose adjusted gross &UR;  &LR; income exceeds $110,000 cannot create
a Roth, while the limit is $160,000 for a married couple filing
jointly.
</P>
<P>
   The rules applying to IRAs are about as complex as anything in
the tax code. Any taxpayer who has an IRA, or is thinking about it,
ought to get a copy of Internal Revenue Service Publication 590.
You can download it from the Internet at  &LR; www.irs.gov &LR; . Or, you can
order a copy by telephone, toll-free, at (800) 829-3676.
</P>
<P>
   Checking FDIC Insurance
</P>
<P>
   Q: When a bank, especially one located out of state, advertises
attractive rates on certificates of deposit, how can you check that
they are insured by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.?
</P>
<P>
   &LR; a  &LR;  A: If you have access to the Internet, go to the FDIC's Web
site. Go to the agency's search engine at
 &LR; www2.fdic.gov/structur/search &LR;   &LR; /findoneinst.cfm &LR; . You will see a
prompt directing you to enter the name of the bank in question.
</P>
<P>
   After you have done that, click on the search button and you
will see a display indicating whether the bank is FDIC-insured _
and, if so, for how long. You also get information such as the date
the bank was founded, the location of the main office and the
number of branches.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have access to the Internet, call the FDIC's
toll-free number: (800) 276-6003.
</P>
<P>
   IRA Deductions
</P>
<P>
   Q: A few years ago, I took a tax deduction on a $2,000
contribution to a deductible IRA. The deduction was later
disallowed by the IRS, because I was enrolled in a pension plan at
work part of that year. The IRS instructed me to pay taxes on the
$2,000, which I did.
</P>
<P>
   Now I want to withdraw money from my IRA. I am not yet 591/2
years old, and therefore would be subject to the 10 percent penalty
for premature IRA distributions. But I wonder whether the penalty
would apply to the $2,000 contribution on which I have already paid
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   A: No. But, there are complications.
</P>
<P>
   You can't just identify the nondeductible $2,000 and take it
out, while leaving the other money in. Because the $2,000 is
mingled with other funds that were deductible, you have to prorate
your withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how that works:
</P>
<P>
   Let's say that you have $10,000 in your IRA, consisting of your
nondeductible $2,000 plus deductible contributions and earnings. If
you withdraw money from the account, all but one-fifth of the
amount ($2,000 divided by $10,000) will be subject to taxes or
penalties. The only way you would be able to get the full $2,000
out tax-free would be to liquidate the entire account.
</P>
<P>
   When you withdraw money from an IRA, you must complete Form
8606, which indicates how much of your withdrawal is taxable and
how much is nontaxable. Also, you should get a copy of IRS
Publication 590, mentioned in the first item in this column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
