<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4714 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-CHAMPFUND--INVESTOR-S     11-29 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAMPFUND--INVESTOR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     Pro Athletes Pool Funds To Cash In on High Tech  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The 49ers may not be making many points on the field, but a number
of current and former players hope to score big in another venue:
venture capital.
<P>
   Ex-49er greats Harris Barton and Ronnie Lott yesterday said they
have raised $40 million from 99 professional athletes and that
their Champion Ventures I fund will invest it with 10 top
technology-focused venture capital funds.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Barton and Lott, investors include past and
present football stars Steve Young, Jerry Rice, Brent Jones, Junior
Bryant, Merton Hanks and Dan Marino; baseball players Barry Bonds,
Eric Karros and Ryne Sandberg; and basketball player Steve Kerr.
</P>
<P>
   The fund was open only to professional sports figures worth a
minimum of $1 million with at least $250,000 to invest.
</P>
<P>
   Former offensive tackle Barton and former defensive back Lott
have both invested in high-tech stocks and have been limited
partners in previous venture capital funds. As general partners in
Champion Ventures, they don't plan to review business plans or
invest directly in hot startups.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they leveraged their connections in Silicon Valley to
gain entry to an elite group of funds that close their doors to
most mortals.
</P>
<P>
   The first Champion Ventures fund-of-funds will invest from $2
million to $5 million each with Accel Partners, Benchmark Capital,
ComVentures, Crosspoint Venture Partners, Mayfield Fund, Mohr
Davidow Ventures, New Enterprise Associates, Redpoint Ventures,
Sequoia Capital and Technology Crossover Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Barton and Lott say they launched Champion Ventures to let other
pro athletes share the opportunity to invest in hot technology
startups. Given the bull market and mania for new Internet stock
offerings, some venture capital firms recently have posted
triple-digit returns.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of professional athletes ``have gotten involved with a lot
of dumb restaurant, car wash and other deals, and had a problem
with capital preservation,'' according to Barton. With venture
capital firms regularly ``ripping the skin off the ball,'' he said
he expected Champion Ventures to beat the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Barton and Lott also see their venture as a way to connect pro
athletes with venture capitalists and startup companies, opening
the way to product endorsements, speaking engagements and
post-career job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The venture capital firms get something out of the deal, too.
``This is a way to use athletes to help brand their companies,''
said Barton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to have an ongoing relationship with Champion
Ventures that will put us and our portfolio companies in closer
contact with some of their high-visibility investors,'' noted
Mayfield Fund General Partner Kevin Fong.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't look like Champion Ventures should have much trouble
attracting new investors. Barton said he and Lott anticipate
closing another $40 million to $80 million fund by next summer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
