<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY, BOSNIA: WAR CRIMINAL SENTENCED
</P>
<P>
   A court in Duesseldorf sentenced Maksim Sokolovic, a 59-year-old
Bosnian Serb and longtime German resident, to nine years in prison
for war crimes in Bosnia in 1992. Sokolovic, who led a paramilitary
unit, was convicted of complicity in genocide and other crimes. He
was tried in Germany to ease the caseload at the tribunal in The
Hague, Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: BRACING FOR VIOLENCE
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Jaime Mayor Oreja said Madrid would not
underestimate the Basque separatist group ETA's threat to resume
attacks after ending a 14-month cease-fire. Arnaldo Otegi, a leader
of the rebels' political wing, called the situation ``extremely
delicate.''
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: PREMIER IS BOLSTERED
</P>
<P>
   The center-left coalition of Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema won
five by-elections, including one in the Communist stronghold of
Bologna, where it narrowly held onto the parliamentary seat vacated
by Romano Prodi, a former prime minister who is now president of
the European Commission. The results were seen as a blow to the
opposition leader Silvio Berlusconi, a former prime minister who
last week was ordered to stand trial in two corruption cases.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG: A SETBACK FOR DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party lost ground in the first district-level
elections since Hong Kong reverted to Chinese rule in 1997.
Although the party won the most seats in the 18 district councils
that advise the government on local issues, it barely edged out the
pro-Beijing Democratic Alliance for the Betterment of Hong Kong,
which more than doubled its seats. Analysts said the party's appeal
has faded as fears about Chinese interference in the territory have
eased.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: PERKS FOR JAILED PREMIER
</P>
<P>
   A court barred the deposed prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, from
making statements about his case, but ruled that he is entitled to
better prison conditions, including a television set, private
bathroom and home cooking, while he awaits trial. Sharif had
complained that he was being treated as a ``common criminal''
despite prison rules that provide for better accommodations for
inmates of higher political or economic status.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: SUSPECTS IN BOMBING
</P>
<P>
   A day after a bomb hurt 48 people at a Cape Town restaurant,
security officials said they had identified the organization
responsible but would not name the group, saying only that it is
well known and has a violent history. Speculation has focused on a
local vigilante group called Pagad, or People Against Gangsterism
and Drugs, which law enforcement agencies have linked to a number
of terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   WEST BANK: MORE ARAFAT CRITICS HELD
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian security officers arrested three more dissidents,
bringing to eight those rounded up for signing a petition critical
of official corruption under Yasser Arafat's Palestinian Authority.
Two more were being held under house arrest. On Wednesday, the
Legislative Council will discuss Arafat's demand to lift the
immunity of eight legislators who also signed the petition so they
can be prosecuted.
</P>
</TEXT>
