<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4723 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DOLLAR-MARKETPLACE-NY     11-29 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLLAR-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE SEESAW OF CURRENCIES, THE DOLLAR STANDS TALL IN THE MIDDLE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One constant of financial markets is that they
regularly defy expectations. It means that losers can be winners,
analysts are caught off guard and explanations of what is occurring
sometimes must be given with a shrug of the shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   These are all features of the newest leg of the Japanese yen's
rally against the dollar and the euro's plunge against both the
dollar and the yen.
</P>
<P>
   Easiest to explain is how the dollar can be strong against the
euro at the same time it is weak against the yen. The dollar's
weakness is a product of what is going on in Japan, not in the
United States, while the dollar's strength has more to do with
worries about Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, this means that the dollar's stumble against the yen
is not as serious as this year's 10 percent slide might imply. In
trading Monday, the Japanese yen shrugged off intervention by the
Bank of Japan to weaken it and finished the day at 102.35 yen to
the dollar, slightly shy of the four-year high of 101.10 it set
Friday, when American markets closed early in the session the day
after Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   But the euro plunged further Monday, setting new lows against
both the dollar and the yen. At $1.0095, the euro is down from
$1.0156 on Friday and almost at parity with the dollar; the euro
finished at 103.50 yen Monday. For the year, the euro is down 13.5
percent against the dollar and 21.8 percent against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The world's three major currencies are now close to a numerical
parity never seen in the currency markets: 100 yen to the dollar
and one dollar to the euro. At least that makes currency
conversions simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``The yen should not be as strong as it is now, but it is,''
mused David Gilmore, a partner in Foreign Exchange Analytics in
Essex, Conn. ``And the euro should not be as weak as it is now, but
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Signals that currency traders would usually watch closely are
having little impact. The yen is strengthening despite the presence
of some negative economic signals, including weak Japanese
household spending in the third quarter. The euro is falling even
though new data show the French and German economies on upward
paths.
</P>
<P>
   What seems to be more critical to these currency moves is a
volatile year-end environment. That climate is partly influenced by
worries about Year 2000 computer problems and partly by money
managers who are fleeing bad bets they made on the euro or are
rushing to the Japanese stock market in the hope that it remains a
good bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flows caused by the Y2K phenomenon will dominate the market,''
said Michael Rosenberg, head of global foreign exchange research at
Deutsche Bank. ``The volume of trading is not what it normally
is.'' This contributes to his sense that the dollar's decline
against the yen and the euro's slide against both the yen and
dollar have ``a feel of free fall.''
</P>
<P>
   In this environment, Karen E. Parker, director of currency
research at Chase Securities, said, ``if you are overweight the
euro, a little bit of bad news is given a lot of weight while good
news is ignored. Japan is the mirror image; a bit of good news is
given a lot of weight and bad news is ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg thinks that in the months ahead the dollar will
rebound against the yen and the euro will rise against the dollar.
But he said money managers who agree with that outlook would not
make such bets in this environment. They are not willing, he said,
to take the risk of a 2 percent or 3 percent loss now for the
chance of a 10 percent gain later next year.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors bet on the euro, the currency of 11 European
countries, when it was introduced in January, Ms. Parker noted.
They lost badly as the euro fell close to parity with the dollar in
July. But they bet on it again as it rallied up to $1.0894 by
mid-October. In the swoon since, she said, they have fled faster
than they did during the euro's first slide.
</P>
<P>
   She said that European monetary officials were also hurting the
euro by creating confusion regarding the euro's importance to their
policies. Last week, the president of the European Central Bank,
Wim Duisenberg, said he was not worried about the euro's decline.
Monday, he said intervention to support the euro was a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder may also have worried
investors about his nation's commitment to restructuring its
economy both by inveighing against Vodafone AirTouch's proposed
hostile takeover of Mannesmann AG, and by arranging a $2.2 billion
bailout of Germany's leading builder, Philipp Holzmann AG.
</P>
<P>
   As for Japan, 10 interventions since June by the Bank of Japan,
including the action Monday, have failed to weaken the yen, both
because the central bank refuses to use more radical means to
weaken the currency and because investors _ most of whom had been
out of Japan for years _ want back in. ``Investors are looking for
value and are finding it in the Japanese stock market,'' Gilmore
said.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, the Nikkei index of 225 issues is up 50
percent in dollar terms; the Topix index of more than 1,300 stocks
is up 72 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts thought that a stronger yen would make Japanese
exports more expensive abroad and thus hurt sales, undermining the
economic boomlet Japan has seen this year and stopping the stock
rally. But the yen has risen 8.5 percent since Sept. 8 against the
dollar, and the Nikkei has climbed 6.9 percent in that time.
</P>
<P>
   As analysts pondered the currency moves, Treasury Secretary
Lawrence H. Summers said Monday that the Clinton administration
still favored a strong dollar. ``Our policy with respect to the
dollar is unchanged: A strong dollar is in the national interest,''
he told reporters, according to Reuters. ``As always, we are
watching developments in currency markets.''
</P>
<P>
   All this leaves forecasters thinking that the trend will
continue in the near term, with the yen moving to an exchange rate
of less than 100 to the dollar while the euro drops to less than $1
as well. So currency conversions could get more difficult.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
