A4725 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-POWER--RATE-HIKE &LR;      11-29 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER--RATE-HIKE </SLUG>
  
 PUC Listens To 2 Sides Over PG&AMP;E's Hike  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Pacific Gas and Electric Co. made its case before the California
Public Utilities Commission Monday for a huge rate increase.
<P>
   Consumer groups, in turn, made their case for why the state's
largest utility should get by with considerably less.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC hearing in San Francisco followed an administrative law
judge's ruling last month that PG&AMP;E should be allowed an annual
rate increase of $243 million. PG&AMP;E had requested $822 million.
</P>
<P>
   The utility subsequently warned that as many as 3,500 workers
could get the sack if its desired rate increase falls through. It
also said it would have to cut back on tree trimming around
electrical lines, potentially increasing fire hazard in residential
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides yesterday used lots of colorful charts and tossed
around a lot of big numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a long, well-choreographed exercise in public
discourse that left some in the hearing room scratching their heads
and fidgeting in their seats.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Gordon Smith, PG&AMP;E's president and chief executive, kicked
things off by insisting that the utility's current rates do not
fully cover its expenses.
</P>
<P>
   He placed the shortfall at ``several hundred million dollars a
year'' _ an amount that Smith said is being borne by PG&AMP;E's
shareholders in the form of reduced dividends.
</P>
<P>
   ``PG&AMP;E's shareholders cannot and will not continue to fund the
difference between what service really costs and what's allowed in
rates,'' he told the commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, PG&AMP;E's shareholders have been fleeing the stock in
droves. The utility's shares closed yesterday at $22.06, down 6
cents from Friday and well off its 52-week high of $34.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most people in this room,'' Smith said, ``I believe lower
rates are better. But lower rates are not better at the expense of
reliability and service customers demand and deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   However, representatives of consumer groups and PG&AMP;E's customers
challenged Smith's argument that reliability and service will be
endangered if the PUC approves the proposed $243 million rate
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Gileau, staff counsel of the Office of Ratepayer
Advocates, said the more than $800 million increase sought by PG&AMP;E
``is simply not warranted.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the utility has overstated both its financial jeopardy
and the impact of a lower rate increase on employees.
</P>
<P>
   This position was echoed by Robert Finkelstein, an attorney for
The Utility Reform Network (TURN), who accused PG&AMP;E of trying to
soak smaller customers for upgrades required by energy-sucking
enterprises in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``PG&AMP;E says it is just responding to consumers' calls for
greater reliability,'' he said. ``This is a crock.''
</P>
<P>
   The PUC is expected to decide on the rate increase within the
next few weeks. A compromise remains a distinct possibility,
allowing both sides to claim partial victory.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E received some noisy support from about 300 members of the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, Local 1245, who
gathered on the sidewalk prior to the hearing to back the utility's
call for a higher increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go down to Silicon Valley and ask them what happens when
there's a glitch in the line,'' said Ken Ball, a union
representative. ``You'll find it's damned important to have
reliable energy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the funds, you don't have the jobs,'' said Gary Ray,
an electric crew foreman who traveled all the way from Bakersfield
for the midday rally. ``If they lay off 3,500 employees and the
power goes out, how long do you think it's going to take to get it
back on?''
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Spatt, a spokeswoman for TURN, said the union members were
merely responding to what she called PG&AMP;E's scare tactics.
``They're really being manipulated by the threat of layoffs,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rich Cowart, an electric crew foreman from Concord, said
that PG&AMP;E employees have crunched the numbers for themselves and
that the threat of cutbacks is very real.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not easily manipulated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
