<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4727 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-REDBACK--MERGER-SFCHR     11-29 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDBACK--MERGER-SFCHRONICLE </SLUG>
  
 &HT;    Redback To Buy Siara Inc. &HT;       By Benny Evangelista
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Redback Networks Inc., a Sunnyvale networking-equipment-maker that
went public just six months ago, agreed Monday to buy Siara Systems
Inc. _ a Mountain View company with no revenues, customers or
products to sell _ for $4.7 billion in stock.
<P>
   Redback sells equipment and software to cable TV and phone
companies that offer high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Redback was mainly after Siara's 170 engineers, who are
developing hardware and software to run high-speed Internet service
over fiber-optic lines. This could let Redback's customers provide
even faster Internet service than is now possible.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is only the latest transaction by companies racing to
build the backbone for new high-speed Internet networks, a race
fueled by the explosive growth of the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   In August, San Jose's Cisco Systems agreed to pay a whopping
$6.9 billion in stock for Cerent Corp., a privately held Petaluma
startup that is also developing equipment to help
telecommunications companies provide faster Internet speeds on
fiber-optic networks.
</P>
<P>
   Cerent Corp. and Siara Systems share a common history. Vinod
Khosla, a partner in the venture capital firm Kleiner Perkins
Caufield &AMP; Byers, helped found both companies.
</P>
<P>
   And several of Cerent's founders left to form Siara. Among them
were David Stiles and Greg Favour, two chip designers who also
helped design the successful K-6 and K-7 computer chips at Advanced
Micro Devices Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Redback Chief Financial Officer Craig Gentner is confident
Siara's engineers have the technology to expand Redback's overall
share of a projected $20-plus billion market for high-speed cable,
fiber-optic and wireless Internet communications by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lot of money, but to get the opportunity to address
a $20 billion market and have the lead on the competition with this
kind of veteran engineering team on both sides, I think, this is
just a phenomenal deal,'' Gentner said.
</P>
<P>
   Siara will let Reback ``leapfrog'' over competitors like Cisco
and Nortel Networks Corp., said analyst Barry Sine of Kaufman Bros.
</P>
<P>
   ``From Redback's perspective, it's a great strategic fit,'' Sine
said. ``It shores up Redback where it needed to be shored up,'' in
the fiber-optic area.
</P>
<P>
   What Siara gains form the deal is Redback's sales and marketing
staff _ something Siara hadn't even started to assemble, said Sine.
</P>
<P>
   Redback's sales and marketing staff could shorten hasten its
product launch, said Sine, who retained his ``strong buy''
recommendation on Redback.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Steven D. Levy of Lehman Brothers agreed the deal made
strategic sense for both companies. However, Levy said he
questioned whether the companies were overstating the overall
dollar value of the deal for Siara's shareholders because it is
based on what he called Redback's currently overvalued stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Redback stock, which debuted at $11.50 per share in May, closed
yesterday at $150, up $13.50.
</P>
<P>
   Redback sells equipment and services to about 120 regional phone
companies and cable providers, including Qwest, UUNET, Bell Canada
International Corp. and GTE Corp.
</P>
<P>
   It posted a net loss of $9.16 million on revenues of $38.1
million for the first nine months of 1999. Last year, it lost $9.9
million on revenues of $9.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gentner said the company only expects to break even for fiscal
year 1999. Still, he hopes the Siara deal will let the company turn
a profit by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Redback will issue 31.3 million shares of stock to acquire
Siara. That will give Siara's owners a 38 percent stake in Redback.
</P>
<P>
   Redback President and CEO Dennis Barsema will remain CEO of the
combined company, with Siara CEO Vivek Ragavan becoming president
and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will keep Siara's headquarters and development
center in Mountain View and a development center in Vancouver,
British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
