<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAMIBIA-ELECT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAMIBIAN VOTERS CHOOSE BETWEEN ISSUES AND SYMBOLS OF INDEPENDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDHOEK, Namibia _ A decade after leading Namibia to
independence, President Sam Nujoma's party faces the first bona
fide challenge to its political leadership this week when voters
elect a president and new parliament.
</P>
<P>
   While the party, the South West Africa People's Organization, is
almost certain to retain control of the presidency and Parliament,
a breakaway party formed this year appears likely to chip away at
the its dominance.
</P>
<P>
   The fight for independence from South Africa, which occupied the
country in defiance of the United Nations, remains fresh in the
memories of many people here, and loyalty to the guerrilla movement
that waged that fight is fierce.
</P>
<P>
   A country of about 1.7 million people, Namibia has been notable
among its neighbors for its relative political and social
stability.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not without problems. Economic growth has slowed
considerably in the last several years. The public health system
has been overwhelmed by AIDS. Schools have been criticized for
failing to improve education. Thousands of Namibian soldiers have
been sent to Congo, at great expense, to help battle rebels there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Namibia is no different from many other African countries in
that the first few years of independence are dominated by
personality and party loyalty and symbolism,'' Andre DuPisani, of
the University of Namibia, said in an interview. ``Now, I think we
are seeing the emergence of the issues as important.''
</P>
<P>
   But many people behind Swapo, as the governing party is known,
still care less about roads and schools than about liberation and
loyalty. ``I will die a member of Swapo,'' Ndahafa Johannes, 36,
who joined at age 13, said after a rally outside party
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the party into the voting, which takes place Tuesday and
Wednesday, will be the movement's father, President Nujoma. First
elected president in 1990, he was re-elected in 1994 to what should
have been a second and final term. But a constitutional change
pushed through Parliament by Swapo has let Nujoma, 70, run again.
</P>
<P>
   With control of almost three-quarters of seats in Parliament,
far more than the two-thirds needed for constitutional amendments,
Swapo can ignore the existing opposition without consequence.
</P>
<P>
   But long as the party goes unchallenged, the country's problems
will not be solved, said Ben Ulenga, presidential candidate of the
new party, the Congress of Democrats. ``There is a feeling that
they are there forever and therefore they can do exactly what they
want,'' said Ulenga, 47, who quit Swapo and his post as ambassador
to Britain last year, frustrated by the party's direction.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the official opposition party, which was fashioned by the
old apartheid regime, the Congress of Democrats aims for the masses
that have supported Swapo. Ulenga's background is likely to give
him credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Like the president, he comes from Namibia's largest ethnic
group, the Ovambo. Active in the struggle for liberation, he spent
several years imprisoned on South Africa's notorious Robben Island
after being captured. For many years after independence, he was a
loyal Swapo leader, serving in the party and in government.
</P>
<P>
   Proud as he is of his past, Ulenga now has to persuade voters
that Swapo's role in the struggle did not earn it eternal loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``History is not a good enough reason to support a party,'' he
said. ``We have to look to the future.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
