<HEADER>
A4734 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-NY-FASHION-SMITH-ART-     11-29 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FASHION-SMITH-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER TRYING TUOSO LIFE, A DESIGNER STOOPS TO SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Calif.)  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT21, has been sent. Non-subscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Wynn Smith begins designing a new collection, he approaches
the matter the way he would sit down to write a short story. First,
he manufactures a character, then conjures for her the kind of
detailed biography that could serve as a model to creative-writing
students in many an MFA program.
</P>
<P>
   For spring 2000, the fourth season he has turned out his
youthful line called Wink, Smith, 34, envisioned a girl named
Amanda Norwood. He had her grow up in Virginia, the daughter of a
strict military family. She worked bitterly hard in high school _
like Reese Witherspoon's striving teenage politico in the film
``Election,'' Smith explained. She attended West Point but then, in
a twist deserving a place on an after-hours cable program, landed
at the Playboy mansion as Hugh Hefner's intern.
</P>
<P>
   The previous season's protagonist, dreamed up by Smith and
Wink's creative director, John Vertin, was a girl named Angel who
fled her Midwestern hometown in the 1930s and, well, things get
complicated from there.
</P>
<P>
   While Smith's Angels and Amandas are far-fetched, the clothes he
puts them in are not. Looking at the pieces, including T-shirts
with the names of bands on them, it might not be easy to guess that
some in the fashion world consider Smith to be among the most
gifted young people designing today, a tailor in the classic
tradition, capable of directing a grand Parisian house. When
Women's Wear Daily recently asked Linda Dresner, owner of the
influential Park Avenue boutique that bears her name, who in her
opinion should take over the venerable ready-to-wear division at
Yves Saint Laurent, she answered Wynn Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dresner's comment makes sense when you consider Smith's
earlier work, which was more inventive, though less financially
viable, for a defunct label known as Wynn. It is tempting to read
into his career trajectory from innovator on the fringe to more
conventional commercial success an allegory for how young designers
fare in America, a country that, increasingly, would live in
Dockers if it could.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes are slightly quirky, somewhat off, but ultimately
simple, sellable pieces, rarely costing more than a few hundred
dollars. There are tweeds with metallic threads, short cotton
shirtdresses, khaki blazers with pockets that sit purposely too
high, bikinis bizarre only when he shows them on the runway over
pantyhose.
</P>
<P>
   It is on the basis of other work, however, that Smith developed
his initial following among fashion cognoscenti, a group very
different from the Jane magazine demographic he outfits now.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the early 1980s, Smith designed and sewed
custom-made suits and evening wear for San Francisco society women.
``I was making difficult things,'' Smith said recently in his tiny
Geary Street studio in San Francisco. ``My hands would be bleeding.
It was self-torture.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Smith, who has lived in San Francisco for the last 16
years, started unveiling small collections of couturelike clothes
in New York under the label Wynn. They gained fans and customers
like the fashion editor Polly Mellen and Amy Fine Collins, a writer
in the International Best Dressed Hall of Fame .
</P>
<P>
   ``The clothes were serious, not wacky deconstructed messes,''
Ms. Collins recalled. ``His stuff didn't look like anyone else's.
It was experimental but very refined at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   The men's wear designer Gene Meyer said, ``It reminded me of
Balenciaga.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith showed his first collections in a suite at the
Sherry-Netherland Hotel, where visitors recall being greeted at the
door by the designer in his pajamas and bare feet. One of the
visitors who came to see Smith's Wynn work was Catherine Detliner,
a buyer for Linda Dresner, among other fancy shops. Ms. Detliner
was so impressed she called people from the hotel and told them to
come check out the clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, he's the best American designer I ever found,'' she
said a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dresner soon began carrying the clothes (generally costing
$1,000 and up). Sales were decent but not great, she said.
Beginning in 1995, Wynn shows were held at Ms. Dresner's New York
shop, with the lower-priced, more trend-conscious Wink collection
introduced along the way, too. In 1998, when it became clear to
Smith that Wink was more financially viable, he stopped designing
his high-end line.
</P>
<P>
   At whatever price, Smith's clothes bear the precision one might
expect from a young man taught to sew as a child by a
great-grandmother named Gertrude Pilkington. Smith and his sister
were brought up in Arkansas by their grandparents, Eveyln and
Winifred Smith, who were doting, if conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother thought curly hair was the downfall of
America,'' Smith joked over lunch at a favorite local restaurant
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Smith's grandmother encouraged his wish to attend the
Fashion Institute of Design and Merchandising in San Francisco.
When he graduated, at 22, he came to New York and landed a job with
Geoffrey Beene, one of his idols _ ``wheeling bust forms and
folding gloves'' in the showroom, Smith recalled. Creatively
unfulfilled but too intimidated to apply for a job as one of
Beene's design assistants, he soon returned to San Francisco, where
he took lessons in pattern making and sewing.
</P>
<P>
   Smith eventually became so enamored of the technical aspects of
making clothes that he spent an entire summer perfecting a pair of
pants cut on the bias. For one of his Wynn collections, he spent
$30,000 on fabric for a relatively small number of sample garments.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is the first to admit that if Wynn didn't take off in ways
he might have hoped, his own self-indulgence was partly to blame.
Many adventurous designers produce unwearable fantasy pieces, but
their collections are often diverse enough to support them. Smith's
were not. ``I was showing see-through things with nothing to go
under them,'' he said. ``At that price point, it's irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   He once labored to make a seamless dress out of three circular
panels. ``I thought, `Isn't this amazing?''' he recalled. `` `I'm a
genius!' Well, no one cared. No one cares if something has no
seams.''
</P>
<P>
   The dress did grace a window at Bergdorf Goodman next to a John
Galliano piece.
</P>
<P>
   When Smith started Wynn, he also seemed to lack focus. A
well-mannered teenager, he rebelled in his late 20s, he said. When
he would show in New York, he and his sister and muse, Mink Smith,
would take the red eye from San Francisco and head for the Sound
Factory, a club, at 6 a.m. Once, in his rush to get there, he left
half the collection at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's current efforts at rebellion appear to take place
largely in the subversive atmosphere he creates at his Wink shows.
At his spring 2000 show in September, the techno-music was loud and
models were made to seem younger and angrier than they probably
were. Some had hair styled into menacing peaks. They walked
furiously, many in sneakers, looking like 15-year-olds determined
to get away from go-nowhere lives full of pimple-faced boyfriends
who sit around listening to White Snake and drinking Colt 45. Maybe
these Amanda clothes were their passport.
nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is something to be said for the fact that Wink
offers well-constructed clothes at reasonable prices. It can also
be forward thinking. Smith was churning out blouses with ties long
before they turned up all over European runways last month. The
line is selling well in the Co-Op at Barneys New York. Kirna
Zabete, the shop in SoHo, has increased its order for next season,
and Bergdorf's will begin offering the clothes in the spring. Ms.
Dresner finds flashes of Smith's brilliance in Wink, and continues
to carry it.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Wink has its admirers among editors _ and stylists, including
Lisa Marie Fernandez, who said: ``There are a lot of designers out
there who can make a nice peacoat, but they don't have something to
say. Wynn has something to say.'' But there are those who lament
Smith's transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all looking for that great American young person,'' said
Marin Hopper, Elle's fashion director. ``He was on the wave of
becoming huge. I wish he'd get back to his collection,'' she added,
referring to the Wynn line, though she also admires Wink.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Baume, a former Vogue fashion editor and a Wynn fan, said
that when she first saw Wink, it seemed to be coming from a
different person from the one she had known. ``It was weird,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Smith claims not to miss the demands of producing a high-end
label all that much. ``Different people see different things in
Wink,'' he said. ``I can reach more people with it. It's not so
alienating.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
