<HEADER>
A4738 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-NHL-COLUMN-LADN     11-29 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE COYOTES MAY BE MOST WILY OF THEM ALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With three teams tied atop the Pacific Division,
Western Conference and the NHL itself, it would seem the greatest
success stories would be the Los Angeles Kings and San Jose Sharks,
because neither made the playoffs last year.
</P>
<P>
   But as the season opens its third month Wednesday, the Phoenix
Coyotes might be on the biggest roll. They are 15-6-3 and have 33
points in 24 games, one fewer than the Kings and four fewer than
the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   Their 4-3 victory over Detroit on Sunday was their sixth in a
row, tying them with Boston for the longest streak this season. It
capped a week in which they defeated New Jersey, Colorado and the
Red Wings. Those teams won four consecutive Stanley Cups before
Dallas did it last June.
</P>
<P>
   It is still four months to the playoffs, but beating teams like
that is critical for the Coyotes, who have lost four straight times
in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
   That can be just as disappointing as not making them at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great, but we're really not getting too worried about
what's going on right now,'' said Shane Doan, who had two goals
against Detroit and now has seven after scoring six all last
season. ``This isn't when it counts. It's April that's big for us.
Right now, we're just trying to keep a businesslike approach.''
</P>
<P>
   But the best sign of a real winner is when everyone contributes.
Last week, Jeremy Roenick scored two hat tricks and slumping Keith
Tkachuk had the game-winning goal against the Kings at Staples
Center. Doan scored twice against Detroit, and the Coyotes came
back from a 2-0 deficit that started when enforcer Louie DeBrusk
scored his first goal in more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   And now they have another hero in goalie Bob Essensa, an
undefeated backup (6-0-1) who will be starting the next six weeks
now that newcomer Sean Burke is out six weeks with a partially torn
tendon in his right thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix had 90 points during the regular season last year and
was expecting to play Detroit in the second round. But somehow the
St. Louis Blues got in the way and the Coyotes went home.
</P>
<P>
   When they returned, top goalie Nikolai Khabibulin decided to
hold out. An unrestricted free agent, Khabibulin thought his 2.13
goals-against average in 63 games would be enough to get a new
contract. The Coyotes aren't budging.
</P>
<P>
   Are they the best team in the West?
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes are 2-0-1 against the Kings, but 0-2 against the
Sharks. And though Phoenix won in Detroit, the Red Wings were
playing without 10 front-liners, including Sergei Federov and
goalie Chris Osgood.
</P>
<P>
   But consider:
</P>
<P>
   __When Roenick scores a point, which he did Sunday with an
assist on the first of four third-period Phoenix goals, the Coyotes
are 12-1-1. When he doesn't score, they're 0-4-1.
</P>
<P>
   __They beat New Jersey, Colorado and Detroit by a combined score
of 15-5.
</P>
<P>
   __The Coyotes' red-hot line of Roenick, Tkachuk and Dallas Drake
had 12 goals and 24 points in the five games before Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   __For the sixth time this season, Phoenix avoided a loss Sunday
after falling behind by two goals. And it was the fourth time the
club stormed back to win. That's something the Coyotes managed to
do only twice during the previous two seasons combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than the alternative,'' Coyotes first-year coach
Bob Francis said. ``We're just taking it a game at a time. We were
looking at these three games in a 60-hour stretch to see where we
stood in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Frequent flyer: Since leaving the Mighty Ducks in June 1998,
goaltender Mikhail Shtalenkov has played for Nashville, Edmonton,
Phoenix and now Florida.
</P>
<P>
   He recently was traded for Burke even though he was the No. 1
goalie in the absence of holdout Khabibulin.
</P>
<P>
   Shtalenkov was surprised when he heard he was headed for Florida
because he had such a great October, going 7-2-2 with a 1.80
goals-against average and .931 save percentage to be named the
NHL's Player of the Month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably scared them to death when I lost the last four
games, so that was probably my mistake,'' Shtalenkov said of the
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is in first place in the Southeast Division. Panthers
coach Terry Murray said he expects Shtalenkov probably will play 20
games the remainder of the season to make sure starter Trevor Kidd
knows he is the No. 1 guy.
</P>
<P>
   Looking up: By losing to the Rangers 6-3 Wednesday, the
Lightning's home winning streak was broken at five games _ one shy
of a franchise record set in the team's only playoff season,
1995-96. The fifth win came over the Flyers, who lead the Northeast
Division.
</P>
<P>
   In that game, a 4-1 victory, backup goalie Zac Bierk, 22, made
30 saves for his second NHL win and first since March 30, 1998.
Bierk's brother is Sebastian Bach, lead singer of the heavy metal
band Skid Row. The only reason Bierk was up with the Lightning was
because Dan Cloutier injured his groin. Then, Kevin Hodson pulled a
groin in the morning workout. Bierk found out he was playing about
90 minutes before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Great debut: No NHL team ever had chosen a goalie as high as the
New York Islanders did in 1997 when they made Roberto Luongo the
fourth overall pick. Now you know why.
</P>
<P>
   In his first game, Luongo made 43 saves against the potent
Boston Bruins. Nine of those shots were by Dave Andreychuk, eight
more by Anson Carter. That was only three fewer than the entire
Islanders team had. But Luongo didn't budge. He was called up Nov.
22 after going 6-6-3 in 15 games in the minors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
