<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG GAME IS ESPN VS. BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The federal trial between ESPN and Major League
Baseball, which starts Dec. 6 in Manhattan, promises to be a dandy
for its revelation of financial details and its demonstration of
long-simmering hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN is suing its partner to prevent baseball from terminating
their regular-season contract after the just completed season,
three years before its scheduled 2002 expiration.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN wants to keep intact its contract: 80 games on Sundays,
Wednesdays and holidays, and ``Baseball Tonight,'' make up crucial
programming for ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   But baseball wants to divorce ESPN because of rage and cash. Or
is it cash and rage? Baseball's hierarchy was infuriated last year
when ESPN purchased National Football League rights for $600
million annually, which led the cable network to propose
transferring three Sunday night baseball games in September to
ESPN2 to make room for pigskin.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball refused to approve the shift of the games _ and wrested
them from ESPN to let the teams show them on their local TV outlets
_ to avoid seeing them relegated to ESPN2, which has 11 million
fewer subscribers than ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Angry, baseball canceled ESPN's contract last April. ESPN
retaliated with its lawsuit, which alleges that baseball's action
is a transparent attempt to extract more cash in a hot market that
has yielded huge increases for the NFL, NASCAR, the National
Collegiate Athletic Association men's basketball tournament and the
National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   If ESPN loses, baseball could peddle the regular-season deal to
TNT or just the Sunday night games to Fox Sports Net or FX. Or ESPN
could re-enter the sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of ESPN's case is its charge that baseball
unreasonably withheld its approval to pre-empt the Sunday night
games in September 1998 and 1999 for events of ``significant viewer
interest,'' or NFL games.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has okayed transfers of games in the past to
accommodate hockey playoff games and other events _ but never on
Sundays. Baseball views the Sunday games as sacrosanct property
with enormous value which does not merit being shuttled to ESPN2
for the more expensive, higher-rated NFL.
</P>
<P>
   In a pretrial hearing last week, United States District Judge
Shira A. Scheindlin repeatedly tried to persuade Robert Kheel, a
lawyer for baseball, to quantify how much baseball was damaged by
ESPN's action.
</P>
<P>
   Give me a dollar figure, she said, as if chasing a phantom.
Kheel repeated that he could not provide a sum because it was
impossible to place a number on being bumped off the network you
contracted to show your games on. If ESPN had negotiated a
pre-emption right, he said, then he might have a figure.
</P>
<P>
   But ESPN paid its $36 million rights fee, didn't it, the judge
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Kheel said, but that was payment to show games, not shuttle
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you quantify hurt?'' Scheindlin said. ``Because hurt
sounds to me a little bit like hurt ego, hurt feelings. `We're the
national pastime and now people will think football is the national
pastime. We're going to become not as important in the public mind
as we once were.' I understand all that. I don't know how you
quantify it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kheel said: ``We have not shown specific losses, your honor, we
agree with you there. What we have said is we believe it did affect
us.''
</P>
<P>
   After a recess, Kheel returned with a hastily hatched damages
theory that went like this: ESPN pays $30 million to broadcast each
NFL game, so baseball's hurt was three NFL games multiplied by 5
percent, or $4.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Lobenfeld, an ESPN lawyer, was not amused. ``I don't know
how, if they got every dollar they contracted for and can't itemize
a penny of anything else, that it hurt them,'' he said. ``They are
basically down to saying, `It hurt my feelings, it's a black eye,
makes me look bad.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Scheindlin ruled that baseball would not be
eligible for major damages. If victorious, it could receive only a
nominal sum.
</P>
<P>
   Scheindlin also ruled that the jury can hear evidence that
baseball's refusal to approve the transfer of games to ESPN2 was
unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence is two letters written by baseball to ESPN during
settlement discussions that proposed large increases in ESPN's
fees.
</P>
<P>
   Irrelevant, baseball argued.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball made two offers, which ESPN alleged to be a blatant
attempt to extract ``extracontractual concessions'' to an existing
contract.
</P>
<P>
   The first offer, made in April 1998, suggested adding $30
million to the $183.6 million ESPN was scheduled to pay baseball
from 1998 to 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Last January came the second offer: raise the 1999-to-2002
rights fees, which average $37.2 million a year, by more than $50
million annually.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, there's more: baseball proposed to extend the contract
for two years, to $125 million for 2003 and $140 million for 2004.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to preclude this evidence, baseball said it would be
``highly prejudicial and lead the court and the jury into
consideration of entirely collateral issues.'' Scheindlin called it
``directly relevant to the critical question of reasonableness.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring a settlement, ESPN and baseball will stage the best game
of the off-season. Best of all, it's free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
