<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-IBF-ORDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE LIMITS EXPENDITURES BY THE IBF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A federal judge, acting on part of a request by
prosecutors that the court take sweeping control of the
International Boxing Federation, issued an order Monday barring its
indicted leadership from making any individual expenditures in
excess of $5,000 without court permission.
</P>
<P>
   In issuing the temporary restraining order against the boxing
sanctioning and ranking organization and its founder, Robert W. Lee
Sr., Judge John W. Bissell of U.S. District Court said he was
concerned about ``preservation of the entity's resources for the
future'' and saw some validity to federal prosecutors' concerns
that funds going into the organization in the coming weeks could be
misdirected by those under indictment.
</P>
<P>
   He rejected arguments by federation lawyers federation and Lee
that the restrictions were an unnecessary move by the federal
prosecutors who were illegally and improperly trying to become
boxing reformers.
</P>
<P>
   The restrictions on spending were an initial step sought by
Robert J. Cleary, the U.S. attorney for New Jersey, in his battle
to wrest control of the organization from private hands in what is
the first attempt to bring a sporting organization under court
supervision. Cleary's office, using the civil provisions of the
Racketeering Influenced and Corrupt Organization Act, moved last
week to have the court appoint a monitor to take over and reform
the IBF less than three weeks after his office obtained a 32-count
indictment against Lee and three other top officials of the
federation, charging them with bribery, racketeering and money
laundering.
</P>
<P>
   Also last week the prosecutors proposed to the court that they
appoint Zachary W. Carter, the former U.S. attorney for the Eastern
District of New York, who is now in private practice, as the
monitor of the sanctioning group with authority to remove the
indicted officials and hire new executives, restructure it and
reform it.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bissell scheduled Dec. 22 for final legal arguments
on the appointment of the monitor. While he did not hint at his
leanings, he did telegraph during the hearing that he saw a proper
and legal role for federal and court intervention in the sport.
``The court perceives a public policy interest in the enhancing of
the integrity of an activity as pervasive as boxing and
particularly one which plays a big role in interstate commerce,''
Bissell said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 65 of Fanwood, N.J.; his son Robert Lee Jr., 38, of Scotch
Plains, N.J., who was liaison to his father; Donald William
Brennan, 86, of Warsaw, Va., chairman of the group's ranking
committee; and Francisco Fernandez, an international commissioner
and South American representative of the group who lives in
Colombia, are charged with extracting $338,000 in bribes from
fighters and their managers in exchange for moving them up in the
rankings and in line for lucrative purses and broadcast proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   Bissell said Monday's order directs the elder Lee and others to
carry on the IBF's ``normal course of business,'' but to avoid
``extraordinary expenditures,'' including any payment of legal fees
for the officials out of organization funds. Bissell said that the
order was not an absolute prohibition and that he would entertain
requests for modifications ``to minimize the impact on the normal
operations'' of the IBF.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Krovatin, the elder Lee's lawyer, called the sweeping
civil action by the prosecutors to seek a court takeover of the
sports organization overreaching and typical of the way prosecutors
try to use the powerful anti-racketeering laws. But Krovatin said
that the civil provisions of the law were as ``vague and
amorphous'' as they were sweeping, and he accused prosecutors of
trying to use them to ``bootstrap'' remedies to which they would
not be entitled even if Lee were eventually found guilty of the
criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Braunreuther, the assistant United States Attorney and
chief of the civil division in New Jersey, raised the specter of
diversion of funds by noting that the IBF was both a nonprofit
organization and a for-profit group in which the elder Lee
controlled 62 percent of the shares. While there has been no
``looting'' of either entity, Braunreuther said, the possibility
exists that Lee could ``hijack'' funds from one organization and
place them with another.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the current federal, civil and criminal
proceedings involving the IBF, there is also a state court action
in which Lee is seeking to oust three minority shareholders from
Oregon of the for-profit IBF, accusing them of bilking the group of
$1.5 million over the last seven years. Hearings in that case are
scheduled in Essex County Superior Court on Dec. 16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
