<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FUTURE-ELIANGONZALEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE FUTURE OF ELIAN GONZALEZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Nov. 30:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Florida Straits, where so many Cubans have lost their
lives trying to make their way across the last Cold War barrier to
the United States, another small, overloaded boat has sunk,
apparently drowning a young woman and casting her 5-year-old son
adrift. For two days after the 16-foot boat went down, Elian
Gonzalez clung to an inner tube before fishermen on Thanksgiving
morning found him and two adults who had survived. His pluck kept
him alive, and brought him to the country his mother and stepfather
may have died trying to reach. Their bodies have not been found.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is, where should Elian Gonzalez be? Authorities
in Cuba, where his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, lives, allege that
the boy was kidnapped by his mother. On Sunday the father formally
asked for his son's return. But the Immigration and Naturalization
Service said Monday that it had already legally paroled Elian to
relatives living in Miami. ``His mother was bringing him to
freedom,'' the boy's uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, said, ``and we don't
want him to go back to a Communist system.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Coast Guard had found the boy at sea, United States
policy would have directed that he be sent back to Cuba. But
because the fishermen brought him to land, he has the legal right
to stay, and that right should not be hastily abridged because of
Elian's age.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers of Cuban boat people are growing after a downturn in
the mid-1990's. A total of 2,254 arrived here this year, while
1,265 were stopped in open water. Another boatload of Cubans
drowned last December.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to win new life here costs lives, and creates
dilemmas to test the wisdom of a Solomon. If the boy's father
wishes, he can petition for custody of Elian, and legal proceedings
in Florida will decide who should raise him. The INS could give the
father permission to come to this country and testify.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, the American system must now accord Elian
Gonzalez the same care and protection that any child would receive
in a custody case. That could mean having a family court consider
the child's wishes, once he has had time to recover from the shock
of losing his mother and also to determine the best home
environment for him. His father has a right to press his claim, and
American authorities have an obligation to make an apolitical
judgment that serves the boy's needs rather than any political
interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 2339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0497 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4747 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BALLET-STRIKE-ART-NYT     11-29 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLET-STRIKE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: A STRIKE OVER MUSIC, NOT MONEY AT BALLET
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ms) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The French composer Darius Milhaud was asked by a
cousin if all the instruments he wrote into a symphonic score
should be played together. ``Preferably,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Ballet, too, prefers its orchestra to sound
like the cohesive ensemble it can be at its best. How to guarantee
excellence is the issue that has divided the ballet management and
its orchestra members. The musicians, represented by Local 802 of
the American Federation of Musicians, went on strike a week ago in
a labor dispute. Taped music has accompanied performances of ``The
Nutcracker.''
</P>
<P>
   The one thing that both sides agreed upon in contract talks was
that this strike was different from the other four in the company
since 1966. It was not a dispute about money or benefits. It was
about changing work schedules to encourage or require musicians to
attend rehearsals for the performances they play. ``Linkage''
between rehearsal and performance was the word used by lawyers on
both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Under the last contract, which expired in September, substitutes
could replace the orchestra's regular musicians at rehearsals or
performances. Although many musicians attend most performances and
rehearsals, they may go on unpaid leave to work or perform outside
the company to supplement their income. Their regular season is 23
weeks a year with the option of playing for the ballet for three
more weeks in Saratoga, N.Y., in July. All orchestra members
receive benefits for 52 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon for substitutes to play at a performance for
which they have not rehearsed or to play at a rehearsal for a
ballet but not at its performance. The same applies to the regular
musicians. Had the orchestra members not gone on strike and played
at the Nov. 23 opening-night gala, 22 of the 62 musicians in the
pit would have been substitutes, the management said.
</P>
<P>
   The company proposed that newly hired orchestra members be
required to play six performances each week (there are seven each
week and more during ``Nutcracker'' season) and attend two out of
four rehearsals designated by the company each week. This would
enable the conductor to know in advance which musicians would be
present, and there would be continuity between rehearsals and
performances.
</P>
<P>
   Current orchestra members would remain free not to attend
specific performances or rehearsals, as under the old contract. But
if they volunteered to join the new system, they would be paid at a
higher rate like the new musicians. Although the orchestra members
had proposed the grandfathering clause by which the current members
could stay on the old system, they rejected the proposal last week.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Leibowitz, the lawyer representing the orchestra
bargaining committee, said that that proposal would create a
two-tier system and divisions among the musicians. Negotiations
between City Ballet and Local 802 ended Monday afternoon after the
ballet management agreed to study new proposals presented by the
musicians. Judy West, the spokeswoman for Local 802, said the union
offered a comprehensive counterproposal. Talks were to resume
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   In this strike, unlike any other at City Ballet, the orchestra
leadership stepped onto risky ground. One reason is that the
musicians in recent years have come under increasing criticism for
the quality of some performances. Another is that ``The
Nutcracker'' run, which began last Friday after two scheduled dark
days, has been accompanied by taped music. This precedent might
affect the musicians' union in labor disputes with Broadway
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   In previous strikes, City Ballet had found it cheaper to cancel
performances. During the six-week orchestra strike in the winter of
1976-77 George Balanchine, the ballet's co-founder, considered
using taped music. He called this ``something to tide us over,''
but not a solution, and added, ``It's a pity that some of the
musicians do not look up a little higher and try to see another
dimension.''
</P>
<P>
   The company canceled most of its ``Nutcracker'' performances and
part of its winter repertory during that strike. The orchestra's
musicians had gone on strike for three days in 1966 and four weeks
in 1970. In 1973 the dancers went out for four weeks on what was
widely interpreted as a move by the management to pre-empt an
orchestra strike. The dancers had asked the ballet to guarantee
them 14 weeks of work, which the company said it could not do
because it had not reached agreement with the orchestra, which
threatened a strike. In effect, the dancers' walkout locked out the
orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   This season the musicians may have committed a tactical error.
Last Saturday afternoon, for instance, the New York State Theater
appeared full with only a scattering of empty spots in the
2,800-seat house. Ticket buyers, staff members and stagehands had
crossed the musicians' picket line and the few refunded tickets
were often resold, providing a bonanza for those who could not get
into previously sold-out performances.
</P>
<P>
   Because many dance companies perform to tape in New York or on
tour (the Miami City Ballet did so recently in Newark with a
Balanchine repertory), dance to recorded music is not a novelty.
</P>
<P>
   At the Saturday matinee the recording was obviously not live
sound but acceptable. The applause rolled in with roars at
traditional moments. Peter Martins, City Ballet's artistic
director, and Anne Parsons, its general manager, said in an
interview that they had decided not to close the State Theater
because 350 people, including dancers, stagehands, ushers and other
staff members, would be out of work and because 125,000 tickets had
been sold for ``The Nutcracker.''
</P>
<P>
   Martins said he considered the orchestra players part of City
Ballet's family. ``It's an excellent orchestra, and I respect them.
They are asked to perform a very advanced and sophisticated musical
repertoire, which is difficult. It's not that they can't play but
that they are not there. Artistically, I feel it's a lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   Martins has often taken the rap for the orchestra's occasional
waywardness. Last year an oboist did not play on time and a dancer,
Miranda Weese, found herself performing a solo to silence for a few
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The attendance rules have inhibited the company's search for a
new music director. Many of the 12 guest conductors invited during
City Ballet's 50th anniversary season in 1998-99 were surprised
that the players they had rehearsed were not always those they saw
at the performance.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parsons said that the company was close to choosing a new
musical director, but that any candidate would need assurance that
the orchestra members are prepared to play as a genuine ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Balanchine and Lincoln Kirstein, the company's
co-founders, had put ``music on a par with dance,'' Martins
emphasized: ``We have to do something so that musicians apply the
same standards of integrity and professionalism in their work as
everyone else. This is the mandate that Balanchine set forth in
this house.''
</P>
<P>
   This is all well and good, but it was under Balanchine that the
current orchestra rules evolved. And changes in lifestyle and
habits are psychological issues, even in the interest of artistic
quality.
</P>
<P>
   As Bernard M. Plum, the lawyer for the ballet management, said,
``It's not about money, and that is what makes it difficult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
