A4757 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-WTO-MAIN-SPI &LR;      11-29 1682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-MAIN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE MINISTERS GATHER FOR RAUCOUS DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With deep divisions among themselves and with tens of thousands
of protesters threatening to shut them down, trade ministers from
135 nations Tuesday gather in Seattle for a difficult round of
talks aimed at reducing barriers to international trade.
</P>
<P>
   The third meeting of the five-year-old World Trade Organization
promises to be a free-wheeling global town hall on the virtues and
vices of globalization, as the world's trade ministers try to speed
up trade liberalization and a panoply of protesters try to slow
them down.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the ministers got their first hint of what promises to
be a raucous weeklong debate when a security scare at the
convention center delayed a forum for hours and forced thousands of
delegates and reporters to spend a chilly damp morning standing on
the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Children costumed as endangered species wandered the streets.
</P>
<P>
   A French sheep farmer angry over tariffs on cheese led a march
on a McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban leader Fidel Castro begged off, saying he was worried he
might be arrested.
</P>
<P>
   And President Clinton, who arrives in Seattle Wednesday morning,
is already altering his schedule to acknowledge the unhappiness in
the air. He promised Monday to hold closed-door meetings with
critics Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as soon as the delegates hit town, many were predicting
failure _ often a brinksmanship tactic employed by trade
negotiators but also an indication of the difficulty of reaching
compromise by the close of the meeting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is demanding to talk about U.S. tactics to protect
politically sensitive industries like steel. The United States
refuses.
</P>
<P>
   The United States insists on talking about European subsidies to
protect agriculture. The Europeans refuse.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, trying to placate its critics, is
pushing the causes of labor and the environment, but they seem to
have persuaded few other nations to join the cause. And labor and
environmental leaders, apparently smelling fear in the air, began
proclaiming victory even before the talks began, saying that the
disarray is a testament to the power of their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The security scare at the convention center Monday, triggered
when a guard spotted a broken lock, had an ironic effect: the WTO
had to delay the one major event it had scheduled at which critics
could speak directly to trade ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Police swept the building and turned up nothing. The symposium
for non-governmental organizations proceeded, a little late and a
little abbreviated.
</P>
<P>
   But the day offered a preview of what is to come.
</P>
<P>
   The city was thick with politicians and dignitaries, many of
them with an ax to grind. Interest groups tried to defend their
cause _ domestic and foreign sugar producers, for example, held
competing events to debate the merits of how the United States
protects its politically powerful sugar industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is pushing for a new trade round that
would be limited to a few topics with strong domestic appeal, such
as agriculture and electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   There is so much disagreement that trade officials at the WTO's
headquarters in Geneva were unable even to come up with an agenda
for this week's gathering in Seattle, so the ministers are meeting
without a script. Their goal is by Friday to come up with an agenda
for a global round of trade liberalization talks that would be
launched here and continued over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Unsexy as these topics may be, the so-called Millennium Round
has already engaged the public more than any previous round of
global negotiations. The WTO has become the focal point of a broad
set of global anxieties about the sovereignty of nations and the
power of multinational corporations. The very tenor of this week's
meeting is being dramatically affected by those fears.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart promised a
boring week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who is a student of trade negotiations will find it's
akin to watching paint dry'' Lockhart said. ``It is not the most
exciting thing in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's own schedule is being shaped by the domestic
political tumult that has greeted the WTO. Two of the Democratic
Party's top constituencies, the environmental and labor movements,
are leading the protests against the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who is spending Tuesday in California, is to arrive in
Seattle early Wednesday and then spend about 30 hours in town,
talking up the benefits of trade, attempting to mollify critics,
and urging delegates to embrace the needs of workers and the
environment even as they work to lower trade barriers.
</P>
<P>
   He is to spend much of his time at the Port of Seattle, touring
a control tower that directs marine traffic and a transit shed
where he will see apples, hay and newsprint readied for export, as
well as a Weyerhaeuser ship handling exports of forest products.
Clinton plans to give a major trade speech to a group of local
farmers, elected officials, and schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of Wednesday afternoon and Thursday morning
Clinton is to address WTO ministers, hold private meetings with
environmental and labor leaders, and sign an International Labor
Organization convention against child labor.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO is essentially a committee of its member governments,
operating by consensus as the members try to forge agreements to
eliminate protectionist tariffs. But the movement to free trade
around the world has become increasingly controversial as many
tariffs are removed and countries increasingly challenge the
non-tariff barriers to trade, such as labor laws and environmental
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's symposium for non-governmental organizations was a
first for the WTO, which considers itself an organization of
governments and whose members often resist direct conversations
with non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Those who came to protest WTO policies said they expected little
of substance to emerge from this week's discussions. Generally,
they termed WTO's Non-Governmental Organization Day _ the official
forum for enviornmental, labor and other groups _ a flop. Activists
in forums outside the official WTO pre-meetings sensed they were
winning at least some points in the court of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I get disoriented when I think we may be about to
win one,'' said Bill Blaikie, a member of the Canadian Parliament,
who cited ``the obvious confusion of the (WTO) leadership about
whether they're going to come out of this with what they thought
they would. ... I think we're on the beginning of a bit of a roll.
I want to be hopeful _ we've lost these things so many times _ but
I want to be hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   Activists are working to head off plans to apply the free trade
rules to investments. They also are working to short-circuit plans
for liberalized trade in timber and other forest products, and
other goods as part of the so-called acellerated tariff
liberalization idea. They also want the WTO to butt out of
discussions over genetically modified foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is perfectly obvious at the moment that the negotiators are
in deadlock,'' said Ronnie Hall of Friends of the Earth's United
Kingdom office. ``They're not going anywhere. It seems there is a
lot of hostility.''
</P>
<P>
   American business is trying to turn public opinion around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first goal is educating the American public, workers and
some policy makers that overwhelming evidence supports expanded
trade in today's global economy,'' said Jerry Jasinowski, president
of National Assocaition of Manufacturers. ``The integration of
America into the global econmy has mvoed forward so rapidly that
people dont understand it and the benefits associatiend with it.
... They are susceptible to the demagogic arguments that trade is a
race to the bottom ... when there's no evidence for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is making a concerted effort to
placate protesters.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefksy, the main
negotiator for the United States, delivered a forceful speech
Monday promising that the America will stick to its proposal to
expand world trade rules to cover labor rights, although it is the
most controversial issue among WTO members.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the International Confederation of Free Trade
Unions, Barshefsky said, ``It is astonishing to me that so many
other countries feel so threatened by the inclusion of these
issues. We intend absolutely to persist in this, and not just in
Seattle, because these issues are fundamental.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience of union leaders, who included AFL-CIO President
John Sweeney, broke into applause. Sweeney had said before the
meeting that it wasn't clear how strongly the Clinton
Administration supports labor rights abroad. ``We'll see,'' he
said. ``After the agreement with China, I'm not so sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Pascal Lamy,trade commissioner for the European Union, said he
opposed a proposal by labor unions to allow WTO trade sanctions
against countries that violate labor rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sanctions are not on the agenda,'' he said, proposing instead
a joint committee of the WTO and International Labor Organization
that ``has nothing to do with imposing advanced social standards on
countries that cannot afford them.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting has particular importance for Washington state, the
most trade dependent in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gary Locke called on the Clinton administration to hold
firm to policies aimed at opening foreign markets and creating fair
competition in the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure that other countries are not putting
United states products and commodities at a competitive
disadvantage becaue of the huge subisidies,'' Locke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that puts our companies and employees at a competitive
disadvantage, and this round of the WTO must address these issue.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporters Bruce Ramsey, Robert McClure and Robert Gavin
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-29-99 2357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
