<DOCNO> NYT19991129.0500 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-29 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4760 &Cx1f; kan-z
a f BC-BANKS-SMALL-KAN &LR;      11-29 1741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-SMALL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE BANK INDUSTRY CONSOLIDATION, CUSTOMERS HAVE MANY CHOICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ When Rick Force and his partner started
selling evidence collection supplies to police departments three
years ago, they set up their business accounts with one of the
city's largest banks.
</P>
<P>
   Force and his partner, Mike Canfield, quickly found out,
however, that a small company such as theirs could not command the
attention offered larger customers. When the bank merged into a
bigger bank company, they felt lost in the shuffle. They had to
keep explaining their unusual business to a series of young
bankers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through account reps like toilet paper,'' Force said.
</P>
<P>
   They have since moved their business to a small community bank,
Missouri Bank &AMP; Trust, where they have received great service _ and
better rates.
</P>
<P>
   Bank consolidation came late to this area, and it continues to
roil the market with changes. Although sometimes confusing, bankers
said, the action has created a boon for business and individual
customers.
</P>
<P>
   It has provided just about every choice in banking a customer
might want. And it has made the market more competitive, pushing up
the interest rates that banks pay for money market accounts and
certificates of deposit and pushing down interest rates on loans
for everything from cars to credit lines.
</P>
<P>
   With the acquisition in September of Mercantile Bancorporation
Inc., based in St. Louis with a big presence in Kansas City, the
area again is feeling the undulations. Mercantile was acquired by
Firstar Corp. of Milwaukee as part of a $10.4 billion merger.
Branches will be converted next year to the Firstar name.
</P>
<P>
   With Firstar's reputation for aggressiveness and strong service,
businesses and bankers alike are eager to see how the next
derivation of the market plays out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is more opportunity than ever before,'' said
local bank consultant Jerry Swords. ``The new banks that have come
along are doing super. Still, things have changed dramatically.
People are doing more of their banking electronically, and banks
are going to have to adapt. If you say you don't care what people
want, that bank won't be around in 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks fall into four basic categories, and with Firstar coming
into the market, Kansas City businesses and consumers have all four
banking models to consider.
</P>
<P>
   The national model is represented by Bank of America, formerly
NationsBank, formerly Boatmen's. It is the country's largest bank
company, with $620 billion in assets and operations in 22 states
and 33 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Firstar, with about $74 billion in assets, is considered a
superregional bank, serving more than one area of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the regional banks, both hometown companies,
Commerce Bancshares Inc. and UMB Financial Corp., with assets under
$12 billion and less geographical reach.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there are many community banks. Most of the new
community banks are drawn to Johnson County and its concentration
of wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel if they can get in and get a niche, that the Johnson
County market will continue to expand into the next decade,'' said
Jim Maag of the Kansas Bankers Association.
</P>
<P>
   It is one reason Kansas ranks near the top nationally in the
lowest number of people per bank office, Maag said. It has about
one bank or branch for every 2,200 persons. New York state has
about twice as many people per bank office.
</P>
<P>
   It is also one of the reasons, bankers said, that customers will
find some of the best deals on loans and bank accounts in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many banks are chasing deposits that it has caused deposit
rate pressure,'' said Alexander Kemper, president and CEO of UMB
Financial Corp. ``It is like taking a football to a soccer match.
It is the wrong tool. What many people in Johnson County are
looking for is wealth management.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he concedes, it is good for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   What Firstar brings specifically to this mix is a commitment to
service that the market has not seen, certainly among large banks,
said Ron Barnes, president and CEO of the newly acquired Mercantile
Bank in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Firstar guarantees to meet certain standards or pay customers a
penalty for coming up short, Barnes said. A customer who waits more
than five minutes for a teller will get $5. A business customer who
has provided all the information needed on a loan request is
guaranteed a response within 48 hours. The penalty for failure is
$25.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not so much that people will fall all over themselves to
receive 25 bucks, but it is the symbolism that service is king and
everyone at Firstar is lined up behind that,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Megabanks such as Firstar also offer a breadth and depth of
products and specialists that companies need as markets become
increasingly global and the economics of business become
increasingly complex, Barnes said. Even small companies are finding
a need for international services.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Nelson extols the benefits of an international bank such as
Bank of America, where he is president of the Kansas City region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a client that just made an acquisition in Italy and
needed financing for its operations there of 25 million lire,''
Nelson said. ``We called our colleagues in Milan, where we have a
bank, and within 24 hours had the financing in place. That is the
advantage of dealing with a global bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant Burcham, whose office at Missouri Bank &AMP; Trust sits in the
shadows of three big downtown banks, tells a different story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a customer whose teen-age kids were going to
Australia, and she wanted ATM cards for them,'' said Burcham,
president of Missouri Bank &AMP; Trust. ``They went to the bank where
they had banked for 25 years, and they wouldn't give the cards
because of their age. They said it was against their rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``She called us from her cell phone in that bank's parking lot.
She had an application that afternoon and debit cards and
traveler's checks the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Responsiveness like that has helped Missouri Bank &AMP; Trust grow
from $37 million in assets in 1992 to $105 million and garnered it
the 1999 Small Business of the Year award from the Greater Kansas
City Chamber of Commerce. The growth came even though the bank has
had one location, no weekend hours and no drive-through window.
Bank owners picked a niche and distinguished the bank with service,
Burcham said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business owners only need a good bank when they have a
problem,'' Burcham said. ``When that happens, we don't have layers
and layers to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a banking theory that the industry will soon look like
a barbell. At one end is a few international banking companies with
huge assets, broad services and phenomenal lending limits. At the
other end are a large number of community banks with small loan
limits but extraordinary personal service. Only a few regional
banks in the middle would survive.
</P>
<P>
   Regional banks here see Kansas City, where small and medium-size
companies dominate the economy, as a perfect place to thrive in
that middle market. They see themselves offering the best features
of big and small.
</P>
<P>
   ``The typical Kansas City middle-market company would prefer to
do business with a decision maker that is local, is successful and
has continuity,'' said Jonathan Kemper, chairman of Commerce Bank.
``That plays into the advantages of our bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Kemper at UMB Financial agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am doubtful that bigger is better. I think better is
better,'' he said. ``You need what I call the three C words:
creativity, continuity and capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   Creativity is needed to find solutions to clients' banking
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Continuity means the business relationship is not constantly
interrupted by mergers that roll new managers through a bank.
</P>
<P>
   Capacity is needed to offer a full range of services required by
clients, Alexander Kemper said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he sees UMB's future brightened by the growth in small
banks. He wants to provide small banks and companies computer and
Internet services to help them compete against their giant
competitors. UMB already is among the largest in the country in
handling financial transactions, such as credit card processing,
for other banks. It now wants to be the intermediary for its
clients in services such as Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be a very romantic vision,'' Alexander Kemper said,
``but the idea of empowering the little guy is very powerful to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mic Aslin, who spent 22 years at UMB Bank and its parent company
before leaving in 1994, thinks the banks that can harness
technology for themselves and their clients will be the banks of
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Aslin became president and chief executive officer of Leawood,
Kan.-based Gold Banc Corp. in February when it bought his computer
networking company, CompuNet Engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Gold Banc is a relatively new company that has been growing into
a regional operator through acquisitions. With deals announced in
October, it will serve 47 communities and have $2.75 billion in
assets. It is taking the national banking model to community banks
by getting into investment banking, insurance, international
banking and Internet banking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies that can tie technology together without killing
themselves with the investment and without making big mistakes,
they will be the banks that will get the real attention,'' Aslin
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   One result of becoming a successful regional bank is living with
constant takeover speculation as other bank companies look to
expand.
</P>
<P>
   As public companies, the Kansas City area's regional banks would
be compelled to consider any serious offer. But top regional bank
executives say they aren't in discussions with any prospective
suitors, and they aren't looking for deals.
</P>
<P>
   There is no disagreement among industry leaders, however, that
consolidation will continue in the area and that it will be good
for bank customers who find the bank that meets their needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that is cause of optimism,'' said Aslin, who also is
an owner of a start-up bank in Johnson County. ``There will be new
products that banks will be able to offer. It means ultimately
everyone who is capable of borrowing money will be able to borrow
money, and that is whether you live in rural areas or in urban
areas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
